<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-A'S-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETICS SHUT OUT YANKEES, 2-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees talked casually about wnning their 100th
game of the regular season because they have long expected to do it
and because they have almost a month to get the one victory
necessary to reach the lofty total. Like every other milestone this
relaxed team has conquered, the Yankees treated the pursuit in a
businesslike fashion. There is no need to get too excited, they
stressed.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there was no reason at all for the Yankees to get too
excited on Wednesday night as a pitcher named Gil Heredia made them
look like impostors in guiding the Oakland Athletics to a 2-0
victory at Yankee Stadium. So the 100th victory celebration, which
was not going to be a celebration for the Yankees anyway, will have
to wait until at least Friday night, when they play the White Sox
in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   It was a long night of anticipating for the Yankees and their
fans because the start of the game was delayed 2 hours 14 minutes
by rain. After it finally started, the A's scored what seemed like
a harmless run off David Cone (18-5) in the first inning and
surprisingly held tight to the lead behind Heredia.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loss, if they win on Friday, the Yankees will still
reach 100 victories in the fifth fewest games in history and will
do it faster, in terms of the calendar date, than any other team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we get to 100, we will go ahead and try and do something
else,'' Paul O'Neill said. ``It's not like our goal was to win 100
games by Sept. 2. Our goal is to win the division and eventually
win the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday night, the Yankees are still at 99-38. Cone
pitched a marvelous game in stifling the A's on one run and four
hits, while striking out 10 in seven innings, but he failed to win
his major league-best 19th game for the third time as Heredia
baffled the Yankees in his second start since Sept. 28, 1996. The
32-year-old right-hander did not allow a run and gave up five hits
and no walks in seven and two-thirds innings.
</P>
<P>
   It did not seem like a positive sign for Heredia when he
dispatched one of the bat boys to the Yankee clubhouse to ask the
players to autograph a baseball for him. It was an unusual request
and it seemed as if it might be arduous for Heredia to oppose a
team he revered enough to ask for autographs. But Heredia was not
awed and he did not surrender a hit in four at-bats with runners in
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunities against Heredia, who spent most of the last
two years in the minors, were scant. Bernie Williams doubled off
the right-center-field fence with two outs in the fourth, but Tino
Martinez grounded back to Heredia. Scott Brosius lined a one-out
double in the eighth but never budged. Derek Jeter poked a two-out
single in the sixth, but Heredia picked him off first.
</P>
<P>
   Cone had to wait more than two hours to throw the first pitch, a
painstaking amount of time for any starting pitcher. It was
probably disruptive for Cone, who purposely does not arrive at the
ball park until 90 minutes before games he pitches because he gets
too antsy.
</P>
<P>
   Once the game started at 9:49 p.m., with most of the soggy fans
still waiting for the Yankees to pursue their 100th, Cone delighted
them by striking out Jason Mc Donald. But Ryan Christenson made
sure that Cone would not chase perfection, as David Wells did the
night before, by singling. Jason Giambi hit a ball that bounced off
the grass and shot past Martinez at first base to advance
Christenson to third, and Matt Stairs's tapper to second was hit
too slow to turn a double play, so the A's had a 1-0 lead.
Christenson homered off Mike Stanton in the eighth for Oakland's
other run.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yanks were concerned about Cone, who had allowed 10
earned runs in his last two starts, there was no need to be
worried. He retired 20 of the last 24 batters he opposed,
registering nine strikeouts in that stretch to keep the
soggy-turned-groggy fans awake.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees could not score, so their 100th victory was
delayed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
