<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWKS SHOW AT LEAST FIVE REASONS FOR FANS TO BELIEVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ So they're alive and kicking. Your 1998
Seattle Seahawks have told you all about that.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Adams, the defensive tackle with his eyes buggin', stars in
those TV ads and all but taunts you to get on board the Hawk
bandwagon. And you know Paul Allen is paying the tab and the money
man is personally stoking the engine.
</P>
<P>
   But there's still a hitch. Four days until the opener of another
season dripping with expectation, you don't know whether you should
believe. You don't know whether you should commit.
</P>
<P>
   Are the Seahawks going to be good as they should be? Or is the
ghost of ex-special teams' coach Dave Arnold going to haunt this
franchise, spooking some other aspect of the team to go
embarrassingly haywire and kill yet another season so full of
promise, so full of expectation?
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks are begging you to get alive and kicking with them.
And there you are, unsure whether to take the plunge.
</P>
<P>
   I understand your pain. Which is why it was time Wednesday to
make one last preseason foray to Seahawkland, stand at the edge of
the practice field and wait for the players to run off. Time to get
a final preseason look and make a determination about what's fair
to ask of these Hawks, what's fair to expect.
</P>
<P>
   And then they came running at me _ more ``You Gotta Love These
Guys'' types than the Mariners can shake a stick at. Big-name
players. Free agents and imports and veterans who are talking about
a certain ``cockiness'' the Hawks have not known since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   And one by one, it seemed clear that there are ample reasons to
go ahead and make the commitment to the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   For example: Brian Habib. One look and it's clear the Hawks'
offensive line is better than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran guard will be the key to the wars that must be won
in the trench, both for the protection of quarterback Warren Moon
and to uncork the upgraded Seahawk running game.
</P>
<P>
   Then, exiting the field, Chad Brown. He is another reason you
can comfortably call yourself a Seahawk believer.
</P>
<P>
   The dominating linebacker now has a new director in Jim Johnson
_ a coach who is going to let Brown line up all over the field this
season. Brown, the former Pro Bowler, will be given the green light
to go at opposing offenses from so many different angles, opponents
will need a prism to figure out where the blitz is coming from.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Brown was rendered almost useless by defensive
schemes that failed to make use of his quickness. This year, it
should be a return to the 13-sack season of Brown's heyday in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Ricky Watters. Braided hair and eyes dancin' almost as
quick as his feet. He is the other guy who should make you put your
trust and faith in the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   The flashy back wearing No. 32 is going to be the primary ball
carrier for the Hawks _ not to mention the primary fire-breather.
(Think we'll miss Chris Warren? Not when Watters wants the ball,
wants to block, wants to lead and wants to rap.)
</P>
<P>
   Watters, despite the ongoing and silly rap against his fiery
nature, is not going to be an attitude problem. He is going to be
THE ATTITUDE. And he is going to be the key to uncorking a balanced
offense that could actually make '98 Hawks better than last year,
when they boasted the NFL's No. 3 offense.
</P>
<P>
   The more Ricky runs, the more defenses will stock the line with
eight-man fronts, which means the surprisingly unselfish Big Ricky
will be happy to let receivers Joey Galloway, James McKnight and
Mike Pritchard take on their single cover men.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads us to the fourth reason to put your faith in the
Hawks: Galloway.
</P>
<P>
   If Dennis Erickson and offensive coordinator Bob Bratkowski
don't insist on Galloway getting the chance to catch 100 passes
this season, then heads will have to roll. Galloway had 72 catches
last season (and nine of those we-know-it's-coming reverses.)
</P>
<P>
   This is the year of the Buckeyes, since Galloway's former
college team is picked No. 1 to win a national title. And this is
the year of the Hawks' major Buckeye, too, since Galloway will be
turned loose, or else.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to reason No. 5 why the Hawks are worth kicking
with in '98: Warren Moon.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Moon did not start Game 1 last season against the
Jets. Moon was the backup on the dead-out-of-the-gate Seahawks _
the team that was absolutely stunned by the pouncing Jets, 41-3, in
that demoralizing opener.
</P>
<P>
   With Moon in the pocket from the start, and with Watters running
and blocking for him, there is no way the Hawks come out flat
Sunday in Philly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those first three or four series are going to be very
important for us because Philadelphia plays well at home,'' Moon
said Wednesday, showing he already knows what to expect and how the
Hawks should counter.
</P>
<P>
   Moon is right. Not letting the first quarter or the first game
or the season get out of hand is crucial for the Hawks. And we have
all been here before, perched on the edge of a new season where the
coaches and the players all insist we should believe like they do.
</P>
<P>
   This time, if all the big fellas who filed by can do what they
can do, there's no reason not to take the plunge.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
