<HEADER>
A6457 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      09-03 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ The Astros came to Turner Field like a band of snipers
intent on taking their best shots at the team with the best record
in the National League.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Snipers typically take their shots from a secluded area so as
not to be discovered. That was hardly the case with the Astros, who
put their hired gun front and center for all the baseball world _
and particularly the Atlanta Braves _ to see.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson shot holes through the Braves for eight innings
and the Killer B's took target practice against Greg Maddux in a
4-2 Astros victory before a sellout crowd of 46,238 Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had 10 strikeouts and held the Braves to four hits. A
cramp in his left calf kept Johnson from shooting for his fourth
complete game in seven starts with the Astros, but it was nothing
like the pain the Astros caused for Maddux on a muggy night in the
South.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell, Craig Biggio and Sean Berry combined for seven
hits and had a home run apiece to pace a 12-hit attack, 10 of the
hits coming off Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we would have played them like this last year, it would
have been a different story in the playoffs,'' Astros right fielder
Derek Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But last year, the Astros didn't have Johnson, who
offered a preview of what he is capable of doing in a big-game
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy is a marquee pitcher who can match up with anyone,''
catcher Brad Ausmus said. ``We're lucky to have him on our side.
He's been everything we bargained for and more.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Maddux didn't hold up his end of the bargain in the
made-for-TV pitchers' duel, he did give the Braves a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux's performance might have been enough to beat most
pitchers but not Johnson _ especially when Johnson settles into a
grove, which he did Wednesday after a fitful start.
</P>
<P>
   After allowing a run in the first inning and walking three
batters in the first three innings, Johnson regrouped, then
dominated. The Big Unit retired 14 of the final 15 batters he faced
before his calf cramped on his first warm-up pitch of the ninth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is fine,'' Johnson said. ``I must have gotten
dehydrated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no big deal,'' manager Larry Dierker said. ``It loosened
up while we (Dierker and trainer Dave Labossiere) were out there.
Randy wanted to finish the game, but we decided to get him out of
there just in case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he pitched a very tenacious game. In the first three
innings, they weren't swinging and missing at all. He had to fight
to keep them to that one run. Once he settled down, he was pretty
tough on them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves could hardly rejoice in Johnson's exit, because that
opened the door for Billy Wagner. Wagner allowed a solo homer to
Andruw Jones but struck out the final two batters he faced to bag
his 27th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for us not to make too much out of this game,''
Wagner said. ``We still haven't locked anything up.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the NL Central, which the Astros lead by 10
games. The magic number to clinch the division is 13.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have won 12 of their last 15 games and trail Atlanta
by three games for the best record in the NL. Wednesday's game
concluded the season series, which the Astros won 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to be worried about us,'' Wagner said. ``I don't
know how they feel about us, but I know I wouldn't want to play us
in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' offense was almost non-existent in last fall's
playoff series against the Braves, but the bats came alive under
tough circumstances Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It's not often Maddux, a four-time Cy Young Award winner, gives
up 10 hits, four runs and three homers _ it was just the second
three-homer game he has allowed in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg Maddux is probably the best pitcher in baseball, along
with Roger Clemens,'' Johnson said. ``But he's human and he makes
bad pitches just like I make bad pitches. We're not invincible.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's much more intelligent than I am, because he doesn't have
a 95- or 98-mph fastball. I would tell any pitcher who wants to be
successful to watch him, because he's the true definition of a
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're different kind of pitchers, but that doesn't mean we
don't have the same type of approach out there as far as trying to
set up hitters. The one thing I have going for me is that I can
challenge the hitters in a way that he can't because of my
fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   That was evident as Johnson struck out six of the last 10
batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (facing Johnson) is scary,'' said Braves third baseman
Chipper Jones, who struck out three times. ``It's a little
unnerving. He's got some 97-mph cheese coming at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves catcher Javy Lopez, who has been as pesky as a rat
against the Astros this season, took a bite of the cheese in the
first inning with a two-out RBI single to give the Braves a 1-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves tried to be patient, drawing three walks in the first
three innings, and take advantage of Johnson's high leg kick once
they got on base. Atlanta had three stolen bases, including Gerald
Williams' swipe in the first inning that set up the Braves' first
run.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell tied the game in the second with a leadoff homer to
right, and Biggio untied the score in the fifth with a two-run
homer to left.
</P>
<P>
   Berry's solo shot in the seventh put the Astros up by three
runs, which was more than enough with Johnson on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hit them good,'' Maddux said. ``It was like any other
game. I don't think I was up any more or down any more than I
usually am. I was where I wanted to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio said, ``We had a lot of hits, but we didn't score a lot
of runs for the hits we had. That tells you how good Maddux is at
keeping his team in the game. But Randy gave us a better chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of those guys are awesome pitchers with nasty stuff. It
was fun to be out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
