<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT PADRES, 4-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The last thing the New York Mets could have afforded
was a second consecutive loss here on Wednesday night. Not after
the Cubs and Giants had both won earlier on Wednesday. And not with
a four-game extended weekend series coming up against the
first-place Braves, against whom the Mets are 0-5 this season.
</P>
<P>
   But Armando Reynoso _ with a lot of help from Lenny Harris,
Edgardo Alfonzo and Mike Piazza _ gave the Mets a 4-1 victory and
made sure the Mets would fly back to New York for a much-needed day
off still trailing Chicago by one game in the National League
wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso (6-1) shut down the N.L. West-leading San Diego Padres
on four hits over eight innings to win for the sixth time in seven
starts this season. And Harris, Alfonzo and Piazza combined to give
him all the runs he would need with three home runs off Andy Ashby
in the first four innings.
</P>
<P>
   The victory enabled the Mets (77-63) to finish a grueling
nine-day, nine-game West Coast swing with a more-than-respectable
5-4 record. The victory also allowed the Mets to keep pace with the
Cubs and stay a game ahead of the Giants in the postseason chase.
</P>
<P>
   John Franco pitched a scoreless ninth for his 31st save and
390th of his career, tying him with Dennis Eckersley for second
place on the major league career list.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets erased an early 1-0 deficit with home runs by three of
their hottest hitters. Harris began the barrage with his fifth of
the season, all of them in the last 16 games, a solo shot to deep
right field that tied the game at 1-1 in the second.
</P>
<P>
   In the following inning, Alfonzo hit his 15th of the year, a
two-run shot to left. It was his fourth home run in the last five
games and put the Mets up by 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Piazza drilled his 28th homer to right-center leading
off the fourth, which gave Reynoso a comfortable 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The homer was Piazza's seventh in the last 13 games. For the
nine-game road trip, he was a sizzling 15 for 28 (.536) with five
homers and 12 runs batted in. The month has only begun, but if the
the All-Star catcher can approach the September he had last season,
when he hit .406 with eight home runs and 27 runs batted in for the
Dodgers, the Mets will greatly improve their chances of reaching
the post-season for the first time since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso lowered his earned run average to 2.64 over 472/3
innings by recording all but two of his 24 outs on infield plays or
on strikeouts (he had six while walking three). The way he is
pitching, Manager Bobby Valentine will find it difficult to leave
the 32-year-old right-hander out of his playoff rotation, should
the Mets qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso allowed a two-out home run to Tony Gwynn in the bottom
of the first to give Gwynn four hits in as many at-bats since he
came back from the disabled list. But Reynoso then settled down and
outpitched the right-hander Andy Ashby (16-7), who has had three
rough outings in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso, who scored on Alfonzo's home run after grounding
sharply into a fielder's choice in the third, doubled hard off
Ashby to open the fifth. And even though Ashby _ who allowed four
runs on four hits in his five innings _ escaped the fifth without
allowing another run, Manager Bruce Bochy pinch-hit for him in the
bottom of the inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
