<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6471 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORST-SCHOOLS-LADN     09-03 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORST-SCHOOLS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. SCHOOL DISTRICT TO LAUNCH ACCOUNTABILITY PLAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERRI HARDY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Superintendent Ruben Zacarias announced that more
than two-thirds of the 100 worst-performing schools in Los Angeles
increased their test scores, then said he would be implementing a
massive districtwide accountability plan modeled on that success.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, all schools in the Los Angeles Unified School
District would be expected to show improvement on yearly
achievement tests. If they fail, they face progressive intervention
and sanctions, including staff dismissals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never been anything like this in the history of Los
Angeles Unified,'' Zacarias said after a news conference Wednesday
at an elementary school in suburban South Central. ``Why should we
be different from the private sector? It's all about
accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   The reform effort is based on stringent new guidelines Zacarias
created for the 100 lowest-performing schools, including six in
L.A.'s San Fernando Valley, named on a list a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But implementation of the plan might not be as smooth as the
superintendent hopes. While the push for boosting student
performance was lauded in some quarters, Zacarias' plan was derided
by union officials.
</P>
<P>
   Day Higuchi, president of United Teachers Los Angeles, said the
plan lacks substance and was not discussed with teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This came out of left field,'' he said. ``What did the
superintendent do, read some book on reform over the weekend and
make up a plan?''
</P>
<P>
   Higuchi said drastic measures proposed by Zacarias would have to
be negotiated with the union.
</P>
<P>
   Eli Brent, president of Associated Administrators of Los
Angeles, said the plan makes principals but not teachers
responsible for failure at the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not against accountability, but I'm for spelling out that
everyone, including teachers, is responsible,'' Brent said. ``But
the LAUSD won't do it because the teachers will have a fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Zacarias made the campaign to boost student
performance at the 100 worst-performing schools the cornerstone of
his reform effort. The schools were required to set improvement
goals and write action plans. They were given $10 million for
remedial programs.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Zacarias said 68 schools raised their test scores
and 30 showed declines or no progress. ``We've seen significant
improvements,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Glenwood Elementary School in suburban Van Nuys showed one of
the most significant leaps -- 12 percentile points.
</P>
<P>
   Principal &UR;  &LR; Diane Agliam said she and her staff have been
focusing on improving literacy for years and are starting to see a
payoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone feels elated that our hard work and diligence has
shown in our test scores,'' Agliam said. ``The challenge now is to
maintain that and continue to improve.''
</P>
<P>
   The schools where scores improved -- some bounded ahead as much
as 18 percentile points -- did so without additional money. The $10
million for remedial programs was funneled to the schools after
students took their achievement tests in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Test scores were based on a composite of the Stanford 9
achievement test, which is a statewide test taken in English, and
its Spanish-language equivalent, the Aprenda.
</P>
<P>
   Schools were also evaluated on decreases in the dropout rate and
increases in six other performance indicators, the number of
students transferred from bilingual to English-language classes,
student attendance, teacher attendance, parent involvement, the
number of students passing college-preparatory classes and the
number of Advanced Placement classes offered.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the information has been analyzed, Zacarias outlined a
step-by-step plan for the 100 schools. The same process will be
used at the rest of the district's campuses after Zacarias and his
staff agree on details.
</P>
<P>
   The 65 campuses on the list that increased test scores and
improved on at least half of their other success indicators were
classified as ``Category 1'' schools. That included four of the six
listed schools in the San Fernando Valley: Glenwood, Broadous
Elementary, Cohasset Elementary and Maclay Middle.
</P>
<P>
   These schools will continue to receive additional resources for
another year, review what worked in their plans to share with the
rest of the district and modify areas that were not as successful.
They were given a $5,000 reward to spend on student achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Category 2'' schools are campuses where scores improved, but
did not see progress on 50 percent of their seven goals. Three of
the 100 schools were in this group. None were in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, ``Category 3'' schools are campuses that did not
improve test scores and are placed on ``academic probation.'' Of
the 31 schools in the 100 that fell in this group, two are in the
Valley: Pacoima Elementary and Olive Vista Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   Each school in this group will be required to rewrite its
academic improvement plan and get it approved by parents, as well
as the regional administrator and assistant superintendent assigned
to the area.
</P>
<P>
   The campuses have to submit a quarterly progress report and a
midterm evaluation by the assistant superintendent. They will also
continue to receive the same stipend for remedial education from
the district.
</P>
<P>
   If these schools don't improve by the end of the 1998-99 year,
they will be placed under ``receivership.'' That means their local
decision-making on budget, hiring and curricula will be suspended
and they will come under the direct supervision of the assistant
superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   If improvement is not made in another year, the school will face
total reorganization, including personnel changes, Zacarias said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Roos, president of Los Angeles Educational Alliance for
Restructuring Now, applauded Zacarias' efforts, even though LEARN
tenets stress local decision-making, authority that could be lost
under the superintendent's plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, some sanctions for nonperformers,'' Roos said. ``On
balance, I think this is a terrific step forward for measurable
accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Governor's Office, where Pete Wilson fought
unsuccessfully for a statewide school accountability plan with
teeth, officials lauded Zacarias' plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased the district is taking the lead on reform,''
said Rich Halberg, education spokesman for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent budget battles, Wilson withheld millions in
education funding to force lawmakers to come up with a statewide
plan. But Halberg said the legislative bill that was passed ``had
no teeth'' and was likely to be vetoed.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
