<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEREZ STOPS PHILLIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Carlos Perez is rooting for Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   So there to start the third inning of Wednesday's 6-0 victory
over the Philadelphia Phillies, Perez walked to the plate, then
stopped to watch baseball's biggest story.
</P>
<P>
   It's a strange sort of pause at Dodger Stadium these days, the
nightly race between Sosa, Perez's fellow Dominican countryman, and
Mark McGwire for Roger Maris home run record that is displayed on
the video screen in left field.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive night, the game was momentarily
delayed. Sosa and McGwire combined for three homers Wednesday and
the highlights carried over into the Dodgers game.
</P>
<P>
   This is much more important than Perez's search for his first
victory as a Dodger, which he got by limiting the Phillies to just
two hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is history,'' said Dodgers center fielder Raul Mondesi,
also Dominican. ``We are all watching Sammy and McGwire.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers fans, who numbered 32,630 on Wednesday, haven't had much
to cheer this season. But they did get the chance to watch a pretty
good game.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, who entered the game with the second-worst run support in
the National League, got home runs from Matt Luke and Eric Karros.
</P>
<P>
   He even scored a run and got another on an RBI single by Mark
Grudzielanek, who came over with him in the July 31 trade from
Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Although he walked two batters in the ninth inning, Perez got a
double-play ground ball to end the game and record his first
shutout in exactly one year.
</P>
<P>
   Perez came in with three losses and three no-decisions in six
starts with the Dodgers, but he should have won his last game.
</P>
<P>
   That was the 5-4 loss to the New York Mets last Friday, when he
gave way to Scott Radinsky in the seventh inning and Radinsky
immediately allowed a game-tying three-run homer to John Olerud.
</P>
<P>
   But Perez also had battled control problems and even went to
team doctors to have his non-pitching shoulder examined.
</P>
<P>
   A week before coming to the Dodgers, Perez was involved in an
auto accident that broke his nose and injured his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   It has affected his usually good control, but Wednesday, he got
ahead of hitters and walked only three.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, who had three complete games with the Expos, also gave
the tired Dodgers bullpen the night off.
</P>
<P>
   Setup man Antonio Osuna is gone for the year with bone chips in
his right elbow. Mark Guthrie has a sore left elbow.
</P>
<P>
   And closer Jeff Shaw, who allowed a monster home run to Bobby
Estalella to open the ninth on Tuesday, is tired and slumping.
</P>
<P>
   Perez (8-13) allowed his first hit to second baseman Mark Lewis
with one out in the second. The other was by right fielder Kevin
Sefcik, who singled with one out in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Luke has been starting in right since Gary Sheffield was lost
for the season with a left ankle sprain.
</P>
<P>
   He was 1 for 6 with one RBI in the first two games but hit a 2-1
fastball by right-hander Tyler Green (6-9) into the right-field
stands for his 10th homer.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers added two in the fifth when Roger Cedeno, getting a
rare start in left, doubled home Perez, who walked, and scored on a
single by Grudzielanek.
</P>
<P>
   Karros had a chance for a two-run homer in the first, but Sefcik
went back to the wall in right to make the catch.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, though, Karros hit the first pitch by Phillies
reliever Mike Grace into the right-field stands.
</P>
<P>
   For Karros, it was his 21st homer and 79th RBI.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers made it 6-0 in the eighth when Mondesi ripped a
two-run single past Phillies third baseman Scott Rolen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
