A6486 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     09-03 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS END TRIP WITH WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ It was supposed to be the road trip from hell, but
the Angels returned home with their halo intact even though one of
them clipped a wing.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels routed the Cleveland Indians 13-5 before a sellout
crowd of 43,200 at Jacobs Field on Wednesday night, completing
their trip to New York, Boston and Cleveland with a 6-4 record.
</P>
<P>
   They left town Aug. 23 with a 2{-game lead over the Texas
Rangers in the AL West, took three of five from the Yankees, two of
three from the Red Sox, split two with the Indians and maintained
that 2{-game lead.
</P>
<P>
   About the only bad news for the Angels was the hamstring injury
suffered by Darin Erstad in the first inning Wednesday. Erstad was
on the disabled list Aug. 4-18 with a strained left hamstring, and
he re-injured the same hamstring in the same spot running to first
base on a two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad, who grabbed the back of his leg and appeared to be in
severe pain as he hobbled to first on what would have been a
double, will be examined by Dr. Lewis Yocum today. Trainer Ned
Bergert said he could not estimate how long Erstad will be out
until after Erstad is examined and has an MRI.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Erstad was in no mood to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until I know the diagnosis, there's no use talking about it,''
he said. ``I just don't feel like talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad's injury, in fact, left the entire bench quiet. It wasn't
until shortstop Gary DiSarcina spoke up that the players got their
heads back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said `Let's go, we've got a game to play,''' DiSarcina said.
``It's an old subject with this team. Honestly, I'm sick of talking
about it. It's something we've grown accustomed to. It's nothing
against Darin, but let's move on. Guys have been getting hurt the
whole year.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina, however, admitted seeing Erstad's reaction had an
impact on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darin's not the type of person that shows a lot of pain,'' he
said. ``Obviously he appeared to be in pain, so the guys were in
shock over it. It's sick to say, but you've got to be professional
about it and play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Erstad's injury, the Angels come home feeling pretty
good about themselves. If there was any doubt about this team's
character, it seemed to be answered in the past 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't show me anything I didn't expect, but they did
show me things you're really happy to see,'' Angels manager Terry
Collins said. ``They met all the pressure of the road trip and
didn't back off a bit. As a matter of fact, they enjoyed the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   As satisfied as they are with their performance on the trip,
Collins says it's time to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can say, `OK, we had a good trip. Now what's the next
challenge?''' he said. ``That is to have a good homestand, try to
beat Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels jumped out to a big lead off Indians starter Bartolo
Colon (13-8), getting two runs in the first inning on Erstad's
single, and five more in second, including Jim Edmonds' three-run
homer.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had 21 hits in all, matching their season high set
June 13 against Texas. Gregg Jefferies and Randy Velarde each had
four hits, while Chris Pritchett _ filling in at first base for
Erstad _ and Edmonds had three hits apiece.
</P>
<P>
   All the offense made things easy for Angels starter Steve
Sparks, who pitched into the seventh inning for the seventh time in
his past nine starts.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks (9-2) gave up five runs and eight hits in 62/3 innings to
earn his sixth consecutive win, but it was bittersweet with
Erstad's injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited about the big win and finishing up the road
trip, but it's all on a sour note,'' DH Tim Salmon said. ``That's
the one thing that's keeping this from being an exciting road trip.
This team's had a lot of experience with these kinds of things. You
kind of wonder if we play better because of the things that have
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you want to have everybody out there in the last
month,'' pitcher Chuck Finley said. ``We lost me last year and what
happened to DiSar a couple years before (1995). You hope it isn't
that bad and we get him back in a couple weeks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
