<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSAIR-CRASH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISSAIR JET CRASHES OFF COAST OF NOVA SCOTIA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout)  (sw) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Swissair plane carrying 227 passengers and crew crashed late
on Wednesday night south of Halifax, Nova Scotia, while on a flight
from Kennedy International Airport in New York to Switzerland, U.S.
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Eyewitnesses and early reports indicated that the plane had
crashed in the Atlantic Ocean, seven miles off the coast and 40
miles south of Halifax. There were conflicting reports about
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Two Halifax newspapers quoted rescue officials as saying that
bodies were pulled from the water, debris and oil slicks had been
spotted in the cold, dark waters, and that an overpowering smell of
jet fuel lingered in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hearing there are no initial signs of survivors,'' said
Bob Burgess, an editor with the Halifax Chronicle-Herald. ``They
are pulling bodies out of the water.''
</P>
<P>
   One official with the Canadian Maritime Operation Center in
Halifax said that the pilot of the flight, No. 111, reported that a
fire had broken out in the cockpit at around 10:30 p.m. Atlantic
Standard Time (9:30 p.m., ET)
</P>
<P>
   Another official, Navy Seaman Sean Kelly, a spokesman for the
Halifax Rescue Coordination Center, said that the plane, which had
been flying over the Atlantic and was carrying 227 passengers and
crew, was then instructed to veer 300 miles to the northwest to
make an emergency landing in Halifax. But airport officials lost
the plane on the radar seven nautical miles south of Peggy's Cove,
near Blandford, a fishing village known as a tourist attraction for
its rugged coastal beauty.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson for Swiss Air, in a statement, said that the
plane had apparently dumped fuel on its way down.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Furman, an official with the National Transportation Safety
Board in Washington, said that the plane had crashed, but that its
exact location was not known.
</P>
<P>
   Eyewitnesses reported hearing a series of frightening sounds on
what had been a placid, moonless night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard an aircraft,'' said Mieke Martin, the proprietor of
the Century House Bed and Breakfast in Blandford, who was lying in
bed with her husband when the hotel began to rumble. ``It was very
low and it had irregular sounds coming from it. It didn't sound
right, like a helicopter sound, or like it was tearing the sky
apart. Seconds later it crashed. There was no explosion. It hit
like a thud. It went into the water.''
</P>
<P>
   She paused. ``I started to think `Oh my God. Those people.' I
knew it went in. I whispered a prayer, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   By early Thursday morning, Canadian officials had dispatched a
Hercules aircraft, two Labrador helicopters and two naval vessels
to search the area. The fishing fleet from the small island
community of 57 people was also out in force, combing the cold
Atlantic for any signs of life, or death. But with the sky
overcast, and no stars or moon to illuminate the horizon, people
involved in the rescue reported that it was hard to see to much of
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in Washington, the National Transportation Safety Board
appeared to be working under the assumption that there had been a
crash. Officials said that the agency would dispatch an 11-member
team to Halifax at 5 on Thursday morning to assist Canadian
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the NTSB said that if there indeed was a crash, it
was not clear whose jurisdiction it was. If it was in international
waters, the Swiss would be in charge of the investigation, because
the MD-11 was registered in that country; if it was within Canadian
territorial waters, then Canada would be in charge.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, by international treaty, the United States would
be involved in the investigation, because the plane was built in
California and the flight originated in New York.
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, the U.S. Navy has extensive experience in
retrieving wreckage and the flight data recorder and cockpit voice
recorder of such planes. Those ``black boxes'' carry pingers that
are activated by water and send out audio signals so they can be
easily located.
</P>
<P>
   The MD-11 is built by Boeing and is produced in Long Beach,
Calif., at its Douglas Products Division. The plane, which first
went into production in 1988 is the world's only large wide-cabin
trijet, with engines mounted on the tail and under each wing. It
features a sophisticated flight deck and advanced automatic system
controls that significantly reduces pilot workload, according to
company literature.
</P>
<P>
   The plane is a modernized version of the DC-10, which also
features the trijet configuration. It is considered the latest
generation in the family line of the DC models, which dates back to
the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   The name was dropped after two cataclysmic crashes in the 1970s,
one in Paris in 1974, the other in Chicago in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   As for Wednesday night's flight, Terry Benczik, a spokeswoman
for the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, said that the
plane took off at 8:19 p.m., and that ``it was a normal routine
takeoff.''
</P>
<P>
   But the other end was a different story.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Farmer, 57, a librarian who lives in Blandford, said she
and her husband, Fraser, 59, an engineer, heard the plane fly
overhead but paid no attention because plane noises were
commonplace in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the engine started sputtering,'' she said. ``Then there
was an explosion as it hit the water I guess although it wasn't
really a sound. It was more a big vibration as if somebody was
shaking the house.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 0205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
