A6500 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN     09-03 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD INJURES HAMSTRING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Angels might be faced with losing Darin Erstad
for the rest of the regular season after the first baseman strained
his left hamstring in the first inning Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad sliced a groundball inside third and down the left-field
line to drive in the Angels' first two runs of the game. But
instead of reaching second easily with a double, he was in obvious
pain as he struggled to reach first base, holding the back of his
leg.
</P>
<P>
   It is the same hamstring Erstad injured Aug. 3 and forced him
onto the disabled list for 15 days. But Erstad's reaction Wednesday
seemed to indicate this time it was worse. He needed help off the
field from trainer Ned Bergert and pitcher Ken Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad will be examined today by Angels medical director Dr.
Lewis Yocum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look good, no,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said.
``There was a lot (of pain). It seems worse (than the injury last
month).''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Collins said Chris Pritchett and Gregg
Jefferies will split time at first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do what we've done all year long,'' Collins said. ``And
that is somebody will step up and get the job done. The big
difference is this is when you need your No. 1 guys. It's
September, not June. He's one of our best players on the team. We
have to hitch the wagons to somebody else and get after it.''
</P>
<P>
   No excuses: The Angels fell apart in 1995 after shortstop Gary
DiSarcina was injured, and the same thing happened last season
after injuries to Chuck Finley and Todd Greene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not use it as an excuse,'' DiSarcina said of Erstad's
injury. ``We played without him in August for two weeks and we can
play without him in September. We played well in August. To use it
as a crutch is stupid. It's a copout. I don't want anyone to say
`Erstad got hurt in September and we couldn't clinch without
him.'''
</P>
<P>
   Finley flat: The Angels are happy with the way they played on
their East Coast road trip, but it's difficult to imagine they did
it without much help from their top starting pitcher Chuck Finley.
</P>
<P>
   Though Finley received two no-decisions in his two starts on the
trip, the Angels lost both games _ 6-5 to the Yankees in 11 innings
on Aug. 28 and 7-6 to the Indians on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the two games, Finley pitched a total of 91/3 innings,
allowing eight runs and 16 hits. Hardly the numbers you'd expect
from your ace.
</P>
<P>
   ``My last start in New York I was tired,'' said Finley, who
pitched on three days rest against the Yankees. ``I was doing what
I could to get through it. (Tuesday) I felt great. I've got to
figure a way to get guys out. My fastball was a little flat.
There's no angle on the ball. It's flat in the zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley said it's a mechanical flaw that he's dealt with in the
past and can be corrected before his next start _ Sunday against
the Royals in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his occasional struggles this season, as well as being
hit twice by line drives on the mound and once in the dugout,
Finley is still among the American League's best pitchers. He ranks
third in the league with a 3.20 ERA, is tied for second in games
started with 30, is fourth in strikeouts with 186 and is ninth in
opponents' batting average at .244.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just been trying to grind it out all year,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
