<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY SHUTS OUT DALLAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ With their defense, bloodied four nights
earlier, back to its dominating best, and the net no stranger to
their attack, the Los Angeles Galaxy got back on track Wednesday
night, destroying what's left of the Dallas Burn before the
smallest Rose Bowl crowd of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Their 3-0 romp, before an announced crowd of 9,113 that appeared
half that, wasn't enough to deliver the Western Conference title
the Chicago Fire forgot to do their part but it gave the Galaxy
(21-7) a Major League Soccer record 61 points and made last
weekend's dreadful loss to Columbus just a memory.
</P>
<P>
   Cobi Jones, MLS's scoring leader, had a goal and an assist, and
Mauricio Cienfuegos and Carlos Hermosillo also tallied as the
Galaxy, finding plenty of space to work with all evening, hammered
the Burn to move within one victory, or one Fire loss, of claiming
its second Western regular-season crown in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to the playoffs, if you drop a game, you face
elimination,'' said Danny Pea, who spearheaded a Galaxy defensive
effort that allowed the Burn (13-15, 31 points) just one shot on
target. ``At this stage of the season, that's the mentality we need
to have: Come back (from losses) and dominate. That's what we
wanted to do tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit again the defense, which surrendered perhaps a half-dozen
scoring opportunities over the span of four one-sided victories
that ended with the 3-0 loss Saturday to Columbus. The Burn, which
was missing three starters four if you count Alain Sutter, who
hasn't played since April create only two decent opportunities as
the Galaxy notched their fifth shutout of season despite losing
captain Robin Fraser to contact lens trouble in the 53rd minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The games might seem easy,'' said Galaxy coach Octavio
Zambrano, ``but we have to look at every game the same and play
100percent. We have a lot to play for finishing first in the
Western Conference that's out main objective, what really
matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Any hope of winning the West on Wednesday disappeared when
Chicago beat Miami, 3-2, on an 83rd-minute goal had it gone to
shootout, the race would have been over but L.A. can clinch it on
Saturday in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos got the first goal, his 13th of the season, in the
29th minute, with Jones picking up an assist to break a tie in the
scoring table with New England's Raul Diaz Arce. Jones' throw-in,
from deep on the left wing, found Greg Vanney streaking past Temoc
Suarez into the box. Vanney's cross found a diving Cienfuegos,
whose sharp seven-yard header caromed off goalkeeper Mark Dodd's
hands en route to the net.
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo netted his fifth in the 54th minute, knocking home a
rebound after Dodd whose phenomenal play in the nets kept the score
much closer than it should have been dove to knock down a 21-yard
blast from Martin Machon.
</P>
<P>
   Jones picked up his 17th goal in 20 games giving him 46 points,
three more than Diaz Arce in the 70th, stripping Brian Haynes on
the right flank, taking the ball into the box and beating Dodd from
10 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn, which was without suspended defender Chad Deering and
midfielder Jason Kreis and injured midfielder Mark Santel, fell
four points behind third-place Colorado in the West but held onto
its two-point lead over Kansas City a 3-2 loser to the Rapids for
the conference's final playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   GALAXY NOTES: Official word is expected late this week or early
next on English-language radio coverage of Galaxy games. L.A. and
One-On-One Sports (1540 AM) are on the verge of an agreement,
Galaxy general manager Danny Villanueva confirmed, for the
remainder of this season and all of the 1999 season. Wednesday's
game was to have been the first broadcast, but there were problems
with some of the contract language. If the agreement is finalized
in time, Saturday's game at Miami might be aired; otherwise, the
coverage will debut Sept.16 at San Jose. Kevin Wall and Rick Davis,
L.A.'s television announcing team, is expected to handle the radio
duties as well. ... KTNQ (1020) will continue as the Galaxy's
Spanish-language station. ... The Galaxy, its anticipated fall
schedule dead with the cancellation of Copa Merconorte, is looking
to play two home exhibitions after the MLS season is over, likely
against Mexican clubs. Three of Mexico's best America, Necaxa and
Guadalajara owe L.A. a game. Villanueva also has talked to with the
Merconorte organizers, Buenos Aires-bases Teledeportes, about
playing in tournaments in Argentina or Chile. ... Defender Paul
Caligiuri missed his second successive game after aggravating a
groin strain in training Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
