<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6528 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-MEYSAN-LADN     09-03 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-MEYSAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEYSAN: BEAUTY MINUS CROWDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONE PINE _ It's been called ``the red-headed stepchild of the
Mount Whitney Trail.''
</P>
<P>
   Long overshadowed by its neighboring world-famous hike to the
highest point in the lower 48 states, Meysan Lakes Trail is in many
ways more difficult, more pristine and certainly less traveled.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Sunday, Doug Davis of West Hills, his 14-year-old
son Sean and another backpacking companion hoofed the Meysan trail
that leads to its namesake lakes. ``It's a nice spot because it's
out of the way,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the way, that is, of the masses searching for the glory
in scaling 14,494-foot Mount Whitney. Those who have trekked the
Mount Whitney Trail know it can be a zoo.
</P>
<P>
   But just a short way from the Whitney trailhead at Whitney
Portal is the outset of underappreciated _ and underestimated _
Meysan Lakes Trail. It's right there on the maps and its trailhead
is clearly flagged on Whitney Portal Road, but hikers must be
blinded to it by the daunting face of Whitney. I was as guilty as
anyone; during my two ascents of Whitney and several excursions to
the portal, I never noticed them.
</P>
<P>
   Meysan Lakes Trail was named after Felix Meysan, whose family
moved to Lone Pine in 1869 and who stocked the lakes with trout in
the 1920s. Starting at an elevation of 7,900 feet, the footpath
climbs 3,300 feet in 4.7 miles before first cresting out at
picturesque Grass Lakes, which is cradled between Lone Pine Peak,
Mounts LeConte, Mallory and Irvine and Candlelight Peak. That's an
ascent of just over 700 feet per mile.
</P>
<P>
   While much longer and higher, the 10.7-mile hump to Whitney
climbs more than 650 feet a mile. So, clearly, the Meysan Lakes
Trail is on par with its arduous brethren; and, for those planning
to attempt Whitney, it provides an excellent opportunity to
acclimate to the High Sierra's rigors and rarefied environs.
</P>
<P>
   Chris and Terry Robbins, who work on tanks at Fort Irwin
Military Reservation northeast of Barstow, found out the hard way
that Meysan Lakes Trail is strenuous. ``I tell you, it would be
neat to have something motorized to go up this thing,'' Terry
Robbins said. The pair packed in too much gear and fell well short
of their aim of camping at Meysan Lake, never reaching their goal
even on a side trip the next day.
</P>
<P>
   While the Whitney trail offers highlights such as Lone Pine
Creek, Lone Pine Lake and Mirror Lake, Meysan Lakes Trail counters
with exquisite Meysan Creek and Grass Lakes, with their mesmerizing
reflective quality and mossy perimeter that one hiker likened to
``walking in a vat of grapes.'' En route is Little Meysan Lake _
visible only from the surrounding mountains _ and 11,500-foot
Meysan Lake proper, which lies above Grass Lakes via a faint
half-mile path scratched into a rocky slope.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what Meysan Lakes Trail doesn't have is the dozens and
dozens of visitors that diminish the appeal of the Mount Whitney
Trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons we chose (Meysan Lakes) was that
(overnight) wilderness permits are available on fairly short
notice,'' Davis said. In fact, the Robbinses secured a backcountry
camping document the day before their journey; that's practically
unheard of for a Whitney trail permit, for which day-trippers and
backpackers alike must often apply six months in advance.
</P>
<P>
   From Whitney Portal's lower campground, the Meysan Lakes Trail
rises quickly past scrub oak, sage and an impressive set of summer
houses. Meysan Creek carves a deep and narrow gulch far below the
course of 96 switchbacks that direct followers to Grass Lakes. The
creek's cool flows are enticing as the reflective heat from the
canyon's granite cliffs fills the air upon entering the John Muir
Wilderness. Trees thicken initially before they thin out at higher
elevations; Davis spotted various firs and lodgepole, Jeffrey and
foxtail pines before he and his son scaled 12,944-foot Lone Pine
Peak, which, from Whitney's summit, appears as a solitary and
stalwart sentry.
</P>
<P>
   At a shady spot in the trail, our hiking trio met a group of
four returning from a two-day fishing trip to Meysan Lake. There
they landed 63 brook trout on two rods, releasing all but six that
wound up in the frying pan. Most were caught on Super Duper, Mepps,
Kastmaster lures and measured in the 11- to 12-inch range,
according to Darrell Sausser of Riverside. ``I thought they were a
little smaller,'' quipped fellow Riverside resident John Young.
``We got to get our stories straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Trout do tend to get bigger on the way home, I told them.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of Indian paint brush give way to precipitous talus as
the trail makes its final push to Grass Lakes. Here the vantage of
13,700-foot Mount Irvine, with its telltale pyramid silhouette, is
unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   Break for lunch, then it's a speedy excursion back to the
portal, with expansive views of the Owens Valley and the Alabama
Hills along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Only 15 people were passed on the Meysan Lakes Trail during our
six-hour adventure. It may not have the glory of the Mount Whitney
Trail, but it doesn't have the glitz, either.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU'RE GOING &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Meysan Lakes Trailhead is found at Whitney Portal, 12 miles
west of Lone Pine on Whitney Portal Road.
</P>
<P>
   Camping is available either on a first-come, first-served basis
and limited to one night's stay or by reservation. Sites are $12
per night. For reservations, call (800) 280-2267. An $8.65
processing fee is charged.
</P>
<P>
   Information for overnight backcountry permits is the same as the
Cottonwood Lakes Basin.
</P>
<P>
   The trail is found on the Mount Langley 7.5-minute series
topographic map.
</P>
<P>
   Allow six hours to complete hike to Grass Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   More details: (760) 876-6200. &QL; 
_Brett Pauly
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
