<HEADLINE>
GOODBYE TO VERO BEACH?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dodgers' threats to leave their spring training site of 50
years in Vero Beach, Fla., have begun to take shape.
</P>
<P>
   The club has contacted officials in Arizona and been approached
by the city of Las Vegas, which is planning to build a $50 million
spring training facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just exploring our options,'' said Dodgers spokesman
Derrick Hall. ``But we are the only team that privately owns and
operates our own spring training facility and that costs a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers celebrated their 50th year in Vero Beach this past
spring. The club's property was part of the $311 million sale from
the O'Malley family to Rupert Murdoch's NewsCorp.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, it was the jewel of spring training facilities, but
competition from nearby cities has drained much of the town's
spring fan base.
</P>
<P>
   Fox also has expressed an interest in moving the club's training
camp closer to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   What also makes the move attractive is that the cities are
willing to put up the money to build the facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said there is no timetable and that Vero Beach has not been
ruled out for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Faith hasn't waned: Roger Cedeno, the projected Opening Day
center fielder, made just his 35th start Wednesday night, not
exactly what the Dodgers had in mind for a one-time top prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno, who had an RBI double and scored before leaving
Wednesday's game with dizziness, never got on track after missing
the first month with a strained left hamstring. But the club says
it is not through with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of teams interested in him (at the trade
deadline), but I wouldn't let him go,'' interim GM Tom Lasorda
said. ``He's young (24), he can run and he's a switch hitter. Those
kinds of guys can be harder to find than the big names.''
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi is the center fielder of the future. That means
only spot starts and pinch hitting for Cedeno. He entered
Wednesday's game batting .243 in 86 games and leads the club with
eight hits and five RBI off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   With Mondesi locked up for the next three years and right
fielder Gary Sheffield the next five, Cedeno's only chance to start
next year is left field, where the Dodgers hope to acquire an
established left-handed bat during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Most concede the biggest drawback in Cedeno's development is a
lack of baseball instincts. He has hurt the club several times with
lapses in judgment on the bases and in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems is he doesn't maintain the confidence he
has playing winter ball or in spring training when he gets here,''
coach Joe Amalfitano said. ``And unfortunately, the expectations of
playing in L.A. do not allow him to learn on the job. We do not
have the luxury of time here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberthal off DL: Phillies catcher Mike Lieberthal, the former
Westlake High standout, came off the disabled list Wednesday, but
it is unlikely he will play again this season because of a stress
fracture in his pelvic region.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberthal, 26, had a breakout season last year with 20 homers
and 77 RBI. Now, he is behind starter Bobby Estalella, backup Mark
Parent, callup Gary Bennett and emergency catcher Ruben Amaro, an
outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``There probably is a one-in-a-thousand chance that he will
play,'' Phillies manager Terry Francona said.
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance Lieberthal still could need surgery, but his
condition has improved since the Dodgers were in Philadelphia in
late July. He now can squat and swing a bat but has trouble
running.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lieberthal will be in uniform for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have my spikes on just in case,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
