<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH FIESTA, ROSE NOT AS SWEET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cade McNown's arm is fine, it's his mind that needs a little
rewiring.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA quarterback has been programmed to spend New Year's Day
in Pasadena for so long, he keeps throwing attention to the Rose
Bowl even though an even better target is breaking free a few yards
farther down the field.
</P>
<P>
   When McNown, wiggling to escape the clutches of any Heisman
Trophy hype, says his real motivation is to get seventh-ranked UCLA
back to the Rose Bowl, his intention isn't to sell the Bruins
short, even if that is sort of like Earl Watson vowing to lead the
Bruins basketball team to the N.I.T.
</P>
<P>
   McNown can be forgiven for finding a rain-slicked football
easier to grasp than the fact the Rose Bowl, long the grand-prize
float in the parade of postseason games, is no better than a
runner-up in this year's procession.
</P>
<P>
   It's blasphemous but true: for any Pacific-10 or Big Ten team
harboring national championship aspirations, Pasadena might as well
be Dubuque, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The Fiesta Bowl is party central this season, with Sun Devil
Stadium the appointed site of the showdown between the No. 1 and
No. 2-ranked teams. College football's latest alliance, the Bowl
Championship Series, was forged this year so the Pac-10 and Big Ten
wouldn't systematically be denied a dance with the belle of the
ball as Michigan was last year and Arizona State the year before
that.
</P>
<P>
   So what happens? No sooner is Pasadena placed on the back burner
(January 2002) for a national-title game then Ohio State, Michigan,
Arizona State and UCLA all find their way into the top-10 in the
national preseason rankings, giving rise to the possibility the
Jan.4 title game could end up looking an awful lot like Rose Bowl
games of yore.
</P>
<P>
   Top-ranked Ohio State battling eighth-ranked ASU for all the
marbles while fifth-ranked Michigan duels UCLA for all the roses?
Stranger things could happen.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, the championship matchup we'd clamor to see
is UCLA against ASU. They're arguably the two top teams in the
Pac-10 but for the second consecutive season they're not scheduled
to play each other. Who's arranging these conference games anyway,
Bob Arum?
</P>
<P>
   ``Cade and I were talking about that earlier,'' ASU wide
receiver Lenzie Jackson said during Pac-10 media day. ``I wish we
had a chance to play each other. It's impossible to say who is the
best team in the Pac-10 if the best teams in the conference don't
meet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils may end up being sorrier not to see the Bruins
than the other way around; if the two schools do wind up sharing
the conference crown, UCLA will get the Rose Bowl bid (barring an
invitation to the Fiesta Bowl) because the Sun Devils have been to
Pasadena since the Bruins' last postseason appearance there, in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   If UCLA or ASU falters, a sneaky-good Arizona team could become
the seventh Pac-10 representative in the Rose Bowl in as many
years. Don't laugh; if Northwestern can represent the Big Ten, why
not the Pac-10's Wildcats?
</P>
<P>
   Goodness knows Arizona has been patient. It is theonly school
in the Pac-10 that hasn't experienced the pomp and pageantry of
Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing quite like it, if you ask Northwestern coach
Gary Barnett. ``A mystical experience'' is what Barnett called his
Wildcats' 1996 trip to the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do anything ethical to get back there,'' added Barnett,
who has mixed feelings about the Pac-10 and Big Ten letting other
teams in to trample on their holy ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a traditionalist,'' Barnett explained. ``I'd hate to give
up the Rose Bowl to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona coach Dick Tomey also loved the Rose Bowl just the way
she was, even if she had given his Wildcats the slip these past 11
years. And yet Tomey endorsed her face lift, having recognized the
Rose Bowl's rich tradition was getting him only so far in the
living rooms of recruits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's been a lot of attention paid to the (Bowl)
Alliance,'' said Tomey, who has been in Tucson so long, we're
pretty sure he pre-dates fajitas. ``The Rose Bowl needed to be part
of it. It's important for recruiting to be able to tell players
they have a chance to compete directly for the national
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   What could be better than to show them? UCLA's McNown might be
the one to do it, so long as he remembers the road he's looking for
is the Interstate 10-East toward Phoenix, not the 210-East headed
for Pasadena. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 0329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
