<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 03:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6579 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     09-03 1422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOLEDO'S TIMING PERFECT THUS FAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The interview would change the course of UCLA football, yet the
participants are foggy on details.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Toledo does not remember what he wore _ suit? sport coat? _
and athletic director Peter Dalis could not recall the date. Was it
before the 1995 Aloha Bowl, or after?
</P>
<P>
   For 30 minutes, they discussed Toledo's candidacy for the vacant
head coaching position. (Terry Donahue had resigned several weeks
earlier.) At the time, Dalis was in hot pursuit of Northwestern's
Gary Barnett after an unsuccessful attempt to lure Rick Neuheisel
from Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   But Toledo's interview went well, better than Dalis expected.
They talked about what the stagnating program needed and why Toledo
was the man to deliver. He talked about his coaching philosophy
(attack, attack, attack) and his tough-love approach to dealing
with players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a real good feeling about Bob, more than anyone I've
ever interviewed for a head coaching position,'' Dalis said
recently.
</P>
<P>
   When Barnett said no, Toledo was next on the list. Dalis'
optimism was high, his expectations modest. The Bruins were 40-29
with Donahue in the '90s, and Dalis believed a return to national
prominence would take four years, perhaps five or six.
</P>
<P>
   But not this.
</P>
<P>
   Not two.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes longer to cycle up than it does to cycle down,''
Dalis said. ``But Bob is way ahead of schedule. He has exceeded my
expectations.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two years after his hiring, on a gray and chilly New Year's
afternoon, Toledo celebrated a Cotton Bowl victory against Texas
A&AMP;M and the bounty it wrought: A 10-game winning streak, a No.5
ranking and, yes, a return to national prominence.
</P>
<P>
   Five weeks later the Bruins signed the most heralded recruiting
class in their history, rated No.1 by several national services.
Last month, UCLA was ranked seventh in both preseason polls and the
Pacific-10 Conference media's pick to win the league.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Toledo is ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took the job, I thought we'd be at this level within
five years _ once we got our recruits and established our
philosophy,'' he said. ``Hopefully, we're making headway.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo's methods are well documented. He hired Kevin Yoxall to
revamp the strength program _ ``He's a big, big part of this,''
Toledo said _ and a slew of solid assistants. He has reinvigorated
the recruiting, implemented a dynamic offense and an attacking
defense that attracts top talent. His energy is boundless, his
optimism unwavering.
</P>
<P>
   Can he keep it up? Is the success permanent or a flare in the
Westwood sky, bright and brief? Can the Bruins compete for the
Pac-10 championship annually and become a fixture in the top-10
alongside Nebraska and Florida State?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing a great job,'' former USC coach John Robinson
said. ``But it's very difficult to remain at that level year in and
year out. When you graduate a senior group, then you start over and
you have a dip. Florida State, Ohio State and Nebraska are the only
ones that stay on top.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 is uniquely competitive among the major conferences.
Six different champions in the past six years. No repeat winner
since Washington in 1992. Only two 11-win teams this decade.
Scholarship reductions, player defections (to the NFL) and tighter
admissions have created unprecedented parity and a miniscule margin
for error. Toledo could hire the best assistants and recruit the
best players and still not return UCLA to its glory of the '80s _
when Donahue won three Rose Bowls and had eight top-15 finishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA, last year and this year, is in a two-year up cycle,''
said Donahue, now a CBS analyst. ``The issue becomes when Bob
starts playing with his players. That's when it's truly his
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, 90 percent of the players who took them to 10 wins
were in the program when he became coach. This year, it'll be 40
percent: (kicker) Chris Sailer, (safety) Larry Atkins, (offensive
tackle) Kris Farris, and (quarterback Cade) McNown are the
holdovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether he can keep it up will be determined over a long
period of time. You have to withhold evaluation until history is
written. But this is a really exciting time for UCLA football.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toledo arrived in 1994, after five years at Texas A&AMP;M. His
mission as offensive coordinator was to energize a sagging offense
and develop a freshman quarterback named McNown.
</P>
<P>
   They clicked immediately. McNown was eager to learn and Toledo,
who tutored pros Chris Miller and Bill Musgrave at Oregon in the
'80s, had much to impart. During the coaching search, when
Neuheisel and Barnett were all the rage, McNown waltzed into Dalis'
office and endorsed his coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sat down, and in a very formal way, described why Bob would
make a good head coach,'' Dalis said. ``I was impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as McNown's rise has paralleled UCLA's, replacing McNown
will dictate future success. This is a critical lesson from the
Donahue years, and one of the few building blocks to prolonged
success that Toledo can control.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the '80s, UCLA reloaded at the most important
position, quarterback. Tom Ramsey departed in 1983, and Neuheisel
stepped in. Neuheisel departed, and along came Steve Bono. When
Bono left, Matt Stephens took over. Then the best of them all, Troy
Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one knew it at the time, Aikman's departure after
the 1988 season signaled the beginning of the end of Donahue's
success. UCLA won 10 games in each of Aikman's two seasons, then
three in '89 and five in '90.
</P>
<P>
   How will the Bruins cope with McNown's departure? A former
walk-on, Drew Bennett, is the projected replacement. If he falters,
UCLA has several young but talented successors: Scott McEwan, Cory
Paus, Ryan McCann and recruit J.P. Losman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Replacing McNown will be a critical question,'' Donahue said.
``If the evaluation process is right, they'll keep it going. If
not, then it gets more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Donahue thought he had reloaded when Tommy Maddox arrived in
1989. Three years later, he was gone _ an early departure to the
NFL from which the Donahue regime never fully recovered. Sure,
Wayne Cook won a Pac-10 title, but he was no Aikman or Maddox. Rob
Walker, Ryan Fien and Steve Buck were not the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Player defections are beyond a coach's control, as is staff
attrition. Donahue lost a plethora of assistants over the years,
from Rich Brooks and Dick Tomey to Homer Smith and Greg Robinson.
It's an unforgiving cycle: good assistants help generate more
victories, but more victories make those assistants marketable. The
better the hire, the quicker that coach is likely to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo felt the ripple effect in December, when defensive
coordinator Rocky Long took the New Mexico job. Toledo hired Nick
Aliotti, who masterminded Oregon's Gang Green defense during its
1994 Rose Bowl run. But if the defense performs, Aliotti will
receive other offers. The Buffalo Bills and Pittsburgh Steelers
contacted offensive coordinator Al Borges last year. How long will
he last?
</P>
<P>
   Injuries can disrupt immediate success, as well. The Bruins
suffered one of their most devastating losses of the decade at
Arizona in 1992. It wasn't the score (23-3) so much as the
pounding: receiver Sean LaChapelle cracked his ribs and defensive
end Arnold Ale broke his leg. A five-game losing streak ensued.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game destroyed us for a number of weeks,'' Donahue said.
</P>
<P>
   It gets back to recruiting. Quality depth offsets most injuries
and player defections _ other than an Aikman, Maddox or McNown, of
course _ and it tempers the impact of graduation. How the Bruins
fare next year depends on recent recruiting. Will freshman DeShaun
Foster run like Karim Abdul-Jabbar or Skip Hicks? Is freshman Blake
Worley the next Chad Overhauser? And what about the quarterbacks?
</P>
<P>
   ``The cycles come when a class graduates,'' John Robinson said.
``When Cade graduates, they have to replace him. I'm not sure how
many teams can stay on top without cycles.''
</P>
<P>
   And no team stays on top forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``USC is a great example,'' Donahue said. ``For 20 years, from
the mid '60s to the mid '80s, USC was as good as any program in the
country. Now they're in a down cycle. That's what happens. You
enjoy great periods of time and then periods that aren't so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo's success could last for years. He should enjoy it while
it's here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
