<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKETT TRIES TO RESTORE MYSTIQUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was shortly after Paul Hackett had been hired to be the USC
football coach and he was making his first campus visit in 20
years. He vaguely remembered the athletic facilities, and was eager
to see what changes had been made since he was an assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   The answer came quickly. Not many.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was the same. The same Heritage Hall. The same
offices. The same field,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   These were not feelings of nostalgia for Hackett. Frankly, he
was appalled so little had been done in the '80s and '90s to
improve the facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone else has used us as a model,'' Hackett said. ``We
used to be at the forefront. Now, we have to leapfrog them.''
</P>
<P>
   The facilities are already undergoing a face-lift at USC, with
an expanded practice field, new dining center, expanded weight room
and extra office space for coaches all either completed or being
built.
</P>
<P>
   But is some plaster and extra grass enough to restore USC to its
previous lofty stature?
</P>
<P>
   Three coaches _ Ted Tollner, Larry Smith, John Robinson _ tried
and ultimately failed to bring USC back to the so-called glory days
of the 1970s when the Trojans captured three national
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hackett gets his chance to return USC to the top of the
college football class that's populated with Nebraska, Florida
State and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football is king at the University of Southern California and
it should be,'' said former player and assistant coach Marv Goux, a
USC fixture from 1952-82. ``I just think you have to keep the
program going and you can't turn it on when you want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Since winning the Rose Bowl after the 1995 season, the Trojans
have gone 12-11. USC may not have won a national championship in 20
years, a Heisman in 17 or beaten UCLA in the last seven games, but
expectations have not changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at a golf tournament with Ronnie Lott, and he said we
need to win every game this year and go 12-0,'' Hackett said.
``Then I turned to Anthony Munoz, and he said, `Win them all and
the Rose Bowl.'''
</P>
<P>
   This is Hackett's task: rebuild a program that doesn't accept
rebuilding. Another challenge is to restore the Trojans' mystique,
that attitude that joined USC on the field during the era of
dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like anybody respects us right now,'' senior wide
receiver Mike Bastianelli said. ``I don't think we really deserve
it the way we've played.''
</P>
<P>
   Goux thinks Hackett can restore the Trojans to their former
greatness. He saw first-hand what Hackett was doing by attending
several practices during training camp at UC Irvine, and so far, he
likes what he sees.
</P>
<P>
   ``History repeats itself. History will repeat itself,'' Goux
said. ``If you get somebody running it right, they can have a great
program. First, you have to have people who can coach. Paul Hackett
has gone out and gotten fine assistants. I've watched them very
closely. They're excellent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will SC win again? You're damn right. I believe they have the
right guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Goux also said he was impressed with Hackett's work habits. But
as important is Hackett's connection to the program. Hackett was an
assistant coach for the Trojans from 1976-80. In that period, USC
went to four bowl games, including three Rose Bowls, and won the
national championship in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows the tradition. It's SC football again,'' Goux said.
``Larry Smith, Ted Tollner, they had no idea about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett, whose father was a professor at the University of
California, is a student and historian. In an unconventional move
this summer, he went to breakfast in Encino with John Wooden,
hoping to pick up a few pointers from the UCLA basketball coaching
legend.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden told him it might take a while, but it is possible to
bring USC back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `If I could hang on in the early years at UCLA, I
knew we could turn it around,''' Hackett said. ``I asked him if he
was frustrated. He said, `I was so frustrated but I knew I was in a
great city and at a great university. I just needed to coach. Just
stay the course.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said Wooden reminded him to be a hands-on coach first
and not become overburdened by the administrative aspects of the
job. To reiterate this, Hackett has a note on his desk based on
that conversation saying, ``Paul, be sure you coach first.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett is also instilling discipline, something Wooden and Goux
stressed. Players are monitored by student assistants to make sure
they attend classes. If they don't, they get to do something
enjoyable like run at 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   A warning was sent to the players last April when Hackett
suspended R. Jay Soward, the team's biggest star, after he had
trouble attending class and was failing two classes.
</P>
<P>
   When Soward got punished, everybody else cleaned up their act,
including Soward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think he'd go through with it but he's pretty
serious,'' Soward said. ``His first goal is to have us take care of
business. This taught me to take care of my responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Soward's troubles, no other player has challenged Hackett,
and they have appreciated his even hand whether dealing with stars
or walk-ons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man doesn't care who you are, he treats everyone
equally,'' wide receiver Billy Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Tradition. Discipline. Organization. All of these practices are
needed for a successful program. They will only work, however, if
Hackett recruits players comparable to the outstanding crops
brought in during the John McKay-Robinson era.
</P>
<P>
   And there may lie a problem bigger than any other for the USC
football coach, in luring top-notch talent. Again, though, the
supporters have an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be harder than it used to be,'' Goux said. ``(But)
there are more better players than there's ever been. This is a big
metropolitan area. Young people dream about going to certain places
like USC.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett did not have an outstanding recruiting reputation at
Pitt, but he held together the core of USC's recruiting class last
winter and has already gotten three commitments this summer.
</P>
<P>
   His initial task to improve on the field is to recruit linemen,
USC's biggest weakness at the moment. The Trojans might sign as
many as 12 linemen this February, in an attempt to recapture the
domination of the Munoz-Brad Budde days, when USC could overpower
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is the foundation of this university,
which has always been linemen,'' Hackett said. ``Great offensive
linemen. Great defensive linemen. That has been the foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett is also a realist, knowing it could take five years to
completely overhaul the program. From the day he was hired, he has
been aware that college football has changed a lot since the 1970s,
and it's a much more competitive world that USC competes against
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conference has changed. I remember people saying when
Arizona State joined the conference that it was going to be
different,'' Hackett said. ``Washington State ... Oregon had a
marvelous run a number of years ago. So that's great. If you're at
those places it's wonderful, and if you're here, it's not so
wonderful. That used to be our sole, exclusive place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
