<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-STRONG-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG MAKES PUSH FOR PLAYING TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not even Frank Strong could imagine how quickly he moved up the
USC depth chart, barely three weeks after he arrived from Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really surprised me,'' Strong said. ``I just go to my room
at night and I'm stuck thinking about how quickly I've adapted to
(college football).''
</P>
<P>
   A 6-foot-2, 200-pound true freshman, Strong came to USC known as
a power runner who was buried under the accolades given to other
prominent Trojans recruits, including prep All-American tailback
Sultan McCullough.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell that a lot of people didn't know me,'' Strong
said. ``We don't get much attention in Stockton.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the USC coaches weren't completely sure what they were
getting in Strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know the level of competition at Stockton,'' USC
coach Paul Hackett said. ``I know what it is for a player at Mater
Dei or (Long Beach) Poly. But he's seized every chance he gets and
everybody makes note.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Strong has opened the coaches' eyes with his
elusiveness, which was not widely known even among some college
recruiters.
</P>
<P>
   Strong was heavily recruited by Nebraska, but he got vibes that
the Cornhuskers were more interested in him as a linebacker, a
position he also played at Franklin High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were like telling me tailback, but I already got an
indication about their moving me to defense,'' Strong said.
</P>
<P>
   There was speculation Strong might be a USC fullback one day,
but since he started practicing, it's been clear that his future is
at tailback. In his first scrimmage, he led all tailbacks with 36
yards in six carries. In the Trojans' second scrimmage, Strong had
39 yards in three carries.
</P>
<P>
   Although he didn't get any carries in the season-opener against
Purdue, Strong is tied for third on the depth with redshirt junior
Petros Papadakis, behind starter Chad Morton and backup Malaefou
McKenzie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been elusive for awhile but I was known more for running
up the middle,'' Strong said. ``It seems like I was a little
underrated for my speed and elusiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong committed to USC before coach John Robinson was fired,
but after the coaching change, gave Nebraska and Cal another shot.
</P>
<P>
   The new USC coaching staff quickly realized that it still wanted
Strong, however, and convinced him to make a campus visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's over 200 pounds and you look at him and he looks thin,''
USC assistant head coach Larry Petroff said. ``He moves really well
and has good speed and vision. He's a natural runner and has
grasped this offense very quickly, which sometimes for a true
freshman is hard to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong was impressed with Hackett and the coaching staff and
quickly re-affirmed his commitment to the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was mainly Coach Hackett and the staff,'' Strong said. ``I
knew they would be father figures to me.''
</P>
<P>
   While Strong harbored ambitions of playing this season for the
Trojans, he knew it was probably a long shot, considering the depth
at running back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would redshirt,'' Strong said. ``Actually, I am
(doing better than I thought).''
</P>
<P>
   Petroff said the key to Strong's early development at USC has
been his ability to adjust physically, emotionally and mentally.
</P>
<P>
   And so far, Strong is not complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going great. My future's here at USC,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 0334EDT &QL; 
