<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-POLI-DIXON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLI-DIXON EXCITES BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first, Brian Poli-Dixon did not understand. Everywhere he
turned, UCLA fans compared him to former Bruins star J.J. Stokes.
The position (receiver), the size (6-5) and the natural talent made
comparisons inevitable, yet Poli-Dixon was bewildered.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Tucson, Ariz., he rarely watched Stokes and
certainly never scrutinized his mannerisms and style of play. In
fact, Poli-Dixon knew very little about Stokes until he got to UCLA
last year and popped in a videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Then he knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I saw why people make the comparison,'' said
Poli-Dixon, a sophomore split end. ``I've gotten up to date on J.J.
Stokes since I got to UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the similarities _ their long and lanky builds, their
gliding strides and deceptive speed _ Stokes and Poli-Dixon are
different in two respects: Stokes had 28 career touchdown
receptions, whereas Poli-Dixon has two. Stokes redshirted as a
freshman, while Poli-Dixon played.
</P>
<P>
   The latter point is critical to assessing Poli-Dixon's
performance to date, and in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Stokes was a consensus All-American as a junior in 1993, with 82
catches and 17 touchdowns. But his rise to greatness actually
occurred in the last two games of the '92 season, when he torched
Oregon and USC for 16 catches and four touchdowns. That success
simply carried over to the following fall.
</P>
<P>
   Stokes was concluding his third year in the program when he
reached stardom. Poli-Dixon, for all his talent, is just beginning
his second year.
</P>
<P>
   Is he ready to bust loose?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the potential,'' receivers coach Ron Caragher said.
``He got experience last year, and I hope he can take it to the
next level. J.J. exploded at the end of his third year. Brian's
starting his second, but he's got a shot. Potentially, they are
very similar.''
</P>
<P>
   For proof, Caragher points to the Houston game, when Poli-Dixon
turned a non-descript screen into a 31-yard touchdown. Watching him
corral the ball, then dash through the defense with fluid, immense
strides, was to watch Stokes all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was just a chance to get my feet wet,'' Poli-Dixon
said. ``It was a whole new world for me. This year, I have more
confidence. Like in the SC game, when I caught a ball and went
(head-to-head) with the guy. This year, I'll try to juke him.''
</P>
<P>
   Poli-Dixon started training camp as the No.2 split end, behind
Brad Melsby. But the Bruins probably will treat him as a third
starter, especially on third downs and goal-line situations _
whenever his size is most valuable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, he'll help us make up the (11) touchdowns we lost
with (Jim) McElroy,'' offensive coordinator Al Borges said. ``I
don't expect him to get 11, but if he can get half that, it'd
help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 0336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 03:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6586 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USC-ANALYSIS-LADN     09-03 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKETT IS KEY FOR USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Virtually any analysis today of the USC football team begins and
ends with new coach Paul Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   This much is already certain: Hackett is extremely detailed,
organized and energetic as he embarks on his inaugural season.
</P>
<P>
   But it is players who win games, no matter how much coaches
would like you to think they influence the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   And Hackett sent out an early red flag last spring when he said,
``The talent level is not quite what I thought it would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pure talent level, I'm a little disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   That might sound like a coach deflecting criticism before it
begins, but Hackett does have a point.
</P>
<P>
   USC will only be as good as its talent. Right now, it has some
incredibly talented players at certain positions (middle
linebacker, wide receiver) and some entirely mediocre spots
(offensive line, defensive line).
</P>
<P>
   When Hackett says games are won in the trenches, it might be
time to worry.
</P>
<P>
   But USC does have enough to turn things around from the past two
seasons, when the Trojans were 12-11.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom says USC will go 7-5, but every season
contains a few surprise moments. If the Trojans steal one or two
games, they go 9-3. That might be judged a minor miracle.
</P>
<P>
   If USC does win nine games, it can thank the defense. The
Trojans return eight starters and probably have the best defense in
the Pacific-10 Conference. Linebackers Chris Claiborne, Mark Cusano
and David Gibson have all turned games around with big plays the
past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   And the secondary _ particularly safeties Grant Pearsall and
Rashard Cook _ is undeniably talented and experienced. Throw in
Daylon McCutcheon at cornerback and there is reason for optimism.
</P>
<P>
   The rear seven should keep USC in a lot of games this season.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive line is suspect. But it was a question mark last
season and wound up being the Pac-10's top defense against the run.
And unlike last year, there's more size and speed along the front
four.
</P>
<P>
   Whether USC can keep its patchwork offensive line from falling
apart and get another overachieving year from its defensive line
will determine whether or not the year is judged a success.
</P>
<P>
   With only one offensive lineman who has started a college game
(Travis Claridge) it might be too much to ask these guys to pass
block against Florida State, Arizona State, Washington or UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   But this is where a coach makes a difference _ at least in his
own mind.
</P>
<P>
   And plenty of people believe Hackett can get results. He's
brought discipline and decisiveness into the program that have been
missing the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Barely a week into training camp, junior quarterbacks John Fox
and Quincy Woods were playing tight end and wide receiver,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   He's made it clear he wants to go with his young quarterbacks,
and he's not about to play favorites at the other positions.
</P>
<P>
   Problem-child wide receiver R. Jay Soward was suspended from the
opener during spring practice for poor academic performance, and
that has put the rest of the team on notice. No other players have
gotten out of line since, and it's fair to say more than a few
might fear Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   Gone forever are the laid-back days of John Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett will be nothing if not disciplined, and it will be
interesting to see if this really translates into more victories.
Hackett is the first to say this is really a five-year plan, but
with players like Soward, Claiborne and Palmer around, Trojans fans
will want immediate results.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule is not overwhelmingly difficult. USC has seven home
games and does not travel to Seattle or Tempe. The Trojans even get
to go to Pullman, Wash., in mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe, just maybe, those top-25 poll votes the Trojans have
received are no completely out of line.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, USC's skill position players can be so intoxicating
that you almost want to overlook the problems in the trenches.
</P>
<P>
   The fans certainly will. They've never been big on rebuilding
years around here.!end!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
