<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL IT BE ROSE BOWL OR EL PASO FOR BRUINS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UCLA coach Bob Toledo is a weather balloon, the first to sense
changing dynamics within his program and altered expectations
without.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' 10-game winning streak, top-rated recruiting class
and Heisman Trophy candidate have combined to generate lofty media
expectations (UCLA is the preseason Pacific-10 Conference favorite)
and escalating fan enthusiasm (record increase in ticket sales).
</P>
<P>
   Toledo recognized the attention months ago, but he did not hide
from it. That acceptance has created more preseason optimism than
has existed since August 1994 _ before J.J. Stokes' bruised thigh
leveled the season.
</P>
<P>
   Is the current good cheer justified?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, and no.
</P>
<P>
   With quarterback Cade McNown, kicker Chris Sailer, a sound
offensive line, depth at receiver and speed on defense, the Bruins
have enough raw materials to win nine games and the Pacific-10
championship. Their health is good. Their schedule is favorable.
Confidence is booming. Heck, make it 10 wins.
</P>
<P>
   But the flip side is this: Lacking an accomplished tailback and
experience on defense, where only four starters return, the Bruins
are not a dominating team _ one capable of beating quality foes on
a bad day. Perhaps they'll reach that point in coming years, when
the freshman class matures, but they aren't there now.
</P>
<P>
   They have no seniors at tailback or receiver. Their most
talented defensive linemen are the most inexperienced. They cannot
possibly repeat the plus-1.82 turnover margin of last season or
replace the Pac-10's career touchdown leader (Skip Hicks). They
must play at Arizona and at Washington, places that invariably
bring out their worst. And the USC streak must end sometime. How
long does a coin keep coming up heads?
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, the Bruins are teetering between good and great,
between seven wins and 10, between the Sun Bowl and the Rose Bowl.
Which way they fall depends not on the studs _ not on McNown or
Sailer, offensive tackle Kris Farris, linebacker Brendan Ayanbadejo
or safety Larry Atkins _ but on the supporting players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, the people surrounding Cade are a concern,''
Toledo said. ``I know Cade will do the right things, but other
people have to do the right things in order for him to perform
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks and receiver Jim McElroy were a devastating combination
last year, accounting for 37 of UCLA's 60 touchdowns. Defenses
crowded the line of scrimmage to contain Hicks, enabling McElroy to
beat them deep. McNown delivered the ball to his scorers like a
premier point guard, on time and on target, but he rarely had to
create the touchdowns himself.
</P>
<P>
   Who fills the 222-point void?
</P>
<P>
   Rather than one or two players, it might be seven or eight.
</P>
<P>
   Jermaine Lewis, Keith Brown and DeShaun Foster will compete for
Hicks' carries and touchdowns. Dan Farmer, Brad Melsby, Freddie
Mitchell and Brian Poli-Dixon will battle for McElroy's receptions
and, more importantly, his big plays.
</P>
<P>
   Individually, there are several potential stars: Foster, of
course, and perhaps Poli-Dixon and Mitchell, too. Collectively,
though, it remains to be seen if they can complement each other the
way Hicks and McElroy did.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the offense seems solid. If Brian Polak or James
Ghezzi perform at right tackle (McNown's blind side), the offensive
line will be one of the Pac-10's best. And the Bruins are so loaded
at tight end that Bryan Fletcher, the most gifted of the bunch, is
running fourth string.
</P>
<P>
   The defense is a greater concern. Sophomore Kenyon Coleman is
the defensive line's anchor, a heavy burden for a 19-year-old just
shedding his baby fat.
</P>
<P>
   Ayanbadejo alone cannot solidify the linebacking. He needs help,
but no one else has ever started a game. Cornerbacks Jason Bell,
Marques Anderson and Damian Allen have shown flashes of talent, and
enough inconsistency to get beat deep.
</P>
<P>
   True freshmen will be asked to contribute on the line (Ken
Kocher), at linebacker (Robert Thomas) and in the secondary (Lovell
Houston). That's hardly reassuring, however talented they might be.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is this: Just as good health, the spectacular
turnover margin and the McNown-Hicks-McElroy symmetry converged to
create surprising success in '97, obstacles might surface to create
unexpected difficulty this year.
</P>
<P>
   Call them bad breaks, vagaries of the game, whatever. But unless
you're at Nebraska or Florida State, you don't book New Year's Day
reservations in September. Things have a way of evening out, and
UCLA's balance sheet reads 8-3, payable Dec. 31, in the Sun Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
