ANTIBODIES AGAINST THYROID GLAND LINKED TO
</P>
<P>
   CHERNOBYL DISASTER Young people living in the former Soviet
republic of Belarus exposed to radioactive fallout from the
Chernobyl disaster are much more likely to have antibodies against
their thyroid glands than children who escaped significant
radiation exposure. It is thought that radiation damage to the
thyroid may trigger an abnormal immune response to the gland that
leads to autoimmune thyroid diseases. Although the study found no
evidence that the antibodies had yet affected the thyroid function
of these young people, the findings suggest that they may develop
autoimmune thyroid diseases later in life that can cause
hypothyroidism. By Michael McCarthy. The Lancet News Service. 1,000
words.
