LATIN AMERICA'S STREET CHILDREN CRY FOR HELP There are 100 million
street children in the world; 40 million live in Latin America. In
Bolivia, 11-year-old Macario, illiterate and homeless, is scheduled
to meet President Hugo Banzer Suarez to help ``show the world that
we are also people,'' and that he and his street friends ``have
talents we want to develop.'' The boy says it is infuriating to see
government officials on TV talk about the rights of children, when
the violence they fear the most comes directly from the
authorities. The Gordian knot of systemic abuse and impunity under
which police forces in Latin America operate must be unravelled. By
Silvana Paternostro. 1,000 words. (Available in English and
