<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-TREES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miami Valley trees losing foliage early
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fall is still weeks away, but many people in the Miami Valley,
Ohio, are already hauling out their rakes and leaf blowers to deal
with growing piles of brown leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Trees are like a business facing a shortage of raw materials,
said Woody Wesig of Woody Tree Medics, and right now some are on
short work weeks and some are going bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a scale of 10, a brown leaf is zero, and a bright green is
a Madonna 10,'' said Wesig. ``We're not seeing too many 10s right
now. Many trees are around five.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons that trees are losing leaves early this
year: too much rain earlier and too little lately, the region's
soil composition, excessive aphids and mites in the spring, and, of
course, El Nino.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Valley is currently going through a mini-drought.
Although August rain levels are barely half an inch below normal at
2.71 inches, most of that precipitation came in three torrential
days early in the month. The rest of the month has been dry, and no
rain is forecast through Sunday, according to the National Weather
Service in Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trees' reaction is not unusual; when it gets hot some start
shedding,'' said Pete Lane of the Ohio State University
Agricultural Extension. ``And August is the time when trees need
more water.''
</P>
<P>
   The extremely wet spring brought on by El Nino, the warm
currents in the Pacific Ocean that disrupted weather patterns all
over the world, set the stage for the trees' early defoliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all started in the spring with excess rainfall,'' said
Wesig. ``Excess moisture fills up the spaces between soil particles
and denies the roots oxygen and it washes away essential elements
the tree needs. As we say, no roots, no top.''
</P>
<P>
   Wesig said the region's soil is also a problem. ``There are a
lot of rocks and clay. It's better for making pottery than making
plants,'' he said. ``When the soil is hostile, roots stay up near
the surface. That makes trees more subject to the fluctuations of
nature.''
</P>
<P>
   The wet spring also increased aphids and mites and certain
pathogens that can disrupt a tree's growth, according to Wesig.
Some areas have also seen Japanese beetle infestations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
