</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEOPLE-READER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jury consultant's a whiz at judging us at a glance
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jo-Ellan Dimitrius is not someone you want to meet when you have
a spot of ketchup on your collar or a sesame seed stuck between
your front teeth.
</P>
<P>
   She'll notice. She notices everything about everyone.
</P>
<P>
   She notices whether they speak clearly, walk straight, slouch in
their seats, drum their fingers. Whether their clothes are too
tight or too short. Whether
</P>
<P>
   they look other people in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   And she's anything but nonjudgmental.
</P>
<P>
   As a jury consultant in more than 600 trials, including O.J.
Simpson's criminal case, she draws fast conclusions about strangers
that help defense attorneys identify the most sympathetic
prospects. She also prepares witnesses to look and sound sincere.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's written a book, ``Reading People'' (Random House,
$23.95), revealing the techniques that prompted a law magazine to
dub her The Seer. You don't have to be facing the electric chair to
be interested.
</P>
<P>
   Dimitrius aims at bosses who hire employees, singles looking for
mates and anyone who wants to make a good impression. Her methods
are universal but have to be applied individually.
</P>
<P>
   You might use them to identify ambition in a file clerk or to
seek a child-care worker who can't imagine doing anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to decide what they want in a friend, a physician
or someone they're hiring,'' she says. ``You have to spend time
thinking about that first.''
</P>
<P>
   First impressions are meaningful, Dimitrius insists, although
she cautions against reading too much into someone's appearance.
After all, people really do have bad hair days.
</P>
<P>
   But cheap wigs, loud colors or scruffy beards may be important
personality clues when weighed with other factors. Among them: what
the person says (and how), body language and how the person
interacts with others.
</P>
<P>
   To really know someone, you have to consider the person's
environment. That means looking into their homes and meeting their
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Environment includes the human environment,'' she says. ``You
learn a lot by looking at who they hang out with and what they do.
Do they do something cultural? Play softball? Go drinking and
carousing?''
</P>
<P>
   The most important factor may be time, a luxury Dimitrius
doesn't have in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``You meet someone who's a lot of fun to be with, the life of
the party, but in time you realize he never chips in to help pay
the bill,'' she says. ``That's particularly a problem in dating.
You jump in before you know the person's character.''
</P>
<P>
   It also takes time to get the hang of reading personal signals,
especially when so many people have cut back on human contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it analysis paralysis,'' Dimitrius says. ``We're used
to reading e-mail and faxes, not meeting people. Get out of your
chair instead of sending a message down the hall. I'd rather see
how a person reacts to news.''
</P>
<P>
   Dimitrius, 45, started building her mental database of character
clues when she was a child, watching her parents' friends at dinner
parties. Her fascination with people led to a fascination with
juries, the subject of her doctoral dissertation at Claremont
Graduate School in California, where she lives. Her high-profile
trial work has led to numerous television appearances on talk and
news shows.
</P>
<P>
   She concedes that practice hasn't made perfect. After 20 years
of marriage, Dimitrius is in mid-divorce. She also concedes that
not everyone enjoys being subjected to her close scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``This explains why my daughter's not forthcoming about bringing
home new boyfriends,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
