<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6839 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-READER-SIDE04-COX     09-03 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-READER-SIDE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PBP-READSIDE
 &HT;    HOW TO READ PEOPLE
 &HT;    How to read people
 &HT;    By DOUGLAS KALAJIAN
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   First, a warning: Author Jo-Ellan Dimitrius cautions against
judging anyone without considering many factors. Common Co5clusions
are often wrong. (For example, a person wearing sunglasses indoors
may not be shifty; he may just have an eye infection.)
</P>
<P>
   But here are some of the signals:
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO JUDGE YOUR BOSS
</P>
<P>
   How a supervisor treats employees is tremendously telling.
</P>
<P>
   If your boss is kind, respectful and friendly with employees, he
or she is probably self-confident, compassionate and generous.
</P>
<P>
   If your boss treats employees like servants, he is probably
insecure, domineering, insensitive and uncaring _ not only in the
workplace but in every aspect of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Watch out for personal inconstancies: People don't flip a switch
and consistently treat their employees one way and their spouse
another. Truly kind and confident people do not treat others in
dramatically different ways depending on their mood or their
perception of what someone can do for them.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO JUDGE OUR CO-WORKERS
</P>
<P>
   The better the relationship between a person and his/her
co-workers, the more likely that he is self-confident and
comfortable with his position in life.
</P>
<P>
   Which three character traits are most likely to predict a
person's behavior?
</P>
<P>
   No trait means the same thing in every person or in every
circumstance. But these three characteristics provide consistently
reliable insight into almost everyone, almost all the time:
</P>
<P>
   1. Compassion: Dimitrius uses a `hardness scale' for judging
people _ on one end is the cold, unemotional, uncaring person; on
the other is the warm and compassionate soul. Cold people tend to
be more critical, punitive and self-centered. Warm people tend to
be more forgiving and make decisions more slowly (to give others
the benefit of the doubt).
</P>
<P>
   2. Socioeconomic background: People who have had to scratch and
claw for everything they have, whether financial or emotional, may
develop a siege mentality and retain it all their life. They may
become intolerant, stingy and defensive; on the other end, they
tend to be focused and hard-working. People who have had their
needs fulfilled tend to feel entitled to everything has been handed
to them, they may lack drive.
</P>
<P>
   3. Satisfaction with life: People who have achieved their
personal goals tend to be more compassionate and optimistic. People
who have not tend to be bitter, negative and pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   WATCH BODY LANGUAGE
</P>
<P>
   Signs of dishonesty:
</P>
<P>
   Sweating
</P>
<P>
   Shaking
</P>
<P>
   Sincere, furrowed-brow look
</P>
<P>
   Running tongue over teeth
</P>
<P>
   Inappropriate familiarity (back-slapping, touching, invading
personal space)
</P>
<P>
   Signs of anger:
</P>
<P>
   Arms, legs or ankles crossed
</P>
<P>
   Short or rapid breath
</P>
<P>
   Stiff, rigid posture
</P>
<P>
   Pointing fingers
</P>
<P>
   REVEALING ITEMS IN THE WORKPLACE
</P>
<P>
   Desktops: A messy desk points to a messy, disorganized person.
</P>
<P>
   Calendars: Sierra Club or pinup? Far Side or Norman Rockwell?
</P>
<P>
   Books: Don't just look at the subject; look to see if they've
been read.
</P>
<P>
   REVEALING ITEMS AT HOME
</P>
<P>
   Flowers and plants: A person likely to be sensuous, sensitive to
beauty and hospitable.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol: Open displays may mean the owner is fond of drinking or
entertaining those who are.
</P>
<P>
   Artwork: If you're attracted to what's hanging on a person's
wall, you may have a lot in common.
</P>
<P>
   Red flag: If someone's home differs dramatically from the way
he/she presents himself/herself publicly, ask yourself, `Which is
authentic?' Usually, the home offers more reliable clues.
</P>
<P>
   TELLING SPEECH PATTERNS
</P>
<P>
   Loud voice: Used to control others, compensate for small stature
or other flaw.
</P>
<P>
   Soft voice: Could suggest lack of confidence (are the words
halting?), but might reflect calm self-assurance if words are
steady and controlled. Could suggest a person who is easily swayed.
</P>
<P>
   Fast speech: Nervousness, anxiety, anger.
</P>
<P>
   Slow speech: Thoughtful, lying, confused.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
