<SLUG> BC-REDHAWKS-PRENTICE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Travis Prentice big on team, not personal goals
 &HT;    By Marty Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, Ohio _ Travis Prentice is no Louie Armstrong when it
comes to blowing his own horn.
</P>
<P>
   The junior tailback from Louisville, Ky., has played in only 22
games, but is on pace to shatter a flock of Miami and Mid-American
Conference rushing and scoring records.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always bringing the records to my attention,'' the
soft-spoken Prentice said, ``but I'm not really big on personal
goals. The only goal I have is to play on the team that wins the
MAC championship. I just run with the football. If the records
happen, they happen.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot happened for the 6-foot-2, 225-pound Prentice last season.
He set school and MAC single-season records with 25 touchdowns and
rushed for 1,549 yards. He was one of eight finalists for the Doak
Walker Award, which goes to the top running back in the country.
</P>
<P>
   As you might expect, those accomplishments had a major effect on
his confidence level heading into a season that begins with
Saturday's road test at nationally-ranked North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I'm capable of,'' he said. ``Last year, I
anticipated what I could do. I backed up Ty King (as a redshirt
freshman), but I never started. I know what I can do a lot better
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the things he does better is keep coach Randy Walker
scrambling for superlatives. ``Travis has great skills, great
talent and a great work ethic, but he's also a great kid. And that
gives him a chance to be real special.''
</P>
<P>
   Being special this season will be much more difficult for
Prentice. The RedHawks graduated quarterback Sam Ricketts and four
starters in the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bath is expected to run the offense at North Carolina,
although Walker hopes John Schacke will be back in time for the
home opener against Toledo on Sept. 26. Schacke, Ricketts' backup
last year, is still recovering from major knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Walker insisted he won't return to the run-oriented offense that
was his trademark until the 1997 season. ``As good as Travis is, he
can't beat 11 (defenders). We have to soften them up by throwing
the football. I have no question that we're going to be able to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Prentice is an unusual blend of speed and power. He can bench
press over 400 pounds and still runs the 40-yard dash in 4.39
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   When most Miami students went home last May, Prentice settled in
for the summer, joining a large contingent of his teammates for
daily workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're stronger,'' he said, ``you can last longer. I try
to treat the fourth quarter like the first quarter. I want to be in
such good condition that I never get tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Prentice said the RedHawks are eager for Saturday's shot at the
Tar Heels, who finished 11-1 last season and crushed Virginia Tech
in the Gator Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of a better way to open the season,'' Prentice
said. ``We'll be able to measure ourselves against a big-market
team. Those guys play Florida State and a lot of big-time teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get the publicity those programs do,'' he added,
``but a lot of our guys can play anywhere. We're not going to be
intimidated. There's a respect factor involved. The only way you
get respect is to play well and win. We expect to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami has a storied past as a giant-killer and Walker wants to
continue that tradition. ``I know not many people will give us much
of a chance against North Carolina, but it only matters if 60 guys
(the traveling squad) think they have a chance. That's what
happened at Virginia Tech last year (24-17) and at Northwestern
(30-28) in 1995.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
