</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Travels with Charley turn out all wet
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was beginning to feel like Tom Joad in the ``Grapes of Wrath''
last week while heading down Highway 21 toward Austin, pulling a
small flatbed trailer loaded with second-and even third-hand
furniture. The inside of my Explorer was crammed so full of boxes
and assorted junk that any type of collision would have buried me
in an avalanche of books, dishes and other personal items. I had to
rely on my sideview mirrors to see anything behind me, or to even
know for sure the trailer was still following me.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it wasn't so bad. I was moving my daughter back to
Austin, this time to an apartment a her first foray into what at
least bears a passing resemblance to the real world. She had cadged
and cajoled the necessary household items from me and her mom, and
I had volunteered to move her. I figure it's payback for all the
times my dad moved me around in the college years, a rite of
passage for both of us.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't worry about rain. Rain has been rare in these parts for
months.We did have a good thunderstorm the night before we left,
but when I got up at 5 a.m. to prepare to leave, the stars were
shining brightly. No problem.
</P>
<P>
   By the time we hit the Trinity River bottom, which I'm happy to
report is looking much greener these days, the clouds had gathered.
In Madisonville, I stopped at Wal-Mart to take stock. It was fixing
to rain, and I had an open-air trailer with a couch, chair and
cheap furniture made out of particle board. We bought tarps,
plastic sheeting and bungee cords. The Wal-Mart cashier knew
exactly what we were doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moving your daughter back to college, aren't you,'' she said.
``Stuff's going to get wet. That Tropical Storm Charley is heading
right through here.''
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Storm Charley? Somehow I had missed that one, what with
Bonnie churning toward the East Coast. Charley slipped in without
much attention, at least from me, cutting across Southern and
Central Texas and dumping loads of rain.
</P>
<P>
   By the time we hit Bryan-College Station, it was coming down
buckets. I stopped to check the tarp, which was hanging on, since I
had used two dozen bungee cords and several pieces of rope. Still,
it was not good news. Everything on the trailer was soaked from the
bottom up about halfway, because of the water coming off the
pavement. My daughter looked stricken. She would be starting life
in a new apartment with furniture that smelled like mildew.
</P>
<P>
   Our Travels with Charley were not pleasant. The wind howled,
tossing the trailer back and forth along the narrow highway. I
rarely got over 50 mph because of the rain. I worried constantly
about the particle board furniture dissolving on the trailer into a
puddle of wet sawdust.
</P>
<P>
   My brother met us at the apartment to help me unload. I was
still shaking after nearly rear-ending someone on I-35 because I
was watching the side-view mirror, still worrying about the danged
rain. Of course, this is a second-story apartment, which made it
even more fun to carry wet furniture up a flight of stairs in the
rain. We got everything inside, dried it off as best we could, and
surveyed the damage.
</P>
<P>
   The couch is OK; apparently it had some type of waterproofing
stuff on it because it dried quickly. The particle-board
entertainment center was a bit wobbly, and likely will not survive
long enough to be handed down as a family heirloom. Actually, we
survived quite well, all things considered.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter was relieved, though nervous about her first time to
live out on her own. (Dorms don't really count. You don't have to
worry about utilities, groceries, etc.) I reassured her she would
do fine and politely declined her offer to let me put together her
particle-board dresser still in the original box. Time to grow up
and learn how to do that type of stuff yourself, I told her.
Besides, I'm terrible at that stuff.
</P>
<P>
   And, I had another date with Charley. I got back in the truck
and headed back the way I came, back to the Pine Curtain a 530
miles driving in one day. The rain lingered until about Crockett.
We here in Deep East Texas got none. The poor folks in West Texas
had floods and loss of life. It could have been worse.
</P>
<P>
   I've called her about three times since leaving. Everything's
fine. She even got the dresser together, though she says it took
eight hours. I could have done it in seven, I'm sure.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. I wrote last week about my fear that a recent birthday
meant I was older than anyone playing pro baseball or football.
Good news. Readers have informed me that Dennis Martinez of the
Braves is three months older than me and still on the roster. In
football, Steve DeBerg of the Atlanta Falcons has a couple of years
on me. Middle age is knocking on the door, but it hasn't quite come
in.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
