<SLUG> BC-DAYTON-DANCE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio dance troup gains PBS recognition
 &HT;    By Terry Morris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Filmmakers working on a Public Broadcasting
series about modern dance have been in Dayton this week to record
the making of a new work by the Dayton Contemporary Dance Company.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Madison D. Lacy, who wrote and filmed two of the
programs in the PBS series Eyes on the Prize and is working with
Ken Burns on the upcoming documentary series, Jazz, said the
footage will be used in a three-program series with the working
title of Free to Dance that will be aired in early 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Lacy and his New York-based crew were shooting performances of
historical black modern dance works by DCDC and other companies the
past summer at the American Dance Festival in Durham, N.C., when
they learned about the collaboration that began in Dayton this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally known choreographers Donald McKayle, 68, and Ronald
Brown, who is in his early 30s, are joining forces for the first
time to make a dance work on DCDC that was commissioned by the
National African-American Museum in Wilberforce as the live
component of an exhibition analyzing the African origins of
physical movements that common throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two choreographers represent different ends of the
generational spectrum. That they had united to create a major
ballet like this one intrigued me,'' Lacy said. ``It fits right in
with our series, which is about the black traditions in American
modern dance. We're hoping to come back and shoot it fully costumed
and performed in February, which will allow us to show the contrast
between the making of it and the finished product.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacy's six-member crew includes Horace Ove, who has made several
dance and drama documentaries for the British Broadcasting Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``When African-American modern dance really started to gel in
this country in the 1950s, it was because of people from all over
this country, not just in New York. I like the idea that we're
coming to Dayton to help tell this story. These dancers are
inspiring others. They're influencing movement in places far from
here,'' Lacy said.
</P>
<P>
   McKayle and Brown said there is no title yet for their work in
progress, which is being done to recordings by the Dirty Dozen
Brass Band. They will be here through Sept. 11 before returning for
two more weeks to complete the dance before its premiere at the
Victoria Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
