<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRESS-CODE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    200 march out of Bastrop High over dress code
 &HT;    By Rebeca Rodriguez
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ An untucked shirt can be a high school
teen-ager's fashion trademark. But to a school administrator in a
society of deadly school shootings, it could be the cover for a
dangerous weapon.
</P>
<P>
   The two views of an untucked shirt collided recently at Bastrop
High School, where school officials' insistence that all shirts be
tucked clashed with some students' drive for individualism. The
result: More than 200 of the school's 1,500 students walked out of
class, gathered in their soccer fields and marched, with police
cars closely following, to what they perceived as the purveyor of
conformity _ the district administration offices.
</P>
<P>
   Three students passed out from heat exhaustion during the
mile-and-a-half march and protest that began at about 10 a.m. and
ended several hours later. They were treated and released from
Smithville Regional Hospital. Martha Hernandez, 16, said the
protest and the district's reaction _ the dress code will be
discussed in a meeting with parents _ demonstrate how strongly both
sides feel.
</P>
<P>
   To students, the rule was meaningless, unfair and a surprise two
weeks into the school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to school Tuesday, and they said tuck in your shirt or
go home,'' Hernandez said. ``We didn't like it at all, so we walked
all the way to the administration building.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Villasen(tilde)or, 18, said the threat of concealed weapons
is not a good enough reason to require students to tuck in their
shirts. ``They said we could conceal weapons with our shirts
hanging out,'' he said, ``but you could still take a weapon to
school with a tucked-in shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a school year following two high-profile national cases
of students killing classmates, education officials are nervous
about safety, even when their school has had few weapons problems.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent John Walch said the dress code, adopted this
summer and distributed on the first day of school, will help make
schools safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a heightened awareness of real baggy shirts that can
hide weapons,'' he said. Exceptions will be made for students who
are pregnant or obese.
</P>
<P>
   While walkouts may be rare, student challenges to dress codes
are not, said Barbara Williams, a spokeswoman with the Texas
Association of School Boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the older grades, the kids are trying to express
themselves,'' Williams said. ``We've all been there,'' but there
are things that school officials can do to make dress codes more
acceptable, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think where they work best is when a district tries to meet
with parents ahead of time,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I frequently get frustrated calls from parents who think the
dress code is too vague. It needs to be clear from the top.''
</P>
<P>
   While Williams says the tension at Bastrop High should
eventually subside, Villasen(tilde)or hopes not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't walk all that way just for nothing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If students don't voice their opposition to rules like this one,
he said, the next step might be the unthinkable: uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody would go to school if they made us wear
uniforms,'' Villasen(tilde)or said.
</P>
<P>
   Bastrop students are not alone in questioning school dress
codes. At a recent meeting of the San Marcos ISD school board,
students and their supporters spent more than two hours debating a
dress code with school board members.
</P>
<P>
   Bastrop school district students' protests recently reversed a
board decision to prohibit the school band from going to
Disneyworld because of the Disney Corp.'s investment policies.
</P>
<P>
   What do you think of the students' action? Let us know at
www.austin360.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
