A6845 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEB-LULING04-COX     09-03 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEB-LULING04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEB in Luling to expand
 &HT;    By R. Michelle Breyer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LULING, Texas _ They set out close to 400 folding chairs in the
Luling Civic Center.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, every one was filled. Another hundred people
stood.
</P>
<P>
   Senior citizens sat next to newborn babies cradled in their
mothers' arms. Farm workers rubbed elbows with chiropractors. Ten
percent of Luling's population _ the same turnout as for the city's
last mayoral election _ gathered Tuesday night for the same reason:
groceries.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Luling came to tell the executives of H-E-B Food
Stores Inc. to replace their tiny, cramped, odoriferous H-E-B _ a
former Piggly Wiggly built more than 40 years ago that is the
town's only food store _ with something bigger and better.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the subject is groceries, people turn out,'' said Luling
Mayor Bryan Nickells.
</P>
<P>
   H-E-B didn't disappoint. Although Luling ranked 16th on a list
of 15 store locations slated for expansion or renovation in 1999,
with some last minute scrambling they swapped with Cleburne for the
15th slot. The room erupted with applause when H-E-B executives
announced the company would pour at least $3.5 million into a new
or renovated Luling store over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   In a place like Austin, where H-E-B has 34 stores and joins a
half-dozen other grocers, it's rare that residents get overzealous
about groceries. Next year alone, H-E-B has four new stores in the
works for Austin, including a new Central Market gourmet store.
</P>
<P>
   But in Luling, where residents have to drive miles if they want
anything more than the basics, a grocery store is not something to
be taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   The existing Luling H-E-B, on the corner of Walnut Street and
Highway 90, has less than 10,000 square feet. It looks more like a
convenience store than a supermarket. Inside, there's a strange
rotting smell that even H-E-B officials can't quite explain.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, most of H-E-B's new Austin grocery stores are
nearly eight times that size. The Luling store doesn't even look
like a distant cousin of H-E-B's fancy Central Market, with its
sushi chef, bins full of portobello mushrooms and arugula and
barrels of gourmet coffees.
</P>
<P>
   Luling _ the self-proclaimed Watermelon Capital of the World,
home of the annual Watermelon Thump _ is only about an hour's drive
from downtown Austin, but to some visitors, it's a world away.
</P>
<P>
   The oily smell of sour crude hangs in the air, rising from the
more than 100 pumping oil wells within the Luling city limits. The
city is home to the Central Texas Oil Patch Museum. And it boasts
some of the best barbecue in the state _ in the world, if you ask a
Luling resident.
</P>
<P>
   With fewer than 6,000 residents, Luling may be small by most
standards. But folks in this farming and oil town, in Southeast
Caldwell County, don't understand why they should have to drive 15
miles to Lockhart or 23 miles to San Marcos or 22 miles to Seguin
to buy the groceries they need at a full-service supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to the super Wal-Mart in San Marcos,'' said Robert J.
Carter, who was born in Luling in 1923 and has lived there ever
since. ``Nearly everybody here goes to the superstores to shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiropractor Walter Nickells _ a Luling city council member,
chamber board member and the youngest son of the city's mayor _
said he doesn't expect a fancy Simon David supermarket like the
ones he left behind in Dallas. But his wife refuses to shop at the
Luling H-E-B, which doesn't even stock diapers for their newborn
baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's embarrassing,'' Nickells said.
</P>
<P>
   For the business leaders of Luling, a town sandwiched between
fast-growing Austin and San Antonio, the flow of dollars outside
city borders has been a major concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an economic developer, I try to plug the leaks in the
community,'' said Trey Bailey, manager of the Luling Area Chamber
of Commerce. ``There's a tremendous amount of consumer dollars
leaving Luling. This is the biggest leak out of our barrel.''
</P>
<P>
   So at the beginning of 1997, Luling residents formed the
seven-member Grocery Retail Task Force. Although the task force
began meeting with H-E-B officials more than a year ago, the
answers were slow in coming, Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   With little concrete information, rumors circulated: H-E-B was
closing the Luling store; H-E-B was building a superstore in
Luling; another grocery chain might be coming to town.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a small town, if you don't know what's happening, you make
it up,'' Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Tuesday night, they got answers.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1 1/2-hour meeting, the citizens of Luling walked out
into the warm night with an air of triumph that comes with knowing
they could influence a multibillion-dollar corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Their feat is all the more amazing considering the competition
for H-E-B's capital.
</P>
<P>
   The $6 billion San Antonio-based grocery chain has 247 stores
and is growing rapidly, moving into new markets from the suburbs of
Dallas to Monterrey, Mexico. Because it is privately held _ still
owned by the Butt family that founded it 93 years ago in Kerrville
_ its growth is fueled solely by the company's profits. With thin
profit margins, each dollar spent must be carefully weighed. And
more often than not, that money goes into fast-growth areas like
Monterrey, where stores are bringing in $1 million a week.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, said Harvey Mabry, president of H-E-B's food and
drug division, smaller markets like Luling can have a tough time
competing. In these smaller markets, H-E-B has been remodeling,
expanding or building new stores in only two to three towns a year.
Last year, it was Burnet, Raymondville and Hondo.
</P>
<P>
   Luling's expansion was scheduled for 2000. But Mabry said he
didn't want to face hundreds of people with news they would have to
wait two more years for a new store. So on Monday, he urged H-E-B's
managing board to put Luling into the 15th slot. They agreed.
H-E-B's regional team will begin planning Luling's store this week.
One way or another, the project will be completed in 1999, Mabry
said.
</P>
<P>
   Luling leaders hope a new H-E-B store will bring more than just
better produce and more varieties of soup. They said they think a
better grocery store will even help attract more commerce and
residents to their city. Luling has been aggressively courting
small manufacturing plants to help diversify its economy _ an
economy once flush with oil money before the oil bust of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Mary French, a Luling real estate broker and 18-year resident of
the city, said Luling already is attracting people _ and they need
groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, she sold homes to families from Colorado and
Las Vegas _ people who could live anywhere else but were lured to
the peaceful, rural atmosphere of Luling, she said. With a median
home price of $58,000, it's more affordable than many of
communities around Austin, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But even with these attributes, the H-E-B has been a black eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm out here everyday, busting my buns, trying to sell this
community,'' French said. ``Then people come back from the H-E-B
and tell me 'My God, does it ever stink.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We deserve better.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
