<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 09:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6846 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATHAM-COLUMN04-COX     09-03 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The whole story of Bubba and how his mother changed her life
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I only knew Bubba for a short time. I talked with him maybe
twice, though if he said any words I don't remember them. I know
for sure he did not talk
</P>
<P>
   much if he spoke at all. And yet of all the people I've met in
my life as a journalist, I remember
</P>
<P>
   Bubba best.
</P>
<P>
   Bubba - that was his real name - was 10 when we met and dying.
He had a terrible condition with a terrible name that his mother,
who had given birth
</P>
<P>
   to Bubba when she was 15, could say as easily as if she had
earned a Harvard medical degree.
</P>
<P>
   But there was nothing ``Harvard'' about Bubba or his mother.
They lived in absolutely the sorriest trailer house I have ever
seen. The front door hung
</P>
<P>
   crooked off its hinges and the rust had almost eaten it through.
</P>
<P>
   They were too poor to own a refrigerator so they had a small ice
chest that kept things cool when they had enough money to buy ice,
which was almost
</P>
<P>
   never.
</P>
<P>
   It was in this environment that Bubba was living and dying. In
this place he was lovingly cared for by his mother, who sometimes
worked three jobs and sometimes worked none because she would get
fired for missing shifts while she was tending to her
terminally-ill son.
</P>
<P>
   Taking care of Bubba was more than wheeling him around in a
wobbly wheelchair -- which, as I recall, was too wide to go through
the narrow door of the trailer house. It also included the daily
unpleasant ritual of having to suck the mucus out of his lungs,
something Bubba could not do for himself.
</P>
<P>
   This happened within the first few minutes of meeting Bubba. He
began choking and I thought he was going to die right before my
eyes. His mother calmly got up, inserted a tube and saved her son's
life.
</P>
<P>
   Their lives were hard for a number of reasons, but particularly
because of a snag in the state law that allowed aid to be given to
sick children who had a chance to live, but not to children who
were within two years of being terminal cases. Bubba was 10, no one
with Bubba's condition had ever lived beyond 12.
</P>
<P>
   Aid denied.
</P>
<P>
   After I wrote about Bubba, the good folks of Angelina County,
Texas responded in a remarkable fashion. The family got a
refrigerator, contributions of all sorts and kinds and, not
surprisingly, the state reconsidered its denial. This was good
because Bubba would live four more years before he finally
succumbed.
</P>
<P>
   But that isn't all of this story and I didn't know the rest
until my telephone rang just this week.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bubba's mother.
</P>
<P>
   After Bubba died, she no longer had much of a purpose in living
-- after all, she'd spent almost all her energy taking care of the
boy. She went into a three-year downward spiral and plumbed the
depths of depression. She stayed in her bed and let the rundown
trailer house go filthy. She didn't work or eat much. She wanted
for all the world to die, just like her son.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day for no particular reason, she decided to get help
for her depression. When she took that first step, she began to
look around her andsee that where she was living had a significant
impact on how she was living. The people around her weren't helping
her overcome her pain and sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   So she moved out to Bonham and took a job as a waitress in a
restaurant. She began to live again, little by little, still poor,
but gaining on pride.
</P>
<P>
   After a while she met a good man who could listen to her
problems.
</P>
<P>
   They got married seven years ago and, with marriage came dreams.
She was a waitress, he could be a businessman. They could open a
restaurant, they
</P>
<P>
   thought.
</P>
<P>
   So on a wish and many prayers, they did just that.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of Los Amigos just off the square in Bonham happened
four, almost five, years ago now. It's a fixture in town and she
and her husband now own a house and rental property.
</P>
<P>
   And you know what she told me as she described her journey from
darkness into light?
</P>
<P>
   ``Praise be to God.''
</P>
<P>
   I can't speak for God, but I'd guess he's pretty impressed with
Bubba's mother himself.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is the editor and publisher of the Marshall News
Messenger
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
