<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FRIDAY COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Friday, September 4, 1998, are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ Early reports indicate that the nascent
Dan Burton ``scandal'' is mostly the tale of a lengthily troubled
marriage. This may bring off the almost impossible trick of turning
Dan Burton into a sympathetic figure. Didn't work for Bill Clinton,
but, what the hey, it's worth a try. (Rosenfeld, Cox News Service)
MOVED WEDNESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ TALLINN, Estonia _ I'm like most Americans
traveling in foreign countries. I recognize only two languages:
English and gibberish. So it was that the words on the pocket of
the Estonian border guard's uniform took the form of a warm
welcome, especially after traveling in Russia: ``Border Guard,'' it
said _ in English! (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED WEDNESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKMAN-COLUMN-1STLEDE _ A new economic system has emerged in
the past decade, founded on computer technology, fueled by
information, held together by an almost religious belief in the
sanctity of free markets and driven by a deep disdain for
centralized government, safety nets and any other restraint on
competition and personal enterprise. Now we're going to see whether
it holds together in a crisis. (Bookman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ After I wrote about Bubba, a terminally ill
child who lived in poverty, the good folks of Angelina County,
Texas responded in a remarkable fashion. This was good because
Bubba would live four more years before he finally succumbed. But
that isn't all of this story and I didn't know the rest until my
telephone rang just this week. It was Bubba's mother. (Latham,
Marshall News Messenger) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ ``Moving your daughter back to college, aren't
you,'' the woman said. ``Stuff's going to get wet. That Tropical
Storm Charley is heading right through here.'' Tropical Storm
Charley? Somehow I had missed that one, what with Bonnie churning
toward the East Coast. Charley slipped in without much attention,
at least from me, cutting across Southern and Central Texas and
dumping loads of rain. (Borders, Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel) MOVED.
</P>
