</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Taking us back to the ballpark
 &HT;    (For release, Sunday, Sept. 6, 1998)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa have done for baseball this
year, in addition to filling stadiums that otherwise would be near
empty, is return the sport to its raw basic: pitcher throws ball,
batter slams the bejabbers out of it.
</P>
<P>
   For too many recent years, the actual playing of the game has
been influenced by other elements, particularly pitching
terminology I cannot comprehend, or by calls by umpires that are
beyond our recognition.
</P>
<P>
   I have been going to baseball games for close to 60 years but
have never seen a balk. Oh, I've seen them called by umpires, but
I've never actually seen one. The only time baseball fans say they
see a balk is when it isn't one. That's when the pitcher wheels
toward third base, then first base, in an attempt to entrap base
runners and doesn't throw the ball to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a balk. What you can't see, apparently, is a balk.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, and without whipping out my baseball rules book,
a balk is something that happens when the pitcher moves in a way he
shouldn't move. He can be called for moving toward home plate, for
barely moving toward home plate, for imperceptibly moving toward
home plate, for subliminally moving toward home plate and, perhaps,
for thinking about moving toward home plate.
</P>
<P>
   Even instant replay fails to show me any of those moves, but the
expert commentator usually says he sees it, so I believe him; he
once played the game. ``There it is,'' the commentator will exclaim
during the replay. ``He twitched the pinky on his left hand. That's
a balk.''
</P>
<P>
   No, I didn't seem him twitch his pinky.
</P>
<P>
   This is similar to the game of hockey, where no one in the arena
sees the puck whiz past the goaltender, he included. Or in
basketball, where players are called for things such as a 3-second
violation, or illegal defense _ all imperceptible to me. Who ever
has seen the punch Muhammad Ali put on Sonny Liston in their Maine
rematch, and who ever saw a downed and writhing soccer player who
really was hurt?
</P>
<P>
   The game of baseball, until McGwire and Sosa brought it back to
earth, was getting too complicated. Growing up, I knew about fast
balls and curve balls, and made believe I understood the
then-terminology about pitches called inshoots and outshoots. And
there was a 1940s-era pitcher, Rip Sewell, who was blooping high,
arcing balls toward home plate. It was called an epheus pitch _
that word not in any of my dictionaries _ and at least I could see
it, going up and coming down.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we are into pitches I certainly cannot discern on the TV
screen, or in the ballpark; pitches such as the circle change, the
split-finger fastball, the cut fastball and the three-seam
something or other. What are they? Who, besides the expert
commentator, knows what they are _ and are those commentators
really bluffing us?
</P>
<P>
   One pitcher the other night was credited on TV with having four
or five different kinds of fastballs. I pondered that and decided
one kind must be 92 miles an hour, another 93 miles an hour, and so
on.
</P>
<P>
   I can separate a fastball from a curve ball, and can spot a
change-up because the batter is fooled into swinging early, but a
circle change? What's that?
</P>
<P>
   Baseball had been slipping past me recently. I was losing touch
with the game because I did not understand the ever-changing
terminology and was doubly confused with baseball players putting
only four fingers into gloves with five-finger openings.
</P>
<P>
   Now I can ignore that for a while. Thanks to McGwire, Sosa and
others, the unsophisticated art of simply crushing a baseball out
of the park has regenerated an interest in baseball that you
couldn't attain in recent years, certainly not with that three-seam
something or other.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
