<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 09:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6855 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN06-COX     09-03 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: As world heats up, Clinton frozen in place
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton has returned from what we may fairly,
alas, call the Pathetic Summit to a worsening sink of foreign
problems that steamy, seamy Monicamess leaves him little authority
to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   The president either must find a way, as he and his dwindling
claque like to say, to put this thing behind him (his testimony-day
speechlet suited most of the public but not his scammed colleagues)
or he must think what is to him nearly unthinkable. He must think
of getting out of the way and letting Vice President Al Gore take
command.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, Clinton is running an empty presidency. The drain had
begun even before the mea-first culpa in which the president
admitted to whoopee he had denied to the public in general and to
his closest circle in person. Like a kid who has wasted his
allowance on trifles, the president has nothing to spend at the end
of the week and nothing to show for what he had at the beginning of
it.
</P>
<P>
   This Monica-borne weakness was already implicated when Clinton,
rather than definitively confronting Saddam Hussein last spring
over Iraq's disruption of arms inspections, took eager refuge in
the uncertain diplomatic shelter U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
had arranged.
</P>
<P>
   The weakness showed, too, when the president cut Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright off at the knees after she had set a
deadline for Israeli movement in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton couldn't stand up to a Congress charging that the
administration was dictating to Israel, when Albright was intending
only to set out U.S. guidelines for an eventual settlement _
admittedly additional pressure on Israel but hardly marching
orders. The peace process is now mired both in Israel's internal
political standoff and in Clinton's own political bog.
</P>
<P>
   The president's trip to an economically and politically
imploding Russia was marginally useful in its show of U.S. concern
_ and canceling it would have flashed exactly the wrong semaphore _
but Clinton could bring no credible message of durable U.S.
commitment. He is too ephemeral a figure himself for that.
</P>
<P>
   Unfairly but to ill effect even so, the president's motive was
widely questioned when he struck back at terrorists who had bombed
two U.S. embassies; his domestic predicament makes such doubts
inevitable. And with timing as exquisite as Jack Benny's, though he
isn't half as funny, Saddam Hussein has run the arms inspectors off
again_ and looks likely to get away with it because the White House
can rally no multilateral effort against him.
</P>
<P>
   India and Pakistan have taken up nuclear arms. North Korea says
it still forswears them but is sly about it and has started lobbing
ballistic missiles into Japan's seas. And the Serbs are once again
getting away with murder, this time in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   None of these matters is wholly a result of the president's
troubles at home but each is being left to drift dangerously
because of those troubles. A victim both of his own misadventures
and of a political vendetta that finagled subpoena power, Clinton
is preoccupied with his political survival. That's understandable.
It is not acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 0949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 09:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6856 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEANIE04-COX     09-03 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEANIE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boy to sell Beanie Baby to help mom
 &HT;    By Aaron Porter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTROSE, Colo. _ The furor over Beanie Babies, stuffed animals
tagged with ``personal information'' about the doll, has reached a
fevered pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to cash in on the craze, Cody Davis plans to sell one of
his prized Beanie Babies to finance his mother's cancer treatment
next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to keep him,'' said 11-year-old Cody, ``but not if it
can help Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   The Davis family was floored when his mother Nancy was diagnosed
with an extremely aggressive form of breast cancer in April.
Thought to be in a low-risk category, Nancy can only wonder what
caused the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we knew what gave her cancer,'' Cody said, ``because
we'd never do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Cody's grandparents obtained a Beanie Baby called ``Glory'' for
him while attending the 1998 Major League Baseball All Star Game in
Denver. Covered with stars, the small bear is kept in a plastic
case with a ticket stub from the game and a certificate of
authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   To raise money for his mother's treatment, bids are being
accepted on ``Glory'' through Sept. 12. The highest bidder gets the
doll, Cody said.
</P>
<P>
   A Beanie Baby collector for some time, Cody now has 31 of the
stuffed dolls, all wrapped in plastic and sitting on a shelf. They
are not for playing, the fifth-grader said adamantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like collecting them,'' Cody explained.
</P>
<P>
   His interest in Beanie Babies is not unusual. According to Dora
Cornman, owner of the Hallmark Shop in Montrose, people of all ages
and all walks of life spend ``megabucks'' on their burgeoning
collections.
</P>
<P>
   Some simply like the stuffed animals, but most see it as a
financial investment, Cornman said. The craze has inflated prices
on some dolls dramatically, with Beanie Babies retailing for less
than $6 being sold to collectors for hundreds of dollars, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the buyer needs to be aware and understand what
they're investing in,'' Cornman said with a laugh. ``It's like the
stock market.''
</P>
<P>
   Cody hopes for a good return, because the Davis family's
insurance company is unwilling to pay for the $50,000 cancer
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy is scheduled for a stem-cell transplant at Rocky Mountain
Cancer Center in September. During the cutting-edge treatment,
doctors will remove stem cells from her bone marrow, bombard her
body with high doses of chemotherapy, then replace the stem cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very confident that it's going to turn out OK,'' Nancy
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis family attributes their ability to cope with the
cancer to a deep-seated faith in God.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hang onto our faith in God,'' Nancy said. ``We're trying
not to dwell on the scary part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that they have come through this real good and through
their faith they've really coped with the trial that they're going
through,'' said their pastor, Ronnie Hanna of Montrose Christian
Church.
</P>
<P>
   Bids for the doll are being accepted by Cody, care of General
Delivery, Montrose Post Office, Montrose CO 91401.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 0951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
