<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6876 &Cx1f; tad-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV05-C     09-03 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: AS DOLLARS WENT WEST, RUBLES WENT SOUTH
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Sept. 6.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If Russia had a government, it would be flat broke.
Before being shown the door, the prior government defaulted on $40
billion in short-term debt _ money that was mostly sucked out of
the country with its connivance by the ruling oligarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the dollars that the International Monetary Fund had
been shoveling into Russia to keep what amounted to an official
Ponzi scheme going are gone. Many of those dollars left in
ruble-to-dollar transfers, to be stashed in distant safe havens.
</P>
<P>
   What remained of the IMF loans went back into the pockets of
Western bankers and governments _ repaying earlier credits that,
left unrepaid, would have accelerated the debacle. Precious little
went to develop natural resources, where it would have done the
most good.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was too much to hope that, after 70 years of
stultifying communism, reform would take hold. But there's really
no way of knowing, because real reform has never been tried in
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   How Russia's oligarchs, ensconced in their armored limousines,
must have snickered into their cell phones over President Clinton's
pep talk to the Moscow university students. Listening to his brave
words, they must have imagined that Clinton lives on another
planet, which, in a sense, he does.
</P>
<P>
   Still, on this planet, missile flight trumps capital flight.
Even if the IMF fails to pay up, an embittered Russia is not about
to revive the Cold War or threaten to start a hot one with
Washington. But a new Kremlin strongman could revive old
relationships with the likes of Libya, Iraq and Syria, undoubtedly
involving military technology transfers. And that in turn imperils
Western interests.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF mandarins in Washington recognize those risks. At the
same time, they are no mood to fork over the next installment of
the remaining $23 billion rescue package _ on the reasonable
grounds that it would be wasted and stolen as well. So what to do?
</P>
<P>
   One solution making the top-level rounds here would do away with
the ruble and put Russia on a firm all-dollar diet. A fully
convertible ruble would have the same result, besides saving any
remaining shreds of Russian honor. In either case, just so many
rubles would circulate _ backed by dollar reserves.
</P>
<P>
   As matters stand, Russians already hold more dollars than
rubles, some $40 billion versus merely $8.5 billion of their own
diluted currency. In fact, more U.S. greenbacks remain in Russian
hands than circulate in the United States, where checks, credit
cards and electronic transfers are the norm in settling debts.
</P>
<P>
   A glut of oil and other commodities has caused world prices to
plunge, sending a fatal monetary torpedo crashing into an already
listing Russian hull. Ironically, Russia faces the prospect of
hyperinflation at a time when deflation poses the biggest risk to
most other major countries.
</P>
<P>
   Making the dollar Russia's reserve currency would free up IMF
funding. It may bring out of hiding stashes of $100 bills tucked
into cookie jars or parked in foreign bank vaults. They would then
be available to pay workers and buy raw materials, giving the
Russian people yet another chance to make a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
