<HEADER>
A6984 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     09-03 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, Sept. 3, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-CANCER (San Francisco) _ Joy Fudem had gone through
radiation, three kinds of hormonal therapies, hit her limit on
chemotherapy and undergone a bone marrow transplant when she
learned last year that she finally was picked in a lottery to
receive the experimental breast cancer drug Herceptin. Soon, women
with Fudem's kind of cancer won't have to rely on chance to get
Herceptin, the first genetically-engineered breast cancer drug. By
ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INVESTMENT-CLUB (Cohoes, N.Y.) _ Arnold Galarneau was ready for
the meeting of his investment club with a file folder full of
research on stocks the club might buy in the wake of Monday's stock
market plunge. So the Dow Jones Industrial Average plunged more
than 512 points on Monday. To Galarneau, it was just an
overreaction. By JO-ANN JOHNSTON.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-LUNCHES (Albany, N.Y.) _ It's the start of the annual
parental back-to-school quandary over what to pack their kids for
lunch. ``It's a tough situation for parents because they want to
send a school lunch that's reasonably healthy and nutritious, but
it has to be something their child will actually eat or it just
sits in the lunch box and does nobody any good,'' said
nutritionist. By PAUL GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTING-ART (Albany, N.Y.) _ The landed gentry in America began
commissioning sporting art in the early 19th century, with Edward
Troye (1808-1874) among the more prominent during this time.
Another artist, George Stubbs, was among the first to study the
anatomy of the horse. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Bill Clinton had to go Russia to
get away from Monica. Willie Brown has to go to China to get away
from questions about San Francisco's bus system, Muni.
Unfortunately for Brown, he doesn't leave for two weeks. Who knows
what could happen? Angry voters could storm City Hall _ if they
don't mind walking to the Civic Center. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-POLITICS (San Francisco) _ In politics, sometimes it's
better to be lucky than good. Just how good Matt Fong is remains
unclear, but he seems lucky. The Republican nominee for Senate is
running against pro-Clinton Democratic incumbent Barbara Boxer at a
time when a lot of people are disgusted with the president. And
Fong is a symbol of hope for Chinese Americans who yearn for
political legitimacy. By WILLIAM WONG.
</P>
<P>
   WWII-SURRENDER (San Francisco) _ Thursday was the 53rd
anniversary of the unconditional surrender of Japan. The insistence
on unconditional surrender is one of the World War II's most
important and meaningful legacies. Whether or not it is a legacy
worth continuing depends on which we want more: peace, or a pause
between wars. By CYNTHIA BASS.
</P>
</TEXT>
