<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONG-BULL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 No. 484 for Sept. 3.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Sept. 2-3, 1998. We're with you, Christie Brinkley! No one
should take you less seriously just because you take your clothes
off for Playboy at your age, and we do realize the gravity of your
situation, says the Burned-Out Newspapercreatures Guild, and this
is BONG Bull No. 484!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAUGHT. &LR;  Old habits die hard in this business. But Rory
Thompson of InformationWeek magazine caught the unattributed quote
in BB 483. It was Rear Adm. Grace Hopper who said it. Thompson's
colleague Senior Editor Rich Levin includes the following in his
e-mail signature, according to Thompson:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much easier to apologize than to get permission.'' _ RADM
Grace Hopper (1906-1992), co-inventor of the COBOL programming
language, pioneer computer programmer, and the woman incorrectly
credited with coining the word `bug' to describe a software
defect.''
</P>
<P>
   (Incorrectly credited? Yes, there is such a thing as
overcrediting.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE 6-POINT BENDAY RULE. &LR;  What college-educated professional
can forget the day the senior professor of the journalism
department came into the classroom in that last week of class, sent
all the audit students and other guests out, locked the door and
solemnly intoned the holy writ of the 6-Point Benday Rule? Not
Gerard Farrell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think most J-schools even teach the 6-Point Benday
Rule anymore, much less require students to memorize or recite it.
Me? I've got it engraved in a brass plaque hanging over my desk,
and try to live by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrell, though not quite professing journalism but certainly
employed by a major Southwestern institution of higher tuition,
reminisced, ``As I recall from my student days (I was an English
major and journalism minor at The University of Texas), the only
thing any J-school prof ever required us to memorize, other than
our own names and the general area of campus where the class was
taught, was the First Amendment. 'Tis true; Marvin Olasky used it
as the single question in his daily 10-point quiz about six times
during the summer session, on an all-or-nothing grading system.
Misplace a comma? That's a zero; now go petition the government for
the redress of your grievance.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIND CANDY. &LR;  Isn't someone supposed to be checking the water in
New York? Is there a paper glut that other publishers haven't heard
about? Don't offer your novel to Ballantine unless it's the caliber
of their new release, ``How To Heal the Hurt by Hating,'' by
performance artist Anita Liberty (139 pp., $10.95, paperback).
</P>
<P>
   Liberty is in fact comedian Suzanne Weber.
</P>
<P>
   She begins, ``My boyfriend, Mitchell, whom I dated for three and
a half years, left me for a woman named Heather and, to get even, I
have devoted my entire career to humiliating him in public.''
</P>
<P>
   A sample of her thought: ``I used to have dreams that Mitchell
came back to me. I still do. But now I call them nightmares.''
</P>
<P>
   (Full disclosure statement: Ballantine rejected BONG Chief
Copyboy Charley Stough's blockbuster novel this week and, to get
even, he has devoted his entire career to publicizing the next
press release Ballantine sent in. Any public humiliation is their
doing. Dang, it's great to be a columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMIX SECTION. &LR;  The Further Adventures of Herman ``Speed''
Graphic, Ace Photographer for the Chagrin Falls Commercial
Scimitar, and his Faithful Companion, Typo the Wonder Pig.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PANEL ONE: &LR;  The Deft Duo zoom to Russia and Ireland with the
presidential expedition, using the copy desk coffee urn, which
converts to a low-orbit rocket with the addition of a Do-Good
Pellet from the pocket of Speed's trenchcoat, a deathbed gift from
an ancient mystic wire service executive editor on a fog-shrouded
Eastern island.
</P>
<P>
   Typo warns, ``Stash the urn carefully, Boss! This use renders
the contents a potent aphrodisiac! Only copy editors are immune!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PANEL TWO: &LR;  Speed defends, ``I don't think there ARE any
contents left, Typo! One taste, and those Russian guys dumped it
all on the radioactive steppes!''
</P>
<P>
   Typo suggests, ``Well, it would've been different if the women
over there didn't eat so many onions!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PANEL THREE: &LR;  Speed marvels, ``I just love the Irish, don't
you, Typo? Always colorful groups parading nowhere, and the crowds
responding with such heavy confetti, and the police and army
tossing back rubber bullets! It's almost like New Orleans Mardi
Gras!''
</P>
<P>
   Typo explains, ``Um, yes, well, just let me write the captions
on this batch, Boss! But wait! Look, in that riverdancing SWAT
team, it's Ursula, my unrequited love! Ursula, Ursula, you've come
back to me...!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PANEL FOUR: &LR;  Before Speed can intervene, the panel is obscured
by popout lettering reading kataSTOMP kataSTOMP kataSTOMP
kataSTOMP!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PANEL FIVE: &LR;  Speed comforts his pal, declaring, ``Just lie
easy, Typo! Amnesty International is sending a contusion team!''
</P>
<P>
   Typo responds, ``Never mind that, Boss! Wasn't she wonderful in
those tapboots? Is there any wonder the music is so popular? Can
you see why I love her so hopelessly...?''
</P>
<P>
   Front-row center for the kick dancing, BONG Chief Copyboy
Charley Stough, Dayton Daily News, 45 S. Ludlow St., Dayton, Ohio
45401 high- signs NYTNS bruisers worldwide. E-mail
copyboy(at)dma.org. Phone (937) 225-2445 after 5 p.m. eastern. Fax
225-2489.
</P>
