<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV08-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JOYS OF CLAMMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday Sept. 8)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a close-up look at job satisfaction go roam a mud flat with
a clammer on an summer morning before the sun comes up.
</P>
<P>
   Clamming is plain, honest labor, no frills, no middle
management, no job evaluation. You have your clamming permit, your
boat, your boots, your clamming fork. You hone in on the clams,
dig, deliver and get paid before you go home.
</P>
<P>
   The clammer does not worry about being replaced by a computer or
forced into early retirement. Like a ballet dancer, the clammer can
work as long as his knees hold up.
</P>
<P>
   My nephew digs clams in the waters off Ipswich, Mass., where
he's lived since he was a toddler.
</P>
<P>
   He says of the life, ``It's simple and it's good.'' He loves the
freedom, the exercise and getting to work in his favorite place in
the world. He isn't making a fortune but he's the least stressed
person in my family.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:30 in the morning Paul wades out from Eagle Hill landing to
where his boat is anchored. A full moon dangles just over his head
and the water is as calm as a pond. Soon there is the pre-dawn
growling of motors from a dozen or so boats and greetings among men
who look and talk like extras in ``Good Will Hunting.'' They drive
off like they're in a road race, hand on the throttle, balancing
coffee mug and cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   It is cold and the light is just becoming rosy as we zing past
moored sailboats and sleeping cottages and come to a place where
you can hear waves breaking but can't see them. A clump of Plum
Island stands between us and the actual Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   The mud is lumpy and full of puddles and tiny craters, like a
brown gooey moon surface. Paul grabs a wire basket, an onion bag
and starts digging.
</P>
<P>
   Clammers here seek the soft shelled Ipswich clam named for the
town. What they come up with today will end up in local clam
shacks, Boston restaurants and on fancy seafood menus around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The skill is in knowing where to go and working fast. Paul fills
a basket with about 35 pounds of clams in 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Clammers work at the whim and order of Mother Nature. They dig
at low tide, starting two hours before the tide gets to its lowest
point, which on this day is 8 a.m. and then two hours after.
</P>
<P>
   The flats have been closed for five days because of rain and
there's a hurricane warning down the coast. Whenever there's a
half-inch of rain there's an automatic rainfall closure because of
runoff pollution into the water. ``You have to give the clams time
to clean themselves,'' Paul explains.
</P>
<P>
   Now each clammer hurriedly stakes a territory, not crowding each
other but getting close enough to yell out if they had something to
say. Mostly they don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a bunch of lonely old boys,'' Paul says with a smile
when I ask him what he thinks about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women. Or you focus on the work or plan the rest of your
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Bent over their work, clammers look like those wooden bottoms-up
cutouts people put on their lawns that are supposed to resemble a
gardener perched over her petunias.
</P>
<P>
   There are two styles of bending, with locked knees or doing a
little bounce and keeping the knees loose. Paul does the latter.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first basket your body loosens up,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Up close all you hear are the sounds of fork hitting shell and
boots lifting out of sucking mud. Here's the rule: Push the toe in
and pull the heel up to disengage your boot.
</P>
<P>
   Paul was 10 years old the first time his father, a newspaper
editor and occasional recreational clammer, took him out. ``My back
killed me. I thought this is crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he says, ``This is God's country. No people, no traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   There also are no restrooms and nobody nearby with a muffin
cart.
</P>
<P>
   Clammers smell of sweat and Skin So Soft, the all-purpose bug
fighter that people on this shore are more allegiant to than
sunscreen.
</P>
<P>
   Bugs are the clammer's nemesis. The north shore gets chewed up
every summer by greenheads, which cling and bite like horseflies,
but clammers dread the midgies. They can swarm on a person like a
scene in African Queen, burrowing into the hair, nose and ears.
Sometimes even when it's hot and humid, Paul wears a turtleneck and
a bandanna over his ears and nose to thwart the midgies. They're
bad at sunrise and sunset but today we're in luck. Maybe the
midgies got stuck overnight in Essex.
</P>
<P>
   Paul doesn't wear gloves but sticks his bare hands deep into the
muck. ``It's the only way to feel the clams,'' he says. Unlike
modern fishing and lobstering, which uses sonar detection, the
clammer has only his hands and his sixth sense to sleuth out the
clams.
</P>
<P>
   It makes it more fair, says Paul. ``Clams have more of a chance
than lobsters do.''
</P>
<P>
   He digs 180 pounds which is the maximum limit each day. At $2 a
pound, the primo price for Ipswich digger, that's $360 and it's not
even lunch time.
</P>
<P>
   As he pilots us home through the thick green maze of the marsh
grasses some Canada geese fly over. Paul grins like Leonardo
DiCaprio at the bow of the Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for the Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
