<SLUG> BC-SPORTING-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTING ART A WINNER WITH THE LANDED GENTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Sporting art became popular in England in the
early to mid-18th century, when artists began depicting the
favorite and prized animals of their patrons or royalty.
</P>
<P>
   Early scenes were of fox-hunting and racing. Most artists worked
in oils, for which they could charge more than drawings or
watercolors.
</P>
<P>
   The landed gentry in America began commissioning sporting art in
the early 19th century, with Edward Troye (1808-1874) among the
more prominent during this time, according to John von Stade,
president of the National Museum of Racing and Hall of Fame in
Saratoga Springs, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   George Stubbs was the first of the sporting artists to study the
anatomy of the horse, delineating from the outer skin to the
skeleton, von Stade said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early sporting artists depicted horses to look like rocking
horses, where the two front legs went in a forward direction and
the two rear went backwards,'' von Stade said. ``But Stubbs painted
them the way they really looked, especially when moving under
various gates, from a walk to a gallop. He defined the athletic
anatomy of the horse. Stubbs was the most original of all sporting
and animal painters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men dominated this field until the later part of the 19th
century, when there were a few women artists,'' von Stade said.
``But even then, they were far and few between until the 20th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Some artists collaborated. ``One artist would paint the
landscape and background, while another artist would paint the
animals and figures,'' von Stade said.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the painting usually depended on the materials at
hand, which ranged from canvas to wood, how much the patron valued
their animal and what they would be willing to pay.
</P>
<P>
   According to von Stade, early sporting art by noted painters
sell anywhere today from $25,000 to $500,000. Works by Stubbs and
British artist Sir Alfred Munnings, who died in 1959, have sold for
more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Famous sporting painter Benjamin Marshall was well known for his
hunting, racing and game shooting scenes. ``I discovered many a man
who will pay me 50 guineas for painting his horse, who thinks 10
guineas too much for painting his wife,'' he once said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 1155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 12:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7076 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KUWAIT-IRAQ-$ADV05-CO     09-03 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KUWAIT-IRAQ-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KUWAITIS WARILY WATCH U.S. POLICY ON IRAQ, QUESTION ITS
INTENTIONS
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Sept. 5 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox Newspapers 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUWAIT CITY, Kuwait _ Billboards in this modern, rebuilt capital
warn the people of this oil-rich nation not to forget their POWs --
the more than 600 thought to be held in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   A few bombed-out buildings downtown still stand like incongruous
war memorials amid the gleaming towers of the sterile city.
</P>
<P>
   And every Kuwaiti has a tale of their life under or flight from
Iraqi occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait's citizens are keenly aware that Iraqi leader Saddam
Hussein still rules and blusters just beyond the border of their
two countries, posing a constant threat. And, they closely followed
recent reports that the United States is allegedly changing its
strategy for keeping Hussein in check.
</P>
<P>
   But they take comfort in the 3,500 U.S. troops out in the
deserts protecting their cities. Also, many in Kuwait -- both the
740,000 Kuwaiti citizens and their 1.1 million foreign workers --
are just tired of the annual Saddam-inspired crises.
</P>
<P>
   They have played host to Hussein's invasion and then Desert
Shield, Storm and Sabre. They stocked up on gas masks when last
year's Desert Thunder looked like another war-in-the-making. Their
newspapers report on the ongoing ``Intrinsic Action'' exercises
that keep American and Kuwaiti troops in shape.
</P>
<P>
   Many say that, unless the United States is serious about
knocking Hussein out of power, they would rather avoid the huge
military build-ups that have raised regional blood pressures in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   It looks like they are in for a quieter United States, for now.
</P>
<P>
   Compare today to last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Hussein closed the door on United Nations weapons
inspections in eight of his palaces. The U.S. aircraft carriers and
troops of Desert Thunder swooped into the region. With American
officials saying that diplomacy will not work without the threat of
force, the build-up continued until a U.N. agreement diffused the
crisis in February.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Hussein went further in cutting off all new
inspections. But the United States has not increased its forces in
Kuwait. Instead, it awaits action from the U.N., which is holding
Iraq under the weight of crushing economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwaitis look on with concern, but also a case of what might be
called build-up fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very much sure about the solid position of the United
States vis-a-vis Iraq,'' said Sulaiman Majed Al-shaheen(CQ),
under-secretary of the Kuwaiti Ministry of Foreign Affairs, in a
recent interview with Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe our friends in the United States realize . . . that when
Saddam Hussein says a word, we find that there is an alert, a
warning, the moving of carriers to the gulf. Suddenly, we find that
everything becomes so calm,'' Al-shaheen said. ``That game costs
that much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides that, there is the accusation, whether it be right or
wrong,'' he added carefully, ``that the United States comes to the
(Persian) Gulf only to show and not to take actions.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Al-shaheen said, unanimity on the U.N. Security Council
will ensure that Iraq is controlled.
</P>
<P>
   He does not hold the United States responsible for removing
Hussein, and said he is not worried about reports that the United
States is going for a lower-profile policing of Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Those reports gained momentum last month after Scott Ritter,
leader of one of the U.N. inspection teams, quit his job, while
accusing the United States of taking the teeth out of the program
that is supposed to find and destroy Hussein's chemical and
biological weapons ``of mass destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritter's comments prompted Congressional criticism, with House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., sounding out about a ``weak
response'' to Hussein's latest violations and Senate leaders saying
they would investigate the Clinton administration's policy.
</P>
<P>
   But, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright denied
discouraging inspections or that the United States' overall policy
has changed. The U.S. goal, she said is still to keep economic
sanctions on Iraq until it gives up its weapons and until Hussein
complies with other U.N. requirements, including the payment of
reparations for war damage.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has asked the U.N. not to even consider
lifting the sanctions until Iraq complies with the inspections,
prompting Hussein to threaten new, unspecified retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been different tools used at different times,''
said a state department official. ``We're not being as militaristic
this time . . . this time we're not playing his game, we're playing
our game.''
</P>
<P>
   February's crisis was diffused when U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan traveled to Baghdad and secured an agreement with Hussein.
But, there had clearly been little support in the Arab world for
U.S. military action and France and Russia, members of the security
council, were hesitant. With this latest defiance, Hussein seems to
have snubbed all those countries and Annan -- not just America.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, U.S. troops patrol and train in the desert, which
sometimes reaches a baking 140 degrees. Officials say the current
contingent is enough to strike Hussein, if needed.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great experimentation ground for new ideas,'' said Sgt.
Brian Goodknight(CQ), 42, who is based at Fort McPherson in
Georgia, and supplies the training equipment. ``We know we have to
employ heavy combat units to answer the threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Collins, an expert in political military studies at the
Center for Strategic and International Studies in Washington, said
the new policy emphasis does not mean the United States has given
in to Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins, a retired U.S. Army colonel, said U.S. policy has
been poorly spelled out by a president distracted by a domestic
scandal and a host of other foreign policy problems -- from North
Korean missile testing to the Russian economic and political
crisis. That will make allies doubt the strength of America's stand
against Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said the Clinton administration should work harder to
unseat Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   That would sit well with many Kuwaitis. They are fond of
Americans and grateful for their war effort -- the Kuwaiti
government built the new $30 million U.S. embassy as a gift and
named a luxury apartment building after former President George
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But, many say that America is using the Hussein threat to keep
its troops in the oil-rich region.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the United States wanted to get rid of Saddam, they could
with one finger,'' said Khaled Al-hassan(CQ), a 31-year-old Kuwaiti
soldier headed with his wife for a vacation in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks President Clinton is mainly interested in keeping oil
prices low, and pre-occupied with both Monica Lewinsky and Saudi
terrorist Osama bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Hamani Al-khatan(CQ), 25, said that seven years after
the Iraqi invasion, she does not like to dwell on Hussein's
continued threat.
</P>
<P>
   But while she and her country have moved on and rebuilt their
prosperous daily lives, despite him, she said ``my mind works all
the time. In the heart and mind, we have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
