<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7077 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRISONER-BERENSON-$AD     09-03 1802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISONER-BERENSON-$ADV06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PARENTS RACE THE CLOCK IN FIGHT TO FREE DAUGHTER FROM PERUVIAN
PRISON
 &HT;    With Rick McKay photos placed in the International folder on the
Cox Server.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Sept. 6 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The kind of call any parent would dread woke Rhoda
Berenson from a deep slumber one Friday evening in early December
1995.
</P>
<P>
   The woman on the other end said she was from the U.S. State
Department. Berenson's daughter, Lori, had been arrested in Peru.
The charge, she thought, was terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   A second call -- this one even more disturbing -- came three
days later over a crackling line, 4,000 miles away, from a panicked
Lori.
</P>
<P>
   She said only four things: The charges were ``preposterous.''
She needed a lawyer. She wanted shoes and underwear. And, her
American Express card must be cancelled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was all some kind of misunderstanding,'' explains
Rhoda Berenson, 55, speaking in the patient tones of someone who's
told the story before. ``That the U.S. government would quickly
sort it out.''
</P>
<P>
   That was 998 days ago, as Berenson's number-minded husband,
Mark, quickly makes clear during an interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the lives of the gregarious, middle-class college
professors has had more intrigue than a James Bond movie.
</P>
<P>
   Their daughter was indeed arrested Nov. 30, 1995, at the tender
age of 26. She was accused of being an upper-echelon member of the
Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement, or MRTA, a violent Marxist
group that was reputedly planning to kidnap members of Peru's
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Berensons hired two attorneys: Thomas Nooter, who
successfully defended a suspect in the World Trade Center bombing,
and Ramsey Clark, a former U.S. attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   But it did little good.
</P>
<P>
   The Berensons call the secret military trial that followed their
daughter's arrest ``a sham.''
</P>
<P>
   Unable to challenge evidence or cross-examine witnesses, Lori
was found guilty of treason on Jan. 11, 1996 by a hooded judge she
never saw.
</P>
<P>
   Their hazel-eyed baby who grew up to sing and play clarinet was
sentenced to life in the notoriously grim Yanamayo prison, perched
on a wind-swept plain high in the frigid, inhospitable Andes of
southeastern Peru.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that powerful people have raised concerns over
a flawed judicial system: President Clinton, former President
Carter, and, most notably, Peru's former prime minister, Javier
Valle Riestra.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that a hard-nosed Peruvian president has, so
far, been unyielding.
</P>
<P>
   President Alberto Fujimori paints a disturbing picture of the
woman he calls ``Comrade Lucia,'' a rebel mastermind who helped run
the safe house where guerrillas had trained for their attack on the
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Berensons admit that their daughter had become somewhat of a
stranger as she stumbled toward adulthood, but insist she is not,
and never was, a terrorist, even if she had associations with the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the New Yorker was part of a terrorist body or
simply a left-leaning do-gooder is no longer the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The burning question today is whether Lori received due process
of the law.
</P>
<P>
   The Berenson's plea for a new trial in a civilian court was
turned down by the Supreme Military Tribunal on July 30.
</P>
<P>
   But the fight's not over yet.
</P>
<P>
   Their last and only hopes are an appeal before the Organization
of American States, or that a more-conciliatory Peruvian government
will have a change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   At stake: nothing less than their daughter's life.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Helene Berenson was raised along with an older sister,
Kathy, in a spacious but nondescript apartment in the Gramercy Park
section of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   She was a straight-A student at the LaGuardia High School of
Performing Arts, who often volunteered at soup kitchens and blood
banks.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Lori was everything a parent could hope for.
</P>
<P>
   She went on to study anthropology at the prestigious
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, which led to two study trips
to El Salvador at a time when Central America's civil wars were in
full swing.
</P>
<P>
   She became keenly interested in the roots of conflict, poverty
and inequality, so much so that she dropped out of school in 1989
to move to Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   She also became increasingly distant from her family and
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Letters to her parents were sporadic, arriving every month or
so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always assumed she would eventually go back to school,''
Rhoda Berenson said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Lori moved to Peru in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
   She obtained accreditation letters from two left-leaning U.S.
publications and told her parents that she hoped to write about the
effect of widespread poverty on Peruvian women.
</P>
<P>
   But the picture the Berensons have of their daughter through
letters and phone calls --observer, traveler, journalist -- is very
different from the one that emerged after Lori's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Peruvian authorities say they have evidence of a 1994 meeting in
Ecuador between Lori and rebel leader, Nestor Cerpa Cartolini --
who helped invade the Japanese ambassador's house in Lima and died
when it was retaken in April 1997 -- and that it was on his orders
that she agreed to help attack the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Berensons say she never knew the man.
</P>
<P>
   Since the trial was secret, it's hard to make an independent
assessment of any of the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   What has become clear, however, is that Lori may have been her
own worst enemy during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the proceeding, Lori was led before television
cameras to make a public statement, which is customary in terrorism
trials. Her eyes looked wild; her hair unruly. Shouting, she
appeared angry and defiant.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is a crime to worry about the subhuman conditions in
which the majority of this population lives, then I will accept my
punishment,'' she screamed.
</P>
<P>
   The Berensons say her appearance was a set-up, that the
government riled Lori by holing her up with a wounded inmate prior
to her appearance. She had no comb, and was forced to yell because
there was no microphone.
</P>
<P>
   But it was like waving a flag before a bull: the judge gave her
life, even after prosecutors requested a 30-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Lori was convicted under a special judicial system created by
Fujimori in 1992 as part of his crackdown on terrorist groups such
as MRTA and Shining Path.
</P>
<P>
   Peru holds some 4,000 political prisoners accused of supporting
various rebel groups, in turn accused of having killed more than
30,000 people since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   With a 97 percent conviction rate, the system's been criticized
by human rights groups around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lori's trial didn't meet international standards,'' said
Carlos Salinas, a spokesman for Amnesty International in Washington
D.C. ``Lori was never allowed to put on a proper defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Lori bides her time in a 6-foot by 10-foot cell in one of
Latin America's harshest prisons. Just last month, the Paris-based
International Federation for Human Rights demanded the facility be
closed due to inhumane conditions.
</P>
<P>
   At 12,000 feet, the Yanamayo prison rarely gets above 40
degrees, a temperature made worse by the icy winds that whip off
Lake Titicaca. Meals, and a bucket of ice-cold water daily, are
disbursed through a hatch in the cell's door. Lori sleeps under
eight blankets, and is allowed outside only an hour a day.
</P>
<P>
   At least once a month, either Mark or Rhoda Berenson makes the
4,000 mile, two-day trek to the prison -- located some 525 miles
southeast of Lima -- where they're allowed an hour with their
daughter, who's always separated from them by a screen. Each trip
costs $1,400.
</P>
<P>
   They generally bring more than 60 pounds of food and toiletries
with them at a time, and through the months they've learned the
idiosyncracies of prison guards: No pen caps or shoe laces; shampoo
must be poured into clear, plastic bags so it is visible.
</P>
<P>
   Once the guards forced Mark Berenson to unwrap hundreds of Halls
cough drops so that they could be inspected.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people usually count the grapes we bring in,'' he said.
``You never know what they're going to make you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhoda Berenson said that during her most recent visit, on Aug.
22, she received a note from her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe in violence. I have never been a member of
the MRTA. I do believe in the ideals of justice and equality,'' it
read in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, say the Berensons, it's not her spirit -- but her
physical health -- that has them so worried.
</P>
<P>
   Lori has chronic laryngitis and talks in a raspy, Lauren
Bacall-like voice. She once had strep throat for seven weeks. She
suffers from digestive problems and her hands are swollen and
discolored.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Berenson's high-profile campaign to get their
daughter a new trial has taken on new urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appeal before the OAS could take from two to seven
years,'' Mark Berenson said. ``We don't have that long, because
Lori doesn't have that long.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Berenson, who says he's 56 going on 100, recently left his
job as a statistics professor at Baruch College, where he has
taught since 1964, to devote more time to Lori's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only 168 hours in a week and I need to concentrate all
of them on Lori,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Each month, the Berensons e-mail updates on Lori's case to more
than 1,000 groups and individuals. Every three months, they mail
updates to another 1,000 or so people.
</P>
<P>
   This summer they led dozens of activists in protesting Fujimori
as he arrived at a Manhattan hotel; this week they'll start calling
members of Congress to ask them to limit U.S. aid to Peru, which
totaled $104 million last year, unless Lori's case is reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   The determined couple whose only previous protests have been
against the Vietnam War admits that a series of sudden ups and
downs have left them on an emotional roller-coaster this summer.
</P>
<P>
   In June, then-Prime Minister Javier Valle Riestra suggested a
pardon for Berenson. But, Fujimori swiftly rejected that idea.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats in Peru have said that Fujimori's dug in his
heels and that little movement in this case is expected until he
leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   But, thanks to some recent political maneuvering, Fujimori, who
won a second-term in 1995, may seek a third term in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Berensons, it looks like they may be the
ones who will have to dig in their heels. And they say they're
ready to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider my daughter a hostage, and, as a father, I'll do
all I can to free her because I'm frantic,'' Mark Berenson said.
``She's the first thing I think about when I wake up, and the last
thought I have before going to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
