<SLUG> BC-CALIF-POLITICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN AMERICANS MAY GIVE FONG EDGE OVER BOXER 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM WONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In politics, as in life, sometimes it's better
to be lucky than good. Just how good Matt Fong is remains unclear,
but he seems lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Fong is the Republican nominee for the U.S. Senate. He is
running against pro-Clinton Democratic incumbent Barbara Boxer at a
time with a lot of people are disgusted with the president. And he
is a symbol of hope for California's Chinese Americans and,
perhaps, other Asian Americans who yearn for political legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Two recent statewide polls show Fong, a lesser-known figure, in
a virtual tie with Boxer. Granted, it's still early, but Fong's
numbers have been rising, while Boxer has flattened out in the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer beat archconservative Bruce Herschensohn six years ago in
a close race. In polls pitting Boxer against any opponent, she
hasn't cracked the magical 50-percent threshold.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Fong had to turn toward the right in the Republican
primary to capture enough of the party's conservative base, he is
more of a moderate, Jack Kemp-style Republican. Boxer, one of the
most liberal senators, is also moving to the center, such as
reminding voters she is tough on crime.
</P>
<P>
   In their first debate recently, Fong wasn't all that good. He
read from notes when he should have been speaking extemporaneously.
He chuckled inappropriately. He called Boxer ``Barbara'' several
times.
</P>
<P>
   But it may not matter when Californians go to the polls in
November. Boxer has the Clinton albatross around her neck, and she
can't count on all Asian-American Democrats to support her because
some are attracted to Fong, a Chinese American who is the current
state treasurer, on the grounds of ethnic pride.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, will pro-choice Republican women cross over to
Boxer, an abortion rights advocate, or will they be so offended by
President Clinton's womanizing that they will stick with their own
party's straitlaced candidate despite his mostly pro-life stance?
</P>
<P>
   Boxer is having a hard time getting out from under questions
about Clinton's character. Her criticisms of Clinton have been
interpreted as tepid while she was aggressive in criticizing others
accused of sexual harassment _ Supreme Court Justice Clarence
Thomas and former Sen. Robert Packwood, R-Ore., for example.
</P>
<P>
   One of the key factors in the Boxer-Fong race could be how the
state's Asian-American voters feel. Boxer won only 52 percent of
the Asian-American vote in 1992. Although not a large percentage of
the state's voters (an estimated 6 percent), Asian-American voters
are increasing as more become naturalized citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Famously independent, California's Asian-American voters are
roughly split among the two parties and many refuse to align
themselves with either party. Their votes remain up for grabs, as
they have for many years.
</P>
<P>
   In a pre-June primary survey by the non-partisan Chinese
American Voters Education Committee, Chinese-American voters in San
Francisco preferred Fong over Boxer by 3-to-1. In a primary
election day exit poll conducted by political consultant Tom Hsieh
Jr., a large majority of Chinese-American voters in San Francisco
supported Fong while an equally large majority voted for a
Democratic candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Fong stands a good chance of getting a majority of
Asian-American independents, and he could get a fair number of
Asian-American Democrats. Some Asian-American Democrats are angry
at their own party for not standing behind Asian-American party
fund-raisers in the campaign-finance scandal. Some don't feel Boxer
has paid much attention to issues important to Asian Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer has lately launched an Asian Americans for Boxer movement,
but as one Asian-American Democrat said privately, she's doing it
to stop the bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   There's still plenty of time for Boxer to take the upper hand
against the relatively inexperienced Fong, but maybe her luck is
running out.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 1245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7133 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-QUINN-BOYS-BO     09-03 2306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-QUINN-BOYS-BOMBING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE LITTLE BOYS, THREE LITTLE GRAVES, AN UNENDING TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By LINDA SLOBODIAN  
 c.1998 The Calgary Sun  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   RASHARKIN, Northern Ireland _ The nightmare never ends. Every
horrific bombing underscores a centuries-old religious division
that political will has yet to mend.
</P>
<P>
   The Quinn family knows the violence all too well. In July,
Richard, Mark and Jason Quinn, three young sons, died in the first
major terrorist attack since the Good Friday peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   In this interview, their mother, Chrissie Quinn, spoke for the
first time about her grief _ a family's dreams shattered, a
country's future in shambles.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, when she fears the grief will drive her insane,
Chrissie Quinn tells herself she's just having a nightmare and that
when she wakes up, all her boys will be alive, laughing and
inseparable, as they always were.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact three of her four boys are lying, inseparable
forever, side by side by side, in their graves. Only her eldest,
Lee, 13, is with her.
</P>
<P>
   The younger brothers _ chatty Richard, 11, gentle Mark, 10, and
wee Jason, the warrior who turned nine just four days before they
died _ were murdered in an evil and cowardly way by someone who
used the name of God as a pitiful excuse for hatred. The family was
targeted while they slept; the terrorist tossed at least one,
perhaps more, firebombs into their home July 12.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, on merciful days, Chrissie is just numb. She's beyond
tears. Months later, the reality hasn't really sunk in.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The winding road to Rasharkin, a town about 35 miles northwest
of Belfast, is quite beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Chrissie Quinn is staying in this mostly Catholic small town
with her mother. Along the way, sheep graze peacefully in gently
rolling hills people proudly describe as ``40 shades of green.''
Church bells seem to be always ringing. Weaving through villages,
one can see children playing in quiet streets with tidy flower
beds. The serenity is so deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   Union Jacks mark areas where Protestants live. None fly in
pockets where Catholics dwell. The area suffers the undercurrent of
hatred that sweeps throughout Northern Ireland pitting Catholic
against Protestants, loyalists against those who aren't.
</P>
<P>
   There's always tension between the Catholic minority that pushes
for a united Ireland, free of British rule, and the 60 percent
pro-British Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   What the religious hatred can do, and has done _ bombings,
shootings and beatings, all especially brutal over the past 30
years _ makes parents overly protective of their children.
</P>
<P>
   And then the death of the Quinn boys in the early morning hours
of July 12 shocked the world and brought it to disbelieving tears.
</P>
<P>
   It happened in the predominantly Protestant town of Ballymoney,
about five miles from Rasharkin. Outrage rocked Northern Ireland, a
place quite accustomed to violence, a place where 1.6 million
people had their hopes pinned on the Good Friday peace agreement
developed last April.
</P>
<P>
   The pact was endorsed in the Irish republic and on May 22, an
overwhelming majority in Northern Ireland voted to give peace a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   But the violence would not be over that easily. Dissidents in
the Irish Republican Army oppose a cease-fire. And some, likely
dissident splinter groups, continue to let off bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Ballymoney is 10 km from Bendooragh, where Chrissie was born.
Ballymoney is where she had lived for 20 years _ and where all her
boys were born and went to school and played with other children,
Protestant and Catholic alike.
</P>
<P>
   It's a place she says she wants to go back to for only one
reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like going there to ask them why ...''
</P>
<P>
   I arrived at Chrissie's mother's home, a pretty row house in a
quiet cul-de-sac, not expecting to see her. Her uncle Harry Patton
wanted to talk but had warned that Chrissie hasn't been strong
enough to face many people.
</P>
<P>
   Yet she's waiting, standing in the living room like a statue,
trying to be brave. So pretty, so fragile and in so much pain. What
does one say to this tormented mother? Who can really know what
she's going through? No one, her Uncle Harry says.
</P>
<P>
   The chatter of children _ her nephews and cousins _ permeates
the small house. But three wee voices are missing.
</P>
<P>
   Chrissie's wearing a new tan sweater, new pants and new shoes,
bought out of necessity because everything she owned _ including
every picture, drawing and treasure of her boys accumulated over
the years _ was destroyed in the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Her eldest son Lee, 13, is ``Grammy's boy.'' He slept here that
tragic night with Chrissie's mom Irene, a kind woman who brings in
tea and chocolate. She smiles, but her eyes reveal an utterly
shattered heart.
</P>
<P>
   Chrissie and her boys lived in the Ballymoney house with her
sister Colette and her four-month-old daughter Shannon. Colette,
18, who was visiting friends that July night, came home at about 9
p.m. to feed Shannon. Her friends urged her to come back _ and
bring the baby with her. She did, and decided they'd both stay the
night. It was a casual decision, one that may have saved their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Chrissie let the three boys stay up late to watch TV. Jason had
nodded off to sleep. She woke him up and sent them all off to bed
at 1 p.m. ``with a tuck and a kiss,'' like she always did, not
knowing it would be the last time she'd feel the loving joy of
doing that.
</P>
<P>
   Two friends were staying over _ Raymond Craig, 31, and Christina
Archibald, 18.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:30 a.m. an explosion rocked the house. Someone had thrown
at least one petrol bomb in through the living room window. A
fireball roared through the house.
</P>
<P>
   Chrissie, Raymond and Christina escaped though a front window.
The boys were trapped in an upper rear bedroom. Their screams
pierced the night.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors poured out of their houses. Craig tried desperately to
get to the boys. He broke a window, cutting himself, but was driven
back by heat and flames.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, young Richard cried: ``I'm in a corner.'' For some
reason he didn't, couldn't, obey pleas from those on the street
urging him to jump. One of the other boys, no one's sure which one,
screamed that his feet were burning. All efforts to get them out
were futile. By the time firemen arrived, the boys were dead.
</P>
<P>
   Chrissie can't say much about that night. She goes pale and
silent for a long time. Until now, she hasn't said much to anyone
except her younger brother Frankie, 23, a handsome young man with a
gold earring and a gentle manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankie lies here on the couch to go to sleep. I won't let
him. I shake him night after night,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Brother and sister talk and she chain smokes. The silence of her
eldest son Lee worries her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lee hasn't talked about it yet,'' Chrissie says. ``And I don't
know what to say to him. Lee sits and daydreams. He was crying the
other morning but he wouldn't talk. Last night ... he was sitting
on his bed looking at a photo of his brothers. I lay down beside
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Who were these boys they'll always grieve for?
</P>
<P>
   Chrissie smiles for the first time when asked to talk about the
boys she devoted her life to. ``All I did was be a mum,'' Chrissie
says, having largely raised them herself.
</P>
<P>
   Their father, whom she divorced, went off to England a long time
ago. Chrissie and their stepfather split up almost a year ago.
``It's the memory of my boys that keeps me sane _ I have to keep
strong for Lee. Every pregnancy was easy. The longest I was in
labor was three hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard liked to be independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard, he was the most outgoing _ hyperactive. His chatter
never stopped. He never stopped running around, playing. I don't
have a picture of the boys together. I could never get Richard to
sit long enough with the other boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a dark look crosses Chrissie's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard had his shoes packed for high school. He was ready to
go. He was going to be in Grade 8. I'm dreading his birthday,'' she
says. It's not until Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The living room door opens. Uncle Harry and a boy with rosy,
chubby cheeks walk in. It's Lee, a shy, teddy bear of a boy who
steals one's heart in a second.
</P>
<P>
   He silently sits on the couch _ as close as he can to his mum.
The boy looks confused. He listens to Chrissie talk about Mark, the
quiet one who had his mind set on being a policeman and had an
insatiable appetite for books.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved to read anything, everything. He'd get off the school
bus with a book open. I like to read as well. We read together. He
used to bring me love stories from the library.'' Another smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark would walk in the house and say 'Mummy, I brought one for
you.' Mark would get teased by other children because he was so
clingy to me.'' His little brother Jason felt obliged to protect
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason stuck up for Mark all the time. He had no fear. His
fists flew if they had to. He was a loner, but Jason was starting
to come out of his shell. Jason was excellent at TV games.''
</P>
<P>
   The brothers were always together. They'd spend most nights
playing cards and TV games and drinking tea Mummy made.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just being boys growing up with their mom,'' she
says. ``My boys were the best boys. They were mine. They didn't
deserve what happened to them. They deserved to grow up. The people
who did this got to grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   Anger is starting to seep into her numbness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am starting to feel angry. That's why I couldn't sleep last
night. And I'm scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland has long been tormented with sectarian
killings. No one needs much of an excuse, a simple anniversary will
do. Things particularly get tense when July 12 approaches, the
anniversary of the 1690 battle when the Catholic army was defeated
by England's Protestant king. Catholics don't want Protestants
parading in their areas. Protestants say it's their right. Conflict
goes hand in hand with demonstrations and parades. And so do
sinister threats.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 300 Protestant and about 25 Catholic homes in
Ballymoney. On the morning of July 11, Catholic families received
letters warning them to ``get out'' from a paramilitary group
identifying itself as the Ulster Volunteer Force. Some of the
envelopes had bullets in them. Many families left to live with
relatives elsewhere _ and are still staying away from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Chrissie's mom had recently moved to Rasharkin because it was
coming up to the 12th. On the 10th, two petrol bombs were hurled
into the house she left. It was empty so they just burned
themselves out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get a letter. I thought I must be excepted,''
Chrissie says.
</P>
<P>
   There had been trouble in the past, but she thought it was over.
``Three years ago around July 12, my husband and my brother fought
with people in the square. It started because my childrens' tennis
ball went into the neighbor's yard.'' The neighbors were
Protestant.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, in a different home in Ballymoney, her second
husband John Dillon, a Catholic, was shot. ``It took his thigh
away,'' Chrissie says. Shortly after, about 15 members of the UVF
came by ``to smash chairs through my windows.'' She asked the
housing executive to move her to another house. They said no.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime after that police visited and said they'd received a
``coded message'' warning that John's life was in danger. The
family fled to England. After six months Chrissie was homesick. She
and the boys returned. All was calm. Her four boys played football
with other children and went to the Protestant school. And now
there is only one.
</P>
<P>
   Chrissie clings to a vow made by police, who Uncle Harry says
``haven't slept _ the whole team hasn't slept.'' ``They promised me
they'll never close this case until they get all of them. I know
there's more than one,'' Chrissie says. ``I want them all caught,''
she says flatly.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the tragedy, the outpouring of grief from
around the world has stunned Chrissie Quinn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just makes you realize there's only a small percentage of
people who are evil,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of letters continue to arrive. Chrissie says some are
written in foreign languages _German, Japanese. It doesn't matter
to her. She knows that whatever the contents are, whoever sent them
meant well. Others offer words of sympathy. And still others
personal stories of their own tragic losses.
</P>
<P>
   Three innocent boys.
</P>
<P>
   Three lives lost in a horrible way.
</P>
<P>
   What's left? One confused brother and one devastated mother who
face spending the rest of their lives without them, trying to make
sense out of why.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the outrage and outpouring of grief, Chrissie
believes, their brutal murders won't help the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, Ireland won't get better. It won't change,'' Chrissie
sighs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Donations can be made to The Quinn Family Fund, P.O. Box
22157, 45 Overlea Blvd., Toronto, Ont., M4H 1N9.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Linda Slobodian is a foreign-affairs columnist for The Calgary
Sun.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
