<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7151 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCMANUS-PARENTS-IMPAC     09-03 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMANUS-PARENTS-IMPACT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 WHAT IS THE IMPACT OF PARENTS ON THEIR KIDS?
 (Commentary)   &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Is your local high school drug-free? Fully 82 percent of
principals say yes.
 &HT;    But 78 percent of high school kids say drugs are used, kept and
sold at their schools, according to a new ''Back to School Teen
Survey.''
 &HT;    Is a 13-year-old at much greater risk of drug use than a
12-year-old? Most parents would say no. They are wrong.
 &HT;    ''The transition from age 12 to 13 is the most critical turning
point in the lives of America's children,'' says the survey by the
National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse (CASA).
 &HT;    It is the year when their access to illegal drugs skyrockets,
while parental involvement in their lives dramatically diminishes.
 &HT;    Fifty percent of 13-year-olds can buy pot vs. only 14 percent of
12-year-olds. It is a big step to go from the sixth grade, where
only 13 percent can buy acid, cocaine or heroin, to the seventh
grade, where 43 percent can buy those hard-core drugs.
 &HT;    Only 15 percent of 12-year-olds say they would not report a
student they see using illegal drugs. But a year later, 48 percent
say they would not snitch.
 &HT;    What are parents doing during this critical year? Withdrawing.
 &HT;    When a sixth grader comes home from school, 17 percent have no
adult to greet them, but 30 percent of seventh graders have no
adult at home.
 &HT;    Result? The percentage of kids who rely most on their parents in
making important decisions drops from 58 to 42 percent in that
crucial year, while those who rely most on friends in making
decisions triples from 7 to 21 percent.
 &HT;    This is tragic. But there is some good news in the CASA report.
 &HT;    Parents can be far more influential in the lives of their
children than many seem to realize. Take the issue of faith. Only a
fifth of students who attend church at least four times a month say
that half their friends drink, compared to 38 percent of those who
attend less than once a month.
 &HT;    Only 8 percent of kids who attend religious services at least
four times a month smoke cigarettes vs. 22 percent who attend less
than once a month.
 &HT;    This is profoundly important. Cigarette smoking is a gateway
drug. Only 10 percent of teens who never smoked get drunk once a
month compared to 63 percent of smokers! Teen smokers are also six
times as likely to be pot users as those who don't smoke.
 &HT;    ''The powerful correlations among teens who smoke, drink and use
marijuana and expect to try an illegal drug in the future make it
essential for parents, principals and teachers to focus on all
substances in their prevention efforts,'' said Joe Califano, CASA
Chairman and former secretary of Health, Education and Welfare.
 &HT;    Those teens who always eat dinner with their parents are more
than twice as likely to never smoke pot as those who rarely eat
with parents.
 &HT;    Thus, the remedies are simple. Eat dinner with your children and
be there when they come home from school. Take them to church. Do
not permit them to smoke.
 &HT;    Perhaps the single most helpful step I took as father was a
present I gave each of my sons at age 12 -- an ''Adolescent
Weekend.'' Leaving the rest of the family home, I took the boy on
his birthday to a great resort, where we played golf for the first
time together, went fishing, and listened to six ''Preparing for
Adolescence'' audio tapes by Dr. James Dobson.
 &HT;    Reg Jones, another father at church, who told me about the
tapes, said, ''I had no well-conceived idea of how to explain
adolescence growing up to them. This seemed like a way to share
with a child, but have a professional explain it.
 &HT;    ``By taking off with a child alone for a weekend, in our busy
lives, that demonstrates how much you care.''
 &HT;    In the first tape, Dobson explains he will talk ''about the
things teenagers worry about most.'' What causes the most pain is a
sense of inferiority, ''that awful awareness that nobody likes you,
that you are not as good as others.'' For example, he notes that 80
percent of teens don't like the way they look. Eighty percent!
 &HT;    I turned off the tape at that point and told each of my boys how
awful I myself had felt being 6 feet 8 inches tall and inept on the
basketball court. It was the first time they had seen me as
vulnerable.
 &HT;    Reg and I are proud of the contributing young men our sons have
grown into.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1998 Mike McManus
