<HEADLINE>
WHAT GORE'S RIVALS SAY ON CLINTON, LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democrats who may run for president have made the
following comments about the Clinton-Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt of Missouri:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wrong and it was reprehensible,'' Gephardt said about
Clinton's relationship with former White House intern Monica S.
Lewinsky. Gephardt, who has not ruled out the possibility of
impeachment proceedings, added: ``I think it's important for us to
not be out there saying he's guilty of impeachment or not, as if we
know.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Senator Bob Kerrey of Nebraska:
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically, we've got to be a lot more than `legally
accurate,' '' Kerrey said, referring to Clinton's description of
his Jan. 17 deposition testimony that he didn't have a sexual
relationship with Lewinsky. ``You either tell the truth or you
don't. And he didn't. He did not provide the full truth.'' Kerrey
once called Clinton an ``unusually good liar.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry of Massachusetts:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to make a judgment until I read the Starr
report,'' Kerry said, referring to a report to be issued by
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr. Kerry also said about
Clinton: ``I know he is prepared to make clear to people the degree
to which he understands that he bears responsibility in creating
the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Senator Bill Bradley of New Jersey:
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has declined to comment on the matter, an aide said. ``I
don't expect Bill (Bradley) to make any kind of proactive
statement,'' aide Ed Turlington said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Senator Paul Wellstone of Minnesota:
</P>
<P>
   ``None of it is defensible,'' Wellstone said about Clinton's
relationship with Lewinsky. Asked whether Clinton should resign or
be impeached, Wellstone said: ``It's premature to talk about that.
We need to wait to see what's in the Starr report and evaluate
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson:
</P>
<P>
   ``He's expressed his contrition,'' Jackson said. ``It takes an
awful lot to face a wife and daughter and live with the fallout ...
We would do well to let that process take place and focus more on
the nation's business.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Compiled by Michael Kranish from newspaper, television and
radio interviews.)
</P>
</TEXT>
