<SLUG> BC-PROBE-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOYALTY TO CLINTON MAY COST GORE IN 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore's unstinting loyalty to
President Clinton is facing its ultimate test, as the aftershocks
of the Monica S. Lewinsky story and a new campaign-finance probe
increase the chances that Gore will face tougher competiton for the
Democratic presidential nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of nervousness in the Gore camp, aides have called
dozens of top campaign donors recently and said that Gore intends
to run for president, but will not distance himself from Clinton.
The calls were made after Clinton acknowledged on Aug. 17 that he
had an inappropriate relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's loyalty has been his most valuable asset as vice
president, but could become a weakness if key constituencies such
as women voters turn against Clinton. And if the global downturn
and the shaky US stock market begin to hurt Americans' pocketbooks,
Gore's strategy of running on the administration's economic record
will have to be rewritten.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Attorney General Janet Reno last week opened a 90-day
preliminary review into whether to ask for an independent counsel
to investigate Gore's fund-raising phone calls, creating the
possibility of a broader probe that could be active while the vice
president is campaigning for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few months ago, Gore was viewed by many as a shoo-in for
the presidential nomination. But recent events, at the least, may
have emboldened Gore's potential rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of a primary challenge may have changed,'' said Roy
Neel, Gore's former chief of staff. ``All of a sudden, different
people may be attracted into primaries. Maybe they wanted to run,
and this gives them a reason for the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Neel said the biggest challenge probably will come from
those who already planned to oppose Gore and will run on issues
unrelated to Lewinsky and the Reno probe. So far, the potential
rivals include House minority leader Richard Gephardt of Missouri,
Senator Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, Senator John F. Kerry of
Massachusetts, and former senator Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Gore allies are unsure of how the events of the last two weeks
will affect the vice president's future.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``A lot of people are concerned,'' said Martin Peretz, the
Cambridge-based chairman of The New Republic magazine and a
longtime Gore confidant. ``The public is sometimes unpredictable
and not exactly rational.''
</P>
<P>
   Political observers see three major scenarios:
</P>
<P>
   _A politically weakened Gore could face months or even years of
investigation from an independent counsel, whose authority could be
expanded, just as Clinton has endured a four-year investigation
that started with a land deal and is ending with his relationship
with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   _Gore, who already was in line to assume expanded
responsibilities after the November elections, could take the lead
on many issues if Clinton's authority weakens. This would heighten
Gore's visibility and help define him in the public mind as he
prepares for the 2000 race.
</P>
<P>
   _If Clinton resigns or is impeached, Gore would become
president, providing both opportunities and problems. As president,
Gore would have a head start on the campaign and could raise money
even more easily. If the stock market steadies itself and the
economy remains strong, Gore will benefit.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gore's presence as president also would remind
Americans about the troubles of the Clinton-Gore administration,
perhaps prompting voters to want a new start in 2000. If the
economy sours, he could be branded as the man who presided over the
end of a prolonged expansion.
</P>
<P>
   It is most likely that Gore, who declined to be interviewed for
this article, will end up with some combination of the weak and
strong scenarios, analysts said, meaning that the vice president
could spend the next two years struggling to establish himself and
battling rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Peretz, like many others interviewed last week, hopes that Gore
will work in the coming months will underscore his identity and
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   However, Marla Romash, a spokeswoman for Gore's political action
committee, said the vice president will not try to reinvent
himself. Asked whether Gore will identify some new issues to run
on, Romash said: ``I don't think there will be any. This vice
president has built a record with the president'' that the public
will support.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, he is one of the most influential vice
presidents in history, leading in areas such as technology,
environment, and international affairs. He led a widely publicized
effort to ``reinvent government'' and cut bureaucracy. But he has
never been able to follow through on his top priority, the
ambitious environmental plans outlined in his best-selling book,
``Earth in the Balance.'' For example, Gore's effort to cut
pollution by enacting a tax on carbon-based products went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   For months, some Gore aides have been saying that the vice
president's wooden personality is just what the country will be
clamoring for in the wake of the Clinton-Lewinsky story. Dull is
in, according to this view. However, other Gore aides cringe at
this idea.
</P>
<P>
   Neel, who served both in the Senate and in the White House with
Gore and is now president of the US Telephone Association, said
Clinton's admission of an inappropriate relationship with Lewinsky
had a personal impact on Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It affects him deeply, personally,'' Neel said. ``There is a
deep personal element of this that may not be understood in a
cynical political context, but it is true. It is just feeling deep
sadness for the president.''
</P>
<P>
   But Neel said Gore would never distance himself from Clinton
because the two are so close. ``If there is a political price to be
paid for the personal loyalty to his friend Bill Clinton in a time
of great personal distress here, then I believe the vice president
is willing to pay the price,'' Neel said.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, many Gore backers say everything is going along
smoothly. But privately, some are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   One of Gore's major financial backers, a Bostonian who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said last week that he is worried Gore will
be ``finished'' unless Clinton steps down and turns the presidency
over to Gore. Otherwise, this contributor said, Gore will be
dragged down the same way Vice President Gerald Ford was hurt by
President Nixon's Watergate actions and delay in resigning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad because Al Gore is a nice man. He is a very loyal
man,'' the Boston contributor said. ``I'm sure deep down he is
furious.''
</P>
<P>
   Romash dismissed the idea that Gore would be best served if
Clinton stepped aside and let Gore become president. ``The elites
are starting this buzz,'' she said, ``and it is just ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gore's aides are clearly concerned about the impact of
the Lewinsky investigation on major campaign donors. After
Clinton's Aug. 17 speech, Gore ally Peter Knight _ who may run
Gore's 2000 campaign _ began calling big contributors to reassure
them, according to a knowledgeable source. Knight declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious problem for Gore may be the possibility of
facing an independent counsel investigation into fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin T. Meehan, the Lowell Democrat, said the
combination of problems facing Gore could reshape the race for the
presidential nomination. ``There are a lot of people looking it,''
Meehan said. While Meehan still thinks Gore will win the
nomination, the congressman said it would be ``very difficult'' to
run for president if he is facing an independent counsel
investigation and the inevitable leaks from such a probe.
</P>
<P>
   Reno previously decided against seeking an independent counsel
because she believed Gore raised only unregulated ``soft money''
when making 45 telephone calls from the White House to solicit
donations. But the Justice Department recently obtained a memo
written by former Gore aide David Strauss that suggests Gore may
have known he was also raising regulated ``hard money,'' which
could violate a law that prohibits soliciting donations on
government property.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has repeatedly said his action are legal and proper, and
his aides said a memo written by a staff member does not prove
anything. But Gore allies fear that if Reno does ask for the
appointment of an independent counsel to examine this narrow issue,
the investigation could be expanded and still be going on when he
is running for president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
