<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSE GROWER A CHAMPION OF ROOT PROPAGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  NASHUA, N.H. _ Mike Lowe is leading a movement to put roses
back where they belong _ on their own roots.
</P>
<P>
   Most roses are grown commercially by fusing the tops of
desirable varieties onto the roots of stronger but homelier types.
Called grafting, the technique gets rose bushes to market bigger
and faster than growing them on their own roots. After World War I
it gradually became an almost universal practice in the industry,
except among growers of miniature roses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started propagating roses on their own roots 20 years ago
because friends asked me to. They couldn't find non-grafted plants
elsewhere,'' said Lowe, 63, a retired Raytheon engineer. What
started out as a hobby became a small home business with a devoted
following among rose aficianados, who have also prized Lowe's
willingness to custom-grow rare antique roses from his own
collection of a thousand varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Now the big rose producers like Weeks and Jackson &AMP; Perkins are
having second thoughts and are also beginning to offer roses grown
on their own roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``All producers are moving in that direction,'' said Keith Zary,
vice president of research for Jackson &AMP; Perkins, the world's
largest rose grower.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a war of the roses, and for Lowe, the smell of victory
is sweetly scented.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lowe and his wife, Irene, propagate roses in the sunroom of
their flower-festooned suburban ranch house along the Salmon River
here. They patiently snip canes from rose bushes into six-inch
cuttings, dip them into Hormondina (a rooting hormone), then stick
them into trays of Pro Mix BX potting mix. When the slips take
root, they are transfered into a greenhouse for several weeks under
intermittent misting, then to a nursery bed to grow for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   In this way, the Lowes have propagated about a thousand kinds of
roses, both modern and antique, usually in batches of a dozen or
less. In fact, half are custom-grown upon request. If you've been
looking for a rosa moyessii ``Sealing Wax,'' Mike Lowe will grow
one just for you _ if you're willing to wait 18 months for
delivery. It's slow work, and the roses themselves grow slowly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Disadvantages of grafting
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So why is this technique worth the time and effort?
</P>
<P>
   ``Own-root roses are hardier. You get an extra zone, which is
important in New England,'' said Zary. ``When you bud or graft a
rose and you have a particularly cold snowless winter, the rose can
freeze back to that bud union. Then you're left with that
rootstock, which you don't want.''
</P>
<P>
   This is one reason why flowers on rose bushes sometimes seem to
mysteriously ``change color'' after a hard winter. Maybe you buy a
``Peace'' rose with large delicately tinted pink petals and one
spring it suddenly puts out small red or white blooms. Miraculous
though it may seem, this is not good. What's really happened is
that the named variety of rose you bought has died or is being
overwhelmed by suckers from the roots of the less desirable rose
onto which it was grafted. Most of the time the understock is ``Dr.
Huey,'' a small red multiflora rose with no smell that blooms for
about five weeks. Dig it up and discard it.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Dr. Huey'' has a dirty little secret. Many roses grafted
onto this rootsock suffer from mosaic virus, which causes yellow
streaks in the leaves and affects the plant's ultimate vigor. The
disease can only be transmitted through grafting. Lowe estimates
that at least 10 percent of roses grafted onto ``Dr Huey'' have the
virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We began a program 30 years ago to eradicate that from our
budding and spent millions of dollars doing it so I feel confident
that our roses are extremely clean,'' said Jackson &AMP; Perkin's Zary.
``That's not true of our competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosaic virus gets its name because new leaf growth is mottled
yellow and green. ``There is some scientific proof you get fewer
flowers, and you have to believe the rose is less vigorous because
you're feeding a parasite. So the virus does some harm,'' Zary
says.
</P>
<P>
   Experts agree that some roses with a weak disposition, including
most hybrid teas, do perform better if they're grafted.
</P>
<P>
   But Lowe, New England director for the American Rose Society,
also maintains that grafted roses start to die out after a decade
while own-root roses can live a century.
</P>
<P>
   It's a claim Zary disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe counters that when grafted roses are long-lived, it's
because the top rose has sprouted its own roots, superseding the
grafted rootstock.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Shrub roses his specialty
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's Own-Root Roses, as Mike Lowe's home business is called,
is a labor of love, and not a money maker. He is in the process of
setting up a partnership which will allow propagation of the roses
he sells to be done in North Carolina, freeing him to concentrate
on breeding.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's favorite roses in his extensive collection are three
modern shrub roses, ``Golden Wings,'' ``Lilian Austin,'' and
``Immortal Juno'' (the most fragrant rose he grows), the antique
white ``Madame Hardy'' (1832), and ``Autumn Sunset,'' his own
discovery, which he says is the closest thing yet to a yellow
repeat-blooming climber that is hardy in the north.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years ago Lowe noticed a cane with fragrant gold
flowers on an apricot orange bush of rosa kordesii ``Westerland.''
He cut it off and propagated it. While the parent rose is a hardy
shrub, the mutation likes to climb. This year it was widely
introduced into the nursery trade by Weeks, the wholesale rose
growers, under the name Lowe registered a decade ago, ``Autumn
Sunset.'' Some plants are grafted and some are grown on their own
roots. It's also sold in Britain through noted rosarian Peter
Beale's nursery in Attleborough.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe, who gets a royalty for each bush sold, says ``Autumn
Sunset'' is more vigorous and fragrant than its parent. ``It's one
of the most fragrant roses I grow. And being a kordesii, it's very
disease resistant. It grows into a climbing shrub 8 to 10 feet
high. It has some dieback in zone five, where we are, but it's
hardy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Autumn Sunset'' is now available from regional nurseries such
as Roseland in Acushnet, Mass. (508-995-4212) or through mail order
from Heirloom Old Garden Roses (503-538-1576) and Edmunds' Roses
(503-682-1476). Ironically Lowe himself may have fewer than a dozen
plants to sell when he has his year-end sale of field-dug roses on
Oct. 31 and Nov. 1 because he deals in such small quantities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Roses in his blood
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's nursery is sort of the second coming of Lowe's Roses. His
father's uncle had a nursery by the same name in the 1800s in
Nottingham, England. His father worked there as a boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He died when I was 6, but my mother talked about it so I
thought I'd grow some roses when I bought my first house.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe never visited the first Lowe's Roses or met his uncle.
``The last catalog I have of them is 1970. I heard it's not there
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   But he found his way into the family business all on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just happen to like roses. I don't know why. Maybe it's
inbred.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Lowe's Roses, Sheffield Road, Nashua, N.H. 03062
(603-888-2214).cq Catalogs, $3; orders placed before May 1, 1999,
will result in delivery 18 months later.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
