<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7169 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-03 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GAMES DON'T COUNT -- BUT THE PAIN IS REAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ We all remember Jack Nicholson, a.k.a.
astronaut Garrett Breedlove, at the airport in ``Terms of
Endearment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost a clean getaway,'' he deadpanned as Shirley MacLaine
approached in a manner that let him know he was deluding himself if
he thought he was going to remain single much longer.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Collins was kind of thinking the same thing as he examined
his busted pinkie, an injury sustained on his last play of last
Saturday night's exhibition victory over the Philadelphia Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   And he got off easy. Marty Moore broke a rib on the last play.
Getting carried off, chair-like, by two burly mates wasn't exactly
the way the onetime Mr. Irrelevant _ who has morphed into a
special-teams Mr. Irreplaceable _ wished to conclude his preseason
duty. Early estimates call for Moore to be out four to six weeks,
although Collins has his doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he'll be back a lot quicker than they say,'' Collins
contends. ``But you know something's busted if he comes out. You've
got to run him over with a dump truck to hurt him.''
</P>
<P>
   You can get hurt in any sport, of course, but football is one of
those deals where you expect to become incapacitated to some
degree. These guys start whacking each other in practice in the
heat of July. If they are very fortunate, they aren't through
whacking each other until the last Sunday in January. If the
Patriots were to be one of those two teams, they could conceivably
have played 25 games. Can you possibly imagine what a body will
feel like by that time? I can't.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so you know you're going to be hurting. It's only a matter
of time. But what you positively, absolutely do not want is to get
hurt in a stupid exhibition game. As each game goes by and you
don't get hurt, you thank the Big Guy upstairs, or somebody. Now
imagine getting down to the final minute of the final exhibition
game and tearing up a knee, shoulder, ankle, or wrist. Or breaking
a rib. Or breaking a little finger.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a clean getaway.
</P>
<P>
   Collins can relate to what Moore's going through to some degree.
He was close to the desired clean getaway in 1996 when he messed up
his knee in the final exhibition game against the Redskins. It was
a severe bruise and it knocked him out of the first three games of
the season. Considering that he was trying to get back into the
good graces of Bill Parcells after staying home on his Tennessee
farm for the entire 1995 season, you can imagine how frustrated
Collins must have felt when he was rendered hors de combat on the
eve of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was having a good preseason and then I got hurt,''
he says. ``I'm on the sidelines saying, `Oh, Lord, why did this
have to happen?' But then you just get back in as quick as you can.
You've just got to go with it.''
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much anyone can do to prevent injury in this game.
The prevailing theory is that you can't simply be floating around
out there trying to stay out of trouble, for that is almost a
guaranteed method to ensure that you will get hurt.
</P>
<P>
   But when you see the exhibition finish line in sight, is it not
human nature to relax?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of guys get nicked in that final game,'' says
seven-year veteran safety Willie Clay. ``Sometimes you're just not
aggressive and you pay the price. I'm not saying that was the case
with Marty ...''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have to finish the thought. The Patriots know that
anyone whose entree into this brutal profession was as ``Mr.
Irrelevant'' (i.e, the very last man selected in the annual college
draft) will never be caught lollygagging around the ol' gridiron.
They know that Marty Moore plays this game with a laudable passion.
Mr. Irrelevants do not take plays off. None of his mates is sure
just how Moore sustained his broken rib, but they would testify in
court that he darn well didn't do it by ogling some blonde in the
fifth row.
</P>
<P>
   They also know that the same is true of Todd Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're out there,'' he explains, ``you must give 100
percent. This is a very violent game, and you've got to treat the
exhibition game the same way you would a regular-season game. You
can't just stand around and watch plays. Things are going on all
the time. The minute you start to let up, that's when something
will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The all-time granddaddy of final-day disasters, at least around
here, occurred on Sept. 1, 1989. Bad enough that Raymond Berry's
Patriots stunk up the joint during a dismal 16-0 loss to the
Packers. Worse, by far, was that during this horrifying practice
game, no fewer than three starters were lost for the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, ouch. Cornerback Ronnie Lippett ruptured his left
Achilles' tendon _ gone. Defensive end Garin Veris tore a left knee
ligament _ gone. Linebacker Andre Tippett, merely the team's best
player at that point, blew out his right shoulder. The preliminary
reports held out some hope that he might get back in action, but it
was a false hope. He, too, would be gone. As were the Patriots'
chances. The team had gone 9-7 the year before and was seriously
thinking about participating in the postseason. Instead, the team
went 5-11 and Raymond Berry went bye-bye.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing like that happened to the Patriots Saturday. You had
Moore and you had Todd Collins. It was a fairly good but not
completely clean getaway.
</P>
<P>
   As for Collins and his broken pinkie, so? It's football, isn't
it? He's not a wide receiver, he's a linebacker. He'll just have to
make a one-handed interception, if need be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just get me some Tylenol,'' Collins shrugs, ``and go to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
