<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_`CONTRACEPTIVE KIT' DESIGNED TO BE SIMPLE   
 _BENIGN BREAST TUMORS ARE STUDIED FOR RISKS   
 _PAYMENT PER PATIENT WEIGHED BY ETHICISTS  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: p53 is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 `Contraceptive kit' designed to be simple
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A newly approved ``emergency contraceptive kit'' costing about
$20 offers women and their physicians an easy way to avoid
unintended pregnancies after unprotected sex or contraceptive
slipups. The kit will be available later this month. A woman can
use it up to 72 hours after sexual exposure. The kit uses old
technology _ a pregnancy self-test, conventional birth control
pills _ but packages it in a way that simplifies its use in
``emergency'' situations. ``Before, patients had to take two pink
tablets now and two in 12 hours, or four of the yellow pills, or
whatever, depending on the brand of birth control pills,'' said Dr.
Anita L. Nelson, director of the Women's Health Care Clinic at
Harbor-UCLA Medical Center in Los Angeles. ``Until now there hasn't
been a really clear, all-in-one kit.''
</P>
<P>
   The new product, called PREVEN Emergency Contraceptive Kit, won
Food and Drug Administration approval Tuesday. A consumer-tested
booklet instructs users to do the pregnancy self-test first,
because the contraceptive will not work if pregnancy has already
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   If the pregnancy test is negative, a user would take two of the
four special-dose oral contraceptives included in the kit, wait 12
hours, then take the other two pills.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy works, Nelson said, by preventing or delaying
ovulation. It may also prevent fertilization of an ovum or
implantation of a fertilized egg in the uterine wall, said the UCLA
gynecologist, who was acting as a medical spokeswoman but said she
has no financial relationship with its manufacturer, Gynetics Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Of 100 women who have unprotected intercourse, eight will
ordinarily become pregnant, Nelson said. If those 100 women used
the new kit properly, only two unwanted pregnancies would occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year the nation had 2.7 million unwanted pregnancies,''
Nelson said. ``Only 1 percent of women have ever used emergency
contraception.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the kit is designed to stop pregnancy before it begins,
and has no connection to the controversial ``abortion pill''
RU-486, which terminates established pregnancies at an early stage,
some right-to-life advocates still condemned it.
</P>
<P>
   American Life League president Judie Brown Wednesday called
PREVEN a ``do-it-yourself abortion kit'' and said the FDA's
approval of it ``does not surprise those of us who understand that
government agencies will go to any length to pander to the sexually
irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Benign breast tumors are studied for risks
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the overwhelming majority of cases, benign breast lumps never
turn cancerous. But doctors and their female patients often wonder
if a benign tumor might presage malignancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe'' is the answer from a new Canadian study of nearly
5,000 women with benign breast disease.
</P>
<P>
   Tissue from 92 women who later developed breast cancer was 2 1/2
times more likely to have an accumulation of a particular protein
called p53, compared to 288 women who stayed cancer-free, after
accounting for all risk factors.
</P>
<P>
   Since the protein is involved with regulating cell division, a
buildup within some benign breast tumors is ``in keeping with a
role for p53 protein in breast cancer development,'' Dr. Thomas E.
Rohan and his University of Toronto colleagues write in the Journal
of the National Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   An accompanying editorial agreed that p53 might become a useful
marker for women with benign breast tumors who should be watched
more closely. Still, they noted, the absolute risk associated with
p53 appears small. Cancer could be expected to develop in only 3.3
percent of those with high p53 levels, vs. 1.3 percent of those
without it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Payment per patient weighed by ethicists
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Capitation _ the fast-increasing method of paying doctors a lump
sump to cover each patient's care _ worries doctors and patients
because it rewards doctors for doing less.
</P>
<P>
   But like it or not, capitation ``is not going to go away soon,''
three Boston ethicists note today in the New England Journal of
Medicine. So they prescribe some features to lessen conflict of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   They urge health plans to insulate doctors from the direct
economic effects of what they do for particular patients. For
instance, no more than 10 percent of a doctor's income should be
``at risk'' because of decisions they make, and the risk should be
pooled by groups of more than 15 doctors caring for more than 250
patients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
