<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7181 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITI-STELLA-BOS &LR;      09-03 1335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-STELLA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO HAITIANS, AIDS QUIP NO LAUGHING MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a, i and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The entire exchange lasts less than a minute, almost lost in
sharp-tongued banter and tropical vistas of the summer movie hit
``How Stella Got Her Groove Back.''
</P>
<P>
   But a passing joke that links four volatile words _ Haitians,
AIDS and ``those people'' _ has dredged up a stinging, decade-old
stigma and turned a feel-good romance into a target of outrage for
Haitians, Haitian-Americans and public health officials across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The joke has newly inflamed a simmering clash of culture between
African Americans and Haitian blacks. Activists say a movie that
was hailed for breaking through black stereotypes has now
reinforced one, one that Haitians say still haunts and humiliates
them _ Haitians as AIDS carriers and Haiti as the diseased,
monkey-to-man birthplace of the HIV virus.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as a bitter, growing chorus of complaints on Internet sites
and radio waves prompted a protest rally in New York Wednesday, and
further plans for a national demonstration in Miami, some who bear
the burden of caring for Haitians with AIDS expressed an outrage
that was tinged with ambivalence.
</P>
<P>
   The energy, emotion and resources that have been mounted against
Hollywood's pop-culture insult is something they rarely see applied
to the long fight against a deadly disease that has hit their
community as hard as any other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie does have certain implications, yes,'' said Eustache
Jean-Louis, who heads the Center for Community Health, Education
and Research in Dorchester. Jean-Louis was among those who led the
fight to lift a ban on all Haitian blood donors imposed by the Food
and Drug Administration, and to amend a high-risk-group list by the
Centers for Disease Control that came to be known as the ``Four-H
Club:'' homosexuals, hemophiliacs, heroin-users and Haitians.
</P>
<P>
   Haitians were removed from the CDC list in 1985; the blood ban
was lifted at the end of 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people with HIV see that this stereotype still continues in
the media, they may not want to come out and get help. That makes
my work and the work of other providers more difficult,''
Jean-Louis said. ``But you cannot be taking to the street because
of two lines in a movie, and then when your next-door neighbor is
dying from a disease, you don't take to the street and instead do
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, based on the best-selling novel by Terry McMillan,
Angela Bassett plays a 40-year-old divorcee and high-powered
stockbroker who travels to Montego Bay and meets a Jamaican man
half her age. When she returns, her sisters question her about the
affair, asking if she used a condom ``because those people have a
history of AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   Another sister then interjects, ``No, that's Haiti, Miss
Manners.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange sparked a spontaneous protest in Miami last week,
and Wednesday Haitians picketed in front of a movie theater in
mid-town Manhattan. On Tuesday, the Haitian consul in Boston _ home
to the third-largest population of Haitian immigrants after New
York and Miami _ joined other organizations to demand an apology, a
re-edit of the film and a studio-sponsored HIV/-AIDS education
campaign by 20th Century Fox.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report by the World Health Organization and
UNAIDS, Haiti is ranked 22d in the world in the rate of adults
living with the disease, with a rate of 5.17 percent. The top
country, Zimbabwe, has a rate of 25.84 percent. The rate in the US
is .76 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Haiti was one of the first countries associated
with the HIV virus, even though at the time Haiti had a much lower
rate of AIDS cases than other Caribbean countries and most US
cities. Almost immediately, the myth about a ``Haitian connection''
to AIDS set off an epidemic of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstered by public fear and flawed research, Haitians were
accused of exporting the virus. Years after medical evidence
debunked the myth among scientists and massive demonstrations
reversed social policy, it lingered in the popular imagination: the
myth found its way into recurring jokes on ``Saturday Night Live''
and ``The Arsenio Hall Show''.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some say, cruel misperceptions are being given new life
before a movie-going audience of millions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm appalled. This is outrageous,'' said Dr. Nicole Prudent, a
pediatrician at Boston Medical Center, who remembers when Haitian
children came to her office crying, shunned by classmates and
worried the virus lay dormant in them. ``We have been fighting
against this for such a long time and people still don't know that
AIDS has no nationality.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bernadine Lormilus heard the joke, shock was the only thing
that kept her from walking out of the theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just boiled me up,'' said Lormilus, 22, who lives in
Brockton and studies elementary education at Regis College in
Weston. ``It's degrading to Haitians, it's degrading to Jamaicans,
it's irrelevant, it's outrageous and it's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   For Lormilus, born in Boston of Haitian parents, the taunts by
classmates of ``go back to your country'' and ``boat people'' are
still raw after 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought all of this was over with about Haitians bringing
AIDS,'' she said. ``To have it in Hollywood where everyone goes to
see it and looks up to these actors is just the worst thing that
can happen. Because once people hear it from them, they'll say it
must be true.''
</P>
<P>
   On the weekend it was released, ``Stella'' was the
second-highest grossing film, pulling in $11.8 million. That was
three weeks ago. Since then it has made another $16.2 million, with
roughly four million viewers, and still ranks in the weekly top ten
grossing films.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue on that scale is a testament to the growing power of
black Americans in film and for McMillan in particular. Her first
novel-to-film, ``Waiting to Exhale,'' was praised for portraying
middle-class women struggling with love and success.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that a joke about Haitians and AIDS could surface in
``Stella,'' some say, shows how weak are the links that bind blacks
of different nationalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that whole scene wasn't there, it wouldn't have taken
anything away from the movie,'' said Brunir Shackleton, who works
for the mayor's Office of Jobs and Community Services in Boston.
``It just makes me feel that the whole so-called brotherhood, the
idea that being black automatically makes you sensitive to the
plight of other people with the same skin color, is lip service.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman at 20th Century Fox WednesdayWednesday said the
studio had no comment. A spokeswoman at Signet Books, which is
releasing the paperback edition of McMillan's book, said the author
was unavailable. The joke about AIDS and Haiti does not appear in
the novel, only the film.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Farmer, a professor at Harvard Medical School who has
written several books on AIDS and Haiti, said most research shows
that HIV probably came to Haiti from North America through
sex-for-money exchanges by tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Of the movie reference to AIDS and Haiti, Farmer said, ``In one
way, you can say, `Sure. It's just a movie.' The problem is, in
order for these misperceptions to stay alive, they have to keep
cropping up in popular culture. As long as they are shored up and
reiterated, they live on.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he supports the march, Farmer said he wishes the same
passion applied to deep-rooted inequalities that have plagued
Haitians in the US and in Haiti for years.
</P>
<P>
   So would Jean-Louis, who once led Boston's battle against the
stigma, and who now helps care for some of the 566 known cases of
Haitians living with full-blown AIDS in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question really is, what are we going to do? What are our
priorities?'' he said. ``AIDS is a reality for Haitians now. ... We
should march for the movie, and we should march for the victims, so
they can seek care and live with dignity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
