<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7183 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORIGINAL-BATMAN-ART-B     09-03 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORIGINAL-BATMAN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPE COD MAN SAYS HIS FATHER CREATED BATMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARWICH, Mass. _ Holy historical accuracy, Batman! Where did you
really come from?
</P>
<P>
   That's the question Frank Foster Jr. is still adamantly raising,
even though Bob Kane is universally recognized as Batman's
inventor. To make his case, Foster, a retired commercial
photographer who lives in Harwich, slowly eases a stiff, slightly
wrinkled piece of paper dated 1932 out of a drawer.
</P>
<P>
   On it are three black-and-white drawings done by Foster's
father, Frank Sr., who attended several Boston art schools. Even a
casual glance reveals a comic strip figure bearing a stunning
resemblance to the Caped Crusader _ the same kind of rat ears on
his cap and a similar costume. There are two names written next to
the figure _ ``Nightwing'' and ``Batman.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's where the intrigue begins. The drawings, if they are the
real thing and were done in 1932, came seven years before the first
Batman comic book hit the newsstands, giving birth to one of
America's most enduring and lucrative superheroes.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sr., who died more than three years ago, went to his grave
believing his idea was lifted either by Kane or Kane's employer,
D.C. Comics So does his wife Ruth, who is 90 and lives in Harwich.
And so do his son Frank, 62, a retired commercial photographer, and
some of Frank Sr.'s friends.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting nearly three years ago at the New York City
headquarters of D.C. Comics, Paul Levitz, the company's executive
vice president and publisher, told Frank Jr. that he did not doubt
the authenticity of his father's drawings, according to notes of
the meeting kept by Foster's attorney, Bernard G. Sykes III, who
also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem, all parties agree, is trying to establish a
clear link between Frank Sr., his drawings, Kane, and D.C. Comics.
A D.C. Comics official said privately that Foster and Kane may
simply have been influenced by the same sources. ``The issue is,
how do you show the direct correlation between his drawing and
seven years thereafter the arrival of Batman at D.C. Comics? And
that's a chain with some missing links,'' Sykes said. ``From a
legal standpoint, in order to prove damages, you have to have some
certainty. And that's a pretty high hurdle.''
</P>
<P>
   At the least, Sykes adds, the story of Foster's drawings is a
``fascinating historical footnote.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our meeting with them was very cordial, and they asked us if
we could tell them more to prove a connecting thread between Mr.
Foster and Mr. Kane, and that's where the situation lies now,''
said Sykes, who has an office in Harwich Port.
</P>
<P>
   Levitz and the other D.C. Comics official who attended the
meeting _ Lillian Laserson, D.C.'s vice president and general
counsel _ were on vacation last week and could not be reached for
comment. &UR;  &LR; Martha Tohomases, a spokeswoman for D.C. Comics, said of
Foster's account, ``That's an interesting story. We have a video
that we just showed at a comic convention in San Diego in which Bob
Kane talks about how he was influenced by da Vinci's sketches for
the Batman character. That's always been the history of Batman here
at D.C. comics.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Jr. says he lacks the money to launch the kind of
investigation _ a scientific analysis of his father's drawings and
hiring detectives to determine if there was any connection between
Frank Sr. and Kane _ needed to try and prove his case. Part of the
reason he has never shown the drawings to anyone other than family
members and close friends before now was, ``I didn't know what I
could do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he recently decided to seek publicity in hopes someone
might come forward with more information on the origins of Batman.
</P>
<P>
   Kane, who has served as a consultant on several Batman movies,
lives in California, but could not be located last week. He has
often said that his inspiration for Batman came from Leonardo da
Vinci's sketches of flying machines, and popular movie heroes from
the 1920s and '30s like Zorro.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Foster's memory has become fuzzier as the years have
passed. But this is the short version of the story, pieced together
from her recollections in a Globe interview, her written statements
to family lawyers, and an affidavit Frank Sr. gave to his attorney
in the 1970s:
</P>
<P>
   Armed with an art degree and a portfolio, including his Batman
drawings, Frank moved to New York in search of work. It was either
late 1936 or early 1937, and Frank made the rounds of numerous
companies that published comic books, dropping off his portfolio.
No one can remember if he visited D.C. Comics, but his son says it
is hard to believe his father did not go there because it was the
biggest comic book company and the offices were just a few blocks
from where his parents lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it could just be that two men had the same idea at
around the same time,'' Sykes said. ``It's happened before. But it
seems like an incredible coincidence. It would be fascinating to go
back and dig around.''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the Fosters moved to Washington in 1940, where
Frank got a job at what is now the National Gallery. It was in
Washington where Frank first spotted the Batman comic. ``He brought
it home and said, `Can you believe this,''' Ruth Foster recalled.
</P>
<P>
   They did not have the time or the money then to raise the issue,
she said, and over the years they stopped worrying about it. ``We
both never doubted what had happened, but as Batman got bigger and
bigger we didn't really think anyone would ever take us
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Jr. also knows he has a difficult case to make. ``But I
would like to see some justice for my father,'' he said. ``At the
very least I would like to see him get some recognition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
