<SLUG> BC-FBC-SPEIGHT-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRONGLY ACCUSED AT BC, KIERNAN SPEIGHT IS STARTING OVER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMPTON, Va. _ Another August, another football season, and
Kiernan Speight was hurting.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good kind of hurt, the kind that comes with two-a-day
sessions, football training camp, and the anticipation of a new
season.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of tiredness that comes on a Saturday morning
late in August after a tough two-hour scrimmage, like this one that
had given him his first real taste of football in almost a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feeling real good,'' said Speight when the session was over.
``Like nothing ever happened. Like this is where I was always meant
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Speight is here at Hampton University, playing cornerback on a
team that will begin its season Saturday against Florida A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly enough, the road that runs past the practice field is
called Emancipation Drive.
</P>
<P>
   He is here among new friends, teammates, and expectations that
weren't even on the radar screen a year ago _ freed, finally, from
the past year, which had been so bleak, so stunning in its reversal
of fortune.
</P>
<P>
   So much had changed, so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   One day he was at Boston College, playing in the Big East, a
defensive back with a football career that once looked full of
potential.
</P>
<P>
   And then, suddenly, his career was in a state of suspended
animation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Heights to depths
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Never had Kiernan Speight felt like such an outsider. ``Why
me?'' he thought. Why couldn't it have been different, the way it
had been a couple of years earlier when he arrived at BC, guided by
his teachers and coaches at H.D. Woodson High School in Washington?
</P>
<P>
   ``An opportunity,'' they told him then. ``A great opportunity to
prove yourself as a student, as a football player, and as a man.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't that, of course. Not yet. He was just 18, out on his
own, wondering where the road would take him next.
</P>
<P>
   But by the middle of the fall, he was not only playing for the
Eagles. He was starting. A freshman! And while the Big East may not
be the Big Ten or the Southeastern Conference, it was still the big
time. Playing at places like Notre Dame and Miami. Getting all that
TV exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Speight experienced all that and marveled at his good fortune.
His mind wandered. One day he would be an NFL cornerback, an
All-American, like Charles Woodson.
</P>
<P>
   Other days, he would be a doctor. He liked that idea, too. At
BC, he took some premed courses. He had goals. Dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Now all that seemed so long ago. Instead of BC, Speight was in
Hampton, walking around a campus that gave him no sense of comfort,
no sense of security.
</P>
<P>
   The faces he saw were those of strangers. Over at Armstrong
Field, where the Division 1-AA Hampton Pirates were practicing,
Speight was also a stranger. Who were those guys, anyway? Football
players, sure. But they weren't teammates. Or friends.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates' coach, a no-nonsense disciplinarian named Joe
Taylor, knew who Speight was. Taylor had also come out of Woodson
and played for the same high school coach, Robert Headen, who had
guided Speight. It was on Headen's request that Speight wound up at
Hampton. But while Taylor knew who Speight was, knew all about his
past and his background and the circumstances that had brought him
to Hampton, he didn't really know Speight, what motivated him, what
ticked him off, what made him tick.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise there, because at that point, last fall, Kiernan
Speight didn't quite know what was in his head or who he was.
</P>
<P>
   All he knew was that he was no longer playing football, no
longer at Boston College, and no longer sure of anything.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
An innocent target
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flashback time. Fall of 1996. The Boston College football team
is going from bad to worse each week. No one, even among the
Eagles, knows what the real problem is. All they know is that it's
getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is Halloween weekend and the Eagles are coming off the
dog game of all dog games, an embarrassing 20-13 loss against a
Pittsburgh team that would lose games that season by scores of
72-0, 45-0, and 60-6.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Eagles, the Panthers had looked like the Steelers.
It was so bad, with so many missed tackles and mistakes, that some
observers jokingly question whether the Eagles tanked the game.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, rumors float around the BC campus. Whispers become
louder. Maybe there is something to the rumors. Talk of shaving
points, of players at least being involved in a gambling scandal,
picks up.
</P>
<P>
   Meetings are held with coach Dan Henning, athletic director Chet
Gladchuk, and school officials. No one is saying anything, but
something is amiss.
</P>
<P>
   In a players' and coaches' meeting Saturday, with the media now
alert to a growing crisis, all hell breaks loose.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there is a gambling scandal. Yes, players have made bets,
and some may have even bet against their own team.
</P>
<P>
   Now names start to come out. Thirteen players in all, which
makes it the biggest betting scandal in NCAA history. Those
targeted in a players-only meeting are Jermaine Monk, Jamall
Anderson, Brandon King, and ... Kiernan Speight.
</P>
<P>
   Speight, stunned that he has been implicated _ and publicly, at
that _ verbally lashes out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not me,'' he says. ``No way.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, with all the minicameras rolling, Middlesex
County District Attorney Thomas Reilly reviews a list of players
implicated. Name after name is announced.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
