<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7200 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SPEIGHT-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     09-03 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SPEIGHT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 HAMPTON, Va.: ... is announced . 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Missing from that list is Kiernan Speight. There are no charges,
no accusations. For all intents and purposes, Speight has been
cleared. He is told he is welcomed back on the team.
</P>
<P>
   But Speight doesn't want to hear that. He wants to hear someone
say publicly, as well as privately, that they are sorry. That they
made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he hears only silence, a silence that he says continues
to this day.
</P>
<P>
   In Speight's mind and in those of his family and friends, the
damage is irreparable.
</P>
<P>
   Go back and play against Notre Dame the next week? You've got to
be kidding. He hires a lawyer, threatens a lawsuit against BC, and
makes the only decision that seems logical. He leaves BC _ forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still doesn't make sense,'' Speight said, months later,
painfully looking back. ``None of it, really. I guess it was guilt
by association more than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A clean slate
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The anger of 18 months ago has left him. He picks through his
memory, reliving the chaos and the confusion with a calm
detachment.
</P>
<P>
   He is older now, wiser. If there is resentment, it is muted.
</P>
<P>
   Others do not feel the same way, however.
</P>
<P>
   At Woodson High School, Susie Kay, a history teacher who was
instrumental in Speight's enrollment at Boston College, wonders how
things went so wrong as well as why they happened.
</P>
<P>
   Speight's father, John, questions all of it with a sense of
regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thankful for what happened to him,'' he said. ``But
since it happened, it was a blessing in disguise.''
</P>
<P>
   John Speight still wonders about the racial aspects of the case,
which he says were a factor.
</P>
<P>
   But what bothers John Speight most is the lack of remorse or
regret from BC officials after the fact, after the allegations had
been withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish deep down they would have apologized,'' he said. ``That
would have helped a lot. But they never did.''
</P>
<P>
   John Speight says his feelings about BC are mixed. ``There are
things I could say but I won't. That time was one of dark clouds.
We didn't know what to say to Kierney. How to help him. But there
were a lot of people in his corner who have helped, and I think
we've all learned from it.''
</P>
<P>
   John Speight says he is not bitter toward BC. ``That's the wrong
word,'' he said. ``Hurt is better. I just think the situation could
have been handled better. Much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Headen makes it clear that he is not as forgiving or
forgetting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder why they would never apologize,'' he said. ``They put
all those guys' pictures in the paper and on television, and
naturally, people think he's guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Headen paused. He concedes that the changeover in the BC
athletic administration has been complete. Henning and Gladchuk are
gone. New levels of communications and crisis management are in
place.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a man who holds grudges in this instance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never send anyone to Boston College,'' he said. ``And
I will tell all the coaches I know to do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom O'Brien, Henning's successor as BC football coach,
understands the anger, the resentment, knowing that he ultimately
will have to pay for it if he loses a blue-chip recruit because of
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happened once when I was at Virginia,'' said O'Brien.
``All you can do is sit down with the coach and explain yourself.
And then hope that time can heal the wounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Speight says he is recovering, slowly but steadily. But it has
been a difficult transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't do well in the first semester,'' said Joe Taylor,
standing on a practice field after last week's scrimmage, looking
over at a player he never thought he'd have a chance to get. ``I
think he needed time to just get used to everything. A lot of it
was still new to him. Now he's fine. It's a win-win situation for
him and for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, a man with a reputation as a no-nonsense coach, says he
checked things out about Speight, even called the NCAA to make sure
there were no lingering eligibility problems.
</P>
<P>
   When he got the go-ahead, he penciled Speight into his plans for
this season. ``He's had the best training camp of anyone so far,''
said Taylor. ``The Kiernan I see in practice now is the Kiernan I
remember coming out of high school.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Looking forward
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speight says he is now focused on the future, not the past.
``All that stuff is behind me now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall was his most difficult period. ``I wasn't even sure I
wanted to be in school,'' he said. ``I was just confused about a
lot of things. I didn't know any people. I thought I might just
take a year off from school. But it's gotten better. I feel I'm
pretty close to being on track.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask him about his tenure at BC and he pauses. ``No, I'm not
angry,'' he says, choosing his words carefully. ``It was just a bad
period. But I don't resent the city or the people there. Boston is
a great city, and the people are great. Things just didn't work
out.''
</P>
<P>
   He has made a change in career objectives as well, dropping his
premed major courses and switching to marketing.
</P>
<P>
   He says if he could step in a time machine and go back three
years, he wouldn't change much in the way he handled things. ``I
regard it as a learning experience,'' he said. ``An unfortunate
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, things just seemed to snowball on us. We started
out with great expectations and we had some disappointing losses,
and things started to steamroll, get out of control. I think the
gambling incident was used as an excuse to blame all those
problems. But it really didn't have anything to do with our
season.''
</P>
<P>
   He is firm in declaring his innocence of any wrongdoing. ``I was
judged guilty because I was part of the group,'' he said. ``But
it's not something I worry about anymore. It's time to move on, and
that's what I'm doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
