<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET SLUMP COULD MEAN RECRUITMENT DOWNTURN AT FUND FIRMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Executive recruiter Joe Haberman was on the phone this week with
one of his clients, a private investment management firm. The
message: Hit the brakes on their search for three new managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to wait until the end of the week to see how the
market responds,'' said Haberman, managing director of the
financial institutions group at A.T. Kearney, a large executive
search firm.
</P>
<P>
   Caution is the watchword at investment management firms around
the country after Monday's stock market plunge. The question of the
moment: What would happen to one of the state's most important
industries if the stock market went south for a prolonged period of
time?
</P>
<P>
   Investment executives insist publicly that such a scenario would
have little or no impact at their companies. History over the last
decade is less conclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund companies and other investment firms have been
hiring people, leasing office space, and contracting for services
at a furious pace through much of the 1990s and almost nonstop over
the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just a question of the impact on a single industry. The
economic ripple effect of the money management work force stretches
far beyond the world of fund accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very high-paying jobs and their impact on the
economy is much greater than the numbers would suggest,'' said Mark
Zandi, chief economist for Regional Financial Associates in West
Chester, Pa. ``One lost job in the mutual fund industry has a much
greater affect than one lost job in retailing or even
manufacturing.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston's commercial real estate market, money managers have
been the clients with a seemingly insatiable appetite. When
developers recently reinvented Lafayette Place as an expanded
office building, investment custodian State Street Bank &AMP; Trust and
mutual fund manager Massachusetts Financial Services signed up to
lease every square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Financial services firms, excluding banks, accounted for more
than 30 percent of all the space in Boston commerical real estate
transactions so far this year, according to Spaulding &AMP; Slye. In
the early 1990s, when real estate was in recession, Fidelity and
its fund competitors seemed to be the only companies looking for
space.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund executives, almost unanimously, said Wednesday that
an extended stock market decline would not force them to make
cutbacks. They pointed to factors such as the powerful and
predictable flow of retirement money into investment accounts as a
steadying influence. They said the most likely impact of a bad
stock market would be slower growth for their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll find that the jobs associated with these types of
savings vehicles are servicing jobs,'' said David Weinstein, chief
of administration and government affairs at Fidelity. ``They are
not so dependent on the level of the Dow or Nasdaq. They are really
more dependent on the number of customers and accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   Those retirement accounts have been a big part of the growth of
leading Boston fund companies like Fidelity and Putnam Investments.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's local payroll has grown from 7,000 to about 13,000
since the start of the 1990s. The company, which occupied 1.2
million square feet of office space in 1990, now needs 3.6 million
square feet to do business.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Putnam Investments employed just over 2,000
people and leased 425,600 square feet. Today, Putnam has 5,600
employees, almost all local, working in just over 1 million square
feet of space.
</P>
<P>
   Even smaller firms like Massachusetts Financial Services have
had an economic impact, increasing its payroll 67 percent to 1,873
in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike a high-tech firm that has to make a new sale of a chip
or a personal computer to maintain its business, ours is a more
stable business,'' said Richard Tibbetts, a managing director at
Putnam Investments in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Several large companies said they had already planned for slower
growth, giving themselves a breather after several years of
high-octane expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had already told analysts we don't expect to see that kind
of explosive growth,'' said Marshall Carter, chief executive of
State Street Corp. ``We want to track our traditional double-digit
(earnings) growth.''
</P>
<P>
   But the experience of the past decade suggests that financial
markets do have an impact on investment firms and their business.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts employment at financial firms, excluding banks,
was nearly flat for four years after the stock market crash of
1987, according to Fred Breimyer, chief economist at State Street
Bank &AMP; Trust. Some firms, including Fidelity, cut their work forces
after the market declines that year.
</P>
<P>
   Those same firms increased their combined work force over the
next several years, but the gains stopped again in 1994 when
interest rates rose sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Investment firms started hiring aggressively again in 1995 and
haven't stopped through this year, boosting total employment by
about 50 percent in 3 1/2 years to about 60,000.
</P>
<P>
   Breimyer and others were skeptical investment firms could
continue to grow quickly in a declining stock market, particularly
after several years of such dramatic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The stocks of many public money management firms reflected
similar apprehension this week.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Boston-based Affiliated Managers Group Inc. continued
a slide that has cut the company's value in half since its July
peak. United Asset Management Corp. stock lost about 15 percent in
a week. Shares of local investment firms as varied as Liberty
Financial Cos., Nvest L.P., and the Pioneer Group Inc. have all
lost substantial ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry has boomed along with a booming stock market,''
said Zandi, the economist. ``It stands to reason that if the market
declines, it's going to take a lot of steam out of the industry's
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
