<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7205 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-03 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUM CALLS FROM A MARRIAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our friends, Judith and Michael, invited us to dinner the other
night, and Judith showed me her new drum, a 3-foot-tall goatskin
and hardwood instrument made in Africa. She is part of a drumming
group that meets every Wednesday night here in Marblehead under the
tutelage of Mohamed Kalifa Camara, her West African teacher.
Judith's not only learning how to drum, she's learning about the
role that drumming has historically played in the rural culture of
Guinea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mohamed taught us one rhythm which signals the beginning of
the coming-of-age ritual,'' she told me, ``and another that summons
the community to resolve a couple's marital difficulties.'' When a
man and wife in Guinea find things getting out of hand, they call a
meeting of their families, and perhaps village officials, to help
them resolve their dispute.
</P>
<P>
   As Judith spoke, I was flooded with memories of a time when my
marriage to Jack was far more tumultuous than it is now. I can
recall two occasions when our emotions were so out of control that
we felt trapped in an impossible situation, afraid to continue
arguing, yet unable to let the matter go. In both instances we
turned to friends or to family, hoping they could keep us from
doing something we might live to regret.
</P>
<P>
   The first incident took place in the '70s. Jack and I had been
married about a dozen years, but our nerves were still raw when it
came to dealing with Jack's sister's suicide, which occurred while
we were on our honeymoon. In those days I was adamantly insisting
that I was merely a bystander to that tragedy, even though every
time Marge and I had been brought together, it had been like
introducing a match to dynamite.
</P>
<P>
   I used to think that if I got upset enough, Jack would stop
challenging my version of the part I'd played in Marge's death. My
cries of pain and outraged declarations of innocence were designed
to persuade him to cease and desist. This time, however, it wasn't
working. As Jack persisted, I became hysterical. I couldn't stop
upping the ante; Jack wasn't willing to capitulate to appease me. I
was sobbing uncontrollably on the bed when he called friends with
whom we'd once shared the circumstances of Marge's death and asked
them if we could come over.
</P>
<P>
   Jack and I each got to present our point of view. I sat on the
couch next to Jim, feeling the comfort of his strength. Jack was in
a chair near Judy, feeling the comfort of her gentleness. I can't
remember a word we said, but when we left after an hour or two, we
had somehow managed to get back in touch with the love that had
brought us together.
</P>
<P>
   I have only a visual image of the second incident. Jack and I,
having driven to Boston separately, were in line outside a movie
theater. I have no idea what we were arguing about, but Jack said
something so infuriating that, for the one time I can remember, I
resorted to violence to make my point. I swung my pocketbook at his
head with all my might. He raised his hand and warded off the blow,
but he was outraged. Trembling with rage myself, I took a page out
of my father's book and stormed off.
</P>
<P>
   I headed for my car. I considered going somewhere Jack would not
be able to find me. I wanted to make him worry, but as I drove, I
cooled down and headed for home. I spent an anxious half-hour in
our kitchen, waiting for Jack to arrive. Finally, the phone rang.
My brother explained that Jack had driven to his place in Watertown
and asked Ken to come home with him to mediate our argument. Ken's
presence helped us focus and created a safe space for us to share
our feelings about what had happened. With an impartial observer in
the same room, Jack and I managed to resolve whatever had set us
off.
</P>
<P>
   We were lucky to have people in our lives who were unafraid of a
highly emotional interaction. By not being too embarrassed to ask
for help, we turned them into the equivalent of a UN peacekeeping
force.
</P>
<P>
   It's no accident that both times Jack was the one who summoned
help. Researcher John Gottman has been able to predict the
likelihood of divorce from the degree of physiological stress the
male experiences in response to the female's perceived criticism or
anger. Too high and the marriage shatters. Jack was wisely trying
to reduce his anxiety to manageable proportions, and in a culture
without tribal gatherings or a counsel of elders, he took the only
course available. He picked up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   He was expecting a dial tone.
</P>
<P>
   What he got was the beating of drums.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
