<HEADLINE>
JONES UNMOVED BY PLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVE VALLEY, Colo. _ By and large, offensive linemen are among
the friendliest, most thoughtful, and most talkative players on a
football team. Even so, they usually go unnoticed except when their
quarterback is being pummeled to bits or their running backs are
being tackled behind them.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive linemen of the Denver Broncos are no different.
They're friendly, thoughtful, and talkative _ not to mention very
good.
</P>
<P>
   But last season they found a way to be noticed.
</P>
<P>
   They stopped talking to the media.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Denver media are talking about the Broncos' offensive
line, because once again, that line is in the spotlight _ and not
because that line is hammering linebackers and defensive linemen as
it did against the Packers in last January's Super Bowl. This
season that line is in flux and has questions swirling around it.
</P>
<P>
   It all started when camp opened in July and speculation was
rampant that Gary Zimmerman once again would ``unretire'' and
return to left tackle, just as he had done a few weeks into the
1997 season. Watching this drama play out and watching it most
closely was Tony Jones, who was moved back to right tackle from
left tackle when Zimmerman came back to the Broncos last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike (Shanahan) had promised what happened in 1997 wouldn't
happen again in 1998,'' said Jones. ``And I put my faith in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones already had made clear to the coach ``that I wasn't going
back to right tackle this year. I told Mike, `This is it. I'm not
playing right tackle. If you want me to play left, I'll play left.
But I'm not playing right tackle.'''
</P>
<P>
   But the two Denver newspapers and the vast media that cover the
Broncos kept reporting on Zimmerman's status _ the reports often
were conflicting _ and Jones was concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed when they moved me to right tackle last
season,'' he said. ``But I looked upon it as a team thing and I
figured, `What do I want here? Do I want to go to the Super Bowl or
do I want to think about personal things?' It was a thing where you
had to put your ego down.''
</P>
<P>
   But the move back to right tackle was far from smooth. ``I think
I was having an All-Pro year at left tackle when they moved me to
right,'' said Jones. ``I wasn't happy when they moved me. I almost
got to the point of retiring, things were so bad. I was frustrated.
I couldn't play right tackle at first.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, an 11-year veteran, had played right tackle for one
season ``way back in 1989, and I couldn't remember nothin' about
it. I remember coming home and telling my wife a couple of times,
`This is it. I can't do it.' There was one game against Oakland
where I was terrible and I was real close to retiring. I battled it
for weeks. I was thinking, `I've been so good at left, I've been
there the whole time, and why do I have to go and start over
again?'''
</P>
<P>
   But ``praying to God'' and his wife's encouragement convinced
him to stay with the team. As the season wore on, Jones felt more
and more at home at right tackle, and by the Super Bowl, the Denver
offensive line was awesome.
</P>
<P>
   So when the talk began anew this summer that Zimmerman might
return, Jones knew that was an experience he did not want to go
through again. But Zimmerman announced finally that he is retired
for good.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is now at left tackle and Harry Swayne, a well-traveled
12-year veteran, is at right tackle. Also gone, though, is right
guard Brian Habib, who left Denver to sign with Seattle. And right
guard became an even larger question mark when David Diaz-Infante,
Habib's replacement, was hurt in the exhibition season, so Dan
Neil, a second-year pro, will be making his first start there
against the Patriots Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   All is not well on this line.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Davis, the running back who's most dependent on
stability in front of him, conceded that it may take a few games
before the new Denver line starts to click.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see teams whose lines have been together for years and
they still didn't get to the point where we were last year,'' said
Jones. But the tackle is confident that Denver's line once again
will be good, even if it may take a few games.
</P>
<P>
   Center Tom Nalen of Foxborough, Mass., and Boston College agrees
with Jones. For one thing, said Nalen, ``Tony played left tackle
throughout camp last year and the first two games (of the 1997
season). And we won those first two games and Terrell had a couple
of 100-yard rushing games. The big deal is with Tony and Harry
switching sides and each getting comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Chemistry on the line ``should be there,'' said Nalen, ``even if
it takes a little time.''
</P>
<P>
   Nalen and Jones said these words only hours before the offensive
line decided to go mute once again in the 1998 season. But going
silent will not be the only reason the Broncos' offensive line _
the team's strength last year _ will be noticed this season. All
eyes will also focus on how well it plays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
