<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS' ATTITUDE TO HOMEWORK CAN SHAPE KIDS' SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ask any American parent what they dread most about the start of
school, and you're likely to get a two-word answer: homework
struggles. Some of the nation's most innovative educators have a
seven-word response: It doesn't have to be that way.
</P>
<P>
   The attitude we bring to homework is what can make a difference,
they say, starting with the very first homework assignment a child
gets in kindergarten or first grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you take it seriously, treat it with respect and even
excitement, or do you see it as onerous and burdensome?'' asks
educator and researcher Carol Seefeldt, a professor at the
University of Maryland Institute for Child Study.
</P>
<P>
   Children, after all, absorb our attitudes. If we see homework as
a pain that interferes with the fun stuff, so will they.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally recognized educator and author Lucy Calkins offers
her family as an example. At the start of each school year, she
hunkers down at the kitchen table with her sons, looking at
assignments, poking into books, checking work, asking questions
and, most of all, having some spirit about it: ``Do you realize all
the fun ideas we can come up with for this?''
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds like Calkins is doing the work for Miles, a sixth
grader, and Evan, a fourth grader, she admits she walks a thin
line. It's a risk she says is worth taking.
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely, one of the points of homework is to help a child
achieve independence in work and thought, she says. But, she adds,
``When your theme is, `It's your work, your responsibility, and you
need to own it,' research shows kids tend to do less, be satisfied
with less, and learn less. If you don't get involved, they don't
know what it is to do an excellent job.''
</P>
<P>
   Calkins' over-involvement peaks at the beginning of school. Her
goal is to get her children used to high standards (again) and to
get new teachers to expect high quality from them. Calkins is
professor of education at Teachers College at Columbia University
and author of ``Raising Lifelong Learners, A Parent's Guide''
(Perseus).
</P>
<P>
   The danger, of course, is that a child gets too dependent on
you, which is why Calkins backs off after a few months. Oh, she'll
still be visible and always ready with questions, conversation, and
poster board, but her hope is that by then, her sons will have
internalized the standards she set.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist Catherine Snow endorses the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What most parents don't realize is that teachers respond more
to a child whose parents are actively involved,'' she says. Snow is
a professor at the Harvard Graduate School of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Calkins's first step is to make sure Miles and Evan have an
assignment pad for writing the homework down, and a folder for
homework papers. She also builds in a time and place for homework
so it becomes as routine as brushing teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Seefeldt encourages this kind of routine starting in first
grade. Indeed, her favorite strategy is to create family homework
time where everyone does some quiet work, including younger,
homework-free siblings who are expected to draw or play quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a high level of structure, even with a high level of
enthusiasm, there's bound to come a time when a fourth or fifth
grader asserts himself: ``It's my homework and I can do it any way
I want, even if it is sloppy or wrong!'' This is where parents
usually turn into Homework Cops.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what gets you into struggles,'' says educational
consultant Dawna Markova. She tells parents to think coach instead
of cop. ``Be a partner, not a boss,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of yelling at your kid, `You're rushing too much! This
is too sloppy! Why aren't you concentrating?' help him see for
himself that he's rushing. Help him figure out for himself what
helps him to be the best possible learner,'' she says. She is
coauthor of ``Learning Unlimited, Using Homework to Engage Your
Child's Natural Style of Intelligence'' (Conari).
</P>
<P>
   Her strategy involves writing a homework contract with your
child that might go something like this: ``We agree to be homework
partners so that John can learn the best way that he learns and so
that homework can be ... fun for him ...'' Clauses might include:
``John promises not to whine or give up. Mom promises not to yell
or offer help unless it's asked for.''
</P>
<P>
   When he does ask for help, have the contract on the table
between you before you look at the math. If it's messy and full of
sloppy errors, the Homework Cop would say, ``How can a teacher read
this? You have to do it over!''
</P>
<P>
   The Homework Coach says, ``I'm going to partner you through.
Here's what I see: 14 correct answers, 6 mistakes, and a paper
that's hard to read. What would you like to see the teacher write
on it? How many answers do you wish were correct?'' Markova says
that approach frees a child from being defensive and enables her to
correct herself because she wants to.
</P>
<P>
   Calkins's answer to ``It's my homework!'' is to show shock and
amazement: ``I can't believe you want to take the quick way out!''
She might even acquiesce: ``For one night, that's fine, but if this
is a habit, we have a lot to talk about. It's my job to steer you
to be the most thoughtful person you can be, just like it's my job
to make sure you eat vegetables.''
</P>
<P>
   When a child gets frustrated, Markova suggests a glass-full vs.
glass-empty approach that helps increase a child's ability to see
what is working. She throws down her pencil in frustration? Point
out what she had done successfully up to that point. She whines
that she can't sit still? What can she do? Jog in place? Run in
circles? Sing at the top of her lungs?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe she begins to learn that she needs to take short breaks
in order to regain her concentration,'' says Markova. ``Or that she
can concentrate better if she has a headset on. Gradually that
translates to other situations. During a test, she calms herself by
humming the song she studied to.''
</P>
<P>
   For the inevitable moment when all your child wants from you is
the answer, Markova has two responses:
</P>
<P>
   _``If I give you the answer, you have to agree to tell me
tomorrow how it helped you learn in school.'' Typically, she says,
a child will admit it didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   _``I'll give you the answer but you have to figure out how I got
it.'' Make sure he agrees that if he can't figure it out, he'll ask
you to help him figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   When a child gets very frustrated, Markova talks about ``sizzle
points.'' ``Help him to figure out what was going on just before he
felt like he wanted to throw something out the window: `Is there a
voice in your head saying you're stupid? Does your stomach tighten
up? Do your hands get sweaty?'''
</P>
<P>
   She says that if he can recognize he's reaching a breaking
point, he can ask himself, `What do I need to do now? Run up and
down the stairs? Make faces in the mirror?' ``Pretty soon,'' says
Markova, ``he can work his own gear shift.''
</P>
<P>
   For the times when no strategy helps, Seefeldt recommends old
fashioned logical consequences. ``If he's satisfied to turn in
sloppy work with wrong answers, the teacher's unhappy response may
be what most motivates him not to do it again,'' she says. If
possible, let a teacher know you're doing that.
</P>
<P>
   For the times when homework is nothing more than busy work,
Calkins says, ``I'd help him get through it as fast as possible.''
She'll type on the computer what Evan dictates to her, or she'll
allow her sons to barter services: Evan helps Miles cut out what he
needs from a magazine in exchange for homework help Miles will
profer at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, her favorite strategy is to stretch her sons'
thinking by making homework fun. Last year, Miles had an assignment
to weigh himself in something other than pounds. ``He was satisfied
to convert to ounces,'' says Calkins, ``but I said, `Wait a minute!
How much do you weigh in Tuckers (the family dog)? Before the night
was out, they had weighed John (their father) in cans of Ragu
spaghetti sauce!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- Always provide time for play after school before homework but
also don't squeeze homework right up to bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   -- The first month of school, ask the teacher for homework
patterns, for instance, that there's more on Tuesday because
there's a math quiz every Wed.
</P>
<P>
   -- Never secretely correct a homework paper.
</P>
<P>
   -- What is the teacher's homework philosophy? What role does she
want you to play? Are there assignments she doesn't want you to
help with? Are there specific ways she wants you to help?
</P>
<P>
   -- Don't dwell on last year's homework struggles. Consider a new
year a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   -- A struggle over a specific assignment may be a signal that
something's wrong with the assignment. A struggle almost every
night is more likely a signal that you and your child have an issue
about something beyond homework.
</P>
<P>
   -- If homework is consistently too easy or too difficult for
your child, be sure to let the teacher know.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AFTERTHOUGHT _ Toddlers who average half an inch taller than their
peers tend to be more aggressive than normal at age 11, according
to a study published in the Archives of General Psychiatry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)nws.globe.com. Her
columns are now on line at Boston.Com, keyword ``parenting.'' For
photocopies of past columns, send a self-addressed, stamped
envelope to Barbara F. Meltz, The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378. Please specify the column.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
