<HEADLINE>
ABUSIVE FATHERS A TENNIS PLAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Though it's not clear who launched the Bad Dads Club
of tennis, the latest member appears to be Marinko Lucic, a Croat
whose rising teenage daughter _ 50th-ranked Mirjana Lucic _ wants
to present him with a restraining order.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not it's to be a belated Father's Day gift, she feels
he's had it coming for years, and she has moved with her mother out
of his household grasp in Makarska to Bradenton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in my life that I really enjoy
tennis,'' she said after overpowering Naoko Sawamatsu of Japan,
4-6, 6-1, 6-1, Wednesday at Flushing Meadow. That set up a US Open
third-round collision tomorrow with her girlhood heroine, Steffi
Graf, whose father happens to be a prominent club member.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen-year-old Mirjana, a 6-footer who strikes tennis balls
ferociously, told a Croatian newspaper, Slobadna Dalmacija of
Split, that her dad beat her when he was displeased with her
results. ``It was going on for a long time,'' she said.
``Everything kind of happened in Wimbledon _ a time when I couldn't
handle it anymore and I just had to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   The breaking-up point apparently was reached when she and Mahesh
Bhupathi lost the Wimbledon mixed doubles final to Serena Williams
and Max Mirnyi. ``Mirjana,'' said a Serbian journalist, ``was
showing too much joy, in his view, happy to be in a Wimbledon
final. But Marinko was furious with her for losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sad and distressing as it is, there's nothing new about parents
who _ physically or mentally _ beat up on their kids for falling
short of expectations or not following orders. Or, in the case of
Peter Graf, Steffi's old man, battering her emotionally with his
misdeeds: philandering, drunkenness, and income tax evasion that
landed him in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have our fathers,'' John F. Kennedy once shrugged,
alluding to the slippery behavior of his own when somebody brought
up an indiscreet act of Martin Luther King's.
</P>
<P>
   While you can point to any number of peerless papas in tennis,
such as Jimmy Evert (Chris Evert's sire) and Bill Moffitt (Billie
Jean King's), the Bad Dads Club has gotten the ink and camera time.
Possibly the founder in the 19th century was John Roosevelt of the
prominent New York family, an uncle of President Franklin Delano
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   He pushed daughters Ellen and Grace in the game at a time when
it was no more than a hit-and-giggle diversion for well-bred young
women in corsets and ankle-length dresses. Ellen Hansell, the
original US champ in 1887, remembered, ``Their father coached and
treated them as if they were a pair of show ponies. We silly,
non-serious-minded players laughed at their early-to-bed and
careful food habits.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1890, Ellen Roosevelt took the US singles and joined Grace
for the doubles title, but soon they were out of the game, perhaps
feeling that father didn't know best about tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Hooker pleased her demanding, wealthy industrialist daddy,
Elon Hooker, by making the US quarterfinals in 1923. But when he
suggested she'd have to work harder for Wimbledon the following
year, she recalled with relish, ``I threw my racket at him and
quit.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most celebrated Bad Dads we know and hiss today, besides
Graf, are Americans named Jaeger, Capriati, and Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Pierce brutalized daughter Mary, verbally and sometimes with
his fists, while motivating her toward the top. After she got a
restraining order, Mary rebounded to win the Australian Open in
1995. She faces Cara Black in the second round today. She's damaged
goods, erratic in her performances but struggling to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Stefano Capriati raised a gold mine named Jennifer. He threw her
among the pros at 13, then watched her win Olympic gold in 1992 and
turn from a sweet, ingenuous kid into a sullen, troubled young
woman. He made sure she roamed the world, competed too much even
when injured, and pursued as many dollars as possible before she
fell apart at 18.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer, 22, was here again, granted a for-old-times'-sake wild
card, trying to find herself. She was heartened by a fond reception
from a large crowd as she lost aimlessly to Jana Novotna, but she
is clearly confused. You hope she can find direction and purpose
missing at home.
</P>
<P>
   Roland Jaeger instilled in his child, Andrea, the joys of
playing hurt, including the French Open with a cracked pelvis. She
was a Top 10 player (No. 5 at 15), a French (1982) and Wimbledon
(1983) finalist _ and scrapped by injuries before she was 20.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary and edifying P.S.: Andrea, one of the great
products of the game, cares lovingly for countless children today,
operating Silver Lining Ranch for terminally ill kids at Aspen,
Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea demonstrates that there's always a chance for the progeny
of the Bad Dads. Mirjana Lucic says she has received ``tremendous
sympathy and support'' from her colleagues and thinks life without
father can be beautiful. We can only hope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
