<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURNS WON'T PUT UP WITH COMPLACENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He was named NHL coach of the year in June, and in many
ways, Pat Burns was as much the toast of the town as rookie of the
year Sergei Samsonov. In his first season behind the Bruins' bench,
Burns led Boston to 91 points (39-30-13), 30 points better than the
year before.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, seated at his desk in the FleetCenter, Burns wouldn't
acknowledge that there was a honeymoon period. Sure, the club
performed better than many expected. But as far as the coach is
concerned, since he didn't know what to expect himself, the idea of
a honeymoon period is a misconception.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the life expectancy for a coach in the NHL?'' he asked.
``Three or four years? If you want to call it a honeymoon period, I
guess I'm OK for this year.''
</P>
<P>
   If there are expectations for the 1998-99 season, they are
likely to be delayed until the five remaining Group 2 free agents
(Jason Allison, Kyle McLaren, Anson Carter, Ted Donato, and Steve
Heinze) are in the fold. Without them, any projections would surely
be greatly diminished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year nobody really expected us to do what we did,'' said
Burns. ``Now, of course, the expectations are that we're going to
do better. There are some changes in the alignment of the divisions
and the schedule is tough again early. So that's going to be
obviously important. The only difference between this year and last
year is that teams aren't going to say, `The Bruins are in town
(and they're) easy.' They're going to say, `We have to work to beat
these guys.' We have to be prepared to have a little bit more
adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   That adversity could begin as early as the first day of training
camp, Sept. 12, when at least one of the five free agents is
expected to sit out. Burns said he won't allow their absence to be
a disruptive influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely no fun,'' said Burns. ``I'm hoping and praying
they'll all be there, but if they're not, I'll have to just turn
the page and go on. There's nothing I can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns is remaining positive about the club's chances for a
resolution with the free agents. He is expecting an even better
season from Allison than last year. One reason Allison came into
his own, ending up as the team's leading scorer and ninth in the
league, was the influence of Burns, who wouldn't allow the player
to coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball is going to be definitely in his court,'' said Burns.
``Last year it was a little bit in mine, but now it's in his. He's
proven what he can do in this league. Now it's all up to him
because the adversity is going to be different. He's not going to
be able to do perhaps what he did over the course of an 82-game
schedule with people not knowing who he is. It took him a while to
get going. He was real close to not even staying on this team last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   This time Allison and Samsonov won't be able to sneak up on
other teams. Opponents will make it their mission to shut them
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not just going to be No. 41 on the ice _ teams are going
to say, `Watch this guy. This guy can break your back,''' Burns
said of Allison. ``He is going to have to know that, and we'll
remind him of that. But I don't think I'm going to have to take the
same course of action I took last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Donato, who had asked to be moved in the spring after his role
under Burns diminished as the season wore on, has a place on the
club, but the coach said he has to earn it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's up to Teddy what kind of role he wants,'' said Burns.
``He can't live in the past, either. He has to live on what he's
going to bring forth to the hockey club. If he wants to bring forth
something to the club which he can do, we'll give him a role. I
don't dislike Teddy Donato. I don't dislike anybody on this hockey
club. My job is to win games. I don't pick on people. Teddy played
some big games for us and he played some not-so-big games for us.
I'm not going to sit here and define his role publicly, that's for
darn sure. He went public, that's his business, but I'm not going
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns believes he treats all players equally and said he'll be
happy to give Donato ice time _ provided Donato plays better.
Donato has acknowledged that he had some struggles last season and
said he will enter this season hungrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't bring something to the table on a certain night,
we're not going to use you,'' said Burns, who has been known to
parcel out ice time shift to shift rather than game to game. ``That
was the same with everybody. Jason sat on the bench. Dmitri
Khristich sat on the bench. They didn't give up and say, `That's
it.' Obviously, Teddy sees himself in a different role or a more
important role. That's all up to him. It's not up to me. If you
want to give me that, we'll give it to you, but it has to be our
way, not your way.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns believes captain Ray Bourque _ who turns 38 in December
and is scheduled to begin negotiating a contract extension next
week _ can play ad infinitum.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as he wants to play and as much as he wants to play,''
said Burns, summing up how Bourque will be used in his 20th NHL
season. ``I said that last year. I'm not going to start saving
Raymond Bourque because he's 38 years old. Save him for what? If he
can play and he can keep up to what he's done, he will play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray is a special person and a special player. Unfortunately,
we don't have a whole bunch of those guys. As long as he wants to
play, he's welcome to play, for me, anyways.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bourque anchors the veteran end of the dressing room along
with Don Sweeney, Dave Ellett, and Ken Baumgartner, Burns said
there are plenty of lessons to be learned by the kids. He expects
Cameron Mann and Shawn Bates, who spent last season in Providence,
to make a contribution in Boston this year, and he is banking on
players such as Hal Gill to build on last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is still a young hockey club and it has a lot to learn,''
said Burns. ``Mann and Bates have a lot of upside. But you can't go
up and then flatten out. That's what they did. This is a big year
for those two guys. With Gill, there's going to be a little bit
more pressure on him. In your second year, it's a little different
because people know you a little bit more. He's going to have to
sit down and really look at that and be able to understand that
it's not going to be like it was.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins had an Achilles' heel last season, it was that
they were a tad undersized. Their strength was in their skating
game, and that should be true again. Burns hopes the size situation
will be improved by forward Landon Wilson, who can best be
described as an enigma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Landon as a boy,'' said Burns. ``He's a great guy.
What's important for him is he can't live on what he's done in the
last 10 minutes. He has to live on what he's going to do in the
next 10 minutes. What we have to get across is it's not the last
two shifts you played well, you just played a bad one. We need his
size. He's a big, strong boy, and we need that up front.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
