<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JETSKI-SLAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WET JET SET RIDES LOUD AND PROUD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMPTON, N.H. _ ``Bummer,'' Mike Bandecchi declared, surveying
the calm seas off Hampton Beach State Park last Sunday. ``I like it
rough.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, don't they all? Bandecchi, a 26-year-old sheet metal
mechanic from Chichester, who's an Ed Marinaro look-alike, wasn't
the only jet skier who couldn't wait for Hurricane Bonnie's skirts
to brush the New England coast. What good's a 450-pound oceangoing
version of a dirt bike if you can't crash a cresting 8-foot wave at
50 miles per hour, point your nose to the sky, and catch some air?
</P>
<P>
   They come here every weekend, just as they do to Newburyport or
Falmouth or anyplace else they hope to catch a wave. Unloading at
the state boat ramp at Hampton Marina, these self-admitted
adrenaline junkies motor their personal watercraft (PWC) _ Jet Ski
is actually a Kawasaki brand name _ out the mouth of the Hampton
River to the ocean. You can see and hear them from the
cheek-by-jowl homes on Seabrook Beach as they buzz like bees off
Beckmans Point, yahooing through jumps, spins, and doughnuts. And
if they fall overboard or capsize, that's part of the game.
``Raising heck and jumping waves'' is how Robert Goss, a
34-year-old bricklayer from Manchester described it.
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, is just the kind of talk that drives boaters,
swimmers, cottagers, and environmentalists crazy. A lot of these
folks tend to see the PWC crowd as uncouth and untrained waterbound
terrorists whose only redeeming value is keeping hospital emergency
rooms busy. Powered by water that is drawn by an inboard motor and
pumped out the rear, PWCs can travel at speeds as high as 75 miles
per hour. There are no brakes, and the craft can't be steered when
the throttle is off, although they can still continue moving via
Newton's laws.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that PWCs are involved in a disproportionate share of
boating accidents. A record 85 operators were killed last year in
the United States. Just this week, a 15-year-old boy riding in a
PWC was killed on Lake Winnipesaukee, 50 miles northwest of
Hampton. Many states and municipalities have placed restrictions on
the machines, and sales finally began to dip in 1997 after a decade
of phenomenal growth. (Current prices of new models range from
$4,800 to $9,400.) Memo to the opposition, however: There are still
an estimated million-plus PWCs flitting through US waters.
</P>
<P>
   And besides, most of the many men and few women (an estimated 85
percent of PWC buyers are males) who trailer their craft here each
weekend don't much care what other people think of them. ``What is
it they call us, `The Psychos of the Beach?''' Rich Ventura of
Billerica, Mass., asked proudly on Sunday. ``Get a couple of girls
on the beach watching me, and I'll stand on my head on this
thing,'' the 27-year-old landscaper added, nodding toward his
Kawasaki.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura was here with Tom D'Ovidio, also from Billerica, also
27, and also a landscaper. After slipping into their wet suits
(optional) and life jackets (required), the pair donned light
zippered boots and padded gloves. As D'Ovidio prepared to launch
his $8,200 Yamaha, which he noted will top off at 72 miles per
hour, he revealed the wave-jumping math that would, alas, be
irrelevant on this particular day. ``The height of your jump is
usually twice the height of the wave,'' he explained. ``Five-foot
waves, 10-foot jumps. Twelve-foot waves, 25-foot jumps.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the winds weren't cooperating, Ventura and D'Ovidio could
at least hang out at what is informally known here as Jet Ski
Beach, on the opposite shore of the Hampton River. The strip of
sand is an informal PWC clubhouse on weekends, a place to spread
your blanket and eat lunch, and from which to periodically motor
forth to the (hopefully) high seas.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five-year-old Bob Healey of Salem comes to Jet Ski Beach
with a gaggle of relatives every couple of weeks or so, beaching
his Sea-Doo GTX in the sand, giving rides to his nephews and
nieces, heading alone into the waves. When he bought his PWC for
$7,600 in 1996, taking a three-year note from a bank, he often
traveled to Winnipesaukee to ride. But the big lake doesn't have a
place where PWCers can hang, he said. And it doesn't have what the
ocean has. ``Once you come out here and hit the waves, you wouldn't
go back there,'' he mused.
</P>
<P>
   (Like a lot of PWC owners here, Healey also owns a motorcycle.
Not surprisingly, the craft tend to be sold by cycle dealers rather
than boat dealers. Sometimes a PWC serves as a motorcycle
substitute. ``My wife won't let me have a motorcycle because I
crashed two of 'em,'' explained Steve Leonard, 25, of Lowell, Mass.
``That's why I got one of these,'' he added, pointing to his
two-month-old Sea-Doo.)
</P>
<P>
   A few yards away, Greg Chicoine, a 24-year-old auto mechanic
from Uxbridge, Mass., lounged on the beach and watched a 20-foot
motorboat speed past, tossing up a significant wake in a no-wake
zone. Shaking his head, Chicoine offered a common lament: ``If that
was a jet skier, the (New Hampshire) Marine Patrol would stop him.
Happens all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet most of the folks jockeying PWCs out here admit _ some a
tad proudly _ that the people who gnash their teeth over jet skiers
often have a case. Every rider has a near-miss story (``The damn
kid nearly landed on top of me!''), although it was almost always
the other guy's fault. ``There are a lot of people out here who
just don't know what they're doing,'' pointed out 32-year-old Mike
Desmarais of Manchester, who races PWCs competitively. Desmarais
puts the blame for hotdogging on the large two- and three-seaters
that now account for almost all PWC sales. The first units that
became popular, nearly a quarter of a century ago, were one-seaters
or even stand-up models, which you seldom see today. ``Those take
at least a season to master,'' Desmarais said. ``Anybody can get on
a two- or three-seater and take right off.'' Literally.
</P>
<P>
   Not that absolutely everyone here was seeking the perfect wave.
Bob and Celeste Schmitt of Nottingham were beginning a leisurely
26-mile run up the coast to Portsmouth and back for lunch, a Sunday
drive on the water. ``I like it because it's easy to park,''
Celeste Schmitt, one of the few women in sight, said of the
family's Polaris three-seater.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bandecchi, meanwhile, had finally given up after a couple
of hours of fruitless waiting for waves. ``Too damn calm,'' he said
as he pulled his Sea-Doo XP Limited two-seater from the water. ``I
guess I'll go find my girlfriend. I'll come back in a few days if
the storm comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bummer, indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
