<HEADER>
A7228 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TEACHABLE-MOM     09-03 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TEACHABLE-MOMENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON/LEWINSKY OFFERED US A `TEACHABLE MOMENT' -- WAS IT LOST? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JIM CASTELLI &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Religious leaders often talk about a teachable moment -- a time
when events focus public attention on a moral question in an
unprecedented way.
</P>
<P>
   For example, during the months leading up to the Gulf War,
Americans conducted an extensive discussion about the nature of a
just war.
</P>
<P>
   The eight months since the Monica Lewinsky scandal emerged has
been a painful time for all Americans. But it has also been a
teachable moment -- a time when the public's attention has been
focused on core moral and ethical issues, including the nature of
sin, forgiveness, and trust; professional ethics, and the
connection between private and public morality.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this moment has been squandered. The tone of
moral debate has been set by the tabloids -- a category that now
includes just about all of the media.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the only religious leaders who have spoken
out are those who hate President Clinton no matter what he does and
those who love him no matter what he does. Most religious leaders
are extremely reluctant to talk about public controversy involving
sex or partisan politics, and this controversy involves both.
</P>
<P>
   But the failure to speak out in a situation that demands cool
heads, nuance and moral perspective is a dereliction of duty on the
part of Americans religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
   This may not be surprising at a time when the professions of
politics, law and media have generally disgraced themselves. But we
expect more from religious leaders, if only because they tell us we
should.
</P>
<P>
   Here, then, are some of the things that religious leaders, and
anyone concerned about morality and ethics, should be saying:
</P>
<P>
   --It is always wrong to spread false and malicious stories.
</P>
<P>
   --Everyone sins. The American Heritage Dictionary defines sin as
``a transgression of a religious or moral law, especially when
deliberate.
</P>
<P>
   Someone once called original sin -- the belief that every human
being sins at some time or other -- the most empirically verifiable
religious belief. Jesus came to the defense of an adulteress woman
by telling a crowd, ``Let he who is without sin cast the first
stone.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of people who mistakenly believe they are without sin are
throwing a lot of stones today.
</P>
<P>
   --All sins are not equal. Sins differ in both their nature and
their context. Stealing a pizza is wrong and so is murder, but the
offenses are far from equal. And stealing a pizza for fun, stealing
it to trade for drugs, and stealing it to feed a starving family
are also very different offenses.
</P>
<P>
   --You have to ask for forgiveness before you can receive it, but
asking isn't enough. If we forgive someone who has not asked for
forgiveness, we only encourage him or her to repeat the offense.
When someone does ask for forgiveness, he or she must also do
penance and take steps to show that he or she will not repeat the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   --The test of your commitment to ethical standards is your
willingness to stick to them when it's not convenient. If grand
jury testimony is supposed to be secret, it's supposed to be secret
even when leaking it would give you an advantage. If reporters are
supposed to verify stories before they report them, they have to
verify them even when skipping that stage would give them a scoop.
If we throw out ethical standards to seek a temporary advantage,
then our commitment to those standards is a sham.
</P>
<P>
   --We must evaluate people by the sum of their actions. About 20
years ago I mused to a wizened editor that good people sometimes do
bad things and bad people sometimes do good things. He replied,
``And there are very few good people or bad people.''
</P>
<P>
   --What we think of someone today can change dramatically
depending upon what they do tomorrow, or what new facts emerge
tomorrow. We evaluate people in different ways in different
circumstances; we may stop considering someone a friend, but still
admire his or her talents.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have always lived with ambiguous attitudes toward
their presidents. Did John F. Kennedy risk his presidency with his
reckless private life? Did Lyndon Johnson do more good with the
Great Society than he did harm with the Vietnam War? Even many
liberals who detested Richard Nixon when he was in office look back
on many of his domestic policies as surprisingly liberal by today's
standards. We should practice humility when we attempt to judge
people.
</P>
<P>
   --We should evaluate public officials primarily on the basis of
their public responsibilities to advance the common good. Private
action is not irrelevant, but it must be seen in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   --Morality is often a matter of proportionality. The just war
theory argues that to be morally justified, the good that a war
achieves must outweigh the evil that it causes. That's a daunting
standard -- one that should apply to every major public
undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Jim Castelli is the author of ``A Plea for Common Sense:
Resolving the Clash Between Religion and Politics'' (Harper &AMP; Row).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
