<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7246 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-KIDS-LATIN-AME     09-03 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-KIDS-LATIN-AMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATIN AMERICA'S STREET CHILDREN CRY FOR HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By SILVANA PATERNOSTRO  
 c.1998 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Bolivia, 11-year-old Macario, illiterate and homeless, who
ran away from home at age 4 and has lived on the streets since
then, is scheduled to meet the president of his country.
</P>
<P>
   Macario wants to ask President Hugo Banzer Suarez to help ``show
the world that we are also people,'' and that he and his street
friends ``have talents we want to develop,'' he told a reporter
from EFE, when asked about the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Macario has a friend, he told the news agency, who
would certainly be an athlete fit to win the Olympics, if given the
opportunity _ Mr. President can you help?
</P>
<P>
   The boy says that actually he wants to convey several things.
For instance, it is infuriating to see government officials on
television talk about the rights of children when the violence they
fear the most comes directly from the authorities. It is this
statement that is most important about the meeting between the boy
and the president.
</P>
<P>
   Macario described how the police extract money from him and
other street children _ how the boys must pay the officers to be
able to sleep an entire night without being awakened by blows and
kicks. ``Some girl from the group has to sleep with a policeman so
that they will leave us in peace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Surely Rev. Morris Bertolli, the priest who runs the Santa
Aquilina Children's Home, a place where many Bolivian street
children have found shelter, and who organized the meeting between
Macario and the president, has the best of intentions.
</P>
<P>
   But the priest's efforts could amount to little more than
providing Banzer with a photo opportunity and a chance to seem
concerned and compassionate about the plight of these unfortunate
children without having to confront the urgent issue _ the constant
abuse they endure from his government's police force.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to be fooled by the possibility of a fairy tale come
true. Who wouldn't be tempted to run with the fantasy that
Macario's friend might win an Olympic medal? But for the millions
of street children who are victims of police brutality it would be
more important, instead, to stop and think about the crude reality
of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   To demand the unraveling of the Gordian knot of systemic abuse
and impunity under which police forces in Latin America operate is
less romantic than asking to turn a street orphan into an Olympic
hero, but it would prove, in the long run, more rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   There are 100 million street children in the world; 40 million
live in Latin America. Macario could very well be speaking for them
all. His mother abandoned him and a younger brother, leaving them
with an abusive father. The abuse must have been intolerable
because Macario preferred, rather than to endure it, to abandon his
sibling and take to the street _ at age 4.
</P>
<P>
   On the street he found friends, other children, and formed his
own street family. Still today, they fight hunger by begging,
eating scraps and inhaling glue. They protect one another from
inclement weather and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Macario's story is not exclusive to Bolivia. It is the same tale
one hears from the ``ninos de la calle'' in Guatemala, from the
gamines in Bogota, from the ``meninos du rua'' in Rio de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, efforts such as Bertolli's exist throughout Latin
America. Catholic groups; non-governmental organizations such as
ChildHope, Covenant House and UNICEF; and even local governments
spend millions of dollars providing these children with the
possibility of a future. They are given homes, sent to school,
taught a skill.
</P>
<P>
   In Colombia, Rev. Javier de Nicolo has spent more than 30 years
giving shelter to these children. He rides a white van into the
dark, dirty and damp streets of downtown Bogota where he invites
the swarms of boys and girls to live in his houses.
</P>
<P>
   In Central America, Casa Alianza, a branch of Covenant House,
has provided thousands of children with a future. I once met a
young man, a former street boy, who was studying to be a doctor;
another one in Bogota was taking a computer programming course.
</P>
<P>
   But these stories, as inspiring as they are, are few and far
apart. The truth is that the offer of a home does not necessarily
mean these children depart from the streets. After their chaotic
lives, many cannot get used to rules, even to the obvious and
necessary ones in these well-meaning programs.
</P>
<P>
   Those who do and stay, still face a life of discrimination,
marginalization and abuse. ``No one wants to employ a former street
boy,'' a social worker once told me.
</P>
<P>
   It would be more beneficial to everyone if more effort were
spent trying to teach society how to change the attitudes toward
street children before offering promises that sound beautiful but
would be very hard, if not impossible to keep. We can start by
changing the attitudes of, say, the private armed guards in Bogota,
who refer to street children as ``desechables,'' disposables.
</P>
<P>
   As for Mexico, if hospital authorities were more considerate in
the way they treat street children who come asking for help, deaths
such as the one of Brenda Ramirez Carrillo would be avoided. This
July in Mexico City, Brenda, a street girl who lived on the Avenida
Insurgentes, was hit by a car. The driver fled, leaving her to die.
She pulled herself together, but was too afraid of doctors to seek
medical help.
</P>
<P>
   It would be better for Banzer to promise that he will act to end
the systemic abuse of street children than to help Macario's friend
in a noble quest to win the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SILVANA PATERNOSTRO, a Colombian-born journalist, is the
author of ``In the Land of God and Man: Confronting Our Sexual
Culture,'' to be published by Dutton in November. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Her article on contemporary life in Cuba is forthcoming in The
New York Times Magazine.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Paternostro has recently reported on Pope John Paul's historic
visit to Cuba, Gabriel Garcia Marquez's efforts to rejuvenate Latin
American journalism, New York City's Latino community and Mexico's
``narco-democracy.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (She is a proud winner of the Center for Documentary Studies'
Dorothea Lange-Paul Taylor Prize for her prior journalism on Cuba;
and has also written for The Paris Review, Spin, The Nation, The
Miami Herald and The New York Daily News. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Paternostro holds a master's degree from Columbia University's
School of International and Public Affairs and is currently a
senior fellow at the World Policy Institute in Manhattan.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
