   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday, Sept. 4, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Tina May at (206) 448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHURCH (Pavolvsk, Russia) _ His country in economic and
political turmoil, the Rev. Valery Svetsov reflects on how the
Russian Orthodox Church has helped his countrymen endure decades of
war, oppression and seemingly endless deprivation. ``An old adage
says, `The Russian man never makes the sign of the cross until the
thunderstorm comes,''' he noted. The heavens have unleashed a
deluge on Mother Russia, and indeed, evidence of revived interest
in the church is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``i'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-FIRE (Undated) William Nicholson's historical romance
``Firelight'' rather audaciously blends a timely and modern theme _
surrogate motherhood _ with an early-Victorian setting and a Gothic
British literary style to come up with only so-so results.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CHAMBERMAID (Undated) ``The Chambermaid'' is an original
and smart film.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-INSOMNIA (Undated) ``Insomnia,'' explores a different kind
of paranoia _ a far more complicated and interesting variety.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-COUGARS-BENDER (Pullman, Wash.) The death of defensive
tackle Leon Bender last spring still affects the Washington State
Cougars as they prepare for their season opener Saturday against
Illinois at Pullman.
</P>
<P>
   By Angelo Bruscas. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
