</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7249 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-FIRELIGHT-SPI &LR;      09-03 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FIRELIGHT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FIRELIGHT' TAKS A LOOK AT SURROGATE MOTHERHOOD IN VICTORIAN ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Nicholson's historical romance ``Firelight'' rather
audaciously blends a timely and modern theme _ surrogate motherhood
_ with an early-Victorian setting and a Gothic British literary
style to come up with only so-so results.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which opened the last Seattle International Film
Festival and begins a regular run today, seemingly lifts its
storyline right out of the '90s cable-movie line-up and plops it
down in the setting of ``Jane Eyre.'' Despite some good moments, it
doesn't fly.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the 1830s, the script has Charles (Stephen Dillane), a
handsome British nobleman tied to a comatose wife, so desperate for
an heir that he's auditioning candidates to anonymously mate with
him, have his child and instantly give it up _ for a fee, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   He finds the ideal match in Elisabeth (Sophie Marceau), a
hard-pressed, drop-dead beautiful Swiss woman with a past. They do
the deed for three days at a French hotel, she has a daughter nine
months later and, as per her contract, promptly vanishes from
Charles' life.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years later, however, she's so tormented by abandoning her
child that she tracks father and daughter down (just how is never
explained), and _ while Charles is away _ snags the job as
governess to her very own daughter (Dominique Belcourt).
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, when Charles returns to find Elisabeth on the
premises, he's not a bit happy about it. But he soon remembers
their several nights of passion together, and, after a while, the
spoiled daughter begins to take to the governess, and ... well, you
know where this is going.
</P>
<P>
   As a first-time director, Nicholson (the screenwriter of
``Nell'' and ``Shadowlands'') has an eye for history and offers up
a handful of impressively executed scenes, including one exciting
and poignant sequence in which surrogate mother and child bond
through a harrowing experience on an ice-covered lake behind the
mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his script seems predictable every step of the way, and
curiously devoid of the scenes that might force us to feel some
emotional investment in the characters or their situation. The film
would be a respectable enough episode of ``Masterpiece Theater''
but is strangely aloof and unsatisfying as a feature film.
</P>
<P>
   It is also somewhat handicapped by having Sophie Marceau as its
star. She's competent, beautiful and has a pouty French elegance
that has worked well for her in many other roles (``Braveheart,''
Maurice Pialat's ``Police''). But she doesn't convey the grand
maternal tragedy necessary to make this film a heartfelt
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Firelight. Directed and written by William Nicholson. Cast:
Sophie Marceau, Stephen Dillane, Kevin Anderson, Lia Williams,
Dominique Belcourt, Joss Ackland. Hollywood Pictures. 104 minutes.
Rated R for adult themes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
