<SLUG> BC-FILM-CHAMBERMAID-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE CHAMBERMAID' IS ORIGINAL AND SMART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until a few weeks ago, the French-Italian-Spanish co-production
``The Chambermaid'' was officially known as ``The Chambermaid of
the Titanic.'' In fact, it's already had a reasonably successful
European run under that intriguing title.
</P>
<P>
   But in the wake of our own mega-hit, ``Titanic,'' the name
reportedly evoked giggles whenever its American distributors (the
Goldwyn Company) brought it up, making them fear the public might
expect the film to be an ``Airplane!''-like spoof.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the new title is even more misleading, and would
seem to doom the film to some corner of the art-house multiplexes.
Too bad, because it's an original and smart film, and one that
obliquely makes a wonderful comment on the recent ``Titanic''
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1912, it's the story of a handsome but shy and somewhat
hen-pecked Frenchman named Horty (Olivier Martinez) who wins a
coal-hauling contest at his Lorraine foundry, with the first prize
of a trip to Southhampton to watch the maiden sailing of the
Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   The night before that event, a beautiful French woman (Aitana
Sanchez Gijon) appears at the door of his hotel room. She has a job
as a chambermaid on the great liner, but all the hotels are full,
so she's hoping that, as a countryman, he might put her up.
</P>
<P>
   He does, they share a bed, and, though she seems to be coming on
to him during the night, he does not respond. The next morning,
she's gone. When he races down to the mooring, he gets there just
in time to watch her steam off into destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Back at his village, he relates the story to his friends, and _
egged on by their prurient interest _ not only lies about
consummating the union but wildly exaggerates it into a night of
passion worthy of the steamiest modern romance writer.
</P>
<P>
   When the Titanic sinks and the chambermaid is not on the list of
survivors, his story takes on a poignancy it didn't have before.
Horty is compelled to embellish his lie again and again. And he's
so spellbinding that people are soon coming from miles around to
hear his voluptuous, bittersweet story.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, he's recruited by a traveling dramatic show, and he
becomes its headliner and a legend all over Northern France. His
presentation takes on elaborate props, and his jealous,
long-suffering wife (Romane Bohringer) eventually gets into the
act, and even insists on portraying the Chambermaid on stage.
</P>
<P>
   As co-written and directed by noted Spanish filmmaker Bigas Luna
(``Jamon, Jamon''), the single downside to the film is that it
feels slightly contrived. It strains credulity here and there, and
the plot mechanics of getting Horty to the Titanic seem
particularly labored. After all, what kind of grand prize is it to
merely watch a ship sail?
</P>
<P>
   Still, the film works as a marvelous metaphor for the magic and
mystery of the artistic process. Horty is not delusional: he knows
exactly what he's doing. It's just that something about his
experience requires him to preserve it, twist it to his
psychological need and have people react to it. The same reason
other artists write books, compose music or paint chapels.
</P>
<P>
   Or make movies. Indeed, the wonder of the film is that it works
as a perfect metaphor for James Cameron's ``Titanic.'' Horty's need
to turn his Titanic experience into romance and mythology is the
same irresistible impulse that Cameron felt _ and we react to the
result pretty much as Horty's slightly less sophisticated audience
does.
</P>
<P>
   In this sense, ``The Chambermaid'' is either a clever
exploitation of the great ``Titanic'' phenomenon, or, more likely
(given the fact they were made at about the same time), an amazing
bit of artistic prescience on the part of Lunas, his team of
writers and Didier Decoin, who wrote the original novel on which
the film is based.
</P>
<P>
   The Chambermaid. Directed by Bigas Luna. Screenplay by Luna,
Cuca Canals, Jean-Louis Benoit. Cast: Olivier Martinez, Aitana
Sanchez Gijon, Romane Bohringer. Goldwyn. 96 minutes. In French
with English subtitles. Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
