<HEADLINE>
`INSOMNIA' IS THE BEST OF THE LOT ABOUT URBAN PARANOIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There has been a rash of movies about urban paranoia with
Kafka-esque leanings lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark City'' thrust its protagonist into an unknown realm and
dared him to solve the mystery of his own identity. ``Pi'' created
a schizophrenic world endured by a mathemetician slowly going
insane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insomnia,'' a 1997 film from Norway, which stars Stellan
Skarsgard (``Breaking The Waves'' and ``Good Will Hunting''), is
the best of the lot. It explores a different kind of paranoia _ a
far more complicated and interesting variety.
</P>
<P>
   Self-imposed panic overtakes chief criminal investigator Jonas
Engstrom (Skarsgard) as he arrives in Norway, the ``land of the
midnight sun,'' to solve the brutal murder of Tanja (Maria
Mathiesen), 17-year-old teenager whose body is found _ hair washed
and nails scrubbed _ in a rubbish heap. But Jonas' panic is
self-inflicted because of guilt and the fear of discovery.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, ``Insomnia,'' which is the debut film from Erik
Skjoldbjaerg, is more psychologically bent on transference and
counter-transference between killer and cop than the standard
cat-and-mouse chase of most American action films.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship is made even more intriguing because Jonas'
terror stems from the fact he has accidentally caused the death of
a colleague _ something he goes to great lengths to conceal. It's
an act that gives him perspective on Tanja's killer _ he, too,
claims her murder was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Skjoldbjaerg says his movie was inspired ``by the notion of
secrecy and how when one chooses to conceal something from others,
the sense of perspective is lost.'' Indeed, Jonas is so remote and
self-absorbed that he is as creepy as the killer he slowly comes to
resemble.
</P>
<P>
   With the unsettling effect of the bright, infernal sun and
Jonas' inability to sleep because of its eternal glare,
``Insomnia'' is a tense, taut suspense thriller in the vein of Lars
von Trier's subliminal ``The Element Of Crime'' or Hitchcock's
repressed mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   Even better is the lack of actual violence. Everything is
implied and, outside of an explicit scene with a carcass of a dog,
the film eschews blood for suggestion and the dark corners of the
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   The film teases with scary suggestion: will a basket of innocent
kittens become victims or will something happen to the beautiful
concierge at Jonas' hotel? Perhaps a detective who seems to know
the truth will run into bad luck. But like a puzzle or a maze,
there is only one logical exit. Skjoldbjaerg taunts us with a ton
of options but he skillfully takes the path that seems in perfect
sync with all that has come to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Insomnia. Directed by Erik Skjoldbjaerg. Written by Nikolaj
Frobenius. Cast: Stellan Skarsgard, Sverre Anker Ousdal, Gisken
Armand, Bjorn Floberg. First Run Features. 97 minutes. In Norwegian
with English subtitles. Unrated but with graphic violence, nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
