<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHURCH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN ORTHODOX CHURCH SEES ITS PRAYERS ANSWERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAVOLVSK, Russia _ His country in turmoil, the Rev. Valery
Svetsov reflected recently on how the Russian Orthodox Church has
helped his countrymen endure decades of war, oppression and
seemingly endless deprivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``An old adage says, `The Russian man never makes the sign of
the cross until the thunderstorm comes,''' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   The heavens have unleashed an economic and political deluge on
Mother Russia, providing urgency to the just-concluded summit
between President Clinton and Russian President Boris Yeltsin. And
true to the adage, many here are returning to religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church where I worshiped was packed today. Adversity
drives people to God, and that is the plus side,'' wrote Kathryn
Teitzel, an outreach worker from University Presbyterian Church in
Seattle, in an e-mail message to friends this week.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of revived interest in the church is everywhere. An
icon and candle shop does a brisk business at the gate to Red
Square in Moscow. Thousands of worshipers crowd into cathedrals
once used as museums. The three-hour Orthodox liturgy is again sung
by Svetsov at St. Nicholas Cathedral in Pavlovsk, which for years
was used as a repair shop for Red Army tanks.
</P>
<P>
   As it experiences a revival, however, the Russian Orthodox
Church remains at the center of controversy. The church hierarchy
was aligned with the state even during the area of Soviet atheism.
Its leaders continue to bless and be blessed by state authority.
The church is involved in business dealings that range from
cigarette imports to bottled water.
</P>
<P>
   A law passed last year and signed by President Boris Yeltsin
enshrines the church as the country's dominant religion and imposes
arduous registration and other requirements on other religious
groups.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the law, the church has competition.
</P>
<P>
   Evangelical Protestant denominations have sent missionaries to
places such as prisons, which have rarely seen an Orthodox priest,
and have brought in goods and social services. An estimated 4,000
evangelical congregations have grown up in Russia, along with 110
Bible schools. Other movements also have gained adherents.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox leaders are not particularly pleased at the competition
for souls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we have a lot of religious movements now, but a lot
of them are not positive,'' said Bishop Konstantin Gorianov, head
of the St. Petersburg Theological Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   It is doubtful that any denomination could ever supplant or
really contest the Orthodox Church. The church has served as a
keeper of the soul and culture of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet state tried everything in its power to diminish and
substitute for church influence, including turning Lenin into a
kind of secular icon. Wedding palaces were erected to substitute
for church marriage ceremonies. Churches were used as granaries and
machine shops. Historic cathedrals in Moscow and St. Petersburg
became museums of atheism.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how many priests were arrested or churches
vandalized, the church remained so influential that Stalin had to
seek its help in mobilizing resistance to the Nazis during World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church kept not only the faith but the culture,'' said the
Rev. Alexander Tkachenko, an Orthodox priest who received
chaplaincy training at Swedish Hospital in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russian people, they always were spiritual,'' he added. ``It
has always been inside us. Every man inside has a gut feeling of
the presence of eternity. Nobody could drive that away.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviets certainly tried. The front door of St. Nicholas
Cathedral has been rebuilt, but visitors can still see where the
door was widened so tanks could be brought inside.
</P>
<P>
   About 75 to 100 worshipers now crowd into a small restored area
that is rich in the smell of incense and where the chants and
rituals go back a thousand years.
</P>
<P>
   St. Nicholas Cathedral gets no support from the Diocese of St.
Petersburg and Ladoga. It is supported by the faithful, and by the
priest's enterprising wife, Ziniada Svetsova, who designs clergy
vestments and presides over a bakery that sells meat pastries to
the nearby Great Palace of Pavlovsk, once a czarist summer home and
now a premier visitor attraction.
</P>
<P>
   The rebuilding parish also has a benefactor thousands of miles
away. It receives money and such needed items as children's
vitamins from St. Augustine's-in-the-Woods Episcopal Church on
Whidbey Island, Wash., one of eight Seattle-area congregations to
have sister parishes in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Soviet authorities began turning property back to the church in
the late 1980s. St. Petersburg had 14 active Orthodox churches
before the era of perestroika; now it has 287. ``When we came here
in 1991, the whole territory of the church was covered with garbage
and metal,'' Svetsov said. ``Water was 3 meters deep in the
basement.''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran priest also is able to do much more ministering.
During the Soviet era, Svetsov was exiled from the city to a remote
country parish after committing the crime of having his picture
taken with foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I could once do was have a service,'' he said. ``I could
not preach about bringing up children in the church. I could not
have a Sunday school. I had to register every baptism with the
authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Soviet authorities permitted only three seminaries to operate in
the country, and chose which students could study for the
priesthood. The total has risen to 27 seminaries, with two to three
applicants for each position.
</P>
<P>
   Gorianov has expanded the curriculum of his seminary to include
topics such as psychology. ``We are now able to tell our students
how to teach philosophy,'' he added. ``Such subjects we were
prohibited to teach.''
</P>
<P>
   In looking forward, church leaders also are looking for ways to
hold together Russia. In July, such former Communist Party
officials as Yeltsin and St. Petersburg's governor, Vladimir
Yakovlev, were on hand for the religious ceremony in which the
remains of Czar Nicholas II were interred at the Cathedral of
Saints Peter and Paul in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachenko watched them. Yeltsin's wife made a sign of the cross,
as did Yakovlev's wife. Their husbands stood solemnly with their
heads bowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot say Yakovlev is a believer, but he is very respectful
toward the church,'' Tkachenko said. He noted that Yeltsin had the
patriarch of the Orthodox Church, Alexsy II, bless his troubled
reign.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``They perhaps understand,'' he said, ``that only the church can
preserve Russia from civil war, from moral destruction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
