<SLUG> BC-INVESTMENT-CLUB-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENT CLUBS SEE OPPORTUNITY IN ROLLER-COASTER WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COHOES, N.Y. _ Arnold Galarneau was ready for the Tuesday night
meeting of the Capitol Investors with file folder full of research
on stocks local investment might buy after Monday's stock market
plunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``These knee-jerk things happen all the time,'' the retired
accountant said. So the Dow Jones industrial average plunged more
than 512 points on Monday. To Galarneau, it was just an
overreaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is OK, inflation is low, interest rates are low,
so what more do you want?'' But since the market tanked the
resident of Cohoes, N.Y., was going to suggest to his fellow
investors that this week would be a good time to buy stocks whose
prices were way down.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy sounded good to his investment club partners. While
some investors were a little more ``apprehensive'' than Galarneau,
the idea of buying recession-resistant retail stocks like Office
Depot made sense, said John Munn, one of Galarneau's peers in the
investment club. In all, Capitol Investors has 14 members.
</P>
<P>
   Investment clubs are gatherings of ordinary people like
Galarneau and Munn, a chemist, who come together once or twice a
month and pool money to put into the stock market. Usually, members
buy shares or pay monthly dues to fund purchases. Members share the
job of researching the stocks and making the purchasing decisions,
and, they say, learn more about stocks and finances than they might
working alone.
</P>
<P>
   Through investment clubs, middle-class people like teachers,
mechanics and government workers find a way into the world of Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   A mother organization, the Michigan-based National Association
of Investment Clubs provides guidance and helps local groups form
and practice the art of investing for the long term, at least three
years out. That generally means finding well-managed companies at
good prices and holding onto the stock for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Some investment club members, including Rick LaPierre of Latham,
N.Y., say that belonging to a club and getting mutual support from
peers helps steady the nerves in trying times. LaPierre tried
investing on his own before joining the 6-year-old Upstate
Investment Club, but said he fared poorly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I panicked at every up and down.'' But the club will likely
hold onto its roster of 16 holdings, including PepsiCo Inc.,
Wendy's International and Prime Medical Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're riding it out,'' said LaPierre, who serves as treasurer
of the 22-member club. As of August, the club's holdings were worth
$53,000.
</P>
<P>
   Capitol Investors, partly since it is a younger club, had only
about $6,000 in its portfolio before Monday's dive, Munn said.
</P>
<P>
   But another young club, Schenectady's We Want $, has amassed
about $30,000 in its two years said club president Dave Anker.
Anker, who owns an auto repair shop in Schenectady, was asked to
steer the club because he had experience investing on his own, and
the 28 other members apparently liked his confidence in the
long-term approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trading, we're investing,'' Anker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
