<P>
   IRELAND-CLINTON _ BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ At stop after stop
here Thursday, President Clinton won praise for shepherding the
Ireland-Northern Ireland peace accord. The congratulatory tone was
markedly different from the economic turmoil and political
uncertainty he addressed in Moscow in the first half of his
overseas trip. At the scene of Northern Ireland's worst terrorist
attack, Clinton consoled relatives of victims of the car bombing
last month that killed 28 people and shattered hundreds of lives in
this religiously mixed farming community. Earlier, the president
told an assemblage of lawmakers and citizens in Belfast that
Catholics and Protestants must pull together with ``courage and
reconciliation'' to build a new Northern Ireland. ``America will
continue to walk the road of renewal with you,'' he declared.
Developing. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 5 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-PEACE _ BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Despite a
well-crafted peace agreement, all is not at peace here. The
bombings by groups determined to see the agreement fail appears to
have all but shattered what little peace there was. But President
Clinton, who arrived here in the land of his ancestors on Thursday,
will attempt to tap the hope that remains in most of the people
here. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-BOX _ DUBLIN, Ireland _ A primer on Ireland-Northern
Ireland. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 5 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS _ MOSCOW _In the wake of President Bill
Clinton's departure following a two-day summit in which he urged
Russian leaders to pull together, Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and acting Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin began making
overtures Thursday to reach a compromise with Communist and
Nationlist leaders. Meanwhile, the Russian ruble -- trading
officially for the first time in a week -- fell hard and fast
Thursday, while Yeltsin and his rivals in the State Duma headed for
a second showdown vote over Chernomyrdin's nomination to become
prime minister. The official ruble rate fell to 13.5 rubles to the
dollar, but traders said it was as low as 17.4 to the dollar. The
ruble had been trading at 6.2 to the dollar last month before it
began its slide. Developing. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 3 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECONOMY (Analysis) _ WASHINGTON _ Russia, despite its
size -- both geographically and in population -- has an economy no
bigger than the Netherlands. That's only a fraction of the size of
the U.S. economy. Then why is that the current economic crisis
gripping the former Communist superpower is being credited with
sounding the alarm for the global economy? That is one of several
questions that have to be addressed on Friday when Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan and U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
meet with Japanese Finance Minister Miyazawa in San Francisco.
(Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 4 p.m. EDT in both the (i)
International and (f) Financial categories.
