Island. (MWilliams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   STORM_ Hurricane Earl moved into south Georgia on Thursday,
bringing winds and heavy rains to an area hit by two devastating
floods in the past four years. At 8 a.m., the center of Hurricane
Earl was about 30 miles south of Albany, moving to the northeast at
16 mph. Its sustained winds were still at hurricane strength, 75
mph, but were expected to diminish as it stayed over land. Albany
had 2 to 3 inches of rain between midnight and 8 a.m. Metro Atlanta
began feeling the storm early this morning, with rain and gusty
winds. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-TAX-RELIEF _ Gov. George W. Bush announces his tax relief
plan at an Austin drug store. It's the latest of several tax rebate
plans political candidates are proposing in anticipation of an
unprecedented budget windfall next year. We look at the proposal,
assess its reception at the Legislature and examine the politics
behind it. Also, checking with economists and other states.
(Herman, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-SENATE _ One is a baseball hall of famer. The other is a
basketball legend from the University of Kentucky. Together Reps.
Jim Bunning (R-Ky.) and Scotty Baesler (D-Ky.) are mixing it up in
one of the nation's closest U.S. Senate contests. Both are vying to
replace retiring Sen. Wendell Ford (D-Ky.) The second in our series
on southern senate races. (Foskett, Cox News Service).
</P>
