(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
BEASTIES-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ The Beastie Boys are surprisingly at
ground zero of today's youth culture with a No. 2 album, down from
No.1, a concert tour that looks like the biggest money-maker of the
year, and a rare mixture of old fans who've stayed true and hoards
of new ones who are jumping on the bandwagon. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
ROBESON-FILM (Los Angeles) _ Paul Robeson was as steadfast as the
Mississippi River of which he sang in ``Show Boat.'' An Academy
series showing Sept. 11 is an opportunity to admire this basso
profundo and Renaissance man who sang ``Old Man River'' and lived
according to his belief that African-Americans would fare better
under socialism. By Bob McCarthy. 
. 
POP-BEAT (Los Angeles) _ Former Stone Roses vocalist Ian Brown has
a special reason for naming his upcoming solo effort ``Unfinished
Monkey Business.'' ``My arms have always been too long for my body.
But I've been called `monkey' all my life, so I thought I'd keep
that theme.'' By Fred Shuster. 
. 
BRITS-VIDEO (LoS Angeles) _ Britain has given us some great
television and ``Absolutely Fabulous'' is no exception. The release
this week of ``Absolutely Fabulous Moments'' on BBC Video is a
chance to see why the critics were raving about this send-up
centered around two ridiculous women in their 40s who refuse to act
their age. By Rob Lowman. 
. 

