<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MONICA-DOUBLESPEAK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WINDUP, A PITCH ... &AMP; CLINTON BLEW IT! 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Eastern time zone or Canada, call BOB FARNELL
at 1-800-535-4425. Or send a fax to him at (717) 646-4850.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Central time zone, call CONNIE WHITE at
1-800-444-0267. Or fax her at (816) 822-1444.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Pacific or Mountain time zones or in Latin
America, call OLIVIA VASQUEZ at (310) 996-0075. Or fax her at (310)
996-0089.
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1998 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   When President Clinton returns to the White House after his long
vacation and business trip, I'm sure there will be quite a bundle
of mail piled up outside his door. Catalogs from Hammacher
Schlemmer, old copies of Golf Digest and Cigar Afficionado, cable
bills, stuff like that.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton wades through the pile, he'll also find a package I
FedExed to him, containing a CD of his new theme song: ``Hard for
Me to Say I'm Sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; After all that we've been through &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; I will make it up to you, I promise you &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hold me now, it's hard for me to say I'm sorry &LR;
</P>
<P>
   You might recall they used that tune in the classic movie
``Summer Lovers,'' starring Peter Gallagher as a smooth charmer who
lives with a blonde but fools around with a brunette. Hey, just
like the president!
</P>
<P>
   This guy is beyond belief. It's not just hard for him to say
he's sorry, it's impossible.
</P>
<P>
   My theory: It's all about ``Love Story.'' You know, the Erich
Segal novel that was turned into the movie in which Ali MacGraw
uttered the immortal line, ``Love means never having to say you're
sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   As you'll recall, popular lore says Segal based the story in
part on the romance of his old Yalie buddy Al Gore and bride-to-be
Tipper. Gore has no doubt taken his Love Story connection to heart
- whispering in Clinton's ear, ``Mr. President, love means never
having to say you're sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   That's my theory and I'm sticking with it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, you knew that sometime during Clinton's visit to
Russia, a reporter was going to ask him about his semi-apology to
the American people and whether he regretted the decision not to
say two words: ``I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Much to the president's chagrin, it happened Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir,'' the reporter said, ``you were just speaking of the
challenges that we face as a nation. And one is reaction since your
admission of a relationship with Ms. Lewinsky _ (Has it) given you
any cause for concern that you may not be as effective as you
should be in leading the country?
</P>
<P>
   There was the windup and the pitch. Now all Clinton had to do
was say, ``You know, I've been thinking a great deal about that,
and I've been listening to what the American people have had to
say, and I understand the concerns of those who believe I wasn't
clear enough in my speech. So let me take this opportunity to say I
am sorry. Truly, deeply sorry for lying to people and prolonging
this madness. And that's the last we're going to speak of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton launched into one of the most astonishing
examples of political doublespeak we've ever heard. You may have
caught snippets of his answer on the evening news, but I'd like to
reprint his answer in its entirety, to truly capture the
slitheringly duplicitous nature of his response.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' the president replied, ``I've actually been quite
heartened by the reaction of the American people and leaders
throughout the world about it. I have acknowledged that I made a
mistake, said that I regretted it, asked to be forgiven, spent a
lot of very valuable time with my family in the last couple of
weeks and said I was going back to work. I believe that's what the
American people want me to do, and based on my conversations with
leaders around the world, I think that's what they want me to do,
and that is what I intend to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you can see from what we're discussing here, there are very
large issues that will affect the future of the American people in
the short run and over the long run. There are large issues that
have to be dealt with now in the world and at home. And so I have
been quite encouraged by what I think the message from the American
people has been and what I know of the message from leaders around
the world has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm going to do my best to continue to go through this
personal process in an appropriate way, but to do my job, to do the
job I was hired to do. And I think it very much needs to be done
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoa, that's more than 200 words of pure, Grade-A, unadulterated
bull-oney.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the same press conference, Clinton offered another
lengthy non-apology, which started thusly: ``Well, to your second
question, I think I can almost reiterate what I said in response to
the first question. I think the question of the tone of the speech
and people's reaction to it is really a function of _ I can't
comment on that ...''
</P>
<P>
   Sigh.
</P>
<P>
   While I continue to maintain the president's personal life is
his and his alone to screw up, he does owe the American people a
straightforward apology for lying to our faces. That he continues
to dance around ``I'm sorry'' and thinks he can assuage us with
classic Clinton-speak tells us we are dealing with the most
self-absorbed president in modern history.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) can be heard on the
``Media Creatures'' show, which airs daily in Chicago from 10 a.m.
to 2 p.m. on WMVP-AM (1000) and appears Tuesday and Thursday at
