<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-BEAT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`UNFINISHED MONKEY BUSINESS' FOR SINGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Former Stone Roses vocalist Ian Brown has a
special reason for naming his upcoming solo effort ``Unfinished
Monkey Business.''
</P>
<P>
   When the British singer first began appearing with the Roses, he
explained, ``the press used to refer to me as `simian lead singer.'
My arms have always been too long for my body. But I've been called
`monkey' all my life, so I thought I'd keep that theme.''
</P>
<P>
   Work on the album began on an eight-track tape deck in Brown's
Manchester bedroom through the winter of 1996 before moving to
Chiswick Reach Studios in West London. Brown produced everything
himself and played most of the instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to sound rough and ready, but I didn't want it to
sound like it was made in an expensive studio,'' Brown said. ``I
wanted it to sound honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the album's standouts is ``Can't See Me,'' based upon a
Stone Roses bass line Brown discovered on an old demo tape. Roses
bassist Mani and original drummer Reni cut the track with Brown,
who embarked on a solo career when Stone Roses imploded two years
ago shortly after a gig at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We broke up mostly because we didn't have a manager and
everyone was on different drugs,'' Brown said. ``I don't take them,
so it was a bit weird for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown plans a local date in November. ``Unfinished Monkey
Business'' (Mercury) is due Oct. 6.
</P>
<P>
   BEST OF THE BRITS: Current releases from the Verve, Pulp and
Portishead are among nine nominees for Britain's prestigious 1998
Mercury Music Prize, presented Sept. 16 in London.
</P>
<P>
   Contenders for the sixth annual honor, which recognizes the
year's most adventurous album, include Asian Dub Foundation's
``Rafis Revenge,'' Catatonia's ``International Velvet,''
Cornershop's ``When I Was Born for the 7th Time'' and Gomez's
``Bring It On.''
</P>
<P>
   The remaining nominees are Massive Attack's ``Mezzanine,''
Portishead's ``Portishead,'' the Verve's ``Urban Hymns,'' Pulp's
``This Is Hardcore'' and the Propellerhead's ``Dex N Drums and Rock
N Roll.''
</P>
<P>
   Asian Dub Foundation, incidentally, opens for Money Mark on
Sept. 12 at the Hollywood Athletic Club.
</P>
<P>
   HAIL SEYMOUR: Mysterious Scottish folkies Belle &AMP; Sebastian on
Tuesday release their third album, ``The Boy With the Arab Strap''
(Matador), complete with a track titled ``Seymour Stein'' after the
music executive and Sire Records founder who signed Madonna and the
Ramones.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-member Belle &AMP; Sebastian's previous effort, ``If
You're Feeling Sinister'' (Enclave), was among the most acclaimed
discs of last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
