<SLUG> BC-BRITS-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN `ABSOLUTELY FABULOUS' SEND-UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rule Britannia, Britannia rule the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   OK, Britain doesn't rule much of anything these days, much less
the airwaves, but over the years it has given us some great
television, from the sublime (``Brideshead Revisited,'' ``I,
Claudius,'' ``The Singing Detective'') to the farcical (``Monty
Python,' ``Fawlty Towers'').
</P>
<P>
   The release this week of ``Absolutely Fabulous Moments'' (BBC
Video; $19.95) is a chance for those who missed the absolutely
fabulous British TV series to find out why the critics were raving.
</P>
<P>
   The show revolves around a pair of self-styled trend-setters in
their 40s _ Edina Monsoon (Jennifer Saunders) and Patsy Stone
(Joanna Lumley) _ who refuse to accept the fact that they're not
young anymore. Eddie and Patsy still party like it's the '60s and
'70s, imbibing ample amounts of booze and drugs and chasing younger
men (usually unsuccessfully). As part of their vain attempt to hold
on to their youth, Eddie (the queen of PR) squeezes into trendy
haute couture fashions at least two sizes too small, while former
Bond girl (as she claims) and current fashion editor (she slept
with the publisher and has a job for life) Patsy has had so much
cosmetic surgery on her face that it seem permanently frozen into
an I'm-hipper-than-thou look, which pretty much sums up the pair's
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Completely clueless as to how silly they look, Eddie and Patsy
are hilarious in their self-absorption. ``Absolutely Fabulous
Moments'' includes highlights and outtakes from the ``Ab Fab''
series, which are strung together within a documentary that Eddie
is doing on herself.
</P>
<P>
   In one scene, Eddie has been wrapped up like a mummy in yet
another futile attempt to lose weight, when her disapproving
college-age daughter, Saffron (Julia Sawalha), asks her to come to
the kitchen to hear some bad news. After waddling down the stairs,
Eddie encounters her mom (June Whitfield), who after much prompting
from Saffron tells Eddie that her father is dead.
</P>
<P>
   Grief or sadness is not part of her repertoire, and watching
Eddie sort of spin the dial on her face as she searches for the
appropriate reaction (while not breaking the wrap, of course) is
hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely Fabulous,'' which was written by Saunders, is a
wicked, satirical look at a generation that can't accept aging and
so falls for the latest fashion trends while refusing to grow up
emotionally. (Eddie is constantly being reproved by her daughter
for her shallowness.) But while Eddie and Patsy are being
lampooned, Saunders is also targeting the double standard we have
in which older men can cavort with young women while older women
are made comic figures. The fact that Saunders and Lumley are
wonderful physical comedians in the tradition of Lucille Ball makes
the point even more.
</P>
<P>
   Series episodes still run on cable's Comedy Central on Saturday
afternoon (check listings), but ``Absolutely Fabulous Moments'' is
a great addition to any video collection.
</P>
<P>
   THE REAL PEEL DEAL: If you were suckered into buying a ticket to
this summer's ``The Avengers,'' our condolences. The film, starring
Uma Thurman and Ralph Fiennes, was directionless and dull. Despite
spending a bundle on special effects, it lacked all the wit and
charm that even one episode of the classic '60s British series had.
So if you are a fan of the original John Steed (Patrick Macnee) and
Mrs. Peel (Diana Rigg), A&AMP;E sells 18 out of 24 episodes from the
1967 season. One tape retails for $12.95; a set of three is $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   TITANIC CURIOSITY: Yes, now that you've gotten your hands on the
video of James Cameron's ``Titanic'' starring someone named
Leonardo DiCaprio, here's a reminder that there are other videos
about the ill-fated ship. (It was a British ship; yes, there is a
premise _ admittedly thin _ to this column).
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;E has an comprehensive 1994 documentary (also called
``Titanic'') that includes rare footage, archival documents and
photos on the ship disaster. It follows the story from the creation
of the supposedly unsinkable ocean liner to its fateful collision
with an iceberg on its maiden voyage across the Atlantic in 1912.
The four-tape, 200-minute documentary retails for $39.99.
</P>
<P>
   The recently released ``Titanica'' (Miramax; $19.99) was
originally an IMAX documentary; so it really doesn't have the
big-screen look on your TV that it had in the theaters. However,
there's enough to look at as the filmmakers take you to the ocean
floor in submersibles to view the world's most famous shipwreck.
The tiny subs are outfitted with powerful lights that illuminate
the Titanic's final resting place. It's an eerie but fascinating
trip as you watch the robotic arm of the sub sift through the
wreckage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 1423EDT &QL; 
