<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR HAS A TRAIN WRECK ON HIS HANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bill Clinton had to go to Russia to get away
from Monica. San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown has to go to China to
get away from the municipal transit system.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Brown, he doesn't leave for two weeks. Who
knows what could happen? Angry voters could storm City Hall _ if
they don't mind walking to the Civic Center.
</P>
<P>
   Brown should feel at home in Shanghai. Mass transit isn't so hot
there, and the city is building a pedestrian tunnel under the
Huangpu River _ an intentional pedestrian tunnel, unlike Muni's.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Brown held a news conference to talk about his
trip to Shanghai. However, reporters were preoccupied with real
adventures _ from one end of San Francisco to the other.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about ``a matter closer to home,'' Brown snapped,
``No, I'm not taking any questions about Muni.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an odd response for a mayor who said he was elected to
speak for the voters. He won't even speak to the voters.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere at the news conference was so tense that the only
laugh came when Brown ally and trip organizer James Fang
accidentally called Brown ``Mr. Chairman.''
</P>
<P>
   For one of the few times in his life, Chairman Willie didn't
have any witty sayings. He was in a foul mood. He would have sent
reporters to re-education camps, if there were any way to get them
there.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he wouldn't talk about it, the messed-up transit system
must be running around Brown's brain because he began the news
conference by saying, ``I'm just delighted we'll be transporting
the flavor of San Francisco to Shanghai.''
</P>
<P>
   Transporting _ a curious choice of words. Try transporting San
Franciscans through San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Among other gifts, Brown will be taking a cable car to Shanghai.
Why can't he take one of those useless cars? Nobody got to ask that
question either.
</P>
<P>
   As the mayor exited the news conference, he fended off reporters
by saying, ``You guys are amazing. I don't want to talk about
Muni.''
</P>
<P>
   Later I told state Sen. Quentin Kopp about this. Kopp, who has
been mentioned as a possible opponent of Brown's in the 1999
election, said: ``You've got to talk about it if you're mayor. If
it isn't working, you've got to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody else was talking about it. While Brown was saying
nothing about Muni in front of the cameras, all the action occurred
offstage.
</P>
<P>
   After the news conference, Brown met behind closed doors with
transit officials, perhaps trying to assess the damage to the
system.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, local pollster David Binder was schmoozing in the
hallway, perhaps trying to assess the damage to the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why Binder was there, the mayor's press secretary,
Kandace Bender, said: ``All kinds of people come in and out of
here. That's the thing, you can describe all kinds of conspiracy
theories.''
</P>
<P>
   The only conspiracy theory I have is that all Muni officials are
behind the grassy knoll, taking a nap.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Binder told reporters he isn't working on Muni. However,
you can see why a pollster would be drawn to the problem. Imagine
the theoretical challenge of trying to construct a poll that gets
any positive responses on the mayor's handling of Muni.
</P>
<P>
   On the local television news Tuesday night, you saw a distinctly
uncharming Mayor Brown trying to avoid even looking at reporter
Thuy Vu, much less answering her.
</P>
<P>
   Vu was interviewing passengers on a Muni Metro car arriving at
Civic Center station, when suddenly riders spotted Brown standing
on the platform. They immediately started booing and cursing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't air much of it,'' said KTVU-TV producer Rosemarie
Thomas. But the footage they did show was frightening enough. It
showed a mayor losing his automatic control system as badly as any
Muni car, and getting in a train wreck of an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, clearly angry at being called nasty names by riders on
camera, didn't even respond to Vu at first. Then he started blaming
Muni's problems on previous mayors dating all the way back to
Dianne Feinstein, now a U.S. senator.
</P>
<P>
   When Vu asked him if he regretted promising to fix Muni within
100 days of taking office, Brown said: ``No, I don't regret any
promises I've ever made.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters are holding you to it,'' Vu said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't argue with me about it. You asked me a question,'' Brown
said. ``The voters should hold me accountable. But what I don't
want is you speaking for the voters. I'm elected to speak for the
voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that backward? Aren't mayors elected to listen to the
voters? It's unfortunate that the mayor has to listen to some
voters calling him obscene names, but he has to understand that
these are people who have been driven to the brink by Muni, rather
than downtown and back home again.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
