<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-LUNCHES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTHFUL SCHOOL LUNCHES REQUIRE SOME PARENTAL CREATIVITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Mindy Holland, a mother of two, paid the price
for trying something different with her 6-year-old son David's
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day, I tried to give him yogurt and he went around telling
everyone that we didn't own any bread in our house and we forced
this on him,'' said Holland, director of youth services at the
Jewish Community Center in Niskayuna, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of waging a daily culinary battle, Holland gave in and
returned to her son's cherished lunchtime entree: tuna fish with
mayonnaise. On a hamburger roll. Nothing else would do for David.
Not celery or pickles. Not bread.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the year of the tuna fish sandwich,'' Holland said.
``He begs for it. I'm just hoping he doesn't eat tuna fish on a
hamburger roll every day for the rest of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   And so begins the annual parental back-to-school quandary over
what to pack their kids for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough situation for parents because they want to send a
school lunch that's reasonably healthy and nutritious, but it has
to be something their child will actually eat or it just sits in
the lunch box and does nobody any good,'' said Jean Bigaouette, a
clinical nutritionist who counsels school-aged children and parents
in her private Albany practice.
</P>
<P>
   Bigaouette said offering alternatives to the standard peanut
butter and jelly sandwich might accomplish both goals.
</P>
<P>
   She has found that kids like an interactive lunch. She suggested
sending in slices of fresh vegetables that kids can dip into
hummus, a favorite salad dressing or cottage cheese. Soups or pasta
dishes in a thermos with crackers or a biscuit can replace
sandwiches as the main course. Try a piece of string cheese rolled
up in a flour tortilla. Even a slice of cold pizza will fill the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't get too weird. Kids want to fit in, Bigaouette said,
and they won't eat something strange from their lunch box, even if
it has the artistry of a chef's nouvelle cuisine creation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a child gets ridiculed for the way his lunch looks because
it's too different from what his peers are eating, he's going to
leave it in the lunch box uneaten,'' Bigaouette said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest concern is a child developing a taste for those
salty, fatty pre-made lunch packs,'' said Nan Windmueller, a
certified nutritionist with a private practice in Albany. She cited
a recent survey that reported more than 10 million children in the
United States are overweight. Among children she works with in her
practice, Windmueller said obesity is the leading health issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obesity is a disease of affluence that begins in childhood,''
Windmueller said. ``It leads to other diseases of affluence like
heart disease and diabetes. It's a matter of over-nutrition in
children, giving them more fuel than is required for the
increasingly sedentary lifestyle of kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Windmueller said she tries to shave calories while boosting
nutrition ideally without the child ever realizing the nutritional
sleight-of-hand going on behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Windmueller suggested replacing a piece of fresh
fruit such as a pear or apple for a small box of raisins (a savings
of about 50 calories). Instead of regular string cheese, substitute
light string cheese (30 calories less). Apple juice is pretty weak
in terms of nutrition, so opt instead for a pop-top fruit can with
mixed fruit in its own juice and no added sugar (70 calories less).
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can shave 100 to 200 calories at lunch while increasing
nutrition, I'm developing good eating habits,'' Windmueller said.
``I'm looking for a strategy for eating healthy, not a strategy for
food deprivation.''
</P>
<P>
   A technique that has worked for Windmueller's clients is to
invite the child to help plan a school lunch, purchase the
ingredients and physically make it. They like feeling involved and
there are no surprises for them when they open that brown bag,
Windmueller said.
</P>
<P>
   Theory and practice often diverge, though.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, a great existential divide has opened up across the
yawning maw of the unpacked lunch box. On one side, the kids. They
clamor for Oscar Mayer Lunchables, a kind of TV dinner at lunch for
kids. It's a pre-fab meal under molded plastic. For $1.99 you get
entree choices such as pepperoni pizza, beef tacos and cheese and
salsa nachos. Each Lunchable also comes with a Capri Sun fruit
drink (10 percent fruit juice) and a Butterfinger or Nestle Crunch
candy bar. Calories are included. The nachos Lunchable, for
example, contains 530 calories (210 calories from fat) and 24 grams
of total fat.
</P>
<P>
   Some students like the Lunchables for the Nickelodeon game of
chance that's included. The back of the box touts instant winners
of 1,000 toy spin-offs from the popular kids' cable TV channel and
three grand prize trips to host the Nickelodeon Nickel-O-Zone show
at the Nick studios in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make Fun of Lunch'' is the Lunchables motto.
</P>
<P>
   But Randy Fox isn't buying the concept. ``I think they're very
expensive, really high in fat and a lot of junk food,'' said the
mother of two daughters in grade school.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the pleading wears Fox down and she relents by packing a
Lunchable once or twice a month for Sharon, a fifth-grader, and
Joanna, a second-grader, in Niskayuna.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle between parent and child over what to pack for a
school lunch requires give-and-take and delicate negotiation. But
Bigaouette stressed that a parent can't just take a bye on this
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents need to remember that the lunch they send in with
their child should represent one-third of the nutrition their child
needs for the day,'' Bigaouette said. ``It's not just a throwaway
thing. It's a real meal. It has to keep the child going through the
most active part of their day.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Think of the four basic food groups as a good framework for
building an adequate school lunch, Bigaouette said.
</P>
<P>
   Parents can begin to strike a balance with what kids like and
what is healthy. Don't fight white bread, for example, and let the
child win that battle if the parent gets a concession on, say,
pretzels instead of potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to packing a school lunch for your child, however,
the best-laid plans of parents can go awry. Forewarned is
forearmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A parent might do a superb job packing a healthy, nutritious
lunch that looks great and is fun to eat,'' Bigaouette said. ``And
then your child goes and trades it with another kid for two candy
bars.''
</P>
<P>
   There's always the school cafeteria lunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 1443EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7344 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAPHICS-EARLY-BUDGET     09-03 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAPHICS-EARLY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
