<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7386 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BREAST-CANCER-HNS &LR;      09-03 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-CANCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA MOVES TOWARD APPROVAL OF NEW BREAST CANCER TREATMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Joy Fudem had gone through radiation and three
kinds of hormonal therapies, hit her limit on chemotherapy and had
a bone-marrow transplant when she learned last year that she
finally had been picked in a lottery to receive the experimental
breast cancer drug Herceptin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just screaming, I was so elated,'' said Fudem, 66, a San
Francisco resident who had been turned down twice in her attempts
to participate in clinical trials of the drug. Now, every Tuesday
she spends a half-hour at the Mount Zion-University of California
at San Francisco Cancer Center getting the antibody infused into
her bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, women with Fudem's kind of cancer won't have to rely on
chance or participate in complicated trials to get a hold of
Herceptin, the first genetically engineered breast cancer drug,
developed by Genentech of South San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a Food and Drug Administration advisory panel
recommended approving the drug for the 25 percent to 30 percent of
breast cancer patients with a genetic abnormality that contributes
to an aggressive form of the disease. The drug helped prolong the
lives of many, especially when used with chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   The advisory panel's recommendation was one of two significant
milestones Wednesday in the fight against breast cancer. Despite
warnings from scientists and advocacy groups, the FDA advisory
panel also voted to recommend tamoxifen, a hormone-related drug
already used to treat breast cancer, for use in preventing the
disease in women who are at high risk for it.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents said that data showing tamoxifen kept breast tumors at
bay were slight and conflicting, and that there were serious risks,
such as increased cases of uterine cancer and other side effects,
from the powerful drug. The FDA panel urged an aggressive education
campaign to make sure only women at the highest risk of getting the
disease were given the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tamoxifen is not a sugar pill,'' said Barbara Brenner,
executive director of San Francisco-based Breast Cancer Action.
``Our concern is about large numbers of women being pressured to
take a drug, the long-term side effects of which are not known, and
the short-term side effects that are known aren't good.''
</P>
<P>
   The FDA panel's actions, part of an accelerated timetable for
reviewing promising breast cancer treatments, signal the growing
attention being paid to the disease, which strikes 178,000 U.S.
women each year. Several other potential drugs are in development,
including therapies like Herceptin, which is designed to interfere
with the chain of events that turns cells cancerous.
</P>
<P>
   Also, raloxifene, already used to treat osteoporosis, is being
touted as a possible breast cancer prevention drug that has fewer
side effects than tamoxifen. Comparative studies of the two
possible preventives _ raloxifene and tamoxifen _ are to begin
later this year. Brenner, however, also is skeptical of raloxifene,
which she said had very little data to support its use.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, pending final approval from the FDA, Genentech said
it was prepared to ship doses of Herceptin to the market later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's hearing was packed with advocates who have worked
for years to speed up development and approval of Herceptin, the
first genetically targeted drug found effective against a major
type of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the beginning of the next phase of breast cancer research
and treatment,'' said Fran Visco, president of the National Breast
Cancer Coalition. ``It's the first targeted therapy shown to have
effectiveness, and it's something we've been looking for a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a quarter of women with breast cancer have a genetic
variation that causes their cancer cells to have extra amounts of a
protein that acts as a receiver for growth-stimulating hormones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of an on-switch for the cancer,'' said John Park, a
cancer scientist at University of California at San
Francisco-Stanford Health Care Breast Care Center. Park has been
involved with Herceptin trials since the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Herceptin binds to it and turns it off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists also believe Herceptin, which is an antibody, may
signal the immune system to begin fighting the tumor, Park said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the drug was not universally effective even for those who
had the right genetic profile. Forty-nine percent of those
receiving Herceptin plus chemotherapy responded to the treatment,
versus 32 percent who received only chemotherapy. One year after
treatment, 78 percent of the Herceptin and chemotherapy patients
were alive, compared with 67 percent of those who received
chemotherapy alone.
</P>
<P>
   Heart problems, mostly non-fatal, have been detected in 28
percent of the women who took Herceptin with a class of
chemotherapy drugs called anthracyclines. For patients who only
received Herceptin, 15 percent responded to the treatment, meaning
in most cases they were not cured but lived several months longer
than expected.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1990s, when Herceptin was first being developed,
advocacy groups played a large role. They sat in with company
officials in drawing up testing standards and helped recruit
patients to the early studies to speed up research, Visco said.
</P>
<P>
   Other activists demonstrated in front of Genentech to try to
force the company to open so-called compassionate care trials,
pioneered by AIDS activists, to make the drug available to very ill
women who would not otherwise be eligible for formal testing.
</P>
<P>
   Even after those programs were set up, so many women wanted the
drug that a lottery was established, and only a fraction of those
eligible were able to get it.
</P>
<P>
   Fudem was one of the lucky ones. Fourteen months later, her
tumors remain, but none has grown or spread. She exercises, works
as a travel agent and says she feels fine.
</P>
<P>
   Since she also received heavy doses of chemotherapy and the
bone-marrow transplant months before starting on Herceptin, it is
not certain which therapy is responsible for stopping the spread.
However, Fudem believes Herceptin has made a big difference. She is
especially grateful because she has had no side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Fudem's doctor, Debu Tripathy, has been involved with Herceptin
since it was just a concept in the late 1980s. He has been able to
treat only about 50 patients at the cancer center with the drug,
even though many more fit the profile for it.
</P>
<P>
   Tripathy said he expected to recommend it for many of the women
now under his care who had been excluded so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty frustrating not to be able to give something that
might help,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
