``Armageddon'' and ``Godzilla'' recede into distant background
mutterings, what, if anything, have this summer's movies taught us
about ourselves and our tastes in film? The most revealing lesson
of the last two months, one that is, I hope, not lost on Hollywood,
may be that popcorn doesn't have to rule the summer box office. The
season's biggest hit, ``Saving Private Ryan,'' is the kind of
prestige film that usually opens after Thanksgiving. And ``Saving
Private Ryan'' isn't an anomaly. A critic's notebook by Stephen
Holden.
</P>
<P>
   MCCALLUM-THEATER (New York) _ As paranoid as it sounds, David
McCallum is absolutely certain he is being shadowed by a Russian
agent. ``He's there every day,'' McCallum said, ``I mean, it's been
30 years, but I can't escape him. Illya Kuryakin is there 24 hours
a day.'' The role for which most fans remember McCallum is that of
Kuryakin, the brooding, mysterious Russian operative in the 1960s
joke-and-dagger spy series ``The Man From U.N.C.L.E.'' McCallum's
current assignment is playing Harold Palmer, the befuddled security
guard in Alan Ayckbourn's comedy ``Communicating Doors,'' his
second play in New York this year after an absence of nearly a
decade. By Jesse McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   UNUSUAL-MUSEUMS (Undated) _ Hugh Francis Hicks, a 76-year-old
dentist in Baltimore, has the largest collection of light bulbs in
the world, the Mount Vernon Museum of Incandescent Lighting. Why do
people collect? It is taken for granted that art is worth
collecting, but collectors collect pretty much everything, without
necessarily thinking that what they collect has esthetic or
monetary value. I spent a few days poking around unusual museums
and other places, wondering about that. I visited a museum of trash
and the basement of a teetotaler in New Jersey who owns several
thousand miniature liquor bottles and several dozen miniature
Vargas pinups from old cigarette packs. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   SAGAMORE-HILL (Undated) _ The house I would most love to go home
to is Sagamore Hill. As an ardent visitor to museum-houses that
offer glimpses of the personal daily lives of their revered
occupants, I feel that Theodore Roosevelt's beloved estate in
Oyster Bay on Long Island, more than any other, seems the perfect
home in which to have grown up. By Mimi Sheraton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FIRELIGHT-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Firelight'': William
Nicholson, director; with Sophie Marceau, Stephen Dillane, Kevin
Anderson, Joss Ackland, Lia Williams, Dominique Belcourt. Reviewed
by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   LIKE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Like It Is'': Paul Oremland,
director; with Steve Bell, Ian Rose and Roger Daltrey. Reviewed by
Anita Gates.
</P>
<P>
   MODULATIONS-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Modulations'': Iare Lee,
director. Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   AT-THE-MOVIES (Hollywood) _ News of the silver screen. By
Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-IN-BRIEF (Undated) _ Capsule reviews by New York Times
critics.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEVIDEO (Undated) _ Short items on what's news in home video
and short reviews of what's new in home video. By Peter M. Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NARWHAL-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Voyage of the Narwhal,''
by Andrea Barrett (Norton). Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   TV-STARTREK (Undated) _ The Sci-Fi Channel is running the 80
original ``Star Trek'' episodes in their original order, with new
introductions by William Shatner, one each weeknight, starting on
Tuesday, Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-COLUMN (New York) _ The Antiques Column. By Wendy
Moonan.
</P>
</TEXT>
