</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-PRIMER-0904-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A PRIMER ON IRELAND-NORTHERN IRELAND
 &HT;    With IRELAND-CLINTON-0904.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ireland at a Glance
</P>
<P>
   Two countries: The island of Ireland comprises the Republic of
Ireland, an independent country with Dublin as its capital, and
Northern Ireland, a province of the United Kingdom with Belfast as
its capital. The island was partitioned in 1921, the year before
the republic gained its independence. Northern Ireland had its own
parliament between 1921 and 1972, when the British government
assumed direct responsibility for governing Northern Ireland. The
two share a 303-mile border.
</P>
<P>
   Population and Religion: Northern Ireland has a population of
1.6 million, with a slight majority declaring their religion to be
Protestant. The Republic of Ireland has a population of 3.5
million, with a large Catholic majority and less than 10 percent of
the population describing themselves as Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   Economics: One of the biggest differences between the two
Irelands has been economics. Northern Ireland, plagued by its
history, has for years received the heaviest doses of public
subsidies of any area of the United Kingdom, amounting to $7
billion a year. It has been a different story in the republic, once
considered just a notch above Third World in the strength of its
economy. Over the decade, the republic has prospered so much that
in 1996 the per capita income there exceeded that in Britain.
Dubliners are buying land and businesses in the north. However, it
is the north that may be benefitting the most from the peace
process: Last year was the best year on record for new investment
in the north, amounting to $1 billion, generating 7,000 new jobs.
Continued economic success is considered essential to the success
of the still-fragile peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The Conflict: Since 1921, the majority of people in Northern
Ireland have voted in successive elections for candidates who have
favored continued union with the United Kingdom, a position known
as Unionism. Unionists are primarily Protestants, while Catholics
in Northern Ireland tend to support a move to become part of the
Republic of Ireland, a position known as nationalism or
republicanism. The Irish Republican Army, or IRA, has been the most
visible advocate of this position. The IRA for years conducted a
guerilla -- many say terrorist -- war to drive the British from
Ireland. Sinn Fein is the political party that represents the
republican movement, while the Ulster Unionist Party represents
those who want to remain part of the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Violence: More than 3,000 people have been killed in sectarian
violence over the last 30 years, many of them civilians killed in
terrorist attacks. The violence was particularly acute in the late
1960s and early 1970s, but has been sporadic since. The largest act
of violence was last month's bombing at the small town of Omagh,
which killed 28 and wounded more than 200.
</P>
<P>
   The Peace Plan: Outlined in the ``Good Friday Agreement,'' which
was approved by representatives of major political parties on April
10, a new Northern Ireland Assembly comprising both sides of the
struggle is undertaking the task of reaching a political settlement
of the dispute. The plan was approved by an overwhelming majority,
about 70 percent, in both the north and south. A new Northern
Ireland Assembly has been elected and will take office soon. The
assembly is intended as the forum to continue the debate over the
fate of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Challenges: Trust remains the over-arching issue. While there
has been considerable progress, key issues stand in the way, chief
among them: Decommissioning, or the disarmament of all sides in the
conflict, particularly the IRA. Even though the participants in the
peace process have disavowed the use of violence, huge stocks of
bombs and weapons remain in the hands of paramilitary organizations
on both sides. Thus far, not one bullet has been turned in. This
threatens to undermine the process because members of the new
assembly, particularly David Trimble, the Ulster unionist who
serves as the assembly's first minister, has said he would not form
a government until this disarmament begins.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
