<HEADER>
A7450 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3TAKE     09-03 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S PLAYING AT THE MOVIES  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The Times of new or
noteworthy movies and film series playing this weekend in New York
City. Ratings and running times are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``ARMAGEDDON,''  &LR;  starring Bruce Willis, Ben Affleck, Liv Tyler
and Steve Buscemi. Directed by Michael Bay (PG-13, 144 minutes).
This big, showy, spirit-crushing summer extravaganza includes not a
single heartfelt moment, unless you count its sequence set in a
strip club. Imminent doom (courtesy of an approaching asteroid)
becomes the excuse for rampant flag-waving, gung-ho patriotism and
a notion of heroism that has nothing whatever to do with real
courage. Willis gets the film's noblest lines for the same reason
that he probably got the set's biggest trailer. Affleck tries
gamely to seem mad about Ms. Tyler, who serves as window dressing
at NASA headquarters. Totally predictable elements _ loud noises,
frequent explosions and bright computer screen colors _ seem as
inevitable and deadly as the asteroid while they create the
illusion of escapist fun (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE AVENGERS,'' &LR;  starring Uma Thurman, Ralph Fiennes, Sean
Connery and Eileen Atkins. Directed by Jeremiah Chechik (PG, 100
minutes). Sometimes major movie studios  &UR; should &LR;  be afraid to
screen expensive fiascoes for the press, but they go ahead anyway.
``The Avengers'' is Warner Brothers' would-be blockbuster that
actually had its light hidden beneath a bushel until opening day,
and no wonder. With pseudo-suave repartee that would make Austin
Powers blush and with so many shades of ``Howard the Duck'' that
one scene depicts man-size pastel teddy bears sitting around a
conference table, it's a film to gall fans of the old television
series and perplex anyone else. I can't remember another Friday
morning show where I heard actual cries of ``Ugh!'' on the way out
the door (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``BLADE,''  &LR; starring Wesley Snipes, Stephen Dorff, Traci Lords
and Kris Kristofferson. Directed by Stephen Norrington (R, 120
minutes). Vampires are plotting to take over the world, and the
only person who can save the planet is a vampiric half-human
superhero named Blade. So much fake blood drips, gushes, explodes
and congeals in this hyperkinetic science-fiction horror film
adapted from a popular comic book that there's barely a scene that
isn't drenched in red. Snipes' Blade is a low-rent Arnold
Schwarzenegger imitation dressed in a ludicrous mixture of black
leather and what look like car seat belts. There's lot of morphing
and Hong Kong action movie-style acrobatics. Dorff is the bratty
leader of the young vampire rebels. The visuals are garish, the
acting wretched (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``DANCE WITH ME,''  &LR; starring Vanessa Williams, Chayanne and
Kris Kristofferson (PG, 126 minutes). A likable mess of a movie,
``Dance With Me'' wants to be the ``Saturday Night Fever'' of salsa
dancing, and in the smoldering-eyed young Puerto Rican star
Chayanne it has found a charismatic Latino answer to John Travolta.
But the story of an ambitious young Cuban who works in a Houston
dance studio run by a man who may or may not be his biological
father ( Kristofferson) meanders so much that the movie never
gathers dramatic momentum, and the dance sequences are hopelessly
choppy and poorly framed. Even a percolating Latin American score
and a winning performance by Ms. Williams as the object of
Chayanne's affection can't hold the pieces together (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``EVER AFTER: A CINDERELLA STORY,''  &LR; starring Drew Barrymore,
Anjelica Huston and Dougray Scott. Directed by Andy Tennant (PG-13,
120 minutes). The clever notion of reinventing Cinderella as a
self-motivated powerhouse who doesn't need a fairy godmother to get
ahead has been reduced into a bland mishmash of comedy and soap
opera. Drew Barrymore is appealing as Danielle, a plucky,
resourceful, slightly tomboyish 16th-century French girl who knows
how to stand up for herself. But her wimpish prince ( Scott) isn't
much of a prize to crow over. And why is Leonardo da Vinci (Patrick
Godfrey) traipsing around France with the ``Mona Lisa'' under his
arm, giving advice to the lovelorn? The most orthodox refugee from
the standard fairy tale is Ms. Huston's haughty stepmother
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``EVEREST,''  &LR; directed by David Brashears with Greg
MacGillivray (not rated; 45 minutes). If life in New York City
doesn't provide enough in the way of thrills, those in search of a
vicarious near-death experience can make their way to the Sony Imax
Theater at Lincoln Square (1998 Broadway, at 68th Street) for a go
at ``Everest.'' There, images of the world's highest mountain _
29,028 feet _ find a frame worthy of the peak's spectacular, lethal
beauty: the eight-story-high, 100-foot-wide screen. This account
focuses mainly on the efforts of three people to scale the peak in
1996 despite yawning chasms of ever-shifting ice, thundering
avalanches, the perils of air so thin that it addles the brain, and
sudden, blinding storms. While this expedition was on the mountain,
as many articles and books were later to relate, other teams made
their way into the so-called death zone, at 25,000 feet, where a
violent storm overtook them. Eight people perished in the worst
single disaster on the mountain. ``Everest'' makes it possible for
armchair adventurers to share the risks and glory of the team's
climb toward heaven (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``54,''  &LR; starring Ryan Phillippe, Salma Hayek, Neve Campbell,
Mike Myers, Lauren Hutton and Michael York. Directed by Mark
Christopher (R, 89 minutes). Mark Christopher's botched-up history
of Studio 54, the notorious late-'70s disco and celebrity hangout,
should have been a depraved Manhattan answer to ``Saturday Night
Fever.'' Instead, it is a juiceless mishmash that can't decide if
it's a nightclub history, a comedy ( Myers' crude ``Saturday Night
Live''-style caricature of Steve Rubell) or a contemporary
variation on the fable of the prodigal son. Phillippe, playing a
19-year-old Jersey City nobody who ascends from busboy to star
bartender at the club, does throw off an occasional spark. But the
movie is so afraid to confront the character's self-promoting
bisexuality that he never really comes alive (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``GONE WITH THE WIND,''  &LR; starring Vivien Leigh, Clark Gable,
Olivia de Havilland, Leslie Howard and Hattie McDaniel. Directed by
Victor Fleming (G, 220 minutes). There's still a lot of robust life
left in this 1939 David O. Selznick adaptation of Margaret
Mitchell's romantic novel of the Old South (possibly as it never
existed) just before, during and after the Civil War. Not a great
film but a satisfying one. The performances by Vivien Leigh, Clark
Gable and Hattie McDaniel are ravishing, and there's grandeur in
the meticulous physical production. The movie shows its age most
unfortunately in the uneven quality of the Technicolor prints,
which, though new, go sort of pinkish more often than they should
(Vincent Canby).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``HENRY FOOL,''  &LR;  starring Thomas Jay Ryan, James Urbaniak and
Parker Posey. Directed by Hal Hartley (R, 138 minutes). The
affectless precision of this filmmaker's previous work is
absolutely no preparation for the brilliance and deep resonance of
this contemporary parable. Without forsaking the clean, spare look
and hyperreal clarity that are his trademarks, Hartley moves into a
much larger realm with a meditation on, among other things, art,
trust, loyalty, politics and popular culture. When Henry Fool (
Ryan) bursts mysteriously into the thankless life of Simon Grim (
Urbaniak) and urges this silent garbage man to start writing, the
results are strange and sublime. Ms. Posey plays Simon's slatternly
sister with nonchalant wit in one of her best roles. A few
glaringly scatological touches don't detract from the film's
elegance of vision (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``HOW STELLA GOT HER GROOVE BACK,''  &LR; starring Angela Bassett,
Taye Diggs and Whoopi Goldberg. Directed by Kevin Rodney Sullivan.
(R, 99 minutes). This silly soft-core fantasy in which 40-year-old
Stella (Ms. Bassett) meets and falls in love with 20-year-old
Winston ( Diggs) while on vacation in Jamaica is part Caribbean
travel brochure (fly to Jamaica and meet the hunk of your dreams)
and part diluted Chippendales-in-the-Caribbean strip show floated
on a bathtub full of suds with some light comedy thrown in. Ms.
Bassett brings real fire to the role of a beautiful
divorced-with-one-son San Francisco stockbroker whose resistance to
romance is broken down in the tropics. But Diggs' nearly perfect
boyfriend is a vapid romance-novel fabrication. Ms. Goldberg
shamelessly stirs up the suds as Stella's raunchy best friend, who
is secretly dying of liver cancer (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE MASK OF ZORRO,''  &LR; starring Antonio Banderas, Anthony
Hopkins and Catherine Zeta-Jones. Directed by Martin Campbell
(PG-13, 130 minutes). Travel back to the days when swashbuckling
was serious business, when boyish adventure films still had their
innocence and when the bravado of thrilling stunt work was all a
movie needed in the way of special effects. Hopkins is marvelously
game as the film's dashing senior Zorro. Banderas was born to play
the aging hero's jokey, hotblooded protege. And he meets his match
in the story's heroine, whose beauty is inevitably described as
``beyond compare.'' This robust old-fashioned adventure should
appeal to older children, but beware of a few needlessly grisly
touches (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``NIGHTS OF CABIRIA,''  &LR; starring Giulietta Masina. Directed by
Federico Fellini (not rated, 117 minutes). Anyone dismayed by the
hyperkinetic emptiness of summertime film spectacles will find the
antidote in this 1957 Fellini masterpiece. It has been refurbished
and revived by the same team that brought back ``Contempt'' last
year, and they display the same acumen in reissuing a film of
special prescience; though it was shot in black and white amid the
poverty of postwar Italy, neither the style nor the searching of
``Cabiria'' has grown dated at all. In a prize-winning and
heartbreaking performance, the star plays a scrappy Roman
streetwalker who drifts almost magically among the film's
astonishingly varied realms. There is more grace and courage in the
famous image of Masina smiling through her tears than in all the
fire-breathing blockbusters Hollywood has to offer (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE OPPOSITE OF SEX,''  &LR; starring Christina Ricci, Martin
Donovan, Lisa Kudrow and Lyle Lovett. Directed by Don Roos (R, 100
minutes). Wicked, foulmouthed and very funny, this gleefully
acerbic comedy finds that Ms. Ricci has morphed enchantingly from
nasty little Wednesday of ``The Addams Family'' into Lolita's evil
twin. Voluptuous and scheming, her poisonous Dedee narrates this
film and announces immediately that she won't be developing a heart
of gold. Which is, of course, mostly a lie. The film brutally
skewers preconceptions about gay and straight life, then lets its
characters intermingle in sweetly unexpected ways. Donovan and Ms.
Kudrow, as unlikely comrades brought together by Dedee's treachery,
deliver the zingers from Roos' screenplay with deadpan panache
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``OUT OF SIGHT,''  &LR; starring George Clooney and Jennifer Lopez.
Directed by Steven Soderbergh (R, 120 minutes). As directed with
terrific panache by Soderbergh in his most frankly commercial
effort, Clooney and Ms. Lopez take an intricate Elmore Leonard
crime tale and give it steam heat. Like ``Get Shorty,'' this story
has been adapted from a Leonard novel by Scott Frank, who knows
exactly how to capture the writer's shrewd, hard-boiled style on
screen. An outstanding supporting cast _ including Don Cheadle,
Dennis Farina and Albert Brooks _ provides the movie with a vivid
rogues' gallery and remains good fun even when the story is
occasionally confusing. To fill in the blanks, go back to Leonard's
version; there are certainly worse ways to spend an afternoon
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE SPANISH PRISONER,''  &LR; starring Campbell Scott, Rebecca
Pidgeon, Ben Gazzara and Steve Martin. Written and directed by
David Mamet (PG, 112 minutes). The most engaging of Mamet's
cinematic puzzles begins with an X-ray at an airport security
check. And the audience will wish it had a similar device for
reading the characters' sneaky minds. No such luck: the mystery
here, in a handsome and Hitchcockian film named for an elaborate
con game, stays tricky to the very end. Scott plays the inventor of
a lucrative, stealable scientific process, with Gazzara as the boss
who's in no hurry to compensate him for it. In an ensemble cast
working entirely on the calculating Mamet wavelength, Martin plays
a rich, debonair mystery man who tells the inventor all about his
pretty young sister. In her performance as a pert, unaccountably
off-kilter secretary, Ms. Pidgeon perfectly embodies the film's
sleight of hand (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE PARENT TRAP,''  &LR; starring Lindsay Lohan, Natasha
Richardson and Dennis Quaid. Directed by Nancy Meyers and written
by David Swift, Ms. Meyers and Charles Shyer (PG, 128 minutes). A
super-cute remake of the old Hayley Mills hit, this time given a
privileged shelter-magazine gloss by the ``Father of the Bride''
team of Ms. Meyers and Shyer. Ms. Richardson and Quaid beam
appealingly as parents who somehow managed to separate their twins
at birth without a twinge of guilt and who seem to have spent all
of the intervening 11{ years shopping. In her dual role as English
and American sisters (one lives in a grand London town house, the
other on a big Napa Valley vineyard; nobody lives in a coal mine),
the spirited Ms. Lohan commandeers the movie as if she had been
taking shrinking-violet lessons from Sharon Stone (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``A PERFECT MURDER,''  &LR; starring Michael Douglas, Gwyneth
Paltrow and Viggo Mortensen. Directed by Andrew Davis (R, 107
minutes). The characters may be cardboard-thin in this film, a
skillfully plotted update of Frederick Knott's play (and Alfred
Hitchcock's film) ``Dial M for Murder,'' but the nasty
cat-and-mouse games they play are icily amusing. Douglas, looking
more than ever like a wattled, riled-up rooster, is Steven Taylor,
a shady Wall Street bond trader in deep financial trouble who hires
his rich wife's handsome lover ( Mortensen), a con man posing as a
painter, to murder her. It's not as easy as he hopes. Ms. Paltrow,
looking chic and twinkly, is the wife, Emily, a translator at the
United Nations, who has her own agenda. The story takes enough
surprising twists to keep you engrossed, and the high-style
ambiance (especially the Taylors' Fifth Avenue apartment) is
mouthwatering (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``SNAKE EYES,''  &LR; starring Nicolas Cage and Gary Sinise.
Directed by Brian De Palma (R, 99 minutes). An assassination, a
fixed heavyweight boxing bout and a perfectly timed hurricane named
Jezebel collide apocalyptically one night in Atlantic City, where
hellfire rains over a hotel and casino appropriately called the
Millennium. Here is where Rick Santoro ( Cage), the sleazy police
detective in charge of security, discovers that his best friend (
Sinise) could also be his nemesis and he has to make hard moral
choices. This entertaining pop fable, which recalls the director's
``Blow Out,'' isn't believable for a second, but it has a pulpy
energy that keeps on chugging (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THERE'S SOMETHING ABOUT MARY,''  &LR; starring Cameron Diaz, Ben
Stiller and Matt Dillon. Directed by Peter and Bobby Farrelly (R,
119 minutes). Sometimes Western civilization declines in
deliriously funny style. Hence this proudly obnoxious comedy is a
hoot in every sense, deserving a smidgen of disapproval and a whole
lot of helpless laughter. Set in motion by a prom, a crush and a
cruel, cruel zipper, this paean to low humor works ridiculously
well because it never stoops to being mean-spirited or (despite all
appearances) authentically inane. The principal cast is bright and
appealing, with Ms. Diaz at her most beautiful and blithe. Do note
that this film strives hard for something to offend everyone, and
that a tolerance for the Farrellys' zit jokes is unfortunately
required (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE TRUMAN SHOW,''  &LR; starring Jim Carrey, Laura Linney and Ed
Harris. Directed by Peter Weir and written by Andrew Niccol (PG,
104 minutes). The ultimate in high-concept ingenuity. Hosannas and
cartwheels for this ingenious media-age fantasy are over the top,
but by comparison with Hollywood's usual notion of summer movie
fare, it's definitely a dazzler. Carrey, refreshingly free of
shtick, gives an instantly iconic performance as a guinea pig for
an entertainment-happy nation, a man whose whole life is a fraud
contrived by Harris' so-called ``televisionary.'' Carrey's innate
edge of volatility gives the material, from a screenplay of
transfixing sci-fi intensity, its trace of danger. Ms. Linney, as
the actress playing a wife whose bluff could be called at any
moment, is the story's spookiest character as well as its perkiest.
Weir unifies the story's many nuances with great finesse (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``WHY DO FOOLS FALL IN LOVE,''  &LR;  starring Larenz Tate, Halle
Berry, Vivica A. Fox and Lela Rochon. Directed by Gregory Nava (R,
112 minutes). In this raucous comic ``Rashomon'' of rock-and-roll,
the brief, meteoric career and busy, turbulent marital life of the
singer Frankie Lymon ( Tate) furnish the pretext for a trip through
time to the 1950s and '60s, when much of a generation fell under
the spell of a new kind of music. At its best, this uneven but
often entertaining movie, written by Tina Andrews, manages to
recapture some of the excitement and turmoil of those days, revel
in high spirits and low-down humor and provide a happy sampler of
hits. At its most mediocre, it is built around a farcical battle
for Lymon's estate among three women (Ms. Berry, Ms. Fox and Ms.
Rochon), each claiming to be his wife and the heir to his
royalties. Lymon's career may have been short and sad, but ``Why Do
Fools Fall in Love'' finds the melodrama of his life in the
exciting music of his time and the tumult of his romances (Van
Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``WRONGFULLY ACCUSED,''  &LR; starring Leslie Nielsen, Richard
Crenna, Kelly Le Brock and Sandra Bernhard. Directed by Pat Proft
(PG-13, 85 minutes). No one can accuse this film of a shortage of
jokes. Nielsen and his co-stars keep them coming. Unfortunately
most of them just aren't very funny, and ``Wrongfully Accused,''
which is essentially a parody of ``The Fugitive,'' feels like a
tangle of funny ideas all dressed up with nowhere to go (Anita
Gates).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 1557EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
