<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Titanic,'' which was released on Tuesday, swamps all else on
video this week. As for video guides, September is once again awash
with updated and new editions.
</P>
<P>
   By far the biggest is ``Video Hound's Golden Movie Retriever''
for 1999 (Visible Ink Press, $21.95), a dreadnought of the genre
with 22,000 reviews (1,000 of them new), 200 pages of listings by
film categories and a dozen appendixes indexing the work of 40,000
actors, directors, screenwriters and composers. Digital video disk
titles are included, as is a roster of Web sites for the movie
hunter.
</P>
<P>
   This year, too, in response to the American Film Institute's
list of 100 best American films, the editors have chosen their own
best, which number 290. Make room for ``Caddyshack,'' ``Living in
Oblivion'' and ``Raising Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Narrowing the perspective considerably, the new visual arts
video catalog from Facets Multimedia, a mail-order distributor in
Chicago, includes about every video available having to do with
artists and how they work.
</P>
<P>
   This guide lists only feature films _ for example, ``Surviving
Picasso,'' ``Moulin Rouge'' and ``La Belle Noiseuse'' _ that are
about painters and sculptors and their lot in the world. Of the
several hundred titles, some are narrated films of museum and
gallery exhibitions; some are documentaries about artists (``Chuck
Close,'' ``Drawing the Line: A Portrait of Keith Haring,'' the
Maysles brothers' ``Christo in Paris''), and still others explore
movements and styles (``Cubism and Non-Objective Art'').
</P>
<P>
   ``They give you something to settle in with after you get home
from the exhibit,'' said Milos Stehlik, Facets' director.
(Information: (800) 331-6197).
</P>
<P>
   Videocassettes of films customarily precede digital video disks,
but in November HBO is scheduled to reverse the order of things and
release ``From the Earth to the Moon,'' its 12-episode miniseries
about the manned Apollo missions of the '60s and '70s, on DVD
months before the production's general release on videotape. That
won't come until next summer, the 30th anniversary of Neil
Armstrong's first steps on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Right now cassettes of the series, which was nominated for 17
Emmy Awards, which are to be presented Sept. 13, are available only
from Columbia House, which sells to members. (Information: (800)
638-2922).
</P>
<P>
   Columbia House is partly owned by Time Warner, which owns HBO
and Warner Brothers studio. Warner Home Video is a leading
proponent of the DVD format. Some distributors see HBO's scheduling
as an effort to promote DVD with a high-profile title that, unlike
a hot new movie, isn't in such high demand that it needs immediate
general release on videotape. Next month, in fact, ``From Earth to
the Moon'' will be rebroadcast on HBO's Signature channel.
</P>
<P>
   So, come November, DVD gets the first call. The 12 episodes will
occupy three of four disks. The fourth will carry extra features
like tours of the solar system, capsule models, mission objectives,
trivia quizzes and links to related Web sites. The price will be
$119.95.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW RELEASES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Primary Colors
</P>
<P>
   Down South there is a governor named Jack Stanton (John
Travolta, left) who is at once so conniving and charming that no
one really knows what is going on with him from one minute to the
next. Jack's mercurial ways, dressed up in good-ol'-boy style and
laced with a little down-home deceit, either help or hurt depending
on the message he's getting across or the indiscretion he's
covering up. Left to pick up after Jack is his smart, stoical wife
(Emma Thompson). Mike Nichols' film, adapted from a novel by Joe
Klein and written by Elaine May, has trouble shifting from
affectionate satire to serious political assessment, becoming a
story, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, ``struggling with
its own identity crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   1998. Universal. $107.37. 143 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Four Little Girls
</P>
<P>
   In Spike Lee's documentary, gentle friends and relatives offer
thoughts about what life might have been for four little girls
killed in the terrorist bombing of the 16th Street Baptist Church
in Birmingham, Ala., on Sept. 15, 1963. ``This was the awakening,''
Walter Cronkite says of the crime that disgusted white America and
galvanized the civil rights movement. Interviews with the girls'
families and older residents reconstruct a powerful sense of what
Birmingham was and how the bombing would change its future. But the
film is most remarkable ``in making the little girls unforgettable
and eliciting the long-buried emotions of those who loved them''
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1997. HBO. $98. 102 minutes. Closed captioned. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   I Love You ... Don't Touch Me
</P>
<P>
   Neurois-driven urban romance wobbles along in the extremely
tentative hands of Katie (Marla Schaffel), who becomes indignant
when Ben (Mitchell Whitfield), a friend with whom she's merely but
closely platonic, begins a torrid affair with another woman. That
steers her in the direction of Wrong, whom she meets in an auto
accident and is the type who compares a woman to wine tasting. With
its 25-year-old heroine who is finicky about men to the point of
being a virgin, Julie Davis' film is ``bright, energetic and
obviously eager to please'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1997. Orion. $100.96. 85 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release
date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Wild Things
</P>
<P>
   In Lucky Blue Bay, Fla., the high school sweethearts (Neve
Campbell and Denise Richards) come leggy and, along with their
mothers, panting after the school's sailing instructor and town
Lothario (Matt Dillon). When the vixenish Kelly (Ms. Richards)
cries rape after some time alone with Sam ( Dillon), appearances
head in one direction and the truth in another in John McNaughton's
``slick, steamy tale of nonstop treachery'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77. 108 minutes. Closed captioned.
R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With summer activities still in full swing, video rentals are
usually slow at this time of year. A marked improvement should be
reflected in weeks to come with the release of ``Titanic'' on
Tuesday. Meanwhile, here are some current best renters.
</P>
<P>
   THE WEDDING SINGER. Wearing a veneer of civility with his formal
wear, Robie (Adam Sandler) croons at other people's weddings while
still nursing the wounds of his own abandonment at the altar. 1998.
New Line. $107.37. 96 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. MARSHALS. Overcoming cartoon-balloon dialogue, Tommy Lee
Jones bristles as a lawman pursuing a refugee from a plane crash
(Wesley Snipes). 1998. Warner. $107.37. 105 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   JACKIE BROWN. With his hipness in high gear, Quentin Tarantino
adapts Elmore Leonard's ``Rum Punch,'' with Pam Grier as an airline
attendant in trouble with the law and the gun runner Ordell Robbie
(Samuel L. Jackson). 1997. Miramax . 154 minutes. Closed captioned.
R.
</P>
<P>
   THE BORROWERS. Around the Lenders house, the disappearance of
small items signals another foray by the Borrowers, a family of
tiny people who live under the floorboards. 1997. Polygram .
$22.95. 83 minutes. Closed captioned. PG.
</P>
<P>
   THE APOSTLE. Robert Duval brilliantly sidesteps all the
stereotypes in his portrayal of the evangelist preacher Euliss
(Sonny) Doolittle. 1997. Universal . $107.37. 148 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   THE BIG LEBOWSKI. Basting in his bubble bath, Jeff Lebowski
(Jeff Bridges) encounters intruders who mistake him for another
Lebowski who has a missing wife named Bunny. 1998. Polygram.
$108.01. 127 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
