<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7465 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTARO-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      09-03 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTARO-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S A 1ST TIME FOR EVERYTHING, UNFORTUNATELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURI NOTARO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - I saw him as I looked through my front window,
watching the stream of kids filter through the streets to the
nearby school on the first day of the new year. While other kids
walked in groups, swinging backpacks and laughing, he shuffled his
feet, looking at the ground as he walked. I knew how he felt.
</P>
<P>
   I've never been a good starter, either.
</P>
<P>
   I remembered the first day of first grade. I behaved myself
until tragedy announced itself at lunchtime when I noticed that my
Partridge Family lunch box was gone. I was frantic, I had nothing
to eat, I would be hungry. Hungry. HUNGRY. I thought, the teacher
can help me, maybe I can share a lunch with someone, so I tapped on
her arm, managed to utter the words ``I forgot . . .'' and then
vomited all over her shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing I knew I was lying down in the back seat of our
station wagon after the principal called my mom to come pick me up.
</P>
<P>
   By third grade, we had moved to Arizona and I had the chance to
start over again in a new school. We were walking single file to
recess and I was just about to make a new friend when a metal
telephone pole struck me in the head, knocking me to the ground.
The whole class saw my Wednesday underwear with the tear at the
waistband when my dress flew up. This time, my mom got there pretty
fast. After she dropped me off for school that morning, she just
sat in the car and waited in the parking lot. That year, the kids
were old enough to group together and identify me as a scapegoat,
known as the ``Dirty Panty Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   When I transferred to junior high, I already had a major crush
on a Mike Smithfield from my sixth-grade class and had waited all
summer to see him. I spotted him at the trash can in the cafeteria
and rushed over to say hi. He nodded, smiled slightly, and I
gawked.
</P>
<P>
   A tense, long moment passed before he said suddenly, ``Um, want
this Snoball?'' and pointed to the pink, coconut-flecked mound that
teetered on the edge of the tray.
</P>
<P>
   I nodded back, taking it. Knowing that this Snoball gift was a
sure sign of tender affection, I sucked up all of my courage in one
deep breath and said, ``Wanna go with me to the dance on Friday?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said simply, but I didn't believe him. I followed him
all the way to his P.E. class at the gym, asking, ``Why? Why won't
you go with me? Why?'' until we hit the baseball field and he just
started running. He ran the entire length of the field, constantly
looking cover his shoulder to see if I was still chasing him. I
stood there for a long time, understanding that Snoballs didn't
always mean love, until Patti Herman, the first girl who smoked at
our school, walked by me and said, ``Hey! Do you think your pants
are tight enough?'' It was she who invented my junior high name,
``Whorie Laurie.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing prepared me for the horror of the first day of eighth
grade. While in choir class, I let a tough girl whom I wanted to be
friends with look in my clutch purse for gum. Instead of finding
Bubble Yum, she emerged clutching my toothbrush (a much-needed tool
since I had just gotten braces) with a massive maxi pad stuck to it
and proceeded to run around the classroom, holding it like a flag
above her head, shouting, ``Guess who has her period! Guess who has
her period!'' I dropped the class the first time she shouted,
``Hey! Kotex Kid! Can I borrow some Midol?''
</P>
<P>
   Things weren't much better in high school. As a new sophomore, I
was adoringly watching Jim Kroeger, a senior, play basketball in
the gym when he called my name for the first time. I turned around
and flashed my biggest, brightest, metal-clad, buck-toothed smile
just in time for him to bounce the basketball right off my head. I
got up, still smiling, and smiled all the way to the nurse, who
looked at the round, patterned welt on my forehead and asked me if
I had walked into a telephone pole. My nickname that year was,
naturally, ``Backboard.''
</P>
<P>
   It's OK, though. In my senior year, Jim Kroeger got Patti Herman
pregnant, married her and then had to get a job cooking hot dogs at
Orange Julius in the foot court at the mall.
</P>
<P>
   And a couple of years ago, I saw Mike Smithfield at Safeway as
he bagged my groceries. ``I want those in a separate bag,'' I said,
interrupting him as he talked about our school days. ``Those need
to be protected. You just can't toss around Snoballs like they were
nothing, you know. They're tender.''
</P>
<P>
   As I watched the little kid shuffle past my house far behind the
pack of other kids on the first day of school, I wondered what was
going to happen to him that day. I decided to give him some
assurance, based on my experience, that everything would eventually
be OK, and went out to the front yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' I said as he neared the edge of my yard, ``all the
kids that pick on you in school will try to sell you insurance when
you grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   He just looked at me. ``Are you trying to abduct me?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I stuttered. ``You just looked so sad, I was trying to .
. .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mind your own business, lady,'' he shot back. ``Don't you have
enough problems of your own?''
</P>
<P>
   He started to walk off, took a few steps and then stopped and
turned around.
</P>
<P>
   ``FREAK!'' he yelled as loud as he could.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I should've started off by offering him a Snoball. &QL; 
Laurie Notaro is a freelance writer. Write to her in care of the
``Rep,'' P.O. Box 2245 NF-19, Phoenix, AZ 85002. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
