NYT-09-03-98 1602EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7473 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     09-03 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; The Allure Of Grandparents &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Michael Douglas says he doesn't quite understand all
those newspaper and magazine stories about the spate of summer
movies in which an older man romances a younger woman. What's so
unusual? he asked. ``It must have been a slow Monica week,'' he
said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas was speaking over his car phone the other afternoon as
he drove from Los Angeles to Santa Barbara. Yes, the 53-year-old
star was married to 25-year-old Gwyneth Paltrow in ``A Perfect
Murder.'' Just as Jack Nicholson, 61, teamed up with Helen Hunt,
35, in ``As Good as It Gets.'' And Warren Beatty, 61, became
entranced with 31-year-old Halle Berry in ``Bulworth.'' And there
was Robert Redford, 61, and Kristin Scott Thomas, 38, in ``The
Horse Whisperer.'' And the list goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Douglas, while ostensibly shrugging off Hollywood's
older-man, younger-woman syndrome, has quietly decided to play a
role that seems not only appropriate but a little gutsy, too,
especially for an actor who has specialized in 40-something macho
parts. Douglas is playing a grandfather _ yes, a grandfather _ in a
forthcoming project called ``Still Life.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, to be made next year by Universal Pictures, is to star
Douglas and Meryl Streep as an unhappily married couple who end a
30-year-marriage just before their daughter and son-in-law die in a
plane crash. Seeking to bring up their young grandchildren and deal
with the tragedy, the couple reunite, tentatively at first, and
rekindle their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a script that moved me,'' said Douglas, referring to
the screenplay by Andrea King, a former journalist for The
Hollywood Reporter. Douglas, who is also producing the film, said
he was not especially aware that the role was a risky one. ``I'm
not conscious of that,'' he said. ``I go with my heart and do
things I like to do. I've never been one to carefully calculate my
career decisions, to sit on the outside looking in. I go with my
passion and what moves me.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with Ms. Streep was another incentive to play a
grandparent. ``I've been looking forward to working with Meryl for
a long time,'' he said. ``And if it doesn't bother Meryl to play a
grandparent, it doesn't bother me.'' ( Douglas is hardly tottering
in the film: he plays a charmer who has a brief affair with a
beautiful young woman.) The film is to be directed by Mimi Leder
(``Deep Impact'').
</P>
<P>
   Ms. King said she had the idea for the screenplay while she was
driving one day and saw an older couple crossing the street with
their two grandchildren between them. ``I thought, `Wouldn't it be
interesting to write a movie about that: grandparents having to be
parents again,''' she said. After handing the script to her agent,
she jotted down a list of actors and actresses who would be ideal
for the top roles. She circled the top two names: Douglas and Ms.
Streep. But Ms. King was concerned that stars would shun the roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hoped the parts were good enough and the story compelling
enough, that it would override their initial fears about playing
the parts,'' Ms. King said. Of Douglas and Ms. Streep taking their
roles, she added: ``That's a very personal transition that actors
have to make. And it takes a very strong belief in oneself and
one's talent to know that they can play parts like these and still
be sexy movie stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the film, Douglas and Ms. Streep are hardly going to
focus on older roles. Douglas, with a laugh, offered no apologies
for his role as a scheming businessman with a very young wife in
``A Perfect Murder.'' ``She was supposed to be a trophy bride,'' he
said. ``And I thought Gwyneth and I looked pretty good, didn't
we?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Alphabet City Success &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Tamara Jenkins, the writer-director of the comedy-drama ``Slums
of Beverly Hills,'' is not celebrating her success by buying a home
in Bel Air. Far from it. She just moved from a tenement on Avenue B
in the East Village to a larger two-bedroom apartment on Avenue A.
``The trouble is it's the loudest apartment in Manhattan: it's like
a boardwalk,'' Ms. Jenkins said. ``I call people and they say,
`What pay phone are you calling from?' It's my apartment! I can't
wait for the winter to shut my windows.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she's funny and irreverent, her quasi-autobiographical
film about a teen-age girl living with her brothers and father in a
series of cheap apartments in Beverly Hills in the 1970s is, in
many ways, quite touching and sweet-natured. The film, made by Fox
Searchlight Pictures, stars Natasha Lyonne as the adolescent and
Alan Arkin as her father. In real-life Ms. Jenkins and her three
brothers _ there are only two in the film _ were brought up mostly
by their father, Manny Jenkins, who was a car salesman with a
gambling problem.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Ms. Jenkins said, the unfancy parts of Beverly
Hills were filled with what she called ``the nomads of divorce
living on the fringes, hoping for the good life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were like the Jewish Joads,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jenkins, who is 35, wrote her film, which cost less than $5
million, with the help of a Guggenheim Fellowship and the Sundance
Institute Screenwriting and Filmmakers lab. (Robert Redford, who
founded Sundance, is the film's executive producer.) Ms. Jenkins
had won prizes for a short film at the 1994 Sundance Film Festival
and at the New York University Graduate Film School.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The success of her film _ it has opened strongly in New York and
Los Angeles to generally good reviews and expanded around the
nation last week _ has not quite gone to Ms. Jenkins' head. As a
result of the movie, she has an agent at International Creative
Management. Scripts are arriving by messenger at her Avenue A
apartment, although most of them are not very good, she said. So
Ms. Jenkins is planning to start writing another movie.
</P>
<P>
   She has no plans to move back to Los Angeles. ``As soon as I
finished the film I got the first flight back to New York,'' Ms.
Jenkins said. ``My relationship to L.A. is very complicated. It's
filled with the ghosts of childhood. And the world of Hollywood _
which I didn't know as a kid _ is very confusing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jenkins, who spoke over the phone from New York, said a
fallout of the film is that producers want to meet her. The
writer-director said she was heading out the door to meet one of
them in a midtown restaurant. ``You get the word, `He looks like
this, and he'll be wearing this and that,''' she said. ``It's like
a strange blind date.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sophie's Choices &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Sophie Marceau is not especially well known in the United
States, but her career here seems poised on a rapid take-off. Mel
Gibson's ``Braveheart'' introduced the French star to English
language audiences, and this was followed by the Bernard Rose film
adaptation of ``Anna Karenina.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know why you get roles or don't get roles,'' she
said. ``It's very mysterious.''
</P>
<P>
   Her newest released film, ``Firelight,'' a romantic drama set in
the 1800s, directed and written by William Nicholson, opens on
Friday. In the film, Ms. Marceau plays a beautiful and enigmatic
governess who bears the child of an English landowner. But this is
only one of several Marceau films that will be seen over the next
year. She recently completed a slapstick comedy, ``Lost and
Found,'' with David Spade, as well as a turn-of-the-century
``Midsummer's Night Dream,'' with, among others, Kevin Kline,
Michelle Pfeiffer and Rupert Everett. ``I was so proud:
Shakespeare! In English,'' she said with a laugh of the Michael
Hoffman film to be released in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marceau has been a French star since she was a teen-ager,
but it was only recently that the American market opened up to an
actress who has exquisite looks, speaks English perfectly and _
unlike many American stars _ doesn't seem to take herself very
seriously. Most of the time she lives in Warsaw with her husband,
Andrzej Zulawski, a writer-director, and their 3-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband got sick of France and decided to go home so I have
one foot in Paris, one foot in Warsaw,'' she said. ``Most of the
time I don't know where I am.'' She's also considering a move to
Los Angeles. ``I cannot imagine staying in Poland forever, America
forever or France forever,'' she said. ``Nothing is forever.
Jumping is what I like.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, she's entranced with Americans. ``I like
Americans,'' she said. ``I like their politeness. They're very
social, very friendly. I don't know if this is superficial or not
but it makes every day life so much easier. I just wish they had
seasons in Los Angeles. I miss seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marceau has been a French star since she was 13 and made her
debut in the box-office hit ``La Boum'' (1980). Two years later,
``La Boum II'' bought her the French equivalent of an Oscar for
``most promising newcomer.'' She also made three films with her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marceau said she had few illusions about her career. ``In
America, I don't know what my future is,'' she said. ``I'm not the
one to decide, am I? There's a system in Hollywood. You have to be
lucky. You have to be there at the right moment. Sometimes it
happens. Sometimes it doesn't. Do American audiences and studios
need me? I don't know. I would like to believe they do.'' She
laughed. ``So far I've been very lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
