<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-INQUIRY (Halifax, Nova Scotia) _ Divers begin the task of
mapping the wreck site of Swissair Flight 111, which crashed at sea
Wednesday night after the pilot reported smoke in the cockpit. All
229 passengers and crew members died in the crash, including 137
Americans. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-SCENE (Peggy's Cove, Nova Scotia) _ Dawn broke on one of
the most photographed spots in Canada, the fishing villages and
polished rock beaches of Nova Scotia's south shore, to reveal an
incongruous horror _ body parts and broken bits of aircraft washing
in the surf. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-NIRELAND (Omagh, Northern Ireland) _ President Clinton
pays homage to the 28 people killed and 220 wounded in the Aug. 15
terrorist bombing in this Catholic community in the heart of
predominantly Protestant Ulster. He appeals to the Northern
Ireland's 1.6 million Protestants and Catholics to resolve their
differences in a new parliament that convenes Sept. 14. By STEWART
M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JUSTICE-PROBE (Washington) _ The Justice Department is examining
whether President Clinton's re-election campaign tried to evade
spending limits, an inquiry that could lead to the appointment of
an independent counsel. Attorney General Janet Reno says she is
looking at new information the agency received in the past few
weeks, but she declined to identify the source of the information.
By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DWI-DEPORTATION (Laredo, Texas) _ Federal immigration officials
say hundreds of legal immigrants in Texas face possible deportation
because they have racked up three or more convictions for drunken
driving. The crackdown is part of a monthlong roundup known as
operation Last Call. By DANE SCHILLER.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-TAXES (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush proposes a tax
cut as the state government enjoys a $3.7 billion projected budget
surplus. Bush says he will push repeal of several sales tax levies
totaling $400 million. His plan includes repealing the taxes on
some health items and Internet access. By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-EARL (Panama City, Fla.) _ Two fishing boats were
caught by Hurricane Earl's sharp turn toward Florida and capsized,
leaving two fishermen missing. The storm moves inland after dumping
up to 20 inches of rain on Panama City. By KIM COBB.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ It's the everyone-does-it defense,
and it isn't pretty. It won't get President Clinton off the hook,
but in a political climate in which Republicans are campaigning
against Democrats on the morality issue, it's legitimate to expose
the hypocrisy of Republican lawmakers guilty of ethical lapses in
their own lives. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARIS (Undated) _ A profile of the late Roger Maris, the
reluctant New York Yankee slugger who is at the center of this
year's chase for history in major-league baseball. While Mark
McGwire and Sammy Sosa pursue the record, Maris remains a mystery
to many baseball fans. By NEIL HOHLFELD.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ As they march toward the playoffs, the
Houston Astros are on pace to set a club record for runs this
weekend and will likely have three players drive in 100 runs for
the first time. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WOMEN (Washington) _ Democrats fear President Clinton's
admitted sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky might lead women
voters, an important constituency for the party, to stay home this
November. With those lost votes would go any chance Democrats have
of taking back the House of Representatives. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BANKRUPTCY-CONGRESS (Washington) _ As personal bankruptcy
filings reach record highs, Republican leaders in Congress are
pressing for passage of legislation that would make it tougher for
people to file for protection from creditors under federal law. By
JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-Q&AMP;A (Washington) _ With the Russian economy in meltdown and
global markets in crisis, economists and political leaders are
looking to the International Monetary Fund for help. We provide
some questions and answers about the IMF, which plays a key role in
the economic health of nations. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
