<SLUG> BC-NETNEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET-WISE CONSUMERS CONFRONT BLUEJEANS THAT HURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Charles Stough is an editor at the Dayton (Ohio) Daily News)  
 By CHARLES STOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In various languages around the world, there they are: Levi
Strauss jeans in bright store-fresh blue, unfaded and
unstonewashed, stiff as boards and already cuffed, appearing in TV
commercials with a promise that if you fall the rock-hard denim
won't scuff as soon as your knee will.
</P>
<P>
   In a note of hyperbole, one spot suggests you can saw a board
with a Hard Jeans leg, assuming you want to play carpenter with
your pants off.
</P>
<P>
   What gives, Mr. Strauss?
</P>
<P>
   ``What have we come to when the major selling point of a product
is how (ital) uncomfortable (unital) it is?'' asks a contributor to
an ad-savvy Usenet newsgroup, alt.tv.commercials. The forum members
had various theories.
</P>
<P>
   ``These ads promise that thes jeans are coarse enough to scrape
your skin,'' someone noted, ``then advocate that you wear them
without underwear, presumably to show how macho you are. I figure
Levis screwed up a few million jeans, inadvertently turning them
coarse and rigid, then some ad genius conceived this campaign as a
way to unload them.''
</P>
<P>
   The legendary jeans makers had no quick answer from a recent
enquiry to their e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   Another Internet user said, ``I had a similar theory, that their
aging-fading process was either too slow or too expensive, so why
not market the `un-aged.' I wonder what it is like to be a fad
maker.''
</P>
<P>
   Fad maker? Users don't have to be very old to recall when all
jeans were cobalt blue and stiff as lumber, so you walked like you
were wearing downspouts. New jeans meant two terrible things:
Back-to-school, or company coming. Only corduroy pants carried a
worse cachet than new, stiff jeans.
</P>
<P>
   And the cuffs were part of the new-boy image, a sign that you
were still growing, which no kid wanted to be if it meant more of
those bruising cheek-pinches from the visiting Aunt Tilly. Cuffs
were also where you carried the two scoops of dirt that emptied
onto Mom's floor at bedtime in revenge.
</P>
<P>
   There was no fad about those jeans. You couldn't wait to put
them through the wash a few times and soften them up, and see them
hang on the line outside and fade. In the retro-fashionable '60s
and '70s the teen magazines were full of bathtub formulae for
quick-aging the beasts, the better to denerdify oneself.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hard Jeans) remind me of jeans from the '50s,'' another
alt.tv.commercials contributor said. ``The best thing that ever
happened to jeans was when they finally wore in. Why would anyone
want to go back?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the Spin &AMP; Marty series on the Mickey Mouse Club
(circa 1954)?'' someone else added. ``Remember the episode when
they broke in the new jeans by soaking them, tying them in knots,
beating them on the ground, and dragging them behind a horse?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's what Strauss has in mind. Return to the thrilling
days of yesteryear, with weekly burr haircuts, Davy Crockett
coonskin hats and shirts buttoned all the way to the neck. Are '90s
parents supposed to be saying, ``Here, kids, suffer like I did?''
</P>
<P>
   If so, look for wire-bristle toothbrushes to flash into fashion.
Corsets with barbed-wire turnbuckles. Sunglasses with contracting
nose bridges that cut off your breathing and raise welts.
</P>
<P>
   And how about some charmingly leaky fountain pens that gradually
brightened those choir robes during the long sermons?
</P>
<P>
   In these days of $50,000 utility vehicles that never leave
pavement and $125 designer jeans for the club set (can't wait to
see Heidi Fleiss model No Excuses when her sentence is up), why
offer Hard Jeans? Does Detroit sell halftracks? Do soapmakers
promote zits? Will discount airlines offer crate class? Well OK,
the airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they are playing on the nerd thing,'' another
contributor suggested. ``Just like everything else you wore when
you were a kid ... You felt like some nerdy kid until your
sneakers/baseball glove/jeans/haircut/etc. wore in. Maybe they are
going for the nostalgia thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nostalgia, oh yeah. It must have started that day at the
designers' lunch table in the Levis cafeteria when the crewcut kid
tried to trade away the raisins in his Johnny Mack Brown lunchbox
and the kid in the hightop Keds said, ``You guys'll have to jog
without me today. Mom starched my Jockeys again!''
</P>
<P>
   And at the next bench the harried marketing people overheard,
and brightened....
</P>
<P>
   Charles Stough is an editor for the Dayton (Ohio) Daily News.
His e-mail address is copyboy(at)dma.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
