<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CALIFORNIA HAS TOP HISPANIC AND ASIAN GROWTH
 &HT;    300&AMP;add. With CENSUS-DATA.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ California led the nation in the growth of state
Hispanic and Asian-American populations since 1990, while Florida
had the largest black population increase, the U.S. Census Bureau
reported Friday(cq).
</P>
<P>
   California saw an increase of 2.2 million Hispanics and nearly
830,000 Asian and Pacific Islanders between 1990 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's black population increased by 480,255 people between
1990 and 1997, a 27.1 percent gain. That was twice as fast as the
state's total population growth of 13.3 percent, to 14.6 million
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, New York had the largest black population with 3.2
million, while California had the largest Hispanic population, 9.9
million.
</P>
<P>
   The District of Columbia had the highest percentage (63 percent)
of black residents among state or state equivalents, while New
Mexico had the highest percentage (40 percent) of Hispanic
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Among counties, Harris County (Houston), Texas, gained the most
black residents, 73,293, while Los Angeles County, California,
gained the most Hispanic residents, 649,404.
</P>
<P>
   Cook County, Illinois, had the largest black population among
counties at 1.4 million, while Los Angeles County had the most
Hispanics, 4.0 million.
</P>
<P>
   The county with the highest proportion of black residents was
Jefferson County, Miss., with 87 percent, while Starr County,
Texas, had the highest share of Hispanics, 98 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The annual Census Bureau report is based on population
estimates, said Larry Sink, a bureau statistician who compiled the
report. The estimates factor in birth and death statistics and are
cross-referenced with racial data supplied by the Social Security
Administration and migration data supplied by the Internal Revenue
Service, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Stan Smith, director of the University of Florida's bureau of
economic and business research, attributed the increase in
Florida's black population to several factors, including:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The state's overall rapid growth.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A higher birth rate among the black population than the white
population.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Social, political and economic changes that have made the
South in general a more attractive place for blacks to live than in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blacks are increasingly in the migration stream (to Florida),
whereas 40 or 50 years ago _ or even 30 years ago _ they were not
well represented,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the increase in Florida's black population could
be attributed to immigration from the Caribbean particularly Haiti,
Jamaica and the Dominican Republic the Census Bureau's Silk said
the great majority of new black residents to the state come from
elsewhere in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Full Census Bureau report:
http://www.census.gov/population/www/estimates/statepop.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  County data:
http://www.census.gov/population/www/estimates/countypop.html
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
