<SLUG> BC-HOPE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE DAVIS HAS KNACK FOR PICKING MOVIE WINNERS 
</HEADLINE>
 DAVIS-MOVIE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MELISSA MORRISON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Hope Davis is a gold-star member of the indie posse.
Like actors Campbell Scott, Julianne Moore, Parker Posey and
Stanley Tucci, she keeps turning up in the kind of low-budget,
high-quality movies that tend to burst out of nowhere to acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   Her latest is ``Next Stop Wonderland,'' which got snapped up for
distribution by the formidable Miramax Films at this year's
Sundance Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' and her gang's credits sound somewhat incestuous. Davis
got her first starring role in 1996's ``The Daytrippers,'' where
she worked with Posey, Scott and Tucci. She shows up next in the
upcoming ``The Imposters,'' which Tucci directs and in which she
co-stars with Scott. She was in last year's ``The Myth of
Fingerprints'' with Moore _ who, as it happens, was originally
supposed to be in ``Big Night,'' co-directed by Tucci and Scott,
but had to drop out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cast your pals,'' Davis said from her suite in Phoenix's
Royal Palms Inn. ``All those people I know well. . . . They are
very intellectual people who live in New York and like certain
types of art and certain types of expression, and they tend to end
up doing stuff that's labeled indie, and then everyone gets to know
one other.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis was in Phoenix to promote her latest indie project, Brad
Anderson's ``Next Stop Wonderland'' (and to hit the Barney's outlet
in New River, Ariz., with her best friend, a doctor at Scottsdale's
Mayo Clinic).
</P>
<P>
   The movie is a bossa nova-inflected love story in which Davis'
character, Erin Castleton, a wry and lovelorn nurse, meets up with
a series of Boston jerks via the personal ads. Meanwhile, she keeps
narrowly missing meeting Alan Monteiro (Alan Gelfant), the guy
obviously meant for her.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax's association with ``Next Stop Wonderland'' ensures it
wide distribution and the imprimatur of accessible artsiness by the
same company that brought you ``Pulp Fiction'' and ``The English
Patient.'' Like ``Daytrippers'' and ``The Myth of Fingerprints,''
two of Davis' other starring turns, ``Next Stop Wonderland'' is one
of a handful of independent movies that escape obscurity every
year.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has just been lucky that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how a career goes: Some of it is intentional, most of
is not,'' she says. ``Most of it is what comes to you.
``Daytrippers'' was the first time that I had been offered the lead
in anything. . . . All the others came about because of
``Daytrippers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Daytrippers,'' directed by Greg Mattola, is about a bickering
Long Island family that bundles into its station wagon for a trip
into Manhattan when Davis' character suspects her husband of
infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis is not long for the rarefied indie world. Like her
counterpart Moore, who's alternated blockbuster studio films such
as Steven Spielberg's ``The Lost World'' with independents, Davis
has made two studio movies in the past six months: the political
thriller ``Arlington Road,'' with Jeff Bridges, and ``Mumford,''
the latest ensemble piece by ``Big Chill'' director Lawrence
Kasdan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (they) are of the quality Stanley would approve of,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her poised-over-the-mainstream status, Davis looks much
more like an East Coast habitue than a Hollywood starlet. She's
wearing a plain gray skirt, blue blouse and red Miu Miu loafers.
Her flowing blond hair has been cropped to her chin for a recent
``Vogue'' photography session. She lives in New York (her loft was
a set in ``Daytrippers'') and grew up in Tenafly, N.J., across the
street from Mira Sorvino.
</P>
<P>
   Davis started her professional career in Chicago, waitressing
until acting started paying the bills. After small parts in
Chicago-filmed movies such as ``Flatliners'' and ``Home Alone,''
she felt ready for New York. There she hooked up with playwright
Nicky Silver, starring in his plays ``The Food Chain'' and
``Pterodactyls,'' which he wrote for her. She continues to act
onstage, appearing with Kevin Kline in Chekhov's ``Ivanov'' last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Independent films, typically made on small budgets by novice
filmmakers, are a crapshoot. Davis beat the odds by making a series
of good ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's actors who always say there's this danger that the
films that you're having a really great time on . . . end up
bombing,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a great time on ``Next Stop Wonderland.'' I was
alone in most of the shooting. I was often shot walking around by
myself, in my house by myself,'' says Davis, who was going through
a divorce at the time. ``It was very lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   She said director/co-writer Anderson, whose debut film was
1996's ``The Darien Gap,'' favored an improvisational approach that
left her uncertain about how the film would ultimately turn out.
</P>
<P>
   The movies she likes to watch are likewise a mix of studio and
independent features. Her favorite films this summer: ``Bulworth''
and ``Buffalo 66.'' She counts ``Lethal Weapon 4'' as a guilty
pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Period romances are her favorite. ``I'm a chick,'' she says. ``I
waited and waited for ``The English Patient'' to come.''
</P>
<P>
   At the video store, she catches up on the work of her favorite
actresses: Meryl Streep, Judy Davis, Jennifer Jason Leigh.
</P>
<P>
   And when she has time off from making films, she reads. ``Let's
see, the last thing I finished was the John Irving book ``A Widow
for a Year,'' which was really great. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate seeing movies of books that I have loved. ``English
Patient'' ended up disappointing me because I loved the book so
much. ``Howards End'' was a tremendous disappointment, even though
it's a very beautiful film, because the novel is so much more
complicated.'' She hates the fact that every good book that comes
out now is immediately optioned for a script.
</P>
<P>
   She said she wants to continue combining theater and independent
films with better-paying studio efforts. Although she got her
cinematic breakthrough roles in independent films, she's not a snob
about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's tons of garbagy independent films being made,'' she
said. ``I get sent scripts for the most bizarre things:
bullfighters and deejays, and one about birthing Jesus _ just
really bizarre stuff that a studio won't make because there's no
reason to put any money behind these films.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
