<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIKE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARE FISTS NO MATCH FOR SHARP CLAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are two villains to hate in ``Like It Is,'' and one is
Roger Daltry, who looks fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   Daltrey plays Kelvin, a well-groomed gay recording-company mogul
with a cynical attitude toward love; regular collagen-injection
appointments; an attraction to boys ``who can't count past 10,''
and no redeeming personality traits whatever.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Like It Is,'' which opens Friday in New York City, is not
Kelvin's story. It's a pleasant but unexceptional romance about two
younger, much nicer Englishmen.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning there is Craig (Steve Bell), a very young man
hanging out on the streets of Blackpool, England, looking
sensitive, baby-faced and ripe for picking. And there is Matt (Ian
Rose), a blond, still-young, more worldly sort, a music promoter
visiting from London.
</P>
<P>
   They meet outside a noisy club and after a courtship ritual
consisting of a cigarette, the question ``You want to come back
then?,'' a little music and the question ``Do you want to go up?''
the two go to bed. It is quickly apparent that Craig is a little
conflicted about his sexuality. Luckily he soon gets over this and
turns up in London.
</P>
<P>
   Matt is glad to see him, but others are not. Enter the second
villain: Matt's roommate, Paula (Dani Behr, a British television
host), a beautiful but hard blonde singer who doesn't seem to have
got the message that gay men don't like sleeping with women.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe it's only attention that Paula wants from Matt.
Whatever the case, Craig's arrival has upset their cozy
arrangement. And Paula really needs Matt right now, what with a
tabloid newspaper having just revealed her true age and her record
company asking for 12 new songs for the next album.
</P>
<P>
   Craig's only means of support has been boxing in illegal
bare-knuckles fights back in Blackpool, so when Kelvin (who is
Matt's boss) offers him a job driving his musician clients here and
there, he's thrilled. But the job takes him out of town, and hey,
this is the intoxicating world of cocaine, loud music and expensive
parties. Things happen.
</P>
<P>
   Kelvin pretty much pushes Craig into the arms of another man (if
only for a one-night stand). Matt cheats, too, or tries to. Paula
doesn't give Matt his telephone messages from Craig. In a heated
moment, Craig calls Paula a ``stuck-up cow'' to her face.
</P>
<P>
   What will prevail, the fast life or true love? And what's really
more brutal and bloody _ bare-knuckle fighting in alleys or the
music business in London?
</P>
<P>
   Rose and Bell do fine jobs as the lovers, and Ms. Behr is
convincingly arrogant and needy. And through it all, Daltrey, now
almost 30 years from his heyday as lead singer of the Who, is
appealingly devilish. At certain angles, however, he is beginning
to bear a mysterious resemblance to Joe Namath. It's probably just
the lighting. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LIKE IT IS
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Paul Oremland; written by Robert Cray, based on a
story by Cray, Oremland and Kevin Sampson; director of photography,
Alistair Cameron; edited by Jan Langford; music by Don McGlashan;
production designer, Tim Sykes; produced by Tracey Gardiner;
released by First Run Features. At the Quad Cinema, 13th Street,
west of Fifth Avenue, Greenwich Village. Running time: 90 minutes.
This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Steve Bell (Craig), Ian Rose (Matt), Roger Daltrey
(Kelvin) and Dani Behr (Paula). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
