<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNUSUAL-MUSEUMS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUMS BUILT ON THE PASSION TO COLLECT . . . ANYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Hugh Francis Hicks is a 76-year-old dentist in downtown
Baltimore, with an office on the parlor floor of an old brownstone
diagonally across the street from the Walters Art Gallery. The
other day, he took me into the building's basement to show me a
collection he has been putting together for nearly 70 years. Hicks
collects light bulbs. He has 60,000 of them.
</P>
<P>
   You probably won't be surprised to learn that this is the
largest collection of light bulbs in the world. Hicks has
officially turned it into a museum, the Mount Vernon Museum of
Incandescent Lighting. It contains the world's biggest bulb (at
50,000 watts and 4 feet high, it's about the size of a shrub) and
also the smallest, which you see only by looking through a
microscope. A pair of Edison's earliest experimental bulbs are
here, with their original Bristol-board filaments. One of them
works.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the bulbs are more or less decoratively arranged in old
glass-and-wood cases, like the ones that turn-of-the-century
museums used to have, the cases containing typewritten labels
explaining, for example, the source of the name Mazda (a
Zoroastrian sun god) and the history of tungsten filaments. A kind
of rabbit warren, the basement includes a room with a big round
table where Hicks serves soda and cookies to visiting
schoolchildren. His museum is open on Thursdays or by appointment.
I phoned ahead. He met me in his office, then turned on the lights.
</P>
<P>
   Why do people collect? I spent a few days poking around unusual
museums and other places, wondering about that. I visited a museum
of trash and the basement of a teetotaler in New Jersey who owns
several thousand miniature liquor bottles and several dozen
miniature Vargas pinups from old cigarette packs. (He doesn't
smoke, either.)
</P>
<P>
   I visited the Nicholas Roerich Museum on the Upper West Side of
Manhattan, a shrine to a once-famous Russian mystic or charlatan,
depending on which accounts of him you read. The museum owns a
collection of his paintings.
</P>
<P>
   It is taken for granted that art is worth collecting, but
collectors collect pretty much everything, without necessarily
thinking that what they collect has esthetic or monetary value.
</P>
<P>
   The writer Walter Benjamin, who collected books, explained that
``one of the finest memories of a collector is the moment when he
rescued a book to which he might never have given a thought, much
less a wishful look, because he found it lonely and abandoned on
the marketplace and bought it to give it its freedom _ the way the
prince bought a beautiful slave girl in `The Arabian Nights.'''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``To a book collector, you see, the true freedom of
all books is somewhere on his shelves.''
</P>
<P>
   Or on public view, through the collector's benefaction.
Sometimes collectors make museums, maybe because they are
exhibitionists or have a sense of civic responsibility or both, and
these museums can have a fascination that is often
indistinguishable from that of art museums.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean that light bulbs are as compelling as paintings to
look at. I mean that the modern museum, whether it is a collection
of art or oddments, derives partly from the old Kunst- und
Wunderkammern, or art- and wonder-cabinets, and it retains its
original aspirations to wonderment.
</P>
<P>
   Kunst- und Wunderkammern began to proliferate, more or less, in
the 16th century, the result of humanist curiosity, technological
advances in things like optics and engineering, a revival of
interest in antique texts that were preoccupied with the marvelous,
and global exploration, which exposed Europe to what seemed like a
strange new world.
</P>
<P>
   Wonderment came to be perceived as a kind of middle state
between ignorance and knowledge, and wonder cabinets were theaters
of the marvelous, museums of accumulated curiosities, proving God's
ingenuity. They contained whatever was the biggest, the smallest,
the rarest, the most exquisite, the most bizarre, the most
grotesque.
</P>
<P>
   Art, astrolabes, armor _ man-made wonders _ were cheek by jowl
with monkeys' teeth and pathological anomalies like human horns. A
German doctor named Lorenz Hoffman had a typical Kunst- und
Wunderkammer: he owned paintings by Duerer and Cranach, a skeleton
of a newborn, two dozen miniature spoons hidden within a cherry
pit, an armband made of elks' hoofs, mummies and various rare
musical instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Frederik Ruysch, a Dutch anatomist, concocted wild tableaux made
of flowers, skulls, kidney stones and diseased organs in his
Wunderkammer in Amsterdam. And one of the first museums in the
United States belonged to the Philadelphia artist Charles Willson
Peale. It contained fossils and stuffed birds as well as paintings.
</P>
<P>
   I happened to be talking with a friend about wonder cabinets
while driving to Hicks' when I noticed a sign on the highway for a
decoy museum in Havre de Grace, Md. Havre de Grace is a sleepy
place on the Susquehanna Flats, where the Susquehanna River meets
Chesapeake Bay. It was duck hunter's nirvana until a series of laws
during the 1930s and '40s curtailed hunting. The Decoy Museum, I
discovered, preserves hundreds of duck decoys by local carvers.
</P>
<P>
   Astonishingly, the carvers are also preserved, in life-size,
full-length polyvinylacetate figures, like decoys of the decoy
makers. There's a big tableau, for example, which lights up when
you press a button, a la Madame Tussaud's, showing a bunch of the
local carvers sitting around a stove in one of the town's decoy
shops in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't always tell the difference between the works of R.
Madison Mitchell, a local funeral director, who was, I gather, the
Giotto of Havre de Grace, and the works of Bob McGaw Jr., who
perfected a way of decorating his decoys that is called scratch
painting. But no doubt the distinctions are obvious to the people
who have looked at the decoys a lot longer than I did.
</P>
<P>
   Connoisseurship, after all, is about making distinctions through
slow, comparative observation, whether it involves paintings or
wooden ducks. Partly it was a desire for a more methodical approach
to collected objects that ushered in a new age of museums two
centuries ago. Museums began to specialize. The balance tipped from
delight toward instruction. The new museums set out to categorize
things, to create order out of the world, or at least to imply that
there is an order. Descartes said that too much wonder can
``pervert the use of reason.'' This was the age of Descartes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the spirit of the wonder cabinets never altogether died. Art
museums today, even collections of light bulbs, though they clearly
are not true wonder cabinets, can trace their origins to them:
their function is still to preserve what's marvelous, to show us
what is rare that we can't see otherwise, or at least to make us
see, with heightened curiosity, what is around us.
</P>
<P>
   I came across a reference in a book by Lawrence Weschler, ``
Wilson's Cabinet of Wonder,'' to a place called the Muetter Museum
in Philadelphia, and I decided to look it up. Thomas Dent Muetter,
it turns out, was a Philadelphia surgeon who went to Paris in the
1830s, when it was the medical Mecca. There he saw hospital wards
arranged according to diseases, so that doctors could compare the
conditions of patients suffering from the same things; he saw
collections of tumors, aneurysms, bones and so on. He returned to
Philadelphia inspired by the systematic connection of morbid
anatomy and clinical pathology. Soon he began to build his own
teaching collection of anatomical and pathological specimens for
the benefit of medical students.
</P>
<P>
   He accumulated hundreds of things: air-dried specimens,
specimens preserved in alcohol, plaster casts, papier-mache models,
watercolors and oil paintings, all of which he bequeathed in 1858
to the College of Physicians of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   I found the museum within a big Georgian building behind a tall
iron gate in the center of the city. It is a two-story calculated
anachronism of polished wood cases, thick burgundy curtains and
brass lamps, and from time to time it organizes shows of topical
interest to keep itself alive and kicking.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, the museum had thousands of things on view,
mundane and otherwise. But in recent years it streamlined its
display, somewhat skewing the public's perception of the collection
by showing only what's most striking or unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Having grown over time, the collection has come to include
extraordinary examples of disease and trauma like the connected
livers of the Siamese twins Chang and Eng; a tumor removed from the
jaw of President Grover Cleveland; the skeletons of a 7-foot-6-inch
man and of a 3-foot-6-inch woman; a bound foot from China; the
remains of the so-called Soap Lady, whose corpse decomposed into a
soapy substance called adipocere, and an entire cabinet of more
than 2,000 objects removed from the throats of choking patients,
the objects carefully arranged in narrow drawers according to type:
meat, nuts, pins, buttons.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that the college, which oversees the museum, has lately
become a little squeamish about the sensational aspect of its own
collection. For several years, photographers like Joel-Peter Witkin
and the team of Gwen Akin and Allan Ludwig used specimens for
pictures that the Muetter published as wall calendars, until it was
decided, evidently, that less spectacular calendars would convey a
tamer and more sober institutional image.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad. I couldn't help seeing much of what was on view in
relation to art: to Gericault's great paintings of severed limbs,
to Kiki Smith's sculptures of flayed figures, to Nayland Blake's
and Damien Hirst's arrangements of medical instruments and, in the
case of the Soap Lady, her mouth wide open, to Zoran Music's
screaming figures. A dried skeleton of a newborn child, hanging by
its outstretched arms, head back (crucifixion pose), even made me
think of Chardin's famous painting of a ray hanging from a hook,
its eyes upturned, as if in a state of spiritual ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to push the connection too far, only to stress how
a place like the Muetter, notwithstanding its serious medical
function, seems neatly to blur the distinction between science and
art by dwelling in the marvelous. Its collection causes us to react
in a way that goes beyond reason and touches our nerves, which is
precisely what art should do.
</P>
<P>
   Was Muetter motivated merely by scientific inquiry? Maybe he
was, but many collections suggest a kind of obsession on the part
of the collector that exceeds practicality. A Manhattan
psychoanalyst, Werner Muensterberger, wrote a book not long ago
called ``Collecting: An Unruly Passion,'' in which he argued that
collecting is, among other things, more or less a form of displaced
childhood longing for parental comfort, the collected objects
becoming, like sucked thumbs, stand-ins for a mother's breast.
</P>
<P>
   I am not a collector. I can't say. Hicks, the light bulb man,
told me that about a dozen years ago two psychiatrists and three
psychologists from Johns Hopkins University came by. ``They were
something,'' he said. ``They didn't blink their eyes. They were
interviewing collectors from all over the world. After spending $4
million, they concluded that collectors collect for the fascination
of an object and for no other reason. Heck, I would have told them
that for $1 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Museum Hours
</P>
<P>
   Here is information about visiting the museums:
</P>
<P>
   NICHOLAS ROERICH MUSEUM, 319 W. 107th St., Manhattan, (212)
864-7752. Hours: Tuesdays through Sundays, 2 to 5 p.m.
Contributions accepted.
</P>
<P>
   MUETTER MUSEUM, College of Physicians of Philadelphia, 19 S.
22nd St., Philadelphia, (215) 563-3737. Hours: Tuesdays through
Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. Admission: $8; $4 for students, the
elderly and children 6 to 18; free for children under 6.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNT VERNON MUSEUM OF INCANDESCENT LIGHTING, 717 Washington
Place, Baltimore, (410) 752-8586. Open the first Thursday of every
month, 4 to 8 p.m., and by appointment. Donations accepted.
</P>
<P>
   DECOY MUSEUM, Giles Street, Havre de Grace, Md., (410) 939-3739.
Hours: daily, 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. Admission: $4; $2 for children 9 to
18; free for children 8 and younger.
</P>
</TEXT>
