<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7512 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      09-03 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTY MAZDA MARKS 10 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Has it really been 10 years since the Mazda Miata
single-handedly reignited America's enthusiasm for lightweight
roadsters, years after the British had packed up their little
sports cars and gone home?
</P>
<P>
   When the Miata appeared on the scene in 1989, it caused an
absolute frenzy of retro longing, especially among those boomers
who still regretted selling off their MGs, Triumphs and Alfa Romeos
many moons ago. Like today's mania for the New Beetle, Miata was so
sought after that it commanded premium prices far above list.
</P>
<P>
   That list price has moved up a bit, and the frenzy has died
down, but Miata remains a singular expression of sports-car virtue.
Others have tried but missed the mark.
</P>
<P>
   A recent flurry of German roadsters from BMW, Porsche and
Mercedes-Benz may eclipse the Miata in performance, but they cost
twice as much. And they probably wouldn't exist if Miata had not
paved the way.
</P>
<P>
   Like the hot-selling MGB of the '60s, the Miata is moderately
priced, fun to drive and imbued with the same magical charm that
turns any back road into a romp. Of course, I'm somewhat partial to
MGBs, especially the red one in my garage.
</P>
<P>
   A free-revving four-banger hooked to a quick-shift five-speed;
fast, precise steering and agile handling; and that undefinable
feeling of contentment that comes from the sun on your face and the
wind mussing your hair, that's what the Miata has succeeded in
bringing back to life.
</P>
<P>
   For the 1999 model (there was no '98 model), Mazda engaged in
the dangerous task of tinkering with a proven winner. The challenge
was to upgrade Miata without spoiling its character or obscuring
its image.
</P>
<P>
   Miata drivers are a loyal group, surveys have shown, with
frequent repeat buyers and many Miata clubs cropping up everywhere,
including Phoenix. And they'd squawk loudly if Mazda ruined the
Miata.
</P>
<P>
   But although the sheet metal has been freshened, the front end
changed and the interior redesigned, from any angle, it's still
unmistakably a Miata.
</P>
<P>
   The new look of the front is brighter, with more personality.
The slightly wider back end, with its bigger taillights and tail
flip, looks sharper and more substantial. The scalloped doors and
side panels add to the sporty look.
</P>
<P>
   And the character is still there. No one who loved the old Miata
should dislike the new one. One friend who drives a Miata likes her
flip-up headlights and was disturbed that the '99 has fixed oval
beams. But that was her only complaint.
</P>
<P>
   She loved the way the new Miata drives. Better in every way, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the body freshening, the new car is slightly faster, a
lot stiffer (improves ride and handling), and a bit roomier.
</P>
<P>
   I last tested a Miata in 1993, at which time one important
factor became immediately obvious: I didn't fit. Not even close.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I'm sort of tall. OK, real tall, 6-foot-6 and mostly legs.
Still, I can find some degree of comfort in 95 percent of the cars
out there, but driving the Miata is the most miserable crunch I've
had in any modern car, including some really teeny stuff.
</P>
<P>
   If only Mazda knew how much tall people appreciate tilt steering
wheels. If the Miata had one, my griping would be over.
</P>
<P>
   But the Miata was so appealing in so many other ways, I soon
forgot my physical pain. This is the kind of car that reminds me
why I like to drive. Eager, quick and responsive, with handling
like a skateboard, it's a pleasure to work the Miata's short, tight
shifter, and throw the little car blithely into turns.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the Miata has a raspy exhaust note that recalls the old
British iron, but our test car had something loose in the exhaust
system that caused a tinny rattle, and nasty smirks from those
within earshot.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension is tight and jouncy like the old British sports
cars, but unlike them, the Miata will soak up major bumps with
ease. Some small stuff, like lane reflectors, will knock it off
track, but not too badly.
</P>
<P>
   The new interior, other than being too darn small, is nicely
done, with a sporty dash, traditional gauges and supportive seats.
The optional Bose stereo system is just great.
</P>
<P>
   The test car was equipped with the Popular Equipment Package, a
$2,330 set of appearance, convenience and performance options that
pretty much included most of the good stuff. Fifteen-inch wheels
and tires are another upgrade, but our car had the 14-inch alloy
rims with performance tires.
</P>
<P>
   A Nardi steering wheel, a real classic touch in any sports car,
is included in the options package. But I wasn't too impressed by
its look or feel. Certainly not like the classic Nardi wheels I
remember.
</P>
<P>
   The convertible top, which thankfully comes with a glass rear
window instead of the previous vinyl, is operated manually but
raises or lowers so easily, you won't miss a power top, which is so
prevalent in today's convertibles.
</P>
<P>
   One glitch: the tonneau that covers the stowed top is a
surprisingly chintzy piece of thin plastic that is certain to
disintegrate in short order.
</P>
<P>
   The trunk has been made a tad bigger by placing the space-saver
spare underneath, but don't plan any major trips unless you send
your suitcases ahead.
</P>
<P>
   One question remains: Does Miata suffer under the stigma of
being a ``girl car,'' with the sort of feminine allure that's
troublesome for testosterone-imbued dudes?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, if you really believe that sort of thing. But there are
plenty of regular guys driving Miatas. Rallying and racing them,
too.
</P>
<P>
   And digging the classic charms of a real sports car. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mazda Miata &QL; 
- Vehicle type: Two-passenger, two-door convertible, rear-wheel
drive. &QL; 
- Base price: $19,770. &QL; 
- Price as tested:$23,680. &QL; 
- Engine: 1.8-liter in-line four, 140 horsepower at 6,500 rpm, 119
pounds-feet of torque at 5,500 rpm. &QL; 
- Transmission: Five-speed stick shift. &QL; 
- Curb weight: 2,299 pounds. &QL; 
- Length:155.3 inches. &QL; 
- Wheelbase:89.2 inches. &QL; 
- EPA fuel economy:25 city, 29 highway. &QL; 
- Highs: Sporty handling.New styling.Fun personality. &QL; 
- Lows: Cramped interior. Chintzy tonneau. No tilt steering. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 1623EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
