<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7535 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-0904-     09-03 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-0904-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUBLE DOWN AGAIN, AND IT LOOKS LIKE CHERNOMYRDIN, TOO
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0904.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The fading Russian ruble again plunged in value against
the dollar on Thursday as the Kremlin made new but vague overtures
to the Communist-dominated parliament on a power-sharing
arrangement to create a new government.
</P>
<P>
   The political stand-off has fueled growing anxiety in the street
that Russia could be lurching toward social unrest. As the ruble
collapses, prices of consumer goods continue to climb and food
shortages are predicted.
</P>
<P>
   But the Duma, the lower house of parliament, appeared set Friday
to again reject the nomination of Viktor Chernomyrdin as President
Yeltsin's choice for prime minister. A second vote against
Chernomyrdin would prolong Russia's power vacuum as the economy
continues to deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   Worried customers continued to crowd the entrances to Russia's
teetering banks seeking, mostly without success, to withdraw their
deposits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hopeless. Russia is crumbling and the people in charge
can only fight among themselves,'' said Yuri Lemankov, as he waited
in a long line outside a Moscow bank.
</P>
<P>
   Angry rhetoric from politicians that Russia's crisis could lead
to rioting in the streets prompted rumors in Moscow and on Western
financial markets that military units were being deployed on the
outskirts of the Russian capital. Russian security officials
refuted the rumors as ``absolutely unfounded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``God forbid a repetition of 1993,'' acting Defense Minister
Igor Sergeyev said, referring to the political crisis in which
Yeltsin used tanks and troops to crush a rebellion by dissidents in
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Sergeyev warned that Russia's 1.7 million-strong armed forces
``are not in a festive mood,'' worrying as are most Russians about
the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Amid warnings of looming food shortages, police in Moscow have
been ordered to fortify their patrols near major food storehouses
and processing plants to guard against theft or illegal shipments
to other regions, the newspaper Sevodnya said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A police spokesman confirmed the report.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials Thursday attributed the possibility of serious
food shortages, which compound the economic problems, to cuts in
imports caused by the weakened ruble and banking crisis.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 percent of retail food sales in Russia are imports and
major Russian food processors rely on 85 to 90 percent of their raw
materials from abroad, according to the ministry of economic
relations and trade.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also forecasted a poor domestic potato harvest this
autumn due to an early summer drought followed by heavy rains in
August. The potato is a staple of the national diet; the average
Russian eats six times more potatoes a year than an American.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin served as prime minister under Yeltsin from 1992
until March of this year and is widely blamed for helping to create
the current economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition lawmakers continued to demand that Yeltsin seek a new
compromise candidate for prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Under the constitution, the Duma can vote three times on a prime
minister's nomination. If rejected, Yeltsin can appoint a prime
minister by decree and dissolve the legislature. New elections then
would take place within three months.
</P>
<P>
   But the angry public mood makes that a dangerous proposition for
both Yeltsin and the Duma.
</P>
<P>
   The average monthly household income in June was 861 rubles,
about $137. With the ruble's devaluation since Aug. 17, the same
income of 861 rubles withered to a value of about $64 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The ruble had been trading at 6.2 to the dollar last month
before it began its slide. The official ruble rate fell to 13.5
rubles Thursday, but traders said it was as low as 17.4 to the
dollar on the street.
</P>
<P>
   A new poll taken on Aug. 29 and released Thursday showed
two-thirds of Russians blame Yeltsin for the financial crisis and
believe he should step down.
</P>
<P>
   Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov said the Duma would
proceed with impeachment proceedings against Yeltsin. But it is a
burdensome process under the Russian constitution and unlikely to
succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking a compromise, the Kremlin approached Duma leaders
Thursday with new discussions on a short-lived agreement reached
last weekend that would have had Yeltsin give up some of his
immense powers to the prime minister and parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin allies announced that the acting prime minister
would deliver a ``sensational speech'' to the parliament's upper
house on Friday outlining his broad plans to deal with Russia's
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, appointed last month by Yeltsin after the
president fired the previous government, received some good news
when the Duma's third largest faction, the Liberal Democratic Party
with 51 seats, announced it would support him on Friday. The bloc,
led by ultra-nationalist Vladimir Zhirinovsky, abstained in the
first vote on Monday, which rejected Chernomyrdin 253-94.
</P>
<P>
   He needs 226 votes in the 450-member Duma.
</P>
<P>
   But Zhirinovsky's endorsement wasn't exactly ringing. ``Bad as
Chernomyrdin may be, he has experience,'' Zhirinovsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A surgeon who has sent 200 patients to the morgue may cure the
201st,'' he added. ``Of course we have pity for the 200 victims,
but that makes him an experienced surgeon.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
