<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7555 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPCORN-SEASON-3TAKES     09-03 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPCORN-SEASON-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER'S CRASH, BOOM, SPLAT PUNCTUATED BY SUBTLER FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Hollywood's popcorn season fades into a filet mignon fall and
the explosions of ``Deep Impact,'' ``Armageddon'' and ``Godzilla''
recede into distant background mutterings, what, if anything, have
this summer's movies taught us about ourselves and our tastes in
film?
</P>
<P>
   The most revealing lesson of the last two months, one that is, I
hope, not lost on Hollywood, may be that popcorn doesn't have to
rule the summer box office notwithstanding the $100-million-plus
gross of the tittery gross-out comedy ``There's Something About
Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   The season's biggest hit, ``Saving Private Ryan,'' is the kind
of prestige film that usually opens after Thanksgiving. Its box
office success during the popcorn season has shown that millions of
summertime moviegoers have no problem in going from the beach to a
gory battlefield devoid of soft-focus kisses or smutty jokes.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Saving Private Ryan'' isn't an anomaly. If you pick and
choose carefully, there is an abundance of smaller films, from
``The Eel'' to ``Return to Paradise,'' catering to discriminating
tastes.
</P>
<P>
   The two most significant American films to be released this
summer _ ``Saving Private Ryan'' and ``Your Friends and Neighbors''
_ reflect the paradoxically divided state of the serious American
film. The popularity of Steven Spielberg's World War II epic can be
seen as a convergence of many currents.
</P>
<P>
   It offers us respite from all the endless, demoralizing sleaze
of Washington gossip and transports us back to what feels like a
nobler, cleaner era. Representing Hollywood at its high-minded
best, it promotes the traditional values of heroism, virtue and
patriotic duty with gripping, cinema-verite-style battle sequences
to make it all seem fresh and up-to-date.
</P>
<P>
   The cheeky little David critically standing up to Spielberg's
Goliath of a hit is Neil LaBute's devastating followup to last
year's punch-in-the-stomach comedy ``In the Company of Men.'' If
the pop literature tells us that men are from Mars and women from
Venus, LaBute's nasty comic satire suggests that they really come
from warring galaxies light years beyond Pluto.
</P>
<P>
   While it's a safe bet that ``Saving Private Ryan,'' a powerful
but flawed movie, will be revered as a classic decades hence, it's
harder to guess what future generations may make of LaBute's
excoriating study of sexual distress among the yuppie class. Will
it be seen as a black-comic forerunner to an emerging genre of
brutal psychological realism or as a decadent manifestation of
social anxiety, a parasitical infection attached to the balloon of
late-90s prosperity?
</P>
<P>
   ``Your Friends and Neighbors'' has the feel of a moralizing
punishment methodically administered by a filmmaker intent on
communicating harsh truths about sex, power and modern manners.
``Your Friends and Neighbors'' is no realistic slice of life.
</P>
<P>
   Its evisceration of the miserable sex lives of two yuppie
couples in an unidentified Midwestern city and the despicable
behavior of the scornful self-styled stud who manipulates them is
as exaggerated and deliberately mannered and tricky as a David
Mamet play.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, LaBute has professed his admiration for the
brittle, satirical style and pointed banter of English Restoration
drama. Two scenes from ``Your Friends and Neighbors'' are actually
set in rehearsals of a comedy by William Wycherley, the
17th-century playwright whose most famous plays, ``The Country
Wife'' and ``The Plain Dealer,'' treat the same themes _ sex,
friendship and elaborate deception and betrayal _ as ``Your Friends
and Neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   The world of yuppie sex and marriage evoked in the movie is
extremely grim. The sexual revolution and the expectations it has
brought have given both men and women an overwhelming sense of
entitlement when it comes to pleasure. But once men and women enter
the bedroom, the men prove to be little boys playing verbal games
for erotic stimulation, while the women wait for a passion their
selfish partners can't even begin to summon.
</P>
<P>
   Their best friend, played with a grim, sneering arrogance by
Jason Patric (who suggests the comedian Dennis Miller on the
warpath), is an avenging stud and misogynist who when asked to
recall the best sex he has ever had, remembers raping a male
classmate in a high school locker room with his friends. This
monster, who practices his pillow talk into a tape recorder and who
viciously berates a date for staining his finely threaded sheets
with her menstrual blood, is a grotesque caricature of irate
American machismo.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the character's exaggeration, he is an uncomfortably
recognizable type, the worst nightmare of feminists, an
unregenerate, unapologetic male chauvinist whose ruthless honesty
lends him a ghastly kind of integrity.
</P>
<P>
   The women are shown as collaborators in their own bedroom
tragedies. One witheringly berates her lover for having to talk so
much during sex. The other reverts into an incommunicative sulk.
The American bedroom, according to ``Your Friends and Neighbors,''
is a battlefield to which men and women repair with impossibly high
expectations and no guidebook about the rules and etiquette of
engagement.
</P>
<P>
   In an even broader sense, the movie is an icy critique of the
value we place on sex. The utopian rhetoric of the sexual
revolution, combined with the commodification of sex to sell
everything under the sun, have guaranteed that millions of people
conditioned to expect erotic salvation on demand are in for a
bitter disappointment when it isn't delivered.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Your Friends and Neighbors'' distills the feisty,
take-no-prisoners style of the small independent movie that has
risen almost as a necessary corollary to Hollywood's phony romantic
schmaltz exemplified by fantasies like ``City of Angels.'' It feels
like a slap in the face, a splash of ice water in a climate
contaminated by scandal-mongering, overheated by talk show
confessions and rampant commercialism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' is in its way as powerful a film as
``Your Friends and Neighbors,'' while being diametrically opposite
in style and content. Where LaBute's film is all pointed, parrying
talk, much of the dialogue in ``Saving Private Ryan'' is half
submerged in the roar of battle.
</P>
<P>
   Where ``Your Friends and Neighbors'' addresses the moment,
``Saving Private Ryan'' looks back to the past. And except for a
jumbled, embarrassing story that Matt Damon's character tells about
three brothers and a girl in a barn, the movie has no allusions to
sex.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is only the latest example of Steven Spielberg's
genius at recasting Hollywood archetypes to make them seem more
contemporary than they really are and in the process delivering
broad, resonant and comfortingly uplifting cultural messages. Yes,
the battlefield sequences, shot with hand-held cameras, with the
gore flying in all directions and the soldiers forging ahead in a
state of panic and chaos, are the most harrowing and realistic ever
filmed.
</P>
<P>
   But for all their horror, they don't, as some critics have
suggested, make ``Saving Private Ryan'' an antiwar movie. World War
II was, after all, America's ``good war.''
</P>
<P>
   The team of American soldiers sent to find the elusive private
is the same carefully selected cross-section _ an Italian, a Jew,
an Irishman, a scared bookish intellectual and so on _ found in the
typical 1940s war movie. While not uniformly virtuous, the group
led by Tom Hanks (playing the same responsible, smart all-American
nice guy embodied in the 40s by an actor like Frederic March), is a
pretty impressive bunch in its solidarity and courage under fire.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's extra resonance has to do with its timing and its
attitude toward war. In the same way that Spielberg's ``Schindler's
List'' acknowledged the Holocaust with a thoroughness and power
that Hollywood never dared before, ``Saving Private Ryan'' feels
like an official act of atonement.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the wounds of the old generation gap are being
tended, as a Hollywood baby boomer apologizes for his peers for not
recognizing the older generation's courage and sacrifice during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Where Hollywood's Vietnam epics had an undertone of absurdism
and American self-hatred, Spielberg's film, which is wrapped in
images of the American flag, is a wholehearted celebration of
American pluck and virtue and honor. But in typical Spielbergian
fashion, the movie goes overboard to make its point.
</P>
<P>
   The one gratingly false note in ``Schindler's List'' has Liam
Neeson breaking into tears at the end of the movie and berating
himself for not doing more to save Holocaust victims. Here, an
elderly World War II veteran weeps at a grave wonders out loud
whether he's been ``good'' enough to deserve salvation. Make no
mistake, this kind of sentimentality is pure Hollywood corn.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a selection of movies playing in New York that also
offer more than popcorn gratification: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Return to Paradise'
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Ruben's drama (loosely based on a 1990 French film called
``Force Majeure'') is oddly similar to ``Saving Private Ryan'' in
its emotional tone and concern with heroism and moral choice,
although it isn't nearly as accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   When three friends who have been living high in Malaysia end
their vacation, one (Joaquin Phoenix) decides to remain in the
country. Unbeknownst to his pals, he is arrested, thrown in prison
and sentenced to death for possessing a brick of hashish, which the
three of them had bought.
</P>
<P>
   The only way he can avoid execution is if his two friends, now
back in New York, return to Malaysia, surrender to the authorities,
assume their share of the blame and spend a minimum of three years
each in a hideous Malaysian prison.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Heche is the lawyer who appeals to their consciences and
becomes romantically involved with the feistier of the two friends
(Vince Vaughn). Very well acted and suspenseful, the movie's
examination of the limits of friendship and heroic self-sacrifice
are deep enough to make you seriously question how you would behave
in similar circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie's romantic element and its overwrought subplot,
involving a pushy journalist tracking down the story, are
thoroughly bogus. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `A Merry War'
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bierman's adaptation of a 1936 novel by George Orwell
wittily skewers the London literary world of the mid-1930s. Richard
E. Grant is a poet who the moment his first book is published (and
is favorably reviewed in The London Times by his wealthy and
cynical publisher) quits his job in advertising to be ``free.''
</P>
<P>
   Barely supporting himself with jobs in dingy book shops, he
sinks into poverty, to the exasperation of his long-suffering
girlfriend (Helena Bonham Carter).
</P>
<P>
   The movie presents an amusingly scathing portrait of the young
poet as a self-destructive narcissist (a $50 check from an American
publication gives him disastrous delusions of upper-class grandeur)
and of the inability of someone born into the middle class to
escape a middle-class life no matter how hard he strains to attain
a bohemian sainthood. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Next Stop Wonderland'
</P>
<P>
   Hope Davis gives a wonderfully complex portrait of an
attractive, introverted night-shift nurse making the dating rounds
in contemporary Boston. The movie switches back and forth between
Ms. Davis and Alan Gelfant, who plays the man she was meant for (a
plumber aspiring to be a marine biologist), going about their daily
affairs and nearly colliding on several occasions but never
connecting.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the movie special is its smart, snappy dialogue
(interwoven with a moody bossa nova score) and a group of funny,
acutely observed minor characters (including an assortment of men
Ms. Davis meets through a personal ad). It captures the texture of
urban single life more richly than any other recent film. But its
ending feels tacked on. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Western'
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to what its title suggests, this quirky, endearing
French road movie directed by Manuel Poirier has nothing to do with
the American Wild West. A Catalan shoe salesman, stranded on the
road after his car has been stolen by a Russian thief, is rescued
by a woman with whom he ends up having a brief, but intense affair.
Accidentally running into the thief, he beats him up, sending him
to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   An unlikely friendship develops between the two, and when the
salesman's new sweetheart asks him to leave for a three-week trial
separation to test their love, the two men team up and hit the road
for a series of adventures that take them to the coast of Brittany.
</P>
<P>
   Since the wiry love-starved thief can't seem to meet girls, the
two begin posing as poll takers conducting a door-to-door survey
asking French women to describe their ideal man. The movie suggests
a much sweeter and wackier 90s version of Bertrand Blier's 70s
classic, ``Going Places.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `The Eel'
</P>
<P>
   In this quirky, symbol-laden Japanese drama, a husband, informed
by an anonymous letter that his wife is having an affair, catches
her in bed with her lover and stabs her to death in a jealous rage.
Released from prison after eight years, he begins a new life as a
barber.
</P>
<P>
   With him he takes a pet eel he raised in prison and which is his
sole confidante. One day near his shop, he stumbles upon the nearly
dead body of a woman who has attempted suicide. He saves her life,
and she becomes his assistant in the shop. But when the jealous
lover who drove her to attempt suicide visits the shop in search of
her, the barber's stable new life and his parole are imperiled.
</P>
<P>
   The serious comedy about passion, violence and the possibility
of redemption is peopled with oddball characters and surreal
touches that give the story an allegorical weight. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `The Thief'
</P>
<P>
   It is 1952 in the Soviet Union, and a beautiful young woman
(Yekaterina Rednikova) and her 6-year-old son (Misha Philipchuk)
are riding on a train. When a handsome army officer makes a play
for the woman, she succumbs, and the three set up house together in
a crowded apartment.
</P>
<P>
   But the army officer isn't what he appears. He's really a
professional burglar and liar (he tells the little boy he's
Stalin's son) who befriends the neighbors, steals their possessions
and skips town.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian film, directed by Pavel Chukhrai, focuses on the
relationship between the boy and the thief, who teaches the child
to fight, lie, steal and be tough. Until their final meeting many
years later, the child grows up revering this charismatic bad
influence (beautifully played by Vladimir Mashkov) as a father.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``The Thief'' can be shamelessly tearjerking, it has an
open-hearted Russian soulfulness that is hard to resist. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `The Chambermaid on the Titanic'
</P>
<P>
   Second only to our need for food and water is our hunger for
stories that can help us make sense of our lives and give our
experiences a romantically ennobling narrative shape. That's the
message of Bigas Luna's film (adapted from a novel by Didier
Decoin) about a poor French foundry worker (Olivier Martinez) who
wins an athletic contest that takes him to England to witness the
maiden voyage of the Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   While in England, he shares hotel quarters with a beautiful,
enigmatic woman who claims to be a chambermaid on the ship but who
has no place to stay. When he returns to France, his friends
pressure him to disclose the details of their night together. He
obliges by inventing a story of a night of grand passion with the
doomed woman that is so spellbinding it carries him from the
foundry to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is directed in a hazy, soft-core style that doesn't
quite gibe with its comic point of view. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `The Governess'
</P>
<P>
   Minnie Driver stars in this tale of a Sephardic Jewish woman
from London who in the early 1840s poses as a Gentile to take a job
as governess to a family on a remote Scottish island. Although the
ruse succeeds, the governess finds herself spiritually alienated
and secretly practices Jewish rituals.
</P>
<P>
   The gulf between the two cultures becomes more acute when she
falls in love with the head of the household (Tom Wilkinson), a
gentleman scientist whom she helps invent photography.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Sandra Goldbacher, this visually ravishing film
reaches a peak of beauty and thoughtfulness in its photography
sequences. But it is marred by a screenplay whose use of
contemporary slang can be jarringly untrue to the period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 1638EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7560 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NARWHAL-BOOK-REVIEW-N     09-03 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NARWHAL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VOYAGE OF THE NARWHAL': TERROR, GUILT, AMBITION IN ICY HEART OF
DARKNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With ``The Voyage of the Narwhal,'' Andrea Barrett _ the winner
of the 1996 National Book Award for ``Ship Fever and Other
Stories'' _ has given us an old-fashioned 19th-century novel that
brings together the two abiding concerns in her work to date: the
mysterious allure of science and the equally mysterious bonds of
familial love and resentment.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Ship Fever,'' ``Narwhal'' showcases Ms. Barrett's gifts
for extracting high drama from the complex world of science and
natural history and for placing her characters in situations that
reveal their fundamental natures. Indeed, ``Narwhal'' is an
adventure story in the way that Conrad's ``Lord Jim'' and ``The
Nigger of the Narcissus'' are adventure stories: the story's
extreme conditions and harrowing experiences, which make for such
gripping reading, are actually moral and spiritual tests that strip
away the characters' public masks and expose their innermost drives
and fears.
</P>
<P>
   On its simplest level, ``Narwhal'' is the story of a fictional
1855 expedition to the Arctic to look for a missing explorer who
disappeared a decade before, an expedition that will cost the lives
of several men and warp the lives of others with memories of guilt
and anger and horror. On another level, it is a story of scientific
hubris and sheer pig-headed ambition, a story meant, in some ways,
to recall such disparate works as Mary Shelley's ``Frankenstein''
and Melville's ``Moby-Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   Does the immensely talented Ms. Barrett succeed in fulfilling
her own large ambitions? The answer is: up to a point. For
three-quarters of her tale, she does a masterful job of weaving her
philosophical subtext into a glistening narrative, crammed full of
rich, pictorial description and tingling suspense. Only in the
novel's final pages does drama give way to melodramatic contrivance
and genuine moral dilemmas to easy, sentimental resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of ``Narwhal'' are two compelling heroes: Erasmus
Wells, a middle-aged naturalist who hopes to use the voyage of the
Narwhal to vindicate himself, to erase his bitter experience of an
earlier journey to the Arctic; and Zechariah Voorhees, Erasmus'
brother-in-law-to-be, who hopes to win glory and fame as commander
of the Narwhal expedition.
</P>
<P>
   The two men could not be more different. Erasmus is shy,
cautious and introspective; Zeke is charismatic, cocky and
impulsive. Erasmus, still mourning the death of the woman he loved,
sees himself as an unconfidant loner; Zeke, certain of the devotion
of Lavinia (Erasmus' sister), comes across as a charming rake.
Before leaving home, Erasmus promises Lavinia that he will keep an
eye on the impetuous Zeke, and make sure that he returns home
safely.
</P>
<P>
   In narrating the long, hazardous journey of the Narwhal (from
Philadelphia to Greenland to the perilous waters near the pole) and
the crew's subsequent travels through the snow and ice, Ms. Barrett
does a superb job of conjuring up the hermetic life on board a
ship, and the magic and terror of the Arctic. Combining a
naturalist's eye with a novelist's imagination, she gives us
descriptions of the polar region reminiscent at once of the
real-life wonders chronicled by Barry Lopez in ``Arctic Dreams''
and the metaphysical landscape of Poe's ``Narrative of A. Gordon
Pym.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Ms. Barrett nimbly sketches in the
personalities of the Narwhal's crew. Besides Erasmus and Zeke,
there are Captain Tyler, a foul-tempered, heavy drinking bully who
resents Zeke's authority; Ned Kynd, the ship's youthful cook, a
cheerful, hardworking man who fled the Irish famine for a new life
in the States; Jan Boerhaave, a doctor and naturalist who shares
Erasmus' passion for knowledge, and an assortment of other officers
and seamen.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Narwhal has reached the polar waters, made
hazardous by icebergs and shifting pack ice, there are portents of
yet more trouble to come. The sled dogs have died of a mysterious
illness, and one of the sailors has succumbed to lockjaw. The crew
has split into factions, and Zeke has grown increasingly moody and
autocratic. It seems that he is not content with the information he
has collected from the local Eskimos about the missing explorer; he
is determined to push ahead, even as winter closes in, to try to
discover what he believes is an open (that is, ice-free) polar sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my NAME on something,'' he tells Erasmus. ``Something
BIG _ is that so hard to understand? I want my name on the map.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeke's ambition has terrible costs: it leads to at least one
more death and causes incalculable suffering to the remainder of
his crew. Caught in the freezing water and hemmed in by ice on all
sides, the Narwhal is unable to return home, and the men are forced
to spend an entire winter in the arctic with dwindling supplies of
food.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, when Zeke leaves on foot to look for his polar sea
and fails to return, Erasmus is faced with making a fateful
decision: to wait for Zeke and thereby face the prospect of making
the crew spend a second (and no doubt deadly) winter in the Arctic,
or assume that Zeke is dead and try to take advantage of the
opportunity afforded by the summer thaw to try to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, Erasmus' decision will have lasting
consequences, not only for Zeke but for Lavinia and for himself.
Indeed, he will be haunted by his decision, much as Lord Jim was
haunted by his, for the remainder of his life.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few sections of ``Narwhal,'' Ms. Barrett's fluent
plotting gives way to a flurry of increasingly contrived events
that seem to belong more to a big Hollywood movie than to the
foregoing portions of this novel.
</P>
<P>
   Although these developments make ``Narwhal'' feel like a
slighter, slicker work than it means to be, they do not tarnish Ms.
Barrett's very real achievements: her ability to convey to the
reader her psychological insights into her characters, her
understanding of the fickle role that chance and luck play in
people's lives, and her appreciation of the raw, unaccommodated
power of nature. She has written a powerful and gripping _ if
finally, flawed _ novel.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE VOYAGE OF THE NARWHAL'
</P>
<P>
   By Andrea Barrett
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 399 pages. W.W. Norton &AMP; Co. $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
