<HEADER>
A7569 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NFL-MATCHUPS-ART-(2TA     09-03 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-MATCHUPS-ART-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS FOR WEEK  1
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (JT)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY 1 P.M. GAMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Falcons at Panthers
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: Atlanta Coach Dan Reeves is 0-3 against Carolina
Coach Dom Capers.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: Many are picking the Falcons to make the playoffs this
season. If they are going to, this is a game they need to win.
True, saying the first game of the season is a big one is a tad bit
overdramatic but the Falcons got off to a poor start last season
and a repeat would kill any postseason hopes. They will look to
quarterback Chris Chandler to lead them to postseason, he of the
90.6 passer rating in September over the past five years. Capers
wants to see two things: That his defense and quarterback Kerry
Collins get back to their old selves. Not yet, Dom. Falcons, 22-10.
</P>
<P>
   Lions at Packers
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: With 100 yards rushing, Barry Sanders can extend his
league-record streak to 14 consecutive 100-yard games. Sanders
needs just 222 rushing yards this season to join Walter Payton as
the only players with 14,000 career rushing yards.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: Very quietly, Packers quarterback Brett Favre has had
a strong preseason. He is just picking up where the team left off.
Green Bay finished last year with the conference's No. 1 pass
offense (231 yards a game) and Favre's 89.3 career passer rating is
one of the best in the league. The Pack will be back, probably in
the conference title game. The Lions, meanwhile, are back to where
they have always been: relying on Sanders and crossing their
fingers that this will be the year quarterback Scott Mitchell comes
out of his coma. They'll keep waiting. And waiting. And waiting.
And waiting. Packers, 28-21.
</P>
<P>
   Jaguars at Bears
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: Bears were 0-4 in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: Last season the Jaguars scored a league-high 300
points on 63 trips into the redzone. That offense could be even
better this year. The Jaguars have more depth and the defense is
Super Bowl caliber. They look like champions already. Then there
are the Bears, nothing but bad news. They've won 12 of the past 14
openers and if they win eight games this year, Coach Dave Wannstedt
should be named coach of the decade. Jaguars, 27-0.
</P>
<P>
   Saints at Rams
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: Saints open on the road for only the seventh time in
32-year team history.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: The battle of the old coaches. Dick Vermeil, though,
is 7-0 lifetime against Mike Ditka. The former Bears coach may have
lost control of his team, with players being hazed by other players
like they're pledging a fraternity, but they play hard for him. As
for Vermeil, this could be a solid season. His quarterback, Tony
Banks, has dedicated himself more than ever, wide receiver Isaac
Bruce is back from a knee injury and tackle Orlando Pace is slimmer
and meaner. After Ditka loses this opener, maybe the players will
haze him. Rams, 14-6.
</P>
<P>
   Steelers at Ravens
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: The Ravens open at their new 68,400-seat stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: Pittsburgh has won the last four division titles, but
there may be a new sheriff in town and it is the Ravens. They could
end up being one of the surprise teams in the league. The Steelers
are good but Baltimore now has enough offensive and defensive
firepower to keep up with each team in the division. Watch
cornerback Rod Woodson, now with the Ravens and formerly with
Pittsburgh. He is looking to prove that the Steelers made a mistake
in releasing him, which is good for at least one interception.
Ravens, 28-21.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks at Eagles
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: Seattle's 247.4 yards passing a game was best in the
NFL last year.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: Because of poor drafting and almost nonexistent
spending on free agents the Eagles find themselves in the middle of
a talent drought. The Seahawks, meanwhile, are swimming in good
players, especially offensively with Warren Moon at quarterback and
former Eagle Ricky Watters at running back. Seattle should win this
game without breathing hard. Seahawks, 21-0.
</P>
<P>
   Buccaneers at Vikings
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: The Buccaneers are going for back-to-back playoff
years for the first time since the 1981-82 season.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: Tampa Bay has a great coach, a great running game and
a solid defense, all the ingredients to make another strong playoff
run. But can they make a super run with average quarterback Trent
Dilfer at the helm? The answer is no and it is the same reason why
they will lose to Minnesota. The Vikings have everything the
Buccaneers do but quarterback Brad Johnson has a 94.5 passer rating
in September and is healthy. He's the difference. Vikings, 35-20.
</P>
<P>
   Oilers at Bengals
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: Tennessee guard Bruce Matthews makes his 166th
straight start, the NFL's longest active streak.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: With the steady Neil O'Donnell at the helm and a solid
running game behind him in back Corey Dillon, the Bengals will do
some damage offensively. But these are two closely matched teams.
Wide receiver Yancy Thigpen gives Tennessee some much needed deep
help and he'll be the difference. Oilers, 17-14.
</P>
<P>
   Redskins at Giants
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: In 1997 the Giants were the first ever NFC East team
to go undefeated in the division with a 7-0-1 record.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: The last time the Giants and Redskins met was last
December, when New York's defense recorded eight turnovers,
including a 35-yard interception return by cornerback Jason Sehorn.
Of course, Sehorn is out for the season with torn ligaments in his
knee but the Giants' defense is still one of the best in the
league. The Redskins have a solid running game and good receivers
but with Gus Frerotte at quarterback the Redskins can only go so
far. The Giants' secret weapons are Coach Jim Fassel and defensive
coordinator Jim Fox. They always seem to find ways to cover up
weaknesses. Giants, 20-13.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SUNDAY 4 P.M. GAMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals at Cowboys
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: Cowboys have won 14 of past 15 games against
Cardinals
</P>
<P>
   Comments: The common thought is that the Cowboys have taken a
step back and the Cardinals two forward. True, Arizona quarterback
Jake Plummer is hot, finishing preseason with a 105.1 passer
rating, but the Cowboys, winless in preseason, will make one last
run. It may be a run to mediocrity but it won't be to the basement.
They'll kick off the season with a big win over a club they always
seem to dominate. Cowboys, 17-0.
</P>
<P>
   Bills at Chargers
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: Bills are 24-7 in September in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: The chest thumping you've heard for the last month is
Chargers quarterback Ryan Leaf after he's zipped a touchdown pass
or thrown for a first down. He has been brilliant in preseason and
at times has been so cocky he looks like a five-year veteran. The
Bills spent a first round pick in prying Rob Johnson away from the
Jaguars and he looks like he's worth it. This game should feature
some solid quarterback play. The Chargers get the edge because
they're at home. Chargers, 21-14.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins at Colts
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: Team is 17-3 under Coach Jimmy Johnson when a runner
has 25 or more carries.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: Quarterback Peyton Manning, at 22 years, 5 months and
13 days, is the seventh youngest starting quarterback in NFL
history. Guess who is before him at 22 years and 4 months? His
father, Archie. Thus Peyton begins the trek of following in his
father's footsteps and like his father's early years in New
Orleans, baby Peyton's will be rough. His offensive line isn't very
good and he opens with a hungry Miami team. Where's dad when you
need him? Dolphins, 30-10.
</P>
<P>
   Jets at 49ers
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: Jets' 8-win turnaround, from 1-15 to 9-7 last season,
is tied for third-best in league history.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: For this game Jets Coach Bill Parcells is basically
playing with house money. If he wins, he is seen as a genius for
going to the 49ers home turf and beating them. If he loses, no one
expects him to win, anyway. This might be a game he can steal. As
great an athlete as wide receiver Jerry Rice is, he is still coming
off a devastating knee injury. He won't be 100 percent and the
49ers without Rice just aren't the same team. Jets, 21-20.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY NIGHT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Raiders at Chiefs
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: Chiefs are 7-1 in last 8 openers.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: The Raiders seem to be back on track with young rookie
head coach Jon Gruden in control. Their practices have been sharper
and the defense, much maligned in recent years, is stronger with
the addition of cornerback Charles Woodson. The Chiefs are dominant
in the regular season and since they hate the Raiders, this will be
a spirited game, won by the Chiefs. Chiefs, 31-21.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONDAY NIGHT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Patriots at Broncos
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: First all-AFC Monday Night Football season-opener
since 1981 when San Diego played Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: It's always gloom and doom with the Patriots. They
don't have a running game. Their defense isn't tough enough. Blah,
blah, blah. But quarterback Drew Bledsoe is what makes the team go.
The Patriots will find some way to run the ball and their defense
is better than it has been in years. Look for New England tight end
Ben Coates to have a big game and the defending Super Bowl
champions to get an early season shock at home. Patriots, 17-14.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
