<HEADER>
A7581 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-03 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ENDURING ATTRACTION OF EGYPT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Egyptian Revival style has been rearing its
sphinxlike head for more than 2,000 years. And, like the sphinx, it
maintains a mysterious allure.
</P>
<P>
   The style was in fashion during the reigns of Emperor Hadrian,
Louis XVI, Napoleon and the English Regent, as well as during the
British Esthetic Movement in the 1870s and the Art Deco period in
the 1920s. And it seems to be transfixing us today.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian Revival pieces are some of the standouts in the
Christie's sale of French and Continental furniture on Sept. 24 in
New York. Christie's is auctioning an elegant circa 1785 Italian
neoclassical settee whose sides are flanked by Egyptian female
caryatids with golden Egyptian wigs. Two matching chairs have
armrests on charming, sleepy, sphinxlike lions. The estimate for
the suite is $30,000 to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's is also selling a circa 1800 Italian neoclassical
console (estimate: $40,000 to $60,000), whose frieze is supported
by two gilded Egyptian male statues.
</P>
<P>
   Will Strafford, the vice president for European furniture at
Christie's, said the figure is Antinous, Emperor Hadrian's favorite
companion. Antinous drowned in the Nile on a visit to Egypt with
Hadrian. The bereft Hadrian gave him a demigod's burial in Rome,
then built an Egyptian pavilion to display his Egyptian sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   The uprights on Christie's table are derived from the antique
sculpture of Antinous rediscovered at Hadrian's villa in Rome in
1740, Strafford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the fascination for Egyptian style is that it is so
otherworldly,'' Strafford said. ``It has a lot to do with the
afterworld and obsession with death,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that the Romans often appropriated the Antinous
image in the 18th century, as seen in the Egyptian Salon in the
Palazzo Massimo and the Egyptian Hall in the Villa Borghesi. Even
Piranesi published Egyptian decorative schemes, in 1769 in his
``Diversi Manieri de Ornare i Cammini.''
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's sale of 19th-century furniture on Oct. 28 features
later Egyptian Revival pieces: a pair of French chenets (fire dogs)
with sphinx heads, circa 1880 (estimate: $3,000 to $5,000), and two
chairs with bone and wood inlays whose low backs are in the form of
birds (estimate: $8,000 to $12,000 each).
</P>
<P>
   There are also some small circular side tables decorated with
hieroglyphs (estimate: $4,000 to $6,000 apiece).
</P>
<P>
   ``They are literally covered from top to bottom,'' said Elaine
Whitmire, head of 19th-century furniture at Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that Egyptian Revival's time has come again.
</P>
<P>
   The New York architect Peter Marino has designed an
American-style Egyptian Revival apartment in New York for Pierre
Berge, the French fashion titan. Marino said the first revival of
the style goes back to the first century B.C., when the Romans took
control of the Nile. ``The Romans wanted their empire to last as
long as the Egyptians' dynasties, so they borrowed their symbols,''
Marino explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our modern lives, we want a connection to the most ancient
things we can think of,'' he said. ``Egyptian style is enduring,
and we all want our work to endure.''
</P>
<P>
   Ariane Dandois, a Paris antiques dealer now in her 25th year in
business, is selling several Egyptian Revival antiques at the Paris
Biennale des Antiquaires, from Sept. 18 to Oct. 4. In her booth she
will have a pair of Empire-style Spanish mahogany and gilt wood
armchairs, circa 1820, with padded backs and seats flanked by
crouching winged sphinxes.
</P>
<P>
   The sphinxes are not unlike models designed by Percier and
Fontaine, the great Empire-style decorators who did so much work
for Napoleon at Fontainebleau and Malmaison.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dandois says she thinks the chairs, one of which is banded
with the initials CMF, were made for a royal palace in Spain during
the reign of Ferdinand VII, 1813-1833. His wife was Marie-Christine
de Bourbon, and Ms. Dandois speculates that CMF may be her
monogram. She is selling the chairs for 950,000 francs, about
$190,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Egyptian taste has been in demand since Europeans discovered
the first temples in the sand,'' Ms. Dandois said. She noted that
Napoleon took mathematicians, engineers and astronomers, along with
54,000 soldiers, on his Egyptian Campaign of 1798. Within months he
founded the Institut d'Egypte there, to study Egyptian
civilization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interest in Egypt goes beyond wars and power,'' she said.
``For a culture to have so great an influence, it has to appeal to
scientists, artists, writers and architects. It's so totally
intellectual. After Napoleon, everyone started to be interested and
reinvented Egyptian style according to the discipline of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dandois is selling a circa 1800 clock in the shape of an
obelisk that rests on four crouching lions. The case is attributed
to Ferdinand Schwerdfeger, one of Marie-Antoinette's favorite
cabinetmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dandois said she thought the clock was probably made by
Jean-Baptiste Thiery, who did an obelisk model in marble that is
now in the Louvre. The lions, Ms. Dandois said, were inspired by
the Egyptian lion statues at the base of the staircase at the
Capitoline Hill in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, at least three antiques dealers are now showing
Egyptian Revival pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Newel Art Galleries has several late-19th-century British
examples, including an etagere incised with Egyptian motifs
($12,500), a gilt and polychrome throne chair with Egyptian figures
($15,000) and an Art Deco love seat with bronze caryatid armrests
by Jean Pascaud ($21,000).
</P>
<P>
   Florian Papp Antiques has several Egyptian Revival pieces in
stock, including an unusual Italian mirror, circa 1810, that is
surmounted by coiled snakes and has Egyptian figures with carved
and gilded heads and feet ($28,000).
</P>
<P>
   Two Regency pieces are elegantly embellished with Egyptian
pilasters: an open bookshelf ($18,500) and a chiffonier with glass
doors ($36,000).
</P>
<P>
   Roger Prigent, the owner of Malmaison Antiques, is a longtime
aficionado of the style. He is selling a pair of mahogany bergeres
signed Jacob Freres, circa 1803, with armrests in the form of
Egyptian female heads ($20,000 each), and a gilded bronze lamp that
has two kneeling Egyptian women ($25,000).
</P>
<P>
   ``They are wearing the Cleopatra wig, just like Elizabeth
Taylor,'' Prigent said.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian Revival style is as enduring as Cleopatra. ``The
mystery of Egypt lives,'' said Madeleine Deschamps, the author of
one of the best books on the subject, ``Empire'' (Abbeville, 1994).
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the French artists Patrick and Anne Poirier created an
eight-foot-long biscuit porcelain centerpiece for Sevres that was
probably inspired by the style of Luxor, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Egyptian art didn't change for 2,000 years; the shapes are
both austere and eternal,'' she said. The Poiriers' temple will be
on view at the American Craft Museum in New York in January.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptomania rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
