A7585 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEANUT-FREE-ZONES-TEX     09-03 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEANUT-FREE-ZONES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. PEANUT MAY BE GETTING RUDE RECEPTION ON AIRLINES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LAURA VOZZELLA 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ Mr. Peanut cuts a first-class figure with his top
hat, monocle and cane, but he could be banished to the back of the
plane.
</P>
<P>
   Out of concern for airline passengers with severe peanut
allergies, federal transportation authorities have ordered airlines
to create ``peanut-free buffer zones'' on their flights.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department order, issued two weeks ago and
already in effect, cited the Air Carrier Access Act, which
prohibits discrimination against disabled passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines must not serve peanuts in an allergic passenger's row
or in the rows immediately in front of and behind him, the
Transportation Department states in a letter sent to the nation's
10 largest carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that providing such a buffer zone is an adequate
modification to a carrier's normal in-flight food service and a
reasonable accommodation for the disability,'' the letter states.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the snack had a few salty words on the subject, and one
industry group _ the Peanut and Tree Nut Processors Association in
Potomac, Md. _ said it has already rallied the Washington legume
lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more meddling and more loss of freedom of choice,'' said
Jack Darrett, mayor of the southeast-central Oklahoma town of
Holdenville, which billed itself as the Peanut Capital of the World
until private prisons and pork outpaced peanuts as its main
industry in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   There was some applause from the peanut gallery.
</P>
<P>
   The measure is potentially life-saving for the estimated 1
million to 2 million Americans who suffer from peanut allergies,
said Anne Munoz-Furlong, founder of Food Allergy Network in
Fairfax, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Although most allergic people have to eat a peanut to have a
reaction, inhaling the airborne protein can be enough to affect
some, she said. That is especially true in an airplane, where
quarters are close, the air is recirculated and hundreds of people
are ripping open pressurized peanut packs at more or less the same
time, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been reports in classrooms of children having
reactions to another kid having a peanut butter sandwich,'' said
Dr. Wesley Burks, a pediatric allergist in Little Rock who has
researched peanut allergies for about 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Burks called the order ``a reasonable guideline.''
</P>
<P>
   But the same measures do not need to be taken for other foods
that people are allergic to, such as milk or eggs, because those do
not cause airborne reactions, said Dr. Moonhee Lee, an area
allergist.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines are not complaining, at least publicly. Fort
Worth-based American Airlines wasn't saying much of anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rarely serve peanuts on our flights. We really don't have
any other comment since we don't serve them that often,'' said a
woman in the airline's corporate communications office, who
declined to give her name.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas-based Southwest Airlines was handling the snack snag with
panache worthy of Mr. Peanut himself, despite the budget carrier's
special link with the legume. Southwest ads have pictured peanuts
and stated: ``This is what our snacks look like. It's also what our
fares look like.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to a passenger request, Southwest started banning
peanuts last year on any flight carrying an allergic passenger,
said Ginger Hardage, a spokeswoman. Passengers on those flights get
raisins instead.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest opted against restricting peanuts in seats around
allergic passengers because they could feel singled out, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that guy in Row 12, that's why'' you can't have peanuts,
Hardage said with a laugh. ``We would never do that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the carrier still gets across its message of peanut pride.
Even on peanut-free flights, crews have handed out the nuts as
passengers deplane.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of our culture,'' Hardage said. ``You can have your
peanuts to go.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
