<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7593 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-GORBY-RUSSIAN-AGO     09-03 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-GORBY-RUSSIAN-AGONY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THE CRISIS WORSENS, RUSSIA NEEDS A GOVERNMENT OF NATIONAL
SALVATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Mikhail Gorbachev's world
affairs column. To publish as a ``separate buy'' article, please
contact one of these New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The presidents of the United States and Russia, who recently met
in Moscow, are both in trouble. Some have called their meeting a
lame-duck summit.
 &HT;    Nevertheless, I believe the decision to meet was a sign of
responsibility. Dialogue must not be broken off, particularly at
such a difficult time.
 &HT;    Too bad the summit produced no tangible results. But the reason
for this failure is all too clear: Each man is politically weakened
because neither was able to engage in the kind of serious
self-criticism that was necessary.
 &HT;    It is also clear that both presidents bear a lot of
responsibility for Russia's plight. The West, and Bill Clinton in
particular, liked the Russian president, who had put an end to
communism and the USSR.
 &HT;    Yeltsin, in exchange for his reforms, expected mountains of gold
_ and, of course, ironclad political support. The West and Clinton
spoke of their support for democratic reforms and market
transition. In reality, as we now see, the democratic character of
those reforms was doubtful at best, and the so-called free market
has degenerated into a paper pyramid.
 &HT;    I doubt that no one was aware of this. Some in the West may have
hoped to benefit from a downwardly spiraling Russia in some way.
They now see that Russia does not suffer in isolation: Stock
exchanges throughout the world have taken some bad hits _ in part,
no one disputes, because of the Russian crisis.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, many Westerners, both those who have gained and those
who have lost, are ready to pack their bags and leave Russia. They
think that Russia cannot be trusted.
 &HT;    Well, they had better look in the mirror and think again. After
all, it was they who thought Russia could be treated like a
streetwalker. True, they were encouraged to do so by the Russian
leaders themselves, who took the country through ``shock therapy.''
 &HT;    Others, apparently including President Clinton, believe that
Russia should not now be abandoned to face its troubles alone. This
is wise, although the realization came too late, after years of
pushing Russia down the path that has taken it to the brink of the
abyss.
 &HT;    Many are afraid that Russia could collapse into chaos. This fear
is not without reason. But it is essential to understand that
cooperation with Russia is in the best interests of the West.
 &HT;    Sooner or later _ I would say, sooner _ Russia will have a new
leadership that will not meekly accept prescriptions from others
and will have to be treated with respect. It will take decisions
consistent with Russia's national interests, which does not,
however, mean it will choose to ignore the ``rules of the global
market'' or tear up its obligations.
 &HT;    Remember that the Gorbachevs, Clintons, Yeltsins and others come
and go while the people of Russia, America, France, Italy, Mexico
and other nations remain, with their own history, traditions, and
all their merits and drawbacks.
 &HT;    I do understand that today it might seem odd to speak of
relations of equality with Russia, torn as it is by the economic
and moral crisis. But the past seven years have demonstrated that
America's biggest mistake would be to try to exploit its position
now as the only superpower. Fortunately for everyone, including
Americans, the coming century will not be an ``American century.''
 &HT;    The situation is at a breaking point; it can't go on like this.
For the second time in six years the Russians' incomes have been
cut in half. A chasm is widening between the small group of ruling
oligarchs and the people, who no longer trust anyone _ certainly
not the president, not his candidate for prime minister, Viktor
Chernomyrdin; nor does the Duma have much credibility.
 &HT;    This is a political crisis: the collapse, the agony of the
ruling regime. No behind-the-scenes dealings, no attempt to mend
matters through some intrigue, can succeed. Neither the bankrupt
politicians nor the tired, out-of-touch president can now save us.
 &HT;    I insist that the only way out is through simultaneous early
elections of the president and the Duma, coupled with a referendum
to amend the Constitution in order to reallocate powers between the
branches of federal government. Yeltsin's voluntary resignation
would open the way to a compromise allowing the formation of a
government of national salvation, capable of coping with the
emergency.
 &HT;    The choice is now stark. If early elections are not held, the
crisis will be resolved by street protests. Even setting the date
for elections would calm people, who would see in it the prospect
to express their will by civilized means.
 &HT;    The alternative to a peaceful course of events is chaos. I hope
the president understands that and is aware of the danger
confronting us all. His era is over, but he has a great chance to
go down in history by moving quickly to call early elections. The
longer he and his entourage cling to power, the greater will be the
danger of the country sliding into total chaos.
 &HT;    Commentators are saying that Russia lacks the caliber of people
who would be capable of restoring order without destroying
democracy or retreating from reforms. That is false. A ``new
center'' that rejects both orthodox communism and radical economic
liberalism does exist.
 &HT;    Its leaders, such as Yuri Luzhkov, Yegor Stroyev, Gregory
Yavlinski and some regional governors, enjoy a lot of public
support _ not in the shape of what would be a Western-style middle
class, but still an impressive array of social forces capable of
winning the elections.
 &HT;    The bodies of federal government formed by this new centrist
front, with the trust and support of the people, could lead Russia
out of our deteriorating crisis.
 &HT;     c.1998 La Stampa  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Mikhail Gorbachev, the last leader of the Soviet Union before
its collapse in 1991 and Nobel Peace Prize winner, now heads the
Gorbachev Foundation, a political think tank in Moscow, with a new
office at Northeastern University, in Boston. He also writes a
monthly commentary column for La Stampa, a newspaper in Turin,
Italy.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
