<HEADER>
A7609 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAGAMORE-HILL-ART-4TA     09-03 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAGAMORE-HILL-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TR'S SAGAMORE HILL: ROUGH RIDER, EASY LIVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MIMI SHERATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The house I would most love to go home to is Sagamore Hill. As
an ardent visitor to museum-houses that offer glimpses of the
personal daily lives of their revered occupants, I feel that
Theodore Roosevelt's beloved estate in Oyster Bay on New York's
Long Island, more than any other, seems the perfect home in which
to have grown up.
</P>
<P>
   This rambling brick, stone and wood house close to Long Island
Sound is a storybook set piece of eaved attic aeries, bay windows,
rainbow glints of stained glass, and surprise rooms whimsically
tucked into unexpected corners across three floors. A child could
feel luxuriously lost and unobserved in one of those rooms yet
totally secure, with instant companionship or genuine help within
easy shouting distance.
</P>
<P>
   Set on a hilltop and completed in 1885, TR's favorite home, the
summer White House from 1902 to 1909, feels not only nurturing and
comfortable but also vaguely mysterious, what with its miles of
books, dark wood paneling, massive furniture and the hundreds of
exotic artifacts collected by a staunch family man who was a
politician, a rancher, a reader and writer; a naturalist and a
conservationist yet also a big-game hunter; a Nobel Prize-winning
peacemaker and a soldier.
</P>
<P>
   It was because of Colonel Roosevelt's role as an organizer of
the Rough Riders cavalry unit during the Spanish-American War in
1898 that I was reminded of Sagamore Hill. The 100th anniversary of
that conflict has been commemorated by several exhibitions this
year, including two on the Rough Riders in Montauk, where 28,000
U.S. troops were quarantined on their return from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   After roughly an hour-and-a-quarter drive from Manhattan to the
estate, my husband and I found it refreshing to walk the winding
path to the front door of the house, past rolling lawns and a
windmill that provided power when this was a working farm, taking
seriously the Roosevelt family motto, ``Qui plantauit curabit.''
(``He who plants, preserves.'') There are majestic shade trees that
include red-blossoming chestnuts and a monumental copper beech at
the house entrance, planted about 1894, perhaps under the eye of TR
himself.
</P>
<P>
   With 90,000 visitors to the estate each year, the National Park
Service has developed hourly tours conducted by well-trained
guides. We had the pleasure of a private tour with Amy Verone, the
amiable and impeccably informed curator. In addition, having reread
portions of ``Theodore Roosevelt: An Autobiography,'' I felt as
though he were whispering hints about his favorite spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love all the seasons,'' he wrote, ``the snows and bare
woods of winter; the rush of growing things and the blossom-spray
of spring; the yellow grain, the ripening fruits and tasseled corn,
and the deep leafy shades that are heralded by the `green dance of
summer'; and the sharp fall winds that tear the brilliant banners
with which the trees greet the dying year. . . . We have great
fireplaces, and in them, the logs roar and crackle during the long
winter evenings. The big piazza is for the hot, still afternoons of
summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Picturing Roosevelt
</P>
<P>
   It is in summer on that expansive gray porch he called a piazza
that I picture the bombastic Roosevelt, comfortably seated in a
rocker, sipping a cool drink to the sound of low voices, in
conversations with his wife or children or, often in the long,
light evenings, with his staff members and guests. That porch was
also the stage from which TR addressed gathered visitors: foreign
dignitaries, Boy Scouts and, during political campaigns, neighbors
who were potential voters. All would gather on the big lawn that
stretched back to a daisy field, which Ms. Verone said is soon to
be restored. Alas, the former view of the Sound cannot be had, as a
forest of trees obscured it long ago.
</P>
<P>
   To a reader, Sagamore Hill is still a paradise, with about 6,000
of the family's original 9,000 titles safely in residence.
Roosevelt had strong views on books and objected to recommended
reading lists in a way especially pertinent now. ``I have no
sympathy whatever with writing lists of One Hundred Best Books,''
he wrote. ``There is no such thing as a hundred books that are best
for all men, or for the majority of men, or for one man at all
times.''
</P>
<P>
   But as much as books were loved at Sagamore Hill, TR notes that
``children are even better.'' He must have loved children to
contend with not only his own 5, but the 16 cousins who often
visited, including, on occasion, the young Eleanor Roosevelt, who
stayed in a second-floor guest room.
</P>
<P>
   Not the least of Sagamore Hill's attractions is the colorful,
ebullient McKinley era it evokes. That period's style and tone
extended beyond the assassination of President William McKinley in
1901, when, as vice president, Roosevelt took office. He then won
another four-year term in 1905. It was a time of opulent high
living, at least for the rich, and a feast for food lovers. Women
were admired for curvaceous hourglass figures, typified by Lillian
Russell; and the trencherman Diamond Jim Brady reportedly primed
his appetite for dinner with three dozen oysters.
</P>
<P>
   It was a period epitomized by ``Life With Father,'' which opened
in 1939 and was the first Broadway play I saw. Written by Howard
Lindsay and Russel Crouse, its seven-year run remains the longest
for a nonmusical show in Broadway history. It was set in a
Manhattan town house that could have been inspired by the one at 28
E. 20th St., where Theodore Roosevelt was born on Oct. 27, 1858. He
is the only New York City native to become president. The town
house is now also a museum, a faithful 1923 reproduction of the
original 19th-century Roosevelt home filled with ornate furnishings
and bric-a-brac, much like those in the ``Life With Father'' stage
sets.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
