<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAGAMORE-HILL-ART-2ND     09-03 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAGAMORE-HILL-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: stage sets.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Treats and Treasure
</P>
<P>
   No rooms at Sagamore Hill suggest the spirit of good living more
than the big homey kitchen and the inviting dining room in which it
would be fun to cook and then eat a Thanksgiving dinner. Its
wood-paneled pantry holds an iron safe that once protected jewelry,
state papers and the household sugar. With a wood- and coal-burning
stove set into a fireplace opening, the kitchen would send forth
the tantalizing aromas of roasting meats and buttery baking pies.
</P>
<P>
   In the dining room, light from opalescent glass sconces sparkles
against vermilion walls to light the carved wood Florentine table,
sideboard and Dante chairs. I imagine the large family happily and
hungrily wandering in from the cozily lighted entrance foyer, which
was the living room before the house was expanded, or from the
cavernous north room with its beamed ceiling and an entrance arch
formed by two soaring elephant tusks.
</P>
<P>
   This last addition to the house, with its snug alcove study,
holds some of the cherished gifts Roosevelt noted in his
autobiography: a bronze Remington sculpture, ``The Bronco Buster'';
a Tiffany silver vase; a Japanese suit of armor from Admiral Togo,
``a favorite hero.'' There are also rare books, paintings and
prints, and a gruesome collection of animal trophies, including
mounted heads, a rhino-foot inkwell and an elephant-foot
wastebasket.
</P>
<P>
   More cheerful are a mantelpiece, desks and chests of darkly
gleaming Philippine wood sent by Army friends, and, as a gift from
the City of Philadelphia, a copy of the chair George Washington
occupied during the Constitutional Convention. Even more
spectacular is the dark, thronelike governor's chair that Roosevelt
used in Albany and took home with him.
</P>
<P>
   If a well-mannered sherry was served before dinner, it might
have been in the only really feminine and delicate room in the
entire house: the blue-and-white drawing room. (``Is drawing room a
more appropriate name than parlor?'' TR asks in his autobiography.)
</P>
<P>
   This was the preserve of his second wife, the elegantly graceful
Edith Kermit Carow Roosevelt, and is furnished with her family
pieces. No one could enter this room uninvited, with the exception
of pets stopping by for water from the wide blue Delft bowl always
beneath Mrs. Roosevelt's writing table.
</P>
<P>
   Soup to Nuts, in Style
</P>
<P>
   The traditional Sagamore Hill Thanksgiving menu, as recorded in
``The American Heritage Cookbook'' (1964), began with oysters,
celery, olives and radishes; went on to consomme, and then
proceeded to not only turkey with stuffing and giblet gravy but
also roast suckling pig, which was a favorite of Roosevelt and his
eldest daughter, Alice. Garnishes included relishes, four
vegetables and salad. Desserts were mince and pumpkin pies, ice
cream, nuts, fruits and chocolate dragees.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Roosevelt was dubbed a gourmand in a magazine article,
a charge to which he responded, ``When anyone desires to make a
widespread impression that the president and family sit down to a
4- or 5-course breakfast, a 6- or 7-course lunch and a 10-course
dinner, the president feels that a denial is not inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   As innocent as such a presidential denial seems by today's
standards, it did not stop counteraccusations of gluttony. There
were reports that a simple meal for TR might be a whole chicken and
a quart of milk, and that ``chicken and milk were by no means the
only things served,'' while others recalled the president stoking
up as prodigiously as a machine and putting seven lumps of sugar in
the presidential coffee, served in a cup that his son Theodore Jr.
described as ``more in the nature of a bathtub.''
</P>
<P>
   An Unusual Hideaway
</P>
<P>
   What I can also imagine is falling asleep after such meals,
perhaps on the sofa under the sloping ceiling of the attic gun
room, TR's hideaway workplace (he thought it had the loveliest view
in the house and the most books), as the late afternoon sun casts a
deep golden glow over walls and shining gun cases. Or perhaps I'd
nap in the comforting rocker in the hushed library as a fire
sputtered in the low, wide fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   On the walls, etchings and paintings depict William and Henry of
Orange and Erasmus, heroes to Roosevelt, whose ancestors were
Dutch. They also appear to be nodding off, although one wide-awake
stalwart is TR's father, Theodore Roosevelt Sr., whom his son
considered ``the best man I have ever known.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other accomplishments, the senior Roosevelt was the
driving force behind the establishment of the American Museum of
Natural History in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   TR himself might have gone up to the master bedroom, there to
catch 40 winks in his massive bed, whose head- and footboards of
honey-gold bird's-eye maple, hand carved with stylized stars and
sunflowers, look peculiarly Hawaiian, although they were made in
Philadelphia. These was among the treasures Roosevelt took to
Sagamore Hill from his family's home at 6 W. 57th St. in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   It was in a smaller, peaceful bedroom that Theodore Roosevelt
died at 60, on Jan. 6, 1919, a day after saying to his wife, ``I
wonder if you will ever know how I love Sagamore Hill.'' Apparently
Mrs. Roosevelt felt the same way. She lived on in the house for
another 29 years, dying there in 1948 at the age of 87.
</P>
<P>
   A woodsy path leads to the Old Orchard Museum, displaying much
memorabilia, both personal and presidential. It is all well
arranged in the Georgian-style house, built in 1938 as the home of
Gen. Theodore Roosevelt Jr., including the Nobel medal TR was given
for his role as peacemaker in the war between Russia and Japan in
1905, his Rough Rider hat and sword, childhood chocolate pot and
toys, political posters and banners for his Republican and
Bullmoose campaigns, as well as a worn piece of stationery on which
he scribbled his ideas for the Sagamore Hill house.
</P>
<P>
   He originally planned to name the house Leeholm, for his first
wife, Alice Lee. Tragically, she died after giving birth to their
daughter, Alice, in 1884, a year before the house was finished. TR
then decided to honor Sagamore Mohannis, a local Indian chief who
signed away his tribe's rights to the land.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving the parking lot, we browsed through the neat
little bookstore in the gatehouse with its books, pamphlets, games
and souvenirs, which included cuddly stuffed teddy bears, named for
Theodore Roosevelt. Behind the shop is a pleasant picnic area that
made us regret not having brought a modest box lunch.
</P>
<P>
   About a mile down the road from Sagamore Hill is the grave site
of TR and Edith Roosevelt in Young's Memorial Cemetery. It is a
pretty walk up a small hill, past worn, aging headstones, ending at
the gated, leafy grave with its modest markings.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
