<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7614 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GABRIEL-MUSIC-AZR &LR;      09-03 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GABRIEL-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATIN LOVED: FANS WORSHIP `IDOL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACIELA SEVILLA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Frank Sinatra remains the Chairman of the Board.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Springsteen is the Boss.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Latin music world, one man overshadows them both.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gabriel is known as nothing less than ``El Idolo de las
Multitudes'' _ the Idol of the Multitudes _ to legions of fans
spanning North, Central and South America.
</P>
<P>
   How big is his star? ``Gigante''.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel drew 75,000 fans to the Pasadena Rose Bowl for a concert
in 1994, and he's outsold crossover star Gloria Estefan in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   A legendary showman, Gabriel's signature is a Vegas-proportioned
shows backed by an orchestra and mariachi band.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the few artists who injects a great enthusiasm
into the audience. From the first song, they start to dance,'' says
Humberto Preciado, a radio host for Spanish-language KSUN-AM (1400)
in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Just shy of 50, Gabriel maintains the dimpled smile of an aging
cherub and delivers a dramatic, energy-packed show befitting a
Latin legend. Partial to glitz _ rhinestones and fur a la Liberace
_ he sends audiences into a frenzy as he camps it up onstage.
</P>
<P>
   But it's his songs, some spun of passion, others filled with
feel-good rhythms, that have pulled in the masses.
</P>
<P>
   ``His music gets you right at the ``corazon'' (heart),'' says
Sonia Moreno, a Phoenix receptionist, explaining her idol's
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel does pour sentiment into much of his music. Songs like
the emotion-packed ballad ``Amor Eterno'' (``Eternal Love''), which
Gabriel wrote in memory of his mother, and ``Hasta Que Te Conoci''
(``Until I Met You'') have become Mexican standards.
</P>
<P>
   But his superstar status is due to more than just a few
tear-jerkers. The Mexican-born Gabriel is also adored as one of
Latin America's most versatile and accomplished songwriters.
</P>
<P>
   During his 27 years on the charts, Gabriel has penned more than
500 songs ranging from love ballads to pop tunes to mariachi songs.
</P>
<P>
   It's the variety of his music that's helped Gabriel attract a
loyal following spanning several generations.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel grew up just across from Texas in the border town of
Juarez. He was the youngest of 10 children raised largely by his
mother, who worked as a housekeeper for a rich family in town.
Gabriel now owns the mansion she worked in.
</P>
<P>
   As a teenager, Gabriel got his start in nightclubs on Juarez's
seedy downtown strip. A shrine to Juarez's famous son now adorns
the window of El Noa Noa, the bar made famous by a Gabriel hit tune
that recalls the early days when he'd sing while patrons danced.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel's first hit in 1971 was ``No Tengo Dinero'' (``I Have No
Money'').
</P>
<P>
   His rise to stardom from obscurity has contributed to the
Gabriel mystique. Now, his fans say Gabriel has assured his place
among the biggest names in showbiz.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is part of our culture,'' Elias says. &QL; 
 &QL; 
For more information, visit Spanish-language
www.juangabriel.com.mx/ on the Internet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7617 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAGAMORE-HILL-ART-3RD     09-03 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAGAMORE-HILL-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: modest markings.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adjacent is the bird sanctuary, which no doubt Theodore
Roosevelt would have approved of. It is the oldest Audubon bird
preserve in the United States, with buildings housing natural
history specimens dear to the heart of TR, aviaries with birds of
prey and 12 acres of sanctuary trails.
</P>
<P>
   Queen Anne-Style Office
</P>
<P>
   There are a few more evidences of Roosevelt in Oyster Bay, a
surprisingly shabby and lackluster town considering its history
dating back to pre-Revolutionary days and the wealth of the
surrounding community.
</P>
<P>
   A good starting point is the ramshackle little Earle-Wightman
House, with its original room dating from about 1720. In it are the
very casual offices of the Oyster Bay Historical Society, where we
found the useful booklet ``A Walking Tour of Oyster Bay'' as well
as other pamphlets, maps and information.
</P>
<P>
   Thus armed, we began at one of the better kept sights, the Moore
Building, a turn-of-the-century office building in the late-Queen
Anne style with a witch's hat tower. Its second floor served as
secretarial offices for President Roosevelt from 1903 to 1908, when
telephone and telegraph hot lines were linked to the White House
and Sagamore Hill. In the enticing Book Mark Cafe on the street
level, one can browse among new and used titles and have a
restorative light meal, outdoors or in.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting old house in the town proved to be Raynham
Hall, built in the saltbox style for the Townsend family in 1738.
An Italianate-Victorian wing was added in the late 19th century by
a grandson, Solomon. There is also a 1916 photograph of Theodore
Roosevelt, who was a friend of Maurice Townsend, the last family
member to live in Raynham Hall. Engaging rooms from both periods
are fairly well preserved, and there are many documents testifying
to the considerable role the Townsends played in several espionage
intrigues of the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   After Sagamore Hill, the most enchanting sight in Oyster Bay is
the Planting Fields Arboretum, a magnificent botanical garden with
400 acres of lawns, flower beds and woodlands, a celebrated heather
garden and greenhouses, one of which is said to hold the largest
collection of camellia specimens in North America, with blooms at
their peak from late February through early April. Other lovely
greenhouses are dedicated to cactus, orchids and African plants.
</P>
<P>
   Originally a quintessential Gold Coast estate, begun in 1904 and
purchased by William Robertson Coe in 1913, the grounds were
landscaped mostly by the Olmsted Brothers firm. Now a state
historic park and on the National Register of Historic Districts,
the arboretum includes gift shops (one in the stunning stone
Tudor-Revival Coe Hall), plant shops, lectures and classes for
adults and children, as well as jazz, pop and classical concerts
throughout the year. Calling on the Vanderbilts
</P>
<P>
   To make a really full day on the beautiful North Shore with its
bays, marinas and wooded thickets, and because we wanted to try an
early dinner at the highly touted Mill River Inn, we decided to see
another museum house, one that recalled a life style totally
different from that of Sagamore Hill. We drove east to Centerport,
about 30 to 45 minutes from Oyster Bay, to the Vanderbilt Museum
Historic Mansion and Planetarium.
</P>
<P>
   Built in stages between 1906 and 1936, this lavish
strawberries-and-cream architectural confection typified the excess
of the Gold Coast during its Roaring '20s heyday. It was the summer
home of William K. Vanderbilt II, great-grandson of Commodore
Cornelius Vanderbilt, the founder of the family fortune, and was
named the Eagles' Nest.
</P>
<P>
   The house and its surrounding grounds overlook Long Island
Sound, where Vanderbilt could gaze at his favorite yacht, Alva. The
estate is adorned with columns from the ruins of Carthage, Belgian
blocks salvaged from New York City streets for a driveway, carved
Spanish doors, Portuguese tiles, Flemish chairs, French needlepoint
and, in the romantic courtyard where plays and concerts are held in
summer, a rococo 19th-century bell tower from Russia. It is a
fantasy of a Spanish-Mediterranean villa and, surprisingly, all of
the rooms are so eminently livable that if I had grown up at
Sagamore Hill, I might choose an easygoing change of pace and spend
my adult summers here.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the graceful, comfortable family parlors and
bedrooms and the gloriously moderne bathrooms, there is a large
natural history museum on the ground floor of the house, displaying
the marine life Vanderbilt assiduously collected. Other buildings
hold animal models, more sea specimens in the Hall of Fishes, and
an insect collection near the gift shop. We walked through gardens
back to the entrance and the planetarium, disappointed that no sky
show was scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   I left wondering what it would be like to join one of the
afternoon teas held in the mansion, where the paying audience
nibbles and sips while actors portray Vanderbilt family members and
contemporaries. Among the characters scheduled to appear in
September and October are Rosamond, William's second wife, chatting
with his sister, Consuelo, who became the Duchess of Marlborough,
and, later, Mae West, the last person one would expect to see
raising a pinky at a tea party.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS in 4th TAKE)
</P>
