<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7618 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0904-C     09-03 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0904-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANALYSIS: RUSSIA'S ECONOMIC CRISIS CONFIRMED THE BAD NEWS FOR
INVESTORS
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-POLITICS-0904.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For more than a year after the Asian economies of
Japan, South Korea, Indonesia and Thailand were sucked into a
tailspin, Wall Street mostly yawned, shrugged and continued to
spiral upward.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, did the collapse of Russia's $360-billion economy --
roughly the economic output of the Netherlands -- finally trigger
the Dow's devastating late summer slide?
</P>
<P>
   Theories abound, but the long and short of it is that the Dow
was overdue for a fall and Russia's woes, serious as they are,
merely confirmed for increasingly skeptical investors that the
world's emerging markets -- abetted by systemic and chronic ills in
Japan -- are undergoing a painful shakeout not likely to resolve
itself soon.
</P>
<P>
   It's been 17 months, after all, since Federal Reserve Board
chairman Alan Greenspan issued his now famous warning that the
stock market was experiencing ''irrational exuberance.'' That's
central banker talk for: Wall Street's shifted from an investment
pool to a casino, and anyone who throws money at it now is acting
more on faith than on reasoned analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's slide from its mid-July highs has been a reminder
to some that investors are paid for putting their money at risk.
What goes up can indeed come down.
</P>
<P>
   The slide had already begun, cautiously to be sure, weeks before
the Russian ruble collapsed on Aug. 17. In the days that followed,
though, investors became increasingly agitated, not only by the
promise of unpaid Russian debts and economic strife in Moscow, but
also by the threat of social and political chaos in a country that
saw its entire system evaporate less than eight years ago and, for
the past 11 days, has been limping along with a sharply divided
parliament and without a government.
</P>
<P>
   The thought of anarchy in a former superpower that still
maintains the world's second-largest nuclear arsenal tends to set
people's teeth on edge -- considerably more so than the prospect of
default on Russian loans.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Russia's economy become the next domino to fall in the
global financial crisis, however, is disconcerting news to
investors who have predicated much of their risk on the premise of
ever-growing world markets.
</P>
<P>
   Investors tend to buy stocks on the prospect of good news.
Scanning the emerging markets -- from Asia to Latin America, to
Africa and to the former Soviet States -- many have concluded that
there's more bad news at the moment than good.
</P>
<P>
   The next shoe to drop, moreover, could well be in China, where
export-driven growth is threatened by its neighbors' currency
devaluations. The 800-pound gorilla of the region, China could send
all of Asia tumbling further into the economic basement by
devaluing its own currency, the renminbi, though Beijing has
repeatedly vowed not to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling emerging markets out of their torpor is a job for the
engines of the industrialized world. And while the economies of the
United States and Europe are healthy, the sick man, Japan, is very
sick indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Its economy, the second-largest in the world, has been flat for
seven of the past eight years and is now in recession.
</P>
<P>
   What's needed to pull it out are dramatic reforms Japanese
politicians have been ducking for decades that would tip the
balance of power away from producers and toward consumers, thereby
encouraging domestic-led growth.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago in Washington, a man named Keizo Obuchi, then Japan's
foreign minister, chuckled when reporters asked him whether Japan
was concerned that the falling yen would spike the annual trade gap
-- more than $50 billion in Japan's favor -- that has caused so
much friction between Tokyo and Washington over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Japan would simply export its way out of its woes, Obuchi said,
noting wryly that the United States was plenty rich enough to
absorb the added imports that strategy would imply.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the yen has slumped further, and Obuchi is now the
country's prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   His recommendations of the last year will doubtless come under
scrutiny Friday night and Saturday, when his finance minister,
Kiichi Miyazawa, meets in San Francisco with Greenspan and U.S.
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   If the three most powerful finance officials in the world can't
come to terms with a way out of the global economic crisis, there
could be more dark days ahead for the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   As Hong Kong's Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa told the Associated
Press on Friday, ''We're all holding our breath.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
