<HEADER>
A7624 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAGAMORE-HILL-ART-4TH     09-03 1525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAGAMORE-HILL-ART-4THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: tea party.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Visiting TR's Turf
</P>
<P>
   Here is information about visiting Sagamore Hill in Oyster Bay,
N.Y., and other Long Island attractions nearby, as well as the
Theodore Roosevelt Birthplace in Manhattan. ``Theodore Roosevelt:
An Autobiography,'' first published in 1913 and then again in 1985
by DaCapo Press, is a loving, welcoming guide to both Roosevelt
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Long Island Attractions
</P>
<P>
   SAGAMORE HILL, 20 Sagamore Hill Road, at Cove Neck Road, Oyster
Bay, (516) 922-4447. Theodore Roosevelt's much-beloved home (with
95 percent of its furnishings original) was built in 1885 at a cost
of $16,975 and served as the summer White House from 1902 to 1909.
Today it attracts some 90,000 visitors a year. With 23 rooms
rambling through three floors, it is the epitome of the
turn-of-the-century American home of the privileged, filled with
books, big-game trophies, commodious furniture and intriguing
personal and Presidential souvenirs. The Old Orchard Museum on the
grounds is attractively laid out in the 1938 Georgian-style home of
TR's son Gen. Theodore Roosevelt Jr. There is a gift shop and a
picnic area. Hours: 9 a.m. to 5 p.m., daily from April through
October; Wednesdays through Sundays the remaining months. Closed
Thanksgiving, Christmas and New Year's Day. Guided tours begin
every half-hour, starting at 10 a.m., with the last one leaving at
4 p.m. Admission: $5; free for those 16 and under.
</P>
<P>
   THEODORE ROOSEVELT GRAVE SITE AND SANCTUARY, 134 Cove Road, at
Cove Neck Road, Oyster Bay, (516) 922-3200. About one mile down the
road from Sagamore Hill, the graves of President and Mrs. Roosevelt
are peacefully set behind an iron gate in hilly, leafy Young's
Memorial Cemetery. Adjacent is the country's oldest Audubon bird
sanctuary, designed by the Olmstead Brothers firm. It includes 12
acres of trails, aviaries housing some 35 varieties of birds of
prey and exhibits relating to TR's interests in natural history.
Hours: 8 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. Mondays through Fridays; 8:30 a.m. to 4
p.m. Saturdays and Sundays. Donations accepted.
</P>
<P>
   PLANTING FIELDS ARBORETUM, Planting Fields Road, off Oyster
Bay-Glen Cove Road, Oyster Bay, (516) 922-9206. This sprawling Gold
Coast estate dating from 1904 became the home of the William
Robertson Coe family in 1913 and was landscaped between 1918 and
1944. It is now a verdant state historic park of more than 400
acres with magnificent trees, blossoming fields and graceful
greenhouses of exotica like cactus, hibiscus and camellias. There
are two gift shops, one in the Tudor-Revival mansion Coe Hall.
Grounds are open daily, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.; most buildings from 10
a.m. to 4 p.m. Admission: Free except for a $4 parking fee from
Memorial Day through Labor Day and weekends and holidays after
Labor Day. There is no charge the rest of the year, except during
special festivals. Information on concert schedules and tickets is
available from Friends of the Arts, (516) 922-0061.
</P>
<P>
   OYSTER BAY HISTORICAL SOCIETY, Earle-Wightman House, 20 Summit
St., Oyster Bay, (516) 922-5032. Dating from about 1720 (and much
in need of sprucing up), this house has two minimally interesting
period rooms, one from about 1740, the other an 1830's addition.
There is a research library with material about the area, as well
as pamphlets and the booklet ``A Walking Tour of Oyster Bay''
($3.95). Hours: Tuesdays through Fridays, 10 a.m. to 2 p.m.;
Saturdays, 9 a.m. to 1 p.m.; Sundays, 1 to 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   RAYNHAM HALL HISTORIC HOUSE MUSEUM, 20 West Main St., Oyster
Bay, (516) 922-6808. Dating from the American Revolution, with a
Victorian addition from the late 19th century, this is a charming,
low-key museum of period rooms. Documents and artifacts go back to
the Revolution. Hours: daily, noon to 5 p.m., from July 1 through
Labor Day; then, Tuesdays through Sundays from 1 to 5 p.m.
Admission: $3; $2, the elderly and students; children under 6 free.
</P>
<P>
   VANDERBILT MUSEUM AND PLANETARIUM, 180 Little Neck Road,
Centerport, (516) 854-5555. Eagles' Nest, the pink and white
confection of a Spanish villa, was the summer home of William K.
Vanderbilt 2d, built between 1910 and 1935. Devoting himself to
marine biology, Vanderbilt collected the specimens of sea life
displayed here. There are other natural history specimens in other
buildings and a complete planetarium with scheduled sky shows.
Concerts and plays are performed in summer in the courtyard, and at
afternoon teas actors portray period personalities like Elsa
Maxwell, Mae West and members of the Vanderbilt family and social
circle. Museum hours: Tuesdays through Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 5
p.m.; Sundays, noon to 5 p.m.; hourly tours begin at 10:30 a.m.,
with the last leaving at 3:30 p.m. Admission: $8; $6 for the
elderly and students, $4 for children. Noon teas with a tour of the
mansion cost $30 for adults, $28 for the elderly, and this month
will be offered, starting on the 12th, on Tuesdays, Wednesdays,
Saturdays and Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   THEODORE ROOSEVELT COUNTY PARK, Third House, Montauk Highway,
Montauk, (516) 854-4985. Rare photographs, personal journals and
memorabilia from the Cuban campaign are displayed in the building
that served as Colonel Roosevelt's headquarters while the Rough
Riders recuperated from malaria and typhoid at Camp Wikoff after
the war. Through Oct. 15. Hours: Wednesdays through Sundays, 10
a.m. to 5 p.m. Free.
</P>
<P>
   ``ROUGH RIDERS DAYS,'' Deep Hollow Ranch, Montauk Highway,
Montauk (516) 476-5076. A re-creation of Camp Wikoff on a portion
of the original campground, featuring John Davidson as Roosevelt,
with a turn-of-the-century county fair and a Wild West show.
Tomorrow and Sunday at noon and 5:30 p.m. Admission: $35; $15 for
children under 12. On Sunday from 3 to 5 p.m. at nearby Montauk
Point Lighthouse, a re-enactment of Roosevelt's visit to the
lighthouse 100 years ago is planned.
</P>
<P>
   Places to Eat
</P>
<P>
   BOOK MARK CAFE, 1 E. Main St., Oyster Bay, (516) 922-0036. An
inviting and well-stocked bookstore with new and used titles is the
setting for a friendly cafe serving lunch, tea, dinner and weekend
brunches. Suitably light sandwiches and salads are preferable to
more ambitious cooked dishes. Save room for the homespun fresh
berries with whipped cream heaped onto scones. The cafe is in the
Moore Building, with a late-Queen Anne tower and mansard roof
dating from 1902. The second floor served as the secretarial
offices of TR's summer White House from 1903 to 1908. Lunch for two
with tip came to $23.
</P>
<P>
   MILL RIVER INN, 160 Mill River Road, Oyster Bay, (516) 922-7768.
About five minutes from the arboretum, this formal, atmospheric
restaurant with mellow lighting and decorative floral photographs
is an option for anyone who wants to have a restful early dinner
before heading home. Food is stylishly modern and, if not quite up
to the rave reviews it has enjoyed, above average, especially in
this area. Good choices included a creamy asparagus soup,
satisfying smoked duck with Asian garnishes, credible roast lamb
and an apple-raisin tart. An appetizer of tiny crab cakes with a
potato pancake would have been fine if served properly hot. Service
is efficient but coolly detached. Dress ranges from jackets and
ties to what the management calls ``neat casual,'' so throw a
jacket and a pair of dress shoes into the car for a
post-sightseeing costume change. A three-course dinner for two,
with two glasses of wine, came to about $145 with tip. Dinner from
6 p.m. to about 9 p.m., Mondays through Saturdays; from 5 p.m. on
Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   BY CAR. Long Island Expressway to Exit 41N, or Northern State
Parkway to Exit 35N. Then follow N.Y. 106 North toward Oyster Bay.
Follow road markers to Sagamore Hill or Planting Fields Arboretum
or into town for other sights. Centerport is northeast of Oyster
Bay on Route 25A. To reach Montauk, take the Long Island Expressway
to Exit 70 and follow the Montauk Highway (Route 27) east.
</P>
<P>
   BY TRAIN. Long Island Railroad to Oyster Bay Station; schedule
and fare information, (718) 217-5477. Taxis are usually at the
station but reservations can be made through Oyster Bay Taxi and
Limo in Syosset, (516) 921-2141. There is no train to Centerport.
</P>
<P>
   And in Manhattan . . .
</P>
<P>
   THEODORE ROOSEVELT BIRTHPLACE, National Historic Site, 28 E.
20th St., (212) 260-1616. The only New York City native to become
president, Theodore Roosevelt was born in a spacious town house on
this site in 1858, four years after it was built. The present house
is a faithful reconstruction completed in 1923 and is beautifully
furnished with Victorian pieces, many from the original rooms or
belonging to close relatives. A gallery in an adjoining building
holds personal and presidential memorabilia. Saturday, Sept. 5, at
2 p.m. there will be a chamber music concert, free with admission.
Hours: Wednesdays through Sundays, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. (closed Labor
Day). Tours begin on the hour, with the last one leaving at 4 p.m.
Admission: $2; free for children 17 and younger.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MIMI SHERATON
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
