<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7694 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-STARTREK-NYT &LR;      09-03 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-STARTREK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPTAIN'S LOG: WE'RE BACK AND, BOY, ARE WE YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the past, the future looked different. It was simpler than
the present future, with brighter colors.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can again experience the past future, thanks to the
return this week of the original ``Star Trek'' series. It never
really went away. For more than 30 years, those episodes have been
careering across the television galaxies, with the crew of the
starship Enterprise doomed to repeat (and repeat and repeat) every
one of its 79 adventures. Eighty, if you count the pilot, which was
not shown but soon will be.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening is this: The Sci-Fi Channel has dusted off the
original three seasons of ``Star Trek,'' replacing the minutes lost
to extra commercials during the years of syndication and adding new
introductions by the series' star, William Shatner (whose voice has
mysteriously dropped three octaves in three decades), and some
brief comments by other people who worked on the shows.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Sci-Fi began showing those episodes, first broadcast
on NBC from 1966 through 1969, in their original order, one each
weeknight at 7:30. (After showing the pilot, which had a mostly
different cast, the channel will offer all the shows again, with
Shatner's co-star, Leonard Nimoy, as host.)
</P>
<P>
   Friday night brings the fourth episode, ``The Naked Time,''
which Shatner says is revered by ``Star Trek'' devotees for the
dramatic scene in which he, as Captain Kirk, and Nimoy, as his
invaluable aide, Spock, grimly smack each other in the face.
(They're under the influence of a dread space disease that strips
its victims of their inhibitions and causes profuse sweating and
waves of ponderous overacting.)
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly enough, it is also the episode in which, during a
desperate effort to escape an imploding (or is it exploding?)
planet, the Enterprise for the first time experiences a speed so
fast that the ship can outrun time.
</P>
<P>
   And so it has, despite obstacles more frightening than that
space disease. Like critics.
</P>
<P>
   As Shatner notes with a wry laugh in his introduction to the
first episode, ``The Man Trap,'' ``Star Trek'' was hardly a hit in
1966. One of the unimpressed reviewers called it ``a dreary mess of
confusion,'' Shatner notes, but ``like so many critics, they're
gone, and we're still here.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's original opening sequence said the Enterprise was on
a five-year mission of exploration. Wishful thinking. The journey
lasted three years. When the show could not draw a big enough
audience against competitors like ``My Three Sons'' and ``Gomer
Pyle, U.S.M.C.,'' NBC pulled the plug.
</P>
<P>
   But if the show's audience wasn't huge, it possessed
unparalleled loyalty. In time, that original series, created by
Gene Roddenberry with a real-life crew that included the art
director Matt Jeffries, inspired nine feature films and four
television series (one was a cartoon based on the original) as well
as an unending meteor shower of books, collectibles, conventions
and other profit centers, including the current Sci-Fi Channel
compilation. (The 90-minute format allows ample time for
advertising.)
</P>
<P>
   Many people who will watch the series already know each episode
by heart. For them, the attraction may be the new material, labeled
`` `Star Trek' Insights.'' After one scene _ in which that disease
drives a crew member to reveal his doubts about the ethics of space
exploration that risks harm to the explorers and the environments
they unwittingly pollute, and makes him declare, ``I don't deserve
to live!'' _ the actor who exclaimed that line, Stewart Moss,
recalls the experience.
</P>
<P>
   The script, by John D.F. Black, ``had a lot of purple prose,''
Moss says. ``It had a lot of heavy emotional dialogue. It scared
me.'' He continues: ``I remember I killed myself with a butter
knife. I was the first man in the history of television to do
that.'' Talk about milestones.
</P>
<P>
   But the real business at hand is the episode itself, complete
with the familiar presence of DeForest Kelley (Dr. McCoy), James
Doohan (Scotty), Nichelle Nichols (Uhura) and George Takei (Sulu).
</P>
<P>
   Seasoned viewers will know that the platinum-blond Yeoman Janice
Rand, played by Grace Lee Whitney, was a regular for the first
season, but the character was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Those with a history of more casual ``Star Trek'' viewing (or
none at all) may be surprised at how different these dramas are
from today's television fare. Look at the simple sets in those
bright Crayola reds and yellows (perhaps to complement the purple
prose) and the costumes: double-knit pajamas and high-heeled black
boots. Protective suits are bright orange, made (it is now
revealed) of shower-curtain material.
</P>
<P>
   These episodes are closer, in chronology and spirit, to 1940s
serials than to anything being created today. Life (and its
fun-house mirror, television) is so packed with ambiguity and
cynicism that entertainment like this, assembled without those
elements, would be rejected as sappy.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, ``Star Trek'' comes from another era, when being
naive was not a criminal offense.
</P>
<P>
   These linear stories _ nearly free of the interlocking subplots
of 1990s prime-time fare _ move slowly through their twists, turns
and brushes with low-key philosophy until everything is resolved in
the final moments. Then everyone on screen holds a sadder-but-wiser
expression for the final fade-out.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the appeal? Doctoral dissertations have grappled with
the question. Sociologists, psychologists and other -ists have had
their say.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this may be part of the answer: These hopeful, low-tech
presentations seem to be the work of individuals with ideas, not
committees with polling data. On their own terms (from their own
time), the shows work. And if those individuals didn't produce
great art, they did come up with some earnest entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you're not ready to structure your life around these
souped-up reruns, you might enjoy a couple. So go, boldly, into the
future by visiting the past. It's not hard to take. Back then, warp
speed wasn't nearly as fast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 1720EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7704 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-PLUNGE-ECONOMI     09-03 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PLUNGE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS RUSSIA STAGGERS, THERE'S NOT MUCH THE WEST CAN DO TO HELP  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This ``separate buy'' article is from the current (week beginning
5 September 1998) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1998 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does Russia matter any more? It is tempting to say no. Once a
superpower with a mighty military machine and a driving belief in
its destiny as the only great nation straddling Europe and Asia,
its economy is now on a par-- in size if not quality -- with
Spain's and only two-thirds as big, by some measures, as
Indonesia's.
</P>
<P>
   Good riddance, then, to the pretensions of a once-proud nation?
And good riddance to its once-heroic but fast-crumbling leader,
Boris Yeltsin?
</P>
<P>
   Not quite yet. Russia still matters hugely by virtue of its
sheer geographical size, lumbering across 11 time zones, with a
large and well-educated population of 147 million, and endowed with
the richest natural resources in the world.
</P>
<P>
   That its human and material potential remains so vast only makes
its latest plunge to ruin all the more regrettable. And it still
boasts an array of nuclear weapons, some of which, though unlikely
to be used, could yet be lost as internal chaos spreads. Meanwhile,
its capacity for political mischief is immense.
</P>
<P>
   As for Yeltsin, his era is drawing to an early close, whether or
not he formally bows out. His second term of office has been little
short of disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   But, given the grisly list of flawed candidates who might
replace him, he may be able to perform one last service -- by
hanging on as a last-gasp president to give a breathing space for a
new order, one with parliament and a coalition government making
the running, that might halt the slide into total anarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, something nastily authoritarian, perhaps even a
thoroughgoing tyranny, could ensue.
</P>
<P>
   The West's ability to help shape a better Russia -- whether
economically or politically -- is limited, as President Bill
Clinton no doubt ascertained during his visit to Moscow this week.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is one area where America and its European friends can
continue to make a difference: security. American efforts to cajole
Russia into signing the START-2 nuclear arms-cutting treaty, held
up by a recalcitrant Duma, need to go on. In its own interests, the
West should go on buying up surplus nuclear material and ensuring,
by bribery if need be, that underpaid Russian scientists do not
sell their skills to rogue countries trying to build nuclear bombs.
</P>
<P>
   On a more conventional plane, as the delicate business of NATO's
enlargement proceeds, the alliance needs to offer every sort of
inducement to Russia to maintain and extend the sort of cooperative
partnership that is already under way.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it must be made plain, to whomever rules in
the Kremlin, that any Russian bullying of small neighbors such as
the Baltics or bigger ones like Ukraine will not be tolerated. As
Russia wobbles, the West must try harder to bolster the countries
on Russia's fringes.
</P>
<P>
   For all these reasons, even if Russia turns sulkily inward, it
must be kept as strategically engaged with the West as possible.
</P>
<P>
   In economics, the kind of engagement of recent years must,
perforce, cease. For the time being at least, Russia has forfeited
hopes for help. The West took a big but reasonable gamble by
lending money to Russia when it was led by a team of reformers
trying to do roughly the right thing. But the Russians have now
flouted just about every condition for getting help from outside.
</P>
<P>
   When, in its own good time, Russia has made real reforms and
something of a civic order, built a tax base and solid
institutions, and learned that honesty in business pays, then the
West should come back in. Not now. And things may well have to get
a lot worse before then.
</P>
<P>
   It is even less wise for the West to play politics: picking
Russian winners is a fool's lottery.
</P>
<P>
   The real reformers -- the likes of Boris Nemtsov, who sadly
failed to achieve much in Russia's recent string of
down-the-rabbit-hole governments -- are simply not going to be
elected. Their sponsorship by the West could make them even more
disliked.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if elections to parliament and the presidency were held
tomorrow, none of the possible winners -- Communists in league with
nationalists, crony-capitalists, ex-military strongmen -- would be
able to save Russia from further ruin. And the drift during the
three months that would have to elapse before people got to the
polls could harm Russia further.
</P>
<P>
   Better, perhaps, if a government of national unity could be
cobbled together, including the Communists, so that an
all-but-neutered Yeltsin and it is to be hoped a more responsible
parliament could stagger on.
</P>
<P>
   Russians, however, may think otherwise; and one could hardly
blame them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7708 &Cx1f; tab-z
