<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7713 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALLMAN-GRAVES-COX     09-03 1497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLMAN-GRAVES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Battle brews in Macon cemetery over resting place of 2 rock
stars
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACON, Ga._It's probably a good thing the Allman Brothers'
``Homecoming'' stop in Atlanta this week isn't in the Georgia town
band members called home. There's trouble here. And Candace Oakley
has pictures to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Page after plastic-sheeted page in Oakley's blue photo album
attests to what she calls ``the freak show'' that has played for
years at the side-by-side graves of her brother Berry and fellow
Allman Brothers founder Duane Allman. Both musicians died in Macon
motorcycle accidents _ Allman in 1971, Oakley in 1972. ``Look,
here's the one where they've left the butts of two marijuana
cigarettes,'' Oakley says.
</P>
<P>
   She flips the page.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the beer cans they leave, empty,'' she continues.
``Usually everything is empty or used. I mean, I don't understand
the whole `tribute' thing to begin with. If they're expecting Berry
and Duane to get up at night and enjoy their `tributes,' why not
leave a full beer?''
</P>
<P>
   Flip.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley's candid spirit should help her as she fights a battle on
two fronts _ City Hall on one, some Allman Brothers fans on the
other. All parties converged a week ago when Macon Mayor Jim
Marshall had an 8-foot chain-link fence topped with razor wire
removed from around the graves less than two months after Oakley
installed it to thwart fans.
</P>
<P>
   Now Oakley is considering building a mausoleum. The mayor is
being rigid about what she can do next with the plot in the
city-owned Rose Hill Cemetery, where deed owners don't have total
title to the property. And the larger fan organizations in Macon
simply want ``Candy'' _ as many refer to her _ ``to just get a
grip.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh I've got lots of, um, fans around here,'' snarls Oakley,
48. Retired from many years in retail, the departed Oakley's
younger sister won't explain what her current source of income is.
``It's not the point,'' she insists. ``It shouldn't be the focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you what: I don't run tours and I don't make any money
off of Allman Brothers marketing,'' she does say. ``I've been
taking care of me and Berry's father most of this decade. (He died
last Oct. 19). Just trying to live a quiet life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've shunned the press for so long,'' continues Oakley, who
awoke this recent afternoon to a call from The Wall Street Journal.
The next day she had her morning Coke as she listened to her
dilemma being discussed on Peach State Radio. ``I guess a sister
just trying to protect her brother's grave has struck a nerve,
huh?'' she giggles slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyway, hun, look at this. ... ''
</P>
<P>
   More pictures.
</P>
<P>
   There's one of pebbles fashioned into a heart on the white
marble crypts.
</P>
<P>
   There's another showing how someone has filled one of the
guitars etched into the two tombs with blue crayon.
</P>
<P>
   And yet another in which a visitor has kissed Oakley's headstone
``with the brightest, reddest, ugliest lipstick she could find,''
his only sibling believes.
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes more cleaning work for Oakley and her
husband, Buford Birdsey, 56. Oakley is the only Allman Brothers
family member in Macon. Allman's daughter Galadrielle lives in
California. And Oakley's widow, Linda, and daughter Brittany reside
in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's basically us out there on our hands and knees with
soap and water brushing off the mess,'' sighs Birdsey, a retired
boat captain who ran charters in Florida and the Bahamas. Now he's
the principal photographer on the couple's grave patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, at the Macon Parks and Recreation Department's
suggestion, Oakley and Birdsey put up a 3-foot fence to protect the
site. It was pulled up and tossed aside in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Then in July, Oakley and her husband discovered a hole where
someone was apparently digging to get into the graves. ``That's
when we said, `Enough is enough,' and we put up the big fence,''
Oakley explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really thought, wrongly, that three days of work (putting
up the 8-footer) that cost about $4,000 might just stop some of
this trouble,'' adds Birdsey.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, ``trouble'' to them may be considered a fitting
tribute to a fan of the polyrhythmic rock band, which is
approaching its 30th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candy really needs to get a grip and listen to the Allmans'
records again,'' says Margo Murdock, 52, owner of a one-chair
barber shop that offers ``alternative therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, the joke side of me wants to say, `What does she think
they did down there at Rose Hill?' Come on now, what did (the
single) `In Memory of Elizabeth Reed' really mean? It was about a
nice flat spot near her grave to smoke, drink and do whatever.
Excuse me, pardon me, did I miss something about the '70s?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody ever went to defile anybody else's grave,'' continues
Murdock. ``It's the Allman Brothers' spirit and essence that people
are coming to take in. She can move the bodies, build a mausoleum
or whatever. People will come. Princess Di isn't in that tunnel
anymore but people still go.''
</P>
<P>
   Murdock is also a founding board member of the Macon-based
Georgia Allman Brothers Band Association, an organization, Oakley
says, that's ``basically inviting people to go down to Rose Hill
and dance on their graves.''
</P>
<P>
   Her other cause of anxiety is known as stop No. 19 on the
association's ``In the footsteps of the Allman Brothers Band'' map
_ the Big House. It's the former residence of Duane Allman, his
girlfriend Donna, their daughter, Berry Oakley, his wife, their
daughter and Candace Oakley. Nobody lives there any more: the house
at 2321 Vineville Ave. has been turned into a stately looking
museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to help (fans) be as much of a part of the Allman
Brothers as they can,'' offers a hesitant Kirsten West. Her husband
Kirk, the band's tour manager, now owns the Big House. Oakley
refers to him ``as one of the pied pipers of this fanatic
mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Candy's motives, I really don't want to get into,'' adds West,
rushing to lock up so she can make the 90-mile drive to Atlanta to
see all five Allman shows. ``I do feel comfortable saying an ugly
razor-wire fence is not an appropriate tribute to Duane and Berry's
spirit. Lighting a candle or lighting whatever seems like the
tribute you'd expect at the grave of two rock legends who died at
24.'' Other such dubious tributes can be found as far as the
often-littered resting place of Doors singer Jim Morrison in Paris
and fellow rocker Jimi Hendrix in Seattle. Otis Redding's widow in
Macon has his remains on her farm, inaccessible to the public. But
even the lesser known people in Rose Hill have graves that are
picked at and painted on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are enhancing security at Rose Hill,'' says the mayor. ``In
fact, before I called for the `Stalag 17' compound to be removed, I
called some people for some private funding to specifically secure
the Allman grave.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Walden, founder and owner of Atlanta-based Capricorn
Records, says he'd help monetarily if asked. ``I'm sympathetic to
all parties involved,'' says Walden, whose former Macon label was
made famous by the Allmans.
</P>
<P>
   Current band members have said nothing about the issue. Singer
Gregg Allman, Duane's younger brother, issued a ``no comment'' this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident this will all be worked out soon,'' the mayor
continues. ``There are plans for more foot patrols now. And in the
long haul, I expect that we'll reach an agreement with the family
about some appropriate treatment like fencing, maybe electronic
surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it won't be is a prisonlike compound,'' he adds. ``This
is a public cemetery with historic character used by thousands of
people. And we want people to feel like Duane and Berry did:
Welcome to come into a serene and peaceful and comfortable place.
We don't want something that says, `Get out of here.'''
</P>
<P>
   He might be wise to start with Oakley's fierce stare.
</P>
<P>
   This week, she was standing near the graves when two out-of-town
fans approached. Architecture student Rob Shortt and his companion,
Liza Jerome, both 29, had traveled from Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   A grimace greeted them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lot of paper you have in your hand, just enough for
two graves, huh?'' Oakley asks. They freeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plan to do some rubbings?''
</P>
<P>
   Shortt nods in the affirmative. Still in the same spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``With what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Charcoal,'' he responds.
</P>
<P>
   Without identifying herself, Oakley squinches her face sternly
and shakes her head no.
</P>
<P>
   A minute later, when Shortt is told who Oakley is and what she's
been dealing with, he explains that he ``didn't want to make any
more trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just paying my respects,'' he says, headed for the Allman
Brothers opening night concert in Atlanta. ``Just wanted to take
something home with me, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he should have settled for a picture.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
