u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN04-COX     09-03 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Sweet tea and bananas: That's Mobile
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not that I wanted a glass of sweet tea. I really prefer it
half-and-half, and most restaurants gladly mix it for you.
</P>
<P>
   But I had to go to the Sweet Tea Sip-Off in Mobile, Ala. because
my friend Jay Greland, the Mobile Register columnist, and the
newspaper itself organized and sponsored it.
</P>
<P>
   I think sweet tea is regarded as more typically Southern than
just plain iced tea. At least you get that impression from the
legions gathered at Cottage Hill Park to compete and celebrate the
sweet stuff.
</P>
<P>
   For five years this fete has been going on, with women bringing
their iced tea to the park to be judged and rewarded. This year,
Jay added banana pudding to the competition, and if you think there
are not scores of ways to zip up this old Southern favorite, you
haven't looked around. I asked what you could do to a banana
pudding that is different from the recipe on the vanilla wafers
box, which has always been my authority.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't get to talk to the winner, Roxanne Vick, nor to Nan
Strickland, who drove 80 miles to enter her pudding. But some
contestants suggested handsome variations, like banana pudding
laced with sherry. One woman suggested fresh peaches to add a
little spirit to the otherwise bland bananas.
</P>
<P>
   We got to the sip-off after lunch at the old Mobile drive-in,
the Dew Drop Inn, where countless couples have courted each other
and indigestion, caused by hot dogs. Our friend and guide Velma
Lassiter Croom thought my daughter, whose father considered the Dew
Drop the equal of the Varsity, should experience that long-loved
eatery. So we stoked up on food before the sip-off, and I have no
personal evaluation to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a very pleasant party, anyhow. Held under a picnic
shelter, it drew families with folding chairs and a lively band,
headed by a singer and guitarist from the Register's circulation
department. When we arrived, they were playing, and one of their
number was caroling ``Stars Fell on Alabama'' at top volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you remember that song?'' I asked my daughter. She said she
did, but I doubted it. Its heyday followed the publication of Carl
Carmer's book of the same title in the mid-1930s. As I remember,
Mr. Carmer hated the song and felt it had somehow cheapened, as
well as exploited, his book.
</P>
<P>
   I loved it. And it did sound fine out there under the big trees,
with the aroma of bananas, long a Mobile specialty, rising from the
picnic tables. In the shade around the shelter, grown-ups lounged
in lawn chairs, babies played on blankets and at least one couple
danced to the band music. Jay and his wife, Cindi, tabulated the
tea and banana pudding entries.
</P>
<P>
   As a sop to the literary life, Jay set up a table for book
autographing by a couple of Alabama authors. Eight or 10 people of
all ages, including a young woman who serves on the Mobile City
Council, lined up to compete for the baby bottle prize, which
rewarded the tea sipper who could sip a baby bottle empty the
fastest. It didn't look like a pleasant way to get your tea, I
thought as I watched their efforts, but they seemed to have
practiced and were in good form.
</P>
<P>
   The councilwoman remarked that she hadn't practiced, but it
seemed a jolly thing to do. ``She's a good sport,'' Jay told me.
</P>
<P>
   I think they all were, and it was a more pleasant event than one
our newspaper has sponsored to raise United Way funds. Some of our
executives have been required to kiss a pig.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
