<SLUG> BC-POKEMON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pokemon: TV monsters gobble big bucks
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think Tamagotchi ``virtual pets.'' Think Beanie Babies. Think
video games. Think TV.
</P>
<P>
   The latest monster from Japan, a potent blend of pop culture
fads, arrives Monday. If you haven't heard of it yet, just wait.
You will.
</P>
<P>
   It's called ``Pokemon,'' short for ``pocket monsters,'' a
plethora of pint-sized critters that will soon materialize on TV,
in video games and in toy stores.
</P>
<P>
   Parents may see ``Pokemon'' as a monster that attacks
pocketbooks _ and given its success in Japan, they'd be right.
There, ``Pokemon'' products have sparked $4 billion in sales in the
past two years. More than 9 million copies of software have been
sold for Nintendo's Game Boy hand-held video game.
</P>
<P>
   To prime the American market for similar sales, Nintendo and the
fast food restaurant KFC, which plans a plush toy promotion in
November, are spending $25 million to introduce ``Pokemon'' here.
That includes sending a Volkswagen Beetle decorated like Pikachu,
one of the monsters, to 10 cities this week, including Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally we would launch a piece of Nintendo software and hope
to sell it for 12 to 16 weeks, and then, like a movie, it's over,''
says George Harrison, a Nintendo America spokesman. ``We're
spending a lot more this fall than we would if we were just trying
to sell a half-million Game Boy games.''
</P>
<P>
   The basic story: Ash, a young boy, aspires to become the world's
greatest Pokemon master by catching and training 150 monsters.
``Pokemon'' creators hope American kids will emulate Ash in trying
to collect and trade the monsters, as real toys or in virtual form
in video games.
</P>
<P>
   The syndicated animated kids' show starts Monday. Two $29.95
Game Boy cartridges arrive Sept. 28. And in November, just in time
for Christmas, comes a line of toys, including action figures and
bean-filled Pokemons, that, like Beanie Babies, will be
periodically retired to enhance their collectibility.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the works: comic books, trading cards and a clothing
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it's been so huge in Japan, there's more cause to
think it may take off here in the same way,'' says Ira Mayer,
publisher of Entertainment Marketing Letter. But success in one
country doesn't necessarily translate into a U.S. smash because of
cultural differences, he cautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pokemon's'' initial round of publicity in the United States
was negative. In Japan last December, 700 kids suffered seizures
while focusing intently on flashing lights in one TV episode, and
the story was widely reported.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the TV show has been edited to eliminate the special
effects suspected of triggering the seizures.
</P>
<P>
   Still, could too much ``Pokemon'' on TV or in the Game Boy turn
kids into monster couch potatoes? Don't worry, there's a product
for that, too.
</P>
<P>
   An electronic ``pet'' called Pokemon Pikachu, coming in November
for $19.95, prods its owner to exercise by keeping track of how far
he walks. The greater the distance, the greater the friendliness
the interactive pet displays to its owner.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
