<HEADER>
A7723 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-VIETNAM-COX     09-03 2786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-VIETNAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    23 years after the Vietnam war, a visitor finds a bustling,
friendly nation that welcomes Americans
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 6: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOI, Vietnam_There's only one country in the world where you
come face to face with the reality of the United States not winning
a war. That reality hits home, more than any other place, at the
Army Museum, a former colonial citadel in Hanoi that follows the
Vietnamese through centuries of war against the Chinese, the
Japanese, the French and the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the museum, you come to a courtyard that appears
to be heaped with junk. Walking closer, your heart sinks as you
realize what the scrap metal is. Rusting fuselages. Battered jet
turbines. Wings with jagged edges where they used to join airplane
bodies, like arms ripped out of sockets. The junk, piled high under
a shade tree, is an assemblage of bombers and fighters who crashed
or were shot down over North Vietnam during the wars against France
and the United States. Small signs identify the remains
dispassionately, as if they were dinosaur bones in a natural
history museum. There's a French Hellcat hit in 1954, an American
F-4 shot down in 1967, a B-52 brought to earth in 1972. You wonder
who died when they fell. You wonder who died when they flew.
</P>
<P>
   You are outside the museum a few minutes later, feeling bruised
and agitated, when a school bus pulls up. A framed portrait of Ho
Chi Minh sits on the dashboard, propped against the windshield.
Children pour out the door and run toward the only Westerner in
sight. The tourist has become a tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``You American?'' one asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good afternoon!'' says another, overenunciating the syllables
as he practices the tongue that has replaced French as Vietnam's
second language.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen students gather around to recite their English drills
and pose for pictures with the visitor. His homeland was their
homeland's enemy many years ago, before any of them were born. To
them, the planes and destruction are history. The Westerner,
standing among them with guidebook and camera, is the reality.
</P>
<P>
   Drink Pepsi, comrades
</P>
<P>
   Before I visited Vietnam this spring, I punched up the World
Wide Web site of the Vietnamese Embassy in Washington. The
Vietnamese must have thought that some re-education was in order
when the nations resumed diplomatic ties in 1995, because one of
the first sentences that appeared on my screen was, ``Vietnam now
is a country, not a war.''
</P>
<P>
   I tried to keep that in mind as the Cathay Pacific airliner
crossed the South China Sea and the shoreline materialized,
followed by pastel green fields and flashes of sunlight glinting
off flooded rice paddies. Vietnam is indeed more than the sum of
its battles. It is an ancient country with a fertile culture and a
tropical beauty that runs from mountains to vast river deltas to a
serpentine coast that has more beachfront than California. Vietnam
would be worth touring even if the best and the brightest in
Washington had never sent a single American there.
</P>
<P>
   But they did _ 3 million of them over 20 years _ and it doesn't
take long to be reminded of it. As the plane started its final
descent into Ho Chi Minh City, I looked up from my guidebook and
saw ranks of half-pipe concrete bunkers sitting abandoned beside
the runway. The airport, Tan Son Nhat, was an enormous U.S. base
during the war. It looked as if the bunkers hadn't been touched
since the last Americans fled before advancing Communist troops 23
years ago. A few minutes later, sobered by these monuments to
futility, we were met on the tarmac by a shuttle bus that urged us,
with every inch of its sides, to DRINK PEPSI!
</P>
<P>
   It's like that all over Vietnam. Just when you remember that
it's a country, not a war, you pass a bomb crater or a crippled
veteran or a Viet Cong cemetery with its red flag streaming over
white markers mustered in an eternal close-order drill. Then you
pass a Ford truck, a billboard for Kentucky Fried Chicken, a
roadside stand selling Coca-Cola, and you remember that it's not
just a country, but an economy. Vietnam remains a socialist state,
but in recent years it has taken tentative steps toward capitalism
and has opened itself to foreign investment. The Cold War has
become the Cola War.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Vietnam has enshrined the war and begun to
capitalize on its tourism potential. There are battlefield parks
and memorials, war museums and art galleries, military reunions and
tours _ there's even a chain of meat-market bars called Apocalypse
Now. Many souvenir shops sell reproduction Viet Cong gear and old
U.S. Army surplus. Of all the war keepsakes I saw, the unlikeliest
was in an airport gift shop; next to the cheap busts of Ho was a
plastic model of a U.S. helicopter piloted by an action figure
named Major Hoss Jones. The shop took American Express.
</P>
<P>
   The curious thing, given the bitter history, is how the
Vietnamese seem to have welcomed the Americans back. They need the
dollars, of course, but it's still a remarkable attitude when you
consider the resentment and hatred that linger after most civil
wars. Look at ours; some people still haven't forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnamese seem more curious about Americans than resentful
of them. At least that's the impression I got during two weeks in
the country, most of it spent touring and talking to people in the
former warring capitals of Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh City. The two
largest cities, they're as different as Los Angeles and Boston. As
I explored them, I drew smiles and questions and more than a few
beggars, but no outward rancor. There was much to see and
experience, most of it unrelated to the war, yet I found myself
drawn to the ashes again and again, the way you can't help but look
over a cliff into an abyss.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting paper tigers in the South
</P>
<P>
   The government calls it Ho Chi Minh City. The people call it
Saigon. The airline monitors say ``HCMC,'' while the luggage tags
say ``SGN.'' Whether it's referred to by its old name or its
conquered name, the city that was the capital of South Vietnam has
become the hustling economic heart of the reunited nation.
</P>
<P>
   Ho Chi Minh City is Vietnam's largest, with more than 5 million
people, and it seemed as if most of them were in the streets as I
was driven to my hotel. Vietnamese traffic makes Atlanta's
Perimeter look stately. Motorbikes and bicycles crowd the laneless
boulevards 15 abreast. Many of them carry impossibly large cargoes
balanced on poles. I saw one bicyclist ferrying what appeared to be
an entire dining room set _ he looked like an ant carrying a
grasshopper.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers of the hopelessly outnumbered cars honk their horns
constantly, creating a manic soundtrack that continues to beep in
your ears after you turn out the lights at night. The dreams are
even more vivid if you take a ride in a cyclo, a bicycle with a
front-mounted passenger seat that throws you face-first into the
traffic melee. It's like being strapped to the bumper of a
Manhattan taxicab.
</P>
<P>
   Saigon went through some hard times after the North Vietnamese
captured the city and renamed it in 1975. Thousands fled or were
imprisoned. But when the government decided to allow the beginnings
of a market economy in the late 1980s, Saigon _ always the
country's most Westernized city _ was the chief beneficiary.
Skyscrapers have begun to rise above the tamarind trees. Hotels
have opened. Prostitutes on motorbikes have returned to Dong Khoi,
the main drag, which runs from the twin spires of Notre Dame
Cathedral to the clamorous bank of the Saigon River.
</P>
<P>
   I am not a Vietnam War veteran, but I followed a veteran's
itinerary. I saw the former U.S. Embassy, the scene of the frantic
helicopter evacuation that signaled the war's end; it was vacant,
still guarded by a rusty barbed wire fence. I had a beer on the
roof of the Hotel Majestic, a French colonial confection on the
riverfront that was a favorite of war correspondents. I visited the
Rex Hotel, where the American military brass used to stage the
body-count briefings that reporters caustically called the ``5
o'clock follies.'' The rooftop garden is one of the most outlandish
places in the city, with palm trees and statues of elephants and a
crown-shaped marquee that lights up the Asian night like something
from Las Vegas. Downstairs, a sign in the lobby welcomed a meeting
of ``the U.S. Army Colonels Delegation.'' It seemed like old times.
</P>
<P>
   Ho Chi Minh City's most popular tourist stop is said to be the
War Remnants Museum, formerly called the War Crimes Museum. The
name has changed, but the spirit hasn't. It's a guilt bath for
foreigners, with an onslaught of grisly pictures and artifacts of
war atrocities. I couldn't stomach it for long.
</P>
<P>
   The other big war attraction in town is Reunification Hall, the
residence of South Vietnamese presidents from 1966 to 1975. The
rambling mansion couldn't feel more frozen in time if it were a
villa in Pompeii. The game room has beer keg chairs, like some den
in Kalamazoo circa 1970. The shelves in the study have titles that
somehow eluded the socialist censors (``The Green Berets''?). The
war rooms in the basement _ a mini-Pentagon _ have yellowed
troop-strength charts and an exhaustive collection of clunky
gray-metal U.S. Army military furniture. Your tax dollars at work.
</P>
<P>
   On the outskirts of the city, there's another tourist stop that
shows how the other side operated. Viet Cong guerrillas started
digging the Cu Chi Tunnels in the early '60s, and by 1973 they had
burrowed 200 miles of passageways under what had been a rubber
plantation. Up to 5,000 guerrillas were stationed there, hiding
like moles by day and slipping out at night to infiltrate and
attack. The U.S. Air Force dropped half a million bombs on Cu Chi,
turning it into a lunar wasteland of craters, but the explosives
didn't exterminate the Communists, and the site has been preserved
as a national park. It is to the Vietnamese what Valley Forge is to
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Our guide, Le Van Tung, a wiry young man with an easy smile,
ushered my group into the earthen tunnels through openings that
seemed scarcely big enough for a groundhog. The entrances were even
tighter during the war, to discourage American GIs from pursuing
the thinner Viet Cong into their lairs. ``If we hadn't enlarged the
holes,'' Tung said, looking me over, ``I'm not sure you could get
in.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next hour, we crawled through suffocating passages,
toured underground barracks and hospitals, sampled the guerrillas'
meager rations of cassava root and green tea, and felt the point of
a bamboo-stick booby trap.
</P>
<P>
   On the way out of the park, I was startled to hear automatic
weapons fire. It came from something called the National Defense
Shooting Range, where you can pay a few bucks and test your aim
with the infantry rifles used during the war. I bought a clip of
five rounds and trained a U.S. Army M-16 at a target _ a paper
tiger _ across the field. The rifle kicked, and all five shots
sailed high. I pulled out another Lincoln and bought a clip for an
AK-47, the smaller, lighter, Soviet-made weapon preferred by the
North Vietnamese. I riddled the tiger and was awarded a prize, a
black-and-white checked scarf. I asked the attendant whether it had
any significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a Viet Cong scarf,'' he said, placing it around my neck
with a big grin. ``You're a Communist now.''
</P>
<P>
   Chilling with Ho in Hanoi
</P>
<P>
   The real Communists are where they've always been, in the north,
especially Hanoi. In some of the capital city's neighborhoods, you
can still hear party propaganda broadcast over loudspeakers on the
street. But even here, in the heart of redness, things are
changing.
</P>
<P>
   Hanoi is a city of layers. Riding in from the airport, I saw
vestiges of the Soviet domination of the 1970s and '80s, as the
Russian-built highway passed ugly monuments done in the
bow-before-me style of Leonid Brezhnev's Moscow. Once in the city,
the driver skirted the Old Quarter, a typically Asian warren of
crooked streets and cramped shop stalls, passed a Buddhist temple,
then entered the French Quarter, a district of spacious boulevards
and beaux-arts buildings _ all painted yellow _ that recalled the
era when this was the capital of French Indochina.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, I passed the most dramatic landmark of the
dawning era of global capitalism. The ``Hanoi Hilton,'' the prison
where American prisoners of war were held and tortured, has been
demolished and replaced by the Hanoi Towers, 20 stories of polished
marble that would be at home in any American city.
</P>
<P>
   Hanoi is smaller than Ho Chi Minh City _ about 3.5 million
people _ and it seems more charming, with its air of history and
its varied architecture, shady parks and placid lakes. Ho Chi Minh
City crackles with business energy, but there's more cultural
bedrock in Hanoi and its museums, monuments and galleries.
</P>
<P>
   Vu Quy Trung, a graduate student, agreed to show me around his
hometown. I met him one overcast morning (the only kind in Hanoi)
at Hoan Kiem, the emerald lake in the heart of the city. An hour
before, the shore had been crowded with Vietnamese starting the day
with tai chi exercises. They had been replaced by street vendors
selling postcards and paperback books with hawkish persistence. One
of them waved a copy of Graham Greene's Vietnam novel ``The Quiet
American'' in my face. I made the mistake of inquiring about the
price, and he dogged us around the lake chattering, ``You buy! You
buy!'' When we finally shook him, he snarled something in
Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did he say?'' I asked Trung.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberated from the young capitalist, we hopped into a taxi for
Hanoi's best-known landmark, the tomb of Ho Chi Minh. The
Vietnamese revere Ho the way Americans once revered George
Washington _ only they call the father of their country ``uncle,''
as in ``Uncle Ho.''
</P>
<P>
   We joined the line of pilgrims outside the mausoleum, a massive,
stepped concrete structure that looks like a cross between a Mayan
temple and a high school football grandstand. A red carpet led into
the edifice, up 33 steps and around into a darkened chamber that
was as chilly as a meat locker. I started to say something, but a
guard, standing stiffly in the green-and-red uniform of the
Vietnamese army, fired an admonishing glare in my direction. I kept
the sacred silence.
</P>
<P>
   And then we beheld him, Ho Chi Minh, the wispy-bearded
revolutionary who led his compatriots against four enemies through
four decades of fighting that claimed the lives of millions of
Vietnamese. He lay propped on a wooden bier, enclosed in glass, his
waxy hands cupped on black covers.
</P>
<P>
   Ho wanted to be cremated, but the powers disregarded his wish
and made an icon of his remains after he died in 1969. He's been
here ever since, except for annual trips to Moscow to recondition
the corpse. The Russians, of course, perfected the art of
preserving Communist mummies.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the mausoleum, I asked Trung what he remembered from his
visits to Uncle Ho, expecting some patriotic sentiment. Instead, he
said, ``Best air conditioning in Hanoi.''
</P>
<P>
   After touring Ho's modest residence _ a three-room house on
stilts that would fit into the presidential game room in Saigon _
we stopped for lunch. Over spring rolls and beer, Trung gave me an
idea of what middle-class life in Hanoi is like. He still lives
with his parents, four of them in three rooms, sharing a bathroom
with several other families. ``It's nice,'' he said, and I imagined
it was, compared to the poverty that weighs down so many
Vietnamese. When I picked up the bill _ $15 _ Trung was deeply
grateful. ``That's more than I spend on food in a week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Our next stop, the Army Museum, was many blocks away, so we
climbed onto Trung's motorbike and braved the Hanoi traffic, which
is almost as crazy as Ho Chi Minh City's. Trung had to go to work,
so we parted at the museum. I spent the rest of the afternoon
wandering from exhibit to exhibit, feeling alternating stabs of
pain over what my country had done and surges of resentment over
the lopsided way it was often being presented.
</P>
<P>
   The captions were in Vietnamese, French and English. I noticed
something in them that hadn't dawned on me until then, and it
served as a reminder that wounds haven't healed just because they
are unseen. The Vietnamese don't refer to the bloodletting of the
1960s and '70s as the Vietnam War. They call it the American War.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
