<HEADER>
A7724 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER04-COX     09-03 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMC plans 2 days of monkey business
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One year before man first landed on the moon, Hollywood
unleashed ``Planet of the Apes,'' a decently filmed sci-fi thriller
with Charlton Heston as, well, Moses in a spacesuit going mug to
mug with humankind's newfound superiors: chimps, gorillas and
orangutans.
</P>
<P>
   For every dollar it cost, ``Apes'' earned back more than four.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood then did what it always does when money's floating
around. It vowed to run the whole concept into the ground. ``Apes''
sparked four sequels and two TV shows, nary a one of them even
barely watchable.
</P>
<P>
   But with little else to do for a holiday weekend, AMC on Sunday
and Monday is trotting out all five films in a kind of
30th-anniversary celebration.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to 1968's ``Planet of the Apes,'' you can watch
1970's ``Beneath the Planet of the Apes,'' 1971's ``Escape From the
Planet of the Apes,'' 1972's ``Conquest of ...'' and 1973's
``Battle for ...'' There's even a new two-hour special _ ``Behind
the Planet of the Apes'' _ for those who ``Can't Get Enough of the
Planet of the Apes.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe only Einstein could figure out why, but when AMC starts
its ``Apes'' marathon at 9 a.m. Sunday the films will first run in
near reverse order. Chicken to the egg, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with a life will likely consider watching only the
original ``Planet'' (3:30 p.m. and 8 p.m. Sunday, 3:30 p.m. and
5:30 p.m. Monday).
</P>
<P>
   But there are reasons to also catch the first hour of ``Behind
the Planet of the Apes'' (5:30 p.m. and 10 p.m. Sunday, 11 p.m. and
4 a.m. Monday). It's full of gee-whiz facts about the original film
you never even knew you needed to know.
</P>
<P>
   -- Who's behind that mask? Edward G. Robinson was hired first to
play the orangutan Dr. Zaius. He even performed in a $5,000 makeup
test used in March 1966 to determine whether the filmmakers could
pull off actors in ape gear without audiences laughing at them.
Robinson later pulled out of the project for health reasons. That's
when Maurice Evans joined up.
</P>
<P>
   -- The prosthetics pro: John Chambers, who created prosthetics
for ``The Munsters,'' ``The Outer Limits'' and ``Lost in Space,''
was the makeup guy, turning 200 actors into apes. He was awarded a
special Oscar. His other claim to fame: Spock's pointy ears for
``Star Trek.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Where'd they find the lovely Nova? Heston's nonspeaking
girlfriend in the film was played by Linda Harrison, a former
beauty queen. She was under contract at the studio but had little
if any acting experience. She also happened to be dating studio
chief Richard Zanuck, the exec who green-lighted the film.
</P>
<P>
   -- It didn't make the cut: Trimmed from the original film was a
sequence shot revealing that Nova was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   -- The sound of the fury: Jerry Goldsmith wrote the music score
and got an Oscar nomination. The score's unusual sounds came from
banging metal mixing bowls, a ram's horn and a Brazilian instrument
that emitted sounds similar to ape vocalizations.
</P>
<P>
   -- The bottom line: ``Planet'' cost $5.8 million to make. It
grossed $26 million.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
