<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-HILITES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Places to see in Vietnam
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 6: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a world of things to see in Vietnam, many of them having
nothing to do with the war. Some highlights:
</P>
<P>
   -- Cao Dai Cathedral: Cao Dai is an indigenous religion that
mingles Eastern and Western faiths and claims 3 million followers.
Its seat, an ornate, exuberantly colored cathedral northwest of Ho
Chi Minh City, has to be the strangest sites in Vietnam. The
novelist Graham Greene called it ``a Walt Disney fantasia of the
East,'' with dragons and enormous eyes staring out from windows and
green snakes slithering down pink columns. The daily noon Mass
makes for quite a show.
</P>
<P>
   -- China Beach: Vietnam has scores of great beaches. The
best-known, thanks to the late-1980s television show of the same
name, is China Beach, a gorgeous crescent of sand set against the
backdrop of the Marble Mountains. During the war, American GIs
based in nearby Danang made the beach their favorite recreation
spot. Now, foreign investors are building Western-style resort
hotels in an effort to turn it into Vietnam's Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   -- Halong Bay: You've probably seen it even if you haven't been
there. More than 1,500 islands rear their limestone heads out of
the Gulf of Tonkin east of Hanoi, a dramatic stretch of coastline
that's been feaured in movies from ``Indochine'' to the latest
James Bond installment. Most visitors see the bay on land-sea tours
out of Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   -- Hoi An: This small town, a few miles from Danang, was once
one of the great ports of Southeast Asia. In the late 1700s the Thu
Bon River silted up, slowing commerce, but the old Asian atmosphere
of narrow streets remains. The centuries-old architecture somehow
escaped this century's wars.
</P>
<P>
   -- Hue: After Vietnam threw off Chinese rule 200 years ago, the
country was united under a monarchy that established its seat in
this small city on the central coast. During the 1968 Tet
Offensive, Hue fell to the Communists and then was retaken in a
battle that some historians regard as the war's worst. The city has
rebuilt, however, and provides a glimpse of an older Vietnam.
Tourists visit to see the temples, the imperial citadel and the
mausoleums of the emperors along the Perfume River.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Mekong Delta: South of Ho Chi Minh City, the country
becomes a vast flatland punctuated by outlets of the mighty Mekong
River, the lifeline of Southeast Asia. This is Vietnam's
breadbasket, with rice and orchards and more tropical fruits than
you've ever seen. Boat tours are booked out of Ho Chi Minh City.
</P>
<P>
   -- My Lai: There were atrocities on all sides during the war;
this hamlet on the central coast is where ours happened. The
Vietnamese have built a memorial park and museum on the site where
U.S. troops massacred several hundred unarmed civilians in 1968.
Visiting is a very sobering experience.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
