</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alliance gives peek at `Lives'
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_Atlanta heard the first of Elton John's new music
Thursday and got a sneak peek of the dance and romance in the Walt
Disney musical ``Elaborate Lives: The Legend of Aida,'' which gets
its world premiere this month at the Alliance Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in a rehearsal room of the Woodruff Arts
Center, Alliance Theatre artistic director Kenny Leon and Disney
executive Tom Schumacher introduced two passion-stoked production
numbers from the upcoming joint production, the first Disney stage
musical not based on an animated film. Both pop-rock numbers showed
impressive tightening since early rehearsals last month in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening, a biracial cast of about 20 _ without sets and
costumes _ sang and danced through the back story of the legend,
the conquest and enslavement of the black Nubian people (including
Princess Aida) by the white Egyptian empire. In a love duet, Aida
(Heather Headley of Broadway's ``The Lion King'') and her Egyptian
soldier lover, Radames (Hank Stratton, a guest star of ``Beverly
Hills, 90210''), sang of their forbidden romance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a long, delicate process,'' Schumacher said,
``especially because `Beauty and the Beast' and `The Lion King'
already had lots of development time (in animated films) before
they reached the stage. This is a bigger challenge. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``(Disney) chose the Alliance,'' Schumacher continued, ``after a
national survey of regional theaters ... not just for the facility
but because of Kenny Leon ... and the audience he's cultivated for
new work.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon said that in his first meeting with Disney execs, ``we
satisfied each others' nervousness'' about forming the kind of rare
partnership of commercial producer and nonprofit arts organization
that also created ``The Who's Tommy'' in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Elton John, who teamed with lyricist Tim Rice on the songs, was
not present but is expected to attend a late rehearsal of the show,
which begins previews Sept. 17. Disney Chairman Michael Eisner will
reportedly be ``in and out of Atlanta'' to track the show's
progress and rule on its readiness for Broadway in early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the appropriate viewer age for this sexily
costumed musical _ sophisticated by the standards of a Disney
family show _ Leon recommended ``9 or 10'' as a starting point.
Schumacher refused to name such a limit, saying, ``It depends on
your children. ... Are they ready to see `The King and I'?''
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are selling briskly but are available (404-733-5000),
mainly in the second half of the eight-week run.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
