<HEADER>
A7729 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTICELLO-3RDTAKE-NY     09-03 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTICELLO-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va.: to earth.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Visiting Monticello &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is information about visiting Monticello, near
Charlottesville, Va. For general information about the area: (888)
293-1776.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   KESWICK HALL, 701 Club Drive, Keswick, Va., (804) 979-3440 or
(800) 274-5391. Our room here, at $345 a night, was lovely, with
Laura Ashley sheets, pillows and towels and a large, well-appointed
bathroom. Eager staff members appeared willing to provide nearly
anything _ for an additional charge. Double room rates start at
$250 and range to $595 for a suite. The afternoon tea is renowned.
If you are a hotel guest, it is included in the price of your room;
otherwise it costs $12.50. There is a special rate of $40 for a
jazz dinner on Sundays through September.
</P>
<P>
   CLIFTON THE COUNTRY INN, 1296 Clifton Inn Drive,
Charlottesville, (804) 971-1800 or (888) 971-1800. This inn is the
former home of Jefferson's daughter Martha Randolph. Doubles range
from $125 to $315 a night, including breakfast. One of the rooms is
the former office of Jefferson's son-in-law. There is a heated spa,
clay tennis courts and a pool.
</P>
<P>
   THE BOARS HEAD INN, Route 250 West, Charlottesville, (804)
296-2181 or (800) 476-1988. This hotel has 175 rooms, a conference
center, 20 tennis courts and a golf course. The rooms are spacious
and airy, with reproductions of Colonial-era furnishings; the lobby
and hallways have authentic furnishings of the period. Double room
rates range from $165 to $315.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   CLIFTON THE COUNTRY INN, 1296 Clifton Inn Drive,
Charlottesville, (804) 971-1800 or (888) 971-1800. Offers a prix
fixe dinner at $58 on Fridays and Saturdays and $48 the rest of the
week. The food is divine. There is one seating each evening at 7:15
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   MICHIE TAVERN, 683 Thomas Jefferson Parkway, Charlottesville,
(804) 977-1234. This tavern is half a mile below Monticello, but if
you are unimpressed by fried chicken, beans and mayonnaise, also
known as ``typical dishes of the Colonial period,'' served by
people dressed in Colonial costumes, it is best to pass. The tavern
serves a $10.50 buffet, not including beverage or dessert. From
April through October the buffet is served from 11:15 a.m. to 3:30
p.m.; from November to March it is served from 11:30 a.m. to 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   C&AMP;O RESTAURANT, 511 E. Water St., Charlottesville, (804)
971-7044. This is one of downtown Charlottesville's best lunch and
dinner spots, offering French country, Pacific Rim and American
Southwest cuisine. Wonderful fish and a terrific wine list. Entrees
range from $12 to $24.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   MONTICELLO, the home of Thomas Jefferson, Route 53, southeast of
Charlottesville, is open every day except Christmas Day, from 8
a.m. to 5 p.m., March to October, and 9 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. the rest
of the year. Admission: $9; children 6 to 11, $5; under 6, free. In
summer and during some weekends, tours of the gardens and of
Mulberry Row, the slave dwellings, are offered daily. Programs
include Monticello Family Workshops, Elderhostel at Monticello and
Plantation Community Tours. There are also special programs during
African-American History Month. Information: (804) 984-9822; the
Web site is www.monticello.org.
</P>
<P>
   UNIVERSITY OF VIRGINIA, on University Avenue, Charlottesville.
The rotunda is open to the public every day of the year except
during a three-week Christmas break for maintenance, on some
holidays and when special events are being held in the rotunda; it
is a good idea to call beforehand. Student guides offer historical
tours of the rotunda and part of the Lawn area during the regular
academic year at 10 a.m., 11 a.m., 2 p.m. 3 p.m. and 4 p.m. During
the summer months historical tours are available for the rotunda
only. Free. Information: (804) 924-7969.
</P>
<P>
   ASH LAWN-HIGHLAND. Only two and a half miles up the hill from
Monticello is the home of Jefferson's close friend James Monroe,
fifth President of the United States. A more modest establishment
than Monticello, it is still lovely to visit. It is open daily
March to October, 9 a.m. to 6 p.m.; November to February, 10 a.m.
to 5 p.m. There are guided tours of the house and self-guided tours
of the slave quarters and surrounding buildings. Admission: $7;
$6.50 for the elderly; $4 for children 6 to 11; children are 6 are
free. Information: (804) 293-9539.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON VINEYARDS. Jefferson gave these vineyards, located
between Monticello and Ash Lawn, to Filippo Mazzei, an Italian
winemaker, so that he could develop a European-style wine. The
winery is open daily from 11 a.m. to 5 p.m., and lunch is available
at a market on the property. Free tours and tastings available
throughout the day. Information: (804) 977-3042 or (800) 272-3042.
</P>
<P>
   MONTPELIER. James Madison's home, an 18th-century version of
Lifestyles of the Rich and Famous Founding Fathers, is about 20
miles from Charlottesville and four miles from the town of Orange.
Guided tours are offered daily through November, beginning at 9:30
a.m., with the last tour at 4 p.m. Admission: $7.50; $6.50 for the
elderly and AAA members; $3.50 for children ages 6 to 11; free for
children under 5.. Hours: Daily, 9:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. Head to the
visitor's center on Route 20; a shuttle bus takes visitors up to
the house. Visitors can also see the house and grounds on their own
and rent an Acoustiguide. Information: (540) 672-2728.
</P>
<P>
   How to Get There
</P>
<P>
   BY AIR: Colgan Air has daily direct flights to Charlottesville
from La Guardia Airport. Special seven-day advance fares, which
require a Saturday night stay, range from $150 to $248 round trip,
excluding tax. Last-minute fares are $306 each way. Information:
(888) 265-4267. U.S. Airways Express has a daily direct flight to
Charlottesville from La Guardia departing at 6:30 p.m.. Round trip
with no restrictions or advance notice is $614. A special $159
round trip fare, depending on availability, requires an advance
reservation of at least one week and a Saturday night stay.
Information: (800) 428-4322.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MARIANNE SZEGEDY-MASZAK
</P>
</TEXT>
