<HEADER>
A7732 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUILT-HISTORY-COX     09-03 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUILT-HISTORY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Showcasing a communal tradition
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_Asha Tyler is only 5 years old, but she already knows to
get out her sewing basket whenever her mother, Darlyne Dandridge,
sits down to work at a quilt.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't realize it yet, but the thread in her needle will
link her to hundreds of African-American quilters across time and
geography. Many of them peer out of photographs taken by the
indefatigable Roland Freeman and displayed in ``A Communion of the
Spirits: African-American Quilters, Preservers and Their Stories''
at the Atlanta History Center. (His book of the same name _$34.95,
Rutledge Hill Press _ is available in the center's shop.)
</P>
<P>
   In a heroic 20-year effort that took the Washington, D.C.,
photographer from coast to coast, he has documented
African-American quilters and their quilts in all their diversity.
His odyssey took him to Mississippi shacks and the homes of
celebrities; it encompassed rural grandmothers and young, urban
sophisticates.
</P>
<P>
   The 130 photographs, each framed in a quilted mat that reflects
something about the quilting club or individual depicted, dominate
the show. The sheer number makes them overwhelming to look at, but
that makes a point as well. Clearly, the desire to make or own
quilts knows no economic, educational or age barriers.
</P>
<P>
   The photos are interspersed with miniature tableaux of quilting
activity, as well as actual quilts. The presence of the real thing
adds immeasurably to the show. They span the spectrum from
traditional geometric patterns and story quilts to the exuberant
syncopated riffs on the old patterns often associated with
African-American quilt making. Some are clearly utilitarian, while
others are intended as works of art to hang on a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Dandridge's own quilt history is a microcosm. ``I have
progressed from traditional patterns to using those patterns with
African fabrics to expressing my own ideas, often about African
womanhood,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   If the figurative quilts are more obviously narrative, even the
abstract designs are rife with meaning. The best example in the
show is a poignant old, worn quilt whose maker elongated the
traditional double wedding ring pattern and called it ``the slave
chain.''
</P>
<P>
   Dandridge, who started a quilting club in Los Angeles, founded
West End Quilters after moving here in 1991. Clearly, quilting
serves an important social function as a great excuse to gather and
share in something.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Roland says that quilts keep you warm,'' Dandridge says,
``he doesn't just mean physically. He means warm at heart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Communion of the Spirits: African-American Quilters,
Preservers and Their Stories''
</P>
<P>
   Through Oct. 6. 10 a.m.-5:30 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays; noon-5:30
p.m. Sundays. $7; $5 senior citizens; $4 ages 6-17; under age 5
free. Atlanta History Center, Atlanta, Ga . 404-814-4000.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: As Roland Freeman's documentary photographs attest,
quilting is a national passion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
