A7733 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VALDEZ-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      09-03 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALDEZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLONING OF PET AN INSULT TO NATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA VALDEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The people who put up $2.3 million to have their dog
cloned provided comics with a deep vein of yuk-yuk material.
</P>
<P>
   But this is more than a high-tech version of what Roy Rogers did
to Trigger.
</P>
<P>
   It's the trivialization of both science and life.
</P>
<P>
   And a sorry demonstration of what researchers will do to get
funding.
</P>
<P>
   The unidentified owners of a collie-husky mix named Missy have
``hired'' a team of about 10 researchers to clone their 12-year-old
pooch. Dr. Mark Westhusin, an associate professor of veterinary
physiology at Texas A&AMP;M University, will head up the group.
</P>
<P>
   He told the ``New York Times'' that the project would yield lots
of valuable information about reproduction in dogs, a
little-studied subject.
</P>
<P>
   Can you say ``spay'' and ``neuter''?
</P>
<P>
   Doggie birth control is not what this is about.
</P>
<P>
   This is about a desire to prolong a friendship. It happens to
all pet lovers when Buster or Boots starts getting gray around the
muzzle.
</P>
<P>
   It happened to me when I was 5 years old and my dog, Shiner, got
hit by a car. He was patient enough to let me dress him up.
Ferocious enough to keep door-to-door salesmen away.
</P>
<P>
   If I could have cloned him, I would have.
</P>
<P>
   But then I never would have known Sheba, the dog who sat on a
footstool by the picture window and waited for me to come home from
school. Every day.
</P>
<P>
   I would have cloned her, too.
</P>
<P>
   But then I never would have met Carmel, who was also the best
dog in the world. If I'd cloned him, I never would have met Max or
Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   They were all treasures.
</P>
<P>
   All different.
</P>
<P>
   Like people. Or leaves. Or snowflakes.
</P>
<P>
   Missy's owners are rich enough to indulge the natural desire to
duplicate a good dog. And foolish enough to think it's possible.
</P>
<P>
   Their ``Missyplicity Project'' will fail because an individual
is more than its genes. Environment and experience are powerful
personality shapers. No matter how well the scientists succeed in
engineering another Missy, they will never succeed in creating
another Missy.
</P>
<P>
   They (begin ital) will (end ital) create a nasty distraction
from more important matters.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic research holds great promise. But to get to those
anticipated cures and other healing wonders, we have to negotiate
our way around an ethical abyss. Should a drowned child be cloned
back to life? Should parents be able to design the perfect baby?
Should brilliant minds be replicated? Should semihumans be
engineered and duplicated to do our dirty work?
</P>
<P>
   We need to consider such questions before we go much further
down DNA's Yellow Brick Road.
</P>
<P>
   We haven't decided what genetic engineering should be. But it
probably shouldn't be about cloning sheep, like last year's
Scottish Dolly. And it certainly shouldn't be about cloning dogs on
demand for people who have more money than sense.
</P>
<P>
   The uniqueness of natural creations _ dogs, people, snowflakes _
is sacred and miraculous. Turning the impressive advances of modern
science to the task of recreating a pet furthers the illusion that
it isn't. &QL; 
And that's a doggone shame. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Linda Valdez is an editorial writer at The Arizona Republic. She
can be reached at linda.valdez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
