<P>
   WORKOUT-BASICS _ Man was not weak and puny for thousands of
years before the Tectrix ClimbMax. So slowly turn around, gently
place the Power Bar on the floor and back away.Come with me. We're
going back to basics. Back to Rocky doing one-handed push-ups and
Travis Bickle curling milk cartons. Back to a time when all a guy
needed to flex his pecs was willpower and a floor. That's right,
back to the zero-cost work out. The workout for real men who are
real broke. (Hibbard, Austin American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHERS-PRAY _ Schools are open and teachers are praying. There
are more than 100 faculty prayer groups in county public schools.
Organized by Network of Christian ministries. We go to some of
their prayer sessions, talk to teachers and to civil libertarians,
who have no problem with it. (Gushee, Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m.
ET. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   POKEMON _ Pokemon, a Japanese pop culture phenomenon, tries its
luck on U.S. shores starting today. It's got elements of toy
smashes like Tamagotchi and Beanie Babies, plus a daily TV show
(starting Monday) and a Nintendo Game Boy (coming later this
month). The toys _ 150 plush collectibles _ roll out in November.
While most parents probably haven't heard of them (unless they
remember a news story last year about hundreds of Japanese kids
having epileptic seizures while watching one particularly intense
episode) they'll soon be inescapable. (LizLee, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   ALLMAN-GRAVES _ As the Allman Brothers Band continues its week
of five shows at the Fox Theatre, a look at the controversy
involving the graves of Allman Brothers Band members Duane Allman
and Berry Oakley in Macon's Rose Hill Cemetery. We talk to Berry's
sister Candace Oakley, at the center of the dispute, about what
she's planning now that city has taken down a chain link fence
around the graves, which like rock graves around the world are
usually littered by fans. (SoMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA 8 p.m. ET. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLE-READER _ Jo-Ellan Dimitrius has written a book, ``Reading
People'' (Random House, $23.95), revealing the techniques that
prompted a law magazine to dub her The Seer. You don't have to be
facing the electric chair to be interested. (Kalajian, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   READER-SIDE _ Tips on how to judge by first impression.
(Kalajian, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BEANIE _ MONTROSE, Colo. _ The furor over Beanie Babies, stuffed
animals tagged with ``personal information'' about the doll, has
reached a fevered pitch. Hoping to cash in on the craze, Cody Davis
plans to sell one of his prized Beanie Babies to finance his
mother's cancer treatment next month. ``I want to keep him,'' said
11-year-old Cody, ``but not if it can help Mom.'' (Porter, Grand
Junction Daily Sentinel) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DRESS-CODE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ An untucked shirt can be a high
school teen-ager's fashion trademark. But to a school administrator
in a society of deadly school shootings, it could be the cover for
a dangerous weapon. The two views of an untucked shirt collided
recently at Bastrop High School, where school officials' insistence
that all shirts be tucked clashed with some students' drive for
individualism. The result: More than 200 of the school's 1,500
students walked out of class. (Rodriguez, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-TREES _ Trees are like a business facing a shortage of raw
materials, said Woody Wesig of Woody Tree Medics, and right now
some are on short work weeks and some are going bankrupt. ``On a
scale of 10, a brown leaf is zero, and a bright green is a Madonna
10,'' said Wesig. ``We're not seeing too many 10s right now. Many
trees are around five.'' There are many reasons that trees are
losing leaves early this year: too much rain earlier and too little
lately. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
