the preseason. They appear to have found three replacements in Jon
Muyres, Dez White and Charlie Rogers. (Rogers, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-GRAMBLING _ Doug Williams first arrived at Grambling in 1974
as a strong-armed quarterback. Nearly a quarter of a century later,
Williams is back as the head coach of his alma mater. Williams has
big shoes to fill in the form of Eddie Robinson, who retired last
year as college football's all-time winningest coach. (Reese
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-REDHAWKS-PRENTICE _ OXFORD, Ohio _ Travis Prentice is no
Louie Armstrong when it comes to blowing his own horn. The junior
tailback from Louisville, Ky., has played in only 22 games, but is
on pace to shatter a flock of Miami and Mid-American Conference
rushing and scoring records. ``People are always bringing the
records to my attention,'' the soft-spoken Prentice said, ``but I'm
not really big on personal goals. The only goal I have is to play
on the team that wins the MAC championship. I just run with the
football. If the records happen, they happen.'' (Williams, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-LONGHORN-COLUMN _ Predictions and observations about the
upcoming Longhorn season. (Wangrin, Austin American-Statesman) ETA
8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-FALCONS-MAIN _ The struggling Atlanta franchise, struggling
to put people in the stands, know that a victory at Carolina might
provide some much-needed relief. Another losing start could be
disasterous for the franchise. (Winkeljohn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
