<P>
   BBO-MARIS-MAIN _ It is considered the most magical number in
sports. But when Roger Maris hit his 61st home run in 1961, it was
almost anticlimatic. It was the first year of expansion and
Commissioner Ford Frick had ruled that to break Babe Ruth's record
of 60 homers, it had to be done in 154 games, not the new 162.
Maris, at 59 after his 154th completed game, finally hit No. 61 on
the final day of the season. Only 23,000 were on hand at Yankee
Stadium when Maris connected off Tracy Stallard of Boston. Most of
the media horde that had made Maris' life difficult were gone by
then, but the pressure continued to hamper Maris. He was never the
same on or off the field. He died at age 51 of cancer in 1985.
(Curtright, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BBO-MARIS-MUSEUM _ Harried shoppers hurry past, most oblivious
to the hometown hero's life on display just outside their glance.
It's hard to find time for history when you have school clothes to
buy. But as Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa get closer to 61 home runs,
more people are starting to stop and stare in amazement at the New
York Yankees uniform with No. 9 on the back or at the historic
baseballs or the grainy black-and-white film. The West Acres
Regional Shopping Center in Fargo, N.D., is home not only to Sears
and the Gap, but the Roger Maris Museum as well. (Curtright,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-MARIS-NINE _ Nine things you probably didn't know about
Roger Maris. (Curtright, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-MARIS-BIO _ Roger Maris bio information with career stats.
(Curtright, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ROGSON _ Son glad Roger Maris is being remembered.
(Curtright, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-REDS _ If Mark McGwire wants to hit the three home runs this
weekend against the Cincinnati Reds he needs to drop Roger Maris
into a baseball history footnote, he won't be taking a ladle to
home plate.
</P>
<P>
   He'll need his bat. Manager Jack McKeon is adamant that McGwire
won't be served any bowls of soup when he faces the Reds tonight,
Saturday afternoon and Sunday afternoon in Busch Stadium. When
Chicago's Sammy Sosa hit two home runs in three games this week
against the Reds, the team's office switchboard lit up.
Paraphrasing most messages - and removing the expletives - the
callers wanted to know, ``Why do you pitch to Sosa and you don't
pitch to McGwire?'' (McCoy, Dayton Daily News) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-HOMERS _ St. Louis is the center of the baseball universe
this weekend. Mark McGwire, at 59 homers and counting, takes dead
aim at the home run record when the Cardinals play the Reds in a
three-game series starting Friday night. The team has received more
than 1,200 media requests (more than an All-Star game); tickets are
being scalped for thousands of dollars; and the sports networks are
scrambling to get the games on the air. (Rosenberg, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
