<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7759 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-ENGLAND-ART-REVIE     09-03 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-ENGLAND-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: SILO MEETS SATELLITE DISH IN THE NEW NEW ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, N.H. _ There has never been a shortage of landscape in
New England, nor, for that matter, of artists to romanticize it
freely. But as industry, technology and suburbia have turned
hamlets into towns and farmland into malls, the focus has
drastically shifted. New takes on the old rural theme of human
harmony with nature are showing up in the work of artists from the
region. We've come a long way from the 19th-century vision of the
Sublime, a view of America as a glorious, pristine land where
nature connected man with God.
</P>
<P>
   How local artists register the rejiggered use and look of the
land is the subject of a catchall but appealing show,
``Post-Pastoral: New Images of the New England Landscape,'' at the
Hood Museum of Art at Dartmouth College here. It sets out some 50
objects made by 15 artists, from paintings to photographs to, well,
manipulated vegetable matter.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the disturbing reality of clearcutting timber and the
surreality of satellite dishes next to silos make viable subject
matter; others dwell nostalgically on the products and phenomena of
nature, and a few bring a resigned and sometimes cynical wit to the
theme of landscape in transition.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its shortcomings, the show is certainly an improvement
on the outmoded juried biennials that the Hood, following the
custom of museums elsewhere, has long mounted as showcases for
local talent. Under a new policy, a series of theme exhibitions, of
which this is the pilot, will replace the hodgepodge biennials,
still allowing artists of the region a forum for their work while
presenting it in a sharper context.
</P>
<P>
   With its diversity of viewpoints, ``Post-Pastoral,'' organized
by Amy Schlegel, a curatorial fellow at the museum, has no real ax
to grind. Its approach is moderate: Not all change is bad, but
change has happened, and here is what it feels like. Although it
basically presents the work of regional artists, a few outlanders
have crept in, like Alan Sonfist of New York, whose concern has
long been the natural landscape, and Dan Ford, a satirical
nostalgist from Brooklyn. But the concentration is on Vermont and
New Hampshire, picture-postcard rural states where megadevelopment
still has the power to shock.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, the aerial photographs of Alex MacLean that
track changes in what he calls ``settlement patterns'' of the two
states. Flying his Cessna 182, MacLean has for 20 years been
viewing from on high the sometimes conflicting arrangements of man
and nature, more recently registering the fact that nature is
losing ground.
</P>
<P>
   Upscale subdivisions in the Shelburne area of Vermont; big bald
patches, caused by clearcutting, in the White Mountain forests of
New Hampshire; an ugly sprawl of storage lockers on a once-pristine
Vermont farm are tellingly depicted in these arresting photographs,
enhanced by their startling perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Esten, also a photographer, documents more subtle changes,
deliberately using a low-tech camera whose fuzzy images are of
sites in the Connecticut River Valley and northeastern Vermont. In
``Brook and White Bucket'' (1994), a commercial paint bucket lies
near a quiet stream; in ``Peak'' (1996), a shabby mobile home
obtrudes on the view of a dignified mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Another photographer, John Willis, accepts the depredations of
beavers as partners in nature's processes, making close-ups of
their dams and lodges with the devotion to detail of an
architectural photographer.
</P>
<P>
   Paintings in the show are less impressive than the photographs.
The most accomplished work in this medium is that of Altoon Sultan,
whose slick Superrealist mode does not have much competition here.
But although her style seems ideal for calendar art, her subject
matter, the ``working landscape'' of farms, is fairly gritty.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Silage, Coventry, Vt. (1996),'' for instance, piles of
fodder serve as a repository for old tires; ``Quonset Barns,
Coventry, Vt.,'' of the same year depicts efficient but ugly
aluminum buildings replacing the picturesque wooden barns that have
long been a cliche of farm life.
</P>
<P>
   Refreshingly, if not always rewardingly, artists who work in
less conventional ways are not in scant supply. One is Suzanne
Pretty, a tapestry maker, whose weavings convey the impact of heavy
industry on a sylvan section of eastern New Hampshire, an unusual
subject for a tapestry maker, to say the least. Her most effective
piece, ``Fragmentation'' (1995-96), shows a stylized forest of
conifers invaded by earth-moving equipment and flatbed trains
lugging logs.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Leslie Fry and Daniel Ladd make much of
nature's bounty. Ms. Fry has produced a group of wonderfully wacky
architectural ministructures that appear to be made of real fruits
and vegetables: brussels sprouts, melons, celery, beans, peanuts
and such.
</P>
<P>
   Ladd has set up what he calls a ``working relationship with
nature,'' an intricate process whereby he grows small gourds in
shaped plaster casts so that the gourds themselves emerge as
sculptural images, from fragments of ancient statues to modern
street fixtures. Their surfaces suggest stone or metal, but their
origins as gourds are betrayed by their protruding stems.
</P>
<P>
   Another natural medium is coaxed into sculpture by Bill Botzow.
His diminutive ``Pine Needle Farmhouse'' (1994), a traditional New
England connected house and barn made of pine needles roughly
covering an armature of stone and plywood, is set up in an outside
court of the museum to play off the postmodern architecture of
Charles Moore and Chad Floyd, who designed the Hood building.
</P>
<P>
   Another outdoor piece, and the most far-out object in the show,
is Lars-Erik Fisk's ``Barn Ball'' (1998), representing the
ubiquitous New England barn. But this one occurs in the form of a
big sphere, its red boards and fieldstone base rounded into a
roly-poly ball, while still allowing a look inside its doors and
windows. The comic shape seems to reflect a kind of Disneyfication
of the rural landscape, and it is seen by Fisk, who also
contributes a ``Field Ball,'' a ``Street Ball'' and a ``Tree Ball''
to the show, as an example of the ``packaging'' of a countryside
once known for its idiosyncracies.
</P>
<P>
   A show that is by turns benign and alarming, ``Post-Pastoral''
is a come-on and a cautionary tale for those who hanker for the
joys of rural life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Post-Pastoral: New Images of the New England Landscape''
remains at the Hood Museum of Art, Dartmouth College, Hanover,
N.H., New Hampshire through Sept. 20
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
