<SLUG> BC-DEEP-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEEP DOWN': DIGGING FOR MEANING IN SLAVERY'S WAKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(js) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORk _ Maybe he just wanted to play the harmonica again.
Whatever his reasons, and try as he might, the charismatic Ruben
Santiago-Hudson cannot overcome the insurmountable obstacles
imposed on him by ``Deep Down,'' a preachy mishmash of a drama
about racism in rural Florida in the early days of the civil rights
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago-Hudson deservedly earned a Tony for his richly detailed
comic portrayal of Canewell, the fidgety harmonica player in August
Wilson's ``Seven Guitars.'' Here he plays Daniel, a plain-spoken
ex-convict of unappreciated depth. In Doug Grissom's muddled work
at the Intar Theater, directed by John Lawler, Daniel takes a job
digging holes on land owned by Ned (Christopher Murney), a
mysterious, grizzled redneck who barks cantankerously whenever
Daniel has the temerity to wonder aloud what they are supposed to
be digging for, although Ned eventually confides that they're
prospecting for gold. Yep, gold.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, making a nuisance of herself around the
excavation site is Ned's teen-age daughter, Hannah (Catherine
Zambri), who spends lazy afternoons hurling racist insults at
Daniel, who is black, and then flirting with him. Her behavior
makes scant impression on Daniel, but nearly gives her father a
coronary. Ned may not mind black men working at his side, but he
draws the line at intimacy with his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual tension, however, is really not the point here, and
neither is an exploration of the relationships among these three
souls. Grissom is a frustratingly restless dramatist; he shifts the
focus about once every 10 to 12 lines. His central thrust seems to
be the notion of coming to terms with one's heritage; it turns out
the old tin cups and chains that Ned and Daniel uncover once
belonged to slaves who lived on the land. Daniel, growing
increasingly swept up by the history of his people, has the idea of
exhibiting the artifacts in a museum.
</P>
<P>
   The pall cast by slavery 100 years down the line is a weighty
theme, but skated over so superficially in ``Deep Down'' that the
audience is provided no insight into what an encounter with the
South's horrible legacy signifies for any of Grissom's characters.
No larger meaning is derived from anything they do or say, and the
play ultimately trails off, like an abandoned ship drifting into
the mist. Ms. Zambri's Hannah is perversely given the play's
closing monologue, a speech that suddenly, and oddly, suggests the
whole evening has been about her.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, when all else fails, Lawler has his players make
music. As the lights go down on one curious scene after another,
Santiago-Hudson whips out his harmonica, accompanied by the blues
guitarist Bill Sims Jr. Sims is the best thing about ``Deep Down''
_ the second-best thing is Charles Kirby's realistic set _ and it
seems completely fitting that Sims' involvement here should have
absolutely nothing to do with anything else that occurs onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Production Notes:
</P>
<P>
   `Deep Down'
</P>
<P>
   By Doug Grissom; directed by John Lawler; executive producers,
Ira Pittelman and Suzette Breitbart; sets by Charles Kirby;
lighting by Bobby Harrell; costumes by Katrin Hutchinson; sound by
Mariusz Glabinski; production supervisor, Robert Thurber; stage
manager, Tiffany Horne; production manager, Robert Easter;
Camilla's artistic directors, Mitchell Riggs and Catherine Zambri;
artistic associate, Jason Howard. Presented by Camilla's, in
association with Moonglow Entertainment. At Intar Theater, 420 W.
42nd St.
</P>
<P>
   With: Bill Sims Jr. (musician), Christopher Murney (Ned), Ruben
Santiago-Hudson (Daniel) and Catherine Zambri (Hannah).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
