<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CRITICPICKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Books: Critic's choice
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 6: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Teresa K. Weaver
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- he closing months of the year offer avid readers an ideal
time for slipping into a nice, cozy novel. This fall, literary
treats from some trusted names _ Tom Wolfe, Alice Walker, John
Updike, Barbara Kingsolver, Philip Roth and Fannie Flagg, to name a
few _ offer ample reason for staying in.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of nonfiction have a full fall ahead as well, with choices
ranging from huge histories to intensely personal memoirs.
</P>
<P>
   Here are Cox News Service book critic Teresa K. Weaver's best
bets:
</P>
<P>
   -- FICTION
</P>
<P>
   ``A Man in Full'' by Tom Wolfe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bech at Bay'' by John Updike
</P>
<P>
   ``By the Light of My Father's Smile'' by Alice Walker
</P>
<P>
   -- NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Century'' by Harold Evans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Seekers: A History of Man's Search for Meaning'' by Daniel
Boorstin.
</P>
<P>
   ``N.C. Wyeth: A Biography'' by David Michaelis.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
