<HEADER>
A7772 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-PICKS-COX     09-03 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-PICKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Minireviews: What's hjot for books this fall
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 6: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Teresa K. Weaver
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   F i c t i o n
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Loop'' by Nicholas Evans (Delacorte, $25.95). Three
years after ``The Horse Whisperer,'' Evans returns with a story of
Helen Ross, a biologist sent alone into the hostile countryside to
protect endangered wolves. (September)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Welcome to the World, Baby Girl!'' by Fannie Flagg (Random
House, $25.95). Eleven years after ``Fried Green Tomatoes at the
Whistle Stop Cafe,'' Alabama native Flagg returns with the story of
Dena Nordstrom, a TV anchorwoman with a dazzling future and a deep,
dark past. (September)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Flights of Angels: Stories'' by Ellen Gilchrist (Little,
Brown &AMP; Co., $24). Twenty new adventures involving the
unforgettable characters that devotees have come to expect from
this National Book Award winner.
</P>
<P>
   (September)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``In the Pond'' by Ha Jin (Zoland Books, $20). This first
novel from the acclaimed short story writer and Emory University
professor depicts life in a small factory town in China: the
maneuvering, petty jealousies and injustices of an ordinary man who
tangles with the party bosses. (November)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Bag of Bones'' by Stephen King (Scribner, $28). A
much-anticipated novel from the master of sheer, screaming horror
contains ``everything I now know about marriage, lust and ghosts.''
It's a deeper, more complex King behind this tale of a grieving
husband plagued by nightmares and writer's block. (Sept. 22)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Poisonwood Bible'' by Barbara Kingsolver
(HarperCollins, $27.50). In her first novel since 1993's ``Pigs in
Heaven,'' Kingsolver tells the story of Nathan Price, an
evangelical Baptist who takes his wife and four daughters to live
in the Belgian Congo in 1959. (Oct. 7)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Blue Light'' by Walter Mosley (Little, Brown &AMP; Co., $23).
In the mid-1960s, several people are struck by a cosmic blue light
that ``quickens'' their DNA, causing them instantaneously to evolve
far beyond the present state of the human race. It's an interesting
departure for Mosley, author of the best-selling Easy Rawlins
mystery series. (October)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Vampire Armand'' by Anne Rice (Knopf, $26.95). In the
latest installment of her Vampire Chronicles, Rice crosses
centuries and continents as she tells the story of Armand,
eternally young with the face of a Botticelli angel, who first
appeared in ``Interview With the Vampire.'' (Oct. 13)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``I Married a Communist'' by Philip Roth (Houghton Mifflin,
$26). At the height of the McCarthy era, radio actor Iron Rinn
(born Ira Ringold) marries the nation's reigning radio actress, Eve
Frame (born Chava Fromkin). With Eve's revelation to a gossip
columnist of her husband's ``espionage'' for the Soviet Union,
their private drama becomes a national scandal. (October)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Best Little Boy in the World Grows Up'' by Andrew
Tobias (Random House, $22.95). In this witty and affirming sequel
to his ``The Best Little Boy in the World'' (written under the
pseudonym John Reid), Tobias tells the story of the next 25 years
in the life of the title character, and the progress of the gay
rights movement. (September)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Bech at Bay'' by John Updike (Knopf, $23). Henry Bech, the
moderately successful writer who was the hero of ``Bech: A Book''
(1970) and ``Bech Is Back'' (1982), is back again _ older but
scarcely wiser. (October)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``By the Light of My Father's Smile'' by Alice Walker (Random
House, $22.95). An American family moves to an outpost in the
remote mountains of Mexico to live amid the Mundo, an endangered
band of mixed-race blacks and Indians. (October)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Two Cities'' by John Edgar Wideman (Houghton Miflin, $24).
A young woman named Kassima retreats from life after losing her
loved ones to Pittsburgh's violent streets. Ultimately, a boxful of
old photographs provides her with an unexpected means of healing.
(September)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``A Man in Full'' by Tom Wolfe (Farrar Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$27.50). This unbelievably hyped novel _ Wolfe's first major work
since ``The Bonfire of the Vanities'' 11 years ago _ is told from
five points of view and centers on Charles Croker, a real estate
developer and former Georgia Tech football hero who finds himself
$1.3 billion in debt and in danger of losing his 29,000-acre
plantation. As Croker's financial woes intensify, Atlanta is thrust
into a racial crisis when a college football star is accused of
raping a blue blood's daughter. (Nov. 10)
</P>
<P>
   N o n f i c t i o n
</P>
<P>
   -- ``King of the World: The Creation of Muhammad Ali'' by David
Remnick (Random House, $25). The Pulitzer Prize-winning author of
``Lenin's Tomb'' (1994) _ and the new editor of The New Yorker _
relates the story of the rise of the legendary Muhammad Ali.
(October)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Something to Declare,'' essays by Julia Alvarez
</P>
<P>
   (Algonquin, $20.95). In her first book of nonfiction, Alvarez
writes about the effects of exile on her life and her writing.
(October)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Seekers: A History of Man's Search for Meaning'' by
Daniel Boorstin (Random House, $25.95). Who are we? Why are we
here? This is the history of the Western heritage of ideas, told
through the lives of great thinkers from Moses and Aristotle to
Karl Marx and Albert Einstein. (September)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The American Heritage History of the United States'' by
Douglas Brinkley (Viking, $50). Acclaimed historian Brinkley (``The
Unfinished Presidency: Jimmy Carter's Quest for Global Peace'')
settles for nothing less than documenting the story of America.
(November)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The American Century'' by Harold Evans (Knopf, $60). A
sweeping, strikingly illustrated account of the people and events
that gave rise to America's political and cultural dominance in the
20th century. (October)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``A Likely Story: One Summer With Lillian Hellman'' by
Rosemary Mahoney (Doubleday, $23.95). This memoir recalls a
17-year-old aspiring writer's
</P>
<P>
   grueling summer in the employ of her idol. (December)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``For the Love of the Game: My Story'' by Michael Jordan
(Crown, $50). The basketball star who transcended sport to become
one of the 20th century's global icons recalls his career. (Oct.
27)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Lindbergh'' by A. Scott Berg (Putnam, $30). A National Book
Award-winning biographer takes on a legendary, controversial and
enigmatic figure in American history, Charles A. Lindbergh.
(September)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Thurgood Marshall: American Revolutionary'' by Juan
Williams (Times Books, $30). The author of the best-selling ``Eyes
on the Prize'' (1987) spent more than eight years researching this
major biography of the late Supreme Court justice, a complex,
compelling figure in American history. (October)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan'' by Edmund Morris (Random
House, $30). The Pulitzer Prize-winning biographer of Theodore
Roosevelt spent 13 years researching and writing this unusual
first-person narrative of the beloved former president. (October)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``All Too Human: A Political Education'' by George
Stephanopoulos (Little, Brown &AMP; Co., $27.95). A candid, irreverent
memoir by the former senior counselor to the president about life
in the White House during President Clinton's first term. (Nov. 19)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Tennis Partner: A Doctor's Story of Friendship and
Loss'' by Abraham Verghese (HarperCollins, $25). Forced to come to
terms with the tragic fate of David, a medical student and former
tennis pro,
</P>
<P>
   Verghese gains a new understanding of the deepest meaning of
friendship. (September)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Eudora Welty: A Writer's Life'' by Ann Waldron (Doubleday).
A former reporter for The Atlanta Constitution reconstructs the
life of the famous author, one of the most reclusive of recluses.
(December)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``N.C. Wyeth: A Biography'' by David Michaelis (Knopf, $40).
The first full-scale biography of a great American illustrator and
the founder of an artistic dynasty. (October)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
