r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIENDS-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      09-03 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIENDS-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENSEMBLE CAST MAKES `FRIENDS' A TALKY DOWNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - All the iars, cheaters and adulterers who wallow
through ``Your Friends and Neighbors'' feel bad about their sexual
transgressions and infidelities. But that doesn't stop them from
sinning every chance they get.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they should run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they share their misery in this unhappy comedy of
venom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your Friends and Neighbors'' displays a painful intimacy about
sexual misery with a group of people who are animated only by the
unease of their frustrated lives and what passes for relationships
among the overanalytical.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Neil LaBute mined this same frigid territory
with his first film, ``In the Company of Men,'' in which his
women-hating heroes mentally tortured a deaf secretary because they
could get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute comes back with sharper and wittier vitriol in ``Your
Friends and Neighbors,'' in which men and women torture each other
under the theory that you always hate the ones you can reach. This
particular ``menage a angst'' centers on three friends:
</P>
<P>
   - Jerry (Ben Stiller), a college drama professor who has never
found a relationship or a romantic moment he can't dissect to
death.
</P>
<P>
   - Barry (Aaron Eckhart), a sexual sniveler who tries to whine
his wife into being happier.
</P>
<P>
   - Cary (Jason Patric), a psychotic who rehearses his bed talk
and seduces women for revenge.
</P>
<P>
   The women they inflict themselves upon include Jerry's longtime
girlfriend (Catherine Keener), who will do anything for a moment of
peace, and Barry's wife (Amy Brenneman), whose most romantic notion
is the cessation of lust.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the whirlpool of their libidos, these friendless
enemies deceive each other in spiraling patterns. Their only solace
is their only punishment: None of them can ever be happy.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute twists his characters through painful rounds of sexual
balletics, a dance at which he has become much more adept than he
was during ``In the Company of Men.''
</P>
<P>
   As scriptwriter, he reveals the bitterness that can underline
the most mundane conversations between men and women who are
through with each other without admitting it.
</P>
<P>
   As director, he films most of the encounters from uncomfortable
angles: too close, too intimate. His shots are designed to make us
uncomfortable, to feel the same dis-ease that his characters do
with their lives.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Your Friends and Neighbors'' would have worked better as a
shorter film or with the addition of other characters who had
something else going on in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute's people are all cut from the same cloth, and the
repetitious pattern wears out the movie's ability to depress us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your Friends and Neighbors'' comes from the same depressive
sexual perspective as ``Carnal Knowledge ''but without attaining
that film's emotional peaks.
</P>
<P>
   Keener complains about all her lovers: ``You just talk too
much.'' It's the problem with the movie, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your Friends and Neighbors'' is rated R for profanity, sex and
nudity. For all its incessant talk about sex, the physical acts are
deglamorized, anti-erotic. That's LaBute's point: Sex is not the
province of Eros. It's the battleground of Ares. 3 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 1735EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
