<HEADLINE>
WAS SUPPORT FROM BLACK CELEBS THE MISSING MAGIC INGREDIENT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is it about being criticized _ and then canned _ that
forces somebody to abandon his middle-of-the-road demeanor and say
what he really thinks?
</P>
<P>
   Magic Johnson, late of ``The Magic Hour,'' or, as my Southern
California colleagues mercilessly dubbed it, ``the tragic hour,''
has renewed vigor. Watch his lame-duck talker and you'll notice a
kind of yeah-we-bad attitude, giving ``Magic'' a certain zip it
lacked precancellation. Still stinks, but the odor no longer
literally cleans out the senses.
</P>
<P>
   Magic is now discussing the disaster, and, surprisingly, he
chose a black-owned outlet to do it. Radio, no less. During his
playing days, Magic wasn't what you'd call an outspoken brother
with a cultural conscience. But change is good, especially when
it's in your favor.
</P>
<P>
   He recently told Los Angeles-based Radioscope, the radio
features syndicate, that black celebrities dissed him and ignored
him, zooming past him as if he were a brother trying to catch a cab
after nightfall. Figured his amateurish hour was too low-wattage to
pump their high-priced wares.
</P>
<P>
   Such snubs hurt his show, he says; he even theorizes that
similar treatment helped bring other late-night brothers to their
knees. He talks of Keenen Ivory Wayans and Sinbad's ``Vibe'' as
having had similar problems with the A-list black folks, whom he
refuses to name (hey, his boldness goes only so far). But let's
face it, how many A-list black film and TV stars are there?
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have to support each other, and we don't do that,''
Magic told Radioscope. ``Black stars think that if they're not on
Leno or Letterman, then they're not making it. That's the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Worse, says the Magic Man, was how some of those black celebs
were unknowingly led astray by white publicists and managers with
no stake in black industry progress. These publicists often run
interference for stars, at the expense of ``worthy black causes.''
</P>
<P>
   I've never thought of a talk show as a social or political
cause, but I get his drift. From the new organizations urging
moviegoers to attend black films on opening weekends (to impress
theater owners enough to keep them showing these and other black
films) to a Los Angeles group campaigning to save black-cast shows
like ``The Parent'Hood,'' there's a sense that black art is dying.
</P>
<P>
   The contention is that if African-Americans don't support black
art, who will? This is a dicey proposition; not every show with a
black cast needs to be saved, and not every movie starring black
folks is a viewing joy. In fact, many are painful disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   Magic's own late-night party tanked partly because of Magic, and
he admits as much, saying, ``Maybe I wasn't the right person.''
Same could be said of Wayans. And Chris Spencer. It became clear
early that Magic was merely a Celebrity chatting up Another
Celebrity, moaning together about the joys and tribulations of
Being Famous. Case in point was last week's show with Will Smith. I
thought I'd stumbled upon three guys (sidekick Tommy Davidson was
in on it) hanging out after a game of hoops.
</P>
<P>
   Magic does make a good point, though I question whether a
professional basketball player who employed a white agent and was
known to be difficult to pin down because of his ``handlers,'' is
the most credible individual to make it.
</P>
<P>
   But welcome back anyway, my brother. He says he'll continue to
urge blacks to support whomever makes the next attempt at a black
variety show because, ``We still need an avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, even though my show is canceled ... all minorities
suffer. Because regardless if the show was good or not, you don't
have an outlet anymore. Now we will complain because we don't have
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   While also remembering we're better off accepting nothing than
just anything.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
