<SLUG> BC-TV-ANIMORPHS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANIMORPHS` BOOK SERIES TAKES SHAPE ON NICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Kids all over America will morph into couch potatoes
tonight, (note: Friday, Aug. 4) as the tube adaptation of the
fabulously popular ``Animorphs'' book series makes its debut on the
Nickelodeon cable network.
</P>
<P>
   The books (15 million in print since 1996) tell the continuing
story of a group of young friends who get the gift of
shape-shifting from a dying alien prince. By becoming any living
creature they touch, the kids, led by brave and true Jake, do
battle against the evil Yeerks, who are trying to take over the
human race.
</P>
<P>
   A live-action TV series based on a megapopular book series would
seem to have a built-in audience ready and waiting for whatever
hits the screen. But expectations will be sky-high among
``Animorphs'' fans, who typically devour the sequential little
books cover to cover.
</P>
<P>
   This new series' toughest competition won't be whatever
counterprogramming the Disney Channel comes up with but, rather,
the millions of mind-movie adaptations already in production inside
young readers' heads.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Forte, executive producer of ``Animorphs,'' knows the
perils of a text-to-TV transition. A couple of years ago, Forte and
Scholastic Productions oversaw just such a transition for the
even-more-popular-if-that's-possible ``Goosebumps'' books. That
anthology series quickly became the most popular thing on kid TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reading the books is a very private experience for kids,''
said Forte, in a recent telephone interview. ``All of this is in
their mind's eye. When you go to television, it becomes a shared
experience. You have to keep true to the things they hold onto,
which are usually the characters and the overall story line.''
</P>
<P>
   Forte said that protecting the makeup of key characters is
all-important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, we would never think of making Jake a loser,'' she
said. ``He would definitely not change.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said ongoing story elements must remain intact, within
``a new reality, one that works for an audio-visual medium.''
</P>
<P>
   The speed of storytelling, for example, will be the chief
difference kids may notice between the books and the new show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pacing is different in the show,'' she said. ``It has to
be, to keep the audience watching. There are pages of descriptive
material and exposition in the books. Exposition doesn't work very
well in television.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also can't do justice to some of the descriptions of what
it feels like to be the animals. What we've done is captured, in a
visual style, that kind of energy and feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   In one scene, for example, the kids morph into lizards. To
capture that moment, the show attempted to visually ``create a
sense of nervousness and jeopardy,'' Forte said. ``We sort of gave
it a `lizardvision' look, for lack of a better term, that gives it
a special energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes sort of our our answer to those very wonderful
descriptions in the book.''
</P>
<P>
   Forte has obviously spent some time analyzing the vast appeal of
the book series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like a metaphor for adolescence and for
childhood,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids have a great sense of empowerment. They're able to
accomplish amazing things, not just through their ability to morph.
They are true heroes. They are loyal, they are smart, they work
cooperatively. It sounds corny, but those are things kids aspire
to.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, they're feeling some alienation as they get
older. People have expectations for them they're not sure how to
meet. The books create a reality that many kids feel already: `I
don't know how to handle this, the changes going on in my life, but
I will prevail. I'll figure out how to do it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The animals are sort of a metaphor for all of that. They are
not controllable, which is just the way kids feel when they get
into adolescence. They don't know how to control themselves, their
body is changing, their feelings are changing, their expectations
are changing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
