<P>
   ELDERHOSTEL (Kotzbebue, Alaska) _ Martha Rowe, three weeks shy
of her 77th birthday, found herself heading out of Kotzebue on a
beat-up yellow bus with a taped-together steering wheel, cracked
windshield and seats that slid around with every bump and curve in
the unpaved road. Her destination was a primitive fish camp on a
narrow strip of gravel beach between the tundra and the Chukchi
Sea, on the outskirts of Kotzebue, 26 miles above the Arctic
Circle, closer to Russia than Anchorage. ``I wanted an adventure,''
said Ms. Rowe, a retired clinical director of physical therapy at
the University of Florida in Gainesville. So did her fellow
travelers, 13 older men and women on a week-long odyssey with
Elderhostel, the nonprofit organization whose educational trips
here and abroad have become a rite of passage for a certain segment
of the 55 and over set. By Sara Rimer.
