<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORFUL NARRATIVE BRINGS QUEST FOR BLACK DIAMONDS, BLACK GOLD TO
LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Black diamonds! Black gold!
</P>
<P>
   Those familiar with the energy business will recognize those as
romantic pseudonyms for lucrative findings of coal and oil.
</P>
<P>
   The phrases are also the title of a compelling work now out by
Fort Worth native Don Woodard about the legendary Texas Pacific
Coal and Oil Co. In full, Woodard's book is titled ``Black
Diamonds! Black Gold: The Saga of Texas Pacific Coal and Oil
Company'' (Texas Tech University Press, 322 pages, $29.95).
</P>
<P>
   The full title is an apt description of this dense book. It is a
saga. But in addition to writing a fascinating and rich history of
a multibillion-dollar energy company, Woodard has also skillfully
captured the spirit of a hundred-year era.
</P>
<P>
   From his description of coal miners drinking at the horseshoe
bar at the Snake Saloon in Thurber to the ``Seventh Street Gang,''
a group of powerful businessmen wielding political clout at the
Fort Worth Club, Woodard has written such a detailed history that
readers will feel they are on the inside.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that is because Woodard was an insider of sorts; he was
a landman for T&AMP;P from 1952 to 1964. But it's his skillful
storytelling that makes the history dance off the page.
</P>
<P>
   And when T&AMP;P first hits its black diamonds and black gold,
readers have a front-row seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day in 1880, while riding through northern Erath's hills,
Will Johnson stopped at a farmhouse for a cool drink of water,''
Woodard writes. ``He told the farmer that he was looking for timber
for his fence post-and-crosstie operation. The sodbuster replied by
telling of the hard time he was having digging a well.
</P>
<P>
   ```Black rock makes it hard to dig,' he allowed, scuffing at a
small pile that had been chiseled from the shallow hole. ...
Johnson became excited _ he knew instantly that the black rock was
coal. As he gazed intently at the substance, visions of black
diamonds danced in his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, W.W. Johnson, a recent Texas transplant supplying posts
and crossties to the Texas and Pacific Railway as it finished the
first transcontinental railroad line, now had a new product for the
railroad: coal. The big black engines on the rail line hungered for
it. And a company was born.
</P>
<P>
   T&AMP;P's first gusher of oil at the McCleskey farm in West Texas,
almost 30 years later, also had a profound impact on the company,
the nearby town of Ranger and the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``News of the McCleskey's storybook ending raced across Texas _
indeed across America _ like a prairie fire,'' Woodard writes.
``There was no radio in 1917 _ the first commercial radio broadcast
did not air until 1920 _ so word was spread by telegram, newspaper,
and word of mouth. ... The fame of Ranger swept over the land and
the black gold rush was on.''
</P>
<P>
   After that a host of businessmen well known to Fort Worth
natives were involved with the company. Among them Amon Carter, Sid
Richardson and H.B. ``Babe'' Fuqua, a former CEO of the company and
a legendary figure.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard pulls from a book on the Fort Worth Club by Irvin Farman
to describe Fuqua's considerable influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some three decades _ the '50s, '60s, and '70s, especially
after the death of Amon Carter in 1955 _ Babe Fuqua's name was
synonymous with civic leadership, hardheaded business acumen and
political clout in Fort Worth,'' Farman wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard adds: ``It could be said that no decision of the Fort
Worth establishment was ever made without Fuqua's acquiescence and
involvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuqua was also instrumental in T&AMP;P's development. But after
decades of growth, the Texas independent was eventually sold in
1963 for $277 million to Indiana-based Joseph E. Seagram &AMP; Sons.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Seagram sold T&AMP;P to Sun Oil Co. for $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Oil spun off the company in 1988 and a year later, the name
changed to Oryx Energy Co., which comes from the Greek word meaning
``to dig,'' Woodard writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``While not a bad name for an oil company, the few graying
veterans who still attend the TP ex-employee Christmas parties in
the 1990s would sniff, `Not as good as Texas Pacific,''' he writes.
``But Texas Pacific was gone with the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for us, Woodard was still around to write its
history before that evaporated into the air as well.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BLURBS
</P>
<P>
   ``The Emperor's Nightingale: Restoring the Integrity of the
Corporation in the Age of Shareholder Activism''
</P>
<P>
   By Robert A.G. Monks
</P>
<P>
   Addison Wesley, $26
</P>
<P>
   Corporations, according to Adam Smith, are artificial life
forms, neither human nor machine, but parts of both. Yet the
corporation is also on the ``verge of a profound restoration: a
return to its original, highly adaptive and accountable form,''
writes investment adviser Robert Monks. Part of that is a
resurgence toward corporate governance, the way corporations
balance power. Monks describes this new climate and the role
shareholders play.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting Started in Security Analysis''
</P>
<P>
   By Peter J. Klein
</P>
<P>
   John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $18.95
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, there is a science to investing, argues
PaineWebber Vice President for Investments Peter Klein. It's called
security analysis, but Klein warns up front that it could take
years, even decades, to master it. His book takes readers through
an overview of the fundamentals of security analysis, with chapters
on accounting, economics, investment mathematics and quantitative
analysis (and those are the easy chapters). Concepts such as equity
analysis and credit analysis are also included.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Write for Results''
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Lauchman
</P>
<P>
   Amacom, $39.95
</P>
<P>
   This is the first book in a series developed by the American
Management Association's publishing arm that combines a book with a
CD-ROM. The association calls this series the Get Ahead Toolkit.
Because of its interactive nature, it provides a much more lively
look at material that can often be troublesome to pick up and read.
This book covers the basics of effective writing; the CD provides
hands-on training using the principles in the book.
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
