<P>
   UNDATED _ What is it about being criticized _ and then canned _
that forces somebody to abandon his middle-of-the-road demeanor and
say what he really thinks? Magic Johnson, late of ``The Magic
Hour,'' or, as my Southern California colleagues mercilessly dubbed
it, ``the tragic hour,'' has renewed vigor. Watch his lame-duck
talker and you'll notice a kind of yeah-we-bad attitude, giving
``Magic'' a certain zip it lacked precancellation. Still stinks,
but the odor no longer literally cleans out the senses. By KEN
PARISH PERKINS. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-BOOKS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Black diamonds! Black gold! Those familiar with the
energy business will recognize those as romantic pseudonyms for
lucrative findings of coal and oil. The phrases are also the title
of a compelling work now out by Fort Worth native Don Woodard about
the legendary Texas Pacific Coal and Oil Co. In full, Woodard's
book is titled ``Black Diamonds! Black Gold: The Saga of Texas
Pacific Coal and Oil Company'' (Texas Tech University Press, 322
pages, $29.95). By TERESA MCUSIC. Story has moved in ``f''
financial category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
