<P>
   AUTO-REVIEW-AZR (Undated) _ Has it really been 10 years since
the Mazda Miata single-handedly reignited America's enthusiasm for
lightweight roadsters, years after the British had packed up their
little sports cars and gone home? By Bob Golfen.
</P>
<P>
   CARS-RACING-NYT (Undated) _ Every form of racing has its
spiritual home: Indianapolis for Indy cars, Charlotte for stock
cars, Pomona for dragsters. And for a half-century, sports-car
racing has had Watkins Glen, N.Y., host from 1961 to 1980 of the
United States Grand Prix Formula One race. By Joseph Siano.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES-BLOOM (Detroit) _ Even with the world's largest
automaker wounded and the U.S. stock market enduring a turbulent
month, cars and trucks sold at a healthy 14.6 million annual rate
in August.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-GALANT (Detroit) _ Mitsubishi Galant: Dressed up and
itching to be the life of the party. By Michelle Krebs. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-REVIEW-BOS (Undated) _ Frontier, introduced as a 1998
model, is a simple truck from Nissan _ actually a line of simple
little pickups, starting with the standard cab equipped with basic
5-speed manual transmission, rear-drive, and a four-cylinder engine
with a sticker price under $12,000. With the $470 delivery charge,
it works out to $12,460 to put a bottom-feeder Nissan Frontier in
your driveway _ and there isn't much dicker in that sticker. The
dealer markup reflected in that price is hardly enough to make it
worthwhile taking it off the delivery truck and mounting the
hubcaps. By John R. White.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ Your next car is being designed by
mathematicians _ number crunchers who spend long hours bending
things, inventing computer models, and wade gleefully through miles
of printouts to perfect the widgets and whatsits that go into a
modern car. To me, at least, there is some fun in this boring work;
the lab has moved onto the track. By John R. White.
</P>
