<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKRUPTCY-CONGRESS-$ADV06-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS SEEKS TO TOUGHEN BANKRUPTCY LAWS AS PERSONAL DEBT MOUNTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 6)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As personal bankruptcy filings reach record highs,
Republican leaders in Congress are pressing hard for a law that
would make it tougher for people to file for protection from
creditors.
</P>
<P>
   One in 70 U.S. households filed for bankruptcy last year,
according to the American Bankruptcy Institute, a nonprofit group
that represents more than 6,300 bankruptcy professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of legislation that would make it harder to qualify
for bankruptcy protection say the system is badly abused by some
people who are escaping debt they are able to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous need for (tougher bankruptcy laws)
because there are those who really do need protection, and those
who are utilizing the laws improperly and shouldn't be able to get
away with it,'' said Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin G.
Hatch, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   An advertisement that has appeared in Capitol Hill newspapers
over the last few weeks shows the feet of a man and a woman
relaxing on a crystal blue beach with a yacht in the background,
ostensibly after filing for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bankruptcy shouldn't be a free ride for the wealthy,'' says
the advertisement, which was paid for by banking and retail
organizations and housing material providers.
</P>
<P>
   But critics of the House and Senate bankruptcy bills say many
people who file for protection are in dire financial straits and
are victimized by risky lending and credit policies.
</P>
<P>
   The typical bankruptcy case doesn't involve someone living high
on the hog, said Elizabeth Warren, a Harvard Law School professor
who specializes in bankruptcy law. She said the average family
seeking protection from creditors makes less than $23,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a poorer, more deeply in debt group of families going
bankrupt every year,'' Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   In attempt to squeeze those beach bums out of the system, bills
pending in the House and Senate aim at shifting some debtors from
Chapter 7 bankruptcies _ the least cumbersome of two choices for
individuals _ into Chapter 13.
</P>
<P>
   Under Chapter 7, a consumer is able to discharge much unsecured
debt, such as credit card or medical bills, within a few months. To
do so, a debtor must liquidate assets and pay what he or she can to
creditors. Under Chapter 13, a debtor commits to repay at least a
portion of the debt with future earnings over three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   Arrangements for repaying secured debt, such as loans for a car
or a house, are typically made separately.
</P>
<P>
   The 186-page House bill, sponsored by Rep. George W. Gekas,
R-Pa., was approved by the House 306 to 118 in June. The 123-page
Senate bill, sponsored by Sen. Charles E. Grassley, R-Iowa, and
Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill, was approved by the Senate Judiciary
panel 16 to 2 in June.
</P>
<P>
   Both bills would prohibit a debtor from filing for Chapter 7 if
the household earned more than the median income _ $51,000 for a
family of four _ and was able to repay at least 20 percent of
unsecured debt.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McGarry, spokesman for the Visa U.S.A. credit card company,
said the current system can allow someone earning $100,000 a year
to file under Chapter 7. He said personal bankruptcy filings cost
the credit card industry $9 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current bankruptcy system is unfair because it allows
people who have an ability to repay a portion of what they owe to
simply walk away,'' McGarry said. ``It's the only social welfare
system not based on need.''
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Culhane, a professor of consumer bankruptcy law at
Creighton University in Omaha, Neb., who is studying how the
legislation would affect debtors, said many people depend on credit
cards because they have lost a job, been divorced or have a serious
illness and huge medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people have no clue how fast interest builds up,''
Culhane said. ```They don't have a real good feel for what interest
rates and late charges can add up to.''
</P>
<P>
   The bills also encourage out-of-court credit counseling.
</P>
<P>
   However, while the Senate bill would empower creditors to
request that a judge decide if a debtor qualifies for Chapter 7,
the House bill would use a computerized formula to determine if a
debtor qualifies. The Clinton administration has denounced the
House bill as ``rigid and arbitrary.''
</P>
<P>
   Differences in the two bills would have to be ironed out by
negotiators from both chambers before the legislation could go to
the president for consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., a supporter of the
Senate bill, said last week he hoped for a vote on bankruptcy
legislation as early as next week. But opponents are threatening to
block it by attaching several controversial amendments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The GOP believes that the bankruptcy system should be a
collection system for the credit card industry, funded by the
taxpayers,'' said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., who has pledged
to try to sink the legislation by attaching a proposal to raise the
minimum wage, which is opposed by many Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley predicted the Senate would ``have to wrestle'' with a
long list of amendments, but added, ``I do expect a bankruptcy bill
will be passed.''
</P>
<P>
   Durbin, a co-sponsor of the Senate bill, now says he won't
support it unless it requires credit card companies to spell out
for consumers how interest rates _ which average 14 percent to 18
percent _ can add up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to avoid the abuses of bankruptcy and the abuses of
credit card solicitation,'' Durbin said. ``A lot of people are
misled. They don't know the real penalties or interest rates. We're
looking for something like the nutrition labels on food that is
easily understood.''
</P>
<P>
   A record 1.35 million consumer bankruptcies were filed in 1997,
and 361,908 were filed in the second quarter of 1998, the most ever
reported in a three-month period, according to the Administrative
Office of the U.S. Courts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Warren characterizes the legislation in Congress as ``a billion
dollar gift to the consumer credit industry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill was written by credit industry lobbyists to further
increase the profitability of the credit card business, which is
already twice as profitable as any other lending business,'' she
said. ``It falls hardest on vulnerable Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s consumer debt shot up, mirrored by a spike in
bankruptcy filings in the 1990s, according to data from the Federal
Reserve and the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation. Warren said
the spike in personal bankruptcy filings was directly linked to
deregulation of consumer interest rates, which enabled banks to
drastically jack up credit card rates in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The wide availability of credit cards and ``risky lending
practices'' by banks have fueled the surge in bankruptcies, said
Samuel Gerdano, executive director of the American Bankruptcy
Institute in Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Gerdano said there is a danger in expecting that a new law alone
is going to change consumers' behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hope people use their freedom responsibly,'' he said.
``When they don't, bankruptcy is there as the kind of economic
cleanup of the household balance sheet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
