<HEADLINE>
EARL CAPSIZES BOATS OFF FLORIDA, LASHES SOUTHEAST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Fla. _ Two fishing vessels straggling to port were
caught and capsized during Hurricane Earl's erratic push into the
Florida Panhandle early Thursday, killing one crew member.
</P>
<P>
   With 80 mph winds and heavy rains, Earl left flooded streets and
power outages as it crossed the state. Tornados spawned as it moved
into the Carolinas, where one person was killed and three others
injured near St. Helena Island south of Charleston, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   James Martin, 33, captain of the Me-Too, and two of his crew
clung to the hull of their capsized boat for four hours off Florida
before being rescued by the Coast Guard. Another crew member from
the companion boat Can-Too was rescued from a life raft about 5
a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The body of Can-Too crew member Kalvin Fountain washed ashore
Thursday morning. The boat's captain, Paul Pence, 68, remains
unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought 17 to 20-foot waves all day and all night,'' said
Martin, squinting through blood-shot eyes. ``The final one took us
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The crews of the two boats had been fishing since last Friday
and were returning to port with a full load. They expected the
storm to follow a north by northwest path, but were caught when it
veered due north, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The storm got a jump on us,'' Martin said. ``We couldn't
outrun it.''
</P>
<P>
   The eye of the category two hurricane made landfall between 1
a.m. and 2 a.m., EDT, Thursday, after dumping more than 12 inches
of rain from its leading edge. Panama City and surrounding counties
reported street flooding, spotty road damage and scattered power
outages, but merchants and hoteliers were relieved that the storm
did no major property damage just days before the Labor Day
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Mandatory evacuations were ordered for residents of some of the
barrier islands off the coast, but most residents chose to ride out
what proved to be a mostly inconvenient storm. By contrast, in 1995
Hurricane Erin killed 11 people and Hurricane Opal killed 27
residents along the Florida Gulf coast.
</P>
<P>
   Earl was downgraded to a tropical storm by mid-morning, as it
continued to churn across Georgia and the Carolinas, dropping heavy
rains.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists were back in coastal waters under sunny skies by noon
Wednesday, but an exhausted Martin was limping on a bandaged leg as
he hoisted himself over the side of a boat returning to the St.
Andrews Marina from another attempt at locating the still-missing
Pence.
</P>
<P>
   He said the two fishing vessels had been coming to shore about
9:30 p.m. Wednesday when the Can-Too capsized just ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were following them in,'' Martin said, ``and it was more or
less a freak sea that hit us. We were running for the pass.''
</P>
<P>
   He saw the life raft deploy on the other boat before his own
boat flipped. Crew member Marcok Blake was later pulled from that
raft.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the water rushed in, it stripped my clothing off,''
Martin said. ``That's how much force it had.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his two crew members, Charles Anderson and Justin Powell,
were trapped under their capsized boat but swam free. They clung to
the hull and waited for rescue. Martin said he feared they would
find Pence, co-owner of both boats, underneath the Can-Too once the
boat is righted.
</P>
<P>
   He described Pence as ``one of the best,'' an experienced
fisherman with decades on the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard was called out for another rescue Wednesday
afternoon, when two men in a sailboat were capsized in the heavy
swells and stranded on Shell Island near here.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard had to turn back a 41-foot boat dispatched to
retrieve them due to the high seas. The Coast Guard was attempting
a second rescue when the two men managed to swim nearly a mile to
shore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
