<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following religion features moved during the last week.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmission of these stories, call 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   FALWELL-NEW CHURCH-TEX (Lynchburg, Va.) _ The Rev. Jerry
Falwell, who emerged on the national scene in 1980 as founder of
the Moral Majority, is planning to build ``the largest sanctuary in
North America'': a 12,000-seat accommodation for his 22,000-member
Thomas Road Baptist Church in Lynchburg, Va. By Jim Jones.
</P>
<P>
   POLYGAMOUS-AZR (Colorado City, Ariz.) _ It was 4:25 p.m. at
Justin's house and the welcome call ``Come to dinner!'' went out
over the intercom. From all over the 35,000 square-foot, 31-bedroom
home the kids came pouring into the cafeteria-sized dining room.
Justin, 45, sat and smiled amid the clang of silverware and plates
as many of his 10 wives and 28 children consumed the contents of
three casserole dishes of enchiladas. Justin is not his real name;
he asked that he and his wives remain anonymous in exchange for
granting a rare glimpse of polygamous life in this fiercely
secretive community on the Utah-Arizona border. By Mark Shaffer.
</P>
<P>
   FUNDAMENTAL-AZR (Colorado City, Ariz.) _ Wayne LeBaron sat on
the couch snuggling with his new bride and shook his head at the
strangeness of it all. LeBaron, who lives at the foot of a
strawberry-colored cliff near this remote polygamist town, knew
something was stirring within the ranks of the Old World _ the
fundamentalist Mormons who control the community. Then the packages
started arriving _ sent to LeBaron's ranch for safekeeping from the
family of his wife, who was raised in Colorado City.Some contained
cassette tapes of popular music. Others had jewelry. But all had
one thing in common, he said: They are considered contraband by the
fundamentalist Mormon leadership that LeBaron says has recently
been reverting to an even more conservative religious stance. By
Mark Shaffer.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-LABYRINTH-COX (Atlanta) _ Atlanta churches are reviving
the tradition of a medieval labyrinth. By Gayle White.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT (Undated) _ Earlier this month, when nearly
800 Anglican bishops from around the world gathered at the Lambeth
Conference, their once-a-decade meeting in Canterbury, England, one
of the more public faces seemed to belong to one of the newer
prelates, Bishop Geralyn Wolf, head of the Episcopal Church's
Diocese of Rhode Island. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
