<HEADER>
A7852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-O'NEILL-THEATER-REVIE     09-03 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-O'NEILL-THEATER-REVIEW-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BREAD AND BUTTER': O'NEILL'S FIRST PLAY OF INTEREST ONLY AS
YARDSTICK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By WILBORN HAMPTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The good news down on Macdougal Street is that the
Provincetown Playhouse has been thoroughly refurbished and is once
again operating as a theater. It seems all the more fitting that
the first productions in the spiffy and comfortable new space
should be given to the works of Eugene O'Neill, whose early plays
were staged there 80 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For the past month, the Playwrights Theater, which will be a
main tenant of the New York University playhouse, has been
presenting an O'Neill festival that has included a cabaret revue of
songs from his plays; a forum featuring Jose Quintero, the director
who has been one of O'Neill's chief interpreters, and the staging
of a series of his early one-act plays. The festival is now ending
with a production of O'Neill's first full-length play, ``Bread and
Butter.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Kennedy Murphy, the artistic director of the Playwrights
Theater, planned the festival as the kickoff of a project to stage
all 49 of O'Neill's known plays. In a bold if risky step, he chose
a virtually unknown O'Neill work as his first offering.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for staging ``Bread and Butter'' as the festival's
main opening attraction must have seemed compelling. Apart from
being the playwright's first full-length work, it is a play that
had never before been staged.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill wrote it in 1914 while undergoing treatment in a
sanitarium for tuberculosis, and sent it off to a producer. When it
was rejected, O'Neill disowned it and tore up his only copy. But
before destroying it, he submitted it for copyright, and that copy
was discovered only a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, O'Neill knew best. ``Bread and Butter'' is interesting
only as a yardstick by which to measure his growth in later works.
In fact, he used the best parts of ``Bread and Butter'' in a
similar play called ``Before Breakfast'' that was staged by the
Provincetown Players while they were still on Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bread and Butter'' concerns John Brown, a young man from
Bridgetown, Conn., who wants to be an artist but faces opposition
from most of his family and his fiancee. Only one sister, Bessie,
supports him. After he spends a year in New York studying art, the
family and the fiancee give him an ultimatum to come back to
Bridgetown or else. It all ends badly.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the writing is stilted and quaint, filled with dialogue
that no one ever spoke, even in 1914. It tries hard to be clever
but ends mostly in calling attention to its cleverness. As a
result, the characters are little more than cardboard figures who
speak mostly in platitudes about Art and Mammon.
</P>
<P>
   Although at two hours the play is short by O'Neill standards, it
is often repetitious and filled with beginning writers' mistakes
like having close friends or relatives tell each other things they
obviously know as a way of filling in background information for
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Only toward the end, when the play's focus shifts from the
debate over John's dreams of being an artist to marital discord and
divorce, can one see the sparks of dramatic fireworks that would
light up O'Neill's later work.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To be fair, Murphy explains all this to the audience before the
performance as a sort of apologia for O'Neill's early lack of
craft. A note in the press material further points out that since
the playwright never intended ``Bread and Butter'' to be produced,
it is being staged without sets or props and with mostly student
actors wearing modern street dress. Unfortunately, this translates
to the audience's watching an undergraduate rehearsal of an
unfinished play.
</P>
<P>
   Some performances in the cast of 14 show promise, but others are
wincingly inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   Kristoffer Polaha, an engaging young actor, is credible as the
young artist, and carries most of the show. Stacie Lents, as his
sister Bessie, and Brent Vimtrup, as his friend Babe, provide good
supporting turns.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, who directed, tries to inject some energy into the
production, but bouts of shouting and aimless pacing around the
stage are interspersed with listless scenes punctuated by awkward
pauses by actors (perhaps trying to remember their lines) who don't
know where to put their hands.
</P>
<P>
   It is a worthy project Murphy has undertaken and one wishes him
well for the future. Like O'Neill's writing, it can only get
better.
</P>
<P>
   `BREAD AND BUTTER'
</P>
<P>
   By Eugene O'Neill; directed by Stephen Kennedy Murphy. Presented
by the Playwrights Theater Festival of O'Neill. At Provincetown
Playhouse.
</P>
<P>
   With: Stan Carp (Brown), Stacie Lents (Bessie), Avram Ludwig
(Edward), Salem Ludwig (Grammont), Kristoffer Polaha (John),
Paulette O'Dowd (Maud) and Brent Vimtrup (Babe).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
