<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Sept. 4, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unusually high humidity and sporadic rains, some with occasional
thunder, marked the weather pattern over Southern California on
Thursday as tropical moisture steadily streamed northward from Baja
California and the Gulf of California. Friday, scattered showers
and thunderstorms will develop over much of the Southwest states as
an upper-level low off the coast of Southern California continues
to summon tropical moisture into the region. With moisture from the
remnants of Hurricane Isis also drawn into the tropical fray,
flooding rains are possible in parts of Southern California,
Arizona and Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Caught by high-altitude winds blowing from the southwest, the
remnants of Hurricane Earl will retreat off the Middle Atlantic
coast. Nonetheless, showers and thunderstorms, some heavy, are
possible early Friday in northeast North Carolina and southeast
Virginia before the system heads out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered strong thunderstorms will douse parts of southern
Florida with moderate to heavy rains as strengthening, moist winds
from the east team with a disturbance moving west from the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, puffy cumulus clouds will mix with sunshine over the
Northeast from the Appalachians westward. Isolated showers will
develop over the Longfellow Mountains of Maine. East of the
mountains, isolated showers will move off the Northeast coast early
Friday morning, followed by a mix of sunshine and cumulus clouds.
Over the coast, some early morning cirrus clouds from the remnants
of Hurricane Earl will gradually dissipate.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: California Thunder
</P>
<P>
   Just before dawn Thursday, Los Angeles residents were awakened
by peals of thunder echoing across the sky as moist, tropical air
from Hurricane Isis streamed north into the state. Thunderstorms
are a rare event across the Los Angeles basin during the month of
September. On average, thunder is observed at the Los Angeles
airport in only three Septembers out of every 10.
</P>
<P>
   Because thunderstorms prosper in hot, humid conditions, the
chill of the adjacent Pacific Ocean and dryness of nearby deserts
make coastal southern California a poor breeding ground for
thunderstorms.
</P>
</TEXT>
