<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7860 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GONZALEZ-ART-REVIEW-2     09-03 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GONZALEZ-ART-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: A WRY AMBIGUITY IN A WORLD OF VIBRANT COLOR AND TABLOID
DRAMAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Multiculturalism is a complicated phenomenon, both
sweet and bitter. During the last decade, artists and even whole
cultures once excluded from mainstream consideration have gained
admission, however tentative, to the contemporary art market
controlled by the United States and Europe. But the terms of entry
are often capricious and constricting.
</P>
<P>
   One minute the institutional demand is for ``international''
styles based on Western models, the next for work deemed culturally
specific enough to be ``authentic.'' The risk in the first case is
the creation of a kind of global homogeneity; in the second, a new
version of exoticism.
</P>
<P>
   As in any period, the most interesting artists manage to
override conventional options and make rules of their own. Such is
the case with the Colombian painter Beatriz Gonzalez, 59, whose
work is on view at El Museo del Barrio in a 30-year survey,
organized by Carolina Ponce de Leon, that also marks the artist's
New York solo debut.
</P>
<P>
   The very title of the show, ``What an Honor to Be With You at
This Historic Moment,'' catches the tone of Ms. Gonzalez's
figurative painting: wry, mock-formal, hiding reserves of emotion
behind a hard-to-read public face. Ambiguity is everywhere: in
images that mix tabloid dramas with canonical art icons; in a
homely-pretty painting style, and in her own half-defiant,
half-resigned description of her work as ``an underdeveloped
painting for underdeveloped countries.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that her work, with its wealth of topical
references, is intimately bound to a time and place. She grew up in
Colombia in the 1940s and '50s and was shaped by a politically
calamitous era now known simply as ``the Violence.'' In the
country's capital, Bogota, she studied painting and art history,
though the city itself had no collection of European art.
</P>
<P>
   What it did have was a vibrant, multiracial culture and an
avidly sensationalistic popular press. And these elements provided
a source for some of Ms. Gonzalez's earliest works, including the
painting titled ``The Sisga Suicides I'' (1965), which opens the
show.
</P>
<P>
   The smallish picture looks straightforward enough: a half-length
depiction of a young man and woman holding hands and absently
smiling. With its simplified forms and eye-catching colors, it
could be a folk painting: a shop sign, say, sentimentally promoting
the rewards of married life.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the image, clipped from a local newspaper, is based on
a photographic portrait that a young couple had had made just
before they committed suicide by drowning. In a farewell letter
they explained that they were deeply in love but, being religiously
devout, preferred death to sullying the woman's purity.
</P>
<P>
   The painting is one of a number from the late 1960s in which Ms.
Gonzalez explored the pervasive violence of Colombian society. In
the same years, she produced an extraordinary series of ink
drawings on the same theme. Some derive from tabloid photos of
crimes of passion and political murders, others from advertisements
for bodybuilding and headache cures. Significantly, in Ms.
Gonzalez's hands, the two types of images are rendered all but
indistinguishable.
</P>
<P>
   Through the '60s and into the '70s she continued to work with
mass-media images, a radical move in a Latin American culture that
equated ``high art'' with European academic tradition. Then she
began to turn the tables by loosely adapting classic European
masterworks to local vernacular formats.
</P>
<P>
   Dating from this time are a group of inventive and irreverent
paintings that Ms. Gonzalez either executed on, or attached to,
pieces of mass-produced furniture or household utensils picked up
in Bogota's open-air markets. Leonardo da Vinci's ``Last Supper''
appears in garish colors and paint-by-number forms on a faux-wood
dining table. A Degas bather is painted on the interior of a tin
wash basin.
</P>
<P>
   Form and function merged spectacularly in several mural-scale
works not included in the show. In one, Ms. Gonzalez reconstituted
a panoramic waterlily painting by Monet on 62 feet of plastic
shower curtain. For another, she painted Renoir's paean to
middle-class leisure, ``Le Moulin de la Galette,'' on a long scroll
of paper, which she offered for sale by the centimeter, like cloth
from a bolt.
</P>
<P>
   These examples of ``underdeveloped'' painting were many things:
homages to artists whom Ms. Gonzalez genuinely admires, but also a
witty blend of public service work and historical illustration.
They allowed Ms. Gonzalez, who exhibits regularly in Colombia and
has taught there for years, to import European masterworks into her
country, even if second hand. And they demonstrated the sea change
that any art undergoes when it is translated from one culture to
another: forms, meanings and valuations change.
</P>
<P>
   Although such ideas make perfect sense in the '90s, when Ms.
Gonzalez exhibited these works at the Venice Biennale in 1978, they
went virtually unnoticed. In the '80s, she changed direction in her
art, circling around to where she had started out, as history
painter of her own country. Once again she drew on current events,
but she now phrased them in more complex formal terms _ fragmented,
expressionistic, surreal _ as is evident in two closely related
paintings she produced in response to a civic catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1985, armed guerrillas occupied the Palace of
Justice in Bogota, taking dozens of magistrates hostage. The
guerrilla group, one of many in Colombia, had been active for years
and had gained considerable public support. Whether the incident
would have ended peaceably is impossible to say. The military,
reportedly acting without orders from the Colombian president,
bombed the building, killing guerrillas and civilians alike.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gonzalez's paintings, both titled ``Mr. President, What an
Honor to be With You at This Historic Moment,'' depict the event
through a hallucinatory lens. In one picture, done in bright
colors, the grinning president and his cabinet, flanked by
uniformed soldiers, sit at a table that has a bouquet of blood-red
flowers as a centerpiece. In the second, done in a somber newsprint
grisaille, the seated figures remain, but the flowers have been
replaced by a charred human torso.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As always, Ms. Gonzalez is less intent on assigning blame for
deeds done _ almost impossible in this case _ than in suggesting
that violence itself is an existential condition. And its power
reverberates through all of her subsequent work, including a series
of paintings from the early 1990s _ ``Island of the Good-Luck
Rabbit'' (1993) is an example _ in which male corpses dressed in
suits and ties, float Ophelia-like in dark water. Whether their
deaths were violent or accidental is uncertain, but they have all
found a watery grave.
</P>
<P>
   In the artist's most recent paintings of single female figures,
politics, art history and the personal merge. The figures are
adapted from two sources: Gauguin's exoticized images of Polynesian
women and news photos, taken last year, of the distraught mothers
of kidnapped Colombian soldiers. In two of the paintings, weeping
brown-skinned woman wear skirts decorated with scenes of a tropical
paradise lost. In a third, the artist depicts herself, nude, her
skin a deathlike blue, her hands covering her face as if she were
peering through her fingers at things she could barely stand to
see.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gonzalez has called her painting ``a regional art that can't
be recognized universally except as a curiosity.'' And it does pose
problems. Its determinedly rough, anti-academic painting style _
awkward forms, workaday surfaces _ will not be to all tastes. And
its culturally grounded references can make its play of humor,
despair and affection hard to interpret.
</P>
<P>
   Yet her work is dynamic enough to suggest many things and offers
intriguing, if oblique, points of comparison with certain of her
New York contemporaries. Her work has, for instance, parallels with
that of Andy Warhol. Both artists deal with similar popular
material, from tabloid disasters to Last Suppers. Both embody their
images in low-art forms (Warhol in industrial silk screen, Ms.
Gonzalez on inexpensive furniture). Both disguise an art of
passionately alert social observation, behind a facade of studied
neutrality.
</P>
<P>
   Warhol, of course, was a key player in the international
mainstream market. Ms. Gonzalez is not. She has chosen to forge an
artistic universe from her home turf, and it is one of remarkable
richness and depth. It is no surprise to learn that when a catalog
of her collected work was being prepared in Colombia in 1984, she
insisted the book be titled ``Beatriz Gonzalez: Provincial
Artist.'' Like many of her colleagues across the world in the
multicultural '90s, she has turned a ``peripheral'' status into a
badge of pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beatriz Gonzalez: What an Honor to Be With You at This
Historic Moment, Works 1965-1997'' remains at El Museo del Barrio,
1230 Fifth Ave., at 104th Street, through Oct. 25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
