 &HT;    AFC Central capsules
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Story
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE JAGUARS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Tom Coughlin is 26-26 in three seasons with the
Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 11-5, second in AFC Central (wild card, lost in
first round of playoffs).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: RB Natrone Means (FA), C Michael Cheever (injury),
QB Rob Johnson (trade), DE Clyde Simmons (cut), FB Ty Hallock (FA),
C Dave Widell (FA), DT Esera Tuaolo (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: LB Bryce Paup (FA), RB Fred Taylor (D-1a), FS
Donovin Darius (D-1b), DE Fernando Smith (FA), C Quentin Neujahr
(FA), CB Cordell Taylor (D-2).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: In just their fourth season, Jaguars have a
legitimate shot to make it to Super Bowl XXXIII. They are one of
NFL's deepest and most well-rounded teams. Secondary is a concern,
but the Jaguars have plenty of young veterans who might be ready to
step up. QB Mark Brunell is the offensive key, but Coughlin would
prefer to run the football. Offensive line is one of the strongest
in league, and OT Tony Boselli might be NFL's best blocker at his
position. Look for Taylor to make an instant impact splitting time
with veteran RB James Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH STEELERS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Bill Cowher is 69-38 in six seasons with the Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 11-5, first in AFC Central (lost in AFC
championship game).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: WR Yancey Thigpen (FA), CB Chad Scott (injury), OT
John Jackson (FA), LB Greg Lloyd (cut), FB Tim Lester (injury),
offensive coordinator Chan Gailey (Dallas), SS Myron Bell (FA), OG
Tom Myslinski (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: Offensive coordinator Ray Sherman (Minnesota), CB
DeWayne Washington (FA), OG Alan Faneca (D-1), DT Jeremy Staat
(D-2), WR Hines Ward (D-3).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: Sooner or later, free agency departures will result
in some slippage in the division. This could be the year. The
season-ending knee injury to Scott has forced SS Carnell Lake to
move to corner again, disrupting the whole secondary. Much on
offense will depend on continued development of QB Kordell Stewart,
who will have more freedom to audible. There is no proven ``go-to''
wideout, so Sherman wants the ball dumped more to the tight ends
and running backs. Pittsburgh is a veteran team that knows how to
win.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE OILERS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Jeff Fisher is 24-30 in four seasons with the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 8-8, third in AFC Central.
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: OG Kevin Donnalley (FA), RB Ronnie Harmon (cut),
KR Mel Gray (retired), TE Rod Lewis (FA), P Reggie Roby (cut).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: WR Yancey Thigpen (FA), WR Kevin Dyson (D-1), TE
Jackie Harris (FA), CB Samari Rolle (D-2), P Craig Hentrich (FA),
CB Dainon Sidney (D-3).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: Too bad Nashville hasn't embraced what should be an
entertaining team. GM Floyd Reese upgraded the receiving corps for
QB Steve McNair, signing free agents Thigpen and Harris and
drafting Dyson in the first round. The trio should make life easier
for McNair, in his second season as the starter, and take pressure
off RB Eddie George. The Oilers blitz as much as any defense in the
league and count on their corners in man-to-man coverage. Fisher
and coordinator Greg Williams are creative and cause lots of
headaches for opposition. This is a fringe playoff team that
probably won't make the postseason because of killer division.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI BENGALS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Bruce Coslet is 14-11 in two seasons with the Bengals
and 40-50 in six NFL seasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 7-9, fourth in AFC Central.
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: DT Dan Wilkinson (trade), QB Boomer Esiason
(retired), LB Gerald Dixon (FA), DE John Copeland (injury), LB Rico
McDonald (FA), FS Bo Orlando (FA), LB Jerry Olsavsky (cut), LB
Andre Collins (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: QB Neil O'Donnell (FA), LB Takeo Spikes (D-1a), LB
Brian Simmons (D-1b), DE Michael Bankston (FA), DE Clyde Simmons
(FA), CB Thomas Randolph (FA), QB Paul Justin (trade), CB Artrell
Hawkins (D-2).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: Even with the change to O'Donnell, the Bengals should
score points. Wideouts Carl Pickens and Darnay Scott can be lethal,
and RB Corey Dillon is an emerging star. A potential problem is
that the demoted Jeff Blake could be a distraction. Complex
zone-blitz scheme should sink in better in defensive coordinator
Dick LeBeau's second season. Linebackers drive the defense, though,
and Cincy has lots of kids there.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE RAVENS
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Ted Marchibroda is 10-21-1 in two seasons with the
Ravens and 83-92-1 in 11 NFL seasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 6-9-1, fifth in AFC Central.
</P>
<P>
   _ Key losses: CB Antonio Langham (FA), QB Vinny Testaverde
(cut), RB Earnest Byner (retired), WR Derrick Alexander (FA), RB
Bam Morris (cut), C Quentin Neujahr (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Key gains: QB Jim Harbaugh (trade), CB Duane Starks (D-1), RB
Errict Rhett (trade), CB Rod Woodson (FA), WR Pat Johnson (D-2), FB
Roosevelt Potts (FA), OT James Atkins (FA), FS Corey Harris (FA).
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: Defense has young quality in linebackers and
safeties, but front four is showing some age. Nobody knows how much
Woodson will help the secondary. Pass rush should be effective; LB
Peter Boulware and DE Michael McCrary are quick, upfield-type
players. WR Jermaine Lewis is emerging but might not post
Alexander's numbers. C Wally Williams ended a long holdout, but the
line could be a problem. Rhett hasn't beaten out second-year RB Jay
Graham.
</P>
