<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7869 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-PHOTO-REVIEW-     09-03 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-PHOTO-REVIEW-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ELEGANCE, GLAMOUR AND STYLE': NICE DRESS, BETTER PICTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Exhibition notes at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By MARGARETT LOKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard Avedon's 1955 photograph of the model Dovima posing
regally between two lively elephants may be overly familiar, but
with its startling contrasts, it is an extraordinary image. It has
less to do with beauty and the beast, and much more to do with
Blakean ``Tiger, tiger, burning bright'' symmetry and the gall of a
fashion photographer to have the mighty animals be a mere backdrop
for a slender woman wearing an expensive evening dress.
</P>
<P>
   But pair this photograph with the actual dress _ as does
``Elegance, Glamour and Style: Fashion and Its Photography,'' at
the Bruce Museum in Greenwich, Conn. _ and what do you get? A close
look at how easily haughty couture can be upstaged by masterly
fashion photographers like Avedon, Baron Adolf de Meyer, George
Hoyningen-Huene, Louise Dahl-Wolfe, Horst P. Horst and Lillian
Bassman.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be the exhibition's intention to have the prominently
displayed costumes fall short of their photographic counterparts,
but this is what happens time and again. This dichotomy is
especially striking when you consider how some of the photographs
literally take a back seat to the costumes: positioned so far back
on the walls only binoculars could afford a good look.
</P>
<P>
   The Yves Saint Laurent for Christian Dior gown in Avedon's
model-with-elephants picture looks perfect on Dovima, but on the
exhibition mannequin, it has awkward shoulders and a clumsy obilike
trailing sash. Similarly, Augustabernard's evening dress in
Hoyningen-Huene's 1933 portrait is an elegantly fluid
black-and-white affair, nothing like the real thing, which
resembles something fashioned out of maroon velvet curtains and
peach satin.
</P>
<P>
   In Horst's 1948 image of a model in a Nettie Rosenstein black
silk evening dress, the costume is boldly high style, the flyaway
angles at the shoulders and back neatly echoed in a flurry of
butterflies on a background wall, the model's shadow delicately
elongated on the wall in front of her. But the exuberance of the
image is hardly matched by the bronze iridescent taffeta evening
dress sitting sedately on the nearby mannequin. And the smokily
enticing silhouette in Ms. Bassman's 1955 rendering of a Charles
James tunic suit bears little resemblance to the boring wool number
on the exhibition mannequin.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial photography is meant to make the object photographed
more desirable than it often is. But one expects that haute couture
will not suffer by comparison. That it does in this exhibition
attests, most satisfyingly, to the magic of photography.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the show, organized by Nancy Hall-Duncan, Bruce
Museum curator of art, and Caroline Rennolds Milbank, a fashion
historian, gives an excellent, though abbreviated, overview of
fashion photography and, by extension, an idealized view of women
who favor designer clothes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to the exhibition's informative wall labels, the
Seeberger Freres _three Parisian brothers, Jules, Louis and Henri,
working in the first decade or so of this century _ were the first
to show society women wearing designer clothing as they went about
their socializing business. Before the Seebergers, models were
generally shown posing indoors, often before a painted backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   A Seeberger Freres image on exhibit predates by a few years
Edward Steichen's Pictorialist picture of women in luminous white
dresses and large hats on steeplechase day in Paris. In the
Seeberger Freres photograph, the dresses of three women at the
races in Paris are exquisitely detailed even as the face of the
woman with her head turned toward the camera is cast in shadow, her
hat a white glowing blur.
</P>
<P>
   During the theatrical 1920s, fashion photography, too, became
theatrical, with models striking stylized poses. The photographer
Sheila Metzner affects a painterly old-fashioned look in her 1984
Fresson photograph of a model in a pleated Fortuny tea gown. But
the fashion photographers of the '20s and '30s produced spare
black-and-white images.
</P>
<P>
   A 1928 de Meyer picture, of Georgia Graves in a Lucien Delong
evening dress, is particularly sublime, with a woman in a slinky
gown and a fur-collared wrap standing beside simple
Japanese-influenced interior furnishings. Sharing the same
elegance-is-all esthetic, Horst toned down a '30s Madeleine Vionnet
sheath _ with its row of rhinestone-set bows down the length of the
gown _ by casting the model in shadow and having her stand to one
side of the picture frame, a pillar of ice taking center stage.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as though he wanted to accentuate a wedding cake of a
Paquin white organdy evening dress festooned with rows of black
lace, Man Ray showed in a 1940 photograph an innocent-looking,
smiling (as opposed to coldly sophisticated) woman in this billowy
confection. Completing the picture is an arty backdrop of
Matisse-like figure drawings.
</P>
<P>
   Equally subversive is a Dahl-Wolfe image of an absurd swimsuit _
a ``balloon suit.'' Countering one absurdity with another, an
elegant model in this Claire McCardell concoction holds an umbrella
and struts her stuff before the brutalist facade of a Frank Lloyd
Wright house.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment in the late '40s, photographic models were loftily
beautiful, with Irving Penn and Cecil Beaton providing two of the
most memorable images. Penn's ``Twelve Most Photographed Models''
salutes remote gorgeousness in haute couture. In Beaton's
photographic illustration of Charles James evening gowns, a bevy of
supremely at ease women in a sumptuous setting of carved wood
paneling, oversized mirrors and a crystal chandelier chat or look
at themselves in the mirror or look at others looking at themselves
in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Any history of fashion photography has to recognize the work of
Paul Schutzer and his 1964 photographs in Life magazine of the
infamous topless bathing suit by Rudi Gernreich. (Schutzer, a
photojournalist, was killed at 36 when an antitank shell hit the
armored vehicle in which he was riding while covering the June 1967
war in the Middle East.) For the Gernreich swimsuit assignment he
took an underwater photograph of a female model in the topless
black swimsuit surrounded by males in black trunks _ the models'
heads obscured by the surface lines of the water. Like Garry
Winogrand's picture of a woman moving gracefully underwater with a
swimming pig, also taken in 1964, Schutzer's image is provocatively
lyrical.
</P>
<P>
   From the late '60s on, fashion photography seems to reflect
funkier, more decadent times and fashions. There is Helmut Newton's
ambiguous picture of a woman with slicked back short hair and
outfitted in a mannish Yves Saint Laurent pinstripe suit, a naked
woman close at hand. There are Steven Meisel's la dolce vita-like
pictures of women in Dolce &AMP; Gabbana garments. And how can a
history of fashion photography exhibit be complete without
Jean-Baptiste Mondino's 1990 portrait of Madonna looking intense
and brassily aggressive in Jean-Paul Gaultier's postmodern gold
corset?
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBITION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ELEGANCE, GLAMOUR AND STYLE: FASHION AND ITS PHOTOGRAPHY'
</P>
<P>
   At the Bruce Museum, 1 Museum Drive, Greenwich, Conn., through
Sept. 20.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
