<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 ROUNDABOUT THEATER NAMES ASSOCIATE ARTISTIC DIRECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scott Ellis, the Broadway director, has agreed to take the new
position of associate artistic director of the Roundabout Theater
Company, the theater announced on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis will assist Todd Haimes, who said he planned to continue
as artistic director of the Roundabout through the coming theater
season and the company's move to its new home in the Selwyn Theater
on West 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   Haimes was named artistic director of Livent Inc. on Wednesday,
assuming some duties of Garth Drabinsky, the company's co-founder
and producer of ``Ragtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky and Myron Gottlieb, a Livent vice president, were
suspended on Aug. 10 after the company's new management team,
headed by Michael Ovitz and Roy Furman, said they had found
accounting irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, who will not work exclusively for the Roundabout, is a
resident director at the theater and has staged several of its
productions.
</P>
<P>
   A three-time Tony Award nominee, Ellis most recently directed
``1776'' at the noncommercial Roundabout; it moved to the Gershwin
Theater for a commercial run and received three 1998 Tony Award
nominations. One was for Ellis as best director of a musical.
</P>
</TEXT>
