<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NIRELAND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEES HOPE FOR PEACE IN ULSTER DESPITE LATEST BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAGH, Northern Ireland _ President Clinton on Thursday solemnly
walked past the scarred, shattered shops along Market Street where
a terrorist car bomb killed 28 people and wounded 220 others last
month.
</P>
<P>
   But as he neared the spot where Market Street changed names to
become High Street, the president and First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton were engulfed by the boisterous shouts and chants of
well-wishers who turned out on a sunny summer day to welcome the
latest pilgrims to pay homage to victims of the Aug. 15 tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see I think is the resilience of the people here,''
said National Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger as he
accompanied the Clintons on their hour-long walk through the heart
of this market town of 27,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are beginning obviously to be able to be joyful as well
as sad at the same time,'' Berger observed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton barnstormed Northern Ireland by helicopter on his second
trip to the troubled province since 1995 when he became the first
American president to visit Ulster.
</P>
<P>
   In Belfast, he urged wary members of the newly created 108-seat
Northern Ireland Assembly to resolve their differences when they
convene on Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Omagh, Clinton consoled more than 500 people mourning
death or injury within their families as a result of the worst
terrorist attack in 29 years.
</P>
<P>
   Later in Armagh, Clinton counseled Northern Ireland's
Protestants and Roman Catholics to keep a watchful eye for
follow-on attacks by extremist paramilitary factions.
</P>
<P>
   Extremists' hopes of quelling the quest for peace ``backfired,''
Clinton declared. ``Out of the unimaginably horrible agony of
Omagh, the people said, `It is high time somebody told these people
that we are through with hate, through with war, through with
destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton offered promises as well of America's helping hand as
feuding parties strive to build a prosperous future on the ruins of
communal warfare that has claimed more than 3,400 lives since 1969.
</P>
<P>
   ~``We all thank you for standing up in the face of such a
soul-searing loss ... and your determined refusal to let a cowardly
crime rob you of the future you have chosen,'' Clinton told the
families of victims here in this mixed Roman Catholic and
Protestant community located in lush dairy country some 60 miles
west of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the United States would add to the $100 million it
has contributed since 1993 to the International Fund for Ireland;
train members of the new assembly; promote cross-border programs;
seek to bolster foreign trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
   Berger, Clinton's top adviser on Northern Ireland, said he
initially urged Clinton to pass up Omagh because he feared a visit
would focus attention on the past instead of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I originally was reluctant about coming here,'' Berger said.
``But this is part of the equation and it was very important that
we came here and I'm glad that we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke with a 14-year-old girl, Claire Gallagher, who was
blinded in the bombing, and her mother, a radiologist who had been
on duty at a Omagh hospital when her daughter was rushed there for
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no word to explain a mindless act of terror that grabs
the life of an innocent,'' Clinton told the families. ``But I think
the only way to truly redeem such a terrible loss is to make the
memories of the innocents monuments to peace.''
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair, who along with his wife
Cherie accompanied the Clintons at stops across Northern Ireland,
said the Omagh bombing had united the divided religious communities
``in grief, outrage and greater determination'' to cement the
peace.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said Clinton encountered a range of emotions. ``Some
were angry; some people were frustrated; some were very determined
to tell him that he had to continue to work on the peace process,''
McCurry said. ``His impression was that many of these families are
at different stages in the grieving process.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons presented a plaque to be placed along Market Street
in remembrance of the victims. ``May their memory serve to foster
peace and reconciliation,'' the plaque said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons and Blairs also laid a wreath in front of
Watterson's, a clothing store at No. 37 High Street. Two
Watterson's staffers were killed in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS - STORY MAY END HERE)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said Clinton's principle achievement was
winning a private commitment from Ulster Unionist Party leader
David Trimble and Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams to hold their
first face-to-face summit next week. Trimble has refused to meet
Adams until Sinn Fein, the political arm of the Irish Republican
Army, agreed to turn over weapons and explosives as required by the
April 10 ``Good Friday'' peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Adams agreed on Monday to begin ``decommissioning'' the IRA
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   In the window of Omagh's Progressive Building Society, a bank, a
red-inked flyer emblazoned with the word ``murder'' and with two
pictures of a red four-door sedan appealed for help from the public
to track down the bombers. Police suspect a 500-pound car bomb,
possibly carried by that auto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you in Omagh on Saturday 15th August 1998?'' the flyer
implored. ``Did you see this vehicle?''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Real I.R.A.'' _ a breakaway faction of the outlawed
Republican Army _ claimed responsibility for the blast that
occurred 29 years to the day after the initial deployment of
British combat troops to Northern Ireland.
</P>
</TEXT>
