<HEADER>
A7880 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DEMOCRATS-$AD     09-03 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DEMOCRATS-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEMOCRATS SAY CLINTON STILL RAKES IN BIG BUCKS
 &HT;    For release Saturday, Sept. 5.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democratic officials say President Clinton's legal
and personal embarrassments haven't harmed his ability to raise
money for his party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is still the biggest asset this party has,''
said Steve Grossman, general chairman of the Democratic National
Committee. He said the party counts on grossing $18 million for the
November elections at 11 ``Unity '98'' events headlining Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The money is intended to help offset a similar $37 million drive
by the Republican party for money to run TV and radio ads that
could swing close U.S. House races in November.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton raised more than $2 million at the first two ``Unity
'98'' events, dinners in Washington and Chicago in early August.
Dates have been set, and fund raising is under way for events Sept.
14 in New York, Sept. 17 in Boston and Sept. 26 in Los Angeles. The
remaining six events are expected to be held in October in St.
Louis, Miami and four other major cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now past our pretty ambitious goal of $3 million for
the New York event, and some of my colleagues in New York think
we'll exceed $3.5 million,'' Grossman said.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices range from a $1,000 ``hard-money'' donation for
distant seats at a Broadway production of ``The Lion King'' to
$100,000 in ``soft money'' for an opportunity to mix and mingle
with the hosts: the Clintons, the Gores, Senate Democratic Leader
Tom Daschle of South Dakota and House Democratic Leader Dick
Gephardt of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a choice'' whether or not to appear at such
events, Gephardt, who has described Clinton's behavior as
``reprehensible,'' told the St. Louis Post Dispatch. ``We need to
have the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Net receipts from the Unity '98 events are being divided equally
among three national committees _ the DNC, the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee and the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three committees are also doing well in our small-dollar,
direct-mail donor receipts,'' said Michael Tucker, communications
director for the senatorial committee. ``Traditional Democratic
donors are sticking with the president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect them to say that,'' said Mike Russell,
communications director of the National Republican Senatorial
Committee. ``If they're telling the truth, they're going to need
every dime.''
</P>
<P>
   While top Democrats head to New York in mid-September, top
Republicans will be in Washington hosting a private fund-raising
briefing for chief executive officers of Fortune 200 companies in
the Business Roundtable.
</P>
<P>
   The $18 million Democratic drive and the $37 million GOP drive
are crucial for the parties, according to political scientist
Stephen Ansolabehere of Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``About half the money a political party raises (in a two-year
election cycle) comes in the last three months before the
election,'' he said. He found the Democratic claim plausible,
because party loyalists give more ``when they feel their dollars
are going to matter, and this year it's an extremely close contest
in the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet brave Democratic talk of how to take over the House by
picking up a dozen seats is starting to fade inside the Beltway.
More Republicans are talking like Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., who
has claimed all along that the GOP majority could add another 10 to
40 seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a normal mid-term election, the president's party loses
about 25 seats,'' Ansolabehere said. ``If the Democrats are able to
stem the damages from this investigation enough to hold the loss to
10 seats, that's pretty impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Stockmeyer, a veteran GOP strategist who now offers
political guidance to corporations, said, ``I wouldn't see it as an
incongruity if party stalwarts feel more motivated to chip in
during a time of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In broad-based programs like telemarketing and direct mail,
the Democrats are dealing with hard-liners who aren't going to
abandon their president until the noose is over the neck,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But both parties plan to raise the bulk of their money in the
kind of big, unregulated gifts known as ``soft money'' that would
be outlawed under legislation the Senate is expected to vote on
shortly after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   While some of those giant gifts come from loyalists like
Grossman, who has given more than $160,000 to his party in the last
year and a half, many come from favor-seekers more interested in
buying access to policy-makers than in helping a party out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House is so narrowly divided right now, that a lot of
pragmatic givers feel obliged to fuel the fire on both sides,''
Stockmeyer said. ``And even the most pragmatic givers, whose money
goes only where the power is, can't afford to abandon any
president, no matter how crippled he is.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
