<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7897 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLIAMS-ART-REVIEW-8     09-03 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIAMS-ART-REVIEW-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS COLLEGE MUSEUM: A HARD-EDGED ZEAL IN IMAGES OF THE
AVANT-GARDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (Eds.: Exhibition notes are at end of review.) 
(js) 
 By KEN JOHNSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. _ Early modernist graphics are nothing if
not upbeat. Embodying enthusiasm for the social and material
possibilities of the new century in bold, insouciant,
scientifically efficient new forms, they generated moods of almost
utopian euphoria. Why then should the story told by ``Graphic
Design in the Mechanical Age,'' a fascinating show at the Williams
College Museum of Art here, be so depressing?
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition was drawn from a vast collection of graphic
material assembled by Merrill Berman, a businessman who lives in
Scarsdale, N.Y. It comprises more than 200 works, including posters
in all the print media as well as original paintings, drawings and
collages by some of the big names in early modernism, like
Alexander Rodchenko, Kurt Schwitters, El Lissitzky, Hannah Hoch and
many lesser-knowns. Along with its indispensable catalog, with
essays by the co-curators, Deborah Rothschild, Darra Goldstein and
Ellen Lupton, the exhibition shows how avant-garde experimentation
in the teens and '20s decisively influenced the development of
mainstream advertising and propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   This, in fact, is what one contemplates with some misgivings:
how innovations meant to liberate consciousness were turned into
tools for controlling consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition begins by setting out several fronts of
avant-garde activity distributed across Europe. In Paris before
World War I, the Italian Futurist Filippo Tommaso Marinetti
produced some of the first aggressively anti-conventional graphic
works, typographically scrambled poems in which, he proclaimed,
``my reformed typesetting allows me to treat words like torpedoes
and hurl them forth at all speeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Dada artists like Tristan Tzara, Francis Picabia and Man
Ray delighted in flouting all forms of conventional logic in order
to disrupt the established intellectual and moral order that gave
rise to World War I. Their posters for exhibitions or theatrical
events defied norms of typographic regularity, mixing diverse
styles, running lines of text every which way and including
surrealistically absurd phrases and images among pieces of real
information.
</P>
<P>
   In Berlin during the 1920s, Hoch, John Heartfield and Raoul
Hausmann developed photomontage into a ferociously acerbic mode of
social commentary for newspapers and magazines, while Russian
Constructivists like Rodchenko, Varvara Stepanova and Lissitzky
worked to mobilize participation in an ongoing social and political
revolution. Combining flat, hard-edged, abstract geometry, punchy
lettering and emblematic images, Constructivist graphic designs
burst with hortatory zeal, whether promoting Communist ideology or
vegetable oil.
</P>
<P>
   In the Netherlands, graphic artists were inspired by the radical
abstraction of De Stijl, the movement founded by Mondrian and Theo
van Doesburg. In De Stijl design there is less interest in the
direct incitement of social change than in the achievement of
partly scientific and partly spiritual purity, which, implicitly,
might help to engender a more orderly and rational world.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their differences, these movements share a belief that
art can reorient society to new values through new forms of public
address. These artists knew of their colleagues' work, influenced
one another and often collaborated, crossing over party lines
between, for example, De Stijl and Dada, as in a densely layered
poster from 1923 by van Doesburg and Schwitters in black, white and
red. In this early work, there's an almost explosive feeling of
cross-fertilizing creative ferment.
</P>
<P>
   What followed, however, is less inspiring. The revolutionary
impulses of avant-garde design died out, leaving a set of formal
rules and mechanical techniques that could be adapted to the needs
of any program or client. A movement called the New Typography,
dedicated to precisely this conception, arose at the end of the
1920s. It emerged from a circle of artists that included Schwitters
as well as expert but lesser-known designers like Paul Schuitema
and Piet Zwart, who went into business creating ads for paying
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The New Typography concentrated on the refinement of forms and
reproductive techniques, including photographic processes. Graphic
design became a science of visual communication; it could be
studied at progressive schools like the Bauhaus and could be
practiced as a regular job.
</P>
<P>
   Here one begins to feel let down. Early design integrated
spiritual and moral purposes with commercial or political purposes.
You feel a militant urgency even in the candy wrappers bearing
stark images of factory buildings bordered by red stripes designed
by Rodchenko (who, in any event, was incapable of creating anything
visually unconvincing). Later design, though it continues to be
formally interesting and often exciting, is morally and spiritually
hollow.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   You don't worry about this too much when contemplating elegant
designs like that of Vilmos Huszar for ``Miss Blanche Virginia
Cigarettes,'' which features a modern smoking woman abstracted on a
yellow field, or Schuitema's lithograph advertising Dutch ham, a
beautiful composition of primary-colored geometric shapes and
modernist lettering. Pieces like Otis Shepard's 1930s poster for
Wrigley's gum, which calls to mind the Pop-Conceptualist paintings
of Ed Ruscha, or Lester Beall's starkly abstracted 1937 posters for
the Rural Electrification Administration in the United States could
be mistaken for art were they not devoid of any compelling value.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to posters glorifying figures like Mussolini
or Stalin, you may feel serious reservations about the relationship
between form and content. A giant 1933 poster by Vasilii
Nikolayevich Elkin showing Stalin and his henchmen towering over
regimented fields of soldiers, while dirigibles and airplanes ply
the luminous sky and the text announces, ``Long Live the Red
Army,'' is an artistic monstrosity.
</P>
<P>
   As a history of how artists developed forms of communication
suited to the complexities and contradictions of modern society,
this show is immensely informative and suggestive. It can be argued
that this material projects a more vivid sense of modernity, of its
fragmentation, speed and intensity, than does fine art of the same
period. And though some of it looks quaint, the language it speaks
is still very much alive in magazines and billboards or on
television and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But the failure of a dream shadows that history. An art of cheap
mass communication that could be not only visually arresting but
transformative in the best sense has never been credibly realized.
Artists like Barbara Kruger and Felix Gonzalez-Torres have tried in
recent years, but their audience of art world sophisticates
remained minuscule. Mainstream graphic design sold its soul to the
devils of consumerism and bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibition Notes:
</P>
<P>
   `Graphic Design in the Mechanical Age'
</P>
<P>
   ``Graphic Design in the Mechanical Age: Selections From the
Merrill Berman Collection'' remains at the Williams College Museum
of Art in Williamstown, Mass., through Nov. 1. The show, sponsored
by Mead Corp., will travel to the Cooper-Hewitt National Design
Museum in New York City (Feb. 9 to May 30) and then
internationally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
