 &HT;     BILL'S WORLD 
 &HT;     By Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Northern Ireland, says Mr. Clinton, is moving ``from the deep
freeze of despair to the warm sunlight of peace.'' Past the high
wall of cliche.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``It's time for us to now go back to the work of the country,''
says the president, ``and give people their government back.'' Who
wants it back?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``There is no possible justification for terrorism,'' Mr.
Clinton says. So what's his plan? Cancel Halloween?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``The ultimate national security of any country,'' says Mr.
Clinton, ``rests in the strength of its own citizens.'' Right. We
need to be able to say, ``Our citizens can beat up your citizens.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``Printing money to pay the bills and bail out the banks does
not help,'' the president says. Especially if you print money with
your own picture on it.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``We are living in a smaller and smaller world,'' says Mr.
Clinton. Why, he can hardly take off his pants without folks
everywhere knowing.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    It looks like another bumper corn crop this year. Our parents'
folks used to grow corn and were so good at it we called them
Grainpa and Grainma.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The federal government estimates Americans spent $7 billion last
year on marijuana. Was a polling firm hired to toke(CQ) the survey?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Because we're Cubs fans, we favor Sammy Sosa over Mark McGwire
in the homer race. But we'd feel more enthusiastic if we were
rooting for Ernie Banks.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The video version of ``Titanic'' now is out. Same story, smaller
ship?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Boris Yeltsin declared his summit with Bill Clinton a success.''
 &HT;    Translation: One president stayed sober, the other celibate.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Russia will get back on its feet,'' Mr. Clinton says. And then
would really go places _ if it could afford shoes.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    We have had intensive, productive negotiations,'' Boris Yeltsin
said of his talks with Mr. Clinton. Was the same true of the
Clintons on vacation?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The president says Russians are committed to building a
brighter, better, stronger future.'' Their historians used to spend
time making up that kind of a past.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    I don't think there are many people in America who are afraid of
Russia any more,'' Mr. Clinton says. Most of the folks afraid of
Russia are Russian.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Aunt Ilse from Oelwein was disappointed by Mr. Clinton's trip to
Russia.
 &HT;    She figured there, at least, he'd say he's crazy.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Mr. Clinton says he's been quite heartened by the reaction of
the
 &HT;    American people'' to his Lewinsky admission. Enough to have
another affair?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Former first dog Rex, who lived in the Reagan White House, died
recently.
 &HT;    It raises an old question: Did the trickle down'' idea grow out
of efforts to housebreak him?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    A new U.N. report suggests world population will continue
growing by 80 million a year well into the next decade. This
suggests a long-term investment in the funeral industry.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    It's official: Mark McGwire has broken Hack Wilson's National
League record for home runs in a season. No wonder. Hack probably
couldn't even pronounce androstenedione.
