 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;     THE NEW HEARTTHROB: THE GIRLY MAN 
 &HT;     By DIANE WHITE    c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Science may have shed light on the mystery of the current crop
of male movie hearthrobs, who almost to a boy-man look like
somebody's little sister. Recent studies of facial attractiveness
have found that people of boths sexes prefer delicate-featured,
rounder-faced, more feminine-looking men over traditionally
masculine-looking types.
</P>
<P>
   From all reports no one seems exactly sure what this means, or
if it means anything, but perhaps helps explain Leonardo DiCaprio,
Matt Damon, Tom Cruise, Brad Pitt, et al., each and every one of
them just too adorable for words.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably a blessing that William Holden, Clark Gable, John
Wayne, and other craggy screen hunks of yore didn't live to see
their places in the popular imagination usurped by a bunch of
baby-faced post-adolescents. I'm trying to imagine Leo sweeping up
Vivien Leigh and ascending that staircase in ``Gone With the
Wind.'' I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the studies are published in the current issue of
Nature. Strange as it may seem to some, illuminating Leo's appeal
was not the main aim of the cross-cultural research, conducted in
Scotland and Japan. Scientists were investigating what makes a face
attractive to both sexes. They weren't surprised when both male and
female subjects expressed a preference for ``ultra-feminized''
female faces, with high, round cheeks, wide eyes, a small nose, and
full lips. But they were caught off guard by the preference for
male faces with similar feminine features.
</P>
<P>
   They had predicted that both female and male subjects would be
drawn to mature male faces with larger features, heavy brows, and
big jaws. They assumed that such men, bristling as they are with
testosterone, would be impressive to other males and irresistible
to females. But they weren't. One of the Scottish researchers told
a New York Times reporter, ``When it was found early on that there
was a preference for feminized male faces, nobody believed it, so
we did it again, and again. The preference for a feminized face
keeps coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that most recently the research team ``replicated this
work among hunter-gatherer tribes in the Amazon.'' Science marches
on, into the heart of the rain forest, in search of answers. Except
there are no answers. The results of these studies are wide open to
intepretation. According to the Times story, one theory put forward
by the researchers is that women may prefer more feminine-looking
men ``because they give the appearance of being sensitive, honest,
and potentially reliable fathers.'' Because they look like women,
presumably.
</P>
<P>
   For women _ particularly for young women, who buy a lot of movie
tickets _ Leo and his ilk are probably less threatening than macho
types. It's safe to swoon over these sweet-looking guys. They're so
sensitive, so vulnerable, so ... feminine?
</P>
<P>
   But what explains the male preference for feminine-looking
males? Maybe hyper-masculine men are intimidating to ordinary men.
In terms of movie idols, for example, what man can measure up to
the super-macho image of John Wayne? Leonardo DiCaprio is merely
cute, therefore no real threat. That's the fantasy, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Another theory: It may be that all the girls and young women who
are crazy over Leo only want to mother him. The current issue of
Psychology Today has a short piece about Lesley Zebrowitz,
professor of psychology at Brandeis and author of a book, ``Reading
Faces.'' Her research indicates that baby-faced adults bring out
the nurturing instincts in both men and women. I can almost see a
remake of ``Sunset Boulevard,'' with Leo as Joe Gillis and Barbra
(``I am big. It's the pictures that got small.'') Streisand as
Norma Desmond. In this version, she adopts him.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BLURRING FACT AND FICTION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DAVID GRIMES &LR;  &QC;   &UR; Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune &LR;  &QC;  These are
sad days for fictionalized journalism.
</P>
<P>
   First Janet Cooke, then Patricia Smith, then Stephen Glass and
now Mike Barnicle have lost their jobs for making up stuff and
passing it off as truth.
</P>
<P>
   This seems to me a terrible hypocrisy as newspapers print
fiction all the time (Blondie, the weather report, presidential
denials, etc.) and nobody gets upset, let alone loses his or her
job.
</P>
<P>
   In my opinion, newspapers need to be running more fiction, not
less, as reality is much too hard to digest over one's morning
coffee. My favorite newspaper is Weekly World News, which prints
nothing but fiction disguised as fact. The Weekly World News is the
media source that I turn to when I want to find out which
congresspeople are under the control of aliens (Newt Gingrich,
Trent Lott and Barney Frank, to name a few), the location of the
latest Elvis sighting (a Blockbuster Video in Columbia, Md.), the
latest, updated date of the End Of The World (Nov. 13, 2003) and
the Bigfoot Diet (apples, romaine lettuce and human brains).
</P>
<P>
   Weekly World News, needless to say, is wildly popular. It has
more readers in a week than The New Republic has in a year. The
paper's writers are not fired for making stuff up. In fact, they
are richly rewarded. (Presumably, if the writers tried to pass off
fact disguised as fiction, they would be fired. After all, that is
the province of the ``mainstream'' press.)
</P>
<P>
   The Weekly World News is also fun to read, whereas mainstream
papers print articles that run the gamut between upsetting and
depressing. (See Monica Lewinsky, Northern Ireland, the NBA, et
al.)
</P>
<P>
   Mob journalism, such as what you see at schoolyard shootings and
presidential sex testimonies, is an ugly sight and plays a large
part in lowering the public esteem of journalists to a station
usually reserved for serial killers and used car salesmen.
</P>
<P>
   Fiction writers, however, want no part of the pack mentality.
They can ``research'' their stories just as capably while lounging
next to the pool or watching television. Fiction writers don't
shove microphones into a murder victim's mother's face and ask her
how she ``feels.'' They don't stand there like ninnies in the
middle of the South Lawn with their toupees flapping in the breeze,
shouting dumb questions at the president while he boards his
helicopter for Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Fiction writers may not hew to all the ``rules'' of traditional
journalism, but they have a dignity and class that is often missing
from their fact-addicted counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas traditional news reporters tend to be disheveled and
distracted, fiction writers are the picture of calm and
sophistication. While traditional news reporters are chasing after
plane crashes and stained dresses, fiction writers are gazing out
the window in quiet contemplation or perhaps curling up for a
mid-afternoon nap.
</P>
<P>
   Fiction writers do not need to worry about misquoting people or
misspelling names, because all the quotes and names are made up.
</P>
<P>
   There is little threat of a libel suit either as fictional
people almost never sue.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking down the news is an expensive, time-consuming business
requiring lots of long-distance telephone calls, plane tickets and
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Fiction writers need only a pad and a pencil, and maybe a
comfortable couch on which to recline during those occasional
lapses in inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Since most people hate journalists and don't believe what they
read in the newspaper anyway, it is doubtful that the public's
faith in journalism will be damaged by replacing fact with fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, it will keep a lot of columnists like myself off the
welfare rolls and make breakfast for all of us a lot easier to
digest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
