u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBITUARY-SEGAL-BOS &LR;      09-03 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-SEGAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRVING SEGAL, AT 79; MIT PROFESSOR, PHYSICS THEORIST  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Irving Segal, a mathematician whose work had applications in
quantum mechanics and astrophysics, died Sunday, Aug. 30, after
collapsing while walking near his home in Lexington, Mass. He was
79.
</P>
<P>
   An expert on functional and harmonic analysis, Mr. Segal was a
professor at Massachusetts Institute of Technology for 28 years.
</P>
<P>
   His early work applied algebraic methods to fundamental physics
and the foundations of quantum field theory. In 1947, he introduced
a system of postulates for general quantum mechanics that reworked
a number of key concepts. More recently, he applied his
chronometric theory to astrophysics, leading to a new theory of the
red-shift in light from receding stars and a new model of the
universe.
</P>
<P>
   At MIT he contributed to the review and upgrading of the
curriculum and was adviser to many graduate students, including
Princeton University professor Edward Nelson, who dedicated his
1983 book, ``Studies in Applied Mathematics,'' to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``His encouragement was strong when I was writing a thesis,''
Nelson wrote, ``and equally important was his total lack of
encouragement when I found a result unrelated to anything beyond
itself. His sense of the global nature of mathematical research is
one of the most valuable things that he imparts to his students. ''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Segal was born in New York City. He graduated from Princeton
in 1937 and earned a doctorate in mathematics at Yale University in
1940.
</P>
<P>
   After serving in the Army during World War II, he taught at the
University of Chicago before joining the faculty at MIT in 1960. He
retired in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Martha (Fox); a daughter, Miriam, of
Lexington; and three children from an earlier marriage to Osa
MacLane of Chicago, William of Bethesda, Md., Andrew of Espinola,
N.M., and Karen of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service will be held at MIT later this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
