<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GEPHARDT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEPHARDT TAKES CONCILIATORY TONE ABOUT CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  MERRIMACK, N.H. _ House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, on a
swing through New Hampshire Thursday to bolster support for
Democratic congressional candidates, took a far more conciliatory
tone toward President Clinton than he did last week when he called
the president's conduct with Monica Lewinsky ``reprehensible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought his original statement was a good statement,''
Gephardt said of Clinton's televised admission that he had had an
improper relationship with the then 22-year-old intern. ``I thought
his statement Thursday was a good statement,'' he said of the
president's mention of seeking forgiveness in response to a
question posed to him after his summit meeting in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been very clear in my view ... He stated them in the
proper manner and he took responsibility for his actions,''
Gephardt said. ``I thought that was courageous. So I think again,
let's get to the issues people want to hear about. People are tired
of hearing about this.''
</P>
<P>
   The scandal was not affecting his party's mission, raising money
and support for Democratic candidates, Gephardt said. Nor did he
believe that it would affect voter turnout in November.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a small crowd of Democratic loyalists at the Red
Caboose, a landmark in the middle of town, Gephardt stressed
education, health care and Social Security _ the issues he said
would help his party regain control of the House of
Representatives. Asked what advice he has been giving Democratic
candidates tempted to distance themselves from Clinton and the sex
scandal, Gephardt counseled patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not jump to conclusions. Let's wait and get the
information when it's available. In the meantime it is extremely
important that we talk about the issues that people care about,''
he said. ``When they sit around the kitchen table, people are
talking about Social Security, education and health care. We need
to deal with those issues in September if we can and then if we
can't, we need to deal with them after the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues Congress may address, Gephardt said, is reform
of the law governing the actions of indepenent counsels who
investigate official wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think having somebody out there for an endless period of
time with an endless budget is the only part of government I know
of that has no check or balance,'' Gephardt said. ``Maybe we ought
to reconsider the way the law works. I am not for getting rid of it
entirely. I think you have got to have some mechanism out there,
but I think we have to limit it more carefully than we have in the
past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 1826EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
