<HEADER>
A7944 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      09-03 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD WILL OF CUSTOMERS, EMPLOYEES IS GOOD BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Back in my school days (well before VCRs, CDs and PCs),
we used to say that the chemicals in the human body were worth 98
cents. I have no idea where the number came from, but it was common
lore.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Morowitz, a biochemist now at George Mason University but
previously at Yale University, took issue with that paltry
appraisal. Using his 1979 biomedical supply catalog, he looked up
the prices of all the body's chemicals and calculated their costs
per pound. They totaled $36,000 a pound. At 168 pounds, Morowitz
figured he was a $6 million-plus man.
</P>
<P>
   ``The $6 million man has become a $6 billion man now,'' Morowitz
said in a telephone interview Wednesday. ``We now can add in the
cost of determining the DNA sequence and making DNA.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does this have to do with the workplace?
</P>
<P>
   I was reminded of the price tag on our bodies when I read a news
item that the Financial Accounting Standards Board has formed a
committee to study the value of intangible assets.
</P>
<P>
   Intangible assets are as important a part of corporate wealth as
are physical assets. Intangibles include the good will of
customers, the reputation of the company and _ in growing
proportion _ intellectual capital.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Brookings Institution study found that hard assets
(land, buildings and equipment) account for only one-third to
one-half of most companies' stock market value. The greater value
is in soft assets such as employee knowledge, customer
satisfaction, manufacturing processes and patents.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``knowledge economy,'' the value of our bodily chemicals
pales in comparison with the value of what we know. That means the
value of employees' thoughts and feelings are more important to the
bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   A biochemist may be able to figure out the physical value of our
brains, but certainly not their metaphysical worth. All brains are
not created equal, for starters. And how does one price the ability
to compose a sonata compared with a sonnet, or the ability to read
computer code compared with Morse code?
</P>
<P>
   But put aside the question of how to evaluate brainpower. The
more relevant workplace question is whether companies understand
the awesome profit influence held by employees.
</P>
<P>
   Do employers understand they're more likely to maximize profits
by improving skills and fostering positive attitudes among their
work force than by installing a new 800 number or upgrading the
computer system?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. Maybe not. It's easier to measure things than
intangibles. It's easy to see that John is a good worker when he
meets his production quota; it's harder to say what John's
experience, skill and good attitude are worth.
</P>
<P>
   Some employers are beginning to quantify employee attitudes.
Sears, Roebuck and Co., for example, surveyed employees in 800
stores, asking them questions about job satisfaction. The retailer
then looked at each store's profits.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise, surprise. When employee attitudes improved, store
profit margins went up _ and it doesn't take a biochemist to
understand why.
</P>
<P>
   Contented employees are more likely to continue working at the
store. Their experience is more likely to translate into better
customer service. Customers are more likely to enjoy shopping
there. Revenue is apt to rise.
</P>
<P>
   And that's my 98 cents' worth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
