<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7947 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAY-RAISES-KAN &LR;      09-03 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAY-RAISES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAY-RAISE REPORT SHOWS ANOTHER YEAR OF 4 PERCENT SALARY INCREASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: A pre-Labor Day headline to think about: ``No
compensation inflation in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how William M. Mercer Inc. introduces its preliminary
salary-increase report for 1999. The subhead emphasizes the point:
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite pressures created by a tightening labor market,
employee compensation costs are not escalating.''
</P>
<P>
   The complete Mercer survey of expected 1999 pay raises won't be
available until later this fall, but all signs point to another
year of standard increases slightly above 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That's not entirely bad news, though. This year's inflation rate
is expected to be under 2 percent, which means real wages, or what
you keep after inflation, will rise in comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, Mercer, a human resource management consulting firm,
surveys midsize to large employers nationally. It derives salary
data covering nearly 11 million workers, or about 10 percent of the
private-sector work force.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercer survey dovetails with predictions made earlier this
year by The Conference Board, a business research organization. The
Conference Board estimated that 1999 salary increases would average
4 percent for the fifth consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   It's the usual story.
</P>
<P>
   Average raises have hovered slightly above 4 percent since 1994.
Since 1993, the annual inflation rate has danced around 3 percent,
although this year's rate is expected to be about 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Conference Board says employees, on average, will have a
real earnings gain of 2.3 percent this year. That's the largest
gain since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Such numbers help to squelch employee dissatisfaction with their
raises.
</P>
<P>
   The strong national economy and rising corporate profits might
have led to more sharing of the wealth. And an exceedingly tight
labor market in many job categories should have driven salaries
higher, according to the theory of supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, survey results indicate only top executives are getting
raises that are notably larger than the rate of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   In a Labor Day missive, AFL-CIO President John Sweeney said
unions had staged a comeback in bargaining power this year. He also
said, ``While many union workers have had big wins, too many
working families continue to lose benefits, job security and pay.''
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO has been a strong critic of the widening gap between
average-worker wages and top executive salaries. The gap has
morale, if not financial, effects on many workers, critics argue.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the static wage picture has a lot to do with changing
compensation philosophies in American corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country's employers appear resolved to hold the line on
fixed compensation costs,'' said Jeffrey J. Fuller, a principal in
the performance and reward consulting practice in Mercer's Kansas
City office.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller said global price competitiveness might be the primary
force. U.S. employers can't or won't increase their prices to
accommodate an increase in base compensation costs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another trend is influencing the stagnant raise pattern:
Employers are moving toward rewarding outstanding performers,
instead of increasing base pay across the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of the annual raise as an entitlement are waning,''
Fuller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compensation dollars are being selectively used to fill
positions requiring critical skills,'' said Charles Peck, The
Conference Board's compensation specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, 48 percent of the companies surveyed by Mercer
reported that the number of employees eligible for pay incentives
had increased. According to this year's review, an additional 22
percent of companies surveyed plan to increase their compensation
reward programs.
</P>
<P>
   Also, employers are turning to contract workers or temporary
help to fill needs rather than hiring full-time employees.
</P>
<P>
   They also are outsourcing entire departments. In some companies,
there will no longer be an in-house employee benefits department;
that function will be handled by a specialist company that does
similar work for multiple employers.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Mercer's early pay-raise predictions are:
</P>
<P>
   - 4.4 percent for top executives
</P>
<P>
   - 4.2 percent for managers
</P>
<P>
   - 4.2 percent for skilled technical and professional workers
</P>
<P>
   - 4.2 percent for non-exempt workers who are eligible for
overtime payments under provisions of the Fair Labor Standards Act.
</P>
<P>
   - 3.9 percent for non-union hourly workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
