<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7950 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOSPITAL-GIFT-KAN &LR;      09-03 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-GIFT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITAL ANNOUNCES $1.1 MILLION GIFT TO FUND RESEARCH CHAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Children's Mercy Hospital took another step
toward building a major medical research program with the
announcement this week of a $1.1 million gift to establish an
endowed chair in immunology.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first of more than $10 million in gifts for research
that the hospital expects to receive over the next few months,
Children's Mercy officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The donation Wednesday from former Marion Merrell Dow Chairman
Fred Lyons will create the third endowed research chair at
Children's Mercy. The two others, for a medical research director
and a clinical pharmacologist, were funded by Marion Merrell Dow
(now Hoechst Marion Roussel) and the University of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The new money ``assures we have the best and brightest,'' said
David Oliver, chairman of the hospital's central governing board.
</P>
<P>
   ``While our achievements have been significant, research is
still a well-kept secret at the hospital,'' he said. ``We are a
first-class research center.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyons is giving the money in honor of his wife, Dee, who has
been a volunteer at the hospital for many years. Lyons said he
hoped his gift would encourage other individuals and businesses to
contribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a start,'' Lyons said at a luncheon to announce
the gift. ``This gift alone won't be enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Children's Mercy began planning about eight years ago to build a
substantial research program. Since then, the hospital has opened
laboratories for research into such areas as genetics, cell biology
and immunology.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the hospital's clinical pharmacology program was
designated by the National Institutes of Health as one of seven
sites nationwide to evaluate new medications for children.
</P>
<P>
   Children's Mercy pharmacology researchers participated in the
development of the first new drug in 25 years to treat tuberculosis
of the lungs. The drug was recently approved for use by the U.S.
Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't deliver the best cutting-edge medicine without a
vigorous research program,'' said Ralph Kauffman, the hospital's
medical research director and holder of one of the hospital's
endowed chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman said immunology, the study of the body's immune system,
was chosen for funding because it is a crucial field affecting the
way doctors treat infectious diseases, organ transplants, cancer
and auto-immune diseases such as lupus and rheumatoid arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   The Dee Lyons Endowed Chair in Pediatric Research Immunology
will ``fill an important gap'' in the hospital's research program,
he said. ``I see this bringing an expertise we don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   The scientist chosen to fill the immunology chair will conduct
his or her own research and be available as a resource to other
researchers at the hospital, Kauffman said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the projects under way that may benefit from an
immunologist's expertise:
</P>
<P>
   - Research on the molecular and clinical aspects of asthma.
</P>
<P>
   - An investigation into the influence one pituitary hormone has
on the immune system.
</P>
<P>
   - Attempts to modify the immune system to prevent rejection of
transplanted pancreatic islet cells to treat diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   - Research into the molecular basis of unpredictable, rare but
life-threatening drug reactions.
</P>
<P>
   Children's Mercy is seeking a matching grant from the University
of Missouri to endow the immunology chair. The university already
has provided matching funds for the two other endowed chairs.
</P>
<P>
   If the grant is approved, the immunology researcher will hold
joint appointments on the staff of Children's Mercy and the faculty
of the University of Missouri-Kansas City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 1842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
