<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7951 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIDDEN-CAMERAS-2TAKES     09-03 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIDDEN-CAMERAS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVAILABILITY OF HIDDEN CAMERAS RAISES QUESTIONS ABOUT PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STACY DOWNS, TERRY COLLINS and RICHARD ESPINOZA  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Hidden cameras watch you on the job, while
you shop, while you gamble...and maybe while you tan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be the walls have ears, but they also have eyes,''
said Stephen Barnhart, owner of Barnhart Security and Alarm
Services in Grandview, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   As technology advances, surveillance cameras that produce
sharper images are becoming less expensive and much smaller _ and
easier to conceal. And business is booming.
</P>
<P>
   Industry sales of spy and security equipment grew from $10
billion in 1985 to $40 billion in 1995, according to CCS
International, which makes and sells the devices in the United
States and Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   People spy on their spouse, their babysitters, and even their
children. Businesses catch customers and employees committing
crimes on tape.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Amanda Tull and Buddy Hall were sentenced in the
January kidnapping of a baby from the University of Kansas Medical
Center in Kansas City, Kan. FBI agents said a key to their quick
capture was the release of hospital and discount store videotapes
that allowed the couple to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   But some say hidden cameras invade people's privacy, catching
their most vulnerable moments on tape.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, police in Lenexa, Kan., arrested a tanning salon
owner after finding videotapes of naked salon customers.
</P>
<P>
   If there's something on your desk or wall, chances are you can
buy those items with a camera inside.
</P>
<P>
   Companies advertising on the Internet offer cameras hidden in
picture frames and wall clocks, in pencil sharpeners and lamps, in
sprinkler heads and smoke detectors. They sell pinhole cameras that
can stare through a stray nail hole in a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Suspect your spouse is cheating? Try the clock radio camera.
Don't trust your babysitter? Try the teddy bear camera.
</P>
<P>
   Prices typically start at a couple of hundred dollars. Color
cameras and wireless models cost more.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City area, residents are starting to buy more
video cameras to protect their homes from vandals, said Garry
McCormack, owner of Alarm Equipment &AMP; Supply of KC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cameras are easier to install than burglar alarms,'' he said.
``It just takes some coaxial cable _ there's not much to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most places that rely on surveillance systems, such as casinos,
hotels and shopping centers, won't talk about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very high-tech security. I'm not even allowed back
there,'' said a casino employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget about it,'' said a Kansas City International Airport
official.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give it all away, then you're letting the bad guys in
on your secrets,'' said the owner of a Kansas City security
company.
</P>
<P>
   William Denton, though, was willing to talk. As the security
manager at Worlds of Fun in Kansas City, he oversees about 30
cameras throughout the amusement park. Eighteen cameras are visibly
posted near the entrances and exits.
</P>
<P>
   The rest are hidden cameras, some about the size of a
wristwatch, placed in the park's retail shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``They help cut down on theft,'' Denton said. ``Everything from
using false credit cards to shoplifting. You can't argue with
videotape. What you see is what you get.''
</P>
<P>
   And from a control room with several monitors, Denton can also
watch his employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell all of them they may be watched by surveillance _ they
just don't know where it's at,'' said Denton, who changes the
location of the hidden cameras by himself each week. ``That's the
element of it, not knowing if you're on camera or not.''
</P>
<P>
   One expert said he doubts that hidden cameras prevent crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been no studies that show that cameras have
deterred robberies at convenience stores,'' said Bill Staples, an
associate professor of sociology at the University of Kansas and
the author of ``The Culture of Surveillance.'' ``They also
indiscriminately tape other things. It might catch someone doing
something embarrassing that could wind up on the news.''
</P>
<P>
   The increasing sophistication of video cameras has been a boon
to one segment of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Voyeurs use cameras hidden in backpacks, shopping bags and
briefcases to catch peeks up women's skirts. Sometimes the images
end up on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voyeurism is going up,'' said David Banisar of Privacy
International, a monitoring group in Washington. ``It's the power
of small, cheap cameras and easy distribution methods through the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Great Britain may have the highest concentration of police
cameras trained on streets and other public areas, privacy experts
say. Banisar said a study of British police tapes revealed that 10
percent to 15 percent of the time the cameras were used to zoom in
on women, apparently for voyeuristic purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The police tapes, which are available to the public, provided
fodder for a businessman who culled salacious episodes for his own
hot-selling tape, ``Caught in the Act.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, TV stations have installed cameras on rooftops to
offer viewers footage of sunsets and traffic jams. But some people
have worried that the cameras could be redirected by remote control
to peer into high-rise apartments.
</P>
<P>
   As Richard Pollack, who controls nine New York traffic cameras,
told The New York Times, ``Rule of thumb: If you can see the Empire
State Building, we can see you.''
</P>
<P>
   In suburban Orlando, Fla., TV stations removed five highway
traffic cameras they had mounted after a county commissioner saw
one pointed away from the road to an apartment complex. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
