<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAMWAY-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE TRAMWAY END': A SELF-EXILE MOURNS THE IRISH DIASPORA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Why, audiences may ask, would anyone want to get
inside the head of a loud international soccer fan hanging around a
German train station? As it turns out, that character, Eoin, an
Irishman a long way from home, does have something worthwhile to
say. But it takes him a long time and a lot of shouting to get
there.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Yeates plays Eoin in ``The Tramway End,'' a one-man show
written by the Irish novelist Dermot Bolger, and he starts off at a
disadvantage. Yeates is lighted most of the time in what may be
meant as a re-creation of railway-terminal glare; unfortunately, in
the tiny Chelsea Playhouse, much of the audience is enveloped by
the glare, too. And Yeates is directed, it seems, to spend his
first few minutes onstage absently reading a newspaper and putting
things away in his backpack. This feels like an acting-class
exercise rather than a performance, albeit reasonably well done.
</P>
<P>
   Eoin lives in Germany, and he's feeling a little down because
Ireland has just lost to the Netherlands in the European soccer
championships. At first Eoin just seems to be reflecting on the
noisy fun of soccer games. He recalls, for instance, a crowd's
singing ``If you hate the Queen of England, clap your hands'' (to
the tune of ``If You're Happy and You Know It''). But his thoughts
turn to home, to Limerick Junction, to train stations where the
place names are spelled out in white stones in the flower beds, to
a family who ``had been in Waterford since before the Normans,'' to
a permanence and a belonging to which he has no chance of
returning.
</P>
<P>
   Eoin is here to mourn the Irish diaspora. He left Ireland
decades ago, when ``the construction game collapsed,'' and now he
sees his own children, like other children in the United States and
around the globe, growing up with Irish faces and foreign accents.
And as he speaks he realizes why he's willing to follow a sports
team from his homeland almost anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were playing for all those generations written out of
history,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He describes a stadium ringing with the applause of an Irish
crowd: ``I saw 30,000 pairs of hands, moving as one, united by
pride.''
</P>
<P>
   At last Thursday night's performance, the audience for ``The
Tramway End'' seemed to want to join in that reaction. Certain
Irish place names got laughs just by being mentioned, in the same
way a television talk-show audience applauds and hoots when a
famous guest mentions his or her hometown. This message should
inspire far more complex emotion than tht. In this production,
sadly, it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tramway End'' continues at the Chelsea Playhouse
Wednesdays through Sundays through Sept. 20.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE TRAMWAY END'
</P>
<P>
   By Dermot Bolger; directed by Jim Jermanok; lighting by Paul
Ziemer; assistant director, Al Nazemian; sound by David Paige;
assistant to Ray Yeates, Carol Ann Brammer. Presented by Command
Performance Productions and Chelsea Live. At the Chelsea Theater.
</P>
<P>
   With: Ray Yeates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
