<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7953 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIDDEN-CAMERAS-2NDTAK     09-03 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIDDEN-CAMERAS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ an apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, the cameras that broadcasters have mounted
around the area aren't powerful enough to pry on people in their
homes, a news producer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in a position to abuse anything because our cameras
can't do anything except wide shots,'' said Alvie Cater, executive
producer at KSHB-TV 41. ``...I'm not aware of any lens in the city
that will let you zoom in and invade on somebody. That would have
to be a powerful lens.''
</P>
<P>
   As technology races ahead, it's leaving the law behind, said
Banisar, and people are getting away with little punishment for
severe privacy invasion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, when a Buffalo, Mo., tanning bed operator was accused
of secretly videotaping his customers, he was charged with child
abuse and endangering the welfare of a child for taping underage
women. Prosecutors at the time could not file serious charges for
taping the adult women, said Jackson County (Mo.) Prosecutor Claire
McCaskill.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Missouri has made it a felony to secretly view,
photograph or film more than one person if the subjects had a
reasonable expectation of privacy. Spying on just one person can
still be prosecuted as an invasion of privacy case, McCaskill said.
</P>
<P>
   The felony charge can be punished with up to five years in
prison and a $5,000 fine. Repeat offenders face up to seven years
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas prosecutors said they use eavesdropping laws in cases
like the Lenexa tanning salon.
</P>
<P>
   Lenexa resident Michael W. Emmons, 32, owner of the Sun Swim USA
salon, has been charged with 13 counts of eavesdropping, a
misdemeanor. If convicted, he could be punished with up to a year
in the county jail and a $2,500 fine for each of the 13 charges.
</P>
<P>
   Many cities have laws against peeping toms, but someone who
``breaks the seal'' on a room _ by drilling a hole or installing a
hidden camera, for instance _ can be charged with eavesdropping.
</P>
<P>
   Later this month, an interim legislative committee is scheduled
to hold hearings in Topeka, Kan., on privacy issues, including the
use of hidden cameras in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Several legal experts said that businesses probably cannot hide
cameras in dressing rooms or restrooms unless people are warned
that they may be recorded.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't always the case, however.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, nine security officers sued Johnson County Community
College in Overland Park, Kan., after learning that a hidden camera
had been installed in the officers' locker room. College
administrators said they had received information about possible
thefts and had heard rumors that guns were being brought on campus.
</P>
<P>
   The officers lost their case in federal court. The judge's
reasoning: Because people could freely enter the locker area at any
time, the officers didn't have a reasonable expectation of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, McCaskill said the law may not even allow an
expectation of privacy for men using public restrooms, because most
are designed with urinals in the open.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County District Attorney Paul Morrison's office files at
least one eavesdropping case a year, but only a few of them have
involved videotaping. In one Johnson County case, a man was charged
for secretly putting a video camera in his roommate's room so he
could record her undressing and sleeping, police said. Police said
another man was charged for hiding a camera to videotape his
family's babysitter using the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Said Morrison: ``People do a lot of weird stuff with cameras.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
