<HEADLINE>
THE MORALITY GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's the everyone-does-it defense and it's not
pretty.
</P>
<P>
   It won't get President Clinton off the hook. His romp with a
young intern and the subsequent attempted coverup is indefensible,
no matter how sinful those who criticize him may also be.
</P>
<P>
   The private lives of the president's pursuers would not be
relevant to his own behavior if the probes of his conduct had
remained within serious legal bounds and relatively free of
partisan coloration.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, however, Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's
investigation of Clinton's activities has been heavily politicized.
Thus it is fair game to question not only the president's character
and motives but those of other politicians who propose to sit in
judgment upon him.
</P>
<P>
   This two-way street has become increasingly traveled as the fall
campaign approaches. Republicans are shamelessly injecting the
issue of presidential credibility into congressional debates on
unrelated issues, as well as into their campaigns against local
Democratic candidates whose names are not Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Demoralized Democrats can either give up and go under or insist
that the Republicans have no lock on purity. A practical way to do
the latter is to point out those on the GOP side who are eager to
ignore their own sins while they pile on Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP message is that the president now lacks the ``moral
authority'' to lead. Okay. But from whence springs the GOP ``moral
authority'' to replace him?
</P>
<P>
   Recently GOP congressional candidates have begun campaigning on
a claim to a higher moral standard than their Democratic opponents
in an effort to smear the president's entire party through guilt by
association. Commercials sponsored by the Republican National
Committee and the Republican Congressional Campaign Committee
project an image of GOP probity, noting slyly that ``honesty does
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, it becomes legitimate, even imperative, for
Democrats to inquire whether the Republicans themselves are the
paragons of virtue they would have us believe or are merely being
hypocritical for political gain. We are reminded of previous bad
behavior on the GOP side, including House Speaker Newt Gingrich's
cavalier treatment of his first wife.
</P>
<P>
   Integrity is a matter of individual character rather than party
label. Throughout history, bad apples have come from every
ideological pole _ and still do.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, chairman of the House Government Reform and
Oversight Committee investigating the president's campaign
fund-raising practices, highlighted the issue this week by whining
that he was being picked on. He complained bitterly that the White
House was spreading nasty rumors about virtuous old him.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, who called Clinton a ``scumbag'' and vowed to ``get''
him, can obviously dish it out _ but can't take it. This is the man
who had no qualms about privacy rights when he personally made
public tapes of Clinton friend Webster Hubbell talking to his wife
from prison about intimate family matters.
</P>
<P>
   Because a Vanity Fair writer is digging into his past, Burton
called a news conference to confess that he and his wife had been
separated three times during their marriage. Burton charged that
the pending article, sight unseen, was part of a White House
``scorched earth'' policy to discredit good Republicans who dare to
expose Clinton's wrongdoings.
</P>
<P>
   This theory of a broad liberal scheme to intimidate Republicans
is the counterpart of First Lady Hillary Clinton's notion that
criticism of her husband is part of a ``vast right-wing
conspiracy.'' Despite a smidgen of truth in both charges, the
existence of some secret, organized plot on either side is
unrealistic, politics being a sloppy business.
</P>
<P>
   And suggesting that the irreverent Vanity Fair is an arm of the
Democratic National Committee doing the president's bidding is
downright silly. The magazine, for instance, recently ran a gushy
one-sided, two-part article slobbering over the noble perfection of
Ronald and Nancy Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Burton's professed outrage that his sex life is being examined
is supposed to make the White House look mean for doing to Burton
exactly what Burton is helping to do to Clinton _ exposing
offensive private behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Although the extent to which the White House is pointing
reporters in the direction of GOP critics with unsavory backgrounds
is not clear, it doesn't really matter so long as the information
provided is factual and properly checked out. A president must be
held to a high moral standard, but his accusers cannot be given a
pass to have none of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The public has a right to know just who these people are who may
be asked to take the extreme step of impeaching a president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
