<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-INTERIOR-MINISTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH INTERIOR MINISTER REPLACED AFTER HEART ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ French Interior Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement was
temporarily replaced Thursday after suffering a heart attack
Wednesday in a routine operation to remove gallstones.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Val-de-Grace military hospital in Paris said his
heart had stopped beating, probably in an allergic reaction to
anesthetics administered for the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors were able to restart his heart, but Chevenement, 59, has
not regained consciousness. Dr. Yves Cudennec, the hospital's chief
doctor, said Thursday night that the minister was slowly improving
in intensive care.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Lionel Jospin asked Jean-Jack Queyranne, a junior
minister for overseas territories, to replace Chevenement while he
recuperated.
</P>
<P>
   Chevenement, long a member of Jospin's Socialist Party, resigned
from it in 1993 to found a leftist group called the Citizens'
Movement. His strong views and outspoken nationalism often brought
him into conflict with governments he served.
</P>
<P>
   As interior minister, he presided over changes in French
immigration and nationality laws that gave anyone born on French
soil the right to acquire citizenship at the age of 18. He also
reviewed the status of tens of thousands of clandestine immigrants
he asked to register and apply for residence papers. About 140,000
did apply, but Chevenement's ministry decided this year that only
half of them qualified.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're obviously all extremely upset about this accident,''
Justice Minister Elisabeth Guigou said after Jospin told Cabinet
ministers that Chevenement would not be back as planned next week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
