<SLUG> BC-CONGO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFERENCE OF CONGO BELLIGERENTS IS PLANNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa _ No cease-fire in the war in the Congo was
worked out Thursday, but a summit meeting of the warring factions
is to be held soon to discuss one, parties to the conflict said.
</P>
<P>
   News of the planned summit meeting came as a conference of the
113-nation Non-Aligned Movement wound up here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In evening news reports, South African President Nelson Mandela
was reported to have abruptly changed his position on the conflict
and to have joined other African leaders in endorsing military
support for its embattled president, Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   But his spokesman said later that a remark by Mandela during a
morning press conference had been taken out of context and
``exaggerated by the media.'' Mandela is sticking to his position
that the situation in Congo cannot be solved by force, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   It was also reported that the summit meeting of the warring
factions would be held as early as this weekend in Victoria Falls,
Zimbabwe _ but both the president of Zimbabwe and a spokesman for
Mandela said no date or place had been set yet. It was not clear
whether South Africa would be invited, since it has no troops in
the Congo. ``We might go as an observer,'' Mandela's spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Angola, Zimbabwe and Namibia have sent troops to aid Kabila, and
Zimbabwe President Robert Mugabe said Thursday that they had
prevented the fall of the capital, Kinshasa. ``Our troops found
armored troops _ troops with armored cars, heavy artillery _ within
40 miles of Kinshasa,'' he said in a speech. ``Had we not
intervened, the government of Laurent Kabila, which we had just
legitimized, would have fallen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
