<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-POIROT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS YOUR CHILD SICK, OR JUST SICK OF SCHOOL?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aching or faking?
</P>
<P>
   Is it the flu or a history test? How do you decide if your child
is sick enough to stay home from school?
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, it's obvious. Repeated diarrhea or vomiting
within the last 24 hours, a rash that is blistering or oozing and
sore, or a severe cold with fever of 100 degrees or more _
especially in a younger child who cannot remember to cover his
mouth when he coughs _ should always keep a child home.
</P>
<P>
   A good first step is to ask yourself: ``If my child were
healthy, would I want her to sit next to a child with these
symptoms?'' says Dr. Robert Hoekelman, professor of pediatrics at
the University of Rochester and a contributing editor to the Merck
Manual of Medical Information _ Home Edition.
</P>
<P>
   ``When children exhibit overt signs of illness such as
listlessness, vomiting or fever, parents can easily make the
decision to keep them home,'' Hoekelman says. ``However, making
this determination can be trickier when children are on the verge
of illness or have been home sick for several days, and the
symptoms are more ambiguous.''
</P>
<P>
   Children should be without fever, vomiting or diarrhea for at
least 24 hours before returning to school. In the case of an
infection that is being treated with antibiotics, a child usually
can return to school after being treated for 24 hours, Hoekelman
says.
</P>
<P>
   The new home edition of the popular manual defines medical terms
and illnesses in consumer-friendly language. It's available in most
bookstores for $29.95. Specialists in many areas contribute their
expertise. Back-to-school outreach
</P>
<P>
   Aetna U.S. Health Care is reaching out to the parents of more
than 11,000 Texas youngsters with an immunization reminder.
Administrators, secretaries and nurses are calling the homes of 12-
and 13-year-olds enrolled in their care plan as part of an
educational campaign against hepatitis B and chickenpox, the newest
vaccine-preventable diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna employees are calling in the evening, on their own time
and sending out follow-up educational materials to increase the
number of area teens who are fully immunized.
</P>
<P>
   As immunization guidelines changed in the early 1990s and new
vaccines were developed, some children were lost in the time warp
and have not received the full set of recommended shots. Breathe
free
</P>
<P>
   It could be a lifesaver for the Tarrant County Hospital
District, but that $20,665,000 anticipated as the first payment
from the state's $17.3 billion tobacco settlement is anything but a
free bonus. Tony Alcini, the district's chief executive officer,
estimates smoking costs taxpayers here $24 million to $30 million a
year in hospital expenses.
</P>
<P>
   True, we have a lot of allergies and smog contributing to lung
problems, but Alcini and company figure the heart disease, chronic
obstructive respiratory disease, lung cancer, emphysema, asthma and
other illnesses linked to tobacco make smoking a costly evil.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figure at least $24 (million) to $30 million of our budget
each year is related to smoking, and that's money we all pay in
taxes,'' Alcini says.
</P>
<P>
   Money from the settlement _ if it overcomes all the legal
roadblocks _ will be used by the public hospital to help finance
the hospital district's respiratory clinic and other services for
people sick from diseases related to smoking.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7687. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
