<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BASEBALL RECLAIMS SEPTEMBER  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark McGwire goes for No. 60 Friday night in St. Louis. Goes for
No. 61. Goes for No. 62. They are coming in bunches for the big
boy. He's got his stroke down. Sammy Sosa is right behind him with
56. Their talent and their growing zest for this marvelous chase
are knocking all the other sports into the ``Transactions'' slot.
</P>
<P>
   We are reminded of the collective hold that baseball, and Babe
Ruth, and Roger Maris, have on us. The games drag on incessantly;
the non-leaders dither; but we always know what Nos. 60 and 61 and
62 signify _ power and reflexes, the ball soaring through the
stratosphere, the slugger gaping at his wondrous act, the gabber in
the booth chanting, ``Going, going, gone.''
</P>
<P>
   We know. It is in our collective genes. The home run is still
America's great signature sporting feat.
</P>
<P>
   In the pre-Jordanian, pre-Monday-Night-Football days, baseball
was always the National Pastime in the United States. However, in
recent years, the Labor Day weekend has become the gateway to the
fall sports, with lavish time and money reserved for the eccentric
and exotic individuals whacking the fuzzy yellow balls at the
United States Open.
</P>
<P>
   Down South, where fans wear their school colors on their license
plates, people are undoubtedly talking college football, but around
the United States and Canada and surely the Dominican Republic,
Sammy Sosa's country, people are talking baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The professional football season starts this weekend, and that
is a big thing for Giants and Jets fans in New York, and Packers
fans in Green Bay, and Cowboys fans in Texas _ but the Cards and
the Cubs are America's teams right now. This reverses a trend that
was widely but perhaps prematurely described as The Death of
Baseball, personified by clumpy suburban kids imitating Michael
Jordan's moves in their local playground. Michael and the Bulls
became an international fetish, via the television cables that
David Stern had prophesied. Bulls caps in China. The Red Oxen.
</P>
<P>
   More people know Michael and Ronaldo of Brazil and even racing
drivers than the big basher from the Gateway and the slugger from
Wrigleyville. But following this summer of the home run, the red
Cardinals cap and the blue Cubs cap will spread through the world,
the way Yankees caps did in November of 1996 when I spotted them in
the narrow streets of Florence, Dante's city.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, baseball had become a temporary and local
preoccupation, squashed collectively by the wonderful owners and
the terrible players in the dance-to-death labor troubles of
1993-94 that killed a World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners were delightful in the Northwest in 1995, and the
politically incorrect nicknames from Atlanta and Cleveland were
having their moments, but baseball was sunk in a morass created by
the brutally short-sighted Bud Selig and Donald Fehr.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, baseball lucks out. Amidst grim evidence of a gambling
scandal by members of the 1919 Chicago White Sox, Babe Ruth hit 54
home runs in 1920 _ 25 more than had ever been hit before. In 1921,
he hit 59 more. It was said that Babe Ruth saved baseball by
hitting baseballs over fences.
</P>
<P>
   It would be exaggerating to say that Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa
(and Junior Griffey and Greg Vaughn) have saved baseball with their
home runs, but the television networks are scrambling to upgrade
their coverage, and the Internet is buzzing with the latest news,
literally pitch by pitch.
</P>
<P>
   What a far cry from the Ruthian days when people stood outside
the Western Union office and followed the World Series via the
ticker. For that matter, Roger Maris' splendid year was closer to
Babe Ruth's time than the age of the proprietary Gates from
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   In this summer of McGwire and Sosa, an old sportscaster named
Bill Weaver in the Maris home town of Fargo, N.D., recalled, ``Back
then, you didn't have highlights on TV or updates on the radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver told Dave Dondoneau of The Fort Worth Star-Telegram how
he used to invite Rudy Maris, the father of Roger, to the station
to follow the crucial games via the old-fashioned tickertape.
``We'd just sit there and wait for the updates,'' Weaver said.
``Tick ... tick ... tick ... HR ... tick ... tick ... tick ... NYY
... tick ... tick ... M ... tick ... A ... tick ... it drove us
crazy waiting to see if the next letter would be an N or an R.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there are web sites and talk radio and cable stations and
networks and national newspapers, making it easy to talk baseball,
when something wonderful is happening. Friday night, in the shadow
of the Gateway Arch, the big man will flex muscles as big as the
river that flows past. Baseball lives.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
