<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7967 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-PEACE-0904-CO     09-03 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-PEACE-0904-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EVEN WOUNDED, CLINTON STILL PROVIDES BOOST FOR STALLED IRISH
PEACE PROCESS
 &HT;    With IRELAND-CLINTON-0904; IRELAND-PRIMER-0904.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARMAGH, Northern Ireland _ Wounded as his presidency may be,
Bill Clinton's return here has generated fresh momentum for a peace
process that at times has seemed hopelessly stalled.
</P>
<P>
   The strain of the summer had taken its toll on the complex
process started four months ago to bring an end to ``the troubles''
that have gnawed at the heart of this island for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Terrorism, which was proclaimed a thing of the past in the
spring, claimed its bloodiest day just last month when 28 people
were killed in a car bomb attack in Omagh. A few weeks earlier,
three young brothers died in their beds when their house in
Ballymoney was firebombed in a sectarian attack.
</P>
<P>
   And as political leaders have struggled to evolve from mortal
enemies to respectful opponents, the process seemed to founder on a
generation of distrust.
</P>
<P>
   The president's visit may have brought the catalyst needed to
produce an important breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, there were clear signs that two key leaders of
opposing sectarian factions may meet -- perhaps even shake hands --
a prospect that three years ago would have been dismissed as
bizarrely optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   The once fierce adversaries, unionist David Trimble and
republican, Gerry Adams, are expected to meet meet next week, said
White House spokesman Michael McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, the leader of the Ulster Unionist Party and first
minister of the new Northern Ireland Assembly, has refused to meet
with Adams, the president of Sinn Fein, the political party long
associated with the Irish Republican Army, or IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Such a meeting would be viewed as clear evidence here that the
peace process has gone beyond the point of no return.
</P>
<P>
   The impasse was approaching the critical point. Trimble has been
suggesting that he may refuse to take his seat in the assembly,
which is expected to hold its first session in a few weeks, with
Adams until the Sinn Fein leader adequately renounced the use of
violence.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of Clinton's arrival, Adams issued his strongest
statement to date renouncing the use of force. ``Sinn Fein believes
the violence we have seen must be for us all a thing of the past,
over, done with and gone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Sinn Fein agreed to participate in an international
commission on disarming paramilitary forces of both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble expressed skepticism, saying he still must see concrete
signs that the IRA is prepared to disarm. ``Words alone cannot heal
the mistrust,'' he said. ``People want not just to hear of peace,
they want to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton nevertheless welcomed the statement. ``Those words were
music to ears all across the world, and they pave the way for the
progress still to come,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the deep differences that remain, the statements
swirling around Clinton's visit seemed to share an acceptance that
the conflict in Northern Ireland has moved from a violent struggle
to a political one.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the surrender of weapons remains elusive, there is
no credible leader on the island who advocates the use of force.
This is a substantial change since Clinton's last visit.
</P>
<P>
   Much else has changed since the 1995 visit to bring Northern
Ireland to this point. The governments of the Republic of Ireland
and the United Kingdom have joined in unprecedented levels of
cooperation to address the problems of Northern Ireland. In the
wake of the Omagh bombings, British Prime Minister Tony Blair and
Irish leader Bertie Ahern have worked in tandem to obtain tougher
anti-terrorism measures from their legislatures. Such cooperation
would have been unthinkable even a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, the process survived the summer with its
terrorism attacks and conflicts over marches by Protestant groups
through Catholic neighborhoods to commemorate the 300-year-old
victory of Protestant hero King William of Orange.
</P>
<P>
   At times Thursday, it seemed that Clinton was treating the peace
process as a foregone conclusion, even holding it as an example for
other conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   However, he reminded business and political leaders in Belfast
that the peace is fragile and cautioned that it would be tested in
the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The terror in Omagh was not the last bomb of the Troubles; it
was the opening shot of a vicious attack on the peace,'' he said.
``The question is not whether there will be more bombs and more
attempts to undo with violence the verdict of the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   ``There well may be,'' he said. ``The question is how will you
react to it all -- to the violence? How will you deal with your
differences? Can the bad habits and brute forces of yesterday break
your will for tomorrow's peace?''
</P>
<P>
   The president's comments often had the ring of someone taking
his leave, and, indeed, Clinton is not expected to return as
president to Ireland -- the site of what is perhaps one of his
greatest foreign policy triumphs.
</P>
<P>
   The president's troubles over his admitted relationship with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, while rarely mentioned
directly, nevertheless is always with him. Hillary Rodham Clinton
has been greeted warmly, usually with standing ovations. She gives
no hint of any problems in her marriage, and the president has
mentioned her frequently in his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the criticism directed toward Clinton on the streets
here has more to do with U.S. attacks in Sudan and Afghanistan
following the embassy bombings in East Africa. Demonstrators
outside Waterfront Hall held up signs comparing the U.S. cruise
missile attacks to the Omagh bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Clinton remains popular here. He is highly
regarded not because he is an Irish-American -- the 14th American
president to hold that distinction -- but because he is considered
unusually adept at maneuvering through the complex political and
cultural forces that play upon the peace process here.
</P>
<P>
   Blair expressed this perception in his introduction: ``Above
all, your grasp, not just of the complexity of the issues, but of
the subtlety of the competing claims for justice, has meant that
your commitment to help was actually matched by your capacity to
help.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
