<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-SALES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETAILERS CITE GOOD SALES FOR AUGUST; ANALYSTS FRET ABOUT REST OF
YEAR
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl)  
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. retailers reported relatively strong sales for August on
Thursday, but analysts warned that continued unease in the stock
market and in the global economy could slow down retail sales for
the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obviously premature to make a call,'' said Jeffrey
Feiner, a retail analyst at Lehman Brothers. ``But certainly the
volatility in the market and in the economic outlook is likely to
cause some slowing in consumer spending. Some companies have been
talking about gradually scaling back orders for Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Retailers enjoyed strong sales increases over the summer, and
August was no exception. Same-store sales, or sales in stores open
at least a year, rose 3.5 percent in August compared with the month
a year earlier, according to the Goldman, Sachs retail composite
index.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the way were discount stores, which have enjoyed two
years of exceptional sales. Wal-Mart Stores Inc. reported a 7.6
percent gain, while Target, a unit of Dayton Hudson Corp., said
sales rose 4.9 percent. Sales at Dollar General rose 7.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Off-price apparel retailers, which have also been strong
performers for several quarters, saw sales slow a bit last month,
perhaps because they had lofty numbers with which to compare. Ross
Stores, for example, said sales rose only 2 percent, while Value
City saw sales fall 1.8 percent. TJX Co. reported a sales gain of 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among all retailers, department stores continued to be the real
laggards. Sales at Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. fell 0.7 percent, and sales
at Federated Department Stores Inc. fell 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   May Department Stores Co. said sales dropped 0.7 percent in
August, and Dillard Department Stores reported a 1 percent
decrease. Neiman Marcus, a unit of Harcourt General Inc., said
sales fell 1.7 percent. Only Saks Fifth Avenue reported a
respectable sales increase _ 7.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Department stores have been weak all year,'' said Richard
Baum, a retail analyst at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. ``They are losing
share to specialty apparel retailers, who are executing better this
year than last year. And then you've got the discount department
stores moving their offerings more upscale, like Target, which is
siphoning off business as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, among specialty apparel merchants, Ann Taylor Stores
said sales rose 15.5 percent, and The Gap Inc.'s sales rose 9
percent. The Limited Inc.'s sales blossomed 7 percent, thanks in
large part to improvements at its Express and Limited women's
chains.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers may also have given some of August's sales to
September because of the late Labor Day. ``There was some pretty
strong evidence that business in the Northwest and Southeast, where
back-to-school is earlier, was better for the month than in the
Northeast,'' Baum said. ``So we don't yet have the full picture of
back to school. We think September will be a strong month, and
we'll have to look at the two together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
