<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7980 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIRELAND-CLINTON-2TAK     09-03 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-CLINTON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARMLY GREETED IN ULSTER, CLINTON URGES LASTING PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (also see NIRELAND-SCENE)  
 (bl)  
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARMAGH, Northern Ireland _ On a rare sunny day marked by the
fragile promise of peace and the wrenching remnants of hatred,
President Clinton on Thursday urged all parties in Northern Ireland
to seize this moment of optimism to secure lasting reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke of hope, but warned of the certainty of more pain to
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you look ahead, to be sure,'' the president told a crowd of
several thousand on a broad greensward in the center of this city
southwest of Belfast, ``in this peace process, there will be false
steps and disappointments. The question is not if the peace will be
challenged. You know it will. The question is, How will you respond
when it is challenged?''
</P>
<P>
   But he urged the people of Northern Ireland to press on in their
quest for peace. ``Three years ago, I pledged that if you chose
peace, America would walk with you,'' Clinton said, referring to
his visit here in late 1995. ``You made the choice, and America
will honor its pledge.''
</P>
<P>
   The president journeyed across Ulster on Thursday, meeting with
members of the new Northern Ireland Assembly in Belfast and with
the families of the victims of the Aug. 15 bombing in Omagh, the
worst attack in Northern Ireland's 29-year civil war. He dedicated
a new university campus that straddles Protestant and Catholic
districts of Belfast, and delivered an evening address at a
``Gathering for Peace'' in Armagh, the ancient spiritual capital of
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere he was met with warmth and acceptance, a welcome
relief after a tense summit meeting in Moscow and months of
personal and political troubles at home. Clinton appeared
noticeably cheered by his reception here, a respite from the debate
still raging in the United States over his honor and his honesty.
</P>
<P>
   He was accompanied everywhere Thursday by British Prime Minister
Tony Blair, a friend and kindred spirit who offered Clinton moral
support during a visit to Washington in January a few days after
the Monica Lewinsky matter became public.
</P>
<P>
   This was Clinton's second visit to Northern Ireland, and while
his reception was not as ecstatic as it was in November 1995, it
clearly lifted his flagging spirits.
</P>
<P>
   In Omagh, crowds a dozen deep lined the streets as Clinton
somberly walked down Market Street past the buildings smashed in a
terrorist bombing three weeks ago that killed 28 and injured 200.
When Clinton entered a hall to speak in Belfast, an audience of 500
gave him an extended ovation. And thousands stood patiently on the
playing fields in Armagh waiting for his 8 p.m. arrival.
</P>
<P>
   The president spent an hour Thursday afternoon with victims of
the bombing and their families at a municipal recreation center in
Omagh, a town of 25,000 located 70 miles west of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   The president spoke briefly, encouraging the people gathered on
a basketball court not to let ``a cowardly crime'' deter them from
the path of peace. He said the terrorism had strengthened the
momentum toward reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened here on Aug. 15 was so incredibly unreasonable,
so shocking to the conscience of every decent person in this land,
that it has perversely had exactly the reverse impact that the
people who perpetrated this act intended,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By killing Catholics and Protestants, young and old, men,
women and children, even those about to be born, people from
Northern Ireland, the Irish Republic and abroad _ by doing all that
in the aftermath of what the people have voted for in Northern
Ireland, it galvanized, strengthened and humanized the impulse to
peace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting the families, Clinton, Hillary Rodham Clinton,
Blair and his wife, Cherie, walked past the bomb's devastation and
greeted hundreds who lined to streets to see them. The two couples
laid a wreath near the spot where the bomb exploded.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has invested much time and the prestige of his office in
brokering a peace accord reached April 10, and his visit Thursday
served as a catalyst for the declaration earlier this week by Sinn
Fein leader Gerry Adams, that violence on all sides must be ``a
thing of the past, over, done with and gone.'' This week Adams also
appointed Sinn Fein's respected chief negotiator, Martin
McGuinness, as the party's representative to a new disarmament
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met with Adams and leaders of all the major parties to
be represented at the new Northern Ireland assembly, which is to
meet formally for the first time later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Clinton believed he had secured the agreement of
David Trimble, leader of the Ulster Unionist Party and the
designated first minister in the new Assembly, to meet next week
with Adams for the first time. Trimble has steadfastly refused for
years to speak with any representatives of Sinn Fein, which the
Protestant Unionists consider the public face of a banned terrorist
organization.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Trimble-Adams meeting is not yet assured, despite Clinton's
prodding, officials acknowledged Thursday evening. ``I think that
there is a good expectation that a meeting will take place next
week,'' said James Steinberg, the president's deputy national
security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Another official said it was likely the meeting would also be
attended by Seamus Mallon, the No. 2 official of the Assembly and
the leader of the Catholic Social Democratic and Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, introducing Clinton at a gathering Thursday morning at
Waterfront Hall in Belfast, praised the president for his role in
securing the April accord and said, ``We are determined to do
everything we can to make this agreement work.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not look directly at Adams, seated 25 feet away in the
front row of the auditorium. ``Words alone cannot heal distrust,''
Trimble said pointedly, ``but deeds will.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, noticeably buoyed by the audience's prolonged ovation
and speaking on an issue close to his heart, said Northern Ireland
had chosen to break with its anguished past by accepting the April
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you must prove that the passion for reason and moderation
can trump the power of extremes,'' he said. ``There will be hard
roads ahead. The terror in Omagh was not the last bomb of the
troubles; it was the opening shot of a vicious attack on the peace.
The question is not whether there will be more bombs and more
attempts to undo with violence the verdict of the ballot box. There
well may be.''
</P>
<P>
   The test of the new accord and Northern Ireland's new governing
structures will be how they respond to future attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said successful implementation of the accord required
the specific steps that were spelled: disarmament by Protestant and
Catholic paramilitary groups; formation of a multi-party executive
council to administer the province's laws; an end to police
brutality and street justice by armed bands; early release of
political prisoners whose organizations forswear violence;
protection of human rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the people of Northern Ireland I say, it is your will for
peace, after all, that has brought your country to this moment of
hope,'' Clinton said at Waterfront Hall. ``Do not let it slip away.
It will not come again in our lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the people who turned out to see Clinton were
grateful for his efforts to foster peace and delighted that he
returned to Ulster.
</P>
<P>
   One skeptic was Gerald Douglas, 68, of Newcastle, Northern
Ireland, who came to Armagh to hear Clinton speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose his intentions are good,'' he said of Clinton's
involvement. But Douglas said Clinton's relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky undercut his authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Northern Ireland is a fairly religious country and we don't
take too kindly to it,'' he said. ``When you become president or
king, you have to set an example, and I don't think he set too good
an example.''
</P>
<P>
   But most others in the crowd were willing to overlook Clinton's
personal weaknesses and simply welcome him back to the land he
claims as his ancestral home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a wee thing for Ireland,'' said Josephine Gay of
Armagh. ``If everybody's washing were hung out, there would be
skeletons in all their closets.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
