<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES BUOYED BY ONGOING STOCK TURMOIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bonds continued to benefit from the turbulence in
stocks Thursday, managing a modest gain.
</P>
<P>
   Investor demand for U.S. government securities, especially for
the shorter maturities, has recently been tied to the rise and fall
of the nation's and overseas stock markets. With stocks down
Thursday, still in reaction to the unresolved economic crisis in
Russia and turbulence in the global financial markets, bonds were
up.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year bond rose 15/32, to 103. The bond's yield, which
moves in the opposite direction, was down to 5.30 percent, from
5.33 percent Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market was poised for the release of the August jobless
report Friday. Analysts forecast a gain of 370,000 new jobs last
month. One estimate was even higher, calling for a gain of as much
as 500,000 new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department released its weekly report on first-time
applications for jobless benefits Thursday for the week ended Aug.
29. The data rose only slightly, indicating that the labor market
was still tight. Claims were up 1,000, to 302,000. The four-week
average of claims _ which economists consider more reliable _ fell
to 302,250, its lowest level in a year.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pugliese, senior vice president and director of fixed
income at J.W. Charles Securities Inc. in Boca Raton, Fla., said,
``The long and the short of it today is that bonds are trading
inversely to the Dow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As for the August employment data being released on Friday, I
have no apprehension about the number,'' he added. ``I think that
all of the positive factors have been factored in at these market
price levels. In other words, we are fully valued here, taking into
account the emerging markets, the stock market, low inflation,
along with a number of other things that bode well for the bond
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping in mind what happened to stocks, Pugliese is being
cautious about bonds: ``I get a little apprehensive when I hear
analysts say bonds are going to go up in price. It makes me a
little nervous. That's why I think any surprise in the employment
numbers tomorrow could just as easily be a negative for Treasuries.
The only reason the bond market traded higher today is because of
the turmoil in the equity markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonds were further bolstered in the afternoon by late buying
linked to Moody's Investors Service downgrading of Brazil's foreign
currency debt rating to B-2 from B-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 1859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
