A8004 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      09-03 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CHEERED IN IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARMAGH, Northern Ireland _ President Clinton took a whirlwind
tour of hope Thursday across the healing scars of this rolling
countryside, basking before adoring crowds, comforting families
ravaged by sectarian war and urging lifelong enemies to let their
violent past give way to a peaceful future.
</P>
<P>
   He was given a hero's welcome, hailed as an architect of this
young and fragile peace, applauded loudly at every stop by crowds
that spilled out of auditoriums and surged against ropelines to
shake his hand.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Clinton warned of the inevitability of future
violence and urged the battle-weary Irish, Protestants and
Catholics alike, to overcome it. And he sternly advised the
paramilitary factions to lay down ``weapons of war that are
obsolete in a Northern Ireland at peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Two proud traditions can exist side by side, bringing people
closer to God and closer to each other,'' Clinton said to a
boisterous outdoor crowd at a park in this quaint city. Later, he
added: ``Three years ago, I pledged that if you chose peace,
America would walk with you. You made the choice and America will
honor its pledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours earlier Clinton landed in the village of Omagh, a town
still reeling from an Aug. 15 car bombing that killed 28 innocent
bystanders _ including a woman pregnant with twins _ and injured
220, in the single worst attack in the 30-year-old guerrilla war
between Catholics and Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met a somber collection of survivors and family members
who had gathered in the same information center where many of them
had been told that their loved ones had died. The president spoke
briefly, then wandered from table to table, first talking with a
14-year-old girl blinded in the blast.
</P>
<P>
   But as Clinton pointed out throughout the day, rather than
weakening the peace plan, the bombing seemed to strengthen the
island's resolve. Those killed included the young and old, men and
women, and perhaps most importantly, Protestants and Catholics,
drawing the two sides together in a common grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It galvanized, strengthened and humanized the impulse to
peace,'' Clinton told the groups, adding separately, ``To all of
you, we thank you for standing up in the face of such a
soul-searching loss and restating your determination to walk the
road of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   By every measure, the daylong tour was a victory lap for
Clinton, an opportunity to showcase what is arguably the most
significant foreign policy triumph in his 5 1/2 years as president.
It was Clinton who played a crucial role in allowing the factions
to reach their Good Friday accord in the spring, through constant
prodding, sage appointments and a last-minute blitz of telephone
lobbying on the eve of the pact.
</P>
<P>
   He has told confidants that his trip to Belfast in 1995, when
100,000 supporters turned out to greet him in a gently falling
snow, was the best day of his presidency. Thursday's visit may rank
as the most timely. Badgered at home by questions of credibility
and fresh off a Russian summit that yielded only specious results,
Clinton seemed enlivened by the loud and repeated ovations he
received at every stop.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in Belfast, in a morning speech before the newly elected
Northern Ireland Assembly, Clinton beamed at his applauding
audience, letting his eyes drift toward the balcony in seeming joy.
As the crowd finally settled back into their chairs, Clinton was
the last official on stage to reluctantly take his seat.
</P>
<P>
   The day even began with an unusual dose of good news. Clinton
arrived from an early morning flight from Moscow, quickly descended
the steps of Air Force One and was handed a newspaper, The
Independent, with the front page headline: ``Trimble agrees to meet
Adams for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   It represented a remarkable turn _ David Trimble, the Protestant
leader of the newly elected Northern Ireland Assembly, and Gerry
Adams, the hard line head of Sinn Fein, the political arm of the
militant Irish Republican Army, coming together despite years of
open disdain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the headline we wanted to see when we got here,'' said
Samuel (Sandy) Berger, Clinton's national security adviser, after
he made a beeline for reporters on the tarmac of the Belfast
airport.
</P>
<P>
   Upon Clinton's arrival, he immediately met with leaders of
virtually every relevant faction at the Stormont Parliament
Building to personally endorse the Good Friday peace plan. He
walked into the room and simply asked, ``What can I do to help?''
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair, who accompanied and lauded
Clinton throughout the day, told him he could concentrate on
stifling private US financial support for militant extremist
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the breakaway splinter factions of the IRA do have
some source of support and we agreed that we can identify and
locate and isolate and eradicate those sources of support in the
United States,'' said Michael McCurry, Clinton's press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   At his morning speech, Clinton seemed unusually subdued, telling
the gathering of well-dressed officials, Adams and Trimble among
them, ``Your destiny is peace.''
</P>
<P>
   By afternoon, Clinton appeared more at ease. Aides said he was
``deeply moved'' in his closed-door meeting with the families in
Omagh, a market city of 18,000 people. When he arrived, in the last
light of a pristine early autumn day, he was outright animated,
working the crowd into repeated cheers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this peace process, there will be false steps and
disappointments,'' said Clinton. ``The question is not if the peace
will be challenged. You know it will be. The question is how will
you respond to it when it is challenged.''
</P>
<P>
   He again raised the bombing in Omagh and added, ``Out of the
unimaginably horrible agony of Omagh, the people said, it is high
time somebody told these people that we are through with hate,
through with war, through with destruction. It will not work
anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
