<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG BALL REVIVES THE NATIONAL PASTIME _ AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Pastime is back. Four years after a strike canceled
the World Series and put major league baseball on the path to
oblivion, the game has been revived by a succession of stunning
performances, specifically Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa's
season-long assault on one of the game's most cherished records.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting four monstrous home runs in two nights in Miami,
Cardinals slugger McGwire goes into tonight's game in St. Louis
with 59 homers. Only Babe Ruth (60 in '27) and Roger Maris (61 in
'61) ever hit more. McGwire has 23 games left in which to hit three
home runs and guarantee immortality.
</P>
<P>
   And so America's summer of stock market woes, ``Saving Private
Ryan,'' and a devil in a blue dress also goes down in the books as
the Summer of the Home Run. Like a favorite son returning from a
stint overseas in the Peace Corps, baseball has come home to remind
us of what was great about the game in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that the home run chase has made a stunning
contribution to bringing the focus back on the field,'' says
baseball commissioner Bud Selig, the man who announced cancellation
of the World Series in 1994. ``It's fascinating. It's why this is
still the greatest game in the world. No other sport reaches people
and captivates the nation the way baseball can.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide attendance is up 3.2 percent and major league
baseball could draw in excess of 70 million fans and wipe out the
attendance record set in 1993 _ one year before the strike. Last
Sunday night's ESPN game, featuring McGwire and the Cardinals, was
the network's second-highest-rated baseball telecast ever, topped
only by Cal Ripken's consecutive-game record-breaker of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the feats of McGwire and Sosa, baseball in 1998
has a New York Yankee team threatening to break the record for wins
(116 by the 1906 Cubs) in a season. There's also been a perfect
game by Yankee lefthander David Wells, a run on Hack Wilson's
68-year-old RBI record (190), and an influx of new superstars,
including Red Sox shortstop Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   In New England, fans are ecstatic about the unexpected rise of
the Red Sox and the possibility of a seven-game playoff series with
the Yankees in October. The trendy Patriots open their season
Monday night against the Super Bowl champion Denver Broncos, but
fans suddenly are talkin' baseball again.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on home runs. Everyone loves the long ball. The summer
of '98 has created a national obsession with the home run chase.
Baseball hasn't had any real pennant races and the games have
become secondary to the inning-by-inning updates of McGwire and
Sosa's respective performances. ESPN's ``SportsCenter'' usually
leads the hour with news of the home run chase, and most newspapers
in the land have devised their own graphic to keep fans up to date
on the march toward Maris. ESPN added Friday night's Cardinals-Reds
game to its lineup, and Fox TV picked up Saturday's game in St.
Louis and had it converted from a night game to a matinee.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time baseball has been bailed out by
tape-measure shots. In 1919, eight members of the Chicago White Sox
were involved in a conspiracy to throw the World Series against
Cincinnati. The ``Black Sox'' scandal threatened to ruin major
league baseball, but the game was saved in part when the
larger-than-life Ruth hit 54 homers in 1920 and 59 in '21 to put
the focus back on the field.
</P>
<P>
   When Maris _ considered a party-crasher in the pantheon of
baseball greats _ hit 61 homers, baseball, and New York in
particular, was still reeling from the relocation of the Dodgers
and Giants to the West Coast. Expansion had watered down the
product, and purists were horrified when the traditional 154-game
season was expanded by eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have McGwire, the red-haired mastodon, hitting a home run
once every eight trips to the plate. This is his third consecutive
season with 50 or more homers (breaking Ruth's record), and he's
been joined by Sosa, a relatively unknown slugger from the
Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Though there have been months of expectation and anticipation
about the quest for 62, few baseball experts believed any player
would be this close with so much time remaining in the season.
McGwire is a whopping six homers ahead of where Maris was after the
same number of games in 1961. Maris did not hit No. 61 until the
final day of the season (against Red Sox righthander Tracy
Stallard). Maris staggered late in the '61 season and lost clumps
of hair from worry. McGwire has practically thrown off all the
pressure. It's no longer a question of ``Can he do it?'' It's
``When can he do it?'' And how many for the Cubs' Sosa, who is at
56 with 22 games left?
</P>
<P>
   The only controversy touching McGwire involves his use of
androstenedione, a naturally occurring steriod sold over the
counter and allowed by major league baseball. McGwire says he takes
``andro'' as a dietary supplement to help him train harder and
recover faster. It is banned by the NFL, the NCAA, and the
International Olympic Committee. Critics have complained that the
Cardinal slugger is sending the wrong message to aspiring young
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy seems to come with the territory. When Maris hit his
61st in New York's 162d game, it was considered tainted because the
new schedule was eight games longer than Ruth's campaign in 1927.
Maris's record was listed with an asterisk until 1991, when former
commissioner Fay Vincent erased the black mark and crowned Maris
the undisputed home run champ. McGwire has a chance to wipe out all
the records long before he gets to 154 games.
</P>
<P>
   More than any sport, baseball is about numbers: 714 was Ruth's
seemingly unassailable career home run total, which was surpassed
by Henry Aaron (who finished with 755) in 1974. It was also assumed
that Lou Gehrig's streak of playing in 2,130 consecutive games
could never be matched, but that was before Ripken (2,617 and
counting) came along. Ted Williams (.406 in 1941) is baseball's
last .400 hitter, and Joe DiMaggio's 56-game hitting streak remains
intact. But Maris's 61 in '61 is going to fall, and everyone, even
the ballplayers, seems happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   Historian Doris Kearns Goodwin, author of the best-selling
``Wait 'Til Next Year,'' says, ``The nicest part is when you see
the other players' awe toward these guys. Usually, they are such
individuals, only worrying about themselves, but in so many of
these stories, you see Sosa giving McGwire credit and the great
Garciaparra talking about it. They must feel it's good for the
whole game. You somehow feel it's a band of brothers, which makes
you feel a sense of them all being together as professionals and
belonging to something that is larger than themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Major league pitchers are part of the story. Stallard became a
trivia answer when he yielded Maris's 61st homer, and the man who
surrenders No. 62 to McGwire faces a lifetime of infamy. Most
pitchers say they'll challenge McGwire and Sosa. They don't want to
give up the record-breaking homer, but they don't want to issue a
walk and appear cowardly.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the seamy issue of 1990s memorabilia madness. In
1961, when Maris hit No. 61, the ball was caught by Sal Durante, a
teenager from Coney Island, who gave it to Maris, posed for a few
pictures, and was rewarded with a $5,000 check from a Sacramento
restaurateur. It's been estimated that the home run ball that
breaks Maris's record could fetch seven figures.
</P>
<P>
   Those who believe in the larger forces _ and the church of
baseball has many disciples of superstition _ take note that Maris
broke Ruth's record 13 years after the Babe died in 1948. Roger
Maris died in 1985. Thirteen years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
