<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE, BRUINS TO TALK CONTRACT EXTENSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ This will be the 20th season for Bruins captain Ray
Bourque, but chances are excellent it won't be his last. Bourque,
who turns 38 in December, is scheduled to sit down with management
next week to discuss a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   This season Bourque will be the lone first-round pick from the
celebrated 1979 entry draft remaining as an active player in the
NHL. Wayne Gretzky came in through the WHA as a priority pick by
Edmonton that year. In addition to Bourque and Gretzky, only Dale
Hunter (selected No. 41 overall), Guy Carbonneau (No. 44), and Mark
Messier (No. 48) remain from the '79 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Bourque repeatedly said he would wait until his
contract ran out at the end of this season before deciding whether
to continue his career. However, after a break this summer which
gave him time to think, he has changed his mind. Right now he
thinks he'll play one extra year, retiring after the 1999-2000
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to go on too long,'' said Bourque, speaking
after a workout at Pingree School in Hamilton. ``Let's keep it
realistic. I think two (more) years and we'll see where we go from
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque said he doesn't yet know if he'll meet only with
president-general manager Harry Sinden or with assistant GM Mike
O'Connell as well. He isn't sure if he'll be accompanied by his
representative, Steve Freyer, or will go on his own for the initial
meeting. But no matter who is in attendance, he figures he'll know
very early if the sides can come to an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go in there and listen to what they have to say
and they'll listen to what I have to say and then we'll see where
we go from there,'' said Bourque. ``I'm going in there to see what
happens but I really don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is discussing specific figures. However, anyone with any
business sense knows that in order for Bourque to forgo
unrestricted free agency next July 1, he will have to have his deal
sweetened for this year. Bourque is scheduled to make $3.5 million
in the last year of his current pact. With Al MacInnis the current
pacesetter for defensemen at $4.5 million, it's likely Bourque will
want to increase his earnings to that same figure for this year,
with a bump to the $5 million range next season. However the
situation gets resolved, Bourque said the decision wasn't driven by
money. It was driven by a reevaluation after some time away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see myself playing more than next year,'' he said. ``I think
that's a definite. When you're going through it, sometimes you
don't really know. But you step away from it for a little bit, you
look at the year and how things went, how I felt, how I played. I
enjoyed myself and things went well. I think I had another solid
year and I don't see why that can't continue. If I stay healthy, I
don't think that will be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque said the summer afforded him some perspective that was
hard to come by during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get done with the season, sometimes there are certain
points of the year where it's longer and tougher and you don't
know,'' he said. ``When you have one year left, you don't know what
you are going to do. But I'm pretty clear on what I want to do now.
I want to play more than this upcoming season.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, he would like to get the extension done quickly and
quietly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it should be done that way,'' he said. ``I don't see
why not, but we'll see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
