<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-CURVEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURVEY NAMED PRESIDENT OF FIDELITY PARENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In his quiet rise to power at Fidelity Investments,
James C. Curvey has helped steer the nation's largest mutual fund
firm through the turbulent waters of competition and crisis. Now
Curvey, Fidelity's influential, behind-the-scenes chief operating
officer, has an even more commanding role.
</P>
<P>
   Curvey, 63, Thursday was named president of Fidelity's parent
company, FMR Corp. The title gives Fidelity's number two man a
stronger hand in daily operations and strategic business planning,
and a greater role in preparing the Boston-based firm for the
future.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment signals that Fidelity's chairman and chief
executive, Edward C. ``Ned'' Johnson III, is gradually assuming a
narrower role in running the firm his father founded just after
World War II. It also underscores what industry observers say is
Curvey's function to prepare the ground for Johnson's 36-year-old
daughter, Abigail, to eventually take over her father's company
should she wish to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Curvey's new title formalizes some arrangements that were
already in place. But it also consolidates the growing, front-stage
position of a man observers say is Johnson's closest confidante and
most trusted adviser.
</P>
<P>
   As president, Curvey now has a greater number of senior
executives reporting to him. Previously only the heads of corporate
administration, finance, and affairs reported to him on operational
issues, while other top executives reported to Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the heads of all of Fidelity's core business units _
including J. Gary Burkhead, who heads sales and distribution,
Robert L. Reynolds, who oversees institutional retirement, Mark A.
Peterson, who heads systems and services, Roger T. Servison, who
oversees international operations, Kevin J. Kelly, head of
institutional investment products, and Timothy T. Hilton, who heads
the Fidelity Capital venture capital unit _ report to Curvey on a
day-to-day basis.
</P>
<P>
   Robert C. Pozen, who heads Fidelity's retail mutual fund unit,
now reports to Curvey on all ``nonfund related'' issues, Fidelity
spokeswoman Anne W. Crowley said. Previously, Pozen reported to
Johnson on all matters.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 67, who shows no signs of retiring any time soon, now
handles only policy matters, including fund management issues.
</P>
<P>
   Curvey retains his current titles of chairman of Fidelity's
powerful 10-person operating committee (the firm's key
decision-making group) and vice chairman of FMR Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Described by industry observers as elegant but hard-driving,
Curvey joined Fidelity in 1982 as human resources director.
Appointed operations chief in May 1997 at a time when Fidelity was
battling a string of defections by fund managers, disappointing
returns, and a lack of coordination among its fractious units,
Curvey played a major role in smoothing things out. Prior to that,
he headed Fidelity Capital, a colorful collection of assets,
ranging from telecommunications firms and art galleries, that
reflects Johnson's varied interests.
</P>
<P>
   Eric M. Kobren, editor of the independent Fidelity Insight
newsletter, said under Curvey's tenure, Fidelity had stabilized by
improving fund returns, slowing attrition, integrating distribution
channels, and cutting costs. Private, family-owned Fidelity had
$692.9 billion in assets under management and 12.3 percent of the
nation's fund market as of the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were growing, but we never really had time to take care of
growing,'' Curvey said in an interview. ``I guess Ned's satisfied
with the job I'm doing.'' The firm last had a president in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Curvey's new title comes as Wall Street gyrates wildly, Fidelity
launches a new advertising campaign, and Abigail P. Johnson
prepares to return to the firm, where she is a senior vice
president assisting Pozen, from maternity leave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
