<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8032 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-SCENE-550&AMP;ADD-N     09-03 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-SCENE-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAINT COASTAL VILLAGE TRANSFORMED BY TRAGEDY OVERNIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CAREY GOLDBERG and MICHAEL COOPER   
 c 1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEGGY'S COVE, Nova Scotia _ When Brendan Fitzgerald, a tourist
from Massachusetts, arrived in Peggy's Cove earlier this week, it
was still known mainly as the most visited, most admired old
fishing village on Nova Scotia's craggy east coast _ necklaced by
great white rocks, serenaded by crashing surf and crowned by a
red-tipped lighthouse worth driving hours to see.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, with the crash of SwissAir Flight 111 just five miles
away, it became synonymous with such places as Lockerbie, Scotland,
and East Moriches, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   And the 60 or so souls here woke up Thursday in a different
hamlet, one whose carefree tourists have been driven out by fire
engines, television vans and somber emergency crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a pleasant place,'' Fitzgerald said. ``It's amazing
how a blanket of sadness can suddenly cover a place.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadness with a hint of horror. From the rounded rocks where
tourists gaze to sea, the vista Thursday included Her Majesty's
Canadian Ship Preserver, a naval supply vessel collecting debris
and passengers' remains, its freezers turning rapidly into a mass
morgue.
</P>
<P>
   To and from the Preserver shuttled Coast Guard cutters and
humble local lobster boats still scouring the swells for flotsam
and jetsam from the plane. By daybreak, officials had said that
there had been no survivors of the crash, but rescue workers said
they still held out hope of finding someone alive.
</P>
<P>
   But in the main, the jobs of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police,
the Canadian Transportation Safety Board and hundreds of other
rescue workers on Thursday consisted largely of fishing out tiny
bits of luggage, seat-rests, stray shoes, body parts and occasional
whole bodies.
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Dartmouth, at a Canadian military base, rescue workers
began to assemble a makeshift morgue in an airplane hangar in
preparation for the platoon of corpses soon to come.
</P>
<P>
   In Peggy's Cove itself, the sadness was mixed with a sense of
the surreal _the abnormal absence of the crowds of ocean-gazers on
the rocks; the edicts of the emergency workers, such as the ban on
children playing in the schoolyard because it was needed as a
helicopter landing spot. Tourists have been barred from the
village, which is normally one of Canada's most popular
destinations, and the prevailing tone of Peggy's Cove seemed turned
from light to dark in a kind of anti-holiday.
</P>
<P>
   On a house's back stoop high above the protected cove for which
the village is named, onlookers watched somberly Thursday as boats
that normally disgorge lobsters or sunburned whale-watchers instead
puttered in with shoes or a child's backpack in forensic-looking
plastic bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like Peggy's Cove has stopped,'' said Darrell
Fralick, 26, the attendant at the town's main parking lot. He had
been awakened at 2:30 a.m. to open the public washrooms in the lot
for use by the media and emergency crews flocking in, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really sad,'' said Tara Gabriel, Fralick's fiancee and an
attendant at the art gallery across the street from the parking
lot. ``This doesn't happen in Peggy's Cove's backyard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear about things like this,'' Fralick said, ``but when it
hits in your backyard, you can feel how other people feel.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``They all have families,'' said John Thomas, who patrols the
rocks of Peggy's Cove to keep tourists from endangering themselves
as they clamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all have people at home waiting,'' Frailick added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine,'' Ms. Gabriel said, ``going to the airport to meet
someone and the flight doesn't come in.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas continued: ``You only see a sign saying `See agent.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Such sympathy, expressed universally hereabouts, is nonetheless
only sympathy, not grief; Peggy's Cove did not lose any of its own
people _ a loss that would be deeply felt in a village dominated by
a handful of families, most of them here since the community was
founded in 1811.
</P>
<P>
   There were no tears to be seen here Thursday, as victims'
identities became known in only a trickle and the victims
themselves remained largely names without faces. Almost all the
recovered bodies were being taken to a Navy ship, not to shore
here.
</P>
<P>
   But there was concern closer to home as well. At least one
fisherman from Peggy's Cove, John Campbell, participated with
dozens of colleagues from nearby in the ghastly work of gathering
up bodies and debris from the sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like that in my life, and I hope I
never do again,'' Campbell, a red-headed man of 34, said quietly
and matter-of-factly Thursday back on the wharf at Peggy's Cove.
</P>
<P>
   It was Campbell and dozens of other veteran lobstermen,
fishermen and small boaters from the coves and villages south of
Halifax who, in the first horrible hours of the rescue effort,
rushed to form the vanguard of the search for survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents expressed concern for the physical _ and
psychological _ safety of those fishermen during their ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Richard E. Walsh, who ministers at the only church in
this town of 60 people, St. John's Anglican Church, said that even
hardened fishermen were having trouble dealing with the scope of
the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fishing village,'' he said. ``The people here know
about tragedies. They know what the sea can do.'' But he added:
``Some of the men are very, very upset. It's quite traumatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Some also expressed dismay that there was never a chance to
rescue anyone, here in a region where the rough Atlantic often
plunges ships into distress, and where daring rescues at sea are a
proud tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Crooks, a lobsterman, said he had considered taking his
boat _ which lacks the lights to run at night _ out to help with
rescues Thursday morning, but by daybreak, word had come that there
were no survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lot of people,'' said Gordon Earle, a Member of
Parliament whose region includes Peggy's Cove, ``The hardest thing
was that there was no one they could save.''
</P>
<P>
   Earle was walking Peggy's Cove's winding streets, he said,
because he wanted to show his support: ``It's quite traumatic for a
community to have this tragic disaster take place right there in
the community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, said Eliza Manuel, chairwoman of the Peggy's Cove
Commission that oversees local land use, ``It's scary to think how
close the crash was to all of us here _ minutes or seconds in the
air.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Manuel's father, John Beale, proprietor of Beales'
Bailiwick, a crafts store specializing in Canadian work, provided
some sage perspective to the strange day.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, an announcer on the all-news radio station
CJCH told listeners that the little village ``certainly takes on a
different meaning from the time you were there with your family
enjoying the beauty of Peggy's Cove.'' And Beale said that some
reporters had been asking him whether its association with tragedy
could damage Peggy's Cove, much as the village of Lockerbie,
Scotland, is now synonymous for many people with the 1988 crash of
Pan Am Flight 109.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ask, `Will the Cove ever be the same?''' he said. ``They
say, `Will people stay away forever?''
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, Beale said, given the public's penchant for sad,
gory stories like the sinking of the Titanic, Peggy's Cove will
most likely not be shunned for its association with tragedy.
Rather, he said, ``It will probably be the reverse. It's a sad
dialogue on society but it's true.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
