<HEADER>
A8037 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POOLPRO-ART-AZR &LR;      09-03 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POOL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR POOL PRO JEANETTE LEE, THE GAME IS HER LIFE  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO MOVED TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
 PRO-ART-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CRAVEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - There is a fine line between devotion and obsession.
</P>
<P>
   For Jeanette Lee, upon that line is balanced a cue stick. Every
day, every hour it hovers precariously between healthy enthusiasm
and destructive fixation.
</P>
<P>
   Lee is one of the best pool players in the nation, in the world
for that matter. She prowls that small patch of green felt like a
tiger smelling fresh meat _ and will do just so at the Penn Ray
WPBA Phoenix Classic, running today through Sunday at Bucky's
Casino in Prescott, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has been dubbed the Black Widow not only because of her
preferred color in fashion, but also because of the killer instinct
that takes over once she looks down the shaft of a cue.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to tell the first person she nearly destroyed at a
pool table was herself.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Lee, born and raised in New York City, was a typical
18-year-old who had no idea what she wanted to be when she grew up.
After landing a job at a software company, she thought about
attending college and becoming a teacher. Or maybe not. Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   That was before colleagues insisted she join them at a new pool
hall in town. It was big and oh so trendy.
</P>
<P>
   Funny how a night out can alter the rest of your life. Not one
detail of that visit has escaped Lee's memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I walked into this incredibly crowded pool room, an
old man caught my eye,'' Lee says from her offices in Cincinnati.
``As I watched him, the people and the music faded away. Pretty
soon all I could hear was the sound of his breathing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so mesmerized by everything he did, the way he lined up
his shots, how one shot led perfectly to another. Everything was so
simple and yet so perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee never picked up a cue stick that evening. It would be the
last pool-free night of her life.
</P>
<P>
   She went to the pool hall the next day and spent a few hours
learning the felt-covered ropes. It was long enough to know she'd
found her passion. It wasn't long before it was an obsession.
</P>
<P>
   Nights at the pool table stretched into early mornings. At one
point she played 37 hours straight before collapsing. Friends had
to carry her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was something there, a chemistry,'' Lee says. ``My life
became pool. Nothing else mattered.''
</P>
<P>
   One day led to another. Lee can't remember times she didn't have
a cue in her hand.
</P>
<P>
   It started to take a toll. Lee suffers from scoliosis, and at
times her back pain became insufferable. She became sick for days
at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I did was play pool,'' Lee says. ``I didn't eat, I didn't
sleep. Finally I said, `OK, I've got to stay within reality here.'
I had to take care of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first few years, she gave no thought to money or a
career. Until she entered a regional tournament and won. And won
another. And another.
</P>
<P>
   Doors she never knew existed opened to her. In 1993 she
qualified for the Women's Professional Billiards Association tour.
She'd become incredibly good incredibly fast.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past five years Lee has won several WPBA tournaments
and has become one of the tour's most popular players. Ranked third
on the tour, she is as busy making personal appearances as she is
competing. She maintains her own Web site (www.jeanettelee.com) and
heads the Jeanette Lee Foundation, a charitable organization.
</P>
<P>
   As busy as she is traveling and meeting fans, she still has a
hobby _ playing pool. In her spare time she likes to play pool. To
relax, she plays pool.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not an obsession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love the game,'' Lee says. ``I'd rather play than go to
a movie or go dancing or whatever. It's just that now I no longer
play to exhaustion.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
