<HEADER>
A8038 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CLINTON-ATTACKS-     09-03 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-ATTACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LACKIES TRYING TO TERRORIZE OPPONENTS  
 (THIS EDITORIAL APPEARS IN FRIDAY'S ARIZONA REPUBLIC)
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - In personal terms, Indiana Rep. Dan Burton's
confession of past troubles in his 38-year marriage, including a
hint of infidelity, was a sad but prudent pre-emptive strike
against a coming magazine article.
</P>
<P>
   But in political terms, it was an outrage _ one more instance of
the campaign of rumors and even terror waged by the Clinton White
House against anyone it views as a threat to the president's
future. Richard Nixon merely made a list of his enemies; Bill
Clinton's lackies (including a notorious private eye) put the fear
of God into them. Criticizing this president can be hazardous to
one's reputation and even health.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Rep. Paul McHale. Within days after calling on Clinton to
resign, the Pennsylvania Democrat was accused by unidentified White
House sources of faking his military record. The accusation was a
lie, but the audacity of aides to a draft dodger challenging the
military authenticity of anyone is little short of breathtaking.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Scott Ritter. The senior and highly praised U.S. weapons
inspector in Iraq, resigned when the administration quietly blocked
critical inspections, and was immediately labeled as a
``disgruntled'' ex-employee who had passed secret documents to
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Or ask Kathleen Willey. Two days before she was to testify about
her presidential groping, she was greeted by a stranger who asked
threatening questions about details of her life, and cited her
children by name.
</P>
<P>
   Or ask Sally Perdue, a former Miss Arkansas who had a fling with
Clinton in 1983 and has said she was warned against talking in 1992
by a campaign aide who noted that she was known to go jogging ``and
we can't guarantee what will happen to your pretty little legs.''
</P>
<P>
   All these incidents, and many others in an ugly litany of
vengeance dating to Little Rock, share a common thread _ instead of
confronting the criticism head on, they seek to smear and
intimidate the critic.
</P>
<P>
   No one suggests Clinton personally ordered all these acts, but
there is no question that the climate in which such conduct
flourishes is created at the top. And Clinton, who hails from a
small, one-party state run by an old-boy network, is used to
getting his way without the fuss and bother of reasoned debate.
</P>
<P>
   With grand jury testimony complete, White House attention has
shifted from witnesses to Congress, where a scorched-earth policy
is now aimed at discouraging members like Burton from thinking
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be working.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, they've just made people madder than hell,'' a House
aide said. At last, an encouraging word.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
