<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8039 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRTRAN-COX     09-03 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AirTran flight attendants threaten spot disruptions
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three years of acrimony between AirTran Airlines and the
Association of Flight Attendants come to a head this weekend, when
the union vows to disrupt operations if a contract is not reached.
</P>
<P>
   But AirTran executives say the union's threats will prove hollow
because of a lack of rank-and-file support and company
countermeasures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan to operate every flight,'' said Thomas Kalil, senior
vice president for operations and customer service at AirTran,
Atlanta's second-largest airline. The low-fare carrier has 120
daily departures from Hartsfield International Airport, where it
handles about 6 percent of the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   A strike countdown ends at midnight tonight, after which the AFA
can stage spot walkouts under a plan dubbed CHAOS, for Creating
Havoc Around Our System.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passengers won't know where or when we'll strike,'' said Bill
Green, president of the AFA local for AirTran. ``All they will know
is that they are stranded.''
</P>
<P>
   The union conducted a ceremonial ``lottery'' Thursday at
Hartsfield to decide which flights might be struck. Another group
of attendants who don't support the union planned a counter-rally
today.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran and union negotiators are in last-ditch contract talks
that could still avert the showdown. Neither side would
characterize their progress Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The mere threat of schedule disruptions is likely to cost
AirTran some business _ a chief element of the union's strategy to
pressure management into a better offer.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike larger airlines, AirTran does not have agreements under
which stranded passengers could trade in their reservations for
seats on rival carriers, although they could seek refunds.
</P>
<P>
   Kalil insisted that won't be a problem. He said AirTran's 700
flight attendants include only a couple hundred who support the
union. The AFA contends it has strong support but could not provide
a membership figure.
</P>
<P>
   Kalil said AirTran already has taken several steps to assure
that any walkouts won't force cancellations. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   Permanent replacements have been hired and trained, and will be
deployed in various cities where they could step in as needed.
Strikers who are replaced would be put on a preferential hiring
list when they agreed to return to work.
</P>
<P>
   Some airport agents are qualified to act as substitute
attendants if needed.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran has removed six seats from each of its DC-9 jets,
cutting the total to 100. That means flights can be staffed by two
attendants rather than the normal three, although Kalil said he
expects that will be rare. The Federal Aviation Administration
conducted safety tests for the two-attendant plan. AirTran passed
this week _ but only after failing the first three times.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute between the airline and the union dates to 1995,
when attendants at the then-ValuJet Airlines voted for AFA
representation. ValuJet merged with Orlando-based AirTran last year
and adopted its name.
</P>
<P>
   On-and-off talks never produced an initial contract, and ill
will grew when AFA leaders publicly criticized ValuJet management
during the three-month shutdown that followed the 1996 crash of
Flight 592 in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the National Mediation Board declared an impasse,
triggering a strike countdown.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the 1996 shutdown and high turnover, many of the
attendants who originally voted for AFA representation are no
longer with the carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Dissident attendants are trying to oust the AFA as their legal
bargaining agent, a laborious process that would require a vote
conducted by federal labor monitors. Karen Malone, one of the
organizers, said the group has 300 petition signatures and is
staging today's pro-company rally at Hartsfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to show our support for the airline and reassure
customers we'll be flying,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Union official David Borer discounted the anti-AFA campaign,
noting that efforts to unseat the union have been made since 1996
without result. In any case, he said, the CHAOS campaign is
designed so that only a few attendants have to take part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with a few flight attendants striking random flights, the
customer has to make a decision and risk rolling the dice and being
stranded at the airport,'' he said. ``The whole idea is to gain
leverage without putting a lot of jobs at risk.'' He said the
tactic has been used successfully at other AFA carriers, including
United and Alaska airlines.
</P>
<P>
   A chief sticking point in the contract talks is a union demand
that all flight attendants pay dues, whether or not they want to
belong to the union.
</P>
<P>
   The AFA argues that is a common feature of union contracts _
including those AirTran has with its pilots and mechanics _ and is
the only fair way to fund bargaining activities that cover all
members of a work group.
</P>
<P>
   Kalil said management promised attendants who don't support the
union it wouldn't accept a contract that forces them to pay union
fees. He said there was no such concern among pilots and mechanics,
``so those were different situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalil said AirTran gave flight attendants two pay raises last
year and is offering an immediate 10 percent raise in the new
contract, which would boost the base monthly salary for a
three-year attendant to about $1,600. That would be followed by 4
percent annual raises through 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Kalil said the airline's offer also boosts per diem pay and
provides a new uniform allowance and moving allowances.
</P>
<P>
   But Borer said the offer is ``still short and leaves them at or
near the bottom of the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalil said the airline will unilaterally implement the new
contract offer even if no agreement is reached _ another move to
discourage support for union walkouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether we reach an agreement or not,'' he said, ``the flight
attendants who work are going to reap the benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
