<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investors pull back
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stocks fell for the second straight session on Thursday as
investors pulled back ahead of the long Labor Day weekend, and
against the backdrop of continued foreign financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Investors aimed to lock in profits so they wouldn't be exposed
to further losses should anything disastrous happen between now and
Tuesday, in which time they would be unable to make a trade.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market, however, continued to benefit from fearful
investors looking for a safe haven from the world's turbulence.
Rising bond prices had the effect of lowering long-term Treasury
yields even more.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the market is still concerned that economic and
financial crises in Russia and Asia are already spreading to Latin
America. Moody's Investors Service downgraded ratings on the debt
of Venezuela and Brazil, and put a downgrade alert on Mexico and
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Market technicians believe the Dow Jones industrial average will
continue to decline until it tests the low of 7,539.07 it reached
on Monday, after falling 513 points. It closed Thursday at
7,682.22.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, most analysts believe the market may need some
major event, such as a cut in interest rates or an improvement in
foreign conditions, to turn stocks around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a bullish headline of major impact, it appears that
the bounce from Monday's sell-off has already reached its point of
diminishing returns,'' said Standard &AMP; Poor's analyst Paul Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Upbeat foreign news may be the least likely, however. There was
further chaos in Japan, as giant steelmaker Toa Steel announced it
would abandon efforts to survive and begin liquidating its assets.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street hopes to get better news about Japan from today's
meeting between Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan and Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi
Miyazawa.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say vigorous economic reform is needed in Japan if it
is to help solve economic problems in the rest of Asia, where Japan
has stronger trade ties than does the United States.
</P>
<P>
   All major stock averages posted losses in volatile trading
Thursday: the blue chip Dow by 1.3 percent, the technology-loaded
Nasdaq composite by 1.3 percent and the Russell 2000 index of
smaller stocks by 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Today's usually important report on August non-farm job growth
and the unemployment rate may get less attention because of the
effects of the General Motors strike.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's report that initial unemployment benefit claims rose
1,000 to 302,000 in the week ending Aug. 29 was interpreted,
however, as further evidence of strong job markets.
</P>
<P>
   But the National Association of Purchasing Management's
non-manufacturing index declined to 52 percent from 57.5 percent in
July, reflecting slower growth in service industries.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
