<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAPORTA-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Research Alliance thanks governor for his support
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gov. Zell Miller described the Georgia Research Alliance as one
of his lifetime's great achievements Thursday, but expressed
concern about the future of two of his other great accomplishments
_ the HOPE scholarship and pre-kindergarten programs.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was attending his eighth annual board meeting of the GRA,
a consortium of top business leaders and presidents of the state's
six research universities. Former and current board members alike
turned out to thank Miller at his last visit with the group as
governor. They credited Miller for supporting $200 million in state
funding over the past eight years, which helped increase Georgia's
technology employment from 86,000 in 1990 to 135,000 last year,
numbers that make Georgia a national leader.
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of continuing Georgia's progress in research and
technology, the GRA board voted unanimously to ask the next
governor to include in his budget $45 million _ its largest request
in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic about the Georgia Research Alliance,'' Miller
told the group. ``Frankly, I'm not as optimistic about the HOPE
scholarship and the pre-K programs. I think politicians in the next
few years will begin to try to fiddle with those two programs.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Miller added that he worries politicians will
want to take Georgia Lottery funds away from education for other
causes, such as fighting crime.
</P>
<P>
   Miller warned that the lottery is not an inexhaustible source of
money. The next governor will have to be careful not to dilute its
impact on education by agreeing to spend it elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've just got to have the vigilance and the commitment,''
Miller said, advising his successor. ``Folks knew that if they
messed with the lottery, I would slap them upside the head.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to recognize the governor, the GRA board announced
it will give an annual $5,000 stipend in Miller's name to a junior
faculty member working in technology at a Georgia university. GRA
President William A. Todd said they wanted to respect the
governor's wishes in not providing plaques or gold cowboy boots,
but in having an award that was in keeping with his initiatives as
governor.
</P>
<P>
   The GRA board hopes to convince the next governor of the
importance of supporting its initiatives, which include funding for
eminent scholars _ a program that brings nationally renown
researchers to Georgia universities _ as well as research labs and
equipment. By investing in the GRA, Todd said the state benefits
with more high-tech jobs by helping Georgia entrepreneurial
companies grow and by attracting new businesses to the state.
</P>
<P>
   The $45 million request includes $3 million for four new eminent
scholars, $10 million in new facilities, $31.1 million in equipment
and $750,000 for developmental funds across the state.
</P>
<P>
   United Way chairman takes job in New York
</P>
<P>
   Neal Purcell, chairman of Metro Atlanta United Way's 1998
campaign, has been named vice chairman of assurance for KPMG-Peat
Marwick in New York _ proving once again Atlanta is a launching pad
for executives of professional firms. Purcell has been KPMG's
managing partner in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Purcell said he will not move to New York full time until he has
completed his civic obligations in Atlanta. ``I plan to stick right
here until we complete the campaign and achieve the $70 million
goal,'' Purcell said Thursday. ``That was one of the conditions
that I made.''
</P>
<P>
   William J. Garrett, United Way's campaign vice president, said
Purcell already had done most of the legwork for the campaign by
naming a top-rate cabinet and completing 52 out of his 55 CEO
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Garrett said United Way hasn't yet figured out how the
campaign will make its $70 million goal, the most ambitious in its
history. But he has been encouraged by early returns. The campaign
will be launched Sept. 16, and the planned victory celebration is
Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his job change, Purcell also had to weather brain
surgery this summer. Calling it a simple operation, Purcell said he
has recovered and was given a clean bill of health by his
neurosurgeon this week.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Purcell has been transferred while in
the midst of important Atlanta civic roles.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, Purcell was in line to be chairman of the
Atlanta Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau, as well as chairman of the
Business Council of Georgia (now the Georgia Chamber of Commerce).
He had to give up those roles when he was transferred to Seattle by
KPMG-Peat Marwick. But when he returned to Atlanta, he became
chairman of the Georgia chamber.
</P>
<P>
   George Sands, who has been active with ACVB, will succeed
Purcell as managing partner of KPMG-Peat Marwick's Southeast
office.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Hassebroek, Atlanta managing partner with Andersen
Consulting, will head the Atlanta United Way campaign in 1999 and
will be available to help Purcell with fund-raising this year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
