u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MANN-OBIT-550(2TAKES)     09-03 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANN-OBIT-550(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. JONATHAN MAX MANN, PIONEER IN CAMPAIGN AGAINST AIDS, 51 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PHILIP J. HILTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Jonathan Max Mann, a pioneer in the international campaign
against AIDS and a founder of a movement to link health issues with
those of human rights, died Wednesday night alongside his wife, Dr.
Mary Lou Clements-Mann, a vaccine scientist at Johns Hopkins School
of Hygiene and Public Health University, in the crash of Swissair
Flight 111 off the coast of Nova Scotia. He was 51 and lived in
Columbia Md.
</P>
<P>
   Mann and Dr. Clements were on their way to Geneva to attend a
series of global strategy sessions on AIDS, sponsored by the World
Health Organization and the United Nations. On Thursday, Gro Harlem
Brundtland, the former prime minister of Norway who is now the WHO
director general, led a memorial service attended by about 80
colleagues on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting tears, she said Mann ``was the kind of person who
changed the course of events by his dedication, conviction and
commitment. He had a burning engagement for human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Mann, who spent a good portion of his career at the Harvard
School of Public Health, came to international prominence in 1986
when he founded and became the first director of the WHO's Global
Program on AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues said he was unusual among public health officers
because he was both fierce and sensitive at the same time, and took
on great challenges with an apparent disregard for their
difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jonathan was the architect of the global mobilization against
AIDS,'' said Dr. Daniel Tarantola, a senior policy adviser for the
director general of WHO. ``He said many times that the way you
define a problem will determine what you do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the spread of HIV, the virus that causes AIDS,
appeared uncontrollable and seemed to create a kind of political
paralysis among health officials around the world. ``Jonathan
determined to project an image of the epidemic that was one of a
disease that could be managed, could be controlled in some ways,''
Tarantola said. ``He defined the problem not only as a terrible
viral disease, but as a social problem to be solved.''
</P>
<P>
   He started the AIDS program with a single assistant and built it
over four years into the WHO's largest program in history,
employing 280 people and expending $109 annually in its budget.
</P>
<P>
   Although mild-mannered, he could be a passionate speaker. In
1989, at an AIDS Action Committee dinner in Boston, he said: ``In
the last few years we have gained confidence that as individuals
and all together we are not condemned passively to allow the
disease AIDS or the fears and forces which it can unleash to
dominate us. Against AIDS we will prevail together, for we will
refuse to be split, or to cast into the shadows those persons,
groups and nations that are affected.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. June Osborne, who had worked with Mann throughout his career
and is president of the Josiah Macy Jr. Foundation, which is
dedicated to improving medical education, said of him: ``He brought
the world together in a practical, unprecedented way. When he was
head of the Global Program, he had developed bilateral working
relations between the WHO and 155 countries around the world. He
got the developing countries to buy, for at least a time, the idea
that we really had a common cause _ to work on this deadly
epidemic.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
