<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8044 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARL04-COX     09-03 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARL04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In Florida, Earl spares some, wallops others
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY BEACH, Fl. _ Ben Simon watched the water rise early
Thursday toward his neat townhouse in the poorly named Gulf
Highlands Beach Resort, wondering if he should gather up his family
and run for high ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty minutes after it was at the edge of the door, it was a
foot deep in the house,'' said Simon, a husky man who has lived in
the 700-unit development for six years. ``I was really praying to
God that the rain would stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon and dozens of his neighbors survived, but their homes in
the low-lying neighborhood just off the main tourist drag in this
resort town were perhaps Bay County's hardest-hit after Hurricane
Earl came calling with torrential rains and 80 mph winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a mess,'' said Bob Wright, who retired here from
Americus, Ga. ``I'm guessing we've got 300 homes flooded in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Panama City Beach's tourist businesses, however, were
spared damage by the storm, although a few still had flooded
parking lots late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really was almost no damage at all,'' said Jayna Leach,
a spokeswoman for the area's convention and tourism bureau. ``We
were really lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourism officials planned to start a crash radio advertising
campaign in key cities _ including Atlanta _ to tell visitors they
should not cancel their plans to visit during the Labor Day
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A tour of the town showed the officials weren't exaggerating.
All along Thomas Drive and Front Beach Road, hotels, restaurants,
go-cart tracks, gift shops and carpet golf operations were open and
virtually untouched by Earl's fury.
</P>
<P>
   No trees down, no signs overturned, no windows blown out, not
even much sand in parking lots. Roofing shingles were still on the
roofs, instead of piled against walls and lining the streets.
</P>
<P>
   It was a far cry from Hurricane Opal in 1995, which devastated
hundreds of beachfront buildings, leaving billions in damage.
</P>
<P>
   But Earl wasn't so gentle further east in Gulf, Franklin,
Wakulla and Taylor counties.
</P>
<P>
   While the storm side-swiped Panama City Beach, its winds staying
mostly side-shore, Earl's powerful eastern quadrant lashed the
low-lying counties south of Tallahassee for hours Wednesday night
with on-shore winds.
</P>
<P>
   The 80- to 100 mph gusts pushed up massive walls of water that
tore at beaches all along the region.
</P>
<P>
   The storm produced a surge estimated at 11 feet, Gov. Lawton
Chiles said, higher in many places than Opal's.
</P>
<P>
   About 20,000 people lost power, including all the residents of
St. George Island, another popular Atlanta vacation destination.
Waves overtopped the causeway on the bridge leading to the barrier
island, shutting off access until midday Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   There were no detailed damage reports Thursday, but at least six
homes on St. George were hit by a tornado spun off from Earl's
tempest.
</P>
<P>
   The storm also capsized eight unlucky mariners, including six
fishermen on two boats based in Orange Beach, Ala., the Me-Too and
the Can-Too. The boats flipped in 16-foot seas about three miles
off Panama City during the height of the storm, with conditions so
bad the Coast Guard couldn't scramble rescue teams for 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the six fishermen eventually were found, but two still
were missing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Two other men whose sailboat capsized managed to reach Shell
Island near Panama City, eventually swimming to the mainland near
Tyndall Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of other casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Earl's biggest impact in Panama City Beach was an estimated 23
inches of rain. Streets in several areas flooded, with the waters
swallowing parked cars and drowning out the engines of several
unwary motorists who tried fording the floods.
</P>
<P>
   A few parking lots at small motels were flooded, but the waters
had receded several feet by late Thursday, helped by fire trucks
that pumped the muddy liquid into the nearby Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   At the Holiday Inn Sunspree Resort, a tunnel that carries guests
under Front Beach Road to a parking lot flooded, but crews were at
work and expected to finish well before the weekend crowds arrive.
The popular high-rise hotel suffered little other damage.
</P>
<P>
   At least two Georgia visitors didn't wait for Labor Day to see
the beach _ they drove down Wednesday night into the teeth of the
storm, just to see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome watching the surf,'' said Donna Long, who drove
down from Cochran with her husband, William. ``I'd do it again in a
New York minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
