<HEADER>
A8045 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MANN-OBIT-2NDTAKE-NYT     09-03 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANN-OBIT-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
 UNDATED: deadly epidemic.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eventually, Mann's zeal on the issue brought him into conflict
with the WHO director general, Dr. Hiroshi Nakajima, and in March
1990 Mann resigned in protest over the organization's failure to
move faster.
</P>
<P>
   Mann went on to raise the point that improved health care
methods, instruments and technology would not alone solve world
health issues. Instead, he said, many diseases and other health
problems are rooted in social issues like education and the status
of women and in the continuing violations of human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Mann, with funds and assistance from Albina du Boisrouvray,
whose son died while on a medical mission in Africa, founded and
became first director of the Francois-Xavier Bagnoud Center for
Health and Human Rights at the Harvard University School of Public
Health. There, he founded the journal Health and Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   He also organized the first world conference on health and human
rights, held at Harvard in 1996. ``Jonathan was a critical player
in this new field,'' Tarantola said, ``bringing together two worlds
that had never spoken to each other _ the world of doctors and
scientists and medical officials, with the world of human rights
activists and lawyers. They had two completely different jargons,
and there was at first only cacophony. But now they speak.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his life, Mann loved the role of founder. When
Allegheny University in Philadelphia asked him to become the dean
of a new school of public health, he seized it, beginning the
position in January.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Curran, dean of the Rollins School of Public Health at
Emory University in Atlanta, hired Mann on a Centers For Disease
Control project early in Mann's career. The job brought him to what
was then the African nation of Zaire and a hot spot of AIDS
research. to found a program in an atmosphere of suspicion and
hostility. Although the Project SIDA at first seemed to have little
chance of success it came to be regarded as the most innovative and
important center of AIDS research in Africa, until President Mobutu
Sese Seko dissolved it in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   It was always safe for scientists and institutions to think of
AIDS as a virus, a transmissable infection, Curran said. But Mann
structured it ``as a human rights issue, and a global rights issue.
He really was a spiritual leader as well as a scientific leader.''
</P>
<P>
   In one line often remembered by colleagues, Mann said at the
World AIDS Summit meeting he had organized in London in 1988: ``We
live in a world threatened by unlimited destructive force, yet we
share a vision of creative potential... AIDS shows us once again
that silence, exclusion and isolation _of individuals, groups, or
nations _ creates a danger for us all.''
</P>
<P>
   Mann was born in Boston and grew up in Newton, Mass. His father,
the late James Mann, was a psychiatrist and psychotherapist, and
his mother, who still lives in Newton, Mass, was a librarian.
Jonathan Mann and earned a BA degree in history from Harvard
University, magna cum laude. He earned an MD from Washington
University School of Medicine in St. Louis, then returned to the
Harvard School of Public Health for a master's degree in public
health. From 1975 to 1977, he worked for to the Centers for Disease
Control in Atlanta as an epidemic intelligence service officer.
</P>
<P>
   He moved to New Mexico in 1977 to become state epidemiologist
and chief medical officer of the state Health Services Division,
where he remained until 1984.
</P>
<P>
   After his terms at Project SIDA and the Global Program on AIDS,
he returned to the Harvard School of Public Health, where he first
directed the International AIDS Center and then the Bagnoud Center
for Health and Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   He was also the editor of the influential two-volume work ``AIDS
in the World,'' which contains of scientific, practical and human
rights articles on AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harvey Fineberg, provost of Harvard University and a
colleague of Mann, said that one of Mann's most characteristic
remarks combined both passion and invitation. ``He used to say to
us, `People say there is no use trying to change the world. But if
we don't try, will it change?' ''
</P>
<P>
   His first marriage, to Marie-Paule Bondat, ended in divorce in
1996. Mann is survived by Ms. Bondat of Boston; their three
children, Naomi, Lydia, and Aaron; his mother, Ida, of Newton,
Mass.; two brothers, Gerald, an obstetrician in Northern
California, and Joshua, a rabbi in Israel; and a sister, Carol, a
rancher in Wyoming.
</P>
</TEXT>
