<HEADER>
A8046 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STORM-COX     09-03 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Earl tears through with floods, tornado
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hurricane Earl lashed the lower half of Georgia with as much as
nine inches of rain Thursday, spawned a tornado that injured five
people near Savannah, and made a bad year worse for many Georgia
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   One flood-prone Albany neighborhood with 60 to 70 residents was
ordered evacuated because water covered the streets and was surging
into a few homes.
</P>
<P>
   Schools were closed Thursday in many southwest Georgia counties,
and there were scattered power outages across the southern part of
the state. But anxious vacation hosts along the Florida panhandle,
normally jammed over the Labor Day weekend, said beaches were
clean, skies were beautiful and plenty of room was available.
</P>
<P>
   At last report Earl had been downgraded to a tropical storm,
with winds around 45 mph, and forecasters said it would continue to
weaken as it moved through Georgia and into South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   In Screven County, five people were injured when a tornado hit a
house about 2 1/2 miles northwest of Sylvania at 11:30 a.m., Paul
Bryan, emergency management director for the county, told the
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   He said one child suffered a broken arm, but he didn't know the
extent of other injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The twister also damaged 27 buildings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little area down from me with trailers. They're not
there anymore,'' said Judith Taylor, a 16-year resident of
Sylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homes were lifted up and dropped back down. But they didn't
come back down in the same place,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Eastman, Dodge County Extension agent Duren Bell said at
midafternoon ``the rain has stopped but the wind has really picked
up.'' Rain gauges in the county, he said, registered from
nineinches in the north to above five in the south.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of open cotton that's being defoliated,'' he
said. ``This wind will blow it out of the bolls. Our nonirrigated
crops needed some rain. They didn't need nine inches. This is going
to take a poor year and make it worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Young of Carrollton, owner of Panama City Beach Rentals in
that Florida panhandle city, rushed to the coast Wednesday night,
fearing the worst.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday he said the sky over the panhandle beaches was
``absolutely beautiful, the prettiest I've seen all summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Earl caused minor damage to wooden stairs and dampened carpets
on some bottom-floor units, but there was no serious damage, Young
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, ``we've had a lot of cancellations'' among
Georgia and Alabama residents seeking a last few days on the
beaches over the Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wednesday, when we didn't know what was going to happen, there
wasn't much we could tell those people who called in, and a lot of
them canceled,'' he said. ``A few people have called back today and
rebooked, and we're trying to reach some of the others.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said he expects plenty of vacancies. His firm has 400
units for rent, he said, and ``we're hoping we'll hit 75 to 80
percent occupancy. I'd guess as a whole the beach occupancy rate
will be around 60 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, more than seven inches of rain, driven by 50 mph
winds, lashed Seminole County. Power lines and trees were felled in
Laurens County. Seven inches of rain washed out dirt roads in
Miller County and three vehicles were damaged when wind blew a
concrete wall down in Peach County.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents of the flooded Albany neighborhood refused to
leave, complaining that the city had not improved flood control in
the neighborhood despite past floods, the wire service reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to stay right here until the city does what it's
supposed to do, cleaning out the drainage ditch and fixing the
pumps,'' said Don Brimer, 61, a retired postal worker. ``Every time
it rains, we get flooded.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Merton, Albany's public works director, said the storm
brought more water than the drainage system was designed to handle.
But all pumps were working fine Thursday, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a few hours of this storm passing, the majority of our
flooding problems will go away,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The river levels are down, so southwest Georgia may escape
severe flooding,'' said Georgia Emergency Management Agency
spokesman Buzz Weiss. ``We're preparing for the worst, because
we've had this experience before ... Alberto, our old friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Storm Alberto stalled over southwest Georgia in 1994,
dumping 24 inches of rain in 24 hours and causing widespread
flooding around the Flint River. It was the state's worst natural
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   In March, about 11,000 Albany area residents fled their homes
when the Flint rose over its banks again.
</P>
<P>
   John Feldt, hydrologist in charge of the Southeast River
Forecast Center in Peachtree City, said Earl is not expected to
cause serious flooding in Georgia unless it stalls the way Alberto
did.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
