<HEADER>
A8047 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRO-TEXASTOUR-840(2T     09-03 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRO-TEXASTOUR-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICAN-AMERICAN-ORIENTED TOUR OF TEXAS TOUCHES ON A SPICY MUSICAL
GUMBO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Doo doo doo doo doo doo doo doo.
Doo-doo-dee-doo-dee-ooh-doo-dee-ooh-doo ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Strains of the score from the hit movie ``The Sting'' plink from
a player piano in your mind as you view the Scott Joplin mural
adorning a wall at Third and Main streets in downtown Texarkana.
</P>
<P>
   Joplin, the composer called the Father of Ragtime Music, is
arguably Texarkana's most famous native son. His rival for that
distinction is Dallas billionaire Ross Perot _ and, in fact, the
Perot Theater is not far from the Joplin mural.
</P>
<P>
   The Texarkana Historical Museum at 219 State Line Ave. features
a permanent Scott Joplin exhibit. It includes the square grand
piano on which Joplin is reputed to have learned to play, along
with sheet music, recordings and other Joplin memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, which is open 10 a.m.-4 p.m. Monday through
Saturday, recently held a Scott Joplin portrait contest, and the
entries are still on display there. For more information about the
Joplin exhibit and other material relating to African-Americans of
the region, call (903) 793-4831.
</P>
<P>
   It is fitting that an African-American-oriented tour of Texas
should commence with Texarkana, which dubs itself the ``Gateway to
the Southwest.'' It must be pointed out, however, that such a tour
should occur in conjunction with a trip for some other purpose.
Most Texas cities have not yet devoted as much attention as
Texarkana has to the African-American elements of their heritage.
</P>
<P>
   If, for example, you happen to be in Marshall, it would be
worthwhile to drop by the campus of historic Wiley College. Wiley
is the alma mater of civil rights leader James Farmer, whose father
was a prominent faculty member there. When Wiley opened in 1873, it
was the first black college chartered by the state of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   To hop deep into the heart of African-American Texas, you should
definitely journey to the Beaumont-Port Arthur area along the
Southeast coast. African-Americans have profoundly flavored the
music, art and diet of the region. Beaumont's home county of
Jefferson is 32 percent African-American, the highest such racial
concentration in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The main campus of Lamar University in Beaumont is on Martin
Luther King Parkway in the southeastern part of the city. The Babe
Zaharias Museum, which houses Beaumont's visitor information
center, is also located on that street.
</P>
<P>
   In Beaumont, the most festive event for African-Americans is
Juneteeth (June 19), the day in 1865 when Gen. Gordon Granger
delivered the belated news of the Emancipation Proclamation to
Texas slaves in Galveston. City-sponsored events blend gospel,
rhythm and blues, and zydeco music. Cajun and creole food,
including the rice and pork sausage mixture called ``boudin,'' is
plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   Houston boasts the mother of all Juneteenth celebrations. It's a
two-part event. The first part consists of the Juneteenth USA
Gospel Festival and the Juneteenth Blues Festival at Miller Outdoor
Theater on the weekend preceding Juneteenth. The second part, which
occurs on the nearest weekend to the actual emancipation
announcement date, is a National Emancipation Association-sponsored
Juneteenth Freedom Festival at the same location.
</P>
<P>
   African-Americans will find two Houston museums particularly
interesting _ The Menil Collection, at 1515 Sul Ross in the Museum
District, and the Contemporary Arts Museum, at 5216 Montrose Blvd.
</P>
<P>
   Currently through Oct. 11, the Menil is featuring ``In and Out:
Native, Folk and Self-Taught Artists,'' an exhibit gleaned from its
permanent collection.
</P>
<P>
   The Contemporary displays through Sept. 20 ``Face of the Gods:
Art and Altars of Africa and the African Americas,'' a spectacular
traveling exhibition from the Museum of African Art in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Moving northward, any Afro-Texas tour must pause in the state
capitol to visit the George Washington Carver Museum. It occupies a
1927-vintage, 1,800-square-foot frame building that once served as
the Austin Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Established in 1979, the museum, at 1165 Angelina St., was the
first neighborhood black history museum opened in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   One of the real gems of the Afro-Texas tour is farther north in
Dallas. The Museum of African-American Life and Culture, at 1620
First Ave. in Fair Park, was established in 1974. It offers African
art and sculpture in addition to exhibits pertaining to
African-American history.
</P>
<P>
   The building makes a symbolic architectural statement. It is
designed to resemble an African cross.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty miles west in Fort Worth, the jazz aficionado can usually
find something to savor at the Caravan of Dreams, a combination
nightclub, museum, botanical garden and little theater at 3112
Houston St. near Sundance Square. Huge murals in the nightclub
portray the evolution of jazz from the arrival of its early stages
via slaves to its eventual acceptance as an important musical
genre.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth's Jubilee Theater, at 506 Main St. in Sundance
Square, is another Afro-Texas jewel. The black ensemble offers
polished productions of mainly musical comedy. Many of its programs
are original works.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth, of course, is noted for its cattle culture heritage.
African-American cowboys figured prominently in its history. They
are represented symbolically by a large bronze statue in the
Stockyards tourist area depicting fabled black cowboy Bill Pickett
bulldogging a longhorn steer.
</P>
<P>
   Heading West out of Fort Worth, the seeker of Texas'
African-American historical and cultural treasures should make a
brief stop in Weatherford to visit the City Greenwood Cemetery. In
that historic burial place, you will find the graves of famous
cattleman Oliver Loving and his African-American sidekick, Bose
Ikard. The black cowboy rode with Loving and Charles Goodnight on
many perilous trail drives. The characters Gus and Captain Call in
Larry McMurtry's novel ``Lonesome Dove'' are based upon Loving and
Goodnight. Ikard was the real-life model for fictional Josh Deets.
</P>
<P>
   San Angelo owes its existence to Fort Concho, one of several
military posts in West Texas staffed in large measure by Buffalo
Soldiers, troops of the African-American 9th and 10th Cavalry and
the 24th and 25th Infantry.
</P>
<P>
   The men of those units engaged in heavy fighting against the
Apache, Comanche and other hostile tribes during the pacification
campaigns of the Old West.
</P>
<P>
   San Angelinos have been restoring the fort for nearly 40 years.
Located between Burgess Street and Avenues C and D, Fort Concho has
become one the area's most popular tourist attractions.
</P>
<P>
   A special exhibit in the fort's Visitor Center honors the
Buffalo Solders, who constructed most of its original buildings.
Local Buffalo Soldier re-enactors also put on demonstrations at the
fort.
</P>
<P>
   Among other existing West Texas forts where Buffalo Soldiers
were posted are Fort Davis National Historic Site in the Big Bend
area, Fort Stockton in the city of the same name that grew up
around it, Fort Richardson State Historic Site near Jacksboro and
Fort Clark in Brackettville.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Clark was the primary post of the heroic detachment of
Seminole Negro Indian Scouts. The scouts were African-Americans
whose ancestors originally intermarried with the Seminole Indians
in Florida. They escaped to Texas and Mexico when the Seminoles
were forced to migrate to the Indian territories in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Seminole Negro scouts won the Medal of Honor
fighting for the U.S. Cavalry in campaigns against the Comanche and
Apache. Several of these Medal of Honor winners are buried in the
tribal cemetery in Brackettville.
</P>
<P>
   No Afro-Texas tour could conclude without a stop in San Antonio.
One of the venues that must be visited in the Alamo city is the
Institute of Texan Cultures in HemisFair Park. It includes a
variety of exhibits pertaining to 26 Texas ethnic and cultural
groups, including African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   And in case you drop by Sea World while in San Antonio, it would
be well to take note of a life-size figure on the Famous Texans
Walk _ a statue of (''doo doo dee doo dee doo ... '') Scott Joplin.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 1943EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
