<SLUG> BC-CRASH-FAA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISSAIR DISASTER PLAN KEEPS STRESS TO A MINUMUM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Under a plan filed three months ago with US
transportation authorities, Swissair officials promised to set up a
toll-free hotline for concerned relatives in the event of a major
air disaster, swiftly compile a detailed passenger list and even
erect a monument to the deceased.
</P>
<P>
   Chillingly, the airline was forced to put that plan into action
Thursday following the crash of Flight 111 in Nova Scotia. Disaster
officials said the plan, which was required by a new federal law,
enabled Swissair and its partner airline, Delta, to avoid the
pitfalls experienced by TWA during its awkward handling of the
Flight 800 crash off Long Island in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no comparison,'' said Jerry Hauer, who heads New York
mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani's office of emergency management. ``The
Swissair and Delta folks have done a really wonderful job in
mobilizing their forces. They were clearly prepared to deal with
this. They had plans in place, they knew what they needed to do and
they went out and did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Giuliani led critics who said TWA caused
additional anguish by failing to provide key information to the
families of Flight 800. The airline, for example, was unable to
produce an accurate passenger list until late the following day,
causing scores of panicked and confused relatives to descend on an
ad-hoc command post at the Ramada Plaza hotel outside John F.
Kennedy International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the scene was calm Thursday at the same Ramada,
where Giuliani and Red Cross crisis specialists spent the night
counseling a handful of families. Many relatives decided to stay
away from the airport because they already were getting information
from hundreds of operators provided by Swissair and Delta over a
toll-free number (1-800-801-0088). Swissair issued four press
releases Thursday and set up an emergency website on internet. It
also offered $20,000 to the family of each passenger.
</P>
<P>
   The hotline was outlined as part of a seven-page Airline Family
Assistance Plan that Swissair filed June 11 with the Transportation
Department and the National Transportation Safety Board. The
airline was required to file the plan under the Aviation Disaster
Family Assistance Act of 1996, which Congress passed following the
criticism surrounding TWA 800.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of the victims of TWA 800 helped write the
legislation. It was extended to foreign carriers such as Swissair
last year. The DOT said nearly 98 percent of all carriers operating
in the US have complied with the law, which also helps coordinate
communication between the airlines and various government agencies
following a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Starting October 1, in an effort to speed up communication even
further, the DOT will require airlines to collect not only the full
names of every American passenger but also a contact name and phone
number.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will never be anything like TWA 800 again,'' said a
senior Department of Transportation official.
</P>
<P>
   Because Tuesday's crash occurred outside the United States,
Swissair was not legally required to implement its Family
Assistance Plan. However, its actions indicated that it had
immediately put the plan into action.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, which was released by Transporation Department
officials, Swissair promised to:
</P>
<P>
   -- Establish a toll-free number dedicated to accident-related
calls within one hour after its Operation Control Center has
received information indicating that an aircraft operated by the
airline has been involved in a major incident and that there are
serious injuries and/or fatalties.
</P>
<P>
   -- Upon request of the National Transportation Safety Board,
provide a list of the names of the passengers who boarded the
aircraft to the NTSB Director of Family Support Services designated
for the accident.
</P>
<P>
   -- Activate a Family Assistance Center to notify the next of kin
of passengers involved in an accident.
</P>
<P>
   -- Provide next of kin with reasonable care, accommodation and
transporation.
</P>
<P>
   -- If the families express a desire for a monument at the
accident site...consult with the family of each passenger about its
construction, including any inscription.
</P>
<P>
   By midnight Thursday, nearly 100 Delta agents were stationed
inside Terminal 3 at JFK. The agents directed about five families
who showed up during the night to the Ramada, where they received
immediate counseling. The toll-free number for relatives was
activated shortly after. Meanwhile, NTSB and Swissair officials
communicated constantly over a separate 24-hour emergency telephone
line that had already been put in place.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, Swissair provided an accurate passenger list to
the State Department and local officials by 3 a.m. The State
Department immediately was able to contact US consulates in
Switzerland and Canada. The airline immediately dispatched
President and CEO Jeffrey Katz to Halifax with an emergency
response team that arrived early Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``On behalf of the men and women of Swissair, I wish to extend
our deepest sympathies to the families and friends of those on
board,'' Walter Vollenweider, the company's vice president, said at
JFK. ``Our thoughts and prayers are with you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know (the airlines) are trying to make this process as least
painful as possible,'' said Shelly Auster, a spokesman for the
American Red Cross. ``You don't want to leave anyone in the dark.
The family members are the most important people here, and you want
to do everything you can to make a tragic situation less
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Hauer, the mayor's director of emergency services, Giuliani
``talked with many of the families. We are not hearing the same
issues that we did two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to get out in front of these things and respond
to the needs of the families,'' he said. ``Being in a state of
suspended animation, not knowing if a loved one is on a flight, it
adds to the pain and the longer that goes on the more painful it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Relatives who did come to the airport Thursday were escorted in
and out of the Ramada by police to avoid the swell of media that
had gather around the hotel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
