<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS HEAD LOWER AS NERVOUSNESS CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices headed broadly lower Thursday as
investors continued to show nervousness about the effects of a
possible global economic slowdown on the profits of American
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of financial and transportation companies, which would be
among the companies hurt worst by a decline in global business
activity, fell most sharply in a volatile day of trading. Also
posting losses were companies like Coca-Cola, Procter &AMP; Gamble and
Gillette, which get large percentages of their income from
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 100.15 points, or 1.3
percent, to 7,682.22. It was the sixth loss in seven days in the
Dow industrials, and other market indexes followed the Dow lower.
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 8.21 points, or slightly less
than 1 percent, to 982.26, while the Nasdaq composite index
declined 20.99, or 1.3 percent, to 1571.86.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in American stocks followed further losses in
European markets, where the fallout from the financial instability
in Russia, including further declines in the value of the ruble,
dragged down share prices. Germany's most-watched stock market
index fell more than 3 percent, while the Financial Times Stock
Exchange index in London fell 2.2 percent, closing below the level
where it started the year.
</P>
<P>
   The weakness in the economies of Asia and, more recently,
Russia, have led many American analysts to cut their estimates of
corporate earnings here. Chuck Hill, director of research for First
Call, which tracks earnings estimates, said Thursday that analysts'
estimates of growth in 1998 operating earnings for the companies in
the S&AMP;P 500 index had declined to 5.3 percent in recent days, from
a previous level of 5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two months, estimates of third-quarter profit growth
has plunged to 2.1 percent from 10 percent. In addition, Hill said,
many analysts are still predicting that fourth-quarter profits will
rise more than 10 percent. He expects those forecasts to be revised
downward, causing overall profit estimates to fall as well.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the last half hour of trading again proved to be
the most volatile part of the day. But where stock prices had been
falling sharply in the final minutes of trading in several previous
sessions, the Dow moved higher Thursday as the blue chips cut their
losses in half in the last 30 minutes of trading.
</P>
<P>
   While some of those sharp swings come from the implementation of
sophisticated trading strategies, traders attributed the late-day
gain Thursday to positive comments about the strength of the
American economy by Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin. Rubin is
scheduled to meet Friday with the Federal Reserve chairman, Alan
Greenspan, and the Japanese finance minister, Kiichi Miyazawa, in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, traders will be watching the August employment
data, which they hope will give some hint whether the domestic
economy has begun to feel any effects from the year-old Asian
malaise.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see the worries in the price of cyclical stocks, the
transportation stocks and shares of plain old-fashioned industrial
companies,'' said Jonathan Olesky, head of block trading at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. ``People are concerned about a possible
downturn in the U.S. that would have been Asian-induced. I think
people are going to be very concerned if they see a jump in
unemployment.'' Analysts generally expect the unemployment rate to
remain steady at 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As such, investors are likely to see continued volatility in the
stock market, ``as long as everybody is focused on daily economic
numbers,'' said Robert Freedman, chief investment officer for John
Hancock Funds.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Shares of bank and financial-service companies continued to take
a pounding Thursday as investors reacted to disclosures of losses
by many of the big banks. Citicorp fell 9 15/16 to 98 13/16, Chase
Manhattan slumped $5.625 to $49.25, American Express lost $6.75 to
$77 and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter fell $5.375 to $53.625.
</P>
<P>
   Also losing ground Thursday were the economically sensitive
transportation stocks, which include airline and trucking
companies. Ryder Systems fell 3 15/16 to $20. Shares of airline
companies fell across the board, with Delta Air Lines slipping
$3.125 to $58.75.
</P>
<P>
   One difference between this year's stock market turmoil and past
periods of volatility, like those in 1987 or 1990, stock traders
say, is that they now have a far harder time gauging the mood of
the market from day to day and minute to minute.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Molnar, a managing director in the retail sales and
trading operations of Salomon Smith Barney, said that as his firm's
trading operations have become more computerized, the volume of
background noise in the trading room has become far less reliable
as an indicator of market swings.
</P>
<P>
   Where a decade ago traders spent much of their day shouting
orders across the floor, today they spend more time punching
buttons on computer terminals. ``If you want to measure the
psychology of the market, you have to watch an individual stock,''
Molnar said.
</P>
<P>
   Molnar, who in 1987 worked at Lehman Brothers, says that in
times like this, sentiment can be as crucial as some fundamental
measures of value. Referring to the famed proponents of the
objective method of investing based on a company's underlying
value, he said: ``If the market is going to snap back 100 points,
that's not Graham and Dodd. That's sentiment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
