   ----------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Yeltsin's voluntary resignation would open the way to a
compromise allowing the formation of a government of national
salvation, capable of coping with the emergency.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   So writes Mikhail Gorbachev, former leader of the Soviet Union
and Nobel Peace Prize winner, about Russia's current economic and
governmental crisis in his latest column from The new York Times
Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   He adds: ``Many Westerners, both those who have gained and those
who have lost, are ready to pack their bags and leave Russia. They
think that Russia cannot be trusted. Well, they had better look in
the mirror and think again. After all, it was they who thought
Russia could be treated like a streetwalker. True, they were
encouraged to do so by the Russian leaders themselves, who took the
country through `shock therapy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at this powerful commentary, which can be purchased
as a one-shot (SEE PURCHASE INFORMATION BELOW.)
</P>
<P>
   HEADLINE: ``AS THE CRISIS WORSENS, RUSSIA NEEDS A GOVERNMENT OF
NATIONAL SALVATION''
</P>
