<SLUG> BC-DELTA-SWISS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Partnership lets Delta fill seats on other planes
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Swissair Flight 111 crashed into the sea off Nova Scotia on
Wednesday night, so did Delta Air Lines Flight 111.
</P>
<P>
   Only one plane went down and it belonged to Swissair. But both
airlines sold seats on the flight and listed it as their own in
computer reservations systems.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement is called code-sharing, and it's a common
feature of international air travel in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows two airlines to serve more places together than they
ever could separately,'' said aviation consultant Michael Boyd.
</P>
<P>
   Delta booked 53 of the 215 passengers on the doomed Swissair
jet. A New York-based Delta flight attendant, Patricia Eberhart,
was among the 14 crew members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I speak for all Delta employees in expressing the
deepest sorrow we all feel concerning this tragedy,'' Delta Chief
Executive Leo Mullin said in an employee memo Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swissair, as the operator of the flight, has primary charge of
the company response to the crash,'' Mullin said. However, he added
Delta sent teams to Nova Scotia and New York to help the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's partnership with Swissair dates to 1988 and is one of
the most extensive in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The two airlines sell seats on several of each others' flights
every day. The New York-Geneva leg by Flight 111 was among the most
popular for Delta passengers booked on Swissair, Delta spokesman
Bill Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   Code-share alliances must be approved by the governments of both
nations involved. Other big U.S. carriers also have foreign
code-share partners. Under federal guidelines, U.S. airlines are
supposed to tell passengers at the time of booking they will be
flying on another carrier's plane.
</P>
<P>
   Code-share deals often involve operational cooperation. Berry
said Delta provided baggage handling for the Swissair jet at New
York's Kennedy Airport but did not perform any maintenance because
Swissair has its own mechanics there.
</P>
<P>
   Delta and Swissair assign their own flight attendants to some of
the most popular code-share flights, which accounted for Eberhart's
presence on Flight 111.
</P>
<P>
   Berry said the operating carrier bears primary liability in the
crash of a code-share flight, although Boyd said that may not
prevent lawsuits against Delta.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd also said the crash of a more obscure code-share partner of
a U.S. airline might raise public and political concern about the
deals. He added he doubts that will happen in this case because
Swissair is respected and well-known.
</P>
<P>
   Swissair is only one of a dozen foreign carriers with which
Delta has code-share deals. Others are Sabena, Austrian Airlines,
TAP Air Portugal, Malev Hungarian Airlines, Aer Lingus, Aeromexico,
Air Jamaica, Finnair and Transbrasil.
</P>
<P>
   These deals enable Delta to offer service to places it doesn't
actually fly, from medium-size cities in Brazil on Transbrasil to
parts of Africa on Sabena.
</P>
<P>
   Berry said Delta holds its partners ``to the same safety
standards we have to meet'' and periodically reviews their records.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
