<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8073 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-SCHROEDER-2ND     09-03 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-SCHROEDER-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BONN: to go.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the biggest questions about Schroeder's destination is
who would help him get there. It appears highly unlikely that the
Social Democrats will gain a clear majority, even if they win, so
he would need a coalition partner. There are two possibilities _ an
alliance with the Greens or teaming up with the Christian Democrats
in the kind of grand coalition Germany had under Kurt Georg
Kiesinger from 1966 to 1969.
</P>
<P>
   When his visitor suggested that a coalition with the often
erratic Greens would make more sense in the party context, because
they are more ideologically compatible, but a grand coalition would
make more sense in a governmental context because of greater
stability Schroeder agreed. Then he added, with a malicious little
grin: ``There's an old saying in this country: If you want to be
successful, think first of your country, then of your party.''
</P>
<P>
   Whose old saying? he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision will not be his alone. Parties matter more in
German politics than in the United States, and Schroeder does not
yet control his party. Oskar Lafontaine, the party leader, is
giving stout backing to Schroeder for now, though he looked
noticeably jumpy recently as Schroeder announced the party program.
Many people wonder what he will do once the ballots have been
counted, and the Christian Democrats are trying to play on that,
suggesting that it would be the party bosses rather than Schroeder
who would call the ideological tune in choosing a partner and
framing government policy.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder tries to equate himself to Clinton and Blair. But the
parallel is inexact. Each of them took office having already won
the main ideological arguments within his own party, and Schroeder,
if he wins, would become chancellor with important questions still
unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Lafontaine, a harsh critic of ``billionaire
capitalists,'' wants to cut the top income tax rate from 53 percent
to 49, while Schroeder wants to bring it down to 45. Schroeder
sometimes emphasizes a ``modern'' Germany that shines in new
technology, as when he named Jost Stillman, a businessman, as an
economic adviser; other times he attacks the pension reform and
labor flexibility that modernizers consider mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it clear, despite tens of thousands of words and endless
columns of analysis in the newspapers, exactly what Schroeder would
do to attack unemployment, one of Germany's most serious and
intractable problems.
</P>
<P>
   The party platform says a Schroeder government would expect
labor unions to permit ``the more flexible organization of work.''
Business, it continues, needs to invest more, innovate more and
provide more apprenticeships. The government itself, it says, needs
to shrink the bureaucracy and increase public spending on research.
</P>
<P>
   It promises a ``crash program'' to fight joblessness among the
young by bringing 100,000 unemployed young people into training
programs.
</P>
<P>
   But the nuts and bolts of the program are still missing.
Persuading labor and business to work together, devising practical
programs and finding the money to pay for them would be the job of
Walter Riester, the highly regarded 54-year-old deputy chairman of
the powerful metalworkers' union, who has been designated as the
labor-minister-to-be in a Schroeder government.
</P>
<P>
   One thing seems plain: with Schroeder as chancellor, Germany
will remain a firm ally of the United States. Diplomats from both
countries seem sure of this, as do officials Schroeder met during
his recent trip to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he stretches a point to dramatize his conversion from
anti-American views. He tells people that ``my daughter was born in
New York,'' when in fact she is his stepdaughter by his fourth
marriage, and until 1997, he had not visited the United States in
more than 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no doubt that Schroeder admires Clinton's political
style, especially his success in repositioning himself and his
party. Schroeder has embraced issues like crime that the Christian
Democrats long dominated. He has even hired Hank Sheinkopf, a
Clinton adviser in 1996, to help with instant rebuttal and research
on the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In the conversation last month, Schroeder said that despite an
all-party agreement that Germany will not commit military forces
abroad except on a U.N. mandate, he could not conceive of Germany
holding back from intervening in the embattled Serbian province of
Kosovo if the United Nations was silent and other European nations
wanted to act. That would please the United States, which has long
felt that the Europeans have been too slow to police their own
turf.
</P>
<P>
   In a long career, Schroeder, who is known as Gerd, has managed
to find a way forward when others might well have felt stymied.
</P>
<P>
   He had no more promising a start in life than Bill Clinton. His
father, a conscript, was killed during the Wehrmacht's retreat from
Russia when Schroeder was only three days old, and his mother
raised him alone while working as a cleaning woman. He dropped out
of school at 14, went to night school and ended up studying law at
Goettingen University during the turbulence of 1968.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Schroeder handles hecklers, commonplace in German
politics, with great aplomb. Asked how he learned, he replied, ``By
heckling.''
</P>
<P>
   After a stint as an member of parliament in Bonn, he won his
party's nomination for prime minister in the state of Lower Saxony
in 1984. He lost that time, but won four years later. Last March,
he gained a third term in a landslide, a victory that clinched his
nomination for chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the good suits and expensive cigars, Schroeder lives
unpretentiously in a smallish apartment in Hanover, the state
capital. He has no vast entourage, disdaining all but the most
basic security protection.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
