<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIADEAD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia friends, U.N. staff among dead
 &HT;    By Doug Payne
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two Georgia women killed in the crash of Swissair Flight 111
held strong religious beliefs that friends and neighbors say would
have helped them in the minutes before the airliner fell into the
sea off Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   Cherie Hastie, 59, and Caroline Smith were next-door neighbors
in east Cobb County until Smith moved to Augusta several years ago,
but distance couldn't separate the two women and they remained best
friends, neighbors said.
</P>
<P>
   The two were traveling to Switzerland to do some sightseeing and
visit Hastie's daughter Elizabeth, 21, who is taking part in a
Christian study program there, said neighbor Nancy Fowler. The
Hasties have another daughter, Cameron, 18, who is enrolled in
college in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Hastie's husband confirmed that the two women were aboard the
flight. However, airline officials have not identified any of the
crash victims, and it is unknown whether other Georgians were been
aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was just a very sweet lady. She's my friend and the person
I share things with,'' William ``Sandy'' Hastie told The Associated
Press on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Hastie is a former Navy captain, and the family lived in
various places around the globe during his career, said Fowler and
Jean Kerr, another neighbor. But the Wednesday flight was Smith's
first trip abroad, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The two women were members of a Bible study group at Johnson
Ferry Baptist Church, where Smith worshiped until she moved to
Augusta. Hastie attended Sunday services at the Church of the
Apostles on Northside Parkway and Smith joined the First
Presbyterian Church in Augusta, the neighbors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Cherie and Caroline lifted all the people on board that
airplane straight to the Lord,'' Kerr said.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson Ferry Baptist Church has been touched by tragedy
twice before in recent years. It was the church attended by Lamar
Allen and his son, Ashton, who died in the July 1976 crash of TWA
Flight 800, and it was where Gloria Chung, who was killed in the
August 1997 crash of a Korean Air passenger jet on Guam, taught
preschool.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been hard being impacted by those three crashes,'' said
church administrator Angela Leveridge. ``It's just tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors were also having trouble dealing with the tragedy. ``I
just said goodbye to her (Hastie) yesterday,'' said Fowler. ``We
already had plans for when she came back.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastie and Smith were both wonderful homemakers and loving
Christian women, said Kerr. They were so alike in disposition and
interests that ``it was uncanny to me that they should wind up as
next-door neighbors,'' Fowler added.
</P>
<P>
   Hastie was effervescent, gracious and ``loved a good joke _ as
long as it was clean _ she couldn't remember them, though,'' said
friend Sarah Belle Tollison. A Charleston native who was a
schoolteacher until she married, she once wore pearls and a silk
blouse while mowing the lawn, Kerr remembers.
</P>
<P>
   Smith ``was a little more reserved,'' and was ``totally devoted
to her daughter,'' Renee Campbell of Peoria, Ill., said Fowler.
Both women were members of a neighborhood sewing club, at which
more eating than stitching was accomplished, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Geneva, Swissair officials and counselors expect to spend at
least another day breaking the news to relatives that their loved
ones died on Flight 111. But U.N. and other sources disclosed that
the 229 victims included some prominent U.N. officials, who
frequently used the flight between the organization's New York
headquarters and its main European office:
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jonathan Mann, a top pioneer in the fight against AIDS and
current dean of Allegheny University of the Health Sciences School
of Public Health in Philadelphia. Mann, an American, was the first
director of the World Health Organization's global program on AIDS
and was en route to a meeting of AIDS experts.
</P>
<P>
   Mary-Lou Clements-Mann, Mann's American wife. A professor in the
Department of International Health at John Hopkins University in
Baltimore. She specialized in research on vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce Gerety, director of African Great Lakes operations for
the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees. An American, Gerety was a
veteran of refugee operations in Sudan, the Philippines,
Afghanistan, Pakistan, Somalia and the Great Lakes area around
Rwanda, Congo and Burundi.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Calvert-Mazy, UNHCR senior social welfare officer. A
Frenchwoman with seven years experience at the refugee agency.
</P>
<P>
   Joachim Bilger, controller of the World Intellectual Property
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig Beaumler, a WIPO official.
</P>
<P>
   Yves de Roussan, UNICEF regional adviser for Central and Eastern
Europe and the Commonwealth of Independent States.
</P>
<P>
   Ingrid Acevedo, the director of public relations for the U.S.
Committee for UNICEF.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
