<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MD-11 had track record as safe, reliable jet
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until now, questions surrounding the MD-11 airliner have had
more to do with sales than safety.
</P>
<P>
   The three-engine wide body _ most identifiable by the upswept
wingtips that reduce drag _ was designed by McDonnell Douglas Corp.
in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But it was quickly eclipsed by competing models from Boeing Co.
and Airbus Industrie, whose planes now dominate wide-body fleets.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, which bought McDonnell Douglas last year, is shutting
down the MD-11 production line when current orders are filled in
2000. Worldwide there are 177 MD-11s in use, a significant number
of them as freighters rather than airliners.
</P>
<P>
   The Swissair crash is the second MD-11 ``hull-loss'' _ industry
parlance for an accident in which the plane is destroyed. The first
was in 1997 when a Federal Express MD-11 crashed and burned during
a landing at Newark, N.J. The crew survived.
</P>
<P>
   Other incidents include an inadvertent in-flight deployment of
wing controls called slats on a China Eastern Airlines MD-11 in
1993. Two people were killed and 60 injured when the jet pitched
severely.
</P>
<P>
   Two U.S. passenger carriers fly the plane: Atlanta-based Delta
Air Lines, which has 16, and American Airlines, which has 11.
</P>
<P>
   Delta had once planned to buy as many as 44, American as many as
50. Both pared back the orders amid a financial slump in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Delta and American encountered shakedown problems with the
model, although spokesmen said they involved economics rather than
safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was first introduced, it was so highly computerized we
had some software problems,'' Delta spokesman Bill Berry said.
``But once they got those fixed, it was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The MD-11 also failed to meet initial range expectations and
could not carry a full passenger load on some routes.
</P>
<P>
   American sold eight MD-11s to FedEx and is scheduled to sell the
rest by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Berry said Delta plans to keep its MD-11s. It uses them
primarily on international flights, including the longest nonstop
in its system, the 6,850-mile Atlanta-Tokyo run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's proven to be a good, reliable airplane,'' Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane is a modernized version of the three-engine DC-10,
whose reputation was marred by three crashes: one in Paris in 1974,
another in Chicago in 1979 and a third in Sioux City, Iowa, in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   The MD-11 has a different wing design, a longer fuselage and
upgraded cockpit systems. It also requires two pilots, while the
DC-10 employs three.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, in a statement Thursday, said MD-11s ``have proven
themselves in terms of safety, reliability and performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
