<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8076 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-SCHROEDER-3RD     09-03 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-SCHROEDER-3RD-TAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BONN: security protection.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lower Saxony, covering most of the northwestern corner of the
country, is perhaps best known outside Germany for the fact that
Hanover's ruling family acceded to the British throne in the person
of George I in 1714. The state includes Hamlen, where the Pied
Piper played, and Wolfsburg, headquarters of Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   A seat on the Volkswagen board goes with the prime minister's
job because the state government is the company's largest
shareholder. And that, by all accounts, has had a major impact on
Schroeder's life. In a number of ways, he modeled himself on the
company's wily chairman, Ferdinand Piech.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, Hanover has held annual trade fairs, and
Schroeder became a regular at them, courting businessmen from all
over Germany, inviting them to dinner at a favorite Italian
restaurant or to a game of tennis.
</P>
<P>
   But he always kept his fences mended with younger, more
proletarian groups as well. Dr. Ludolf von Wertenberg, the head of
the Federation of German Industries, who served as a Christian
Democratic member of parliament when Schroeder was also in Bonn,
recalled that Schroeder always asked beforehand precisely who would
be in the audience when he was invited to make a speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students? He'd show up in a turtleneck,'' von Wertenberg said
in an interview in his Cologne office. ``Entrepreneurs? The whitest
shirt you ever saw. He's amazingly good on his feet, never uses
texts or notes if he can avoid it, and if he sensed that what he
was saying wasn't going over well, he'd change gears within
seconds. Nice guy, provacateur, it didn't matter, as long as he
wasn't ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   He bulled his way to the nomination for prime minister, taking
his case over the heads of the party leaders to the rank-and-file.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schroeder's will for power is certainly impressive,'' the
former party chairman, Hans-Jochen Vogel, wrote in his memoirs.
``But the question increasingly is, What does he want to do with
that power?''
</P>
<P>
   But the leaders gave him his shot at the chancellorship anyway,
and he opened his campaign two weeks ago with three rallies in a
single day, in Berlin, Munich and Bonn. Relaxed, at times almost
professorial in his interviews and news conferences, he let it rip
on the stump. His voice hoarse from shouting, his face almost as
red as his power necktie, Schroeder greeted the crowds with both
arms aloft in a V-for-Victory sign like Richard Nixon's.
</P>
<P>
   At Rheinaue Park in Bonn, along the riverfront, there were
bratwurst stands and beer vendors, hot-air balloons and rock
musicians. Some in the audience wore football jerseys marked
``Schroeder 10'' _ a reference to the candidate's habit of giving
people a flyer listing nine reasons to vote for the Social
Democrats and telling them, ``The 10th is Helmut Kohl.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also a lot of talk, from Schroeder and other party
figures about building an economy that was both humane and
efficient, some complaints about the lot of the lowest-paid people
in German society and the inevitable vague allusion to a new
alliance linking labor, management and government.
</P>
<P>
   But there was not a single mention of socialism.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, Schroeder got into some tried-and-true Social
Democratic grooves, lambasting the government, for example, for
allowing disabled workers to collect only 80 per cent of their
wages when sick. This, he said, ``is not social justice; they can't
go to the store and pay 80 per cent of the price of a loaf of bread
or get their landlord to give them a 20 percent discount.''
</P>
<P>
   That went over well enough with the crowd of 8,000 to 10,000,
even though they had been soaked by intermittent rains. But what
they had on their minds most of all, it seemed, was what Schroeder
is concentrating on: winning.
</P>
<P>
   Their loudest cheers came when he told them: ``We want to win _
we will win _ because we want to do _ we will do _ something for
the German people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
