<HEADER>
A8077 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTH-SENATE04-COX     09-03 1354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-SENATE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Kentucky's Baesler, campaign reform a big deal
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Rep. Scotty Baesler (D-Ky.), a big backer of
campaign finance reform, raised a ruckus on Capitol Hill when the
House passed legislation last month banning unlimited donations to
the national parties and clamping down on issue advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Down home in Kentucky, however, political realities have
tempered Baesler's enthusiasm considerably as he campaigns in one
of the Senate's hottest races, hoping to replace retiring Sen.
Wendell Ford (D-Ky.).
</P>
<P>
   Senior Democrats in the Bluegrass State say the campaign finance
issue will have little impact on how voters choose between Baesler
and Rep. Jim Bunning (R-Ky.), a six-term Republican who voted
against the House campaign finance bill. Baesler himself says he
doesn't think campaign finance will be ``the issue here, but it
will be an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   To top it off, Baesler is now getting punished by the very
political spending the House reform bill sought to cut off. The
state Republican party is spending an estimated $250,000 a week for
two and a half weeks in unregulated donations to run ``issue
advertisements'' promoting Bunning's record on Social Security,
perhaps the single most important issue in the race.
</P>
<P>
   The source of the state party funds is the National Republican
Senatorial Committee (NRSC), chaired by Kentucky's junior Sen.
Mitch McConnell and the Senate's most articulate and combative
opponent of campaign finance legislation.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell, elected to a third term in 1996, says he is living
proof that no American politician has ever lost by being opposed to
campaign finance reform. This year's Kentucky contest appears to be
proving the corollary true as well: no candidate can win on the
campaign finance issue, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably not a burning issue with a lot of people,'' says
Gov. Paul Patton, the state's top Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   That explains why Baesler, the former mayor of Lexington, spends
most of his time talking to voters about safeguarding social
security, protecting patients against heath maintenance
organizations and enacting pay equity for women.
</P>
<P>
   He says he plans to highlight his support for campaign finance
reform in upcoming commercials but mainly to show voters he can get
things done.
</P>
<P>
   One of only four open Senate contests, this year's Kentucky
battle is shaping up to be one of the closest in the country. In
neighboring Indiana, former governor Evan Bayh, a Democrat, is the
clear favorite to replace Sen. Dan Coats (R-Ind.), and Blanche
Lambert-Lincoln, a former congresswoman, is also favored to succeed
retiring Sen. Dale Bumpers (D-Ark.) in the Razorback State.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. George Voinovich, meanwhile, appears to have a
solid lead to replace retiring Ohio Democrat Sen. John Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky Democrats, who control all the statewide offices, are
rallying behind Baesler to keep Ford's seat in Democratic hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' urgency is real. In the 1990s five of the state's
six congressional seats have switched Republican even though
registered Democrats outnumber Republicans two to one.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell is marshaling the influence of the national party and
the NRSC to help Bunning. The Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee (DSCC), the Democratic counterpart to the NRSC, puts
Kentucky at the top of its list of must-win states.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates themselves, both former athletes, are also fierce
competitors. Baesler was captain of the University of Kentucky
basketball team, which inspires religious devotion among state
residents. Bunning pitched in the major leagues for the Detroit
Tigers and the Philadelphia Phillies and in 1996 was inducted into
the Baseball Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   As veteran House members, both are also no strangers to the
partisan fighting that dominates the lower chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Bunning is campaigning on the achievements of Congressional
Republicans, claiming credit for balancing the federal budget,
cutting taxes and reforming welfare. He hammers Baesler for voting
against the 1997 balanced-budget bill and voting for the NAFTA
trade agreement with Canada and Mexico _ a vote that Baesler has
since said was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say sorry after it happened,'' Bunning told
Republicans in Campbellsville, Ky., last week. ``That's an excuse.
You'd better been smart enough to know what would happen before you
vote on the darn thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, a Fruit of the Loom underwear plant closed in
Campbellsville, laying off the last of about 4,000 employees,
because the company found cheaper labor outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Baesler, meanwhile, paints Bunning as too conservative for
average Kentuckians, calling attention to Bunning's opposition to
the Family and Medical Leave Act and HMO reform. Both issues are
likely to count with women swing voters, among whom polls show
Baesler has an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be really important from my perspective to
prevent Jim from moving to the middle,'' Baesler says. ``He's never
been in the middle. I'm going to make sure people understand Jim is
to the right of the center.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the public rhetoric, however, the most pressing issue for
both candidates is money.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is perhaps most dire for Baesler, who spent about
$535,000 to come out on top of a three-way Democratic primary May
26. Since the primary, the candidate has been on a feverish
fund-raising campaign, drawing on Patton and Ford to help.
</P>
<P>
   Baesler, a tobacco farmer, snubbed President Clinton two years
ago when the president traveled to Lexington because of Clinton's
attacks on tobacco. But despite the president's unsavory sex
scandal, Baesler welcomed Clinton three weeks ago for a Louisville
fund-raiser that generated about $400,000 for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bunning faced only token opposition in his primary and emerged
with $1.6 million in the bank. Still, Bunning has set an aggressive
fund-raising goal for the campaign, intending to raise another
$700,000 by Nov. 3, or about $10,000 a day between now and the
election.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Bush was in Kentucky to raise money for Bunning
on Tuesday. Bunning has enlisted National Rifle Association
chairman Charleton Heston, Sen. Fred Thompson (R-Tenn.) and former
Bob Dole running mate Jack Kemp for additional fund-raisers before
the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned that the big amount of national money will
distort the outcome,'' says Patton, expressing the No.1 fear among
Kentucky Democrats. ``It could be huge amounts.''
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates also are expecting a deluge of outside spending
for and against them. The National Right to Life Committee already
has attacked Baesler for supporting campaign finance legislation,
which would subject issue ads to the same regulations as political
action committees if they used the name or likeness of a candidate
60 days prior to an election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully expect the AFL-CIO and the (National Education
Association) to be in on behalf of my opponent,'' Bunning says.
``And I fully expect that I will have to answer those out of my own
campaign pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Bunning has been the biggest beneficiary of outside
spending.
</P>
<P>
   The state party ads running now, courtesy of the NRSC, highlight
Bunning's stewardship of the House sub-committee overseeing Social
Security. At a minimum, the ads are helping introduce Bunning to
voters outside his northern Kentucky congressional district, where
he isn't as well known.
</P>
<P>
   The ads don't explicitly tell voters to vote for Bunning in the
upcoming election and therefore escape the $400,000 limitation
imposed on national parties contributing to Senate candidates here.
</P>
<P>
   Baesler criticizes the ads for papering over what he terms
Bunning's ``horrendous'' record on senior issues. But he hasn't
challenged the NRSC's right to air the ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see what they say when we start doing ours,'' he says
gamely. ``I think I will get some help independent
expenditure-wise. ... I know so.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
