</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-TALKS-385&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA MAY BE PLANNING ANOTHER MISSILE TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ North Korea may be preparing to test another
missile, U.S. and Japanese officials said Thursday, even as North
Korean diplomats met in New York to discuss their missile and
nuclear programs with U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has detected a flurry of activity at the same
military base along North Korea's northeastern coast used to launch
a two-stage ballistic missile Monday, a U.S. government official
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the official added, it appeared that North Korea was
making preparations to test one or more of its older missiles, not
the advanced missile tested for the first time Monday by firing it
in an arc over Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The preparations suggest that North Korea's reclusive
government, led by Kim Jong Il, was brushing aside international
protests over Monday's test, which has inflamed tensions in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Japan and South Korea, responding to North Korea's preparations
at the site about 20 miles north of Kimchaek, placed their
militaries on higher states of alert Thursday. Their foreign
ministers, Masahiko Komura and Hong Soon-young, met in Tokyo to
discuss how to respond to North Korea's tests.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has already withdrawn an offer to begin talks on
establishing diplomatic relations with North Korea and suspended a
$1 billion payment to the Korean Energy Development Organization,
the international agency building nuclear reactors in the North in
exchange for its pledge in 1994 to halt construction of nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, North Korea's deputy minister for foreign affairs,
Kim Gye Gwan, met with a U.S. delegation led by Charles Kartman,
the State Department's special envoy for Korea.
</P>
<P>
   While the Clinton administration has officially voiced concern
over North Korea's test, some officials have sought to play down
the significance of it, as well as the new activity detected at the
launch site this week. Some agencies within the U.S. government
also appeared divided over the significance of the preparations now
under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there is activity around the launch site, it is not at
all certain there is going to be any kind of test,'' one official
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, a senior Japanese official said his government was
specifically warned by the United States that a second missile
launch was likely in the next few days.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even as the launch site buzzed with activity, the European Union
on Thursday called on North Korea to refrain from further tests. A
statement issued by Austria, in its capacity as the union's current
president, said the tests inflamed tensions. The statement also
deplored the fact North Korea would devote resources to missile
development while its people faced severe hunger.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the Pentagon announced that it would send six
powerful bombers _ three B-52s and three B-2s _ to Guam on a
previously unscheduled training exercise, but officials were
adamant that the decision to dispatch them to the Pacific Ocean
over this coming weekend had nothing to do with North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's test of a two-stage, medium-range missile, called the
Taepodong-1, represented a significant advance in North Korea's
missile program, according to arms experts. The missile can carry
conventional or nuclear weapons and has a range of 900 to 1,200
miles, putting all of Japan within striking distance.
</P>
<P>
   The first stage of the missile soared into the sky and then
dropped into the Sea of Japan. The second stage continued over
Japan's main island before plunging into the Pacific, 360 miles
northeast of the American military base in Misawa.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, North Korea had only tested a single-stage missile,
called the Nodong, which has a shorter range and is considered
unreliable. North Korea tested the Nodong only once, in 1993. It
also has two variants of the Scud missile, originally developed by
the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea could be planning to follow up Monday's test with
new tests of these missiles, the U.S. government official said.
After testing the Nodong in 1993, North Korea fired three Scuds
into the Sea of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In another indication that North Korea might be preparing more
tests, the officials said Thursday, North Korea had issued a
maritime alert to ships passing through the Sea of Japan,
indicating that there could be military activity in the area until
Sept. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has 37,000 troops in South Korea and 44,000 in
Japan. The Taepodong would bring all of them within striking
distance of North Korea.
</P>
</TEXT>
