u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-MOOD-360(2TAKE     09-03 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MOOD-360(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN CONSUMERS BEGIN TO FEEL IMPACT OF FINANCIAL CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The wasting disease ravaging Russia's ruble and banks
has begun to infect everyday commerce in shops and groceries, with
unsettling implications _ not just for ordinary citizens, but for
the Russian government, which rises and falls on their trust.
</P>
<P>
   From personal visits, interviews and anecdotal reports on the
Internet and in newspapers, it is apparent that many food markets
and hard-goods stores are running out of popular items, from rice
to televisions. Moreover, retailers are finding it increasingly
hard to replenish their inventories.
</P>
<P>
   The potential for far worse shortages exists. Government and
private analysts said Thursday that grain harvests are running 30
percent behind last year, that meat and cooking oil supplies are
dwindling, and that potato crops _ the bedrock of the Russian diet
_ have been devastated by hard rains.
</P>
<P>
   That does not add up to a winter of starvation, the Russian
Institute of Agrarian and Market Studies told the Interfax news
service. But it does signal that food shortages may become a
national problem at a time when dissatisfaction with the government
already is at fever pitch.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the shortages are less a problem than an
annoyance. Moscow still bustles; an enormous fleet of Mercedes
still clogs streets and new strings of flashing lights celebrate
the city's 851st anniversary. To an uninterested visitor, many
store shelves seem full.
</P>
<P>
   But the edgy feeling of uncertainty that permeates the city is
easy to confirm on closer inspection.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly pregnant shelves hold no butter or rice and fewer
soft drinks and snack foods: panic buyers have snapped them up.
</P>
<P>
   Electronics stores are selling floor models of televisions
because their back rooms are depleted.
</P>
<P>
   ``People get their salaries and they want to spend it on
something before it loses its value. So they put it into a product
they can use later,'' one distributor said.
</P>
<P>
   The variety of other goods, from soups to diapers, is dwindling
as popular brands are bought out. What is left are mostly Russian
brands of lower quality and price _ or, at least, less visibility.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In St. Petersburg, a meat importer, Aleksei Ivanov, said
Thursday that demand for Russia's scrawny, softball-sized chickens
is mushrooming.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet on Thursday evening, one plaintive Moscow
resident begged for help in finding kitty litter, saying she had
canvassed about 10 stores only to find that importers were not
restocking Moscow retailers. ``I don't know if Kesha the cat can
hold off much longer,'' she typed.
</P>
<P>
   Such shortfalls are largely due to the out-of-control spin of
the ruble. The value of Russia's basic unit of currency has
shriveled from nearly 16 cents to barely 5 1/2 cents just since
mid-August, including a fall of some 50 per cent this week alone.
</P>
<P>
   Having toppled Russia's prime minister and wrecked the banking
system, the ruble's plummet is now inflicting a triple whammy on
commerce. The prices of imported items, and even Russian items with
imported components, are skyrocketing. Foreign firms, which supply
an amazing share of Russia's food and dry goods, are refusing to
let Russian companies buy on credit because they fear the ruble's
value will have fallen so far by the time bills come due that
customers will be unable to pay them.
</P>
<P>
   And Russian consumers, who see prices rising and goods vanishing
as retailers fail to replenish their stocks, have begun hoarding
both imported and domestic products. Thus do shelves become even
thinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buckwheat. Millet. Rice. Macaroni. Sugar. Salt. Flour,'' said
a clerk at the Grocery Store _ most Russian markets still carry
generic names like ``Grocery Store'' and ``Department Store'' _ as
she ticked off a list of sold-out items Thursday evening. As this
particularly disheveled downtown market, the price of canned peas
has risen from six to 8.1 rubles in two days, a kilo of nectarines
from 17 to 33 rubles and cauliflower from 17.1 to 20.7 rubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's to be done?'' she asked. ``People have to eat.'' So
quickly do prices change that a variety of merchants _ wholesalers,
distributors, even some restaurants and cafes _ no longer bother to
price their goods in rubles, but in ``unit equivalents,'' a
gray-market tender that magically floats each day to correspond
with the number of rubles needed to buy a dollar _ if, in fact, any
dollars were available to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Harman, financial manager of the Cherkizovsky Meat
Processing Factory here, said he pays ``u.e.'s'' of rubles for
sausage casings from a manufacturer in the Don River valley, some
275 miles south of Moscow. Because imported materials are used to
make the casings, he said, their price must float to account for
the changing cost of the raw materials.
</P>
<P>
   And imported materials make up a stunning percentage of Russian
foods and other goods. According to Andrei Kushnerenko, a deputy at
the Ministry for Foreign Economic Relations and Trade quoted by
Interfax, Moscow's food processors buy 85 to 90 per cent of their
raw materials abroad.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that importers demand payment in foreign
currencies, often dollars, and foreign currencies are next to
impossible to obtain.
</P>
<P>
   For example, consider the plight of Monolit, a St. Petersburg
importer of Spanish foods. It currently holds an investment of some
$150,000 in food _ olive oil, canned fish and so on _ delivered
before the full force of the current crisis hit. Were the company
to actually sell the products, the devalued rubles it would collect
might now cover half the purchase cost. But in any case, Monolit
could not pay: the Spanish do not want rubles, and the government
so far is not converting rubles into more stable currencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system has almost collapsed,'' Artyom Kolobanov, Monolit's
general director, said in an interview Thursday. ``I hope there are
smart people in the country who can stop this chaos. If this entire
structure collapses, it will take a long time to restore it. If the
problem is not solved in the next two or three weeks, the collapse
of the ruble will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, where the city government has some influence over
food distribution, many major distributors and wholesalers are
rationing deliveries, Harman said.
</P>
<P>
   His meat-processing company has shifted much of its distribution
from rural areas to Moscow, where the demand is greatest, and could
continue selling for some six weeks more under the current
conditions. But he said most Moscow companies do not enjoy such
large inventories, and so they _ and the Russian government _ have
little time to stabilize the ruble and resume normal business.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Petersburg, an official of the city's leading dairy
supplier, Boris &AMP; Pavel, said the company could continue for no
more than a month before it would be forced to shut its doors. Some
80 per cent of the company's goods are imported, and it has lost
hundreds of thousands of dollars in the last 10 days alone, said
its general director, Nikolai Guchevsky. ``I have no words to
describe the situation,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``We
didn't expect this,''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
