</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BANKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREEFALLING RUBLE BRINGS ANGRY DEPOSITORS TO BANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Crowds of angry depositors filled the halls of Moscow's
best-known banks Thursday as the ruble took another plunge a day
after Russia's Central Bank announced it was powerless to stop the
Russian currency's freefall.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Bank set the ruble at 13.46 to the dollar, more than
twice the rate of 6.3 before the Aug. 17 devaluation, and far
beyond the rate of 9.5 rubles to the dollar the bank had set as the
outer limit for trading in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But in trading at the Moscow Interbank Currency Exchange
(MICEX), reopened Thursday after a week-long shutdown by the
Central Bank, the ruble slid to a bid/offer rate of 16.000/22.000
to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the ruble will continue to fall as long as
political instability endures, highlighted by the battle over a new
government being waged by an aging President Boris Yeltsin and the
opposition-led lower house of parliament, the State Duma.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin wants the Duma to approve Acting Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin in a vote scheduled for Friday. But the
Communist-dominated Duma has vowed to block Chernomyrdin, who was
prime minister for five years until this March and whom opposition
leaders blame for many of Russia's economic troubles. The Duma
overwhelmingly rejected Chernomyrdin in a vote Monday. President
Clinton, before departing Moscow early Thursday, told Chernomyrdin
he had to find a way to form a government as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as no one has any idea who is running the government,
and what it plans to do, the ruble rate will fall,'' said Veniamin
Simonov, chief analyst at MICEX.
</P>
<P>
   While the ruble's freefall has caused no street riots like the
public disorder that overtook Indonesia last fall, Russians have
begun sinking their fast depreciating rubles into durable goods and
staple products. Panic buying and hoarding has been on the increase
amid reports that importers, wary of uncertainty surrounding the
ruble, have stopped food shipments.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the anxiety moved to a new front after the Central
Bank on Wednesday ordered six leading commercial banks to turn over
their individual depositors' savings accounts to the state-owned
savings bank, Sberbank.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial banks, which had invested heavily in high-return,
short-term treasury bills, where caught by surprise on Aug. 17 when
the government announced it would not be able to pay Treasury-bill
holders and abandoned its four-year policy of defending the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   The currency has plunged ever since, prompting depositors to
rush to withdraw their savings. But the banks, suddenly caught with
inadequate funds by the government's devaluation and default, have
turned away clients with empty hands.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, promising there would be no repeat of 1992, when
Russians' life savings were wiped out overnight when prices were
freed and the ruble plunged to near-worthlessness, has vowed to
protect depositors this time. Acting on that pledge, the Central
Bank Wednesday ordered six banks _ Most Bank, SBS-Agro, Menatep,
Inkombank, Promstroi Bank and Mosbiznes Bank _ to surrender
individual savings accounts to Sberbank.
</P>
<P>
   Depositors have until Sept. 26 to make the change, but worried
Muscovites filled the banks' offices Thursday morning to try to
find out what was happening to their money. For those who opened
dollar accounts, a transfer to Sberbank will mean heavy losses _
the money will be exchanged at the Sept. 1 rate of 10.88 rubles to
the dollar. Even transferring ruble accounts into Sberbank is not
something many Muscovites do easily _ it was Sberbank where most
people kept their money in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin Thursday tried to calm Russians, telling them it
was their choice whether or not to transfer their accounts, and
that they had plenty of time. He also scolded the Central Bank for
its poor job in explaining the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appeal to the population: there is no need to hurry to fill
out a declaration to transfer your savings from commercial banks to
Sberbank,'' Chernomyrdin said in remarks carried by all three major
television news networks.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin also said he would present ``radical proposals'' to
solve the economic crisis during a meeting Friday with the upper
house of parliament, the Federation Council. One of Chernomyrdin's
aides, Boris Fyodorov, is pushing the idea of setting up a fixed
currency peg similar to the one successfully implemented in
Argentina in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin did not elaborate on his plans, and his words were
unlikely to reassure many of the Russians who have deposited an
estimated $21 billion in commercial banks. These people drew
confidence from the banks' professional appearance and such modern
features as automated teller machines and credit cards, as well as
the ability to hold accounts in dollars as a hedge against the
ruble's instability. But that trust has now crumbled, along with
any residual belief in the authorities' ability to right the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we trust Sberbank if we don't trust our own
country?,'' asked Tatyana Chernosheva, as she stood in line outside
the modern office of Most Bank in a western Moscow bedroom
community. NTV television showed another woman in a different line
saying much the same thing: ``How can you trust the state bank if
you don't trust the state?''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all a well-calculated tactic to separate the people
from their money _ again,'' said another man in line, who refused
to give his name but with whom everyone in line agreed with grim
nods.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the bank, clerks refused to comment and wary security men
in suits kept watch over the crowd. Alexandr Polyakov, a vice
president of Most Bank, was one of several commercial bank leaders
who criticized the Central Bank's move.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Central Bank) was hoping to calm the panic, but it has
had the opposite effect and raised it to another degree,'' Polyakov
said.
</P>
<P>
   At a nearby SBS-Agro bank, another line formed. Russia's second
largest bank, SBS-Agro has already been taken under Central Bank
administration, and Central Bank chairman Sergei Dubinin has said
SBS-Agro is effectively bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Another once powerful bank, Menatep, has already laid off 1,000
employees, according to the English language daily, The Moscow
Times.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's private banks grew quickly after the 1991 Soviet
collapse and the beginning of the transition from a centralized
economy. The new bankers were often well-connected insiders who
hustled to lay claim to Communist party money, pension funds, and
other assets that were lying in the ruins of the Soviet system in
the chaotic early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The banks grew rich and powerful speculating on Russia's debt
market, and, among the most powerful banks, by acquiring lucrative
holdings in Russian industry through their Kremlin connections.
Until now, the presidents of Most Bank, Incombank, SBS-Agro and
Menatep _ the banks forced to give up their deposits _ were among
the magnates known as the ``oligarchs'' for their legendary
influence on Russian politics. But for all their power, critics say
they have been poor bankers, and were already vulnerable long
before the latest crisis hit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Material from Globe wire services was used to prepare this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
