<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSSET HAD THE WRONG TICKET, THE RIGHT TIMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marc Rosset's name might have been in the obituary
page instead of the sports pages this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Rosset, one of the more famous citizens of Switzerland, held a
ticket on Wednesday night's ill-fated Swissair Flight 111 out of
New York's Kennedy Airport that crashed in Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   But here was the 6-foot-7-inch Rosset, the most Alpine of
professional tennis players _ Olympic gold medalist in 1992 _ at
Flushing Meadow Thursday, feeling as if he'd won the US Open even
though he was a first-round loser. Feeling very lucky because he
didn't show up for Flight 111 to Zurich.
</P>
<P>
   Also feeling ``very sad for the (229) people who lost their
lives. Now I feel close to them. You know, Switzerland is a small
country, 6 million and ... 60 of them went just like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosset wasn't sure why he didn't join them.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday he acknowledged still being ``a little bit afraid. So
close to death. I changed my mind about leaving last night, and
it's a strange feeling to realize that changing my mind changed my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   His opening-round defeat by Dominik Hrbaty Monday might have
been a death sentence. ``My coach and I had decided to stay a
couple more days to practice, to go home Wednesday,'' Rosset said.
``But you know, I didn't feel like packing. Some friends wanted to
have dinner. I changed my mind Tuesday. Sometimes ... you just
decide to change your mind. You wake up, you feel different. Why? I
don't know. For no real reason, I changed my mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I was going to go (Friday), but I can't fly for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosset's blue eyes, offsetting a scraggly blond beard, were
bleary Thursday. Understandably. ``I stayed up all night watching
CNN,'' he said, ``hoping the people would be all right, calling
friends to let them know I was OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came home from dinner, a friend called to tell me to
turn on the TV. That's how I found out how lucky I was. The first
thing I did was call my parents in Geneva _ it was 2 a.m. there _
and let them know I wasn't on the plane. They knew about the crash
and were worried that I might be. I called my coach, Pierre
Simsolo, to let him know we were pretty lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were supposed to practice (Friday), but I'm not able to do
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are pretty close like this,'' he added, ``maybe you
realize, `Maybe I am going to try to enjoy more my life, like every
day.' For sure now, I hope it's going to help me to be relaxed for
the end of my career, not to take the thing maybe too seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The so-called pressure of a tennis match, the fear of defeat,
will probably seem trivial to Rosset.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Sampras, the four-time champ pushed hard Thursday in four
sets by 22-year-old American rookie Paul Goldstein, said, ``It's
something you think about, a crash, as much as we fly. But you
can't stop flying.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of his predecessors as US champs died young in airplanes.
Mexican Rafael Osuna, winner of the 1963 title, was 30 and had
performed brilliantly to lead a 1969 Davis Cup triumph over
Australia days before boarding an airliner that plunged into a
mountain near Monterey. Joe Hunt, victor in 1943, was a 25-year-old
US Navy pilot killed in a Florida training mission 17 months later.
</P>
<P>
   Mats Wilander can empathize with Rosset. Shortly after capturing
the 1988 US Open, he booked a seat on the doomed Pan American
flight from Europe to New York that ended in pieces in Lockerbie,
Scotland. At the last minute, he picked another airline, feeling
the routing was better for him.
</P>
<P>
   Californian Derrick Rostagno, who nearly beat champ Boris Becker
during the 1989 Open, also can empathize with Rosset. In 1986,
after playing a minor Mexican tournament, he boarded a plane to Los
Angeles, via Mexico City. At the stopover in Mexico City, he
decided to get off to play another small-change event there. The
plane went down en route to LA.
</P>
<P>
   Rosset's countrywoman and sometime mixed doubles partner,
reigning women's champion Martina Hingis, rushed up to hug him.
``Planes can be scary,'' she said. ``You have no chance, not like
in a car. But this is our life.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosset said, ``The life has to go on. After home, I go to
central Asia, Uzbekistan, to play in Tashkent ... I wonder if I can
get a boat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
