<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-MANN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH CUTS SHORT LIVES OF CRUSADERS AGAINST AIDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Since he resigned in 1990 after a bitter dispute with
the World Health Organization's director over global AIDS policy,
Dr. Jonathan Mann hadn't set foot in the organization's
Geneva-based headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   He had planned to return Thursday. With his nemesis gone and a
more simpatico WHO director in place, the ever-restless 51-year-old
Mann looked forward to a series of talks about how he might launch
a new phase of his career in international health.
</P>
<P>
   But the crash of Geneva-bound Swissair Flight 111 Wednesday
night turned what was supposed to have been a grand reunion into a
harrowing memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   Mann's wife, Johns Hopkins University vaccine expert Mary Lou
Clements-Mann, also perished in the crash. She had planned to
attend meetings on how to design an AIDS vaccine that would be
practical for use in developing nations where 90 percent of human
immunodeficiency virus (HIV) infections occur.
</P>
<P>
   Planned agendas were canceled as 500 of the Manns' stunned
colleagues gathered in WHO's biggest auditorium _ the same room
where Mann announced his resignation as director of the Global
Program on AIDS on March 16, 1990 _ to absorb the news and
contemplate its poignant timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very emotional indeed,'' said Daniel Tarantola, a
Harvard AIDS Institute scientist who will shortly become a top
adviser to Dr. Harlem Gro Brundtland, the new WHO director.
``Jonathan was very popular at WHO.''
</P>
<P>
   As he sat in the auditorium Thursday, Tarantola remembered the
staff's reaction to Mann's resignation eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hundreds of people formed a sort of escort or fence outside
the room when Jonathan left and applauded him. It was an emotional
departure,'' Tarantola said. ``He was about to come back as a
guest, a friend, a colleague.''
</P>
<P>
   Tributes to Mann, one of the most visible and passionate of the
world's first-generation warriors against the AIDS epidemic,
clogged media fax machines Thursday. Their theme was appreciation
for a man who insisted, with rare eloquence, that the virus would
never be stopped as long as governments, societies, and individuals
persisted in stigmatizing those it was most likely to infect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never get used to losing our friends in the fight against
AIDS,'' said Larry Kessler, executive director of the Massachusetts
AIDS Action Committee. ``I just feel this is a tremendous loss. Jon
was a true missionary, a very powerful voice about the
interconnection of health, justice, and human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My generation will not see a better man,'' added Dr. June
Osborn, former chairman of the President's AIDS Commission and now
president of the Josiah Macy Jr. Foundation. ``He made an
extraordinary mark on the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Mann's influence was more than rhetorical. In the late 1980s, he
successfully pushed the World Health Assembly to pass a strong
resolution urging its 187 member nations not to discriminate
against people with AIDS or HIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``That resolution was a landmark,'' Tarantola said. ``I can
assure you governments would have passed laws restricting the
rights of people with HIV/AIDS, imposing mandatory testing, even
putting them in jail. There was a search-and-destroy frenzy.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Mann enjoyed the spotlight, his career was marked by
unconventional zigs and zags dictated more by principle and passion
than by ambition or self-preservation. His friends believe he is
one of only two people to relinquish an endowed professorship at
Harvard _ a report that university officials Thursday said they
could not confirm.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston native whose father was a well-known psychiatrist and
whose mother is a retired librarian and artist, Mann graduated from
Harvard in 1969 and got a medical degree from Washington University
Medical School in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   A stint with the US Centers for Disease Control convinced Mann
he wanted to work in public health, and by the early 1980s he was
in Zaire, antagonizing government authorities loathe to acknowledge
the emerging AIDS epidemic. By 1986, Mann was founding director of
the WHO's global program on AIDS, but disputes over funding and
philosophy put him on a collision course with WHO's then-director,
Hiroshi Nakajima.
</P>
<P>
   After he resigned with a blast at Nakajima, Mann took a post at
the Harvard School of Public Health, where in 1993 he founded the
Francois-Xavier Bagnoud Center for Health and Human Rights with a
$20 million gift, the largest Harvard had received in two decades.
</P>
<P>
   But last year Mann announced he would give up the professorship
to become founding dean of a new public health school at Allegheny
University of the Health Sciences in Philadelphia. ``The idea of
creating a new school along the lines of his vision of public
health was incredibly appealing to him,'' said Sofia Gruskin,
director of the human rights program at the Bagnoud Center.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Allegheny University is suffering from severe
financial problems that recently led Mann to explore options in
Geneva. ``He was really excited about this trip and what it might
mean,'' Gruskin said. ``He had a lot of hope that finally the WHO
and he were sharing a similar vision. When we taught courses
together, he liked to tell students, `This course is for people who
believe the world can change.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mann is survived by his mother, Ida Mann, of Newton, Mass.; twin
daughters by his first marriage, Naomi, of Washington, D.C., and
Lydia, of Boston; and a son, Aaron, a Peace Corps volunteer now in
Burkina-Fasso.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
