<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8098 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-TENNIS-HNS &LR;      09-03 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-TENNIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNIS PRACTICE KEEPS SWISS PLAYER OFF DOOMED FLIGHT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
(Filed in ``a'' and ``s'') 
 
By ALAN TRUEX 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When tennis player Marc Rosset lost his first-round
match at the U.S. Open this week, he booked a flight home to
Geneva. It was Swissair Flight 111, the one that crashed Wednesday
night off the coast of Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Rosset changed his mind. He decided to stay in New
York an extra day to get more hardcourt practice.
</P>
<P>
   Rosset lost his match Monday against Dominik Hrbaty of Slovakia.
On Tuesday, he made a reservation on the doomed flight.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday night, he talked with his coach and decided to
practice Wednesday and fly home Thursday night instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `OK, let's stay one more night,''' Rosset said at a
news conference Thursday. ``Sometimes, you make a decision and you
don't know why, and a couple of days later you realize you changed
your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Saved it, actually.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came back to my room last night,'' Rosset said, ``and a
friend of mine who lives in New York calls me, and he says, `You'd
better watch CNN because the flight you were supposd to take just
crashed.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned on my TV, and then I called my parents and my friends
to let them know I was not on that flight. You have to try to call
most of the people who care about you just to make them secure.''
</P>
<P>
   The crash killed 229 people.
</P>
<P>
   Rosset's parents had been trying to call him, hoping he had
changed his mind about his flight plans. But they had been unable
to get their calls through the overheated telephone lines of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say they were pretty glad to hear my voice,'' Rosset
said. ``I feel really sad for the people who were on that plane. I
watched CNN all night long, and they show the airport in Geneva
with all the families that are waiting, all the friends, and I feel
really sad for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Rosset now has ambivalence about flying. ``I have to
say that to fly is pretty secure,'' he said. ``You have less chance
to die in a flying accident than in the car or on the street here
in New York. But last night makes me realize you still have a
chance that something wrong happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a little bit afraid,'' he admitted. ``I have plans to fly
tonight, but I don't know if I can do it, honestly.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosset, 28, is in his 11th year of traveling on the Association
of Tennis Professionals tour.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He is not the first tennis traveler to have a close brush with
death by flight.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled Derrick Rostagno, who was en route to Los Angeles
with a stop in Mexico City. Upon landing in Mexico, Rostagno
suddenly decided to get off the plane to enter a satellite
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   One of Rostagno's friends on the tour, Andre Agassi, recalled:
``Eleven minutes after that plane took off, it blew, and that was
it. He was supposed to stay on that plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you travel the world like we do,'' Agassi said, ``you are
bound to have your share of travel difficulties, but you pray to
God nobody has to ever go through that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rosset feels his near-death experience will change his
perspective on life. ``Maybe it is going to help me relax for the
end of my career,'' he said. ``Maybe I am going to try to enjoy
more my life, like every day.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
