<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8105 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONN-TROOPERS-SHOT-BO     09-03 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-TROOPERS-SHOT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE TROOPERS   AMONG FIVE WOUNDED IN SHOOTOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE EBBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLINGTON, Conn. _ Called to investigate a routine crime just
after starting their shift Thursday, rookie State Trooper Michael
Hoague and his field training supervisor, Mark Pelletier had no
idea what was in store for them.
</P>
<P>
   About 8 a.m. Thursday, they approached a remote Willington
mobile home to question the suspect, Edward Premo, about damage to
his neighbor's car. Moments later, they were in a firefight.
</P>
<P>
   Premo had emerged, armed with two handguns, and opened fire on
the stunned officers, officials said. They managed to return fire,
and were joined by a third trooper, James Reidy, who answered their
call for help.
</P>
<P>
   When the shooting ended, Premo, a 40-year-old postal driver, and
all three officers lay seriously wounded outside the mobile home on
River Road.
</P>
<P>
   All four men were taken to Johnson Memorial Hospital, where they
underwent emergency surgery and were expected to fully recover. All
were listed in stable condition, and Premo faced a litany of
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Premo, who rented the mobile home near Interstate 84, was
apparently prepared for battle. Police said investigators found his
home rigged with several hand-made explosives.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb squad was called in after the state police tactical
unit entered the home and found one of the undetonated devices.
River Road was then sealed off and specialists began a day-long
effort just to get in the home and search it.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday, State Police Col. John F.
Bardelli said he could not recall a shooting of this magnitude
involving his department. Counselors were brought in to help
stunned troopers in this rural community, in northeastern
Connecticut just south of the Massachusetts border.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sobering experience,'' said Lt. Ralph Carpenter, the
department's new public information officer.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John Rowland canceled a trip to Washington, D.C. Thursday
and visited the troopers in the hospital. He said their spirits
were high but their experience points to the constant danger in
even apparently routine police work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a constant reminder,'' he said. ``That's the difficult
part of the job _ always being on guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said they did not know Premo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all trying to find out who he is,'' said a nearby
resident, Natalie Williams. ``He wasn't a big psycho who we all
knew about. It's always been a quiet town.''
</P>
<P>
   At the press conference, Bardelli gave this account of the
incident:
</P>
<P>
   At 7:50 a.m., Peltier and Hoague were dispatched to the River
Road trailer after Premo's neighbor called and accused him of
vandalizing her car.
</P>
<P>
   Pelletier, who has been a trooper for five years, was paired
with Hoague, who had just graduated from the police academy a few
weeks ago. Having just begun their morning shift, the officers
considered it a low-priority call; they have sole jurisdiction over
the town of Willington.
</P>
<P>
   When they arrived at the trailer on River Road _ just a few
miles from a state police barracks in Tolland _ Premo was outside
the house, armed with two handguns.
</P>
<P>
   A furious shootout ensued: Though they were hit, both officers
fired back at Premo, then took cover, calling for help.
</P>
<P>
   Police would not say which trooper's shots struck Premo, but he
was still firing _ and had grabbed an assault rifle by the time
Reidy, a 14-year veteran, sped up. Reidy was hit before he left his
cruiser, but he, too, managed to return fire. He was the only
officer who wasn't wearing a bulletproof vest.
</P>
<P>
   At least two passers-by called for help and even flagged down a
passing ambulance. Premo was apparently wounded and subdued by the
time other officers arrived.
</P>
<P>
   State troopers had no explanation for the attack, or for Premo's
home arsenal. When they realized the mobile home had explosives
inside, police ordered the bomb squad to conduct a slow, careful
entry into the house.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the day, police said, officers found several
apparent explosive devices, Carpenter said. He declined to describe
them as bombs, saying they were still being examined.
</P>
<P>
   Premo was not well known to police in this community, and had no
known criminal record in Connecticut, Carpenter said. A check of
Tolland County Courts showed no criminal charges or civil claims
against him. Carpenter did not specify the charges Premo now faces.
</P>
<P>
   Though troopers scoured the area overhead with a helicopter and
had barricaded the road, they insisted they believe Premo was alone
and they did not expect to arrest anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Premo apparently lived alone in the mobile home on property
owned by Pisciotta Real Estate. Property manager Michelle Pisciotta
said she never had any complaints about Premo, who routinely
stopped in and politely paid his rent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't even aware if he had a telephone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For six years, Premo has worked as a truck driver for the U.S.
Postal Service in Hartford, delivering mail from the plant to post
offices, according to spokeswoman Christine Dugas &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Another spokesman, Steve Korker, said Premo had been off work
without pay for about a week.
</P>
<P>
   Korker would not elaborate because of personnel policies. He
explained that employees can be put on ``non-work status'' for
various reasons that range from requesting days off without pay to
disciplinary action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
