u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DWI-DEPORTATION-HNS &LR;      09-03 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DWI-DEPORTATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INS PLANS TO DEPORT LEGAL IMMIGRANTS WITH DWI CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARO ROBBINS  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A statewide roundup of legal immigrants with three
or more drunken-driving convictions ended Thursday, leaving almost
500 of them facing deportation, U.S. Immigration and Naturalization
Service officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed Operation Last Call, the week-long sweep was timed to
precede the Labor Day holiday. Last Labor Day, 20 people died in
alcohol-related accidents in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The first of its kind, the operation corralled 76 convicted
felons in the San Antonio District that sweeps from Del Rio to
Victoria and from Waco to Laredo, INS officials told a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government has the authority, through the INS, to
remove habitual felony drunk drivers from the streets of our
communities,'' said Benito Lopez, the INS acting assistant
investigations director for the district. ``We take that
responsibility seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said 101 people were apprehended in the Harlingen District
which encompasses the Rio Grande Valley, 104 were found in the El
Paso District, 200 were arrested in the Dallas District and 34 in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The targets were taken to county lockups around the state. How
many posted bond was not known, Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   The operation, which was both criticized and applauded by
observers, marked the first time immigration officials targeted DWI
felony offenders on a large scale.
</P>
<P>
   They only took aim at drunken drivers for the first time in
February after the U.S. Board of Immigration Appeals added felony
DWI convictions to the list of offenses punishable by deportation.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, most offenders convicted more than twice for driving
while intoxicated are considered felons.
</P>
<P>
   Since February, INS officers have been regularly but quietly
checking court and jail records, looking for immigrants, Lopez
said. This week's sweep, however, focused on areas such as Beeville
and Victoria, where a lack of staff has prevented daily checks.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said he did not know how many immigrants had been deported
for DWI convictions. But immigration attorneys say the cases have
started to trickle in.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio lawyer Josephine Daly said she has been helping a
legal permanent resident fight deportation since he was convicted
in July for a third DWI offense.
</P>
<P>
   She described him as an engine mechanic, a married father of two
who has lived in the United States since age 10. She said her
client might have fought his earlier DWI cases, if he had known
they could come back to pry him from his home.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers who handle criminal cases agreed the new INS policy has
ramifications for the criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   The policy may prolong cases as more immigrants reject plea
bargains that quickly dispose of DWI charges, said Robert Valdez, a
San Antonio lawyer whose main practice is such cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something new, and it's probably going to mean more
people are going to want their cases tried,'' Valdez said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney David Lunan, chief of the Bexar
County task force that prosecutes felony-level DWI cases, agreed
the policy could spur more trials.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the policy, like Rogelio Nunez, director of the
Harlingen-based immigration advocacy group Proyecto Libertad, said
the government is punishing breadwinners who already have paid the
fines and served the jail time demanded by criminal codes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have done what the law requires,'' Nunez said. ``Now
they're being picked up without any warning of any kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Others took issue with the Board of Immigration Appeals decision
that characterized drunken driving as a violent offense.
</P>
<P>
   If someone who drives drunk without hitting anything is violent,
what's that make a speeder? asked Joseph De Mott, a San Antonio
immigration lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping the federal courts is going to overturn the
decision of the board,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8107 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISE-BOS     09-03 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO MULLS REOPENING CLINTON FUNDRAISING PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno, in a step toward the
appointment of an independent counsel to investigate President
Clinton, is reviewing whether his 1996 campaign dodged spending
limits through the use of ``issue advocacy ads,'' legal sources
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Reno is expected to decide by the middle of next week whether
she will open a 90-day inquiry to determine if Clinton and his
aides violated campaign-spending laws by their involvement in
Democratic National Committee television ads that promoted his
programs.
</P>
<P>
   A new inquiry by Reno, who had earlier rejected calls form
Republicans and campaign-watchdog groups to investigate issue ads,
would represent a further broadening of inquiries into the Clinton
campaign's practices in the '96 election. Already, there are 90-day
investigations covering Vice Presdient Al Gore and former White
Hosue aide Harold Ickes, and a new inquiry would have the potential
to reach into the highest level of the White House and ensnarl the
president himself.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, if Reno ultimately decides to seek an independent
counsel, the resulting probe could encompass similar use of issue
ads by the Republicans in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Clinton's private attorney David Kendall spent 90
minutes at the Justice Department trying to convince investigators
that there was no reason to launch a preliminary investigation, a
source said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Thursday about an inquiry into the president, Reno said,
``All I can say is that we have new information. I cannot comment
on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokesman Bert Brandenburg refused to
disclose the specifics of the new information. ``The department is
reviewing new information with regard to issue advocacy advertising
and the 1996 campaign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential campaign finance system provides some public
financing for candidates who adhere to campaign-spending limits.
The political parties are permitted to run issue ads, which
advocate positions but do not explicitly endorse a candidate, and
not have them count against the limit.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 campaign, however, the president and his top
advisers _ as well as GOP candidate Bob Dole _ were directly
involved in creating party-financed ads that in effect backed their
candidacies. If the DNC ads were counted as campaign spending, the
Clinton campaign would have received an illegal $42 million
contribution from the DNC.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph E. Sandler, general counsel at the Democratic National
Committee, said a staff audit done by the Federal Election
Commission triggered Reno's initial 30-day review, which expires
next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a staff legal opinion that the commission itself
hasn't had a chance to address,'' Sandler said in an interview.
``It's not the view of the FEC. It's just some auditor's legal
opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in a joint statement, Sandler and Lyn Utrecht, general
counsel for Clinton-Gore '96, insisted that the ads were ``entirely
legal.''
</P>
<P>
   The FEC ``has long presumed that political parties' issue ads
are coordinated with their federal candidates and are intended, in
part, to promote those candidates' elections.'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Furthermore, under FEC rules, a political party ad that
mentions a federal candidate does not count as a contribution to
that candidate unless it contains an `electioneering' message,
urging a vote for the candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads promoted the Clinton administration's positions on such
topics as Medicaid, Medicare, education, the environment and crime,
and often contrasted those views against the Republicans'.
</P>
<P>
   James Kennedy, a White House lawyer and spokesman, said, ``Both
parties fully were engaged in the issue ads. Clearly the Democrats,
but the Republicans were actively out there with their issue ads
and, indeed, continue to be. Sugegstions there might be some
problems with them would dramatically change the understanding of
both parties about the legal situation.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 television interview, Dole said of one such ad: ``It
doesn't say `Bob Dole for president.' It has my _ it talks about
the Bob Dole story. It also talks about issues. It never mentions
the word that I'm _ it never says that I'm running for president,
though I hope that it's fairly obvious, since i'm the only one in
the picture!''
</P>
<P>
   In Kendall's meeting Wednesday at the Justice Department, he
argued that the department had already reviewed whether Clinton
acted properly on campaign finance matters and that there was no
specific new information to warrant a new investigation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe staff member Michael Kranish contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
