<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8111 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-RECORDS-850(2T     09-03 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-RECORDS-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SPORTS, THERE'S NOTHING QUITE LIKE WITH BASEBALL'S HOME RUN
MARK  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pursuit of baseball's home run record took a day off
Thursday, giving the contenders, Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa, and
everyone else a chance to relax and take a few deep breaths before
they resume the most captivating and chronicled sports chase in
recent decades.
</P>
<P>
   No other sport has seen anything like it; in fact, no other
sport seems to have a record that can equal the home run record for
glamour and notoriety. It may not be the most difficult record to
achieve, even in its own sport, but it has taken an unyielding grip
on the summer sports scene that no other milestone could seemingly
match.
</P>
<P>
   Take the following test, for example, without consulting
reference books.
</P>
<P>
   (1) Who holds the National Football League record for most
touchdowns scored in a season, and how many did he score?
</P>
<P>
   (2) Who holds the National Basketball Association record for
most points scored in a season, and how many did he score?
</P>
<P>
   (3) Who holds the National Hockey League record for most goals
scored in a season, and how many did he score?
</P>
<P>
   (4) Who holds the major-league baseball record for most home
runs hits in a season, and how many did he hit?
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the last question is certainly more widely known
now because of the ongoing exploits of McGwire and Sosa, who have
spent the better part of the summer chasing Roger Maris'
37-year-old mark of 61 home runs in a season. McGwire, who has
raised his total to 59 home runs with 12 in the St. Louis
Cardinals' last 17 games and his last 52 times at bat, and Sosa,
who has remained doggedly close with 56, rested Thursday in their
mad-dash pursuit of the home run record.
</P>
<P>
   They resume their seemingly inevitable quest Friday night,
McGwire at home against the Cincinnati Reds and Sosa in Pittsburgh,
where the Chicago Cubs open a weekend series with the Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   No pursuit of a record in any other sport has created the
electrifying atmosphere in which McGwire and Sosa take their daily
whacks. Touchdowns, baskets, goals are scored throughout the sports
year, but nothing grabs attention like home runs, especially the
prospect of a record number of home runs.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that challenges to Joe DiMaggio's 56-game hitting
streak or to the .400 batting average barrier could match the
intensity of the attention that is focused on the home run chase,
but those challenges have been virtually nonexistent. Occasionally
players have flirted with hitting .400 _ a mark last achieved by
Ted Williams (.406) in 1941 _ but never in the last month of the
season. And DiMaggio's streak has never been seriously threatened;
no player has reached 50 games, and Pete Rose's 44-game streak in
1978 stands as the closest challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The home run is a unique sports event,'' Fay Vincent, the
former baseball commissioner, said. ``No other sport has anything
like it. Everything in football requires two or more people. On one
team one guy can hit a home run and change everything. It's the
single most dramatic one-man event. There's so much magic that
surrounds a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   And when one man, let alone two, pursues the record, fans
everywhere watch. It has engulfed fans at all levels.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Reich, a lawyer, who has represented players in three of the
four major professional team sports, recounted a recent experience
at a Cardinals' game in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mario Lemieux wanted to see McGwire,'' said Reich, who took
the former hockey superstar to the game. ``We went in the dugout
before the game, and McGwire gave him a bat. Then he hit a home run
and Mario was one of the first to jump up and give him a standing
ovation.''
</P>
<P>
   Steffi Graf is another star athlete who has become enthralled
with the home run chase. ``I'm very excited about it and I check it
every day,'' she said. She is one of only five players to win
tennis' Grand Slam, but when told that no one had ever hit 62 home
runs, she acknowledged ``Well, I guess that's tougher then.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials from other sports acknowledge the allure of the
home-run pursuit. ``I'm a hockey fan first and foremost,'' said
Gary Bettman, commissioner of the National Hockey League, ``but the
energy and excitement are contagious.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary people, even casual sports fans, have become caught up
in the McGwire-Sosa onslaught, too.
</P>
<P>
   John Walsh, senior vice president and executive editor of ESPN,
related that on the day Sosa hit his 56th home run, Wednesday, he
called his wife, and ``she knew Sosa had hit a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As wonderful an athlete as Michael Jordan is,'' Walsh added,
``and as great as his achievements are, I don't think there was
that kind of excitement as the Bulls were setting their record. I
can't think of another record that has the same excitement to it as
the home run record.'' As executive vice president of Elias Sports
Bureau, the best-known official sports statistician, Steve Hirdt
spends his life dealing in numbers and records. Nothing comes close
to the home run record, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the attention given to it this year solidifies that
argument, if there ever was an argument,'' Hirdt said. ``I think
it's the sexiest record in sports. It's appealing both to casual
fans and dyed-in-the-wool fans. It's a very easy concept to
understand even for someone who isn't interested in baseball at
all, and the more you know about baseball the more you realize how
difficult it is to achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Further explaining his assessment, Hirdt cited three ``really
important'' components for a good record that this one has:
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 1, the home run is baseball's signature play. Second, a
home run is something that is difficult to gerrymander. Three, it
has an unyielding time limit.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's daily schedule enhances the interest. Every day for
six months, the drama of such a race builds.
</P>
<P>
   The home run record, of course, dates further back into sports
history than those in other sports, and its creator is seen as the
reason interest in it has been sustained for more than seven
decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all tied up in Babe Ruth; it's tied up in that
mythology,'' Reich said. ``It's punctuated now by the fact that
McGwire reminds people of that Ruthian mythology.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth, said Steve Greenberg, president of Classic Sports, is an
American icon. ``His is the name that was associated with that
record for the better part of our lifetimes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was,'' Hirdt noted, ``the first record that got people
interested in records.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg said other sports' records don't rank with the one
Ruth established, first with 59 home runs in 1921, then with 60 in
1927.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average fan probably doesn't know those other records,''
he said, alluding to the quiz. ``I'm an average sports fan. I don't
know who holds the record for goals in a season in the NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of baseball, probably the best-known record, at least to
some of the people interviewed, is the 100 points that Wilt
Chamberlain scored in an NBA game March 2, 1962. Hirdt said the
number itself makes it attractive, as does the player who achieved
the number.
</P>
<P>
   But Hirdt also said, ``In baseball, you have only a certain
number of turns in a season to do something, whereas in other
sports you can achieve records a little more easily by deciding to
do so, giving the ball to a running back to gain a record number of
yards or giving a player enough shots in basketball so he can score
a certain number of points.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg agreed that the Chamberlain record was a great
achievement, but he added, ``On the other hand, it was one night.
He also averaged 50 points a game that season. That's amazing. But
basketball isn't baseball. With all due respect to Wilt and David
Stern, it wasn't then and it isn't now. It doesn't capture the
heart of America like baseball does.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the National Football League's best-known records was the
2,003 yards O.J. Simpson gained rushing in the 1973 season. And
that was before he really became well known. But his record has
been eclipsed, and the 2,105 yards that Eric Dickerson gained in
1984 is not a number that comes readily rolling off even football
fans' lips.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Hirdt suggested, it was the number.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because O.J. Simpson was right at the 2.000 mark, that had a
lot to do with it,'' he said. ``More people are familiar with O.J.
Simpson aside from his more recent notoriety than Eric Dickerson at
2,105.''
</P>
<P>
   Reich, the sports agent, recalled Lemieux's chase of Wayne
Gretzky's consecutive-game scoring streak in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was going to break it until his back went out,'' Reich
related. ``But even that wasn't like this. The record for goals in
a season was a blow-the-roof-off record, but it's not even close.
This is the ultimate.'' In recent weeks, Reich said, he has been at
parks in Cleveland, Pittsburgh, Los Angeles, Chicago and New York.
``The excitement is unbelievable over this,'' he said. ``People
can't get enough of this. This is mythology in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone, though, is captive to the chase. When Jim Fassel,
the New York Giants coach, was asked if he was following the home
run race, he said, ``I only read football news in the paper. If I
catch it on the television at the right time, then I'll follow it.
Otherwise I'm asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   But he readily acknowledged that football has no record that
compares. ''A home run in baseball,'' he said, ``is the ultimate
when it comes to records and that kind of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Steffi Graf was asked if hitting 62 home runs is harder than
winning a grand slam in tennis? ``How many people have done this?''
she asked. Told no one had hit 62, she said, ``Well, I guess it's a
bit tougher then.'' Part of the answer, then, to Question 4 on the
test is 61. And the player who hit that many home runs was Roger
Maris. But everybody knows that. How many know that Emmitt Thomas
scored a record 25 touchdowns in 1995, that Chamberlain scored a
record 4,029 points in the 1961-62 NBA. season and Gretzky scored a
record 92 goals in the 1981-82 NHL season?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
