<HEADER>
A8114 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LIEBERMAN-BOS     09-03 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LIEBERMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR CASTIGATES CLINTON IN SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senator Joseph Lieberman, a Connecticut Democrat
known for his independence and personal probity, said Thursday in a
dramatic address on the Senate floor that President Clinton's
``immoral'' relationship with Monica S. Lewinsky hurt the country,
but he stopped short of calling for censure.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman bluntly said Clinton's sexual relationship with an
employee half his age in the workplace and in the vicinity of the
Oval Office ``is not just inappropriate, it is immoral. It is
harmful because it sends a message about what is appropriate
behavior to children. The president's behavior with Miss Lewinsky
... has, I fear, compromised his moral authority.''
</P>
<P>
   The moderate Democrat said Clinton's behavior warranted some
type of rebuke, a statement that could help set the stage for some
sort of congressional action that would indicate disapproval but
sidestep an impeachment and removal from office. But ``it is
premature to do so ... until we have received the report of the
independent counsel and the White House's response to it.''
</P>
<P>
   In stern terms, Lieberman said: ``The transgressions are too
consequential for us to walk way and leave the impression for our
children today and our posterity tomorrow that what he acknowledges
he did within the White House is acceptable behavior for our
nation's leader. On the contrary, as I have said, it is wrong and
unacceptable and should be followed by some measure of public
rebuke and accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time since Clinton publicly admitted on Aug. 17
to an ``inappropriate'' relationship with the former White House
intern that a fellow Democrat has addressed the issue on the Senate
floor. There were few senators in the chamber as Lieberman spoke.
</P>
<P>
   But moments after the speech, two other Democrats, Senators Bob
Kerrey of Nebraska and Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, hailed
Lieberman for his comments. Their remarks signaled deep Democratic
dissatisfaction with Clinton's behavior and his public admission.
Two Republicans, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and Senator
Strom Thurmond of South Carolina, also praised Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Toiv, Clinton's deputy press secretary, did not criticize
Lieberman in reacting to the address.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has great respect for Senator Lieberman because
of the key role he has played in the president's accomplishments on
behalf of the American people,'' Toiv said. ``It's always hardest
to hear criticism from a friend, but I am sure the president will
consider Senator Lieberman's words with the same care with which
they were delivered.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman had considered calling for a formal censure of Clinton
but was urged against taking that step by the Senate Democratic
leaders and by White House officials. ``It seems to me that talk of
impeachment and resignation at this time is unjust and unwise,'' he
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said Clinton had ``diminished the office he holds and
the country he represents.'' He said Clinton's wrongdoing was
``serious'' and his assumption of responsibility for his behavior
``inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He failed to show that he understood his behavior had
diminished the office he holds and the country he serves and that
it is inconsistent with the mainstream American values that he has
advanced as president,'' said Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is a deeply religious man known for personal
rectitude. He was among the group of centrist Democrats, including
Clinton, who established the Democratic Leadership Council to steer
the party back to the middle after Walter F. Mondale's presidential
defeat in 1984. Lieberman described his first public statement on
Clinton's admission the most difficult of his public career.
</P>
<P>
   He challenged Clinton's assertion that his behavior was private
and a matter that should concern only his family. Lieberman said
Clinton's private behavior was the public's business because
Clinton, as president, had the obligation to set an example to the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether we or he thinks it fair or not, the reality is that in
1998 a president's private life is public,'' Lieberman said during
his 25-minute speech.
</P>
<P>
   He said Clinton had undercut the efforts of parents to teach
their children the value of honesty and undermined the trust the
American people have in the president's word.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has hurt his credibility and perhaps his chances
of moving his policy agenda further,'' said Lieberman. ``But the
harm extends beyond the political arena. The misconduct may be
reinforcing one of the worst messages being delivered by our
popular culture, which is that values are fungible. And I am
concerned that his misconduct may help to blur some of the most
important bright lines of right and wrong in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Clinton's public admission last month, Lieberman
said: ``My immediate reaction to this statement was deep
disappointment and personal anger. I was disappointed because the
president of the United States had just confessed to engaging in an
extramarital affair with a young woman in his employ and to
willfully deceiving the nation about his conduct. I was personally
angry because Clinton had jeopardized his administration's historic
record of accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   After Lieberman's speech, Kerrey took to the floor and said
Clinton's behavior was ``serious and unquestionably public.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a moral dimension that may be more important than any
legislation we have done,'' said Kerrey.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan thanked his colleague from Connecticut for ``saying
what needed to be said and saying it in a manner that gives us hope
at a time of profound despond.''
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan, who at 71 is the oldest of the senators who spoke,
said, ``I am the older of the three and therefore have sinned the
most. But we have to resolve this. The senator did not call for any
immediate precipitous action. We have a process in place, imperfect
in many respects. In time and a not distant time a point of
decision will come to the Congress and it will be for us to
discharge our duty.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Democratic members of Congress have said Clinton's public
statements failed to adequately express genuine regret. But they
have felt constrained from speaking out. Only one Democrat,
Representative Paul McHale of Pennsylvania, who is leaving office
this year, has called for Clinton's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   When Senator Robert Bennett, a Utah Republican, urged his fellow
Republicans on Tuesday to back a formal censure resolution against
the president during a GOP policy luncheon, his suggestion was
dismissed as premature by his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Even senators like Bob Smith, the New Hampshire Republican who
has called for Clinton to resign, now say that Congress should not
act until after it receives a report from Starr.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8117 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MARIS-HNS &LR;      09-03 1966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MARIS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Nearly 13 years ago, Roger Maris died of lymphatic cancer at age 51
in a Houston hospital. The obituaries recounted what, by and large,
was a sad story of a man trapped by his success, a man whose
accomplishments were never fully appreciated.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This summer, the man who hit 61 home runs in 1961 for the New
York Yankees and was largely vilified for breaking Babe Ruth's
record is being viewed in a kinder fashion.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis' Mark McGwire enters this weekend's series against
Cincinnati at Busch Stadium with 59 home runs. It seems a foregone
conclusion McGwire, and perhaps Chicago's Sammy Sosa (56 homers),
will break Maris' record.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Shannon has a unique perspective on this summer of power.
Shannon is a broadcaster for the Cardinals; he could be behind the
microphone when McGwire breaks Maris' record.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 years ago, after Maris was traded from the Yankees
to the Cardinals, Shannon and Maris were teammates on the 1967 and
'68 St. Louis teams that won two National League pennants and one
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon and Maris remained close friends until Maris' death, and
Shannon senses that baseball fans are taking a closer look at what
the soft-spoken but iron-willed Maris had to endure in that
record-breaking season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's going to happen is that now Roger is going to
be looked at in a different light,'' Shannon said Wednesday night
from Miami, where McGwire hit a pair of home runs against the
Florida Marlins. ``Before, Roger was the villain, the bad guy who
wiped out Ruth's record. Now, it's like he's kind of the underdog.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new era as far as Roger Maris is concerned. I wish he
could be here for it.''
</P>
<P>
   If he were, Shannon thinks Maris would be pulling for McGwire to
break the record. In addition, Maris would appreciate that fans
across the nation are pulling for either McGwire or Sosa _ or both
_ to set a new mark.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case in 1961, when Maris had to overcome both
the stigma of chasing Ruth and having legendary teammate Mickey
Mantle competing with him for the record in the same season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd be loving this,'' said Shannon. ``First, the fact that
everybody is pulling for these guys, I think he'd relish that. He'd
be right there, pulling for them, too. I think Roger would have
loved to sit down and talk to these guys about what they're going
through and what he went through.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think if he were here, he'd be pulling for McGwire. Mark
is a Cardinal and Roger was a Cardinal, so he'd probably be a
little biased for McGwire.''
</P>
<P>
   Maris found happiness in his two seasons with the Cardinals, his
final two in the game.
</P>
<P>
   He was out of the glare of New York, where he was booed by the
fans in his final seasons with the Yankees and had a running feud
with the media.
</P>
<P>
   Maris, who was born, raised and buried in Fargo, N.D., clearly
was uncomfortable in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   When Maris went from the Kansas City Athletics to the Yankees in
a seven-player deal Dec. 11, 1959, the trade was significant
because of the players the Yankees gave up, not those they
acquired.
</P>
<P>
   Don Larsen, who pitched a perfect game for the Yankees in the
1956 World Series, and outfielder Hank Bauer, a veteran who had
been with the team since 1948 and was popular among his teammates,
went to Kansas City. In those days, being traded to Kansas City was
roughly equivalent to being sent to Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   Maris? He was a 25-year-old outfielder who had played three
seasons with Cleveland and Kansas City for teams that went a
combined 215-246. Maris had a total of 58 home runs and 203 RBIs in
388 games in the majors and had not hit above .273 _ decent numbers
but hardly enough to turn heads in the Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Maris, the Yankees acquired light-hitting infielder
Joe DeMaestri, who was out of baseball by 1961, and first baseman
Kent Hadley, who played only 55 games for the Yankees in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   New York also gave up young infielders Norm Siebern, who had
several good years with the A's, and Marv Throneberry, who became
``Marvelous Marv'' in a later incarnation with the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of trades, this one was a yawner. What happened during
the next two seasons, however, turned New York and the rest of the
baseball world upside down.
</P>
<P>
   From nowhere, Maris was the man who threatened Ruth's
single-season record of 60 home runs, who outshone teammate Mantle.
Among Yankees fans, Maris was an outsider who was stalking two of
the most deified legends of the historic franchise.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, it wasn't Maris against Ruth or Maris against Mantle as
much as Maris against the tradition of baseball's proudest and most
successful team.
</P>
<P>
   Astros coach Matt Galante was 17 and living in Brooklyn in 1961.
Galante admits he was not a Yankees fan. In fact, he despised the
team that had beaten his beloved Dodgers in the World Series five
times from 1947 to 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Galante remembers the feeling running against Maris as the
assault on Ruth's record unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mantle would have been better from a New Yorker's point of
view,'' said Galante. ``Maris wasn't a Yankee, you know what I'm
saying? He was traded over to the Yankees. In a lot of people's
minds, the Yankees were (Yogi) Berra and Mantle and (Phil) Rizzuto
and that core. It was almost like an outsider was doing this, even
though he had Yankee pin stripes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mantle was the hero of New York, for Yankees fans. You always
heard about Mantle because he was a great player and he was a
Yankee. Mantle was a guy who was out on the town, always in the
papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy (Maris), he wasn't that rowdy Yankee that you thought
of like Ruth and Mantle. He was a nice guy, just a nice guy who
didn't even seem like a Yankee. He was a traded guy who nobody knew
much about. He wasn't part of that core.''
</P>
<P>
   Mantle finished the 1961 season with 54 home runs, a remarkable
achievement considering he batted behind Maris in the lineup.
Though Maris, Mantle and teammate Bob Cerv shared an apartment in
Queens during the '61 season, it was reported often that summer
that Maris and Mantle did not get along and that they had an icy
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, says Shannon, Mantle benefited from Maris' presence and
enjoyed their friendship immensely.
</P>
<P>
   As the New York media bore down on Maris, Mantle finally was
given some peace. He often kidded Maris about having to deal with
the pressure that Mantle previously had shouldered alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt about it, the guy who really loved all the attention
Roger was getting was Mantle,'' said Shannon. ``Before Roger got
there and started going after the record, Mickey was the whipping
boy. After Roger got there that year, Mickey was the fair-haired
boy and Roger became the whipping boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger told me that Mickey used to laugh like crazy about that.
You know, they lived together, and whenever Maris would talk about
the media, Mantle would give him a look and say, `How's it feel,
big boy? I've been down that road.'''
</P>
<P>
   Maris wasn't ready for the onslaught of attention he received in
1961.
</P>
<P>
   In his first year with the Yankees, he hit .283 with 39 homers
and 112 RBIs and was named American League Most Valuable Player. In
his first year in New York, Maris enjoyed a cordial relationship
with the fans and media.
</P>
<P>
   That changed when Maris became the player who stalked Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   Early in 1961, it didn't seem as if Maris would threaten any
records. In mid-May, he was batting .210 with four home runs. Maris
finished May with five homers in the final week. He was on his way
to history.
</P>
<P>
   Maris' best day was July 25, when he hit two homers in the first
game of a doubleheader against the White Sox, then belted two more
in the second game.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, he reached 40 and passed Mantle for good.
</P>
<P>
   Around that time, commissioner Ford Frick ruled that if anyone
were going to break Ruth's record, it would have to be done in 154
games. The schedule had been boosted to 162 games that year because
of the game's first expansion (bringing in the Los Angeles Angels
and Washington Senators).
</P>
<P>
   If the record homer were hit after the 154th game, it would be
noted in the record book with an asterisk.
</P>
<P>
   By Sept. 9, Maris had 56 homers. He had three weeks and 20 games
to hit five homers. With the relentless pressure closing in on him,
Maris went into a power drought. He didn't hit No. 57 until Sept.
16, following with No. 58 the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Maris tied Ruth's mark in the Yankees' 159th game, on Sept. 26.
</P>
<P>
   He was still at 60 on the final day of the season but responded
with No. 61 against Boston rookie Tracy Stallard in the fourth
inning. After the game, his quotes spoke volumes of what he had
been through.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ordeal is over,'' Maris said. ``A thing like this can make
a nervous wreck of you. The pressure was terrific _ mentally much
more than physically.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have no idea what it is to put up with something like this
for two months. People around you all the time. You can't eat, you
can't sleep _ you can't even think. Maybe I wouldn't do it all over
again if I had the chance. Sometimes, I feel it wasn't worth the
aggravation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if I never hit another home run, this is the one they can
never take away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Maris was never the same after 1961. His top home-run total
thereafter was 33 in 1962. A wrist injury robbed him of much of his
power in the mid-1960s.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he went to St. Louis in 1967, he was a shell of his
former self, hitting a combined 14 homers in 225 games with the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't a power guy at all by the time he came over to St.
Louis,'' said Astros manager Larry Dierker, who faced Maris a
couple of times while pitching for Houston. ``He was a good, solid
player. I think the thing that we were all amazed by was that he
was a lot better all-around ballplayer than we all imagined and
less of a home-run hitter than we all imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   What also struck Dierker was the way Maris quietly went about
his business. There was no strut, no bravado, nothing that would
indicate this was a player who had broken the single-season
home-run mark only six seasons earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed like a very good guy, but it was almost like he was
having no fun,'' said Dierker. ``He wasn't like the Babe or the
Mick. He was like, beige, you know. Just kind of beige. He was a
home-run hitter who acted like a utility guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Maris retired after the 1968 season to run a beer
distributorship in Gainesville, Fla. _ a plum he received from
Cardinals owner August A. Busch Jr. for playing in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Maris stayed away from baseball until 1984, when he returned for
Old Timers Day at Yankee Stadium at the request of Yankees owner
George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   Maris was undergoing cancer treatment by that time. He died Dec.
14, 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon said he has had several conversations with McGwire this
summer about Maris, and McGwire has come to appreciate the ordeal
of having the nation watch each and every at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one thing that's come out of this is that it's
illustrated just how difficult this feat is and how difficult it
was for Roger Maris to accomplish,'' said Shannon. ``More and more
people realize the adverse conditions Roger went through, with
everybody openly against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even Mark, during a press conference the other day, said that
everybody is pulling for him, and it's tough to handle. In his
(Maris') case, everybody was pulling against him. What's coming out
is just how strong a person Roger was. He was tough as nails.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we get closer to it (McGwire's quest for 62), I'm thinking
about him a lot. I know he's looking down and watching with a big
smile on his face.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
