<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-SCENE-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S VISIT COINCIDES WITH WIDESPREAD OPTIMISM IN ULSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (also see NIRELAND-CLINTON)  
 (bl)  
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ If President Clinton visited Moscow
at one of Russia's most trying moments, he came to Belfast at one
of Northern Ireland's most promising.
</P>
<P>
   There is an unexpected momentum here toward firming up the terms
of the April peace settlement, and for the first time people are
expressing confidence that the conflict between the two warring
religious communities that has cost more than 3,200 lives in the
past three decades is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the type of violence we have seen for 30 years
has ended, and we are entering a new phase in the type of approach
we have to the political process,'' said Seamus Mallon, the
snowy-haired deputy leader of the new power-sharing Northern
Ireland Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Emblematic of the change was the appearance Thursday of Mallon
and the Assembly's leader, David Trimble, enthusiastically if
awkwardly waving at crowds of cheering people who turned out on a
brilliantly sunny day in Belfast to greet Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   People have been accustomed to see them instead facing down the
public with grim news briefings on the intransigence of their
political opponents and then ducking into the drab government
buildings where peace talks dragged on for more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   Until recent weeks, people were also unaccustomed even to seeing
them together because Mallon is a Catholic and Trimble a
Protestant.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Wood, the former information officer of Britain's Northern
Ireland Office, looked out over the gathering of Catholic and
Protestant politicians gabbing together as they awaited Clinton in
Waterfront Hall on Thursday morning and said: ``Just a couple of
years ago this scenario would have been unthinkable. If someone had
tried to script it, they would have been told, `Go lie down and get
over it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The harsh tone of public life here that had long been
characterized by a no-compromise, no-surrender attitude began to
change with the signing of the accord in April and the campaigns
for public approval in a referendum in May and for the election in
June of the Assembly that the pact created.
</P>
<P>
   But the incident that has animated the halting process was one
that was aimed at stilling it _ the bombing by renegade Catholic
guerrillas in Omagh on Aug. 15, which killed 28 people and injured
more than 200 others, the highest death toll of any single episode
in Ulster's bloody history.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Michael Keaveny, who buried two of the victims, said he
felt that in a horrible way the Omagh bomb could end up being a
``catalyst for peace.'' He said, ``I have a feeling this was the
end of the violence and the beginning of a new era.''
</P>
<P>
   The group that planted the bomb, which calls itself the Real
IRA, is made up of disaffected members of the Irish Republican Army
who left the organization because it adopted a cease-fire 14 months
ago and, through Sinn Fein, its political wing, held a role in the
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   The Real IRA had vowed to disrupt the peace agreement with
violence. But it has found itself isolated by public revulsion,
condemned by Sinn Fein and made the target of emergency anti-terror
laws passed early Thursday morning by the British and Irish
parliaments.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, representatives of the Real IRA said that in a
coordinated 90-minute period earlier this week, senior IRA
officials visited the homes of dissidents and ordered them to
disband. ``In the last 48 hours threats have been received from
fellow republicans,'' a spokesman said. He complained that the
action ``sullies the name of republicanism.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``new era'' that Keaveny spoke of picked up particular pace
this week with an announcement by the main IRA that it had set up a
special unit to find the bodies of people abducted in the 1970s. In
addition, Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams again denounced the Omagh
bombing, said violence in Northern Ireland was ``a thing of the
past, over, done with and gone,'' and committed his party to the
effort to disarm paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Trimble, once a hard-line tribal politician, was
showing off his new cross-community colors with a reworking of the
long notorious comment of the original Northern Ireland Assembly's
first speaker 75 years ago: ``This is a Protestant parliament for a
Protestant people.'' In Trimble's version, ``This is a pluralist
parliament for a pluralist people.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Much of the accelerated pace of events had to do with the visit
of Clinton, who was welcomed by British Prime Minister Tony Blair
as the U.S president who had done more for peace in Northern
Ireland than any other.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks introducing Clinton on Thursday, Trimble said he
would talk with anyone who had a proven interest in peace _ a
statement of significance, because he has never spoken directly to
Adams in public and has been threatening to block Adams from taking
a position in the Ulster cabinet that the Sinn Fein vote total
entitles him to. Trimble's argument was that Adams had not declared
the war over and was not cooperating with plans to disarm
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   The Sinn Fein leader addressed both complaints in his comments
this week, and the expectation is that Trimble will now seek the
approval of his own party to end to its snub of Adams. ``Nothing
beats talking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble is to meet Adams in a gathering of party leaders he has
called for Monday, and the face-to-face talks that the two men have
never had could follow later in the week. An end to their personal
estrangement would ease widespread fears of a disruptive deadlock
over the makeup of the new cabinet, clearing the last major
impediment to setting up the government called for in the peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The problems ahead are dense and formidable, but they concern
organizational complexities rather than the structural issues that
have continually imperiled the accord. The new Assembly is to take
over the power now exercised here by London in February.
</P>
<P>
   David McKittrick, an author of several reference books on
Northern Ireland, said in a column in The Independent of London on
Thursday that the violently polarized politics he had witnessed his
entire life seem to have yielded its grip on the province.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at this early stage, the new institutions and structures
are providing a political coherence that Northern Ireland has never
known before,'' he said. ``The ultimate aims of Unionists and
republicans are as far apart as ever, but the agreement has already
delivered an unexpectedly firm area of common ground.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
