<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8122 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-03 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE DAYS OF SEPTEMBER  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By A.M. ROSENTHAL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In September of 1998, when it seemed that some Americans would
lose money in the stock market and others might even lose jobs,
America and its government focused on nations they felt were to
blame, and on what American policy should be toward them. Russia,
Indonesia, Japan and so on.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In September of 1998, when it has become a reality for decades
past and a probability for decades ahead that terrorists selected
Americans for death, the United States and its government pays
attention only after a terrorist attack, and then briefly. The
United States had no international anti-terrorist policy that was
either consistent, effective, understood by the world or that
frightened terrorist nations. Iraq, Syria, Iran, Libya and so on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Historians of the future will write paragraphs like those two.
They will try to explain why the strongest country in the world
could not deal with terrorism, its troops and its masters. But
Americans can figure out the reasons right now. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Americans cannot get their heads around the fact that those
two-bit countries have us on the run politically and even
militarily. And in the high reaches of our government dwell
officials of medium ability, without sufficient power of
intellectual constancy to understand the past, see the present and,
through both, envision and lucidly discuss the future.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's top foreign-affairs officials could not answer
questions from Ohio college students without trembling. The way the
administration has managed foreign affairs leads our allies and
beneficiaries to tell us to get lost, and Saddam Hussein just to
dispatch a vassal to slap us down. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I believe the attacks against Afghanistan and the Sudan were
justified in a war against killers who cannot defuse generations of
hatred or its bombs. But Washington created the impression that
Osama bin Laden was Dr. No _ the fountainhead of world terror. The
job is to deal with terrorist groups and the terrorist nations
without which they could not exist long _ both halves of a poison
mushroom, not one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Does anybody believe that two Libyan intelligence officers
decided all by themselves to blow up Pan Am 103, thoughtfully
keeping the secret from their commander, Colonel Gadhafi?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright tries to deal with Iran
through its president, Mohamed Khatami. Sometimes the U.S. press
calls it her finest moment. Could she find time to tell him that we
would appreciate his suggesting publicly that the ayatollahs who
control Iran stop sending certain daily planes into
Syrian-controlled Lebanon? I mean the ones loaded with killing
material destined not only for Israel _ oh, that _ but for chosen
enemies worldwide.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saddam is the terrorist who influences most other terrorists.
The United States is now so weak in mind and muscle that it allows
him to bar U.N. inspections _ again and again.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scott Ritter is making it hard to think only about stocks and
bonds. A former Marine major, he headed U.N. inspectors assigned to
track down the Iraqi and foreign network that Saddam uses to
conceal the renewal of his nuclear, chemical and biological weapon
programs. The Ritter team needed one more surprise inspection. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was scheduled for Aug. 10, and canceled Aug. 8, on U.S.
demand. Ritter resigned _ to tell Americans what they should know.
He testified Thursday before a Senate committee. He says that
despite the cancellation, and U.S. interventions, earlier
inspections showed the network began and ended at Saddam's office
door. We do not have to be inspection experts to understand what
that means.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As long as Saddam exists, so will Iraq's plans to become a power
in weapons of mass destruction _ for itself and for selected
traveling terrorists. Washington apparently does not want that
advertised, possibly because after six years in office the Clinton
administration has no plan to make him non-exist. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And now please note well: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ritter nor any of the other U.N. inspectors believe that
without enforcement Saddam will allow the full inspection he
promised. That would end his programs for weapons of mass
destruction. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In this September of 1998, Ritter told senators that without
effective inspections, Saddam Hussein would have nuclear weapons
within three years. And he said that without that inspection Saddam
would have bacteriological weapons in six months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
