</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHERNOMYRDIN RALLIES FORCES FOR ANOTHER TRY AT CONFIRMATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also RUSSIA-MOOD)  
(js) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As Russia's political crisis heads for its next
showdown, on Friday, Acting Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin
rallied new forces Thursday to try and stop the Communist-led lower
house of parliament from rejecting his nomination a second time.
</P>
<P>
   With the economy in danger of following its currency into free
fall, the pressure to find a way out of a looming constitutional
confrontation intensified. President Boris Yeltsin proposed late
Thursday to reopen talks on sharing power with the
opposition-dominated lower house, the Duma.
</P>
<P>
   It was the collapse of a similar accord, tentatively reached
last weekend, that set the stage for Chernomyrdin's overwhelming
rejection by the lower house on a first vote on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   If Chernomyrdin is rejected again on Friday, as many observers
predict, then Yeltsin, whose authority is now at the lowest ebb of
his seven-year presidency, faces a politically agonizing choice. If
he resubmits Chernomyrdin's nomination and it is rejected a third
time, he would have to disband the lower house and call for new
parliamentary elections, an expensive and unsettling option for a
country gripped by a depression.
</P>
<P>
   Or the president could drop Chernomyrdin as a cause not worth
fighting for and put forward a compromise candidate. Among those
most often mentioned are Yegor Stroyev, chairman of the Federation
Council, the upper house of parliament; Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov;
or, possibly, one of the increasingly powerful regional governors.
</P>
<P>
   As the political heat rose in Moscow on Thursday, Chernomyrdin
met 50 regional leaders in his office in the Russian government
building, lobbying support for a nonbinding vote on his candidacy
in the upper house of parliament on Friday. The upper house is made
up of leaders of regional governments and legislatures, whose
influence has been growing, as the authority of the central
government here has waned.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation, while not decisive, could sway deputies in
the lower house, who have become increasingly mindful of the
opinion of their local political bosses. So far the regional
leaders have been divided in their support for Chernomyrdin, with a
significant bloc emerging on Thursday that called for Yeltsin to
submit another nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Before heading to the lower house on Friday afternoon,
Chernomyrdin is due to present what he has described as a radical
plan of action to extract Russia from its economic paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Fyodorov, an economic reformer whom Yeltsin installed
Wednesday as an acting deputy prime minister, has called for tight
currency controls, including a currency board, an experiment that
has proved successful in reining in wayward economies like
Argentina and Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
   Fyodorov met Thursday with a former fiance minister of
Argentina, Domingo Cavallo, an expert on currency boards who is
among the figures here to discuss how to rescue the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The ruble took another plunge Thursday, to 13.4 to the dollar on
electronic interbank trading, sending new shivers through a
financial system that is teetering on the edge of collapse.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin's address on Friday could end a week of guessing
about what he would do with the economy if he is confirmed as prime
minister. The lower house has pressed for a program that would
reinstate some elements of the state-dominated Soviet system,
including price controls and a new infusion of rubles to prop up
ailing industries.
</P>
<P>
   Fyodorov has vowed to block any new printing of rubles, which he
said would only lead to hyperinflation.
</P>
<P>
   In an about-face on Thursday, Vladimir Zhirinovsky, leader of an
ultranationalist party, announced that he would switch camps and
support Chernomyrdin's nomination. Zhirinovsky, known for his
extravagant behavior and last-minute reversals, said he still
shared the Communists' distaste for Chernomyrdin and his policies,
but feared serious consequences if the lower house continued to
block the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first vote was a purely political gesture,'' Zhirinovsky
said, adding that it was a ``form of protest.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with the defection of the 51 votes that Zhirinovsky
controls, the numbers in the lower house still do not add up to a
victory for Chernomyrdin, experts said. Speaker Gennady Seleznyov
said he expected no more than 150 of 450 members to support
Chernomyrdin, who won 94 in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist Party, the largest in the lower house, still
resolutely opposes Chernomyrdin, and several other smaller leftist
parties have also held firm, at least publicly. But some of those
have reportedly been negotiating with Chernomyrdin's team over
ministerial portfolios and may also be awaiting the recommendation
of the upper house.
</P>
<P>
   Seleznyov met Thursday with Valentin Yumachev, head of Yeltsin's
presidential administration, to discuss a new draft of the accord
of last weekend, submitted by the Kremlin with ``slight
corrections.'' The first accord would have redistributed some of
the president's considerable powers to the parliament, giving it a
greater role in naming and dismissing governments. The pact would
have also imposed a moratorium on the parliament's votes of no
confidence in the government and halted impeachment proceedings
against Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   In the event of a second defeat for Chernomyrdin, Yeltsin could
face one of the most significant decisions of his presidency, as
well as one of his last. Chernomyrdin, baron of the Russian gas
industry before serving for five years as prime minister, is a
major figure who has built a long list of IOU's over the years. His
candidacy has been backed by the financial and industrial tycoons,
and on Thursday he received a strong endorsement from his successor
at the gas monopoly, Gazprom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2033EDT &QL; 
