u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-BOS &LR;      09-03 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AIDES RELEASE NEW DETAILS ABOUT LEWINSKY RELATIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Foreshadowing President Clinton's defense against
the independent counsel's upcoming report to Congress, the
president's legal advisers are releasing new details of Clinton's
efforts to help Monica S. Lewinsky get a job and explanations of
what happened to gifts he gave the former intern.
</P>
<P>
   The advisers, speaking on condition of anonymity, hope releasing
the information will convince people Clinton did not obstruct
justice, an allegation they expect from Kenneth W. Starr's
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the advisers said, Clinton sought to help Lewinsky
get a job in July 1997, five months after aides now say Clinton
ended a sexual relationship with her. At one point, according to
advisers, Clinton asked whether Lewinsky might fit into a job at
the Old Executive Office Building, next to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   To some people, such questions would be interpreted as a
presidential order, suggesting Clinton may have been obstructing
justice by trying to get Lewinsky a job to keep her quiet. But,
Clinton's advisers said Thursday, Lewinsky was so distrusted by
some top White House officials that no job was offered.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky felt abandoned after failing to land a job at or next
to the White House, Clinton advisers said, and her anger toward
Clinton and others was soon recorded in secretly taped
conversations with Linda R. Tripp, followed by the revelation of
the sexual affair.
</P>
<P>
   This, at least, is the scenario presented by advisers close to
Clinton and familiar with his grand jury testimony on Aug. 17. The
advisers provided a series of details about how the relationship
between Clinton and Lewinsky ended and what Clinton did to help
Lewinsky deal with the aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advisers provided these details Thursday because they
believe the actions show the president did not push his aides to
rehire Lewinsky or get her a job recommendation after his initial
request was rebuffed. Clinton's advisers said this shows the
president did not try to obstruct justice by getting her a job in
exchange for her silence.
</P>
<P>
   But to Starr and his prosecutors, the same set of events may be
viewed differently. To prosecutors, the revelations that Clinton
took even more steps to help Lewinsky get a job than has been
previously acknowledged might show the depth of the president's
personal efforts to help the intern and thus perhaps keep her
quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advisers say a physical relationship between Clinton
and Lewinsky began around November 1995, continued after Lewinsky
was transferred to the Pentagon in April 1996 and ended in February
1997. That is earlier than has been stated in some reports.
</P>
<P>
   After February 1997, Lewinsky visited Clinton at the White House
at least once a month but did not have sexual relations, the
advisers said. Lewinsky told Clinton she considered her transfer to
the Pentagon a blot on her record and asked to be moved back to the
White House, the advisers said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton asked a senior personnel aide, Marsha Scott, whether
Lewinsky could get a job at the Old Executive Office Building, an
adviser said. But Scott rejected the idea after other aides told
her that Lewinsky was ``stalking'' the president, the adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   Former federal prosecutor Robert Ullmann of Boston said there is
a fine line between helping a friend and obstructing justice. ``A
prosecutor can argue that anything he did for a potential witness
had an improper motive,'' Ullmann said, ``but obviously people do
favors for people they know for all sorts of reasons that have
nothing to do with obstructing criminal investigations.'' Ullmann
said it might be difficult for Starr to prove Clinton was
obstructing justice in the July 1997 effort to get Lewinsky a job
because ``that is before she became a centerpiece of Starr's
case.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing months, as it became more likely that Paula Jones
would be allowed to bring her sexual harassment lawsuit against the
president, Clinton took other steps to try to help Lewinsky get a
job. He asked his friend Vernon E. Jordan Jr. to help Lewinsky and
also asked a White House official to consider writing a job
recommendation for her. Jordan did help Lewinsky get a job offer in
New York that was later rescinded. The White House official did not
make the job recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are also examining whether Clinton tried to conceal
the fact that he gave gifts to Lewinsky. Clinton's gifts included a
T-shirt from the Black Dog restaurant on Martha's Vineyard, a
photograph of the president and a beach wrap-around dress. The
gifts were subpoenaed last December by lawyers in the Jones case.
Starr is investigating whether Clinton instructed Lewinsky to
return the gifts to his secretary so Jones' lawyers couldn't obtain
them.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky reportedly testified to the grand jury that Clinton
told her to give the gifts to his secretary, Betty Currie. As
Lewinsky reportedly recalled it, Clinton said she didn't have to
turn over gifts that weren't in her possession. If true, that might
be evidence that Clinton tried to obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's advisers said Currie gave a different version,
telling the grand jury Lewinsky called her to come over and
retrieve the gifts, according to Clinton advisers.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, the advisers said, the gifts were modest
mementos Clinton presented to many White House workers. Moreover,
Clinton advisers said the president gave Lewinsky other gifts after
the subpoena in the Jones case was issued, thus undercutting
suggestions Clinton wanted to conceal the items.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is in the interest of Clinton advisers to say
Currie collected the gifts at Lewinsky's direction _ instead of
being asked by Clinton _ because that would help clear the
president of possibly obstructing justice. It may be impossible to
determine who actually said what until the transcripts of the
testimony by Clinton, Currie and Lewinsky are released. Still, the
efforts at ``spinning'' the explanation about the gifts shows that
Clinton aides are concerned it could become a central part of
Starr's case.
</P>
<P>
   But another source close to the investigation _ and who does not
believe Clinton's explanation _ said the president's advisers are
trying to taint Lewinsky's credibility. The source, who does not
want to be identified, questioned why Currie would have collected
the gifts from Lewinsky unless Clinton had told her to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advisers feel confident they have dismissed another
potential obstruction of justice allegation, the ``talking points''
that Lewinsky presented to Tripp, instructing her one-time friend
to say she knew of no improper relationship between Clinton and
Kathleen Willey, a White House volunteer who later said the
president made an improper advance toward her.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, many analysts suggested the talking points
were orchestrated at the White House, perhaps with Clinton's
knowledge. But, according to Clinton advisers, Lewinsky reportedly
told the grand jury she wrote them on her own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
