<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HOME-RUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPN, FOX PLAN EXTENSIVE HOME RUN COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It won't be all home runs all the time, but it will be pretty
close as both ESPN and Fox air this holiday weekend's record chase
by Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the lineup: Friday night ESPN airs the Reds-Cardinals
game at 8. Saturday Fox has Reds-Cardinals at 1 p.m. On Sunday, if
McGwire is at 60 home runs, Fox will air Reds-Cardinals at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   On Labor Day, ESPN airs the Cardinals-Cubs game at 2 p.m.
Tuesday night, Fox will show Cardinals-Cubs at 8 if either McGwire
or Chicago's Sammy Sosa has 60. For Wednesday, ESPN is still
debating whether to air the 7:30 Cardinals-Reds game.
</P>
<P>
   Both networks hastily rescheduled programming to enhance their
chances of showing the home run that breaks Roger Maris's all-time
record of 61, set in 1961. St. Louis slugger McGwire enters the
weekend with 59, Sosa with 56.
</P>
<P>
   While it's still debatable whether the home run chase is good
baseball, it clearly gets good ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge sports story,'' said ESPN spokesman Josh
Krulewitz. ``It's all happened so fast. We all knew McGwire was
creeping up to the record, but now he has hit the accelerator and
is actually on the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, McGwire hit his 55th home run on ESPN's Sunday
night telecast. The cable sports giant earned a 5.5 rating, its
highest this year. The 22 Sunday night games have averaged a 2.5.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's highest baseball rating ever was a 7.5 in 1995 when
Baltimore's Cal Ripken played in his 2,131st straight game,
breaking Lou Gehrig's record.
</P>
<P>
   Fox senior producer John ``Flip'' Filippelli is excited about
airing the historic homer. ``McGwire will get all of the
attention,'' said Filippelli. ``We will have several cameras
isolating him, all the reaction, all the sound bites _ everything
will be around McGwire.''
</P>
<P>
   Filippelli said that because the Reds and Cardinals are not in
playoff contention, Fox will focus on McGwire, McGwire, McGwire. On
Tuesday night, Filippelli said, more attention will be paid to Sosa
and the Cubs because they have a shot at the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The home run chase has added poignancy for Filippelli, who
received Maris's autograph as a 9-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maris was one of my favorite players,'' he said, ``and
breaking his record transcends the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8132 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HOMERS-COX     09-03 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HOMERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chasing history: McGwire bats for the ages
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On rare occasions, baseball braces for a great achievement,
knowing that it is on the verge of a memorable moment: Hank Aaron
circling the bases after breaking Babe Ruth's all-time home run
record; Cal Ripken circling Camden Yards after surpassing Lou
Gehrig's consecutive game streak.
</P>
<P>
   Another such moment is at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire returns to St. Louis _ a town that knows a little
about baseball tradition _ with 59 home runs this season, just two
away from what was thought to be the unbreakable record that Roger
Maris set 37 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The pursuit of Maris has breathed life into a sport that seemed
determined to kill itself this decade. At home or on the road, fans
jam the ballpark to see McGwire, showing up as early as three hours
before the game to watch him launch majestic blasts in batting
practice. He receives huge ovations from rival crowds, and even
opposing players seem awed by his performance.
</P>
<P>
   He's closing in on the record rapidly _ five home runs in his
last 12 at-bats _ and the excitement level in St. Louis is rising
just as fast.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning tonight, the Cardinals face the Cincinnati Reds for
three games, before the Chicago Cubs and Sammy Sosa, who has 56
homers, come in for two games Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   All five games at Busch Stadium, capacity 49,625, are sold out,
and scalpers are asking as much as $2,500 for a ticket. Even so,
that price would be a bargain for the fan who retrieves the
history-making ball: A home-shopping network has offered $250,000
for it.
</P>
<P>
   Media representatives are arriving in droves from around the
world. More than 1,200 media requests have been handled, about the
number that baseball receives for its All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Every boy in St. Louis seems to be wearing a Cardinals jersey
with McGwire's No. 25 on the back. Signs tracking McGwire's
home-run total hang from school buildings, tops of billboards and
mailboxes. McGwire memorabilia is hot, the hottest being a $20
T-shirt with his face on the front and the words ``The Quest for
62'' on the back.
</P>
<P>
   Outside town, aboard the Casino Queen on the Mississippi River,
26 television sets have been set up in the sports bar. Reception
has been a problem when the boat is cruising the river, but casino
officials plan to install a satellite dish.
</P>
<P>
   Fans in Atlanta will have a slightly more difficult time
following the chase over the Labor Day weekend than fans on that
gambling ship or elsewhere in the St. Louis area.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's game will be televised on ESPN at 8 p.m. Originally
the game was to be shown only in St. Louis, but ESPN negotiated
Thursday for the rights to carry it nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game will be televised to much of the nation on Fox
at 1 p.m., but Atlanta viewers will get the Braves-Mets game.
Expect cutaways to the Cards-Reds game whenever McGwire comes to
bat.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game will be televised only if McGwire is at 60 or 61
home runs, on Fox at 4 p.m., after the network's early NFL game. If
he's still at 59, the game will be at 2:1 p.m. and will not be
televised here.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's game will be televised on ESPN at 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The situation has left Fox sports executive director Ed Goren
dizzy. ``It's the most complicated equation I've ever faced,''
Goren said.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, perhaps the only one whose head isn't spinning from all
the hoopla, spent Thursday with his family. He appears eager to
break the record but cautions that he might not be the only one to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not look too far ahead,'' he said after hitting two home
runs Wednesday night in Florida. ``We have a whole month of the
season left. There's a great, great possibility that there's going
to be two or three guys (who break the record). I wouldn't rule out
Ken Griffey,'' who has 47 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is batting just .154 against the Reds this season, and
has been walked 11 times. Tonight, he will face Pete Harnisch, who
has given up one home run to McGwire in eight at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Harnisch, part of a pitching staff that has allowed the
second-most homers in the league _ 164 in 140 games _ certainly
doesn't want to be remembered as the pitcher who gave up the homer
to tie or beat Maris' mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the whole world's hoping we give up home runs to the
guy, but we've got jobs to do,'' Harnisch said. ``Hey, I'm as much
a fan as anyone else when I'm not pitching and I'm sitting home
watching TV. But when I'm out there, I've got a job to do, and I'm
trying to get him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
