<HEADER>
A8133 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HOMERS-WHY-COX     09-03 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HOMERS-WHY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Why are baseballs flying out of ballparks in great numbers?
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox New Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ As manager of the Chicago Cubs, Jim Riggleman
watches his own player, Sammy Sosa, with a smile. But when he
watches Mark McGwire against his team, he grimaces.
</P>
<P>
   He knows that on any pitch Sosa and McGwire can catapult a
baseball far into the great beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Why are baseballs flying out of ballparks in great numbers?
Already this season, 22 players have hit 30 or more home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last eight to 10 years, hitters have made a lot more
progress than pitchers,'' Riggleman told The Chicago Tribune.
``Hitters have gotten stronger and the parks have gotten smaller.
Hitters are recognizing the forkball now.''
</P>
<P>
   It was about 20 years ago that San Francisco manager Roger Craig
developed and pushed the split-finger fastball. Hitters, though,
have caught up with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitchers are going to have to come up with something to even
the score again,'' Riggleman said. ``Maybe they'll have to raise
the mound. All I know is that it has made it frustrating for a
manager. You think you have the game in hand and, boom, the ball is
over the fence.''
</P>
<P>
   Until 1996, the most players to hit 40 or more homers in the
same season was eight _ and that was 1961 when Maris hit his 61. It
also was an expansion year, just as this season is an expansion
year that thins out the pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, 12 players hit 40 or more home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago relief pitcher Rod Beck says he doesn't care if Mark
McGwire is taking andro or nitro or Cheerios, what he is doing is
amazing. But he makes another point. He says baseballs used to be
so soft he could move the cover with his fingers. Now you can use a
baseball to sink an 8-ball.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, the way McGwire is locked in, he probably
could use a pool stick and whack a baseball 450 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has 59 homers and it's the first couple of days in
September . . . and that's a joke,'' teammate Tom Lampkin says.
``This can't be happening. It's daily. It's nonstop. It's
continuous disbelief. We just laugh and shake our heads. There is
nothing you can say.''
</P>
<P>
   Stories abound about Roger Maris losing his hair and his
appetite during his chase of Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't the case for McGwire. They call him Big Red because
of his hair and he doffed his cap to show everybody his hair is
firmly in place and said, ``It's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day before he hit home runs Nos. 58 and 59, McGwire went
to lunch in Fort Lauderdale with Lampkin and performed a Ruthian
feat. Babe Ruth was known for his gastronomical abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Well, McGwire ate a steak, a teriyaki chicken breast, a bowl of
chicken noodle soup, rice pilaf, a baked potato, a plate of salad
and washed it all down with two large jugs of iced tea.
</P>
<P>
   If he had eaten another steak, he might have hit three homers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
