<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8135 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MARIS-MAIN-COX     09-03 1757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MARIS-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Saga of '61
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The lower deck in right field was jammed. So were the bleachers
in right center. But most of the rest of mammoth Yankee Stadium _
which then could hold 70,000 _ was empty as Roger Maris strode to
the plate to face Boston Red Sox rookie Tracy Stallard with one out
in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Only 23,154 were in attendance at ``the House that Ruth Built''
and most were not there on Oct. 1, 1961, to be a part of baseball
history. The real lure was a chance to hit the lottery. Buy a
ticket to the last game of the season and maybe catch a $5,000
home-run ball.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 61 is a magical number _ the most revered in sports.
Thirty-seven years ago, it carried an asterisk; it would count only
if someone could reach it in 154 completed games.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Ford Frick's ruling to protect Babe Ruth _ his old
friend _ had sapped much of the excitement out of the last few
games of the 1961 season. After a summer of suspense, anything now
would be almost anticlimactic. Officially, the race was over.
</P>
<P>
   Except to Maris. After all he had put up with, the 27-year-old
outfielder was determined not to let the season end without at
least one more home run.
</P>
<P>
   It was 2:42 p.m. on a bright Sunday in the Bronx. There was no
national TV coverage, but New Yorkers not interested in the
football Giants' game at Washington could tune into the Yankees on
WPIX (Channel 11). It was Phil Rizzuto's turn in the TV booth. He
always did the fourth inning, giving Mel Allen and Red Barber a
break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two balls, no strikes on Roger Maris. Here's the windup.
Fastball, hit deep to right! This could be it! Way back there! Holy
Cow, he did it! Sixty-one for Maris! Look at 'em fight for that
ball out there!''
</P>
<P>
   Sal Durante, a 19-year-old truck driver from Brooklyn, won the
battle. He received $5,000 as promised by a California restaurant
owner, who eventually gave the ball back to Maris.
</P>
<P>
   The player almost no one considered worthy of beating Ruth's 60
homers had hit 61 _ while not technically breaking the record. The
homer brought Maris _ booed on the road and sometimes even at home
_ vindication, if not happiness.
</P>
<P>
   As Maris circled the bases with his head down, his mind went
blank, he later said. But he wouldn't have had a catchy quote
anyway. Certainly not for the sportswriters who had hounded him for
months. He had to be pushed out of the dugout by his teammates to
wave his cap to the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know what I have to show for those 61 home runs?''
Maris was quoted as saying after he retired in 1968. ``Nothing.
Exactly nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball Maris hit for No. 61 is now in the National Baseball
Hall of Fame, as is his bat. Maris, who died in 1985 at age 51 of
lymphatic cancer, is not. The asterisk was not removed from his
record until six years after his death.
</P>
<P>
   `Wanted to be one of the guys'
</P>
<P>
   ``All I wanted was to be a good ballplayer, hit 25 or 30 homers,
drive in around 100 runs, hit .280 and help my club win pennants,''
Maris said. ``I just wanted to be one of the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Maris was the American League MVP in both 1960 and 1961, but
finished his injury-plagued 12-year career in 1968 with a .260
lifetime average. He had 275 home runs, meaning that he hit 22
percent of his career homers in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   No player seemed less suited for the national spotlight. He was
uncomfortable around strangers, quick to anger and unwilling to
compromise on anything. He just wanted to do his job and be left
alone by the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have no idea what it is like to put up with something like
this for two months,'' Maris said late in the 1961 season. ``People
around you all the time. You can't eat. You can't sleep. You can't
even think.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire feels for what Maris must have gone through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have got a lot of people rooting for us,'' McGwire said.
``He didn't. He had fans rooting against him. He had the media
rooting against him. Two strikes against you like that playing in
New York City isn't good.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming before ESPN, sports-talk radio and always-present
television cameras, the media onslaught that Maris faced was
minuscule compared with what McGwire and Sammy Sosa must deal with
today.
</P>
<P>
   Badgered by the press
</P>
<P>
   ``It was usually just 15 or 20 reporters with notepads, and no
TV cameras,'' remembers Leonard Koppett, who covered the Yankees
for the New York Post. ``You have more people covering a routine
ball game now. But Maris wasn't ready for the attention, and the
Yankees didn't do anything to help him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Fishel was the Yankees' public-relations director. Later, he
said he regretted not thinking of having mass press conferences at
scheduled times. In 1961, Maris was badgered for hours before and
after every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a lot easier for Maris today,'' Koppett
said.
</P>
<P>
   The friction between Maris and the media didn't intensify into a
war until the next season. But there is no question that few
members of the press corps wanted Ruth's record broken. The same
with most of the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there were five people in the country not
connected to Maris in some way that wanted him to do it,'' Koppett
said. ``If someone had to do it, the choice was Mickey Mantle. Not
Maris.''
</P>
<P>
   They were the M&AMP;M boys _ Mantle and Maris, Murder and Mayhem.
With Mantle batting behind him, Maris was not walked intentionally
a single time as their homer spree became the talk of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to boo me,'' Mantle recalled before his death.
``Then Roger came along, and I was the hero, and he was the one
they gave a hard time.''
</P>
<P>
   By late July, Maris had 40 homers and Mantle 38, as balls flew
out of American League ballparks in the first year of expansion to
10 teams and a 162-game schedule. Frick _ who had ghostwritten
articles for Ruth while a sportswriter _ made his ruling. Ruth's
record must be broken in 154 completed games. Anything done after
that would be listed separately with a ``distinctive mark.''
</P>
<P>
   The home-run race continued, and in Maris' hometown of Fargo,
N.D., TV sportscaster Bill Weaver, now 78, decided to put a Western
Union ticker in his office. Every night, Weaver and Maris' father,
Rudy, would huddle around the ticker and wait for news.
</P>
<P>
   Maris alone
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way news traveled in those days,'' Weaver said.
``The machine would sound, and the first thing that would come over
was `HR.' Then there would be some more ticking and it would say
``N.Y.' And then there would come an `M' and an `A,' and I would
look at Rudy, and he would look at me, and we would hold our
breaths. Would it be Maris or Mantle? When it said `Maris,' we
would jump around.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Weaver would break into NBC programing with a bulletin for
Maris' hometown fans.
</P>
<P>
   It was still a two-man battle on Sept. 10. Maris had 56 homers
and Mantle 53. But Mantle came down with a virus and soon was
knocked out of the race. Announcer Allen sent Mantle to a Manhattan
doctor noted for treating celebrities. The doctor gave Mantle a
shot, but the needle hit a bone by mistake. An infection developed
and Mantle missed most of the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Maris, a well-built 6-feet, 200 pounds, was alone to face the
pressure, which became worse and worse. He hit two homers in
Detroit to reach 58, but he was booed, got in an argument with a
fan and hid from the press after one game. Small patches of his
hair in the back of his crew cut were falling out.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he had one game left to beat Frick's edict _ and Ruth's
record. It was Sept. 20, and the Yankees were in Baltimore. Maris,
overcome with nerves, walked into manager Ralph Houk's office.
According to Houk, Maris was crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at the end of my rope,'' Maris reportedly told Houk. ``I
can't take it any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Calmed by Houk, Maris played against the Orioles and almost
caught the ghost of Ruth in the Babe's hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Maris hit No. 59, off Milt Pappas, in his second at-bat. Then in
the seventh inning, against reliever Dick Hall, he almost blasted
No. 60. But his long drive went foul. He batted once more in the
ninth, but grounded out weakly to first against knuckleballer Hoyt
Wilhelm, a future Hall of Famer.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure builds
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees won 4-2 before 21,032 to clinch first place. The
pennant race was over, and so was the homer race, as far as Frick
was concerned. The headlines read, New York Slugger Falls One Short
of Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   But the season still had eight games to go.
</P>
<P>
   Maris went homerless in a three-game series in Boston. ``I
though the pressure would be off me,'' Maris said. ``But I was
wrong. It is worse than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at Yankees Stadium, a relieved Maris hit No. 60 off Jack
Fisher of Baltimore before 19,401. He then took the next game off,
going shopping with his wife, who was visiting New York after
giving birth to the couple's fourth child earlier in the month.
</P>
<P>
   Three games against Boston remained. It took until the last one
for Maris to connect.
</P>
<P>
   Stallard, the victim, refuses to talk about the homer now. But
after the 1-0 loss, he said: ``I'm not going to lose a lot of sleep
over it. The guy hit a bunch of homers off other pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   `He was misunderstood'
</P>
<P>
   No. 61 made headlines around the country, but most papers played
the story on the sports front, not Page 1. None of the top sports
columnists was at the game, most taking the day off in preparation
for the World Series, which would begin the following Wednesday
against Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times ran a profile of Maris in its Man in the News
feature. It was headlined Angry King of Swat and quoted Maris as
saying, ``Even the Yankee clubhouse attendants think I'm tough to
live with. I guess they're right. I'm miffed most of the time,
regardless of how I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems Maris was loved only by his family, hometown fans and
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was misunderstood,'' said former Yankee second baseman
Bobby Richardson, who delivered the eulogy at Maris' funeral in
Fargo. ``He was a private man. He didn't take much to the acclaim
and adulation of the hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Maris is buried in Fargo's Holy Cross Catholic Cemetery, beneath
a diamond-shaped headstone. No. 9 is in pinstripes taking a mighty
left-handed swing. Each side of the bat is chiseled 61 _ for the
year and for his home-run total. At the base of the marker are the
words ``Against All Odds.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
