<HEADER>
A8136 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MARIS-MUSEUM-COX     09-03 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MARIS-MUSEUM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maris museum not on beaten path
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harried shoppers hurry past, most oblivious to the hometown
hero's life on display just outside their glance. It's hard to find
time for history when you have school clothes to buy.
</P>
<P>
   But as Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa get closer to 61 home runs,
more people are starting to stop and stare at the New York Yankees
uniform with No. 9 on the back, the historic baseballs or the
grainy black-and-white film.
</P>
<P>
   The West Acres shopping mall in Fargo, N.D., is home not only to
Sears and the Gap but also to the Roger Maris Museum.
</P>
<P>
   West Acres _ the largest mall within a 200-mile radius _ pulls
in 2 million shoppers a year. It isn't known how many have stopped
this summer at the museum, which really is a mamoth 72-foot-long
trophy case 10 feet high and 12 feet wide. There is no admission
charge, and the guest book is manned only part-time.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here are following the home-run race, but it really
hasn't had a dramatic effect on the museum,'' curator Jim
McLaughlin, 73, said. ``Folks here kinda take it for granted, and
we're too far out of the way to get many tourists. But we do get a
few. We've had people come from Chicago and Denver just to see the
museum. And a farmer from Ohio who was here for a show recently
passed up his tour to come over and spend some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Maris spent only 11 of his 51 years living in Fargo, which is
just across the Red River from Minnesota. But he went to high
school in the city of 70,000, played his first minor-league season
here and always considered it home.
</P>
<P>
   Maris, who lived in Gainesville, Fla., after he retired, was
approached about a museum while attending the 1983 American Legion
World Series in Fargo. At first, he was against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want that much attention,'' McLauglin said. ``But
Moose Skowron, one of his old Yankees teammates, was with him and
thought it was a great idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Maris relented, but with two conditions: The memorabilia had to
be placed where people could easily see them, and no admission
could be charged.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin and Bob Smith, a longtime family friend, flew to
Gainesville and brought back more than 100 items in a rented
U-Haul. The museum was dedicated on June 23, 1984. A year later
Maris was dead, a victim of lymphatic cancer.
</P>
<P>
   There are now 160 items on display in the museum _ including
Maris' high school football uniform, photographs with presidents
Truman, Kennedy, Reagan and Ford, and the Hickok Belt, awarded
Maris as the athlete of the year in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   But the highlights of the museum for most visitors are the
home-run balls and the film narrated by Mel Allen that captures
each Ballantine Blast from 50 through 61.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the 11 home run balls are in the museum. Missing is No.
61 _ which is in the National Baseball Hall of Fame at Cooperstown,
N.Y., along with Maris' bat _ and No. 59.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger's story was that the fellow who caught No. 59 in
Baltimore owned a meat market,'' McLaughlin said. ``He told Roger
he would give it to him if he came to his store. Then the fellow
said he could have it for $2,500. Roger left. He didn't think it
was worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
