<HEADER>
A8137 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MARIS-NINE-COX     09-03 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MARIS-NINE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nine things you probably didn't know about Roger Maris
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1
</P>
<P>
   Name change
</P>
<P>
   He was born Roger Eugene Maras _ not Maris. The spelling was
officially changed by the family in 1955, after Roger had played
three years in the minors. Roger's father, Rudy, was tired of going
to games and hearing fans and opposing players deride his son as
Mar-ass. Asked later in a questionnaire about why his name was
changed, Maris replied: ``Immaterial.''
</P>
<P>
   2
</P>
<P>
   Almost a Sooner
</P>
<P>
   Maris was a standout high school football player at Shanley
Catholic in Fargo, N.D., and was offered a scholarship by coach Bud
Wilkinson to play at Oklahoma. But Maris, who set a national record
in 1951 with four kickoff returns for touchdowns in one game,
lasted only a few days in Oklahoma. ``I wasn't cut out for
school,'' he said later.
</P>
<P>
   3
</P>
<P>
   Housemates
</P>
<P>
   Some columnists had them feuding, but Maris and Mickey Mantle
actually lived together during the 1961 season. They shared a
modest apartment in Queens with fellow outfielder Bob Cerv, while
their families remained in Kansas City and Dallas, respectively.
Maris regularly cooked breakfast for his housemates.
</P>
<P>
   4
</P>
<P>
   Short porch
</P>
<P>
   It was only 296 feet down the right-field line at old Yankee
Stadium, and Maris, a left-handed batter, was a dead pull hitter.
But 31 of his 61 homers were hit on the road.
</P>
<P>
   5
</P>
<P>
   Batting order
</P>
<P>
   Maris hit fourth _ behind Mantle _ in 1960, his first year with
the Yankees. But Ralph Houk switched the order when he became
manager in 1961. Maris drew 90 walks in '61, none intentional. Babe
Ruth had Lou Gehrig batting behind him in 1927.
</P>
<P>
   6
</P>
<P>
   Rainout
</P>
<P>
   Maris actually hit 62 homers in 1961. But he lost one when an
early-season game at Baltimore was rained out. Mantle had homered
in the same game.
</P>
<P>
   7
</P>
<P>
   At-bats
</P>
<P>
   Although his team played eight fewer games, Babe Ruth had almost
as many plate appearances when he hit 60 homers in 1927 as Maris
did in 1961. Ruth came to bat 678 times; Maris 684. The 1927 and
'61 teams both played tie games.
</P>
<P>
   8
</P>
<P>
   Asterisk
</P>
<P>
   In his ``asterisk ruling,'' commissioner Ford Frick declared
that Ruth's home-run record had to be broken in 154 games _ the
length of the American League schedule until 1961. However, Maris'
61 never really carried an asterisk. Both Maris and Ruth were
listed in the record books until 1991, when commissioner Fay
Vincent ruled that only Maris' record stood.
</P>
<P>
   9
</P>
<P>
   Numbers
</P>
<P>
   Maris boycotted Yankee Stadium after his trade to St. Louis but
relented in the early 1980s. His No. 9 was retired on Oldtimers'
Day in 1984 and a plaque unveiled in the stadium's monument park.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
