<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8138 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ROGSON-COX     09-03 0213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROGSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maris' son has mixed feelings
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kevin Maris was 13 months old when his father, Roger, hit No.
61, and he has spent a lifetime living with the record. Naturally,
he'll be sad when the mark falls, he said, but glad that his dad is
finally geting some of the recognition he deserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's finally getting his due,'' said Kevin, baseball coach at
Oak Hall School near Gainesville, Fla. ``It's really helped boost
him in the light of a new generation of kids that didn't really
understand who Roger Maris was and what he accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin, the third of six children, drove 5 1/2 hours to Atlanta
in August to meet Mark McGwire when the Cardinals were playing the
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely mixed emotions,'' said Kevin, 38. ``I think
anytime anybody sets a record ... they don't want to see the record
just gone. I think they'd be lying if they told you different. Even
if it is broken, dad will still be American League record-holder.''
</P>
<P>
   And if his father were alive?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's enjoying every bit of it,'' Kevin said. ``I'm
sure he's watching every swing from up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8139 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-MAIN-COX     09-03 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons' biggest woe is poor attendance
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jessie Tuggle, who has been around longer than any other current
Atlanta Falcon, has seen a lot in his 11 seasons. But two things at
least he's never witnessed: a Falcons' victory in the road-opener
and a win at Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   So when Tuggle and his teammates line up to play the Panthers
Sunday in Ericsson Stadium, the middle linebacker will be chasing
down a couple personal demons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize it had been 12 years since we won one (a
31-10 win at New Orleans in 1986); that's kind of amazing,'' said
Tuggle, who is 0-11 in road openers, beginning with his rookie
season in '87. ``All I really remember is a lot of them (for a
total of five) were in Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   But as season-openers go, this one is about far more important
matters than snapping that ugly streak, or the one that has seen
the Falcons lose all three games played in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons franchise lost between $8 million and $10 million
last season, when their second straight miserable start _ 1-7,
after an 0-8 mark in 1996 _ doomed the team in the eyes of fans,
who stayed away by the tens of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta sold an average of 48,003 ticket per game last year,
ranking 28th out of 30 NFL teams, ahead of only Tennessee and
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the worst of it.
</P>
<P>
   An average of 39,841 bothered showing up, meaning that 8,162 _
17 percent _ had tickets each week but found another way to spend
their time.
</P>
<P>
   At least this game can be seen on television (Fox, Channel 5)
unlike all of those home games, which have been blacked out locally
for the past two-and-a-half years.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a chance to make a very important impression on
potential paying customers. The Falcons have sold about 42,000
tickets for the Sept. 13 home-opener at Philadelphia, some 30,000
of them season tickets, down from 31,219 last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Dome's capacity is 71,228, and team president Taylor
Smith said the Falcons need to sell an average of ``about 55,000''
tickets to begin thinking about black ink after two years of red
ink.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is huge,'' said Rob Jackson, vice president of
marketing &AMP; sales. ``It's important for fans to see the
improvements (head coach) Dan Reeves has made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more than 5,000 decisions away from selling that Dome
out, because we know that most of those decisions (are) going to be
almost four tickets per decision. We've got to get these casual
fans interested in our product, and it's a 3 1/2-hour commercial
every time we're on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   History says it will be a hard sell. The Falcons have had just
seven winning seasons in 32, and 13 of the last 15 seasons have
been below .500. Although they're 16-16 in season-openers, home or
away, the Falcons are 9-22-1 in all road-openers.
</P>
<P>
   After their miserable start last season, the Falcons won six of
eight and hope to build on that finish.
</P>
<P>
   Since the NFL went to a 16-game schedule in 1978, of the 269
teams that lost opening games, 209 (77.7 percent) did not make the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking to have a winning record, and make the
playoffs, that shows you how important winning the opening game is,
particularly against an (NFC West) division opponent,'' Reeves
said. ``We're trying to win fans, so it's certainly important for
us to start as best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Even players realize that this game is big for several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a lot of people watching, and if we win,
it will help the following week,'' wide receiver Terance Mathis
said. ``And not only do we (at least) need to win in the last
seconds, we need to go out there and have a great performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you win a game on the road decisively, people say,
'What's this team about?' and maybe they'll come watch. If you
pound on them on the road, there's no question you're a good
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor Smith knows the Falcons are facing an uphill battle, one
made more difficult because many of metro Atlanta's 3 million
residents are not natives. The team's track record also has created
a deeply rooted pessimism about the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's deserved, because we haven't been a consistent
winner,'' Smith said. ``It's a great market, a great city to be in,
but because of our history, we've put ourselves in this position.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to be successful, we have to build the fan base. There
are a lot of people who have not been won over, the million or so
people who have moved to Atlanta the past 10 years. And a lot of
others are skeptics, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are guaranteed just $4 million per year in Dome
revenue, a number that goes up only when stadium revenues go past a
certain point. In comparison, the Dallas Cowboys get $40 million in
stadium revenue.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Falcons' slice of the pie from the NFL's new TV
deal figures to increase quite a bit, from about $42 million last
year to an average of about $73 million over the next eight years,
the salary cap likewise took a big jump this season, pushing
payroll up by more than $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are trying hard to change their image, and generate
money through game-day revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and his staff have worked out corporate sponsorships
with Ingles supermarkets, Georgia Power Co., Delta Air Lines,
Arby's, Sprint, Reebok, among others. They're helping foot the bill
for increased and upbeat advertising and promotion, and some of the
companies are buying tickets by the thousands for some games.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the emphasis is the team's new radio contract with
Jacor Communications, which has more than 100 stations around
Georgia, and with WAGA/Channel 5.
</P>
<P>
   But image isn't everything. It won't matter that the Falcons
have the lowest average ticket price in the NFL at $32.15 if the
product isn't very good. Getting that family or that group of four
to spend what is calculated to be an average of $185 per foursome
on parking, tickets, beer, soft drinks, souvenirs and a program is
in large measure out of Jackson's hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we see it, we have different layers of fans,'' he said.
``The die-hards who are going to be at the Dome all the time, fans
who will go to a few games and the casual fans, those who might
listen on the radio or watch on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we've got that casual fan out there who's not going to
stay home from Stone Mountain Park; he's going to cut the grass, go
picnicking, ride his bike or something. We've got to get these
casual fans interested in our product. And if we play well,
especially on TV, that's very big.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
