<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8142 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-VICTIMS-ART-2ND     09-03 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-VICTIMS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: in Geneva. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two officials with UNICEF were on the flight. Yves de Roussan, a
Canadian, worked with adolescents who were abandoned or ran afoul
of the law and was UNICEF's regional adviser for Central and
Eastern Europe. Ingrid Acevedo, 32, an American who was director of
public relations for UNICEF's U.S. National Committee, was on her
way to attend a meeting to plan for an annual communications
workshop.
</P>
<P>
   As an expression of mourning, all 185 flags of the U.N.'s member
states were taken down Thursday at the U.N. complex perched along
the East River in midtown Manhattan. The blue and white U.N. flag
was lowered to half-staff in both New York and in Geneva. A
memorial service was planned in Geneva for Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The plane had its share of chronic fliers. It was small wonder
that Norman Scoular was on a plane flight Wednesday night. Last
year, in carrying out the demands of business, he spent 337 nights
in hotel rooms. Scoular, 45, a Scottish-born resident of
Manchester, England, was the chief executive of Sylvania Lighting
International, which had been recently acquired by SLI Inc. of
Canton, Mass., and of which he had become chief operating officer.
After meeting with SLI officials, he had boarded Flight 111 to go
to Geneva to shut down an office there.
</P>
<P>
   Don Scheer was a 49-year-old biochemist from Norfolk, Mass., who
journeyed the globe promoting his discoveries. He was in fact
tiring of the travel and Tuesday night told his brother, Jerry,
that after one more trip to Europe to tout a product he designed to
separate DNA strands, he was going to sink into his couch, flick on
his 35-inch television and scream his lungs out for the Cleveland
Indians, the team he loved. Scheer took Flight 111 with his wife,
Diane. He was going to Budapest and then planned to join her in
Greece for a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought the Indians stunk and weren't going anywhere, but
that was his team,'' said Jerry Scheer, laughing for a minute as he
remembered that last conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved sports,'' Jerry Scheer said. ``We talked about
college football coming up. We talked how on Thanksgiving we were
going to watch three football games in a row. And then I told him,
``Have a safe trip.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Brookhaven National Laboratory in Upton, N.Y., said that it
lost both a physicist and a guest researcher in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Klaus Kinder-Geiger, 36, a German citizen who was an associate
theoretical physicist at the laboratory, was on his way to Trento,
Italy, where he was to speak at a physics workshop. He then planned
to continue his work at a particle physics laboratory in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   Per Spanne, 53, a Swedish citizen, was a guest researcher at
Brookhaven's Synchrotron Light Source facility. His career was
rooted in finding new ways to use X-rays to diagnose disease and
for high-resolution imaging of objects. He helped pioneer a
technique known as phase-contrast microtomography that allows
detailed images of the interior of solid objects.
</P>
<P>
   As is always true with international flights, even in the last
gasps of summer, some of the passengers were bound for pleasure.
John Mortimer, 75, a former executive of The New York Times, had
boarded the flight with his wife, Hilda, 69, on their way to a
vacation in the south of France. Mortimer had joined The Times in
1965 as the paper's industrial relations director and held several
personnel and industrial relations positions before, in 1982, being
named assistant to the president of New York Times Co. He retired
at the end of 1983. Mrs. Mortimer was on the staff of various
non-profit organizations engaged in education exchange and other
international issues. They lived in Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Tara Nelson was on Flight 111 to carry out a good deed and for
love. She was to meet her boyfriend, Edward Fierastale, in Geneva.
They were then traveling to Grenoble, where he was going to propose
to her and she was going to help her sister, Judy, nine months
pregnant, give birth.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nelson, 35, was a naturopathic doctor who spurned drugs in
favor of natural agencies like herbs and sunshine. She recently
closed her practice in Mystic, Conn., and was about to open an
office in Manhattan, where her parents live. ``You couldn't get an
appointment with Tara,'' said her mother, Sheila, who was in tears.
``It would take six months. She was so successful. And she met her
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Disaster inevitably has its other side, those individuals whose
moments of vacillation saved their lives. Marc Rosset, 27, the
Swiss tennis player, told reporters at the U.S. Open that he was
booked on the doomed Flight 111 after his first-round defeat forced
his early departure from the tournament. Not long before he was due
at the airport, he said he chose to stay one more day to get in
some practice with the top-level hitting partners available at the
tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
