<SLUG> BC-CRASH-FAMILIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK OFFICIALS LAUD AIRLINES' HANDLING OF CRASH AFTERMATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CRASH-RDP, CRASH-SCENE, CRASH-INQUIRY, CRASH-VICTIMS,
CRASH-OBIT-MANN and CRASH-OBIT-CLEMENTS-MANN)  
(Eds: This top will be followed by a 500-wd. add) 
(js) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As relatives of passengers aboard Swissair Flight 111
filed into the Ramada Plaza Hotel at John F. Kennedy Airport
Thursday and huddled in a private conference room to wrestle with
their grief, the scene carried poignant echoes of July 1996, when
families reeling from the crash of Trans World Airlines Flight 800
gathered under the same roof.
</P>
<P>
   There was a similar sense of astonishment over what had
happened. There was a similar hunger to know how and why.
</P>
<P>
   But what appeared to be missing, at least for now, was the
rancor. For while TWA drew fury from some relatives and politicians
for taking too long to confirm Flight 800's passenger list and not
tending aggressively enough to families' needs, Swissair and Delta,
the U.S. carrier through which some passengers had booked their
tickets, seemed intent on avoiding those charges.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Hauer, director of the mayor's Office of Emergency
Management, said there was ``no comparison'' between the actions of
Swissair and Delta and those of TWA two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an extraordinary amount of care and attention
paid to the details, which can make a horrendous situation that
much more horrendous,'' Hauer said Thursday. ``I've seen questions
get answered, and I've seen needs get met quickly, efficiently and
with great compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who stormed television news programs in
1996 to attack TWA, offered Swissair and Delta nothing but praise
at a press conference early Thursday evening at the Ramada.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines have handled this exceptionally well from the
beginning,'' the mayor said. ``Not only did they have plenty of
people, but they had people trained to know how to deal with this
kind of situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
