<SLUG> BC-FUNDRAISING-775(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO RENEWS INQUIRY INTO ISSUE ADS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON and JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After two years of rejecting calls for an outside
investigation of spending by the 1996 Clinton-Gore campaign,
Attorney General Janet Reno has seized on a Federal Election
Commission audit to reopen the Justice Department's review of
whether an independent prosecutor should examine the issue.
</P>
<P>
   A summary of the findings of FEC field auditors, subpoenaed by
the Justice Department, strongly questions the legality of a
multimillion advertising campaign underwritten by the Democratic
National Committee in 1996 that indirectly helped the Clinton-Gore
campaign, government officials said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The summary memorandum grew out of a routine financial review of
the 1996 presidential election that is due to be completed by the
end of the year. The memo concluded that so-called party ``issue
ads'' paid for by the DNC were really thinly veiled Clinton-Gore
re-election ads and thus violated campaign spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   If Reno decides to proceed with an outside inquiry after a
90-day preliminary review, President Clinton could be a pivotal
subject because he was deeply involved in the ad campaign. He
approved scripts for the ads and discussed the ads with his
political consultants. A former political adviser, Dick Morris, the
architect of the advertising campaign, called the president the
``day-to-day operational director of our TV-ad campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, James Kennedy, a White House spokesman, called the
use of the issue ads ``entirely legal and appropriate.'' Kennedy
emphasized that the ads were ``cleared by legal counsel'' and did
not violate campaign spending limits. ``We are confident that, at
the end of its review, the Justice Department will arrive at a fair
conclusion based on the facts and the law,'' Kennedy said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Clinton's lawyer, David Kendall, met with Reno's
advisers to persuade the Justice Department to postpone a decision
on the issue until the preliminary audit findings are reviewed by
the election commission, the officials said. He is said to have
also urged Justice Department officials to keep the focus of the
inquiry on the campaign instead of Clinton. On Thursday, Kendall
would not discuss the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   According to lawyers who have seen the FEC memo, the auditors
concluded that the Democratic issue ads contained electioneering
messages that could have violated federal election laws. Issue ads
are supposed to be generic party messages, not appeals for specific
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The auditors also found that the issue ads paid for by the DNC
should be counted as contributions to the Clinton-Gore campaign. If
the auditors' conclusions are upheld by the FEC, the Clinton-Gore
campaign could be sanctioned and fined for exceeding the spending
limits that apply to publicly funded campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's aides expect that she will use the auditors' conclusions
to advance to a 90-day preliminary investigation, a step that could
lead to appointment of an independent prosecutor, the officials
said. That decision, which is expected next week, would represent a
stark reversal for the attorney general, who has stated
emphatically on three separate occasions that the Justice
Department's investigations into the ads uncovered no evidence of
any crime.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent days, Reno has appeared to soften in her resolve
to avoid an outside inquiry into campaign finance issues. Within
the last week, she has ordered two 90-day inquiries, one into Vice
President Al Gore's statements about his telephone solicitations
from the White House and another intotestimony to a Senate
committee by Harold Ickes, a presidential adviser, about White
House involvement with the Teamsters union.
</P>
<P>
   An independent counsel's inquiry into the issue ads, however, is
potentially far broader than those likely to emerge from the Gore
or Ickes matters, because it goes to the heart of the financing of
the 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials said on Thursday that despite
Reno's past unwillingness to invoke the independent counsel
statute, she has not altered her interpretation of the law. In
July, when Reno appeared before the Senate Judiciary Committee, she
defined what appeared to be a narrow approach to applying the
independent counsel law to violations of federal election law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law governing these allegations is far from clear and it
is impossible to conclude on what we know that anyone could have
violated it knowingly and willfully,'' Reno said. ``At the same
time, the FEC is pursuing this and if they determine that there is
evidence, they will refer it to us and if it reflects on a covered
person and is specific and credible with respect to a covered
person, I will trigger the act.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to her past refusals to refer the Democratic issue
ads to an independent prosecutor, Reno quickly seized on the
auditors' memo even before the FEC itself reached any conclusion on
the matter. The FEC commissioners have not yet reviewed the final
1996 audit, and the Clinton-Gore campaign has only recently
submitted its response challenging the auditors' conclusions. In
the past, the commissioners have sometimes rejected the conclusions
of the auditors. The commission itself has also lost some court
battles in attempts to restrict issue advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Justice Department's focus appears to be on the
Democrats, election commission auditors have also questioned the
legality of issue ads paid for by the Republican National Committee
that benefited the campaign of Bob Dole, the party's 1996
presidential candidate. A lawyer for the Dole campaign declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Gore campaign defended the legality of the ads, as
did Democratic Party officials. In an interview, Joseph Sandler,
the DNC's general counsel, said, ``Our view is that the audit
report isn't evidence of anything.'' A spokeswoman for the election
commission declined to comment on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Sandler said he and Lyn Utrecht, the Clinton-Gore campaign's
general counsel, sat in on virtually all of the creative meetings
where the issue ads were designed to make sure that they did not
run afoul of election laws. Sometimes, the lawyers had heated
arguments with Morris and the creative team over how prominently
the president and his re-election message should be featured in the
party ads.
</P>
<P>
   Still, given the highly technical nature of federal election
regulations governing issue advertising, Sandler said ``It won't
shock me that lawyers would disagree'' about the legality of the ad
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The ads fall in a murky and relatively untested area of election
law. The political parties are allowed to underwrite advertising as
long as the ads do not expressly advocate the election or defeat of
specific candidates. While federal candidates must pay for their
own ads with contributions that are limited by the election laws,
the political parties can pay for a big portion of their
advertising with unlimited contributions from wealthy individuals,
corporations and labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints about the issue ads were among the first accusations
to emerge from the 1996 campaign. During the president's
re-election, Democrats poured $42 million of party funds into an
advertising blitz designed by Clinton and his campaign consultants.
</P>
<P>
   As Reno weighs her decision, the political parties have joined
in a lawsuit to expand the use of issue ads. Their lawsuit against
the Federal Election Commission, filed earlier this year by the
Republican National Committee and the Ohio Democratic Party, is
pending. Republicans have announced plans for a multimillion issue
ad campaign focusing on the scandals of the Clinton administration
and calling for more honesty in government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
