<SLUG> BC-BANKS-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL UNEXPECTEDLY DEFERS BANK REFORM BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the last minute Thursday, the Senate Banking
Committee postponed consideration of a bill to overhaul the
nation's banking laws as an unexpected dispute emerged over banking
services for low-income consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The vote on the bill was delayed for two weeks after an early
morning session in which Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, announced that
he would offer an amendment to weaken provisions in the bill
requiring new financial companies to provide services to low-income
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's proposal would have unraveled a carefully arranged set
of amendments worked out by banking, insurance, brokerage and
consumer groups to assure that the committee would pass the bill
and move it to the Senate floor. The measure would sweep away
Depression-era restrictions that separate banks from the insurance
and securities industries.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly two decades, Congress has debated whether to make it
easier for financial-services conglomerates to be created. In a
historic vote in May, the House approved a measure allowing for
those changes. Momentum had been building in Congress for the
Senate to take up the measure before adjourning in October instead
of forcing Congress to begin the process over again next year.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 90 financial-services lobbyists lined up outside
the Senate Banking Committee room and with the meeting about to
begin, word of the postponement began to spread through the
hallways.
</P>
<P>
   An hour after the meeting was to begin, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato,
R-N.Y., the chairman of the committee, issued a statement saying
that although the panel had ``made substantial progress in
resolving the major issues that have divided the financial services
community for years, we have not been able to resolve all of the
differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet lobbyists for banks, insurance companies and Wall Street
firms expressed confidence Thursday that the measure still had a
chance of passing, although few welcomed the delay. ``This delay
came as an enormous surprise to all of us,'' said Kenneth Guenther,
spokesman for the Independent Banks Association of America. ``But
the bill is not dead in any way. It still has surprising momentum
and bipartisan support.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the Gramm amendment would have eliminated
provisions that extend requirements of the Community Reinvestment
Act to new financial-services conglomerates _ even though
conglomerates like Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. and Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
have said they are willing to accept these rules, which require
banks to extend loans in areas in which they collect deposits.
Historically, Gramm has strongly opposed any requirements on banks
to provide services to low-income areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Gramm has heartfelt and strong objections to the CRA
act, and his views have been plain from the beginning,'' said Larry
Neal, a spokesman for the senator. Neal said that Gramm supported
the bill except for the expansion of the requirements for
low-income areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
