<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-UN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF U.N. INSPECTOR REPORTS MORE INTERFERENCE FROM IRAQ  
 (JT )
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The chief U.N. weapons inspector for Iraq said
Thursday that the government of Saddam Hussein had gone beyond its
decision to block surprise inspections and is now interfering with
routine monitoring operations.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector, Richard Butler, told the Security Council about
the deteriorating situation in Iraq as the United States and
Britain moved to keep comprehensive sanctions on the Iraqis until
they resume cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The two nations introduced a resolution Thursday condemning Iraq
and putting future sanctions reviews on hold. The measure is
expected to be voted on next week, probably after more negotiations
with Iraq's supporters, the Russians and Chinese. Security Council
members will study the draft resolution over the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Butler, chairman of the U.N. Special Commission, said Thursday
that he had been able to carry out only the increasingly
circumscribed activities that Iraq permitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is less than the whole monitoring program,'' he told
reporters. ``We are doing no disarmament work.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler told the Council that Iraq had blocked the commission on
three occasions since Aug. 5, when the Iraqis stopped allowing new
on-site inspections and said they would allow only long-term
surveillance and monitoring of previously designated sites.
</P>
<P>
   In the second week of August, Butler said, the Iraqis refused
information about and access to equipment used for test-launching
their Samoud missile, saying it was outside the mandate of the
commission, known as UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 16, inspectors were told that they could not return to a
previously visited site because it was a military area. The Iraqis
had threatened in the past to exclude all military sites, which
would in effect gut large parts of the inspection program.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 1, Iraqis barred inspectors from a place where missile
parts had been tagged and stored by UNSCOM for further observation.
Iraq said the area was not a ``declared site,'' a distinction that
appears to have been turned into a new reason for denying access.
</P>
<P>
   In all such cases, refusals of access raise suspicions that the
material sought may have been removed and possibly returned to use
in prohibited weapons programs. Iraq must abolish all chemical,
biological, nuclear and certain missile systems as well as the
means of producing them for sanctions to end. With no support for
military action to enforce Baghdad's compliance, however, Iraq and
the Security Council appear to be settling in for a long standoff,
or another mediation effort by the secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
   British and American diplomats are banking on the growth of what
one envoy called ``a rising tide'' against the Iraqis, who have
been confident for a year that sanctions will be gone by the end of
1998. The Russians and Chinese, however, have continued to argue
for including encouraging overtures to Iraq, hoping that rewards
for cooperation will budge Baghdad in ways that threats will not.
</P>
<P>
   The British and American resolution introduced Thursday makes a
gesture in that direction, saying the Council will ``respond
favorably to future progress made in the disarmament process.''
</P>
<P>
   But some diplomats say that this does not go far enough, and
that if the Council had rewarded Iraq in July by closing the
nuclear inspection file and switching to long-term monitoring, Iraq
might not have become so obstructive a month later.
</P>
<P>
   Some Chinese, Russian and other diplomats also favor a review of
relations with Iraq and possibly a restructuring of UNSCOM,
following Iraqi accusations that Butler and his inspectors have
overstepped their authority.
</P>
<P>
   The criticisms of UNSCOM and Butler were resurrected after an
American inspector, William Scott Ritter Jr., resigned from the
commission, accusing the Security Council and Secretary-General
Kofi Annan of giving ground to the Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Richardson, the U.S. representative, said in an interview
on Monday before accompanying President Clinton to Moscow, where
Iraq was discussed among aides from both sides, that he saw no
likelihood of changes in UNSCOM, especially at the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Butler is safe because of his strong relationship with the
secretary-general,'' Richardson said. ``It's in the best interests
of the Security Council and the U.N. to keep such a credible
independent force like Butler doing his job. I think that despite
this latest scuffle, Butler has improved his standing with other
Security Council members besides Britain and the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said Annan has been much more supportive of Butler
behind the scenes than many believe to be the case.
</P>
<P>
   The shift in American policy from threatening Iraq militarily to
building a diplomatic front against Baghdad in the Security Council
has been welcomed by some pivotal members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a blessing,'' said Antonio Monteiro, Portugal's
representative and the chairman of the Council's Iraq sanctions
committee. ``Unilateral actions are very dangerous. We have enough
anger in the world. Why do we want to provoke more gaps between us
in the Western world and the Arabs? If we can contain Iraq in a
reasonable way, and I believe we can, is that not better than using
force?''
</P>
<P>
   Monteiro and several other envoys said there is no nation that
wants to tolerate Iraqi defiance or allow Iraq to escape sanctions
unilaterally, despite all its grievances.
</P>
<P>
   ``First they comply,'' Monteiro said of the Iraqis. ``Then we
see what we can do to take them on board.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
