<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSAIR-CRASH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKERS SEARCH FOR VICTIMS OF SWISSAIR CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEGGYS COVE, Nova Scotia _ The reek of jet fuel suffused the
salt spray Thursday as scores of search vessels, from Canadian
naval frigates to small fishing boats, criss-crossed dozens of
square miles of sea blanketed with the detritus of disaster _ a
child's ``Hello Kitty'' daypack, bits of fuselage, and corpses
rolling in the heavy swell.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers aboard Swissair Flight 111 apparently spent their
final terrifying minutes Wednesday night struggling into survival
gear while crew members gave safety instructions and the pilot made
a desperate descent toward the safety of Halifax International
Airport after reporting smoke on board.
</P>
<P>
   The McDonnell-Douglas MD-11 jet smashed into the cold Atlantic
about five miles south of this picturesque fishing village, killing
all 229 people aboard the flight bound for Geneva from New York's
John F. Kennedy International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   According to Canadian investigators, the crash occurred 16 long
minutes after the pilot radioed the first distress call reporting
smoke in the cabin and passengers were told to ready themselves for
an emergency landing.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the several dozen bodies retrieved from the sea Thursday
were clad in life jackets. Most were so badly mutilated, however,
that it was impossible to determine whether they had suffered burns
or other injuries that might suggest an explosion.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the crash remained a mystery, although officials in
Ottawa and Washington were quick to downplay the possibility of a
terrorist bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our preliminary indications do not point toward terrorism or
some other criminal activity,'' said Jim Margolin, a spokesman for
the FBI, adding that the federal law enforcment agency had not
dispatched a team to Canada. Investigators are working on the scene
at New York's JFK airport, however.
</P>
<P>
   Searchers Thursday night had all but abandoned hope of finding
survivors. ``We are continuing to look, but the sea is cold, and
time is passing,'' said Commander Rick Town of the Canadian Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Vessels and aircraft continued to scour the sea in a massive
effort to locate the nearly 200 bodies still missing, but the
emphasis of the search was shifting to a ``technical search'' for
flight recorders and wreckage that might explain the horrific
crash.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of victims were Americans; Swissair reported that
136 passengers and one crew member were United States citizens. The
dead included Dr. Jonathan Mann, a former professor at Harvard's
School of Public Health and a pioneer in the fight against AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Swissair, an international airline with one of the world's best
safety records, refused to release passenger lists until all family
members were notified. In addition to the Americans, a spokesman
said, the dead include 41 Swiss nationals, 30 French citizens and a
number of other nationalities.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian search officials said it was impossible to give an
accurate count of bodies retrieved so far because searchers were
often finding only incomplete remains of humans torn apart by the
terrible impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scene is very grisly, very confusing,'' said
Lieutenant-Commander Glenn Chamberlain of Canada's Maritime
Atlantic Command, specifying only that ``dozens'' of bodies had
been taken aboard vessels.
</P>
<P>
   The effort was hampered by high waves and occasional rain
squalls, although visibility started improving around midday. Tides
and wind left debris spread across a wide swath of sea. The stench
of aviation fuel or the sight of torn bodies caused the eyes of
searchers to stream tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most terrible sight I've ever seen on the sea,''
said Craig Sanford, operator of a whale-watching boat that was
among the first vessels to reach the scene in the rain-lashed
blackness. ``There were bodies and pieces of people floating among
chunks of Styrofoam, cabin panels and luggage.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the blackness of early morning, Canadian rescue
helicopters dropped parachute flares whose eerie orange glow
coupled with the sweep of searchlights provided the only
illumination for the fishing boats, naval frigates, Coast Guard
craft, police vessels and even a Dutch cruise ship that started
converging on the sea site within an hour of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out full of hope for survivors,'' said Major Donald
LeBlanc, pilot of a military Sea Stallion chopper that coursed over
the wreckage for hours before dawn. ``We had night vision goggles,
and were popping flares, but there was nothing to see but the
debris scattered everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The doomed aircraft was cruising at an altitude of 33,000 feet
in Canadian airspace a little over an hour after taking off from
New York at 8:18 p.m. Eastern time when the pilot reported smoke in
the cockpit and urgently requested permission to reverse course and
head for Boston's Logan Airport, according to Canadian
transportation safety officials.
</P>
<P>
   But air controllers directed Captain Urs Zimmermann to head for
Halifax because it was closer. Vic Derden, the &UR;  &LR; Canadian
Transportation Safety Board's investigator in charge of the
probe, &UR;  &LR; was asked by a reporter if it was accurate that rerouting
the plane consumed ``four or five minutes.'' Derden replied,
``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Canadian air traffic controllers put the plane into a pattern to
dump its fuel. It was not clear whether fuel was jettisoned.
</P>
<P>
   Officials gave slightly conflicting time sequences, but the
plane apparently disappeared from radar view at 9:38 after
descending to 8,000 feet, where it was expected to dump over 200
tons of fuel in preparation for a crash landing. It hit the water a
few minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Peterson, a security guard working a late shift near Peggys
Cove, was monitoring air traffic on his scanner radio. He told the
Canadian Broadcasting Corporation that he heard what may have been
the pilot's last frantic message. ``He said he was dumping fuel.
Then he said, `We're going down,''' said Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft plunged into rough seas between 20 and 30 miles
short of the runway after making a howling passage over Nova
Scotia's Aspotogan Peninsula. The precise site of the crash was
still unknown Thursday night and floating wreckage was strewn
within a radius of about 15 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was banging something loud, you could just tell something
was awful wrong,'' said Linda Reed , describing the plane as
shrieking so low over her family's home in the coastal hamlet of
Blandford that ``the windows rattled and the roof shook like it was
being ripped off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple minutes later there came a sort of boom,'' she said.
``Then came only a silence.''
</P>
<P>
   For a few hours after the crash, there were persistent reports
of survivors, and Halifax's Queen Elizabeth II Hospital ordered
extra staff to stand by to prepare for an influx of injured.
</P>
<P>
   But the rumors were based on discovery of an empty life raft _
deflated and badly damaged _ and boat lights mistaken for rescue
beacons.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian officials will head the investigation into the crash
assisted by aviation safety investigators from the United States
and Switzerland. Forensic specialists from New England were also
headed for Nova Scotia to assist in the makeshift morgue at
Shearwater military base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will spare nothing in trying to discover all the reasons
for this tragedy,'' said Benoit Bouchard, chairman of the Canadian
Transportation Safety Board. ``We will be looking especially hard
at any possible lack of safety aspects that could have led to the
crash of Flight 111. Priority will be given to recovering the
aircraft's on-board flight recorders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we find any evidence of criminal wrongdoing, it will be
immediately directed to the RCMP,'' he said, referring to the Royal
Canadian Mounted Police.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian officials reported discovery of what appeared to be a
large section of fuselage resting in waters estimated to be 100
feet deep. Divers were reported ready to descend into the depths at
first light today as part of an investigation that could last
months.
</P>
<P>
   With its famous lighthouse, narrow harbor and brightly-painted
houses clinging like limpets to bare rocks rising from the sea,
Peggy's Cove is one of Atlantic Canada's most popular tourist
haunts. But Thursday the chartered buses and curious hordes were
replaced by media from across North America and Europe as the
village became command center for the recovery effort _ and a
drop-off point for vessels carrying grim cargo.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,500 people were involved in the search, including
the crews of two Canadian warships, Coast Guard and police vessels
and an extraordinary flotilla of fishing boats and pleasure craft
that took risks on seas heaving with wreckage. The energies
directed by fishermen and other volunteers did not flag even after
it became obvious there would be no miracles, no survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even after you accept that, `No, we aren't going to find any
one alive out there,' you just keep going,'' said fisherwoman Ellen
Haynes, as she retrieved from the water a stuffed toy animal, a
woman's pocketbook, and a folder full of what appeared to be family
photos. ``You want to see these belongings returned to loved ones.
It isn't much, maybe, but it's what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Anne Kornblut of the Globe staff contributed from Boston to
this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
