<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES NORTHERN IRELAND TO STAND BY PEACE PLAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARMAGH, Northern Ireland _ President Clinton came to the
spiritual heart of this troubled land Thursday to urge its people
to stand by peace even as they are tested with violence.
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand people attended a ``gathering for peace'' in
this historic city where St. Patrick built his stone church atop a
hill surrounded by lush green meadows and where Protestant churches
have added to the steepled skyline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for reminding us of one of life's most important
lessons, that is it never too late for a new beginning,'' Clinton
said to a cheering crowd after stops in Belfast, Omagh and Armagh.
``And remember, you will be tested again and again, but a God of
grace has given you a new beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, joined by British
Prime Minister Tony Blair and his wife, Cherie, earlier consoled
the victims and families at Omagh where an Aug. 15 explosion in the
city center left 28 dead and 330 wounded. It was the worst
terrorist incident in 30 years of the Troubles, a term used to
describe the terrorist campaign and the strife in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``By killing Catholics and Protestants, young and old, men,
women and children, even those about to be born ... it galvanized,
strengthened and humanized the impulse to peace,'' Clinton told the
victims.
</P>
<P>
   The president visited Northern Ireland for the second time in
three years to underscore his support for the Good Friday peace
plan that offers hope of a political end to the sectarian violence
between Catholics and Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   The pact, approved by voters in Northern Ireland and Ireland
this spring, recreates a Northern Ireland Assembly to give both
Unionists and Nationalists representation while also reaffirming
Northern Ireland as a part of the United Kingdom. The new
108-member assembly meets for the first time this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The democratic underpinning of this agreement is now beyond
doubt or question. It is there by the will of the people and it is
our job to see the will of the people done,'' Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrived to banner headlines proclaiming a new
development in which David Trimble, first minister of the new
Northern Ireland Assembly, will meet next week with Sinn Fein
leader Gerry Adams. The announcement came after Sinn Fein, the
political arm of the Irish Republican Army, issued a declaration
saying violence must end.
</P>
<P>
   Adams sat in the audience at Belfast's Waterfront Hall where
Clinton made his first stop on a daylong tour of Northern Ireland.
Clinton and Blair were joined by Trimble, a Protestant, and Seamus
Mallon, the Catholic deputy first minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. President, as first minister, I will speak to anyone who
has the good of Northern Ireland at heart. But, of course, no
democrat can tolerate coercive threats. But once we can speak in
freedom, once we are agreed our only weapons will be our words,
then there is nothing that cannot be said; there is nothing that
cannot be achieved,'' Trimble said.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble and others have wanted a tougher statement from Sinn
Fein. ``The path ahead is for true democrats only. And I cannot
reconcile seeking positions in government with a failure to
discharge responsibilities under the agreement to dismantle
terrorist organizations,'' Trimble said.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger, the U.S. national security adviser,
showed Clinton a copy of the newspaper highlighting next week's
meeting between Trimble and Adams as soon as the president stepped
off Air Force One after a flight from Moscow to Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the headline we wanted to see when we got here,''
Berger said. ``This is a very important step forward in terms of
the process of building peace.''
</P>
<P>
   In a private session between Clinton, Blair and the assembly
leaders, the president asked, ``What can I do to help?'' Clinton
had made a substantial political investment in the Northern Ireland
peace process, dispatching former Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell of Maine to help broker the deal and repeatedly nudging
the process along.
</P>
<P>
   Later in his public address to the assembly members, Clinton
said, ``Difficult, sometimes wrenching decisions lie ahead, but
they must be made. And because you have agreed to share
responsibilities, whenever possible you must try to act in concert,
not conflict; to overcome obstacles, not create them; to rise above
petty disputes, not fuel them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called on the assembly to ``decommission the weapons of
war,'' to form an executive council, to adopt a police force for
all people and bring an end to street justice and retaliations.
</P>
<P>
   There have been several deadly attacks since the peace accord
was voted into place, from the deaths of three young Catholic
brothers killed in a fire started by a bomb to the unprecedented
car bombing attack in Omagh.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be hard roads ahead. The terror in Omagh was not
the last bomb of the Troubles; it was the opening shot of a vicious
attack on the peace,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   At Omagh, the Clintons and Blairs met for more than an hour with
victims. After Clinton made a brief address to the families, he
talked to a 14-year-old girl blinded by the blast and her mother
who was working at the hospital as a radiologist the day of the
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said Clinton was clearly moved by the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The president and first lady as well as the Blairs also walked
down Market Street to view the devastation first hand. The car
bomb, set by extremists denounced by the IRA, destroyed surrounding
buildings on both sides of the street.
</P>
<P>
   The welcome in Northern Ireland proved a respite for Clinton
after a two-day summit with Russian President Boris Yeltsin that
seemed to accomplish little in a nation beset by tremendous
economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, Clinton's ideological kin, heaped praise upon the
president. ``I wish to say this to you: There is no president of
the United States of America that has done more for peace in
Northern Ireland than you,'' Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons later flew to Dublin where they will spend two days
before returning to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
