u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMS-GEPHARDT-600&AMP;ADD     09-03 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-GEPHARDT-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEPHARDT, IN NEW HAMPSHIRE, TRUMPETS PARTY'S ISSUES  
 (JT )
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZETTE ALVAREZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Trying to instill optimism about the November
elections, Rep. Dick Gephardt, the minority leader, arrived here
Thursday eager to snuff out talk of President Clinton's travails
with a rousing chorus of hard-core Democratic philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   The word scandal or the name Monica Lewinsky did not drop from
Gephardt's lips once in his series of speeches at fund-raisers and
at a senior citizen center here. Instead, Gephardt, who angered the
White House last week with comments about possible impeachment
proceedings, tried to galvanize voters around the one strategy that
Democrats believe could bolster their party, or at least soothe it,
as the fall campaign season kicks off.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to talk about the issues because the issues are
important in people's lives,'' Gephardt, D-Mo., told supporters of
Peter Flood, who is challenging Rep. John Sununu, a Republican, in
New Hampshire's 1st Congressional District here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we get our message across?'' Gephardt said. ``I believe we
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of his speeches Thursday took place, though, before a few
of his prominent counterparts in the Senate broke ranks with the
party leadership and denounced the president's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   On learning that Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut had
stopped just short of calling for Congress to censure the
president, but had excoriated him for ``immoral'' actions, Gephardt
seemed both bewildered and exasperated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we ought to get ahead of ourselves,'' he said.
``Let's not jump to conclusions. We need to deal with what's in
front of us. We'll take care of whatever comes, I hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gephardt rebuked the president for his relationship
with Ms. Lewinsky just last week in calling Clinton's actions
``wrong and reprehensible,'' the congressman quickly tempered his
public comments. He had received angry phone calls from some
Clinton supporters and Erskine Bowles, the White House chief of
staff. Gephardt said that in a weekend telephone conversation, he
and the president spoke cordially about issues.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Gephardt chose not to revisit the question of
Clinton's relationship with Ms. Lewinsky. He has said he believes
that the president's public admissions have been sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   But answering reporters' questions earlier in the day, Gephardt
did not shy away from reinforcing his beliefs that a House
impeachment inquiry should be conducted in a ``fair and objective
way,'' without ``jumping to conclusions.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt also had sharp words for Republican leaders who were
drafting the framework for the inquiry and the report from the
Whitewater independent counsel, Kenneth Starr. So far, Gephardt
said, there has been no cooperation, an assertion disputed by
Republicans. Among other things, Democrats on the Judiciary
Committee say they are awaiting approval for money to hire more
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't talk to us,'' Gephardt said. ``If they do this the
way they have done everything in the past three years, it will not
be nonpartisan.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example of the tension with Republicans, he cited the fact
that Abbe Lowell had yet to sign his contract to serve as minority
counsel because the Republicans had not yet approved the money for
it.
</P>
<P>
   And although Rep. Henry Hyde, the Illinois Republican who heads
the Judiciary Committee, has been praised as fair, and his lead
counsel, David Schippers, is a lifelong Democrat, Gephardt said he
was still concerned that the process could bog down in secrecy and
shenanigans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all has the appearance of being possibly bipartisan,'' he
said, ``but the proof is in the practice.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Here in New Hampshire, where he campaigned for his party's
presidential nomination in 1988 and is expected to revisit the
trail again as a candidate in 2000, Gephardt tried to focus on the
Democrats' bread and butter issues, like education, managed health
care and Social Security. In his speeches, he cheered Clinton's
agenda on programs like education.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' prospects in the polls this year are far from
certain, consultants and strategists say. In an election that
favored incumbents from the start, the president's troubles could
hamper the enthusiasm of Democratic voters and keep even greater
numbers of them home.
</P>
<P>
   Although Democrats say fund-raising efforts have not suffered,
Republicans assert that they may take as many as 20 seats in
November. And some Republican candidates and incumbents are already
using the Lewinsky matter to chip away at the competition, framing
it in terms of values and ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic candidates and supporters said they simply wished
that the whole matter could be put to rest. The president has
behaved badly, they said, but his presidential record should speak
for itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up believing I should look for the gold and iron in
everybody I came in contact with,'' Flood said, adding that he
would welcome a visit by the president. ``Clinton has a mother lode
of gold, only today it's his iron that's showing.''
</P>
<P>
   But one of Flood's supporter, Sharon Penasack, was decidedly
less upbeat about the political fallout surrounding Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's devastating,'' she said. ``I can see why any
politician wants to step away from this. I personally want to step
away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
