<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On Deck: New York Mets
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: Tonight at 7:40, Saturday at 1:15 p.m., Sunday and Monday
at 1:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   TV, radio: TBS will televise tonight and Sunday, Fox on Saturday
and Fox Sports South on Monday; WSB/750 AM will broadcast all four
games.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: Tonight, LHP Tom Glavine (18-5, 2.61
ERA; 10-4, 3.29 lifetime vs. Mets) vs. LHP Al Leiter (13-5, 2.47;
2-2, 2.12 lifetime vs. Braves); Saturday, RHP Kevin Millwood (14-8,
4.45; 1-0, 2.00) vs. RHP Bobby Jones (9-7, 4.14; 3-7, 5.38);
Sunday, RHP John Smoltz (13-3, 3.33; 8-7, 3.87) vs. RHP Rick Reed
(16-8, 3.27; 2-0, 3.89). Monday, LHP Denny Neagle (14-11, 3.69;
5-3, 4.05) vs. RHP Masato Yoshii (5-8, 3.91; 0-2, 8.39).
</P>
<P>
   Series history: The Mets lead the all-time series 201-199, but
the Braves have won all five meetings this season. ... Atlanta
closed the season's first half with a three-game sweep of the Mets
July 3-5 at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Mets leaders: Avg. _ John Olerud (.342). RBI _ Mike Piazza (93).
HR _ Piazza (28). SB _ Brian McRae (20). W _ Rick Reed (16). ERA _
Dennis Cook (2.10). SV _ John Franco (31).
</P>
<P>
   Quickly: The Mets are in the middle of the NL wild-card race,
one game behind the Cubs. Their Tuesday loss in San Diego dropped
the Mets out of the wild-card lead for the first time since Aug.
17. ... When they won four of their last six games to finish 5-4
against the Giants, Dodgers and Padres on a West Coast road trip,
it marked the Mets' first winning West Coast trip since 1994 and
fourth in 18 such trips in the '90s. With three homers in each of
their last two games, the Mets hit 15 homers on that trip. ...
Since being acquired from Cincinnati, OF Lenny Harris has five
homers in 39 at-bats. He previously had hit just 20 career homers
in 2,775 at-bats (1,162 games). Edgardo Alfonzo has hit a
career-high 15 homers, nine in the last 30 games. ... When John
Franco recorded his 31st save Wednesday, it was also the 390th of
his career, tying him with Dennis Eckersley for second on the
all-time save list, 88 behind career leader Lee Smith. ...Todd
Hundley was scheduled to catch his first game Thursday since
undergoing reconstructive elbow surgery last Sept. 26 _ but it was
with the Mets' Class AAA Norfolk affiliate. After missing the first
88 games of the season, Hundley was activated July 11, playing as
an outfielder. After several fielding misadventures in left,
Hundley declared the outfield experiment a failure. He went on the
disabled list Aug. 28 with a sore right elbow and began a rehab
assignment Aug. 31 with Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
