<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-TRECEIVERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech receivers battle inexperience
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Georgia Tech sophomore receiver Dez White was running a short
sideline pattern in a drill this preseason, one where he was
supposed to catch the ball and tap his feet for a few steps before
he got to the sideline. White caught the ball, started tapping and
somehow tripped over his feet and fell.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Rogers and Jon Muyres, who like White will start for the
first time at receiver on Saturday against Boston College, couldn't
help but laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, they wouldn't have.
</P>
<P>
   White was a freshman, nervous about his coaches' reactions.
Rogers and Muyres wouldn't even have been in the drill. Rogers was
working out with the running backs last year; Muyres was on the
defensive field as a free safety. But this year they could all
laugh, learn and move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a receiver, you go full speed,'' White said. ``If
you don't do everything right, you'll end up on your face.''
</P>
<P>
   In the practices since Harvey Middleton and Derrick Steagall
departed, along with their 3,930 receiving yards and 22 touchdowns,
Tech'sreceivers have been toughened by remarks and articles
referring to them as a question mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken so much flak,'' White said. ``It's made us grow
together.''
</P>
<P>
   For at least one more day, the three players might be the best
judges of each other:
</P>
<P>
   Best hands: Currently, it's a tossup, while Mike Sheridan, the
only returning receiver, is still out with a knee sprain.
</P>
<P>
   Fastest: Both Rogers and White have been clocked in the 4.3
range in the 40. Rogers said Muyres has deceptively good speed.
</P>
<P>
   The best moves off the line of scrimmage: White.
</P>
<P>
   The best moves after a catch: Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   In the best shape: Not Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was running (split end) one day I was out (with a sore
foot), running a bunch of deep cuts,'' Muyres said. ``He'd come
back in the huddle and bend over and say, `I've never felt like
this before.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I thought running backs did a lot of running,''
Rogers said. ``The receivers run more than any other guys on the
team. You've got to get in a different kind of shape.''
</P>
<P>
   The most experienced: White. He played 70 or 80 snaps at
receiver last year over a stretch of four or five games but only
one ball came his way. Still, White, who played mostly safety in
high school, has spent a year working with the receivers in
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in there every day (last year) worried about how
practice was going to come out,'' White said. ``Now, I'm just more
relaxed and determined.''
</P>
<P>
   The most improved: Muyres. He earned a starting spot after a
strong spring practice, making the conversion back to offense where
he played two years ago as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of practice, the trio of players are ready for a
real test.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time to get out there and show what we can do,''
Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
