<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GRAMBLING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Williams ready for season to get going
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doug Williams' demeanor is starting to change a little as he
moves closer to his place in college football history.
</P>
<P>
   When Williams leads Grambling University into Saturday's home
game against Alcorn State, he will coach his first game as the
successor to Eddie Robinson, college football's all-time winningest
coach. Williams, who coached at Morehouse College last season, has
been accommodating with all of the media requests and fan interest
leading up to the game, but he's ready to put all of it behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to get this first one over,'' said Williams who
returned to his alma mater eight months ago. ``The players are now
beginning to see a change in my demeanor. The volume of my voice
has changed. I'm getting less sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Tiger quarterback and Super Bowl MVP has been getting
three to four requests per day to appear on radio talk shows, and a
number of local and national writers have been in town on a daily
basis to witness the first preseason without Robinson since 1941.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand all of that, the interest in the changing of
the guard here,'' Williams said. ``But I've made sure that it
didn't interfere with practices. It hasn't been a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told our players that we can't get caught up in all the hype
because, when all of that is over, it's going to come down to how
well they performed on the field. That's what's going to really
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   In his effort to rebuild a tradition-rich program that has
fallen on hard times, Williams has tried to change the atmosphere
around a team that finished with back-to-back 3-8 records at the
end of Robinson's storied career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere now is more business-like,'' junior offensive
tackle Corey Bembry said. ``It's more competitive. You know that if
you don't work hard and prepare during the week, you aren't going
to play on Saturdays.'' How will the Williams' approach translate?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the only thing I can guarantee,'' Williams said, ``is
that we'll play hard for 60 minutes. We'll compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
