<HEADER>
A8167 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UGA-TACKLES-COX     09-03 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-TACKLES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia's terrors at tackle
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Athens _ When Georgia opens its season Saturday against Kent,
the Bulldogs will have a rookie quarterback, an inexperienced
receiving corps and a rebuilt offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Two things that won't change, however, are Georgia's anchors on
its offensive line _ senior bookends Matt Stinchcomb and Chris
Terry, perhaps the nation's best pair of tackles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say there might be a better tackle in the country, but I
don't believe there's two better tackles on one team,'' Georgia
coach Jim Donnan said.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-foot-6, 298-pounder from Parkview High, Stinchcomb played in
all 11 games as a freshman in '96 and earned his first career start
against Georgia Tech in the regular-season finale. He's started all
23 games since.
</P>
<P>
   Stinchcomb was rated the third-best tackle eligible for next
spring's NFL Draft in preseason grades by National Football
Scouting, Inc., one of two services used by pro clubs. Wisconsin's
Aaron Gibson, rated the second-best senior available for the draft,
and Florida's Zach Piller were the only tackles rated ahead of
Stinchcomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Stinchcomb) might need a little more weight, but he's got a
big frame and long arms,'' said Bob Ferguson, vice president of
player personnel for the Arizona Cardinals. ``You can see he plays
hard. He looks like a blue-collar guy to me, and technically he
seems very sound.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gibson and Piller are both noted for their overpowering
strength, Stinchcomb, who has a 3.94 grade-point average in
business, says he uses technique and intelligence to dominate
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say my upper-body strength is sub-par,'' Stinchcomb said.
``My upper body has always lagged behind. I'm not overpowering up
top at all. I'm not going to annihilate a guy off the line and
drive him 10 yards back. But I've got long arms, so that helps.''
</P>
<P>
   While Stinchcomb and cornerback Champ Bailey have a shot at
becoming Georgia's first consensus All-Americans since tailback
Garrison Hearst in 1992, some NFL insiders think that Terry could
move past Stinchcomb in the draft with a solid season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty underrated,'' Stinchcomb said, ``especially if you
take into account that he's only been doing this for a year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's in front of him,'' offensive line coach Chris
Scelfo said. ``He's growing into the position, and he knows what's
expected of him.''
</P>
<P>
   For three years, Terry, a 6-6, 290-pounder from Jacksonville,
was a little-used defensive end. He often was the odd man out in a
defensive front that included current NFL players Jason Ferguson
(N.Y. Jets), Jermaine Smith (Green Bay Packers) and Phillip Daniels
(Seattle Seahawks).
</P>
<P>
   ``I played behind some pretty good players on defense,'' Terry
said. ``I thought my time was going to come there. But when coach
Donnan came to Georgia, he told me he thought I could be a better
offensive tackle because of my height and size. Obviously, he was
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Stinchcomb and Terry yielded only two sacks each last season,
Scelfo said. Stinchcomb graded at 90 percent or better blocking in
10 of 12 games; Terry graded over 80 percent in 8 of 12 contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``With those two tackles, we really feel like we'll be able to
run the football,'' Donnan said. ``And with an inexperienced
quarterback, that's going to be a must.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
