<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8176 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMS-CLINTON-920&AMP;ADD-     09-03 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-CLINTON-920&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC SENATOR DENOUNCES CLINTON ON LEWINSKY FUROR 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Unleashing the swelling discontent among Democrats
about President Clinton, Sen. Joseph Lieberman denounced the
president's conduct in the Lewinsky scandal on Thursday as
``disgraceful'' and ``immoral'' and said the issue carried deep
moral consequences for the country.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking forcefully yet deliberately in a 24-minute speech from
the Senate floor, Lieberman, a respected centrist Democrat from
Connecticut, punctured several of Clinton's explanations about
Monica Lewinsky, notably the president's assertion that his
relationship with her was a private issue within his own family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such behavior is not just inappropriate _ it is immoral,''
said the 56-year-old Lieberman, who was elected in 1988. ``And it
is harmful, for it sends a message of what is acceptable behavior
to the larger American family _ particularly to our children _
which is as influential as the negative messages communicated by
the entertainment culture.''
</P>
<P>
   While they were thoughtful and measured, Lieberman's remarks
were by far the most pointed of any Democrat thus far, and
threatened to undermine an intense drive by the White House and
leading Democrats to contain the political fallout from Clinton's
disclosure two weeks ago that he had an improper relationship with
Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said the talk of impeachment and resignation was
``unjust and unwise'' at this time. He stopped short of calling for
Congress to censure the president, as the senator had considered,
saying such a move would be premature. But he suggested there be
some sort of public rebuke of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's comments immediately prompted two of Lieberman's
Democratic colleagues, Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York and
Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, to break their silence and rise to the
Senate floor to praise Lieberman _ and offer more bristling words
for the president. And Republicans, including Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, lauded Lieberman's for what Lott termed his
``moral compass.''
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton's grand jury testimony last month, Lieberman
became the first senator of either party to rise on the Senate
floor as it resumed session this week to address the disclosure.
When Lieberman began to speak, the chamber was relatively empty but
several of his colleagues soon came in. After his speech, the
senator sat alone, his hands folded in his lap, as colleagues from
both parties approached him. Sen. Thomas Daschle, the minority
leader, who had earlier this week tried to muzzle Lieberman and
other disaffected Democrats, put his arm around him.
</P>
<P>
   Other leading Democrats have scolded the president, but mostly
in terse statements; none had spoken out before Thursday about the
moral implications of Clinton's behavior. And many Democrats said
they feared that Lieberman's remarks would force Democrats who are
facing re-election in November to also speak at length about the
president's conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Standing calmly at his desk on the Senate floor and reading from
a text that advisers said he had been refining for several days,
Lieberman said he was provoked not only by Clinton's relationship
but by what he said was the president's failure to level with the
American people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's relationship with Ms. Lewinsky not only
contradicted the values he has publicly embraced over the last six
years,'' Lieberman said. ``It has, I fear, compromised his moral
authority at a time when Americans of every political persuasion
agree that the decline of the family is one of the most pressing
problems we are facing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevertheless,'' he continued, ``I believe the president could
have lessened the harm his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky has
caused if he had acknowledged his mistake and spoken with candor
about it to the American people shortly after it became public in
January.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House was so concerned that Lieberman's words could be
politically devastating that Erskine Bowles, Clinton's chief of
staff, along with Daschle and others, implored him earlier this
week not to speak out at least until the president returned from
Russia and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   But Lieberman, unable to hold himself back any longer, said,
``The implications for our country are so serious that I feel a
responsibility to my constituents in Connecticut, as well as to my
conscience, to voice my concerns forthrightly and publicly.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House responded in a low-key manner, careful not to
stoke the matter. ``The president has great respect for Senator
Lieberman because of the key role he has played in the president's
accomplishments on behalf of the American people,'' said Barry
Toiv, a White House spokesman. ``It's always hardest to hear
criticism from a friend. But I am sure the president will consider
Senator Lieberman's words with the same care with which they were
delivered.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is the Senate's only practicing Orthodox Jew, and he
has often spoken out on moral issues. He is close to many
conservatives including William Bennett, a former education
secretary in the Reagan Administration, who, in his new book, ``The
Death of Outrage,'' also argued that Clinton's troubles have
threatened the moral foundation of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   His comments also carried particular weight because though
Lieberman and the president have clashed over matters such as
American policy toward Bosnia, the two have been longtime
confidants. Lieberman is chairman of the Democratic Leadership
Council, a moderate group, that Clinton headed before running for
president.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lieberman's speech on Thursday evening could mark a turning
point in how members of Congress respond to the Lewinsky matter. As
the Watergate scandal was unfolding in March of 1974, Sen. James
Buckley of New York became the first conservative Republican to
call for President Richard Nixon's resignation. His remarks,
calling for ``an extraordinary act of statesman and courage,'' were
widely viewed as a major force in moving conservative opinion on
Capitol Hill against the president.
</P>
<P>
   With Lieberman's remarks, the tensions and anger within
Democratic ranks burst front and center. The White House had
already scrambled to respond to Democratic House candidates who
have said they do not want the president to campaign in their
districts. And senators in both parties said they spurned
entreaties from the White House for them to join the president in
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go over there being asked Lewinsky questions
all the time,'' one Democratic senator said on Thursday, speaking
on condition of anonymity. ``I'd rather talk about policy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
