<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8178 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-AIRLINE-BOS &LR;      09-03 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-AIRLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORST HAPPENS DESPITE AIRLINE'S BRILLIANT RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Crash-FAA; i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a safe airplane owned by one of the world's safest
airlines and flown by an unusually experienced crew.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Wednesday's crash of Swissair Flight 111 off the coast
of Nova Scotia, only one MD-11 _ the second generation of the DC-10
_ had been destroyed in an accident. The last fatal accident for
Swissair was in Athens in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   All 229 aboard Swissair 111 died in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The flight crew of Captain Urs Zimmermann, 50, and First Officer
Stephan Loew, 36, were both instructors with considerable
experience in the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   And still, the worst happened. While the cause of the crash is
yet to be determined, there are indications of an onboard fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great lingering fear, for lack of a better word, for
airmen is an inflight fire,'' said a veteran airline pilot who
Wednesday evening flew a Boeing 767 from Europe to New York's John
F. Kennedy Airport and who asked not to be identified. ``It can so
easily get out of control, your options are so limited and time is
so critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Swissair Flight 111, bound for Geneva, took off from Kennedy at
8:18 p.m. Wednesday with 215 passengers and a crew of 14 on board.
It was was handled by Federal Aviation Administration controllers
at the Boston Center in Nashua, N.H., as it flew over New England
and out into the Atlantic. Nothing seemed untoward.
</P>
<P>
   Supervision of the plane was handed off to Canadian controllers,
located in Moncton, New Brunswick, as Swissair 111 reached a point
in the Gulf of Maine, about 150 miles east of Nantucket and north
of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The controllers in Moncton handle virtually all airliners headed
to Europe from Boston and New York and from airports as far west as
Chicago and far south as Atlanta. This ``evening push'' is their
busiest time of day.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Moncton controllers received the airplane, the
crew sent a distress message calling out ``Pan, pan, pan'' at about
9:15 p.m. (EDT). The crew reported there was smoke in the cockpit,
according to Tony Rushton, vice president of the Canadian Air
Traffic Controllers Association.
</P>
<P>
   In the precise language of aviation, the ``Pan'' call is not a
declaration of emergency, but rather the declaration of an
abnormality on board the airplane and that the crew may not follow
its flight plan.
</P>
<P>
   The crew then requested to head to Boston's Logan International
Airport. Swissair serves Logan and has a contract with Delta Air
Lines to perform maintenance work on its planes. Airlines usually
prefer to have planes land at airports where maintenance
relationships are already established.
</P>
<P>
   However, aviation sources said controllers informed the crew
that Logan was 192 miles away and Halifax International Airport was
42 miles away. The crew decided to go to Halifax and was vectored
toward that airport.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the pilot requested approval to dump fuel. ``It
was put into a pattern'' so it could dump the fuel, said Rushton,
who noted that he was relying on the recollection of controllers
who handled the plane, rather than radar tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear they were boring circles in the sky and dumping fuel,''
said one Federal Aviation Administration source.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel is jettisoned to lighten an aircraft on landing. The
maximum takeoff weight of an aircraft is always higher than the
maximum landing weight. A plane that is too heavy on landing may
overshoot the runway, or collapse its landing gear, or burst tires.
But in a life and death situation, aviation specialists said, a
pilot would declare an emergency and not use the ``pan'' call. Nor
would a pilot waste time dumping fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an aircraft is going to come out of the sky, no one is
bothering to ask the question: `What is the best weight to land
this aircraft at?''' said the veteran pilot. ``No one would stay
aloft just to dump fuel. It is simply nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is possible that the event on board seemed less of a
crisis than it was.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:25 p.m. (EDT) the pilot realized the gravity of the
situation and declared an emergency. It was the last transmission
received from the aircraft, Rushton said. About seven minutes
later, when the plane was between 10,000 and 8,000 feet altitude
the plane's identification signal disappeared from Moncton radar
scopes and controllers could not contact the airplane. They then
called search and rescue.
</P>
<P>
   For a few more moments, controllers could still see the blip of
the plane on the radar. Then it too disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance of the identifaction signal could have meant
only one thing: a complete electrical failure on board the aircraft
that would shut down the plane's transponder sending the
identification signal to radar. The loss of radio contact,
meanwhile, could be either because of an electrical failure or the
pilots had lost consciousness, succumbing to fumes in the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kinds of fumes that occur in a cabin of a burning airliner
are very quickly incapacitating,'' said the veteran pilot. ``The
crew can get pure oxygen. But it is possible, everyone on board was
dead when they hit the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, while Canadian officials are beginning their
investigation into the cause of the crash, some high ranking
transportation officials in Washington expressed dismay over the
slow pace with which the investigation is proceeding and expressed
concern about salvage efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The US government offered to send US Navy salvage teams,
veterans of the TWA Flight 800 recovery operation in 1996, but the
Canadians declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they have their own Navy and they can do it,'' said
one National Transportation Safety Board official who asked not to
be identified. ``They can do it, but they will learn from the same
painful mistakes we learned.''
</P>
<P>
   The MD-11 aircraft was delivered to Swissair in 1991. It had
35,998 flight hours and 6,554 takeoffs and landings. While the
successor to the DC-10, the MD-11 was a much more reliable aircraft
and underwent a full certification process from the FAA, as if it
was a brand new aircraft, rather than a derivative model.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft was positioned to do very well, but its
performance, in terms of range, did not live up to the advance
billing of its manufacturer, McDonnell-Douglas. Boeing, which
bought McDonnell-Douglas, had previously announced it would shut
down production of the plane in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   David Stempler, president of the Air Travelers Association, a
passenger advocacy group, said Swissair is ``among the world's
safest airlines. They are first rate and had not had a fatal
accident in 19 years. They have great maintenance, quality flight
training. Sometimes, even a good airline will have an aberational
event.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Anne Kornblut of the Glboe Staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
