<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SALES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WAKE OF STRIKES, GM POSTS AUGUST SALES DROP 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Still struggling with the aftermath of two strikes, the General
Motors Corp. reported Thursday that car and light-truck sales fell
36.4 percent in August. At the same time, the Ford Motor Co.
reported a stronger-than-expected 8.1 percent increase in sales.
</P>
<P>
   GM's lower sales pushed the industry down even though nearly all
auto companies selling vehicles in the United States reported
higher sales. Vehicle sales for the month totaled 1,229,989 cars
and light trucks, a decrease of 6.6 percent compared with sales in
the month a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 675,173 cars were sold, down 8.8 percent, and truck
sales were off 3.8 percent at 554,816. The seasonally adjusted
selling rate dipped to 14.6 million cars and light trucks after
running at a rate of more than 16 million for the last three
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering the GM strike and the expiration of the loyalty
coupons,'' incentives that ran from April to July, ``these are very
strong numbers,'' said David Healy, an auto analyst for Burnham
Securities in New York.
</P>
<P>
   GM sold 271,177 cars and light trucks during the month, a 36.4
percent decline compared with sales in August 1997. Car sales were
156,876, down 37.4 percent, and light-truck sales totaled 112,362,
down 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of nearly every model in GM's line dropped 30 percent to
40 percent. The largest sales declines were in vehicles with the
lowest inventories, such as full-size sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of GM's North American assembly operations were
closed for 54 days in June and July because of strikes by the
United Automobile Workers at two parts plants in Flint, Mich. GM's
plants are now operating on overtime to push inventory levels back
to normal in October.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 percent of GM's August sales came in the last 10
days of the month. The level of sales in those 10 days were close
to the level of sales in the last 10 days of August 1997. For the
year so far, GM's vehicle sales trail 1997 sales by 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At Ford, sales were stronger than analysts expected. Ford
reported that its Ford, Mercury, Lincoln and Jaguar divisions sold
323,599 cars and light trucks in August, an 8.1 percent increase
compared with figures from August 1997. Ford sold 129,527 cars, up
1.3 percent from a year earlier, and 189,809 light trucks, up 13.2
percent, a new industry record for monthly truck sales.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every major vehicle manufacturer reporting sales this
week experienced higher sales in August compared with those in the
month a year earlier; some set records.
</P>
<P>
   Sales for the Chrysler Corp. were up 3.5 percent. Toyota
reported its best August ever for its Toyota and Lexus brands, up
10.9 percent. Sales of Mercedes-Benz, a unit of Daimler-Benz, rose
75.8 percent, and BMW sales increased by 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen AG had its best August in 17 years, with a 71.3
percent increase in sales, passing full-year sales for 1997. Its
Audi brand enjoyed its best August since 1986, with sales up 37.7
percent. Volvo sales increased 8.5 percent, and Porsche AG sales
jumped 134.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Subaru of America had its best August since 1989, with a 9.3
percent increase in sales. Mazda had its best month since March
1995, with sales up 37.8 percent. Kia Motors America reported sales
up 26.8 percent, and Nissan sales rose 2.9 percent. Isuzu sales
rose 5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most automotive executives and automotive analysts predict the
industry will close the year on a high note despite the
roller-coaster behavior of the stock market and the Asian financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasts generally indicate 1998 car and light-truck sales will
be about 15.5 million units, which would be the fifth consecutive
year of more than 15 million units sold.
</P>
</TEXT>
