</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-RDP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATORS SEARCH FOR CLUES IN SWISSAIR CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CRASH-SCENE, CRASH-INQUIRY, CRASH-FAMILIES,
CRASH-VICTIMS, CRASH-OBIT-MANN and CRASH-OBIT-CLEMENTS-MANN) (ART
ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dozens of bodies and bits of wreckage were recovered from choppy
seas off Nova Scotia on Thursday as officials sought to determine
why a Swissair jetliner bound from New York to Geneva began smoking
and fell into the Atlantic minutes short of an emergency landing in
Halifax Wednesday night, apparently killing all 229 people on
board.
</P>
<P>
   As Canadian naval vessels and a flotilla of fishermen searched
the crash site five miles off a picturesque village called Peggy's
Cove on Nova Scotia's south shore, it seemed unlikely that any
survivors would be found, though all hope was not abandoned. Many
of the victims' grieving families gathered in New York and Geneva,
and some were flown to Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   Among the victims were Jonathan Mann, the first director of the
World Health Organization's AIDS program, and several other U.N.
officials whose work had taken them into hazardous regions,
including Pierce Gerety, a Harvard-educated lawyer who had worked
for years on behalf of refugees in strife-torn regions of Africa
and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investigators said that, although the cause of the
crash was still a mystery and might not be learned for weeks or
months, there were no immediate indications that the wide-bodied
jet, a McDonnell-Douglas MD-11, had been brought down by an
explosion or an act of criminality or terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing to indicate at this time any possibility or
suggestion of any criminal act,'' Terry Ryan, a deputy commissioner
of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police, told a news conference.
Similar comments came from the White House, the FBI, Swissair and
Canadian and American air safety officials.
</P>
<P>
   Searchers, who retrieved at least 36 bodies, as well as body
parts and debris that included clothing, baggage and seat cushions,
spotted in the afternoon what seemed to be a large piece of the
aircraft intact _ perhaps the fuselage, containing many of the
victims and the flight data recorders _ in about 120 feet of water.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, unlike Trans World Airlines Flight 800, which blew up
without warning in the sky off the south shore of Long Island soon
after takeoff from Kennedy International Airport on July 17, 1996,
with a loss of 230 lives, investigators said Swissair Flight 111
apparently did not explode, but ran into trouble about 15 minutes
before it crashed and did not break up until it hit the water.
</P>
<P>
   Reconstructing the doomed flight, investigators said the plane
left Kennedy Airport at 8:17 p.m. and, nearly an hour later, was
out over the Atlantic in Canadian airspace, cruising at 33,000 feet
about 320 miles east-northeast of Boston, when the pilot radioed
air controllers in Moncton, New Brunswick, at 9:14 p.m. that there
was smoke in the cabin, its source unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Vic Gerden, the investigator in charge for Canada's National
Transportation Safety Board, said the pilot proposed going back to
Boston's Logan Airport for an emergency landing, and had begun
turning when the Canadian controller told him that Halifax
International Airport was closer, only about 70 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, identified by Swissair officials as Urs Zimmermann,
50, aided by the co-pilot, Stefan Low, 36, turned again toward
Halifax and flew on for 11 minutes, gradually descending to 9,600
feet, according to radar tracking data. During that time, the
passengers and crew were told of the emergency and put on life
jackets, which were later found on some bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The cockpit crew and the controllers at Moncton spoke to one
another at various points as a rescue center at Halifax was
notified and arrangements to clear the way for the landing were
made. As the plane crossed over the south shore of Nova Scotia and
headed inland toward Halifax Airport 30 to 40 miles away, however,
it suddenly changed course again, apparently after the pilot
concluded that he had to dump some of his fuel at sea, Gerden said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerden said it was the pilot's decision to do this, probably
because an emergency landing is safer without heavily loaded fuel
tanks, or because the plane might have been easier to land without
the extra weight. In any event, radar tracking data showed that the
plane circled left and flew in a wide arc over land, down St.
Margaret's Bay and out over the ocean again, traveling at little
more than half its normal cruising speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, the aircraft was too heavy to land while
approaching Halifax and had to dump some fuel,'' Gerden said. ``My
understanding is that he would have turned or maneuvered somewhat
to dump the fuel prior to attempting the landing because he was too
heavy to land.''
</P>
<P>
   At 9:25 p.m., the fuel dumping began _ rescuers later reported a
heavy odor of fuel on the water _ and, for reasons that were
unclear Thursday, the crew raised its distress call to a formal
mayday emergency. Five minutes later, at 9:30 p.m., under moonless
but clear skies, the plane suddenly plunged into the ocean.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The plane, when it fell, was about 40 miles, or 7 to 10 minutes
of flying time, short of Halifax Airport, officials said, and there
no explanation why it happened. No one suggested that the plane had
dumped too much fuel and run out. And no one suggested that the
pilot's decision to twice divert his course _ first to head for
Boston and then, with Halifax Airport less than 40 miles away, to
circle around back to sea and dump fuel _ had been a judgment
error.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses in Peggy's Cove, Blandford, Hubbards and other coastal
towns, many of them already in bed _ it was 10:30 p.m., local time
_ reported hearing the sputtering noises of an aircraft passing
overhead, and then a thunderous crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting with my husband outside by the little cottage
behind our house, by the water,'' said Sharon Hoagland, 48, of
Hubbards, on St. Margaret's Bay, 10 miles from the crash site. ``We
heard a huge sound. Initially I thought it was thunder. Then we
herd a smaller second rumble. It was a thunderous boom, but there
was no rain, no lightning.''
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Blandford, Mabel Schnare, was at her son's house by
the water. ``I heard this big noise,'' she said. ``My, oh my, I
said to myself. What does this fool think he's doing, flying so
low. It was so loud I thought it would hit the house.'' A moment
later, the house shook violently.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Comdr. Glenn Chamberlain, a spokesman for the Canadian Navy
and Coast Guard's joint rescue command center in Halifax, said that
local boaters with intimate knowledge of treacherous coastal waters
_ fishermen, lobstermen and others _ provided invaluable aid in the
early hours after the crash. Many ran down and pushed out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's people who recognized that this was a tragedy, that
people needed help, and they didn't pause to think _ they just went
and helped,'' Chamberlain said. The seas, relatively calm at the
time of the crash, grew to angry 10 foot swells through the night
as drenching rains fell and winds rose to a howl.
</P>
<P>
   Within 40 minutes of the crash, the small boaters were joined by
Canadian Navy and Coast Guard vessels: frigates, cutters, supply
ships, helicopters and other craft, including police boats. Flares
rocketed aloft and fell slowly on parachutes, and the night search
recovered the first bodies.
</P>
<P>
   But heavy weather forced a suspension until dawn, after which
the small boaters were sent home. By late morning, the operation
involved more than 1,500 search and rescue personnel on land, sea
and in the air. A makeshift morgue was set up aboard the Canadian
supply ship, HMCS Preserver, which had decks for helicopters and a
crew of 250.
</P>
<P>
   A small armada of search vessels, led by the Canadian frigate,
HMCS Ville de Quebec, hunted on a grid that was gradually expanded
from 5 square miles to 10 or more square miles. Several seaborne
helicopters were joined by land-based planes flying out of
Shearwater, a Canadian Forces base at Dartmouth, across Halifax
harbor from the provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
   A large morgue also was set up at Shearwater, and bodies, as
they were recovered, were to be flown there, officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
