<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8188 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DREAMWORKS-STUDIO-2TA     09-03 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREAMWORKS-STUDIO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HOLLYWOOD STUDIO WRANGLES OVER PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was the high-tech vision that was supposed to
make the dream in Dreamworks come true, the first newly built
Hollywood studio in nearly 60 years, nestled in a 1,000-acre tract
amid the coastal wetlands where Howard Hughes built his giant
seaplane, the Spruce Goose.
</P>
<P>
   But now Dreamworks SKG, the studio partnership of Steven
Spielberg, Jeffrey Katzenberg and David Geffen, is threatening to
pull out of the proposed Playa Vista development in the Ballona
Wetlands just north of Los Angeles International Airport. And city
officials here are warning that if Dreamworks goes, the whole
residential-office-retail project may be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   It is a classic clash of Hollywood egos and New York investors,
and it involves not only money but also local power politics and a
newly resurgent real estate market in a battle for a piece of the
booming movie business that has filled up existing studio space and
helped fuel the region's economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the developers, led by the investment houses of
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. and Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., want to
impose more costs and conditions for building the new studio than
Dreamworks is willing to accept.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, in anonymous sniping in the trade press and
leaked letters, each side has accused the other of bad faith and of
working to sabotage the deal. The developer's camp has questioned
whether Dreamworks, which is still feeling its way nearly four
years after its founding, really wants to build its own studio
after all, while Dreamworks allies speculate that the developer is
trying to get higher-paying tenants and a better return on its
investment now that the local real estate market is hot again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreamworks has given all that it can give,'' Katzenberg wrote
to the developers last month in a letter that also included threats
to look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are truly at a point where we cannot, and will not, give
any more,'' he added in the letter, a copy of which was sent to
Mayor Richard J. Riordan, Gov. Pete Wilson and other officials. The
letter has since become public and has led to the latest round of
wrangling over a project that has been stalled for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamworks wants enough land to build and operate its own
headquarters and studios, up to 15 state-of-the-art sound stages at
a cost of about $200 million. But the developer, Playa Capital,
which took control of the site last year after the original
investors' financing collapsed, now wants to develop at least some
studio space on its own, and then lease it back to Dreamworks or
other users at rates that Dreamworks officials say are unrealistic
and exorbitant.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the world of stupid ideas, that's an Olympic winner,'' said
one senior Dreamworks executive, speaking on condition of anonymity
and adding that it would be far preferable for the studio to
continue renting production space as needed from existing studios.
</P>
<P>
   But in an intense public lobbying campaign this week, Dreamworks
has hardly behaved like a player ready to fold its cards. Instead,
it has repeatedly flashed them, enlisting the vocal support of
state and local officials to reinforce its position that its
involvement is crucial to the overall project's success.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan has offered to help mediate, and even the head of the
Motion Picture Association, Jack Valenti, has weighed in.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the city and state originally agreed to provide more
than $70 million in incentives and employment tax credits to the
project on the basis of Dreamworks' involvement in it, and local
community and environmental groups long wary of development in one
of the last remaining stretches of coastal wetlands in greater Los
Angeles also lent their support, largely on the basis of
Dreamworks' tenancy and a plan to restore much of the wetlands.
This week such groups warned the developer against upsetting that
balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recent statements by the new owners of Playa Vista force me to
question those commitments,'' City Councilwoman Ruth Galanter, who
represents the area, said this week. ``Their recent statements that
Dreamworks doesn't fit their vision for Playa Vista make me suspect
that they plan to return to their earlier plans to build hotels and
office complexes. This is contrary to the vision they promised
us.''
</P>
<P>
   State transportation officials have also warned that the
developer could lose millions of dollars earmarked for road
improvements that were contingent on Dreamworks moving to the site.
</P>
<P>
   But Peter Denniston, president of Playa Capital, issued a
statement on Wednesday noting that the developer cannot deviate
from the current city-approved plan without additional review and
city council approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this condition not as a constraint but rather as a
testament to our conviction to stand by our promises,'' Denniston
said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dreamworks announced its plan with great fanfare three years ago
in the old hangar where the Spruce Goose was built in World War II.
The new studio, the first one built here since Warner Brothers
moved to the San Fernando Valley in the 1930s, was to be the anchor
of a special media district that would create nearly 9,000 jobs and
3,000 housing units and generate billions of dollars in revenue for
the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a full-fledged studio, the quality of the job is
higher, the pay level is higher and there's a sense of endurance
and continuity,'' Valenti said in a telephone interview from Paris
this week. ``It's the difference between owning your car and
renting one.''
</P>
<P>
   But after months of financing problems and public wrangling with
Dreamworks, the original local developer, Robert Maguire, lost
control of the project last year, and the studio had to begin
negotiations over again with the new owners.
</P>
<P>
   The project was also held up by litigation by some environmental
groups, although a federal court has so far temporarily barred work
on only 16 acres, most of it centered in a freshwater marsh,
pending a fuller review by the Army Corps of Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the local real estate market had sharply
rebounded, and the new owners and the moguls spent much of the last
year haggling over terms.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the tax credits, transportation subsidies and
intangible marquee value that Dreamworks would bring to the
project, the developer agreed to give the studio a plot of land _
Dreamworks says it was 35 acres _ at no cost. But the studio
contended that it needed 12 more acres, and reluctantly agreed this
summer to pay the developer $20 million for it, according to
Katzenberg's letter.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Katzenberg wrote, the developer increased the price to
more than $48 million, an amount Katzenberg dismissed as
``completely unacceptable.'' And Dreamworks said the developer sent
a subsequent proposal offering even less free land, and the idea of
divided control of the sound stages, in which Dreamworks would
control some and Playa Capital the rest. It was this proposal that
appeared to particularly outrage the studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a better deal with most of the studios around town
today than we would have with Playa Capital,'' one Dreamworks
official said. ``They simply do not understand this business at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Playa Capital officials declined to comment in any detail on the
negotiations, except to say, as the vice president of corporate
affairs, David A. Herbst, put it: ``The bottom line is we want to
make it happen. We want to do whatever we can to make Dreamworks a
part of Playa Vista.''
</P>
<P>
   But one person close to the negotiations, who spoke on condition
of anonymity, said that the developer had been renting out the vast
old Hughes hangar and surrounding buildings as sound stages since
1994, and that there still seemed room for compromise.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the Dreamworks partners themselves had
varying views of the project, with Spielberg pressing hardest for
it while Geffen, who became a billionaire in the record business
and has always liked to operate with low overhead, was reluctant to
invest so heavily in real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg, who cut his teeth as a young city hall aide in the
administration of former Mayor John V. Lindsay of New York, has
taken the lead in negotiations, and one Dreamworks official said
the partners now seemed more united in their determination to
proceed, if not at Playa Vista then by expanding their existing
operation on the Universal Studios lot or some other site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
