</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-SCENE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH SCENE: `IT'S PRETTY NUMBING TO SEE THAT KIND OF CARNAGE' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEGGY'S COVE, Nova Scotia _ A picture postcard turned Thursday
into a scene from hell.
</P>
<P>
   This quaint, rock-ribbed village, one of the most idyllic spots
on Canada's Atlantic coast, became the staging area for the search
following the crash of Swissair Flight 111.
</P>
<P>
   At first it was to be a point of search and rescue, but after a
brief flurry of hope and speculation in the ink-dark hours before
dawn, the prospect of survivors dimmed and then burned away with
the fog.
</P>
<P>
   Daybreak brought a scene from one of the coastal rescue novels
that dot eastern Canada's literary landscape. But death usually
comes up from the deep, not down from the sky.
</P>
<P>
   On the misty horizon were the dim outlines of Canadian Navy
vessels. Skittering in and out of the flimsy-looking dock were
local fishing craft that joined the gruesome scouting mission,
retrieving soggy wallets and purses, shoes and ties along with
bodies and pieces of bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never get really used to it, but you accept it,'' said
Robert Murphy, deputy fire chief at nearby Seabright.
</P>
<P>
   The search effort pressed on into Thursday night and Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like 7-Eleven,'' said Lt. Cmdr. Jacques Fauteux of the
Rescue Coordination Center. ``We carry on day and night.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after dark Thursday, Fauteux refused to give up hope of
finding a survivor, which other officials said was a brave but
improbable position, especially in the face of Swissair's
declaration that all aboard were dead.
</P>
<P>
   Fauteux said that as a mariner he could never count out ``sheer
will power.''
</P>
<P>
   Lives have been lost at Peggy's Cove less dramatically than in
the crash of a jumbo jet. Among the marine tragedies that Murphy
recalled from his years in the Halifax County emergency service was
a woman being washed off the thrusting boulders that make this
point one of the first sights a visitor is likely to head for in
Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   Clapboard and shingle houses line the shore and winding roads.
Lobster traps are stacked about. The scene is completed by a stubby
white beacon, with a red turret and a steady, phosphorescent green
light that is a silent reminder of the terror that the changeable
sea and weather can hold.
</P>
<P>
   The initial search Thursday was hampered by rains from the tail
end of Hurricane Danielle. But for much of the day, a bright,
warming sun seemed to mock the urgent bustle of the emergency
workers and their grim task.
</P>
<P>
   A piece of radio tape, which seemed to be played as an
interminable loop by a local station, told what was really going
on: ``Call after call is asking for body bags.'' In the night,
yellow-orange flares, with two-million candle power, gave the
search scene a touch of Dante. Harsh search lights from hovering
helicopters created a similar effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty numbing to see that kind of carnage,'' said Jim
Buckley, who sped to the search site in his whale-watching boat.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers feared that tuna and mackerel nets, which provide
the livelihood for many in the area, would complicate the search,
snagging debris and making it difficult for the boats to navigate.
</P>
<P>
   Initially the jarring thud of the crash made some coastal
residents believe they were hearing thunder and that an unexpected
storm _ if any storms in this part of the world are truly
unexpected _ was moving in.
</P>
<P>
   Although the crash awakened many, it was news to many in nearby
Halifax, the provincial capital, when they awoke.
</P>
<P>
   A Halifax taxi driver said he had ``popped in the tape for
`Titanic,''' then went directly to bed when the newly released
video finished.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was a reminder that the Halifax area has long lived
with dramatic tragedies. The city is home to a cemetery with the
remains of more than 100 unclaimed victims of the ``unsinkable''
ocean liner's deadly brush with a North Atlantic iceberg in 1912.
Halifax ships were called on then to pick up the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Halifax was rocked by a thundering explosion in 1917 when an
empty freighter struck a loaded munitions ship in its harbor. Two
thousand were killed and the north part of the city flattened. Some
old buildings still bear marks from the blast. Scientists count it
the largest manmade explosion before the nuclear age.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the slumbering taxi driver was rousted by his
dispatcher to ferry reporters from the Halifax airport to Peggy's
Cove and other assembly points for the region's latest emergency.
</P>
<P>
   The airport learned about the distress of SR111 while the flight
was still aloft. Preparations for an emergency landing were under
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had all the fire trucks ready,'' said Andrew Arthur, 23,
a fueler and pilot for the Avitat private aviation service.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Arthur, who was out on the taxiway, said he didn't
grasp the gravity of moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really understand the panicky situation,'' he said.
``I assumed it was a small commuter plane,'' of which Halifax sees
a lot more than jumbo jets.
</P>
<P>
   But then he heard the distress in the voice of the air traffic
controller from Moncton, New Brunswick, who was attempting to talk
the Swissair pilot to a touch-down in Halifax. And he heard how
much fuel the plane was trying to dump _ tens of thousands of
pounds _ to ensure a shorter landing.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, Arthur said, the Moncton controller gave a desperate
sigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that's all we can do,'' the controller said, as the
plane disappeared from radar.
</P>
<P>
   Coastal residents felt the shockwaves of the MD-11 hitting the
ocean.
</P>
<P>
   At Peggy's Cove, the first of what may be many sad, frantic days
was about to begin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
