<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8204 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-INQUIRY-NYT &LR;      09-03 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCHERS FOCUS ON BODIES RATHER THAN BLACK BOXES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CRASH-RDP, CRASH-SCENE, CRASH-FAMILIES, CRASH-VICTIMS,
CRASH-OBIT-MANN, CRASH-OBIT-CLEMENTS-MANN and CRASH-OBIT-GERITY) 
(mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEGGY'S COVE, Nova Scotia _ The area where the Swissair jet went
down Wednesday night is still under the control of search and
rescue officials here, and investigators have not yet begun to look
for the ``black boxes,'' the cockpit voice recorder and flight data
recorders, that are most likely to provide important clues to the
reason for the plane's flight path and for the crash itself,
officials here said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they concentrated on looking for bodies _ even
survivors, a spokesman for the Halifax Search Coordination Center
insisted Thursday evening. The search area is spreading because of
the wind and tides.
</P>
<P>
   Even 24 hours after the jet crashed, apparently plunging
abruptly in the last few thousand feet, Lt. Commander Jacques
Fauteaux said someone might have survived. ``Sometimes, scientific
figures don't actually work, if you have will power,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the rescue workers, about 1,200 of them at any given time,
still in charge, the chairman of the Transportation Safety Board,
Benoit Bouchard, said in an interview that investigators had not
yet begun looking for the black boxes. Each recorder is equipped
with a ``pinger'' that is supposed to emit a regular sonar signal
when it is immersed in water, and the pinger can be located by
towing a listening array behind a ship.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Bouchard said, the only available clues are the
radar tapes, which will be reviewed beginning on Friday, and the
tapes of conversations between the pilots and controllers at
Monckton (New Brunswick) Center, which handles transatlantic
traffic handed off from Boston or New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard said that the crew of the Swiss Air plane, an MD-11,
had radioed that they had smoke in the cockpit at 10:14 local time
(9:14 P.M. ET) and had disappeared from radar at 10:30 p.m. In that
16 minutes he said the plane had begun to divert toward Halifax,
and then made a circle apparently to dump fuel.
</P>
<P>
   For many big planes, the maximum takeoff weight exceeds the
maximum permissible landing weight, with the weight of the fuel
being more than the landing gear can handle as the plane thumps
down under the runway. In normal operation, this is not a problem
because the fuel is burned en route.
</P>
<P>
   In crashes at sea, investigators usually look for the flight
data recorder and pocket voice recorders to determine what parts of
the plane they need to recover from the ocean floor. An exception
was the crash two years ago of TWA Flight 800, when the cockpit
voice recorder and flight data recorder did not appear to offer
them any clues, so they tried to recover the whole airplane.
</P>
<P>
   In the Valujet crash in 1996, of a DC 9 that went down in the
Florida Everglades shortly after take-off from Miami, the flight
data recorder noted a pressure spike that gave strong evidence of
an explosion. That, combined with the recovery of some of the
cargo, gave clear indication the source was hazardous oxygen
generators.
</P>
<P>
   How long before the Canadian authorities try to recover the
black boxes is not clear. Fauteaux would not say how many bodies
had been recovered and no effort had begun to recover those under
water, which might be the majority of the passengers and crew. He
pledged, though, that searchers would explore ``every possible
avenue to find survivors, if survivors there are.''
</P>
<P>
   The search area is expected to expand as time passes. Searchers
are using infrared sensors, to find objects that are a different
temperature from the sea, including bodies and aircraft parts. They
are also using detectors to look for magnetic anomalies, indicating
large pieces of metal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fauteaux, in response to a question, said he did not know if
Canadian authorities would request help from the United States.
Water depth at the scene of the crash is about 120 feet, he said;
that is not nearly as deep as other spots from which pieces of
aircraft wreckage, large and small, have been found and raised.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
