<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TAXES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PROPOSES $400 MILLION CONSUMER TAX CUT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush proposed Thursday a $400
million consumer tax cut, including repeal of the sales tax on
nonprescription drugs, diapers and health aids, except birth
control devices such as condoms.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also proposed a sales tax exemption for Internet access and
a sales-tax holiday in late July through early August 2000 on
inexpensive clothing for school children.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a direct way to return money to Texas families,'' Bush
said. ``These tax cuts are for the people who pay the bills _ the
moms and dads who buy diapers and school clothes for their children
and the senior citizens who spend a disproportionate share of their
income on over-the-counter medicines.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic gubernatorial candidate Garry Mauro called the
proposal a flip-flop by a governor who last year proposed a
half-cent general sales tax increase to pay for his property tax
reduction plan. Mauro said Bush's plan last year would have raised
taxes on all the items he now proposes eliminating from sales
taxation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is talking out of both sides of his mouth,''
Mauro said. ``Last year, Governor Bush tried to raise the sales tax
by $1.6 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's sales-tax cut proposal is the latest offering to voters
from the state's Democratic and Republican candidates as they try
to take advantage of a projected $3.7 billion state budget surplus
that could grow to as much as $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are proposing that we should spend up the surplus on a
bunch of new government programs,'' Bush said Thursday. ``I
disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the challenges of the next session will be to resist
the temptation to spend all the money and fuel future big
government,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he will make more proposals as the campaign goes
along, and indicated some may involve spending. When asked about
it, Bush declined to rule out a teacher pay raise, which Mauro has
proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Bush's tax cuts would take effect in September 1999, but
the sales-tax holiday on children's clothing would not occur until
2000. Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said the sales tax holiday
would be for one year but would be extended into the future if the
economy allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Bush previously had proposed several business tax cuts,
including a research and development tax credit for high-tech
businesses and a proposal to exempt companies with less than
$100,000 in annual sales from the state franchise tax.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lieutenant governor candidate Rick Perry has endorsed
Bush's tax cut proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic lieutenant governor candidate John Sharp has proposed
a larger franchise tax cut, exempting businesses that earn $250,000
a year or less. Sharp also proposed a one-time sales tax holiday in
August 1999 on children's clothing and school supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro also has proposed a tax cut. His would eliminate the sales
tax on motor vehicles and pay for it by doubling the tax on liquor
and tobacco. Mauro said the tax cut would save Texas families more
than $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he believes exempting sales taxes on over-the-counter
medicine will be more meaningful to Texans than cutting the sales
tax on motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (a motor vehicle sales tax cut) generally affects people
one out of every seven years. I believe in affecting people's lives
every year,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his proposal will save Texas families an average of
$70 a year and will benefit low-income families and senior citizens
the most.
</P>
<P>
   But Mauro said the tax increase Bush proposed last year would
have increased state tax revenues on over-the-counter medicine by
$12 million, on diapers by $8.8 million and on health aids by $4
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything Bush says today should be taken with a grain of
salt,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said in an op-ed article in 1997 that his tax plan would
cost average families $71 a year in increased sales taxes but save
them $333 a year in property taxes. For renters, the property tax
cut was expected to create savings in rents.
</P>
<P>
   Bush won passage of a far less aggressive property tax cut paid
for by a state budget surplus. That property tax cut saved
homeowners $140 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush budget analyst James LeBas said birth control devices were
left out of the tax cut on health aids because the idea was to give
a break to people with injuries or long-term problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about a situation where people are treating an
injury: Band-Aids, gauze, ice bags, corn pads, canes. We're talking
about not adding a tax insult to injury,'' LeBas said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and lieutenant governor candidates are not the only
ones talking about the budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   In the race from state comptroller, Republican Carole Keeton
Rylander has proposed an additional $1 billion in state property
tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Paul Hobby has said it would be better to use the state
surplus to pay off state debt. He said the state is paying up to
$500 million a year now on debt service.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
