u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-TIRE-COX     09-03 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-TIRE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elliott: Gordon too good to be cheater
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Elliott thinks it's resources, talent and application, not
doctored tires, that has the Hendrick Motorsports team of driver
Jeff Gordon and crew chief Ray Evernham at the top of the Winston
Cup points standings.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott said he was unaware until Wednesday of the post-race
controversy coming out of last week's race at New Hampshire. And in
his opinion, it's mostly a matter of Gordon being able to outrun
the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott relates to Gordon's situation. That's the way it was in
the mid-1980s, before restrictor plates, when Elliott won 29 times
from 1985 to '89. And everybody thought he was cheating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can relate to what they're going through,'' Elliott said.
``When you win as much as they have, people are going to believe
you cheated. I really don't think Jeff and Ray are doing anything
wrong. They don't have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott said it's not usual for a team with the resources of
Hendrick Motorsports to be as successful as it is without cheating.
He also disagrees with Jack Roush, Martin's team owner, who said
``two tires have never, never made it where a car can go out and
outrun a car with four new tires.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At Michigan, two tires ran as good as four,'' Elliott said.
``Same with Loudon; they ran just as good. There are certain race
tracks where it doesn't matter, and in my opinion, Michigan and
Loudon are two of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Roush complained to NASCAR officials Sunday after Martin
finished second to Gordon for the fourth time in the last six
races. That race followed the pattern of the Pepsi 400 at Michigan,
where a late two-tire change brought Gordon's car to life, winning
a race Martin seemed to have under control.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR apparently had suspicions before Roush called for tires
to be checked after Sunday's race. The tires were confiscated after
the race.
</P>
<P>
   Roush offered another theory for Gordon's late-race revival _
that Gordon's Chevrolet was capable of doing more all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps it is precipitated by the advantage the Chevrolet has
over the Fords, since NASCAR shortened and narrowed our spoiler
earlier this year,'' Roush told the Charlotte Observer. ``They may
be laying back, and then turning it on at some point so as to
capitalize on that advantage to ice this championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two-tire change late in the race then allows them to
present the appearance that their comeback stems from having a
brilliant crew chief and a driver who turns in a heroic effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Roush said all he wants is for his driver to have a fair shot at
winning the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark is at the top of his game,'' Roush said. ``We don't want
him to lose the championship because somebody is doing something
that is outside the bounds of the spirt of NASCAR's rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin contends the impounding of tires was routine. There are
no hard feelings between the two, he said, even though Roush and
Evernham engaged in a shouting match in the garage after the New
Hampshire race. Notes: NASCAR announced a 34-race schedule Thursday
for the 1999 season, one more than a year ago. In addition, both
Atlanta races were given new dates _ one better than last year and
one worse.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Primestar 500 moves from March 8 to March 14, which
should be a move toward nicer weather. The season-ending NAPA 500
wasn't so fortunate. It moves two weeks later, from Nov. 8 to Nov.
21.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami-Dade Homestead Motorsports Complex, south of Miami, is
the newest addition. Running on Nov. 14, it also will be the site
of the season-ender for the BGN Series teams.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
