<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-JUSTICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ORDERS MICROSOFT TO TURN OVER DOCUMENTS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge Thursday ordered lawyers for
Microsoft Corp. to produce documents detailing the company's
relationship with Apple Computer Inc. and Intel Corp., saying
allegations that Microsoft bullied those companies may be relevant
to the antitrust case scheduled for trial later this month.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge also agreed to consider in two weeks Microsoft's
requests to either narrow the scope of the case or to delay by
months the Sept. 23 start of the trial if the company has to defend
broader antitrust claims.
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers, who originally focused their attention on
Microsoft's competition with Netscape Communications Corp., told
the judge that evidence concerning Microsoft's conduct toward Apple
and Intel, as well as Bristol Technology Inc., Caldera Inc.,
RealNetworks Inc. and Sun Microsystems Inc., may help them
demonstrate a pattern of illegally anti-competitive conduct by
Microsoft. Bristol, Caldera and Sun have filed private antitrust
lawsuits against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft lawyers are resisting the government's exploration of
the company's relationship with companies other than Netscape,
saying that the tactic is unfair because it comes so soon _ 20 days
_ before the start of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft warned yesterday that if it is to defend against
charges surrounding all those companies, it will need months more
to prepare .
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is trying to expand its case at the eleventh
hour by adding a multitude of new allegations and topics to the
case,'' Microsoft attorney John Warden said after the hearing. ``We
don't think the trial should be expanded to include these
allegations ... but they're groundless and we'll rebut them if
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Warden said that if the government wanted to litigate other
issues beyond Microsoft's handling of the browser market, it should
file another case against the company.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department Special Trial Counsel David Boies said the
evidence about companies such as Apple and RealNetworks will help
prove a pattern of misconduct by Microsoft, which stands accused of
illegally attempting to exploit a monopoly on computer operating
systems to gain share in the market for Internet browsers.
</P>
<P>
   The government believes Microsoft tried to persuade Intel, a
chip manufacturer, to stop developing software, Apple to stop
marketing its QuickTime multimedia technology for use with Windows,
and RealNetworks Inc. not to share its technology with Microsoft's
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft went to Apple and said, `You ought to get out of the
business of selling QuickTime for Windows, and if you will agree to
get out, we will agree to help you in other areas,''' Boies said.
``That is part of a pattern that helps demonstrate the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Boies also accused Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates of trying to
get Apple to help Microsoft undermine Sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think there's substantial expansion of the case,'' he
told reporters. ``What is at issue here is additional evidence of
the claims that have already been made.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson said he would consider a request
to narrow the scope of the trial _ as well as any request to delay
the trial _ at a hearing Sept. 17. In the meantime, Microsoft must
produce the documents sought by the government, including papers
referring to various meetings between high-ranking Microsoft
executives and employees of Apple and Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also ordered Microsoft to make available to government
lawyers databases detailing pricing and other issues associated
with Microsoft's sale of Windows licenses to computer
manufacturers. Microsoft said it would comply promptly with the
judge's order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
