<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8223 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-SFCHRON &LR;      09-03 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Microsoft Must Hand Over Evidence   By Benny Evangelista  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
A federal judge ordered Microsoft Corp. yesterday to turn over
information, including communications with Apple Computer and Intel
Corp., that the government says will bolster its landmark antitrust
case against the software giant.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The ruling is a setback for Microsoft, which wants to keep
the case as narrowly focused as possible.
</P>
<P>
   If U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson goes a step
further by letting the Department of Justice use the new
information to broaden the case, Microsoft says it will seek to
postpone the scheduled September 23 trial date by as much as six
months.
</P>
<P>
   However, such a delay could backfire against Microsoft,
antitrust experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm Microsoft, I'd be really thoughtful about asking for a
delay because it benefits the government as much as it does
Microsoft,'' said Rich Gray, an intellectual-property attorney at
Bergeson, Eliopoulos, Grady &AMP; Gray in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is accused of violating antitrust laws by bundling its
Internet Explorer Web browser with its Windows operating system
software and using licensing agreements with computer-makers and
Internet service providers to cut off a competing browser from
Netscape Communications of Mountain View.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Yesterday, Jackson ruled in favor of a Justice Department
motion that Microsoft turn over documents that the government hopes
will show that Microsoft has exerted pressure on industry allies
like Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Among the documents the government sought were any communication
between Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates and Senior Vice President
Paul Maritz, and any Intel representatives from 1995 to 1997. Also,
the government requested correspondence from Microsoft executives
Eric Engstrom and Chris Phillips to any representative of Apple
from 1996 to this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's motion stated that the new information
showed ``evidence of Microsoft's attempts to induce others,
including Intel and Apple, to take action to hamper Netscape ... or
to undermine the threat they pose to Microsoft's monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft argued that the government was trying to ``transform
this case into a ... `kitchen sink monstrosity' '' by introducing
evidence that did not directly deal with the browser issue central
to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson did not rule on Microsoft's motion against broadening
the scope of the case but indicated that he was leaning toward the
government's side when he told Microsoft lawyer John Warden, ``My
view of the case as raised by the (government's) complaint is not
as narrow as yours.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft spokesman Jim Cullinan said the company would comply
with Jackson's order as soon as possible, though he said it still
was unclear how many documents were involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue was never that we wouldn't produce the documents,''
Cullinan said. ``The issue is basically whether the government
should be allowed to rewrite and expand its case at the last
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Wall, a partner with McCutchen, Doyle, Brown &AMP; Enersen of
San Francisco, said the government's case was weakened in June when
a federal appeals court ruled that Microsoft's browser was legally
integrated into the Windows 95 &UR;  &LR; operating system.
</P>
<P>
   So the government, as in many monopoly cases, needs to bolster
its case by using the ``classic antitrust argument'' that there was
a wide pattern of monopolistic abuse, said Wall, a former Justice
Department attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plaintiff in an antitrust case tries to create a stew,''
Wall said. ``You try to put some meat and potatoes in to make it an
interesting stew. They (the government) obviously thought the broth
was a little thin.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has scheduled a September 11 hearing on Microsoft's
motion to dismiss all or part of the case. Another hearing is
scheduled for September 17 on Microsoft's motion to avoid
broadening the scope of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he allows the case to be expanded, he should grant a delay
_ and most judges would _ to give Microsoft time to respond to the
new allegations,'' Wall said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
