r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      09-03 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Behind the Scenes at Robertson Stephens' Investment Arm   By Mark Veverka  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Now that the divorce between Robertson Stephens and BankAmerica
(soon to be NationsBank) has been finalized this week, the
investment bank's former money management group is going through
some separation anxiety.
<TEXT>
<P>
   BankBoston closed its buyout of Robertson Stephens earlier this
week, giving the technology boutique yet another new moniker:
BankBoston Robertson Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   The deal rids NationsBank, which bought the former Montgomery
Securities, of the duplication dilemma it would have faced when the
Charlotte bank officially takes over BofA in October. (Montgomery
and Robby would have overlapped considerably).
</P>
<P>
   The odd guy out in this complicated merger mess has been Robby's
struggling investment arm, which is still owned by BofA but on the
block.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the fund group _ Robertson Stephens Investment
Management _ is still trying to get its house in order before being
sold.
</P>
<P>
   The investment arm has filed documents with the Securities and
Exchange Commission that would allow it to merge one of its
underperforming funds into another fund, which itself has been
lackluster.
</P>
<P>
   In a story reported in the financial trade paper InvestmentNews,
Robertson Stephens Investment Management is seriously mulling a
plan to merge its malnourished Developing Countries Fund into its
small-cap value Partners Fund. Developing Countries has been unable
to attract enough new investors to cover its costs, confirms a
Robertson Stephens Investment Management spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Developing Countries isn't expected to turn around
in the near future, the spokeswoman says. Across the board,
emerging markets funds have been hammered largely by the Asian
economic crisis. But Robby Investment's Developing Countries fund
has performed even worse than its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Fund analysts question the logic behind rolling an emerging
markets fund into a small-cap value fund because the categories are
so vastly different and don't usually coexist. For its part, Robby
Investment is saying that no final decision has been made, and it
is considering other alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if implemented, the move is curious at best. And it
raises questions as to whether there are any serious outside
suitors interested at all in buying Robby Investment.
</P>
<P>
   But apparently some sort of deal is in the works. Robby
Investment President Randy Hecht ``doesn't see a definitive
agreement shaping up until the end of September,'' the spokeswoman
says.
</P>
<P>
   What's the word on the Street? Investment banking and money
management sources speculate that the fund group's management may
be holding out to buy the unit at a discount.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
