<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-FBN-WOODSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAVENS' WOODSON SAID TO VIOLATE DRUG POLICY  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rod Woodson of the Baltimore Ravens, a member of the National
Football League's 75th anniversary team, violated the league's
substance-abuse policy last month when he refused to take a second
random drug test, according to executives from several teams. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Woodson, one of the best cornerbacks to play the game, did not
fail the drug test, but according to the league's drug policy, a
refusal to take a test counts as a failure. Therefore, Woodson
entered Stage 1 of the league's substance-abuse program. It calls
for an evaluation by a psychiatrist, as well as an increase in
random drug testing.
</P>
<P>
   If Woodson, who has never failed a drug test, refuses to take
another random test, he could be suspended for four games.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the secrecy of its drug program, no one in the NFL is
allowed to comment, and neither are officials from the players
association. Woodson could not be reached for comment and his
agent, Eugene Parker, did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Players are randomly selected by the league's computer for
testing for illegal substances such as marijuana or cocaine and
performance-enhancing substances such as steroids and
androstenedione. Woodson was tested and, according to NFL team
executives, passed the test.
</P>
<P>
   But the following day, Woodson's name was again randomly
generated by the computer. The league executives said some players
during the season are randomly selected four, five or even six
times and most do not complain or refuse to take the test. Each
player in the NFL is randomly tested each season at least once.
</P>
<P>
   Woodson was infuriated when he was selected again, saying he had
already been tested only a day earlier and he was not going to be
tested again, several team executives said. He stormed out of the
testing area and, one team executive said, ``was very nasty.''
</P>
<P>
   Several days later, after Woodson had calmed down, he took the
second test and again did not test positive for any illegal or
banned substances.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the NFL was upset with Woodson for refusing to take the
test at first. The league felt that someone of his stature _ a
future Hall of Famer _ should have taken the test and not set a bad
example for other players.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens' owner, Art Modell, said he had no knowledge of
Woodson's situation. The NFL and players association have been
discussing the matter.
</P>
<P>
   There are three things that could happen:
</P>
<P>
   1. Woodson remains in Stage 1, is evaluated by a therapist who
determines he does not have a problem, and since he has not failed
any tests, he is released from the program.
</P>
<P>
   2. The NFL could reach a compromise with the union on Woodson's
behalf and Woodson could be reprimanded or fined in place of being
in the drug program.
</P>
<P>
   3. The NFL could stick to the letter of the law and Woodson
would remain in the program. Woodson could then appeal and an
arbitrator would either uphold the NFL's decision or throw it out.
</P>
<P>
   Woodson, however, will play in the team's opener against his old
team, the Pittsburgh Steelers, on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2147EDT &QL; 
