   (NYT13) ATLANTA -- Sept. 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN. SEPT., 6 --
MUTFUND-SHORT, 9-3 -- Michael Orkin, the portfolio manager of the
Caldwell and Orkin Market Opportunity fund, is a big-picture
thinker. He expects ``a significant bear market between now and the
next 10 years with a 60 percent-plus downside.'' (Alan S.
Weiner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- Sept. 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN. SEPT., 6 --
ABOUT-CARS-ISUZU, 9-3 -- With the Amigo, Isuzu has a mini-utility
worthy of challenging the Jeep Wrangler. The 1998 Amigo still comes
with a canvas top and soft plastic windows in the back. But a
hard-roof option is due this summer, as a 1999 model. Moreover,
both the softtop and hardtop versions offer more of what appealed
to buyers of the old Amigo, plus an optional dose of muscle and
luxury. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- Sept. 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 6 --
CAR-SMART-KIA, 9-3 -- The 1999 Kia Sportage has some rough edges,
but it won't give anyone a case of sticker shock. While the
Sportage two-door convertible from Korea is certainly ready to
deliver fun, fun, fun for the beach-blanket crowd, there's no
mistaking it for the more polished, car-like miniature sport
utilities from Japan. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Sept. 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 6 --
PRISONER-BERENSON-C0X, 9-3 -- Mark and Rhoda Berenson hold a photo
of their daughter, Lori, taken about a year before she was arrested
and convicted in 1996. The 28-year-old MIT graduate was convicted
of plotting to take over Peru's Congress by hooded judges during a
secret trial. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 3, 1998 -- SUB-CRASH-OBIT-MANN,
9-3 -- A total of 136 U.S. citizens, including Dr. Jonathan Mann of
Harvard's School of Public Health, a leading AIDS expert, were
among 229 people from 14 countries who died when Swissair flight
111 crashed at 9:30 p.m. Wednesday into the sea off Canada,
officials said Thursday. Swissair said there were no survivors in
the worst disaster in the country's 70-year-long aviation history.
(Wendy Maeda/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) PEGGY'S COVE, Nova Scotia -- Sept. 3, 1998 --
SUB-CRASH-RDP, 9-3 -- Police examining debris found at sea -
possibly part of the outer skin of the plane - from the Wednesday
night crash of Swissair flight 111. A total of 136 U.S. citizens,
including a leading AIDS expert, were among 229 people from 14
countries who died when the Swissair jet crashed at 9:30 p.m.
Wednesday into the sea off Canada, officials said on Thursday.
(Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) OYSTER BAY, N.Y. -- Sept. 3, 1998 -- SAGAMORE-HILL-2, 9-3
-- The bird sanctuary at the Theodore Roosevelt grave site in
Sagamore Hill. Roosevelt's beloved estate in Oyster Bay on Long
Island, more than any other, seems the perfect home in which to
have grown up. (Lois Raimondo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) OYSTER BAY, N.Y. -- Sept. 3, 1998 -- SAGAMORE-HILL-1, 9-3
-- A view of Sagamore Hill, Theodore Roosevelt's beloved estate in
Oyster Bay on Long Island. This rambling brick, stone and wood
house close to Long Island Sound is a storybook set piece of eaved
attic aeries, bay windows, rainbow glints of stained glass, and
surprise rooms whimsically tucked into unexpected corners across
three floors. A child could feel luxuriously lost yet totally
secure in one of those rooms. (Lois Raimondo/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Sept. 3, 1998 -- MCCALLUM-THEATER, 9-3 --
David McCallum's current assignment is playing a befuddled security
guard in Alan Ayckbourn's comedy ``Communicating Doors.'' ``It's
been 30 years, but I can't escape him. Illya Kuryakin is there 24
hours a day,'' he says of the role for which most fans remember
him: Kuryakin, the brooding, mysterious Russian operative in the
1960s joke-and-dagger spy series ``The Man From U.N.C.L.E.'' (Linda
Rosier/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) HARWICH, Mass. -- Sept. 3, 1998 -- ORIGINAL-BATMAN-BOS,
9-3 -- Ruth Foster holds her late husband, Frank's, 1932 drawings
of Batman. The drawings, if they are the real thing, came seven
years before the first Batman comic book hit the newsstands.
Foster, who died more than three years ago, went to his grave
believing his idea was lifted either by Bob Kane, who is recognized
as Batman's inventors Kane's employer, D.C. Comics. (Pam
Berry/Boston Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Sept. 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN. SEPT., 6 --
MARSHALL-MENENTOS-ART, 9-3 -- Kerry James Marshall in his studio.
Some of Marshall's new work is featured in ``Mementos,'' which
opens Friday at the Brooklyn Museum, where it is supplemented by a
small selection of works dating from 1994 to 1996. Although it
includes four large bannerlike paintings, ``Mementos'' is a single
installation, or suite of works, that also contains sculpture,
photography, prints and video of images and slogans associated with
the racial struggles of the 60's. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Sept. 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN. SEPT., 6 --
ERNESTO-PUJOL-ART, 9-2 -- Ernesto Pujol in his Brooklyn studio with
a new work, a photograph showing men's feet, shod and unshod. The
Linda Kirkland Gallery will present this, Pujol's first
photographic efforts in a group show titled ``Some Like it Hot.''
The exhibition opens Saturday and runs through Oct. 17. (Nancy
Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Sept. 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN. SEPT., 6 --
EMMYLOU-HARRIS-MUSIC, 9-2 -- Emmylou Harris waits backstage before
the taping an appearance on ``Late Night With Conan O'Brien.''
``I'm fortunate in that for me there's life beyond radio,'' Ms.
Harris, now 51, who first came to prominence while singing harmony
with the country rock artist Gram Parsons in the 1970s. ``I stick
my head in the sand and get to do the kind of music I want to do.''
Her new album, ``Spyboy,'' is a live career retrospective. (Andrea
Mohin/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
