<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SOHO-SATELLITE-NY     09-03 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SOHO-SATELLITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SATELLITE TO STUDY SUN IS REVIVING FROM DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The disabled SOHO spacecraft is responding to
commands and slowly recovering from a series of ground control
errors that almost caused the loss of the valuable scientific
observatory, officials said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers are gradually reawakening the joint American-European
spacecraft, the Solar and Heliospheric Observatory, which went
silent more than a month ago. Astronomers believe it may be
possible to have the $1 billion spacecraft back in operation in a
couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   At a joint news conference held here and in Paris by the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration and the European
Space Agency, officials released results of an investigation board
into how controllers lost communication with SOHO on June 24, when
it spun out of control and could not get adequate power from the
Sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board has concluded that there were no anomalies onboard
the SOHO spacecraft, but that a number of ground errors led to the
major loss of attitude experienced by the spacecraft,'' the panel's
report said.
</P>
<P>
   The board, made up of engineers and officials from the two space
agencies, said the loss of SOHO was a direct result of operational
errors, a failure to adequately monitor the status of the
spacecraft and the use of rescue procedures that had not been
adequately tested.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Roger Bonnet, the European agency's director of science,
said from Paris that there was no single cause or single individual
responsible for what happened to the spacecraft, but that numerous
factors and people were at fault. ``The report points a finger at
nobody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The solar observatory was launched on Dec. 2. 1995. SOHO is
equipped with special instruments to study sunlight at different
wavelengths and to analyze particles and magnetic fields generated
by the Sun. The satellite orbits at a point between Earth and the
Sun where the gravity of each body cancels out the other and keeps
the craft in a stable spot.
</P>
<P>
   Since its launching, SOHO has made numerous major discoveries,
including rivers of charged particles flowing over the surface of
the Sun and the first detection of sunquakes, and has charted
streams of plasma moving from the Sun to Earth as well as 51 comets
passing near or colliding with the Sun, said Dr. Joseph Gurman,
NASA's project scientist for the mission.
</P>
<P>
   Although the spacecraft was designed to operate for only two
years, scientists had hoped to continue the mission into the next
century, as the Sun goes through a period of maximum activity.
</P>
<P>
   The report released on Thursday said controllers had lost
control of the craft during a maintenance period in which several
recalibration operations normally done separately were compressed
together. This resulted in using new procedures for the first time,
which led to problems.
</P>
<P>
   No one noticed that one of three gyroscopes, spinning devices
that help stabilize the craft, was turned off after it was tested,
the report said. Computer instructions sent to the craft that would
be used in case of emergencies required this gyroscope to be
running, it said, and when the craft later went into this safety
mode when problems arose, the trouble cascaded.
</P>
<P>
   The control team did not adequately check the status of the
craft while trying to bring it back on line and used a series of
new instructions written in previous months to streamline
operations that had not been adequately tested, the board said.
</P>
<P>
   The panel recommended a series of procedural changes and testing
of computer programs that it said should prevent such problems in
the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
