<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT ORDERED TO PROVIDE MORE ANTITRUST EVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge ordered the Microsoft Corp.
Thursday to give the Justice Department reams of new evidence that
government lawyers say will bolster their antitrust case against
the software giant.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's lawyers had argued that the new evidence, intended
to demonstrate that the company pressured and bullied the Intel
Corp., Apple Computer and the Real Networks Corp., should not be a
part of the case since it was not specifically mentioned in the
original lawsuits filed by the Justice Department and 20 states on
May 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these things are the subjects of whole trials,'' John
Warden, a Microsoft lawyer, complained to Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson of United States district court at a hearing Thursday
afternoon. ``There has to be an end to bringing in new matters that
we have to be prepared to defend ourselves against.''
</P>
<P>
   Warden warned that Microsoft would ask for a six-month delay in
the trial, which is scheduled to begin in just three weeks, if the
company was suddenly required to defend itself against all of the
new evidence, too.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Department lawyers argued that it was common and
natural to come upon new evidence during pretrial discovery and
research. And once the judge satisfied himself that the government
was asking for evidence only to bolster existing charges against
Microsoft _ not new charges _ he ordered the company to comply.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he would hear Microsoft's request for a substantial
delay during another scheduled hearing later this month. And the
judge noted that he could, if he chose, rule to exclude the new
evidence at that time.
</P>
<P>
   With the new evidence, government lawyers say they plan to show
that Microsoft used its dominant position in the market for
computer operating systems to force companies that competed with it
in other areas to cede the market to Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, the Justice Department and 20 states said they
would use the material to show that Microsoft tried to force other
companies to end any support for the Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape makes a browser, the software used to navigate the
World Wide Web, that is the principal competition to Microsoft's
browser, and Microsoft's many-faceted effort to win the competition
with Netscape is the central focus of the antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new evidence shows that Microsoft has gone out and
engaged in the same kinds of anti-competitive behavior with other
companies as they did with Netscape,'' said David Boies, a Justice
Department lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Warden told Jackson that Microsoft had only recently learned
that government lawyers were interested in Microsoft's interactions
with these other companies, leaving the company no time to prepare
a defense.
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers said they had asked numerous questions on
these subjects during pretrial interviews that had been under way
for weeks. But, Warden said, ``Dribbling stuff out in the course of
depositions, during expedited proceedings, does not constitute
adequate notice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
