<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PENALTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUMBER OF EXECUTIONS IN CHINA SEEMS TO DECLINE, RIGHTS GROUP SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (af)  
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The number of criminals executed in China appears to
have dropped significantly in the last year, since the passage of a
new criminal law that restricts use of the death sentence, human
rights monitors say. But they emphasize that China still executes
far more people than any other nation.
</P>
<P>
   Relying on Chinese news media accounts of executions, a new
report to be released by Amnesty International on Saturday
estimates there were about 3,000 executions in 1997, down from
4,367 the year before. The group cautioned that since the Chinese
government guards the number of executions as a state secret, the
actual number may be far higher than its estimate and the apparent
drop may be misleading.
</P>
<P>
   But prominent judges in China have also noted the trend. John
Kamm, a San Francisco businessman and human rights activist who
frequently visits China, said that this week a supreme court judge
told him there had been a ``big, big drop'' in the number of
executions since the criminal code was enacted last year.
</P>
<P>
   But Catherine Baber, a researcher for Amnesty International in
Hong Kong was reluctant to celebrate. ``It may well be that there
is some reduction,'' she said. ``But we're playing blind. It would
help matters a lot if the Chinese government would back up its
claims with numbers and document the crimes involved.
</P>
<P>
   With Mary Robinson, the U.N. human rights commissioner due to
arrive here this week, the klieg lights are on China's human rights
record. China has promised to sign the International Covenant on
Civil and Political Rights, Convention, but has not specified when.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the revision in the Criminal Procedure Code, which
took effect in October 1997, does afford defendants at least
somewhat improved protection from capital punishment, at least on
paper.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese judges have traditionally enjoyed broad discretion in
handing out sentences, including death sentences, which have been
given for a wide range of crimes including rape, murder, forgery,
corruption, drug trafficking and robbery.
</P>
<P>
   But legal experts have long complained that Chinese courts are
so arbitrary and inconsistent that some criminals who were executed
were charged with relatively minor offenses. For example, Ma
Zhaochen, a peasant from Henan Province, was sentenced to death two
years ago after a string of petty robberies, that brought him a
total of $1600.
</P>
<P>
   The new Criminal Procedure Code gives judges some guidelines as
to when the death penalty may be considered, stipulating for
example that only robberies involving banks or the theft of
cultural relics merit execution, Kamm said.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking with the past, it says that pregnant women and juvenile
offenders cannot be executed.
</P>
<P>
   Kamm, who has for seven years coaxed and reasoned with the
Chinese government to gain the release of prisoners held for their
political and religious beliefs, said that Chinese officials have
showed greater willingness to discuss aspects of their justice
system since the summit meeting between President Clinton and
President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
   After two and a half years of stonewalling, the Ministry of
Justice has started to provide Kamm with information about
prisoners he has inquired about. In 1995, as part of Kamm's
``Prisoner Information Project,'' the government agreed to give him
information on a list of 100 people who were in jail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
