<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8241 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-INQUIRY-HNS &LR;      09-03 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-INQUIRY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH INQUIRY BEGINS AS GRISLY SEARCH FOR BODIES CONTINUES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ Searchers, by air and sea, scoured the
gray Atlantic on Thursday for wreckage and remains from the crash
of a Swissair jumbo jet that killed all 229 aboard, including 136
U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian law enforcement and transport authorities, beginning
what could be a months-long investigation, refused to rule out
terrorism as a cause but said there was no immediate reason to
believe that a criminal act downed the New York-to-Geneva flight
near this provincial capital. A Swissair official contended the
plane was ``in perfect working order.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. government agencies, including the FBI, monitored the
search and assisted the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``All initial information indicates that it was an accident,''
U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno said in Washington. President
Clinton, traveling in Northern Ireland, said, ``We are deeply
grieved.''
</P>
<P>
   At least seven United Nations' staff members were on the flight,
which a spokesman for the world organization likened to ``the U.N.
airbus'' because it shuttled daily from New York, the U.N.
headquarters, to the Swiss city where many of its international
agencies have offices. Swissair said passengers were from 14
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Among the passengers was a key AIDS researcher, Dr. Jonathan
Mann, a former professor at the Harvard School of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot of Flight 111 alerted air controllers to a crisis,
including smoke inside the cockpit, within an hour of departing
from New York's John F. Kennedy International Airport and was being
directed toward an emergency landing at Halifax. Efforts to
stabilize the three-engine MD-11 failed, and 10 minutes before it
was expected at Halifax the plane crashed in the Atlantic Ocean
about five miles off picturesque Peggy's Cove.
</P>
<P>
   The plane went down about 10:30 p.m. Atlantic time Wednesday
(9:30 p.m. EDT), with 215 passengers, including two infants, and 14
crew members.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Peggy's Cove and Blandford, the two points at the
southern end of St. Margarets Bay, reported hearing a
window-rattling thud.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis, from the time that the plane was at 33,000 feet and
the crew reported smoke until it disappeared from controllers'
radar, lasted about 15 minutes, Canadian officials said. The final
communication from the plane, aviation sources said, was the
pilot's message of ``pan, pan, pan,'' the ultimate distress call.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers were apparently aware that the plane was in
trouble. Searchers reported that at least some of the corpses were
wearing life vests. Philippe Bruggisser, chief executive officer of
Swissair's parent group, said in Zurich, Switzerland, that the crew
had prepared the passengers for an emergency landing.
</P>
<P>
   At midday Thursday, the Royal Canadian Mounted Police said 36
bodies had been recovered from the chill waters, but RCMP Lt. Cmdr.
Glen Chamberlain almost immediately added that his agency would not
update the count soon. He indicated that was because the number of
severed body parts being found made it difficult to determine how
many different bodies had been located.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as confusing, as grisly as that,'' Chamberlain said.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies and body parts as well as small pieces of the plane
and crash debris were taken aboard a flotilla of boats that
included official Canadian vessels and fishing craft from the
villages that dot the coast southwest of Halifax. Sorting of the
recovered items, primarily clothing and baggage, and possible
reassembly of the plane was expected to be carried out at Canadian
Forces Base Shearwater in Dartmouth, across the harbor from
Halifax.
</P>
<P>
   The wreckage was scattered over a six square mile area, Canadian
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Nova Scotia Premier Russell MacLellan said searchers had ``a
good idea where the plane rests,'' in up to 150 feet of water. RCMP
officials said, however, it was not certain when divers would
attempt to recover the two crucial recorders that should have
captured the cockpit conversation and instrument readings from the
crippled plane.
</P>
<P>
   Without that data, said Benoit Bouchard, chairman of Canada's
Transportation Safety Board, theories of what happened to the
flight were speculation, and he offered no interim judgment on what
downed the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the data gathering process,'' said Dick Derden, chief
accident investigator. He commiserated with victims' families as
well as the public: ``I know everyone would like to know'' the
cause.
</P>
<P>
   The crash comes about two years after another jumbo jet bound
from New York to Europe crashed in the Atlantic. TWA Flight 800, a
Boeing 747, went down in July 1996 off Long Island, N.Y. The cause
of the crash has not been pinpointed, although attention focused on
electrical and fuel-vapor problems in an empty center fuel tank.
U.S. government investigators have ruled out foul play. Families of
the TWA victims have accused the U.S. investigators of
foot-dragging and indecision.
</P>
<P>
   Families and friends of the Swissair passengers were offered
consolation and grief counseling at the New York and Geneva
airports, and Swissair said it would fly relatives to Halifax,
where local officials began searching for 900 hotel rooms as the
summer tourist season tapered off.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard and Derden were questioned closely about the decision
of air traffic controllers at Moncton, New Brunswick, to have the
Swissair flight attempt to land at Halifax.
</P>
<P>
   Derden confirmed that the pilot, identified by Swissair as Urs
Zimmermann, first asked to be diverted to Boston and had turned
back toward the U.S. city when he was told by a Moncton controller
that Halifax was closer. At that point, a Canadian aviation source
said, the plane was about 200 miles from Boston and 50 miles from
Halifax.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot indicated the plane was too heavy to land immediately
at Halifax and apparently began to dump more than 100,000 pounds of
jet fuel in the waters off Halifax. With a fuel load for a
trans-Atlantic flight, the plane would have been so heavy that it
could have been unable to stop before running off the Halifax
runway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have turned or maneuvered'' in the dumping process,
Derden said, refusing to assess what that might have meant in the
flight's final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Georges Schorderet, chief financial officer of Swissair parent
SAirGroup, said the MD-11 entered service in August 1991 and was
overhauled about a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This airplane was in perfect working order,`` Schorderet said.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard said he had consulted with Jim Hall, chairman of the
U.S. National Transportation Safety Board, who had dispatched
agents to Canada. Under an international agreement, the United
States, as home of the aircraft's manufacturer, McDonnell Douglas
(since bought by Boeing), and Switzerland, as home of the plane's
licensing owner, can participate in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already had wonderful collaboration,'' Bouchard said
during an afternoon news conference at Peggy's Cove.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
