<SLUG> BC-NY-ROSS-CAMPAIGN-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEUTENANT GOVERNOR LOSES HUSBAND'S FINANCING IN GUBERNATORIAL
RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lt. Gov. Betsy McCaughey Ross announced Thursday that
her husband had withdrawn most of the financial backing for her
gubernatorial candidacy, forcing her to drastically scale back her
campaign and curtail the extensive round of television advertising
that most politicians say is critical to her success in the
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCaughey Ross, who is seeking the Democratic nomination to
challenge Gov. George Pataki, attributed the campaign retrenchment
to what she described as a ``substantially reduced contribution
from my husband,'' Wilbur Ross Jr., a senior managing director of
Rothschild Inc. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   She left little doubt, in a generally cheerful interview, that
Ross had essentially cut the legs out from under what had been the
grander ambitions of his wife's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am entering the final stage of my campaign with a much
lighter pocketbook,'' Ms. McCaughey Ross declared. But she said she
was not discouraged, adding that her husband had promised enough
money to pay for some advertisements in the last six days of the
race, and pledging to turn her adversity to her advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an empowering event,'' Ms. McCaughey Ross said, after
returning from a campaign stop at a pizza shop in lower Manhattan,
where she said she was cheered by a lunch-time crowd. ``I am $2
million lighter and going strong. It was such a wonderful feeling
to hear people say, `You go girl!'''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by Ms. McCaughey Ross capped weeks of turmoil
in her campaign, with senior staff aides streaming out and some
Democratic supporters expressing second thoughts about backing her.
Taken together, the events suggested that her campaign _ which had
once been seen as formidable, in part because of her husband's
promise of support and in part because she is the only woman in the
Democratic field _ is in danger of becoming marginalized.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCaughey Ross said she was not prepared to discuss the
reasons for her husband's withdrawal of the donation. ``It was for
reasons unrelated to this campaign, for personal and financial
reasons,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, who was in Anchorage, Alaska, on business, did not return
telephone calls Thursday. His associates said his decision was
based, in part, on his own financial difficulties, the result of
losses in the stock market, and, in part, on polls that persuaded
him that his wife's chances of becoming the next governor of New
York were not good.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCaughey Ross, addressing a question that had been raised
by many of her supporters as she and her husband engaged in an
unusually public negotiation over his commitment to her political
career, said that their marriage remained intact. ``We're fine,''
she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. McCaughey Ross said Thursday evening that Ross was taking
back $2.25 million he had put into her campaign. She said that
would leave her husband's total overall contribution _ including
cash and in-kind contributions in the form of rent for the town
house that serves as her campaign headquarters _ at $1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that money has already been spent on staff, polling and
petition drives. Asked if her husband might give her more money,
Ms. McCaughey Ross laughed and said, ``I am sure he would prefer to
speak for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCaughey Ross said her husband's remaining money, plus
whatever funds she could raise, would go to television advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The television advertising will be less extensive than my
supporters and I had originally hoped,'' she said, though she
asserted it would be ``competitive and effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Associates of the couple put the advertising figure at around
$800,000. The ads are to be filmed this weekend and are to start
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But even this latest modest promise by Ross was greeted
cautiously by his wife's supporters, some of whom said they were
shellshocked by the latest turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   Since March, the candidate and her husband have been promising
that the television campaign was imminent, and disenchantment has
grown with each passing week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll believe it when I see it,'' one of Ms. McCaughey Ross'
supporters said Thursday about the latest promise.
</P>
</TEXT>
