<SLUG> BC-BBO-HOMERUN-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIZARRE COINCIDENCES LIVEN HOME RUN RECORD CHASE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa, separated by three home runs in
their quest to break Roger Maris' record, take a bizarre
coincidence into their games Friday night as their spirited rivalry
resumes.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, only two away from tying the 37-year-old record, is at
home in St. Louis, facing the Cincinnati Reds, the only National
League team that has not allowed any of his 59 home runs. Sosa
plays in Pittsburgh, where the Chicago Cubs open a weekend series
with the Pirates, whose pitchers are the only ones in the league
who have not given up any of his 56 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   With four home runs in his last five official times at bat,
McGwire conceivably could reach 62 before the end of the weekend,
but he'll have to do better against the scheduled starters, Pete
Harnisch, Dennis Reyes and Brett Tomko, and their relief help, than
he did in the first six games between the teams in the first half
of July.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire not only didn't hit a home run against the Reds, but he
also managed to get only two hits in 13 at-bats. He walked 11
times. The only game the Reds didn't walk him was the one in which
he only pinch-hit. He did not face Harnisch, Friday night's
starter, in any of those games.
</P>
<P>
   Harnisch and Tomko have given up 21 home runs each, making them
the team leaders in that department.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is on a torrid home run streak, hitting 12 in the
Cardinals' last 17 games and in only 52 at-bats. He didn't play in
one of those games, pinch-hit in another and was ejected in yet
another after heatedly disputing a called third strike in the first
inning.
</P>
<P>
   It was only last Monday that Sosa caught McGwire, hitting his
55th home run against Tomko at Wrigley Field in Chicago. But just
as he has whenever Sosa has tied him, McGwire responded almost
immediately. The next night, against the Marlins in Florida,
McGwire cracked his 56th and 57th home runs.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday afternoon, Sosa chipped away at McGwire's lead,
hitting a home run against Jason Bere of the Reds. But in
consecutive at-bats that night against the friendly Florida
pitchers, McGwire created an even wider gap, slugging Nos. 58 and
59.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa appeared in five of the six games the Cubs played against
the Pirates in July, collecting four hits in 20 at-bats and
striking out nine times. The Pirates walked him only twice.
</P>
<P>
   He is scheduled to face Jason Schmidt Friday night, Sean
Lawrence Saturday night and Chris Peters Sunday. The Cubs beat
Schmidt and Peters in July.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the record is broken this weekend, the series in St.
Louis and Pittsburgh will serve only as a prelude to the two-game
series in St. Louis next Monday and Tuesday. Those are the days the
Cubs will visit Busch Stadium, setting up the prospect of a
shootout for the record between the two challengers.
</P>
<P>
   In their previous head-to-head confrontations, McGwire hit his
11th, 12th, 46th, 48th and 49th home runs while Sosa hit his
seventh, 44th and 48th.
</P>
<P>
   It was the last game with the Cubs, in fact, that got McGwire
out of his drought. He had hit only two home runs in the Cardinals'
previous 18 games when he suddenly connected for a pair against
Terry Mulholland and Matt Karchner of the Cubs. That explosion
triggered the torrent of home runs that has placed him on the
threshold of the record of 61 that Maris set in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   There will be one difference in the games the Cardinals and the
Cubs will play. The Cardinals are not in a race for a postseason
spot; the Cubs are. They hold a one-game lead over the Mets, who
play the Atlanta Braves this weekend. Sosa has said his first
priority is to play in October. McGwire doesn't have that option
this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
