<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT SENATOR CALLS CLINTON'S BEHAVIOR `IMMORAL' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a sign of the political trouble lying ahead,
Sen. Joseph Lieberman, a moderate Democrat and longtime ally of
President Clinton, harshly rebuked the president Thursday for his
``immoral'' relationship with Monica Lewinsky and for lying about
it for seven months.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who said the president had ``compromised his moral
authority,'' was the first member of either party to criticize
Clinton from the Senate floor since he went on national television
to acknowledge his affair with the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president apparently had extramarital relations with an
employee half his age and did so in the workplace in the vicinity
of the Oval Office. Such behavior is not just inappropriate, it is
immoral,'' said Lieberman, whose association with Clinton goes back
almost three decades.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut senator said that while he feels ``deep
disappointment and personal anger,'' toward the president, it would
be ``unjust and unwise'' for Congress to consider any formal action
against Clinton until the legal process plays out.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-minute speech by Lieberman was immediately praised by
Republican Majority Leader Trent Lott and by two other moderate
Democratic senators _ Patrick Moynihan of New York and Bob Kerrey
of Nebraska. Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle, who earlier this
week urged Democrats to stick with the president, put his arm
around Lieberman and whispered to him privately.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Clinton was in Ireland on Thursday and had not heard
Lieberman's remarks, said White House spokesman Barry Toiv, adding
that Clinton has ``great respect'' for the senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always hardest to hear criticism from a friend, but I am
sure the president will consider Sen. Lieberman's words with the
same care with which they were delivered,'' Toiv said.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials had known Lieberman was preparing a
statement and feared he might deliver it while Clinton was meeting
with Russian President Boris Yeltsin earlier this week. At the
urging of White House Chief of Staff Erskine Bowles, Lieberman
agreed to delay his remarks until the Russian leg of Clinton's trip
was over.
</P>
<P>
   While calling talk of impeachment and resignation ``premature,''
Lieberman urged other lawmakers to speak out against the immorality
of Clinton's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's relationship with Ms. Lewinsky not only
contradicted the values he has publicly embraced over the last six
years,'' Lieberman said. ``It has, I fear, compromised his moral
authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he disagrees with Clinton's contention that the
public should not be inquiring into his private affairs. ``I
disagree that this is nobody's business,'' the senator said. ``The
reality is that, in 1998, the president's private life is public.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman and Clinton have known each other since 1970, when
Clinton, then a law student at Yale University, was a volunteer in
Lieberman's first political campaign _ a run for the U.S. House _
which he lost. Lieberman is chairman of the Democratic Leadership
Council, a moderate group once headed by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman called the president's public statements _ both on
Aug. 17 and his remarks this week from Russia _ inadequate. The
senator said Clinton should fully accept responsibility for his
extramarital affair and for his seven-month lie.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan praised Lieberman for saying ``what needed to be
said.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey shared Lieberman's view that a White House affair is not
simply a private matter and echoed Lieberman's call for Clinton
``to go far further than what he did`` in his Aug. 17 confession.
``It was not just inappropriate behavior,'' the Nebraskan said.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan agreed. ``It was not adequate,'' he said, adding that
Lieberman's remarks reflected ``the full measure of that
inadequacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Since January, independent counsel Kenneth Starr has been
investigating whether Clinton lied under oath or engaged in an
illegal cover-up of his relationship with Lewinsky. Starr and his
team of prosecutors are preparing a report that is expected to
arrive at the Capitol in late September.
</P>
<P>
   Republican officials in the House are preparing to receive the
report and to conduct a closed-door review to determine if an
formal impeachment inquiry should be held. If articles of
impeachment are voted out of the House, the Senate would be called
on to hear the case and decide whether to remove the president from
office.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
