<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WOMEN-SLAIN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURSUIT OF COMPLAINTS BY POLICE QUESTIONED IN MURDER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER and JANE GROSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ A day after an unemployed school aide was
arrested for the murder of one woman and was first suspected in the
death of seven others, new questions arose Thursday over how
aggressively police pursued complaints from at least two
prostitutes who contended that they were assaulted by the suspect
in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of four of the women that the school aide, Kendall
Francois, 27, is suspected of murdering over two years have been
removed from his parents' house here near the campus of Vassar
College. But officials said that they knew there still were more
bodies to be removed.
</P>
<P>
   Georgiana Johnson, hovering at the crime scene, said that her
daughter, Debbie Annan, who was not killed, had twice told police
that she barely escaped alive from an encounter with Francois, who
had picked her up on the corner of Academy and Montgomery Street,
took her to his home for paid sex and attempted to strangle her.
Mrs. Johnson said that her daughter, then an addict and prostitute
who occasionally assisted police in undercover drug operations, had
given detectives Francois' name and address as early as last
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``They totally ignored her,'' said Mrs. Johnson, one of many
friends and relatives of the victims who stood outside 99 Fulton
Ave. Mrs. Johnson added that her daughter now lives in Ocala, Fla.,
clean of her crack addiction and is working double shifts as a
cashier at a convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   A similar story was told by a second woman, a one-time
prostitute who now lives outside Poughkeepsie, in Dutchess County,
and was interviewed on tape by WCBS radio's Irene Cornell. The
woman said that she told police that Francois had tried to strangle
her in November 1996, a month after the first disappearance in the
case. She remembered that during the assault Francois suddenly
stopped himself from choking her and said: ``Oh my God, I almost
did it again.'' She too managed to escape and flagged down a squad
car from the town of Poughkeepsie.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Lanza, afternoon producer for the station, declined to
identify the woman, but said she told them that after the incident
she was interviewed twice more by police, once shortly after the
disappearance of the seventh woman missing in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. William Siegrist, a spokesman for the investigating task
force made up of detectives from both the city and town of
Poughkeepsie as well as the state police, would not comment on the
specific complaints. But he defended police handling of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the complaints that came to us were handled in a proper
manner and we have done everything we can to solve this crime,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also denied that because seven of the eight women were street
prostitutes, police were lackadaisical. ``I've tried to maintain
that these women were human beings and should be treated with as
much respect as any other person,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the ramshackle house where Francois lived, investigators
in white jump suits and goggles continued their search for remains
and Mrs. Johnson talked about her daughter's inability to get the
attention of police, saying: ``They didn't even take a report.''
</P>
<P>
   But another parent of a possible victim offered a drastically
different account of how police had pursued the case.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Barone, whose daughter Gina disappeared on Dec. 9,
1996, said investigators followed every lead and interviewed every
person she had suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``They absolutely did their job,'' Mrs. Barone said. ``They
picked up on it the day I reported her missing, and took it from
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Barone, a well-dressed woman accompanied by two nieces,
spoke with uncanny calm, despite the fact that her daughter, a drug
addict since the age of 12, was expected to be among the
decomposing bodies inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my head, I'd come to terms with it,'' Mrs. Barone said. ``I
had a feeling she was gone all this time. I always felt when the
good Lord thought I was ready to hear it, I'd hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dutchess County district attorney, William Grady, declined
to give details of the long investigation into the missing
prostitutes, all of whom are now presumed dead and inside Francois'
house. But the district attorney said that many women had come
forward with accounts of ``rough sex'' with Francois. All of their
stories were taken seriously, the district attorney said,
regardless of their background or demeanor. ``But just because
incidents took place doesn't mean arrests can happen,'' he said.
``You need probable cause, sufficient evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Police Thursday wheeled out a fourth body on a stretcher from
the green clapboard house in which Francois lived with his parents,
McKinley and Paulette Francois, and a teen-age sister, Kirstyn.
They also brought a supply of new rakes and shovels presumably to
dig up more remains or evidence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
