<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8258 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-DEBATE-NYT &LR;      09-03 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-DEBATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SOMETHING LIKE A DEBATE, KOHL DEFENDS WHILE A RELAXED SCHROEDER
TAUNTS HIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ In the closest thing to a televised
presidential debate before elections this month, Chancellor Helmut
Kohl gave a rambling defense Thursday of his role as a statesman
and the architect of German reunification.
</P>
<P>
   Looking avuncular and almost unaware that he is in danger of
losing his bid for re-election in just a few weeks, Kohl, 68,
squared off in parliament against the man who now leads him in
popularity polls: Gerhard Schroeder, 54, the Social Democratic
Party's candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, appearing confident and relaxed in his speech,
accused Kohl of having fallen completely out of touch with the
needs of the country and the demands of the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job of a chancellor is to bring the country together,''
Schroeder taunted. ``There was a time you understood that. But in
the meantime you seem to have totally forgotten it.''
</P>
<P>
   The faceoff had been built up in German media as a climactic
rhetorical duel, the only direct confrontation between Kohl and
Schroeder before the elections on Sept. 27. It was not a debate,
but rather a pair of speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules Thursday, the two candidates merely delivered
rival statements to parliament on the ostensible issue of debating
the latest government budget. There was little opportunity for
spontaneous repartee, clever riposts or other displays of quick
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl, who has been chancellor for 16 years, is in the toughest
fight of his career. With nationwide unemployment at 10.7 percent _
and nearly twice that high in the formerly Communist eastern half
of the country _ Kohl is lagging behind Schroeder in most polls by
three to six percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl has adamantly refused Schroeder's demands to take part in
any sort of American-style debate on prime-time television,
probably because the chancellor cannot begin to compete with his
challenger in performing before the cameras. Kohl often exudes a
homey warmth and an endearing lack of pretentiousness, but he is
also an obese man who wanders into long reminiscences and speaks
indistinctly.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, by contrast, has mastered the art of being at ease
before cameras and projecting a wide range of emotions from humor
to righteous passion.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Thursday, Kohl talked for nearly an hour about his
historical accomplishments as a statesman. He dwelt proudly on his
role in uniting East and West Germany, blasting Schroeder and the
Social Democrats for fretting about the costs.
</P>
<P>
   He talked at length about his role in creating a single European
currency, though that is a change that most Germans are skeptical
about.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, wearing a charcoal-colored suit and striped silk tie,
hammered away at the idea that Kohl has been in power too long and
allowed Germany to sink into record levels of unemployment while
raising taxes ever higher.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder also taunted the chancellor about not entering a true
debate. ``I read all the time I can't be pinned down,'' he said,
alluding to criticisms that he has not given enough detail about
his positions on issues. ``Well, come on then, pin me down.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's performances reinforced the sense that the election
campaign is less about deep policy differences than it is about
images and personalities. Kohl is campaigning on the image of
stability and security, as well as his status as Europe's most
influential leader. His campaign slogan is ``World Class for
Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder is campaigning on the promise of dynamism and personal
abilities. A pragmatist who has tried to blur his party's Socialist
traditions, he is running on an ambiguous idea of forging a ``new
middle'' that defends Germany's generous social programs while
promoting a vaguely pro-business agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates Thursday pledged their allegiance to roughly
similar concepts for broad tax reform as well as to a continuation
of Germany's social-market economy. Both endorsed continued heavy
financial support for eastern Germany, mired in depression and
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl accused Schroeder and the Social Democrats of being
ambivalent supporters of reunifying with East Germany, a charge
that Schroeder denied. Kohl also accused the Social Democrats of
blocking tax reform for the last several years, only to support
their own plan now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like one of Pavlov's experiments with dogs,'' Kohl said.
``You just look at me, and you're already against it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder focused on the argument that Kohl has fallen
completely out of touch. ``At the beginning of our campaign, we
Social Democrats said `Thank you Helmut, but enough is enough,' ''
he said. But now, he continued, ``your people don't even say thank
you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
