<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PURSUIT OF THE PURSUERS, THEN AND NOW  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not hard to imagine how Roger Maris would handle the news
media if he were making his assault on Babe Ruth's record of 60
home runs in 1998. The shy, small-town man from Minnesota and North
Dakota wearied of the pack of reporters who chronicled his 61-home
run season in 1961. What if hundreds of reporters tailed him from
city to city, many from cable television and radio outlets unheard
of 37 years ago? What if a Howard Stern lackey taunted him with
tawdry questions?
</P>
<P>
   A clue to Maris' feelings can be found in ``Roger Maris:
Reluctant Hero,'' an ESPN Classic documentary. Recalling her
husband's funeral in Fargo, N.D., in 1985, Pat Maris said,
``Somebody said to me isn't it funny all these reporters are here,
just freezing by the grave site, and Roger is probably just
laughing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Managing the pressure of nightly questioning without screaming
is a formidable task, so Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire should be
admired for their handling of the news media. Sosa has been a
delight all along; McGwire has loosened during his recent tear.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, after slugging his 58th and 59th home runs
in Florida, McGwire faced a post-game news conference. The sight of
reporters seated in neat rows, not jammed around his locker
shouting questions, delighted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I passed myself,'' he said with a smile, a reference to
exceeding his 58 home run total last season. ``I feel pretty proud
of passing myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Someday, McGwire and Sosa will get their documentaries. A&AMP;E's
``Biography'' series will probably have them done by November. But
Maris is a harder subject. He was most at ease with his wife and
six children, not with a world that did not welcome his surpassing
of Ruth's record. He would have preferred to play his career in
quiet Kansas City, never having been traded to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN Classic's melancholy hourlong film captures his reticence
(Tuesday, at 7:30 p.m. on ESPN and 10 p.m. on ESPN Classic), using
home movies, archival footage and interviews with teammates,
friends, family and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the most reserved, quiet individual I think I ever
knew,'' said Bobby Richardson, a former Yankee second baseman.
``And so I think the press portrayal was not the real Roger
Maris.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably true. Baseball historian Robert Creamer remembers
seeing a gentle Maris, playing with his young children during
spring training. But that image did not prevail. Perhaps if Maris
had hit 61 home runs 10 years before, he might have had an easier
time. But he came along just as the press was growing more
adventurous and seeking something more than pat answers to softball
questions.
</P>
<P>
   The press railed when he refused to talk to reporters after a
mid-September game and was shocked when he sat out the 159th game,
after his 60th home run. He relaxed by walking around Manhattan
with his wife. ``The press couldn't quite understand that,'' Pat
Maris said in the film, ``but he just felt like he really had an
awful lot of pressure and he really needed the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever problems Maris had with the press in 1961, the film
notes that they worsened in 1962. After columnist Jimmy Cannon felt
snubbed by Maris, Cannon unleashed an attack accusing Maris of
``treacherous smallness.''
</P>
<P>
   So Maris was happy to leave New York's harsh glare after the
1966 season for the calm of St. Louis. Now, McGwire is a beloved
monument in St. Louis, and Sosa is delighting Chicago. But both
might as well be playing in our backyards.
</P>
<P>
   Fox and ESPN spent the past week jockeying to take the
McGwire-Sosa saga to an audience broader than the teams' markets,
and they persuaded major-league baseball to let them shift coming
local games to national telecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN will show Friday night's 8 p.m. Cincinnati-St. Louis game.
Fox will show Saturday's 1 p.m. Reds-Cardinals game to 61 percent
of the country; viewers of other games, like the Braves-Mets, will
see McGwire bat during live updates.
</P>
<P>
   If McGwire or Sosa stands at 60 or 61 by Sunday, Fox will show
the Reds-Cardinals game to 80 percent of the country; the rest will
see the Dallas-Arizona football game. Meanwhile, ESPN is holding
discussions with major-league baseball about picking up Sunday's
game if Fox does not. For ESPN, carrying full games will ensure
showing all home runs; on Wednesday, ESPN inexplicably failed to
cut live from its baseball coverage of an Angels-Indians game to
McGwire's 58th and 59th home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN will carry the Cubs-Cardinals game on Monday, Labor Day. On
Tuesday, the Fox-owned cable network FX will carry the
Cubs-Cardinals game; if McGwire or Sosa has 60 or 61, the telecast
will shift to Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're still talking about this next week,'' said Ed Goren,
co-executive producer of Fox Sports, ``put me in a doggie bag.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're watching cartoons or soap operas or sitcoms but not
any of the games, baseball has authorized other networks to show
clips of the 62nd home run as quickly as they wish, rather than
waiting until the game ends.
</P>
<P>
   There may be no way to escape the assault on Roger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
