</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-FAMILIES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES RUSH TO ACCOMMODATE NEEDS OF SURVIVORS' NEXT OF KIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs for additions.)   (See also CRASH-RDP, CRASH-SCENE, CRASH-INQUIRY, CRASH-VICTIMS,
CRASH-OBIT-MANN, CRASH-OBIT-CLEMENTS-MANN and CRASH-OBIT-GERETY)  
(js) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As relatives of passengers aboard Swissair Flight 111 filed into
the Ramada Plaza Hotel at Kennedy International Airport Thursday
and huddled in a private conference room to wrestle with their
grief, the scene carried poignant echoes of July 1996, when
families reeling from the crash of Trans World Airlines Flight 800
gathered under the same roof.
</P>
<P>
   There was a similar sense of astonishment over what had
happened. There was a similar hunger to know how and why.
</P>
<P>
   But what appeared to be missing, at least for now, was the
rancor. For while TWA drew fury from some relatives and politicians
for taking too long to confirm Flight 800's passenger list and not
tending aggressively enough to families' needs, Swissair and Delta,
the U.S. carrier through which some passengers had booked their
tickets, seemed intent on avoiding those charges.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Hauer, director of the mayor's Office of Emergency
Management, said there was ``no comparison'' between the actions of
Swissair and Delta and those of TWA two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an extraordinary amount of care and attention
paid to the details, which can make a horrendous situation that
much more horrendous,'' Hauer said Thursday. ``I've seen questions
get answered, and I've seen needs get met quickly, efficiently and
with great compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who stormed television news programs in
1996 to attack TWA, offered Swissair and Delta nothing but praise
at a press conference early Thursday evening at the Ramada.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines have handled this exceptionally well from the
beginning,'' the mayor said. ``Not only did they have plenty of
people, but they had people trained to know how to deal with this
kind of situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Flight 111 went down on Wednesday around 9:30 p.m. EST, and by
1:10 a.m., according to a spokesman for Swissair, the airline was
providing information on the identity of passengers to relatives
over a special telephone line.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, it took nearly 20 hours for TWA to provide a
passenger manifest to New York City officials who repeatedly
requested one.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Merlis, a senior vice president with the Air Transport
Association, a trade group that represents U.S. airlines, said the
Family Assistance Act, a federal law passed in 1996 in response to
criticisms levied against TWA, compels airlines to work as quickly
as possible to release passenger lists following crashes, even at
the expense of errors. Although it applies only to crashes in the
United States, Merlis said, most airlines have adopted that
standard.
</P>
<P>
   Swissair and Delta also hustled to make flight arrangements for
relatives who wanted to travel to Halifax, Nova Scotia, near the
site of the crash. Charter flights from both Geneva and Newark were
scheduled to arrive there Friday. The airlines also flooded both
the Ramada in New York and the airport in Geneva with airline
officials, grief counselors and clergy to talk to relatives.
</P>
<P>
   But even such painstaking accommodations could do little to
assuage survivors' sorrow. At the Geneva airport, as the passenger
list was read out loud Thursday, relatives hearing the names of
loved ones broke into sobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was there,'' one person blurted out. ``Oh, my God.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the conference room in the Ramada, the somber atmosphere was
interrupted at one point by a woman's uncontrollable screaming.
Darren Mudge, a Salvation Army officer who was there, said she was
quickly taken out of the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of thing can become contagious, because everyone is
right there, on the edge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Counselors at the Ramada outnumbered relatives 3-to-1; many had
rushed automatically to the hotel as soon as they heard about the
crash because they remembered the important role they had played
for relatives in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some relatives of the passengers aboard TWA Flight
800 began making plans to travel to Halifax to offer support to the
newly grieving mothers and fathers, daughters and sons, who would
be gathering there.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Becker of St. Petersburg, Fla., whose 19-year-old
daughter, Michele, was killed aboard Flight 800, said late Thursday
night that the Flight 800 families were merely awaiting an
assurance from Delta that they would be able to see the relatives
of passengers who died on Swissair Flight 111.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
