<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LIEBERMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON IS DENOUNCED IN SENATE BY LONGTIME ALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)   (bl)  
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Clinton and Joe Lieberman go back a long way.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, Clinton, then a Yale Law School student, worked as a
volunteer in Lieberman's campaign for the Connecticut state Senate,
often going door to door throughout the state to promote him.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two years later, as the presidential primaries were about
to begin, U.S. Sen. Joseph Lieberman repaid Clinton by becoming the
first lawmaker from the North to endorse him for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``He offers the country a whole new generation of leadership,''
Lieberman said of Clinton at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, that bond of loyalty was broken when the
56-year-old junior senator from Connecticut took to the Senate
floor to chastise the president for ``immoral'' behavior and to
express anger that Clinton had deceived him.
</P>
<P>
   Given who he is, Lieberman's somber, heartfelt speech should not
have been surprising. The Senate's only practicing Orthodox Jew, he
does not work on the Sabbath except when the Senate has votes late
on Friday nights _ and then he walks four and a half miles home
from Capitol Hill to Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   A man who calls his mother every day, Lieberman has crusaded
during his decade in the Senate for a more moral America. In 1995
he fought hard to win Senate approval of a requirement that new
televisions be equipped with an electronic device to enable parents
to block out programs that contain objectionable material. He has
also pressed manufacturers of video games and the music industry to
stop selling products with obscene and violent material.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has also built a reputation as being willing to put
his personal values over party interests and has broken ranks with
Clinton before.
</P>
<P>
   Early in Clinton's presidency, Lieberman was the strongest voice
among Senate Democrats in criticizing the administration on moral
grounds for not taking tougher action to stop ``genocide'' in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   To the administration's dismay, Lieberman joined forces with
Republican Senate Leader Bob Dole to co-sponsor legislation to
unilaterally end the arms embargo against the Bosnian government to
help the Bosnians win the war against the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he rankled fellow Democrats when he emerged as the
Democrat who was toughest on his fellow party members at hearings
of the Senate committee investigating possible campaign finance
abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a loyalty higher than just that of party,'' he said
then. ``My loyalty is to the public interest.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, Lieberman has waited to see what his colleagues were
doing before stating his position, earning the nickname ``Hamlet on
the Potomac.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, he originally announced his support for Supreme Court
nominee Clarence Thomas, then withdrew that support just before the
confirmation vote after learning of accusations that Thomas had
sexually harassed Anita Hill when they worked at federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, when Clinton needed all the Democratic votes he
could muster for his budget-balancing plan, Lieberman wavered _ on
national television _ before eventually supporting Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But even when he disagreed with the president, Lieberman went
out of his way not to criticize him personally.
</P>
<P>
   No longer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2234EDT &QL; 
