A8319 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTION-COMMISSION-N     09-03 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTION-COMMISSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP DROPS EFFORT TO REMOVE ELECTION COUNSEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ky.)  (js) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Senate Republican agreed Thursday to drop an
effort to oust Lawrence Noble, the general counsel of the Federal
Election Commission who has aggressively pursued accusations of
campaign spending violations.
</P>
<P>
   The retreat reflected a recognition that the matter would have
split the party's moderates and conservatives and stalled the
movement of 13 spending bills that Congress must pass to provide
the government with money in time for the start of the 1999 fiscal
year on Oct. 1. The Noble matter was attached to the spending bill
for the Treasury Department and Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans in the House and Senate wanted Noble, whose job
has had no term limit, to face re-election by the election
commission's six members every four years.
</P>
<P>
   Under Thursday's agreement, future general counsels will have to
be renewed every six years, but Noble will essentially be
grandfathered into his job until 2008. Then, Noble, who began
working for the government in 1977, will be 55 and have 30 years of
government service _ allowing him to retire with benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats declared a victory in shielding Noble, who has called
for a ban on unregulated contributions to political parties, or
``soft money,'' and who initiated an investigation against the
Christian Coalition and Gopac, the political action committee once
headed by Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., said the maneuver to undermine Noble
was a blatant effort by Republicans to influence an independent
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Recent changes within the commission have eased Republican
concerns that Noble could move unchecked against Republican
interests, making his ouster less urgent.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats suggested that any effort to weaken the commission
would undermine Republican calls for an independent counsel to
investigate fund raising by President Clinton and Vice President Al
Gore in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who had led the fight against
Noble, said Thursday that he was dropping his opposition because
Democrats were making a fuss, although they did not have the votes
to block it.
</P>
<P>
   Senate aides said McConnell was under enormous pressure from
Republican leaders to drop his opposition to Noble. With just five
weeks to go until adjournment, the House and Senate have sent only
one of the 13 bills to the president for his signature. Once the
Noble matter was out of the way, the Senate passed the Treasury
bill on a vote of 91-5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
