</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-INQUIRY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLIGHT 111 MAY HAVE PLUNGED ABRUPTLY INTO SEA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for new top and rewrite throughout; new hed)  (See also CRASH-RDP, CRASH-SCENE, CRASH-FAMILIES, CRASH-VICTIMS,
CRASH-OBIT-MANN, CRASH-OBIT-CLEMENTS-MANN and CRASH-OBIT-GERETY) 
(mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEGGY'S COVE, Nova Scotia _ Although there are few clues as yet
to the cause of Wednesday night's crash of Swissair Flight 111, the
chairman of Canada's transportation safety board said Thursday
evening that the plane disappeared from radar at ``7,000 or 8,000
or 9,000 feet,'' about 16 minutes after pilots first alerted
controllers about smoke in the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   The finding could indicate an abrupt plunge into the sea by the
jumbo jet, whose pilots up until then had been descending from a
cruising altitude in hopes of making an emergency landing in
Halifax, about 35 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   So far, with most of the wreckage of the plane sitting in about
120 feet of water, safety investigators say they have little to
work with in determining the cause of the crash. They expect to
begin reviewing radar tapes of the plane's flight path on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The area where the jumbo jet crashed is still under the control
of search and rescue officials here, and investigators have not yet
begun to look for the black box flight recorders that are most
likely to provide important clues to the reason for the plane's
flight path and for the crash itself, officials here said Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they concentrated on looking for bodies _ even
survivors, a spokesman for the Halifax Search Coordination Center
insisted Thursday evening. The search area is spreading with the
wind and tides.
</P>
<P>
   Even 24 hours after the jet crashed, Lt. Commander Jacques
Fauteaux said someone might have survived. ``Sometimes, scientific
figures don't actually work, if you have willpower,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the rescue workers, about 1,200 of them at any given time,
still in charge, the chairman of the Transportation Safety Board,
Benoit Bouchard, said in an interview that investigators had not
yet begun looking for the black boxes. Each recorder is equipped
with a ``pinger'' that is supposed to emit a regular sonar signal
when it is immersed in water, and the pinger can be located by
towing a listening array behind a ship.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Bouchard said, the only available clues are the
radar tapes and the tapes of conversations between the pilots and
controllers at Monckton (New Brunswick) Center, which handles
transatlantic traffic handed off from Boston or New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard said that the crew of the Swissair plane radioed that
there was smoke in the cockpit at 10:14 local time (9:14 p.m. ET).
Sixteen minutes later, at 10:30 p.m., the plane disappeared from
radar.
</P>
<P>
   In that 16 minutes, he said, the plane had turned toward Halifax
and then circled to the west and south, apparently to dump fuel.
For many big planes, the maximum takeoff weight exceeds the maximum
permissible landing weight, with the weight of the fuel being more
than the landing gear can handle as the plane thumps down on the
runway. In normal operation, this is not a problem because the fuel
is burned en route.
</P>
<P>
   By aviation standards, the plane that crashed Wednesday was
fairly young, having been put into service in August 1991. With an
engine under each wing and one in the tail, the MD-11 is a longer,
wider and more efficient version the DC-10, which is still flown by
many airlines around the world. It can seat 285 to 410 passengers,
but Swissair Flight 111 was configured to hold 239 passengers in
three classes, the airline said.
</P>
<P>
   The 229 lives lost in the crash are the first deaths to result
from a crash of an MD-11 jetliner since the model entered
commercial service in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The jet, manufactured by McDonnell Douglas Corp., now part of
Boeing Co., has had its share of troubles, namely the deaths of two
passengers in 1993 after a plane pitched violently in flight and a
crash landing in Newark, N.J., last year in which a Federal Express
cargo jet flipped over and caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   But in its brief history the MD-11's problems have been more
commercial than safety-related. It has most recently been popular
as a cargo jet with carriers such as Federal Express. But earlier
this year, Boeing announced that it would stop production of the
plane in 2,000 because there were too few buyers.
</P>
<P>
   In crashes at sea, investigators usually look for the flight
data recorder and cockpit voice recorders to determine what parts
of the plane they need to recover from the ocean floor. An
exception was the crash two years ago of TWA Flight 800, when the
cockpit voice recorder and flight data recorder did not appear to
offer them any clues, so they tried to recover the whole airplane.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 crash of a Valujet DC-9 that went down in the
Florida everglades shortly after take-off from Miami, the flight
data recorder noted a pressure spike that gave strong evidence of
an explosion. That, combined with the recovery of some of the
cargo, gave clear indication the source was hazardous oxygen
generators.
</P>
<P>
   How long before the Canadian authorities try to recover the
black boxes is not clear. Fauteaux would not say how many bodies
had been recovered and no effort had begun to recover those under
water, which might be the majority of the passengers and crew. He
pledged, though, that searchers would explore ``every possible
avenue to find survivors, if survivors there are.''
</P>
<P>
   Fauteaux, in response to a question, said he did not know if
Canadian authorities would request help from the United States.
Water depth at the scene of the crash is about 120 feet, he said;
that is not nearly as deep as other spots from which pieces of
aircraft wreckage, large and small, have been found and raised.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
