<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (af) 
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LATIN AMERICA TELLS IMF THAT ECONOMIES ARE SOUND &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Officials from nine Latin American nations, who are in
Washington for a two-day meeting with the International Monetary
Fund, said their economies were basically sound and should not be
penalized by investors because of the financial turmoil in Asia and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America markets did not heed the comments, however. They
fell sharply one day after Colombia devalued its currency. Moody's
Investors Service also downgraded its rating of Brazil's foreign
currency debt Thursrday, sending Brazil's main stock market index
down 8.6 percent. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA'S CRISIS IS DEEPENING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the crisis in Russia seems to be worsening and the ruble
continues to decline, many of that country's food markets and
hard-goods stores are running out of supplies. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN WOES CUT LEHMAN PROFITS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers became the latest brokerage firm to say that the
financial turmoil in Russia and other developing countries would
reduce its net income. Lehman had expected net income for the
quarter to be about $211 million, but now estimates that it will be
$151 million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLEA FOR AN END TO NORTHWEST STRIKE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The governor of Minnesota, Arne Carlson, called on President
Clinton to order the pilots of Northwest Airlines back to work, but
the White House reiterated its belief that the two sides should
return to the bargaining table. The move by the Minnesota governor,
which follows the same request from other governors, came on the
sixth day of the strike and a day after Northwest laid off more
than half its 51,000 workers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL SALES INCREASE 3.5 PERCENT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American retailers reported sales in stores open at least a year
rose 3.5 percent in August, but analysts warned that continued
unease about the economy could slow retail sales for the rest of
the year. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT ORDERED TO PROVIDE FILES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ordered Microsoft to give the Justice Department
reams of new evidence that government lawyers say will bolster
their antitrust case. Microsoft's lawyers had argued that the
evidence should not be a part of the case because it was not
specifically mentioned in the original lawsuits. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHELL AND TEXACO IN EUROPEAN MATCH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Dutch/Shell and Texaco plan to combine their refining and
marketing businesses in Europe, a step that could further speed a
trend toward cutting costs and capacity as the oil industry
struggles with declining profit. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil prices surged, after Nigerian and Russian shipments
were delayed. Crude oil for October delivery rose $1, to $14.67 a
barrel. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN MAY NATIONALIZE SOME BANKS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Japan's government is wrestling with what to do with one of its
deeply troubled large banks, Long-Term Credit Bank, which has $180
billion in assets. One of the possibilities frequently mentioned is
nationalization. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 FORMER STRATTON HEADS INDICTED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two former principals of Stratton Oakmont, the defunct brokerage
firm, have been indicted in an international securities fraud and
money-laundering scheme that federal prosecutors say was intended
to manipulate the stocks of two small companies. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GRAMM FORCES DELAY IN BANK BILL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Banking Committee postponed consideration of a bill
to overhaul the nation's banking laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
