<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKSTRETCH, NOT BACK NINE, FOR NAKATANI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Del Mar season enters its final weekend, Corey Nakatani
holds a comfortable but hardly insurmountable lead in the jockey
standings.
</P>
<P>
   Quick, somebody hide his golf clubs.
</P>
<P>
   When Nakatani was in the same position with two weeks left in
the Hollywood Park meeting in July, he missed four racing days to
play in a celebrity golf tournament in Lake Tahoe. The absence cost
him the riding title, which went to Chris McCarron, who won 52
races to Nakatani's 50, and forced him to miss an important race
aboard Manistique, who won the Hollywood Oaks under Gary Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   Horsemen saw Nakatani's golfing spree as a case of misplaced
priorities. Someone suggested that the men and women of the press
box, in addition to naming the best horse, jockey and trainer of
the meet, also vote for ``Golfer of the Meet.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 27-year-old jockey and his agent defended the decision,
saying they simply followed through on a commitment to the
tournament sponsors, a commitment made before Nakatani knew about
Manistique or the possibility of a title.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much racing, a rider needs a break every once in a
while,'' agent Bob Meldahl said. ``He'd been invited to do this for
three or four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an agent, you say, `This isn't the right time.' But, you
know what, there never is a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Nakatani, a wrestler at Northview High in Covina and a good
all-around athlete despite standing 5-foot-1, finished 22nd in the
tournament, won by former hockey star Mario Lemieux, but was best
among first-time participants. He collected $5,048.
</P>
<P>
   More important, he believes, he won some valuable
national-television exposure for horse racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to show what good athletes jockeys are, and I think I
did that,'' Nakatani said. ``I played very well in the
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   As for those who criticized his decision, he said, ``That's
their opinion. I don't worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   It boils down to how much value you attach to a track riding
title, which offers no tangible reward but does bring valuable
publicity, not to mention pride. Nakatani seems to care less about
titles than most jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``All riding titles mean is that you're having a great meet,''
he said. ``I'd rather ride the right horses for the right people.''
</P>
<P>
   Nakatani, whose last title came at Santa Anita in 1996 and whose
first Del Mar title came in 1994, is on the verge of winning this
one because he's riding more of the right horses for more of the
right people.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of on- and off-the-track crises and controversies
sapped his desire in 1996-97, Nakatani said he had ``gotten over
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Meldahl said he is demonstrating that newfound devotion by
accepting mounts of all kinds, including cheap claiming horses he
used to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've realized you've got to take care of the trainers that
take care of you,'' the agent said.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into the last five days at Del Mar, Nakatani had 35
victories, including stakes winners Sharp Cat, Tuzla, See You Soon,
Sicy d'Alsace and Daring General.
</P>
<P>
   Second with 28 is Gary Stevens, who is injured and out for the
rest of the meet, leaving Alex Solis, with 27, as the only jockey
with a chance to catch Nakatani.
</P>
<P>
   Del Mar will run through Monday, take a break Tuesday, and tack
on closing day Wednesday. After the Los Angeles County Fair opens
Thursday in Pomona, Nakatani will head to Belmont Park in New York
for some weekend stakes mounts, including Gentlemen in the Sept. 19
Woodward Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   If he gets off to a good start at Belmont, he might continue
riding there until the start of Santa Anita on Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   But if he doesn't, it's time for golf.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Down the stretch: &LR;  River Bay will try to add the Del Mar
Handicap to his Southern California stakes victories when the Bobby
Frankel-trained 5-year-old faces six horses at 1] miles on
Saturday. He'll carry 123 pounds, three more than Dowty, and will
have Solis riding.
</P>
<P>
   That race is not to be confused with Sunday's Del Mar Breeders'
Cup Handicap, a main-track mile that will be led by Old Trieste.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's Del Mar Derby will feature Ladies Din, the Oceanside
and La Jolla winner, and Keene Dancer, an eastern shipper.
</P>
<P>
   The meet ends with Wednesday's Del Mar Futurity, with Worldly
Manner trying to make it three straight for trainer Bob Baffert by
emulating Silver Charm and Souvenir Copy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Leading men: &LR;  In the space of four days, the jockeys' and
trainers' records for victories in a career at Del Mar fell to
Laffit Pincay and Ron McAnally.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay's 890th winner in 23 seasons was Lady Cadet in an
allowance race on Wednesday. Bill Shoemaker had 889 winners at Del
Mar.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay, 51, who returned Sunday from a collarbone fracture, now
is within 200 of Shoemaker's world record (8,833).
</P>
<P>
   McAnally got his 375th Del Mar winner, one more than Farrell
Jones' record, when King Clef won an allowance turf race on
Sunday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
