<SLUG> BC-FBC-AUBURN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leard has a tough act to follow at Auburn
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, Ala. _ Ben Leard had a number of worries prior to
Auburn's season-opener with Virginia Thursday night at Jordan-Hare
Stadium. A lot them, however, had nothing to do with the No. 16
Cavaliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest problem has been getting enough tickets to take
care of my family,'' said Leard, the sophomore from Hartwell who
made his first college start in Thursday night's
nationally-televised game. ``I don't know where they all come
from.''
</P>
<P>
   This was nothing new for Leard, who had to come up with 40
tickets for family members last November when Auburn played at
Georiga, as everybody in the Leard clan wanted to make the short
drive from Hartwell to Athens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally had to have a talk with my mom about getting this
thing under control,'' Leard said. ``I can't spend my college
career being a ticket broker.''
</P>
<P>
   With the family's ticket needs fulfilled, for this week at
least, Leard could finally turn all of his attention to Thursday
night's game where he would be very much in the spotlight. For
against Virginia, Leard had the unenviable task of replacing
Dameyune Craig, who threw for 3,277 yards and 18 touchdowns while
leading the Tigers to a 10-3 record last seson. Craig was the
leader and the focal point of the Auburn offense for two seasons.
Thursday night the mantle was officially turned over to Leard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people are going to compare me to Dameyune and I can't
do anything about that,'' said Leard, who threw only two passes
(completing one) as Craig's backup last season. ``But I can't be
Dameyune. I can only be myself. That was something he taught me.''
</P>
<P>
   Leard said his job going into Thursday night's contest was to
keep his mistakes to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's simple,'' said Leard. ``The coaches are not
asking me to win the game. They are asking me not to lose it. I'm
supposed to get the ball to the right people at the right time and
make sure we don't turn it over. If I can do that, I'll be okay.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia arrived at Auburn Thursday night with what many think
will be its best team since 1990, when the Cavaliers were ranked
No. 1 deep into the season. Virginia is solid on offense, with
quarterback Aaron Brooks and running back Thomas Jones, but its
hopes for a big season hinge on a defense that returns nine
starters from a unit that finished No. 24 in the nation in 1997.
The Cavs defense was led by strong safety Anthony Poindexter, a
consensus All-American.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
