<SLUG> BC-NY-KENYA-BOMBING-NYT10 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENYA BOMBING DEFENDANT'S LAWYER MAY BE REPLACED 
</HEADLINE>
  
8  nypt 9   (  af11)  
 By BENJAMIN   WEISER12   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The lawyer for one of two defendants charged in the
bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Kenya may be replaced Friday at a
hearing in U.S. district court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   It could not be determined precisely why Magistrate Judge Kevin
Fox has moved to change the lawyer for Mohammed Saddiq &UR; 13 &LR; 
Odeh &UR; 14 &LR; , the defendant. But the lawyer, Jack Sachs &UR; 15 &LR; , said he
was told that the reasons involve his ability to carry two
potential death penalty cases at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day that Sachs &UR; 15 &LR;  was assigned to represent
Odeh &UR; 14 &LR; , he was also appointed to defend a man in an unrelated
capital case, involving interstate kidnapping and murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs &UR; 15 &LR;  said Thursday that he believed that he could handle
both matters, and that he hoped to continue to represent Odeh &UR; 14 &LR; 
if his client so desired.
</P>
<P>
   Odeh &UR; 14 &LR;  was charged last month with conspiracy to commit
murder, use of a weapon of mass destruction, and 12 counts of
murder, one count for each of the 12 Americans killed in the
Nairobi bombing. If he is convicted, Odeh &UR; 14 &LR;  could face a maximum
term of life in prison or death.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs &UR; 15 &LR;  said he had already met with Odeh &UR; 14 &LR;  four times at
the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan, and interviewed
him extensively. He said he had also interviewed Odeh's &UR; 14 &LR;  wife,
who remains in Kenya, by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's to be a change, it has to be done by the judge,''
Sachs &UR; 15 &LR;  said. ``I would like to keep the case, but I have to go
with whatever is decided.''
</P>
<P>
   Sachs &UR; 15 &LR;  is one of about 150 lawyers who are eligible to be
appointed by judges to represent indigent defendants in U.S.
district court in Manhattan, and reimbursed by the government for
their work. In capital cases, the burden on lawyers is considered
to be so large that defendants are provided with two lawyers paid
by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs &UR; 15 &LR; , 69, said he has been practicing law in U.S. court in
Manhattan since the early 1970s &UR; 16 &LR; . He said he is currently a sole
practitioner.
</P>
<P>
   In the federal complaint against Odeh &UR; 14 &LR; , prosecutors have said
he had denied taking part in a direct role in the embassy bombings
but admitted to being a member of a terrorist group run by the
wealthy Islamic militant, Osama &UR; 17 &LR;  bin Laden, whom the authorities
suspect is behind the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors also said he accepted some responsibility for
the attacks as a member of the bin Laden group. The bombing in
Kenya killed 258 people and wounded thousands of others.
</P>
<P>
   After Odeh &UR; 14 &LR;  was charged last month, Sachs &UR; 15 &LR;  denied to
reporters that his client had confessed to any role in the
bombings. But he said Odeh &UR; 14 &LR;  did acknowledge being a member of
the bin Laden organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
