<HEADER>
A8341 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-TAX-RELIEF-COX     09-03 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-TAX-RELIEF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gov. Bush proposes tax cuts
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Gov. George W. Bush on Thursday proposed funneling some
of the projected state budget surplus back into Texans' wallets _ a
diaper, a cough and a cut at a time.
</P>
<P>
   In a plan that would save an average Texas family about $35 a
year, Bush called for scrapping the sales tax on over-the-counter
medicine, diapers and health aids, including bandages, foot-care
products and other items used to treat health problems.
</P>
<P>
   After some discussion with his staff, Bush, a champion of
abstinence, decided that condoms and other non-prescription
birth-control devices would not be included in the tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a direct way to return money to Texas families,'' Bush
said at a news conference at a South Austin drug store. ``These tax
cuts are for the people who pay the bills. The moms and dads who
buy diapers and school clothes for their children, and the senior
citizens who spend a disproportionate share of their income on
over-the-counter medicines.''
</P>
<P>
   The tax-cut package, with an annual bottom line of $200 million,
also includes ending the sales tax on Internet access and a
establishing a two-week, back-to-school moratorium on sales tax on
clothing and footwear. The moratorium would occur every year in
late July and early August.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers announced by Bush reflect savings to taxpayers if
the products were exempted from the state's 6.25 percent sales tax.
Actual savings would be greater because local governments also tax
the products. For example, Austin residents pay a combined sales
tax of 8.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush became the latest politician to offer his two cents on tax
cuts, a popular campaign theme this year in the wake of projections
that the state will have an additional $6.3 billion in additional
revenue to spend by the end of the 2000-2001 budget cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan drew backing and criticism from his Democratic
opponent, Land Commissioner Garry Mauro. Mauro, who is campaigning
on a theme of ``filies first'' said he is ``very happy because the
debate is going to be about how we help Texas families and not how
we help the rich and powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also noted that Bush _ as part of his semi-successful
property tax cut plan in 1997 _ had proposed raising the state
sales tax from 6.25 percent to 6.75 percent, a change that would
have increased the levy on the items he now wants to exempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago he proposed raising those same taxes,'' Mauro
said. ``I wonder if it's just an election-year ploy instead of a
reflection of his basic values.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro, when he announced his candidacy Nov. 17, has proposed
eliminating sales taxes on cars, pickups and minivans, a change he
said would save Texans $1.8 billion a year. Mauro also has proposed
a tax increase: doubling the levy on mixed beverages, liquor and
tobacco products. Overall, he said, his tax overhaul would amount
to more than $1 million in tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``His tax cut is much smaller than mine,'' Mauro said of Bush's
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush plan offers smaller, but more frequent savings. For
example, the more you change the baby, the more you save. The Mauro
plan offers savings in large chunks by scrapping the sales tax on a
big-ticket item: the family vehicle. The tax saving on the purchase
of a $22,000 vehicle would be $1,375. But Texans who enjoy an
occasional mixed drink or like to smoke or chew would pay increased
taxes in years in which they do not buy a vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Bush noted that Mauro's cut would only mean money for people who
buy vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It generally effects people one out of every seven years,''
said Bush. ``I believe in affecting people's lives every year.''
</P>
<P>
   The tax-cutting proposals come after State Comptroller John
Sharp projected in July that the state would have a $3.7 billion
surplus when the two-year budget cycle ends next August. Sharp also
predicted state revenues will increase by $2.6 billion during the
2000-2001 budget cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp, the Democratic nominee for lieutenant governor, wants to
spend some of the state's prosperity on a back-to-school moratorium
on sales tax on school supplies and clothing under $50, as well as
a college-scholarship program.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Perry, Sharp's GOP opponent, has sided with Bush's tax-cut
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The budget surplus belongs to the taxpayers of Texas, not to
the government,'' Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas state government is among many enjoying strong economies.
A recent report by the National Conference of State Legislatures
showed that lawmakers around the country this year approved tax
cuts totaling $3.8 billion. Fifteen states cut taxes by 1 percent
or more. Only one state, Wyoming, raised taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-three states also socked away some of the money, putting
it in rainy day funds or other accounts earmarked for leaner times.
</P>
<P>
   As Texas politicians pitched tax-cut plans, a prominent Texas
economist said that's exactly the wrong way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is 11th-hour politicking,'' said Bernard Weinstein,
director of the Center for Economic Development at the University
of North Texas. ``Because of the economic uncertainty . . . I would
rather have that money in reserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein said stock market volatility and economic woes around
the world could turn the Texas economy around.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who will offer up more tax cuts in coming weeks, said his
overall plan will include a cushion for just such a contingency.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we have seen recently there seems to be some skittishness
on the stock market,'' he said. ``So I think it is really important
for those of us who intend to be around to have some cushion in the
budget to make sure that we don't commit it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas lawmakers, when they last met in 1997, approved a $1
billion property tax cut for homeowners, some of which was lost to
local tax increases. The reduction was what was left of Bush's
ambitious, unsuccessful plan to cut homeowners' property taxes by
$3 billion, a proposal that included raising the state sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he has more tax cuts up his sleeve, as well as
proposals for spending additional money on public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay tuned,'' he said when asked if he will proposed a teacher
pay raise. Mauro is proposing a $6,000 pay hike for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush previously has proposed a plan to exempt some small
businesses from the franchise tax. Combined with a cut aimed at
encouraging research and development, the Bush business tax plan
would cost the state $250 million over a two-year budget cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he opposes using the surplus to roll back the state
sales tax rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``My judgment is that it is best to target the sales tax cuts.
It is best to say that diapers matter to guys like you who have had
a plethora of children,'' he told a reporter who has four kids.
</P>
<P>
   American-Statesman staff writer A. Phillips Brooks contributed
to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
