<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 23:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHELL-TEXACO-NYT &LR;      09-03 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHELL-TEXACO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHELL AND TEXACO TO JOIN EUROPEAN REFINING AND SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Royal Dutch/Shell and Texaco said Thursday they would combine
their refining and marketing businesses in Europe, a step that
could further speed a trend toward cutting costs and capacity as
the industry struggles with declining profit.
</P>
<P>
   This would be the second major combination in Europe, following
a decision in 1996 by British Petroleum and Mobil to merge their
refining and sales units _ a move that has squeezed about $500
million a year out of operating costs.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance announced Thursday would cement Shell's leadership
position in Europe, where Texaco has been a laggard. Even though
the European market may have slower growth potential than do some
developing regions, Shell and Texaco said that by joining some
operations they could save about $200 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance would combine Shell's 17 refineries in Europe with
Texaco's in Pembroke, Wales, and in the Dutch port of Rotterdam,
where it owns 35 percent of a refinery. Shell has 12,954 gasoline
stations in Europe and employs 25,000 in refining and marketing,
while Texaco has 2,984 stations and 4,300 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The venture between BP and Mobil led to the closing of one
refinery and a reduction of European service stations to 8,400 from
9,000. The two companies cut more than 2,000 jobs from a total work
force of 17,500.
</P>
<P>
   The combinations in Europe are part of an industry-wide trend
toward consolidating ``downstream operations'' _ refining and
marketing. Last year, for example, Shell, Texaco and the Saudi
state oil company agreed to combine their refining and marketing in
the United States with the goal of saving $800 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   While the European cost-cutting by companies is not expected to
have an immediate effect in the United States, the trend could in
the long term make it harder to export petroleum products from
Europe. On the U.S. East Coast, imports of gasoline from Europe
have often helped ease tight supplies during periods of peak
demand, like summer.
</P>
<P>
   As world refining capacity gets tighter, consolidation in Europe
will have an impact on profit margins from refining and on gasoline
prices in the United States, said Frederick Leuffer, an oil analyst
with Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. ``It will take some time, though,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the combination of Shell and Texaco refining in Europe,
which together supply about 15 percent of Europe's needs, is not
expected to lead to any major cuts in capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Europe still has 5 percent to 10 percent more capacity that it
needs to meet demand, said Greg Quine of J.P. Morgan Securities in
London. ``It's next to impossible to close a refinery in Europe,''
he said, adding that cleanup costs would be huge and that unions
and governments could be expected to oppose a major closing. The
venture requires regulators' approval.
</P>
<P>
   Texaco, based in White Plains, N.Y., has been seeking a way to
improve its refining business for some time. Talks with Shell began
last year, which resulted in a memorandum of understanding to form
an alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Shell, which is the world's largest publicly traded oil company,
will own 88 percent of the venture; Texaco will have 12 percent.
Together, the two will control 19 refineries and be able to process
2.1 million barrels of oil a day, or about 15 percent of European
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Texaco rose 43.75 cents Thursday, to $57.6875.
U.S.-listed shares of Royal Dutch Petroleum, which owns 60 percent
of the Royal Dutch/Shell Group, gained 75 cents, to $45.4375.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
