<HEADLINE>
TWO FORMER STRATTON OAKMONT OFFICIALS INDICTED ON FRAUD CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Ind.)   (af)  
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two former principals of a defunct brokerage firm,
Stratton Oakmont Inc., have been indicted in an international
securities fraud and money laundering scheme that federal
prosecutors say tried to manipulate the stock of two small
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment, unsealed Thursday in U.S. district court in
Brooklyn, charges Jordan Ross Belfort, 36, Stratton's former
chairman, and Daniel Mark Porush, 41, its former president, with 27
counts of securities fraud, conspiracy to commit securities fraud,
money laundering, conspiracy to launder monetary instruments and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   While Belfort and Porush both have a long history of run-ins
with securities regulators, the charges in the indictment are the
first against them that have the possibility of long prison
sentences, federal prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   The two each face a maximum sentence of 20 years and fines of up
to $10 million. They each could also be required to forfeit $5
million of personal property.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Porush was accused of perjury, also a criminal
offense, in connection with an insider trading investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Belfort and Porush said Thursday that their clients
were innocent and would fight the charges in court.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, the defendants set up a complex web
of foreign bank accounts and corporations to secretly buy millions
of shares of underpriced stock in two companies they secretly
controlled: Dollar Time Group, a retail chain, and the Aquanatural
Co., a water purification and dispensing equipment provider.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say the shares were issued to a company owned or
controlled by the two men that falsely claimed to be a foreign
entity. Under an exemption to Securities and Exchange Commission
registration requirements, such companies can issue stock at
below-market prices without filing a registration statement.
</P>
<P>
   The stock must be issued to foreigners who will hold it for at
least 41 days before reselling it into the U.S. market. The
defendants are accused of pressuring Stratton employees to resell
the shares to clients, at higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants earned profits of at least about $5 million on
the scheme, said Joel Cohen, an assistant U.S. attorney. They also
tried to bribe potential witnesses to help conceal their scheme, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The indictments are the latest run-in for officials of Stratton
Oakmont, which was based in Lake Success, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, five former Stratton principals and a broker were
barred from the securities industry as part of a settlement with
the SEC. They were also ordered by a National Association of
Securities Dealers arbitration panel to pay an Indiana retiree
$13.1 million, including $10.5 million in punitive damages, in the
largest investor award ever.
</P>
<P>
   In January, regulators announced that the brokerage firm would
be liquidated by a court-appointed trustee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
