<SLUG> BC-CT-TROOPERS-SHOT-335&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE TROOPERS AND SUSPECT SHOT IN CONNECTICUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE ALLEN    c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLINGTON, Conn. _ A man whose mobile home held an arsenal of
firearms and explosives opened fire on three state troopers without
warning Thursday after two of them tried to question him about a
neighbor's complaint of vandalism, state police said.
</P>
<P>
   In the exchange of gunfire, all three troopers were wounded, as
was the shooter, identified as Edward Premo, 40, a tractor-trailer
driver for the Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just ambushed them. Simple as that,'' said Lt. Lawrence
Gibeault of the Connecticut State Police. ``We have no idea why.''
</P>
<P>
   After ambulances had taken away the four wounded men,
investigators discovered that the trailer had been booby-trapped
with homemade explosives. Troopers from the bomb squad closed the
road for two miles in either direction as they worked to defuse the
explosives, which officials described as unspecified
``anti-personnel devices.''
</P>
<P>
   The wounds to the troopers, one of whom was a rookie less than
two months out of the academy, were described as serious but not
life-threatening. The troopers were listed in stable condition
Thursday night at Johnson Memorial Hospital in nearby Stafford
Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Premo was under armed guard Thursday night and listed in stable
condition, also at Johnson Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   The troopers who responded to the initial complaint were
identified as Mark Pelletier, who has been on the job five years,
and Michael Hogue, who graduated from the State Police Academy on
July 24.
</P>
<P>
   Trooper 1st Class James Reidy, a 14-year veteran, received the
most serious wounds of the three when he responded to his
colleagues' radio call of ``shots fired.'' The troopers' ages and
towns were not released.
</P>
<P>
   The troopers required surgery, but Premo did not, a hospital
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Premo had at least two handguns and at least one
assault rifle, which he used to fire on the troopers. The charges
against him, which police said would include attempted murder, were
still being determined Thursday night.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Inside Premo's sagging brown trailer, police said, officers
found about 50 devices that can be used to maim or kill, including
four homemade bombs and three crude land mines made with shotgun
shells mounted on wooden blocks, with fishing line to trip the
victim.
</P>
<P>
   Among the books seized from the trailer were ``Homemade
Semtex,'' ``Highly Explosive Pyrotechnic Compositions'' and an Army
manual, ``Unconventional Warfare Techniques and Devices.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John Rowland canceled a trip to Washington on Thursday and
visited the wounded troopers at the hospital. ``They were shook up,
obviously, but they're pretty rugged young men,'' he said. '
</P>
<P>
   The shootout began after a woman who lives near Premo called
police at 7:50 a.m. to say that someone had vandalized her vehicle.
Willington, a small town in northeastern Connecticut, has no police
force and is served only by state police.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always say there's no such thing as a routine call,'' said
Lt. Ralph Carpenter, the chief spokesman for the state police.
``This is proof.''
</P>
<P>
   The call came from River Road, just four miles from the police
barracks in Tolland where the troopers are stationed. The caller
said she suspected Premo of damaging her car. Carpenter said that
when the two troopers went to interview him, Premo met them in his
driveway, pulled out a pistol and started shooting, hitting them
both several times. The two returned fire, took cover and called
for backup.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter said Premo went somewhere _ behind a tree or back in
the house _ and got an assault rifle.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived, Reidy, who kept a four-leaf clover under his
visor for luck, slowed down in front of the trailer and was shot
three times before he was even able to get out of his cruiser,
police said. The suspect used the crook of a tree to steady his aim
as he shot, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Reidy was was unable to steer his car, which rolled until a
passer-by grabbed the wheel, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   A man in a pickup truck drove past while the shooting was going
on, dialed 911 and made a U-turn back to the firefight. Lt. Col.
Timothy Barry, the commander of field operations, said the suspect
aimed at the passing driver, but returned to firing at the
troopers. The man stayed to warn other troopers responding that the
suspect was still crouched by a hedge in front of the trailer.
</P>
<P>
   By evening, the bomb squad was still working and investigators
had not been able to search the mobile home. It became obvious the
investigation would be long when the police escorted a portable
toilet past the roadblock. Police dogs were brought in, and a
helicopter borrowed from the Massachusetts State Police buzzed the
area.
</P>
<P>
   Willington, in the hills of northeastern Connecticut, is a small
New England town where citizens vote in a 270-year-old meeting
house and the town office is housed in a former button factory.
Most of the 6,300 residents commute to Hartford or the University
of Connecticut in Storrs.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they could find no criminal record for Premo in
Connecticut and planned to check nearby states.
</P>
<P>
   Premo went to work for the Postal Service in 1992, Since 1995,
he had driven a truck for the postal service in Hartford.
</P>
</TEXT>
