<HEADLINE>
KENYA BOMBING DEFENDANT'S LAWYER MAY BE REPLACED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resent to correct garble. No changes)   (af)  
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The lawyer for one of two defendants charged in the
bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Kenya may be replaced Friday at a
hearing in U.S. district court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   It could not be determined precisely why Magistrate Judge Kevin
Fox has moved to change the lawyer for Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, the
defendant. But the lawyer, Jack Sachs, said he was told that the
reasons involve his ability to carry two potential death penalty
cases at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day that Sachs was assigned to represent Odeh, he
was also appointed to defend a man in an unrelated capital case,
involving interstate kidnapping and murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs said Thursday that he believed that he could handle both
matters, and that he hoped to continue to represent Odeh if his
client so desired.
</P>
<P>
   Odeh was charged last month with conspiracy to commit murder,
use of a weapon of mass destruction, and 12 counts of murder, one
count for each of the 12 Americans killed in the Nairobi bombing.
If he is convicted, Odeh could face a maximum term of life in
prison or death.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs said he had already met with Odeh four times at the
Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan, and interviewed him
extensively. He said he had also interviewed Odeh's wife, who
remains in Kenya, by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's to be a change, it has to be done by the judge,''
Sachs said. ``I would like to keep the case, but I have to go with
whatever is decided.''
</P>
<P>
   Sachs is one of about 150 lawyers who are eligible to be
appointed by judges to represent indigent defendants in U.S.
district court in Manhattan, and reimbursed by the government for
their work. In capital cases, the burden on lawyers is considered
to be so large that defendants are provided with two lawyers paid
by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs, 69, said he has been practicing law in U.S. court in
Manhattan since the early 1970s. He said he is currently a sole
practitioner.
</P>
<P>
   In the federal complaint against Odeh, prosecutors have said he
had denied taking part in a direct role in the embassy bombings but
admitted to being a member of a terrorist group run by the wealthy
Islamic militant, Osama bin Laden, whom the authorities suspect is
behind the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors also said he accepted some responsibility for
the attacks as a member of the bin Laden group. The bombing in
Kenya killed 258 people and wounded thousands of others.
</P>
<P>
   After Odeh was charged last month, Sachs denied to reporters
that his client had confessed to any role in the bombings. But he
said Odeh did acknowledge being a member of the bin Laden
organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0443 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8491 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-WEST-LADN     09-03 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST: `THIS IS THE PLACE I BELONG'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ The imaginary scales in Jerry West's psyche were at
a perfectly weighted deadlock: On the side marked ``resign'' were
the immense stresses of running one of the NBA's top franchises. On
the other scale, marked ``stay,'' were the great joys of doing that
same job.
</P>
<P>
   Balanced scales meant indecision for the 60-year-old executive
vice president, who contemplated walking away after 16 years at the
helm of the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   But then the scales tipped hard. There was his commitment to
young stars Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, the emotional
investment West had made in this dynasty-in-waiting, his feelings
of loyalty. And, finally, the look on the faces of West's two sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some pretty long faces,'' West noted. Ryan and Jonnie West,
ages 19 and 10 _ and perhaps Shaq's two biggest fans _ wouldn't let
Dad walk away.
</P>
<P>
   ``(They) absolutely love the Lakers, and they particularly love
(O'Neal).... There was one point when my two boys came into the
room... and the first question out of their mouths was, `Are you
still gonna get season seats?'''
</P>
<P>
   The West family's seats are safe, as is the future of the
Lakers, with Jerry West's signing of a four-year contract extension
Thursday morning. The deal, reportedly worth $3.5 million annually,
goes into effect in 1999 and runs through the 2002-03 season.
</P>
<P>
   A burned-out, stressed-out West spent the summer considering
everything from a sabbatical to resignation to retirement. And he
also considered at least one tempting, highly lucrative and
``challenging'' opportunity elsewhere that he declined to detail.
</P>
<P>
   Then, two weeks ago, just before West departed for his home away
from home in West Virginia, Lakers owner Jerry Buss offered the new
contract _ which, West insists, is ``not something that I asked
for.... This isn't about money.''
</P>
<P>
   But the offer clearly influenced his decision. West requested a
small alteration in the deal, and on the evening of Aug. 27, Buss
called and agreed to the change. A short while later, around 12:15
Friday morning, West's months-long quandary ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the place I belong,'' West told reporters Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is he might not have reached that conclusion without
an assist from the labor-troubled league. NBA owners imposed a
lockout of players July 1, halting all business and giving league
executives an extended vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A godsend,'' West said of the lockout, ``because once the
(June 24) draft was over, I could start to work on myself.... I can
honestly tell you that if we had not had this time, I may not have
made this decision.''
</P>
<P>
   West's departure could have thrown a remarkably stable franchise
into turmoil. After 16 years under West, the Lakers could have ably
moved forward under his close protege, general manager Mitch
Kupchak.
</P>
<P>
   But it is West's personality and his legacy as player and
executive _ with three NBA championships and seven Finals
appearances _ that helps attract marquee players like O'Neal and
Bryant. Both young stars had hinted they might leave after next
season if West resigned, and West said his commitment to O'Neal
especially weighed heavily on him.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Lakers can again concentrate on reclaiming the
franchise's past glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always told you I felt he would stay because the Lakers
without Jerry is like a hamburger without a bun,'' coach Del Harris
said. ``He's been such a central part of our success here for so
many years, that was an important thing for the Lakers to maintain
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Had West decided to walk away, it would not have been to pursue
another NBA job.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me to go anywhere else would have been ridiculous,'' West
said. ``I don't care what kind of offers they were. I probably
couldn't have faced myself when I got up in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Buss was reportedly out of town but issued a statement praising
West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has meant more to the Los Angeles Lakers franchise than
Jerry West,'' Buss said. ``Since 1960 he has brought talent,
intelligence, class, dignity _ and success _ to this team, this
city and this organization. Keeping him here will ensure that the
Lakers will be one of the best-run franchises in sports well into
the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   The new deal virtually guarantees West's career will end where
it began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would very definitely think this would be my last
contract,'' West said, then added with a laugh, ``I'll probably die
behind that desk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
