<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LILY TOMLIN IN ADVERTISING DEBUT WITH FIDELITY'S PETER LYNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 C.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lily Tomlin, who once searched for signs of
intelligent life in the universe, is joining Peter Lynch to help
investors search for signs of intelligent life on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tomlin and three of her comedic characters will appear with
Lynch, the former mutual fund manager, in a television, print and
poster campaign for Fidelity Investments that carries the theme
``Key things every investor should know.''
</P>
<P>
   The ambitious campaign by Hill, Holliday, Connors, Cosmopulos in
Boston, which begins Sept. 11, is meant to develop a brighter
personality for the Fidelity brand as it educates Americans about
their finances _ and peddles, in a low-key manner, Fidelity
products like mutual funds and brokerage services.
</P>
<P>
   That the odd couple's campaign comes as investors nervously
monitor the gyrations of stocks, bonds and currencies around the
world is a coincidence because the ads have been under development
for six months. But the campaign addresses such timely topics as
volatility and risk; in one commercial, Lynch, exercising on a
treadmill, informs Ms. Tomlin, playing her Valley Girl character
Suzie as a ``stress technician,'' that stocks have declined ``25
percent or more four times since 1970.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign marks the first time that a celebrity has appeared
in advertising for Fidelity, which is part of FMR Corp. It is also
the first time that Lynch, who used to manage the Fidelity Magellan
Fund, is being used as a spokesman by Fidelity, where he is now
vice chairman of Fidelity Management and Research Co.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the campaign represents the first advertising work for
Ms. Tomlin, she said Thursday as she, Lynch and Fidelity executives
discussed the ads at a news conference in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tomlin confirmed a tale often told on Madison Avenue that
she once turned down an offer from AT&AMP;T to appear in a commercial
as Ernestine, the snippy telephone operator whose nasal rendition
of ``One ringy-dingy . . . two ringy-dingys'' became a national
catch phrase when she performed on ``Rowan and Martin's Laugh-In.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I also didn't believe in investing in the stock market in
those days,'' Ms. Tomlin said ruefully, because ``my politics
wouldn't allow me to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the error of those ways now,'' she added, as a result of
``my own money dribbled away'' by business managers who would
invest ``in limited partnerships and all kinds of convoluted
syndicates that they put people like me in in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I would like people to be empowered by having a share in
this country and some security for the future,'' particularly
``women and young people,'' Ms. Tomlin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When only an elite group has a stake in the future,'' she
added, ``that's divisive.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch could not quite match Ms. Tomlin's humorous asides at the
news conference. She slyly jabbed at stock market arcana like the
Elliott wave theory and the perhaps apocryphal ``McClellan
oscillator,'' and sagely advised that ``the two most important
things I've begun to learn a little too late in life are to wear
more sunscreen and to invest.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked which Fidelity funds she owned, Ms. Tomlin replied:
``An equity utilities fund and a growth and income fund. Does that
make sense?''
</P>
<P>
   But Lynch drew chuckles for some of his frank remarks. He
derided investors who freak out when indexes fall sharply; after
all, he asserted, residents of Minnesota ``don't panic and say,
`This is the end of the world''' when temperatures plunge in
wintertime.
</P>
<P>
   And Lynch mocked timing stock purchases and sales to months of
the year by likening that strategy to buying a house based on the
name of the street on which it is situated.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch acquits himself well in the commercials with Ms. Tomlin.
(He appears without her in corporate spots, which begin running
Sept. 5, that focus on Fidelity's experience and service.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the commercial in which Lynch trods the treadmill
alongside Suzie, he discusses the pitfalls of ``information
overload'' with Ms. Tomlin's character of Judith Beasley, the
tasteful homemaker, and talks about the futility of chasing ``hot
tips'' with Ms. Tomlin's character of Pauline, a short-tempered
clerk at the motor vehicle bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not Lily Tomlin telling her fans `Put your money here,'''
said Gail Schoenbrunn, senior vice president and group creative
director at Hill, Holliday, a unit of Interpublic Group of Cos.
Rather, she added, depicting Ms. Tomlin as her characters is an
effective method to illustrate ``the different kinds of
situations'' about which investors need to be informed.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tomlin collaborated with the agency on the campaign, Ms.
Schoenbrunn said, sending tapes of her performances to help select
which characters to feature and ``corresponding a lot by e-mail''
on the scripts. The ads eschewed famous characters like Ernestine
or Edith Ann, the bratty child, she added, because ``we were
concerned it not appear as if the celebrity was overtaking the
message.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, though, a celebrity at all?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get people to sit up and take notice,'' said
Stephen Cone, president at Fidelity Customer Marketing and
Development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using Lily and Peter together gets more attention than
garden-variety financial service advertising,'' he added, ``with
people looking at pie charts on computer screens or your
ever-popular landscape scenes of footprints in the desert or
airbrushed older people riding on horseback on the beach.''
</P>
<P>
   A second celebrity may appear in a campaign Fidelity plans to
introduce in October; Adweek and USA Today reported recently that
Don Rickles would appear in those ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not necessarily the case,'' Cone said. ``I haven't
finalized the next spots yet. The only person we have under
contract at the moment is Lily.''
</P>
<P>
   And in a contradictory stance for a company that asks its
customers for financial information, Cone declined to discuss how
much Fidelity would spend on the campaign through the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every company has its little rules,'' Cone said of Fidelity's
consideration of ad spending as proprietary information, ``and this
is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Competitive Media Reporting, a unit of VNU NV,
Fidelity spent $90 million last year on advertising.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
