<SLUG> BC-LEHMAN-LOSS-LIKELY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEHMAN EXPECTS RUSSIAN TURMOIL TO HELP CUT NET BY $60 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. said Thursday that the
financial turmoil in Russia and other developing countries would
reduce its net income by $60 million for the three months ended
Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street brokerage firm said it had expected its net
income for its third fiscal quarter to be about $211 million but
now estimates that it will come in at $151 million, a sharp fall
from the $197 million net income it reported in the period a year
earlier. Lehman also said its earnings for the first three quarters
of its fiscal year would be about $662 million, up from $462
million for the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman's estimates follow similar announcements from many U.S.
and European financial institutions, including Citicorp, Chase
Manhattan, Bankers Trust, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette and Barclays PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, analysts said Thursday, U.S. and European
institutions have lost billions of dollars as they have had to
write off their holdings of Russian debt.
</P>
<P>
   As the stock market has stumbled in recent weeks, the shares of
brokerage firms have been particularly hard hit, and Thursday was
no exception. Lehman's stock fell $3.75 a share, to $38.375, down
sharply from $85 on July 13, its high for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Revised forecasts by First Call Corp. published Thursday for the
three months ending Sept. 30 show a cut of 11 percent in Lehman's
expected earnings per share, to $1.36 a share. Similar revisions of
analysts' consensus estimates for third-quarter earnings predict
reductions of as little as 3 percent for Charles Schwab and as much
as 52 percent for Bear Stearns, according to First Call, the
research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the bad news is out yet, some analysts fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's potentially more to come _ Latin America appears to be
deteriorating,'' said Joan S. Solotar, an analyst at Donaldson.
``And hedge funds, which might have been meeting margin calls at
the end of August might not be by the end of September.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Lehman estimate, however, was better than some analysts
had expected. ``Not bad for a trading house, actually,'' said John
Keefe, president of Keefe Worldwide Information Services. ``It was
one of the smaller numbers among the capital markets brokers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman spokesman William Ahearn declined to elaborate on the
announcement and said the firm would provide more information in
the coming weeks, when it released full results for its third
quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
