<SLUG> BC-NJ-TEACHER-STRIKE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-275&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. DISTRICT'S SCHOOL YEAR BEGINS WITH STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resent to correct garble. No changes.)   (bl)  
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just three-and-a-half hours before the first day of school
Thursday, teachers went on strike in the largest district in
Monmouth County, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The walkout in Middletown Township came as predawn bargaining
failed after two years of futile negotiations and frosty relations
between the sprawling suburb's 800 teachers and its school board.
The strike guaranteed a rocky start to the new school year for
10,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   At issue were wage increases, the possible loss of teacher
preparation time and proposals that all teachers pay part of their
health insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Students arrived at their schools to find regular teachers
walking the picket lines, and substitutes and administrators
staffing classrooms and straining to handle book distribution and
other typical routines of a new academic year. Students were
dismissed after four hours because of the strike, said Karen
Kondek, a spokeswoman for the Middletown school board.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials complained bitterly that board officials had
gone to state court Wednesday afternoon and sought a back-to-work
order even before a last round of talks had started.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unheard of to seek a restraining order hours before
bargaining begins,'' said Karen Joseph, a spokeswoman for the New
Jersey Education Association, the statewide teachers' union.
``Clearly, this board of education had no intention of settling
this dispute last night.''
</P>
<P>
   The district did get the restraining order during the night, but
Ms. Kondek said that the board did not plan to seek contempt
citations against the strikers until court deputies had served all
of them with the order.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Joseph said Middletown's teachers were still angry that the
board invoked a rarely used state labor law in late July to impose
a contract consisting of its ``last best offer'' for the 1998-99
academic year. In the 30 years since passage of the law, school
boards have imposed contracts nine times on teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Joseph said Middletown's union would not agree to a new
contract until the board rescinded the imposed contract, which
replaced a contract that ended two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The imposed contract provided for an annual pay increase of 2.8
percent for five years. The union wants an average annual increase
of 4 percent for six years, to match the average increase that
other districts in Monmouth have granted recently, Ms. Joseph said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Belluscio, a spokesman for the New Jersey School Boards
Association, said that a law passed in 1985 raised salaries for
starting teachers to $18,500 from about $13,000. Now, it is about
$31,000, Belluscio said.
</P>
<P>
   School boards in New Jersey facing these steadily increasing
wage costs have looked for savings by requiring teachers to pay
higher deductibles and a share of the premiums for health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Middletown's board is trying now to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, the board persuaded voters to approve a $78 million
bond issue, the largest in the state, to finance repairs and
additions to the township's two high schools and three middle
schools.
</P>
<P>
   To produce savings elsewhere, the board wants to take away one
of the two preparation periods that middle school teachers have and
require all teachers to pay $600 to $1,900 a year for health
insurance premiums, depending on their family size and years of
service, school officials said. Both of these conditions are part
of the imposed contract, union officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Joseph, the union spokeswoman, said Middletown's teachers
were resisting because no other district in Monmouth County had
those conditions. In the last round of bargaining, the teachers
offered to contribute to premiums for dental insurance and increase
their co-payment for prescription medicines.
</P>
<P>
   But she said the school board did not respond with a
counteroffer until 4 a.m. Thursday, a half-hour before the strike
deadline and too late to prevent the walkout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
