u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-WHITMAN-GOP-NYT &LR;      09-03 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-WHITMAN-GOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. GOVERNOR TO STUMP FOR REPUBLICANS IN 6 STATES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mont., Nev., Ariz., N.M., Calif., Hawaii, N.J.)   (bl)  
 By JENNIFER PRESTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Gov. Christie Whitman begins a weeklong,
six-state campaign swing in Montana on Friday. Along the way, she
will raise money for fellow Republicans and try to bolster the
campaigns of more than a dozen candidates, as well as her own
standing within the party.
</P>
<P>
   Although some political analysts had predicted that Whitman's
narrow re-election victory last fall would reduce the number of
invitations she gets from across the country, her office said that
had not been the case. Whitman administration officials said that
27 state party organizations had asked her to help raise money or
join candidates on the campaign trail this fall.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is welcoming Whitman's arrival. Her role as a
prominent leader of the Republican Party's moderate wing, and her
support of abortion rights, is expected to attract anti-abortion
protesters at some stops.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Koutnik, the executive director of the Christian
Coalition of Montana, said she had been besieged by telephone calls
from members of her group who said they were outraged that Whitman
was campaigning on behalf of Republicans in their state.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has mounted a national campaign to abolish the pro-life
plank of the GOP platform,'' Mrs. Koutnik said. ``We don't want her
basically stumping to have us somehow overlook our deeply help
convictions on the most fundamental issue to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana Republican Party chairwoman Sue Aleksich-Akey said that
opposition to Whitman's visit by some of the party's more
conservative members had not dampened enthusiasm for the
$50-a-person fund-raising event that the governor is attending
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Also expected at the event are Gov. Marc Racicot and Rep. Rick
Hill, the state's most prominent Republican on the ballot this
year. Hill differs with Whitman on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since the Christian Coalition took after us, our phone
has been ringing off the hook with reservations,'' Ms.
Aleksich-Akey said. ``I am a very good Republican. I vote for
Republicans even if I disagree with them on a single issue.''
</P>
<P>
   That has been Whitman's mantra for the national Republican
Party. She has repeatedly urged party members to stop focusing on
abortion rights and to start emphasizing fiscal issues, like
cutting taxes and controlling government spending.
</P>
<P>
   During her trip to Montana, Nevada, Arizona, New Mexico,
California and Hawaii, Whitman is scheduled to appear with
candidates who both support and oppose abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have consistently campaigned for people who don't share my
position of that issue because I don't believe it to be the
dominant issue,'' she said, as she prepared to leave on her trip.
``I don't believe that you become a national party by drawing lines
in the sand and saying you have to be ideologically pure on one or
two issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said she was making the trip because she was raised to
believe in the importance of supporting Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the daughter of the state chairman and a national
committeewoman,'' she said. ``I was brought up to be supportive of
other candidates. And that's what I'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   And since education, lower taxes and safer streets were major
campaign themes for most of the candidates, she said that she
intended to talk a lot about her efforts in New Jersey to improve
public schools, cut taxes and reduce crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
