<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSITIONS AVAILABLE AT UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Bruins concluded training camp Thursday with a Rose Bowl
scrimmage designed, in part, to evaluate personnel at three
positions:
</P>
<P>
   Tailback, where Antelope Valley High graduate Jermaine Lewis,
Keith Brown and DeShaun Foster are competing to replace Skip Hicks.
The Bruins will announce a starter today, but Toledo stressed that
all three will play against Texas.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: Foster, who scampered 45 yards on his
first carry Thursday and was again the most impressive runner, will
not start.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a freshman, he's made a few mistakes, and he's still
learning,'' Toledo said. ``The upperclassmen have not hurt
themselves so that they should be beaten out.''
</P>
<P>
   Free safety, where Eric Whitfield, Jason Stephens and Tod
McBride opened camp vying for Shaun Williams' position.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are two. McBride, whose bad knees limit his coverage
skills, has moved to strong safety behind Larry Atkins.
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield is a superb athlete, one of UCLA's best, but tends to
short-circuit in coverage situations. Stephens is a redshirt
freshman with no game experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll know (today),'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is moving Atkins to free safety and sliding the
available personnel to the strong side. McBride, for one, is more
suited for its run-support demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry is getting some work at free safety, but he won't be the
starter,'' Toledo said. ``If the free safeties don't do the job,
our contingency is to move Larry.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside linebacker, where Michael Wiley, Santi Hall and Ali
Azziz are competing. One will start, one will play second string.
The third will slide to the other side behind Brendan Ayanbadejo.
</P>
<P>
   Wiley is the best athlete, but Hall, a redshirt freshman, is an
intriguing talent with his 243-pound frame and 35-inch vertical
jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a very bright future,'' outside linebackers coach Bob
Field said. ``But he was a little behind the other two in terms of
conditioning in fall camp. He's running extra to try to catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   QB corner: Second-string quarterback Drew Bennett is slowly
regaining his form after a rough start. Thousand Oaks resident
Scott McEwan has improved, but not enough to challenge Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting to the point where I feel (Bennett) is an
adequate backup now,'' Toledo said. ``He was putting too much
pressure on himself. He knows if something happens to Cade
(McNown), he would have to lead the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Snapper situation: Two subtle but significant personnel losses
from last season were long snappers Chris Rubio (place kicks) and
Mark Weisman (punts).
</P>
<P>
   So far, walk-on Jeff Grau is the No.1 snapper on kicks and tight
end Ryan Neufeld the top punt snapper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
