<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-US-OPEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS AND AGASSI STUMBLE BUT DON'T FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just when it seemed that this 1998 U.S. Open was
going to make a habit of parceling out the drama in tiny doses,
Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi received simultaneous scares
Thursday. A pair of unintimidating but intriguing challengers
summoned the audacity to trip up the former Open champions before
they had even reached the third round.
</P>
<P>
   Though Sampras and Agassi took a humble stumble, neither took
the big fall.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, the four-time Open champion who can tie Roy Emerson's
career record of 12 Grand Slams by staying on track for a fifth
U.S. Open title, was menaced by Stanford's Paul Goldstein, a
256th-ranked wild card whose main tour experience consists of a
single victory in the first round here, courtesy of an opponent's
default.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old Goldstein may have been a neophyte, but through
two sets it was Sampras, with his racquet flailing like a fly
swatter, his shots straying like buckshot and a grimace of disgust
on his face, who played like a pretender before settling down to
business with a 7-6 (7-4), 2-6, 6-3, 6-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those days where I wasn't playing that
great, just had to try and find a way to get through it, and I
did,'' said Sampras, who was not offended by the
challenger-friendly hooting and hollering that emanated from the
packed gallery once word leaked out that the big man on campus was
taking a ribbing from a genuine underdog.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really wasn't any big deal,'' Sampras said. ``You just have
to shut it out. It wasn't like they were rooting against me, they
were just pulling for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein admitted it had been his hope to keep things
competitive and keep Sampras engaged in Louis Armstrong Stadium,
the court where Sampras won all four of his Open titles, ``for at
least an hour.'' Instead, helped along by 24 unforced errors in the
first set by the top-seeded player and 19 more in the second,
Goldstein prolonged Sampras' discomfort for 2 hours 8 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi's distress lasted even longer. After drawing an
interesting second-round opponent in Guillaume Raoux, who warmed up
for this Open by knocking its defending champion, Patrick Rafter,
off his pedestal two weeks ago in New Haven, Agassi proceeded to
joust with him for 2 hours 56 minutes. The mood in the half-empty
stadium was lethargic when the Las Vegan, wearing tent-sized black
shorts beneath his baggy white smock, strutted through the first
two sets like a little penguin. But things heated up once Raoux
caught Agassi napping and sent the match into a fifth set, with
Agassi winning, 6-3, 6-2, 6-7 (6-8), 3-6, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been a little up and down, tweaking the idiosyncrasies
of my game,'' Agassi said. ``I was really frustrated with myself
for letting it get to the fourth set, it was careless tennis, and
you can't afford to have that happen or you're going to be in the
fifth. I think it certainly was a wake-up call of sorts for me to
be up two sets and not to close it out.''
</P>
<P>
   After getting his Grand Slam wake-up call from Raoux, Agassi
gave one of his own to the USTA and its Davis Cup administrators,
who might be under the mistaken impression that he plans to play if
the team reaches the final. He is refusing to face Italy later this
month in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was in my back yard, I wouldn't walk out the back
door,'' said Agassi, whose charity gala in Las Vegas takes place
the same weekend as the semifinal. Though Agassi agreed to
represent the United States against Italy if it chose a West Coast
site, he decided not to play after the USTA selected Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me three phone calls and we could easily have played in
Vegas,'' Agassi said. ``Davis Cup has always been very important to
me, but year after year it never ceases to amaze me what decisions
get made without the players' input. I'm tired of it and have no
interest in playing the rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, all of the prominently seeded women zipped through
their assignments without a hitch, and without losing a set. Faced
with a second-round test against Iva Majoli of Croatia, who cost
her last year's Grand Slam sweep by defeating her in the French
Open final, the Open's defending champion, Martina Hingis,
negotiated it with escalating ease, 7-6 (7-4), 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay Davenport, seeded second and still chasing her first
career Slam along with Hingis' top ranking, trounced 34-year-old
Lori McNeil of Houston, 6-1, 6-1. And fourth-seeded Arantxa Sanchez
Vicario, the defending French Open champion and this Slam's 1994
champion, eliminated Fabiano Zuluaga, 6-3, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams, a breakthrough finalist last year and seeded
fifth this year, patched up her differences with the WTA by
affixing the tour's logo patch to the shoulder of the racy key lime
swimsuit-turned-tennis-tube she wore for her 6-1, 6-3 demolition of
Anne Kremer. Williams was fined $100 for failing to wear the patch
for her first-round match, and faced a $500 fine if she repeated
the transgression Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Though her sponsor, Reebok, claimed she was contractually
obligated not to add the logo to any of the seven sleeveless
outfits it designed for the Open, and though her coach and father,
Richard, threatened a lawsuit against the tour, Williams downplayed
the brouhaha.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the missing patch had been restored to her outfit,
Williams said: ``Deviation is common among humans. It just seems I
am always in the middle after controversy, so it is nothing new for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams last year deflected the mess that ensued after her
infamous semifinal collision with Irina Spirlea prompted her father
to call Spirlea ``a tall, white turkey'' with racist intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really separate from those type of things,'' said
Williams, who termed her bump with Spirlea accidental and said she
bore no grudges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
