<HEADLINE>
OLD WESTBURY TO BE MODEL FOR NEW SUNY STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Old Westbury, N.Y., campus of the State University of New
York has had a reputation in recent years for having some of the
weakest students and lowest graduation rates among SUNY's 64
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the 30-year-old college, which has an unusually high
percentage of minority students and has largely been ignored by
SUNY administrators for more than a decade, is about to become a
kind of demonstration project for the SUNY board and its efforts to
remake the university.
</P>
<P>
   The trustees have charged Old Westbury's new interim president,
Dr. W. Hubert Keen, with transforming the campus. And he will lay
out his vision in a speech to the college Friday, calling for
higher admissions standards, a more rigorous general education
base, less reliance on taxpayer support and more public
accountability through a system of clear measurements.
</P>
<P>
   He will also recommend a ``zero-tolerance'' policy to remove
students who break campus rules, as well as a substantial
building-and-repair program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan of action promises a fundamental transformation of
SUNY at Old Westbury,'' Keen said. ``We will graduate only students
who meet the standards being demanded by the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Keen's ideas closely resemble those of the SUNY
trustees, who say they want to attract better students to the
university and improve its quality. They are also trying to shape a
performance evaluation system that will determine which campuses
get more money and which get less. And they are trying to develop a
core curriculum that they can apply on all campuses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Keen, who applauds all of those initiatives, was appointed in
the spring with enthusiastic backing from the SUNY board and from
the institution's College Council, an advisory board that has
played an active role recently in trying to find a way to bolster
the Long Island college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Hubert's own philosophy was consistent with where the
SUNY board is headed,'' said William Howell, a businessman who is
chairman of the council. He said that he had been impressed with
Keen because he seemed to be someone who could work with the
college's multiple constituencies in turning a vision into reality.
</P>
<P>
   While the trustees work to put their ideas into effect at all of
SUNY's 64 colleges, Keen will be focused on a 605-acre campus with
about 3,700 students _ about half of them members of minority
groups _ and a faculty of 120 full-time and 100 part-time members.
</P>
<P>
   A soft-spoken biologist who was not known for making waves as
provost of the City University of New York's York College, he
sought to play down the possible upheaval from his plan in a
telephone interview this week. He said he preferred to think of it
as a series of ``bold steps'' rather than something
``revolutionary'' or ``radical.'' And he was quick to say that any
transformation must be the result of a ``consensus-building
process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a good deal of reform attitude among the faculty,''
he said, adding that even before his arrival in June, the faculty
and staff at Old Westbury had begun to conduct their own
self-examination in response to SUNY's request that all colleges
review their missions.
</P>
<P>
   Although faculty members at Old Westbury have not yet heard
Keen's proposals, many of them are eager to improve the college
physically and educationally, and to receive more support from
SUNY.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood is hopeful,'' said Gretchen Johnson, an associate
professor in teacher education and the new chairwoman of the
college's faculty senate. ``A lot of faculty are a little worried
about whether we will be able to maintain the original mission of
the college, but realize there needs to be change to support that
mission better.''
</P>
<P>
   The original mission of Old Westbury called for it to serve
``nontraditional students,'' including adults and high school
students who were not well prepared for college.
</P>
<P>
   One question Old Westbury will face as it considers the Keen
plan is whether it is possible to raise admissions criteria and
still maintain its diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Keen would like to require a score of at least 1,000 on the
College Board's SAT exams, slightly below the national average of
1,017. Old Westbury does not now require that applicants take the
SAT, but those who have submitted scores in recent years have
scored less than 750 on average, substantially lower than the
proposed cutoff.
</P>
<P>
   Keen said he believes Old Westbury could raise its admissions
criteria and still maintain its diverse mix ``because Old Westbury
is an institution already identified by ethnic students and
minorities as a place they will feel welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will be more respected for the steps we are taking
here,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Carroll, president of the Empire Foundation, a
conservative research group that studies public higher education in
New York state, said the strategy for Old Westbury is just what is
needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The student body is just ridiculous; the place is like a
mediocre high school,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
