</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KENYA-BOMBING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENYA BOMBING DEFENDANT'S LAWYER MAY BE REPLACED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resent to correct garble. No changes)   (af)  
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The lawyer for one of two defendants charged in the
bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Kenya may be replaced Friday at a
hearing in U.S. district court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   It could not be determined precisely why Magistrate Judge Kevin
Fox has moved to change the lawyer for Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, the
defendant. But the lawyer, Jack Sachs, said he was told that the
reasons involve his ability to carry two potential death penalty
cases at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day that Sachs was assigned to represent Odeh, he
was also appointed to defend a man in an unrelated capital case,
involving interstate kidnapping and murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs said Thursday that he believed that he could handle both
matters, and that he hoped to continue to represent Odeh if his
client so desired.
</P>
<P>
   Odeh was charged last month with conspiracy to commit murder,
use of a weapon of mass destruction, and 12 counts of murder, one
count for each of the 12 Americans killed in the Nairobi bombing.
If he is convicted, Odeh could face a maximum term of life in
prison or death.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs said he had already met with Odeh four times at the
Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan, and interviewed him
extensively. He said he had also interviewed Odeh's wife, who
remains in Kenya, by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's to be a change, it has to be done by the judge,''
Sachs said. ``I would like to keep the case, but I have to go with
whatever is decided.''
</P>
<P>
   Sachs is one of about 150 lawyers who are eligible to be
appointed by judges to represent indigent defendants in U.S.
district court in Manhattan, and reimbursed by the government for
their work. In capital cases, the burden on lawyers is considered
to be so large that defendants are provided with two lawyers paid
by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs, 69, said he has been practicing law in U.S. court in
Manhattan since the early 1970s. He said he is currently a sole
practitioner.
</P>
<P>
   In the federal complaint against Odeh, prosecutors have said he
had denied taking part in a direct role in the embassy bombings but
admitted to being a member of a terrorist group run by the wealthy
Islamic militant, Osama bin Laden, whom the authorities suspect is
behind the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors also said he accepted some responsibility for
the attacks as a member of the bin Laden group. The bombing in
Kenya killed 258 people and wounded thousands of others.
</P>
<P>
   After Odeh was charged last month, Sachs denied to reporters
that his client had confessed to any role in the bombings. But he
said Odeh did acknowledge being a member of the bin Laden
organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
