</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-DEMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE CANDIDATES STRESS AID FOR THE YOUNG, OLD AND ILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a speech that her aides billed as a major policy
address, Geraldine Ferraro said Thursday night that government
should help relieve some of the financial burden borne by families
of the chronically ill, and she called for a comprehensive federal
regulation of the long-term-care industry.
</P>
<P>
   Her opponents in New York's Democratic primary race for U.S.
Senate _ Mark Green and Charles Schumer _ also avowed their
commitment to protecting the vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking during an upstate campaign swing Thursday, Green, the
New York City public advocate, concentrated on programs to help
children. And Schumer, a congressman representing parts of Brooklyn
and Queens, emphasized his record of defending Medicare and Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro spoke in New York City before the Democratic Leadership
for the 21st Century, a group of under-40 Democratic advocates. She
devoted much of her speech to an attack on the Republican
incumbent, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, whom she described as an enemy of
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   In her speech, which her campaign staff finished writing barely
an hour before she was to deliver it, Ferraro referred to her
personal experience of caring for elderly relatives and emphasized
what she has claimed are her special concerns for women's issues.
She said that most providers of care in the home, whether family
members or hired nurses, are women.
</P>
<P>
   To ease the cost of long-term care, Ferraro proposed a program
of federal grants to subsidize home care, tax deductions for
long-term-care insurance and a federal law that would permit
employees to use unpaid leave to take sick relatives to doctors'
appointments. ``Long-term care,'' she said, ``requires long-term
solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next few days, during the Labor Day weekend, much of the
action in the Democratic race for Senate will take place outside of
New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro is scheduled to set out Friday on a four-day road tour
that will take her to Binghamton, Ithaca, Rochester, Syracuse,
Albany and a handful of towns in between. She was in Buffalo
earlier this week, as was Schumer. Green was there Thursday and is
in the midst of his own campaign tour to Democratic outposts in the
northern part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   But for big-city Democrats, it can be chilly up north.
</P>
<P>
   At the state fair in Syracuse, Green found himself rebuffed in
his efforts to greet and shake the hands of passers-by. ``There are
a few more Republicans up here than in Manhattan,'' he remarked
before settling for a barbecue lunch of pulled-pork sandwiches. ``I
am getting that feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Green found the reception friendlier in Rochester, where he
inaugurated what he called, in a dig at a favorite Republican
theme, his ``Green Family Values Tour.'' Accompanied by Mayor
William Johnson, one of his more ardent backers, he told a friendly
group of assembled Democrats that he wanted to create a social
security system for children that would feature universal health
insurance for children and pregnant women and finance the
renovation of schools nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a campaign upstate is not expensive in terms of money _
the price of television and radio advertising is much less than in
the New York City market _ but can be costly in time. Still,
campaign strategists say that to ignore the upstate Democratic
organizations and officials during the primary would be to court
trouble in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer and Green, in particular, have actively sought the
endorsement of local politicians in upstate counties. ``They do
help provide credibility to voters who may not be as familiar with
the candidate,'' said Monroe County Democratic chairman Robert
Cook, who has decided to stay neutral in the Senate primary.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has spent about one day a week upstate during the last
few weeks. He spent a day in Buffalo this week and said he would go
back before the Sept. 15 primary. His television ads in other
upstate markets began running this week.
</P>
<P>
   Even more than his opponents, Schumer has tried to tailor his
message to reach different audiences. This week, he jumped into a
local controversy and urged a Buffalo managed-care company to
include among its providers a popular network of Catholic
hospitals. His television ads in upstate cities emphasize his
commitment to job programs and urban development.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is plenty of anti-New York feeling,'' Schumer said in an
interview, but I think I've shown upstate people I care about the
same things they do.'' He said he did change his demeanor or his
opinions to fit the geography. ``I am pretty much the same wherever
I go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer spent Thursday close to home, expounding on his record
of support for Medicare, Social Security and pension reform to the
elderly residents of the Prospect Park Residence in Brooklyn, an
assisted-living facility that is literally steps away from the
apartment building where he lives.
</P>
<P>
   The event, however, seemed a little out of kilter. Schumer
arrived 35 minutes late and was greeted with a one-man rendition of
``Happy Days Are Here Again,'' played by an entertainer named Banjo
Bob, a regular at the residence who had gamely tried to keep the
drowsy seniors occupied during the wait.
</P>
<P>
   Although the facility is private, does not accept Medicaid and
rents out its air-conditioned apartments for $2,100 to $4,500 a
month, Schumer spoke of his efforts in Congress to prevent cuts in
such programs as Meals on Wheels for the elderly poor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
