<HEADLINE>
DODGERS REDUCED TO SPOILER ROLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One team will be playing for a wild-card berth
this weekend and, unfortunately for the Dodgers, it will be the
guys in the black hats.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Giants enter tonight's series opener at Dodger
Stadium trailing the Chicago Cubs by two games and the New York
Mets by one for the final National League playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   Spoiler? It's a label the Dodgers don't want, especially during
the first week of September. But whenever these two teams get
together, there always seems to be something on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time it happens on the final weekend of the series,
but this year, the Dodgers close out the season with four bitterly
contested games against the Milwaukee Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ready to think about us as a spoiler,'' center fielder
Raul Mondesi said. ``There is a month left. We can't think about
that. This is a big series coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Giants, who have won 9 of 12, maybe. And the Dodgers
don't have a month left. They are eight games back with just 21 to
play. The last time these two teams played, July 13-15, the Giants
took two of three, including an emotional 5-3 victory by former
Dodger Orel Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Giants and Dodgers will play a far more critical
series in two weeks in San Francisco, every game is important.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Giants are playing with a lot of intensity,'' said former
Dodger Mike Piazza, whose Mets took two of three from San Francisco
last week. ``They don't beat themselves. This should be great until
the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so great for the Dodgers, but at least they have their
memories.
</P>
<P>
   In the final game of Piazza's rookie year (1993), he hit two
home runs to eliminate the Giants, who won 103 games that year.
</P>
<P>
   Although Giants left fielder Barry Bonds is on a tear with 11
homers and 23 RBI in his last 20 games, second baseman Jeff Kent
has been just as important.
</P>
<P>
   Since returning from a knee injury 38 games ago, Kent has 52
RBI. He has a 13-game hitting streak with seven homers and 18 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds' (105) and Kent's (104) RBI totals mark the first time
since 1961-62 that the Giants have had back-to-back 100 RBI seasons
(Willie Mays and Orlando Cepeda).
</P>
<P>
   The absence of Kent and tonight's starter Shawn Estes, who
returns after missing a month with shoulder problems, has been the
Giants' biggest curse this season.
</P>
<P>
   This game will mark the first time Kent and Estes have been
active together since June 9. The Giants were just a game behind
San Diego in the National League West. Now, it's 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: The Dodgers are at .500 (70-70) for the 29th time
this season. After sweeping the Phillies, they also are hoping to
win four straight for the first time this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
