<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LABOR-HISTORIAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR HISTORIAN'S LIFE'S WORK: HONORING THOSE WHO LABORED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One day last summer, Dr. Debra Bernhardt rode to the
17th story of 200 Park Avenue South, at 17th Street, and made her
way to the roof. Stepping past the air-conditioning equipment and
water pipes, she stood at the edge of the building and gazed down
at what had become of Union Square, for so long the switchyard of
labor organizing and radical agitation in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The union halls and socialist publishers were mostly gone,
replaced by upscale stores and restaurants like Barnes &AMP; Noble and
the Heartland Brewery. The old Communist Party headquarters on
Union Square East was now a Toys ``R'' Us. The Zeckendorf Tower
condominiums had replaced the S. Klein department store, which in
its day had replaced Joe's, the workingman's saloon that was the
setting for that old wisp of streetcorner doggerel, ``The Face on
the Barroom Floor.''
</P>
<P>
   And just below, on the paved plaza at the north end of Union
Square Park, the city's foodies prowled for goat cheese and
jalapeno jelly and 15 kinds of sprouts in the greenmarket on the
exact site of the Sept. 5, 1882, parade that was later recognized
as the nation's first Labor Day celebration. Back then, the people
marching through the square were seeking something else _ an
eight-hour workday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bernhardt shook her head and lifted her camera, as if
recalling the past to life. She had positioned herself so that her
photographs would align with the lithographs of that first parade,
matching the geography if not the passionate exuberance of the
original park. And when she was finished, the pictures would become
yet another piece of her meticulously gathered evidence of the
specific and significant past struggling to be heard above the ring
of electronic cash registers and fevered construction around this
patch of green.
</P>
<P>
   Her three years of work will pay off Sept. 12, when the National
Park Service officially declares Union Square Park a national
historic landmark, largely on the strength of her research. The
local labor movement will rouse itself to re-enact that first
parade, with volunteers dressed like such historical firebrands as
Samuel Gompers and Frances Perkins, and marchers carrying signs
with ancient slogans like ``Eight Hours a Legal Day's Work'' and
``Party Hacks to the Rear.'' (The latter could become a bit awkward
once the real Labor Day parade begins, a few hours later, with its
usual phalanx of election-year office seekers.)
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bernhardt, the director of the Robert F. Wagner Labor
Archives at New York University, is more accustomed to the cocoon
of library shelves than the cacophony of a parade, but she will be
there as co-chairman of the event with Brian McLaughlin, president
of the city's Central Labor Council, which sponsored her research
along with the Amalgamated Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, submitted to the U.S. Interior Department, came
after she and local labor officials realized how little of the
park's history had been preserved, and how few of the nation's
2,250 historic landmarks were related to the labor movement (25, to
be precise).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost so much of our history,'' she said earlier this
week in a shady corner of the park. ``No one realizes that the
eight-hour day was won by working people on these streets, in this
park. We wanted to celebrate the fact that ordinary people were
able to express their rights to free speech and assembly on this
spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bernhardt, 45, wears her politics on her sleeve, as a
soft-spoken but ardent child of labor who puts a union label on her
business card, sings in the New York City Labor Chorus, and is
known to friends by the nickname of Debs, after the socialist
presidential candidate and labor leader.
</P>
<P>
   But even though the archives _ a collection of hundreds of
thousands of personal papers, books, journals, badges and
photographs _ are a center for scholarly research on anarchism,
communism, and labor socialism, she describes herself as a ``Hubert
Humphrey Democrat,'' who was a Mo Udall delegate to the 1976
Democratic Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Democratic diaper baby from the Rust Belt,'' she said,
having been infused with pro-labor sentiment from an early age.
Many of her Danish-American male relatives were iron miners in the
upper-peninsula town of Iron River, Mich., where she grew up, and
her parents had only slightly less strenuous careers as high school
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   She now lives with her husband and two children in Boerum Hill,
Brooklyn, and still wears, as a necklace, a piece of burnished iron
slag from the foundry where her grandfather worked.
</P>
<P>
   The old plant is closed now, as are most of the mines, and she
says she carries them around in her head along with her father's
exhortation not to forget where she came from. That has led to an
energetic career as an archivist helping to remember where everyone
else came from, snapping up personal papers of aging labor leaders
and locals and assisting researchers in the stacks.
</P>
<P>
   For the landmark project she dug up old newspaper accounts of
the first parade, and reminded the park service of the soapbox
speeches and workers' rallies in Union Square that will now be
remembered with a plaque and several historical signs somewhere
within the fresh vegetable stands of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it wouldn't hurt if all this also reminds labor itself of
its noble traditions,'' she added, smiling subversively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
