<SLUG> BC-CRASH-OBIT-MORTIMER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN MORTIMER, FORMER N.Y. TIMES EXECUTIVE, AND WIFE ARE CRASH
VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Conn.)   (bl)  
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Mortimer, 75, a former senior vice president of The New
York Times for personnel and industrial relations, and his wife of
22 years, Hilda, 69, died in the Swissair plane crash Wednesday.
They lived in Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   They were on their way to a vacation in France, their family
said.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Bishow, a retired senior vice president for operations at
The New York Times, said Thursday that Mortimer played the dominant
role on behalf of the newspaper in negotiations before and during
every strike while he was with The Times during the 1960s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Mortimer was born in Bronxville, N.Y. He served in the Army Air
Force in the South Pacific during World War II and graduated from
Williams College in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   After working in industrial relations at The New York Daily
News, he joined The New York Times in 1962 as industrial relations
manager and held a succession of industrial relations and personnel
positions. From 1973 to 1981, he was senior vice president for
personnel and industrial relations. He later held other positions,
including senior vice president and assistant to the general
manager of the newspaper and, finally, assistant to the president
of The New York Times Co., before retiring in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Mortimer's first wife, the former Harriet Watson, died in 1974
after more than 20 years of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Mortimer's survivors include two daughters, Claire Mortimer of
Berkeley, Calif., and Katherine Mortimer of Albany, Calif.; a son,
Stewart of Tucson, Ariz.; a brother, Donald, of Riverside, Conn.;
and a sister, Mary Hillegas, also of Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mortimer, the former Hilda Barnes Belcher, retired after
being on the paid staff of a succession of nonprofit organizations
engaged in arranging international student exchanges and in similar
activities. One was the Institute of International Education. A
previous marriage, to Robert S. Huffman, ended in divorce in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mortimer's survivors include a daughter, Susan Parker Boal
of Salisbury, Conn.; a son, Philip B. Huffman of Williston, Vt.;
four sisters, Marjorie S. Belcher of Washington, Elizabeth B.
Rogers of Champaign, Ill., and Helen C. Belcher and Ruth S.
Belcher, both of Plymouth, Mass.; and a brother, Edward L. Belcher
of Rochester, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980903.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8533 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-IMMIGRANT-DEPORT-4     09-03 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-IMMIGRANT-DEPORT-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRANT FIGHTS OFF THREATENED DEPORTATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MIRTA OJITO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A week after he was told that the U.S. government
would no longer try to deport him to his native country, Jesus
Collado, a Dominican immigrant who has lived in New York for 24
years, is facing new challenges: learning to live again without
fear and paying the bills that have accumulated during his 16-month
ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have lived with the fear of being separated from my family
for such a long time that I don't even know what I feel anymore,''
said Collado, 45, a restaurant owner and father of three who still
cries when he remembers the months he spent detained by the
Immigration and Naturalization Service in York, Pa. ``It will be a
long time before that feeling in my heart leaves me.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Judge Douglas Schoppert of Immigration Court in New
York dismissed the deportation case against Collado, a legal
resident of the United States who, upon returning from a trip to
the Dominican Republic last April, was stopped by immigration
officials at Kennedy International Airport and sent to jail to
await deportation for a crime he committed 24 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Collado's case attracted immediate national attention because
his ordeal highlighted the effects that tougher immigration laws,
passed in 1996, could have on the lives of ordinary citizens who
committed crimes long ago. In 1974, Collado was convicted of
statutory rape, a misdemeanor, for having sex with his girlfriend,
who was 13.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials used his case to illustrate how the law
had tied their hands by taking away the agency's discretionary
powers in certain deportation cases. Members of Congress used the
case to contend that the immigration agency was interpreting the
law too harshly and wasting resources in the process. Collado
became the subject of speeches on the Senate floor and special
bills were introduced to stop his deportation.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for immigrants used the case to show that
anti-immigrant feelings sweeping the country were destroying the
lives of hard-working women and men like Collado.
</P>
<P>
   Schoppert did not explain his ruling. But Collado's lawyer,
Kerry Bretz, said the case was dismissed because he had been able
to show that the agency had erred in holding his client for almost
seven months and in trying to deport him for a misdemeanor that did
not warrant such treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials said they would not appeal the judge's
ruling. They have given Collado back his passport and his green
card. He is free to travel abroad and to re-enter the United
States, his home since he was 19.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Collado said he was relieved by the judge's decision. But, he
added, he still cannot rest easy. While he was detained, he almost
lost his restaurant in upper Manhattan. He said he owes $13,000 to
vendors, $36,000 in back rent to his landlord and about $30,000 in
medical bills; both his wife and 19-year-old daughter had serious
health problems last year. He sleeps fitfully and visits a
psychologist once a week.
</P>
<P>
   Collado was released from jail last October, but he remained
under the threat of deportation until last month when lawyers for
the INS suddenly filed a motion to dismiss his case because, they
argued, he had demonstrated he was eligible to become a U.S.
citizen _ a test of good moral character that allows immigration
officials to drop deportation proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   But Bretz, Collado's lawyer, filed his own motion arguing that
the case should be dismissed for other reasons. Bretz argued that
the immigration agency should never have tried to deport him to
begin with. Lawyers for the agency did not oppose that motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``INS made a mistake and the result is that Jesus' life was
turned around for a long time,'' Bretz said. ``They should have
never locked him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bretz said he planned to file a civil suit against the agency on
Collado's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is an exception, overlooked until now, to the same law
that allowed the agency to detain Collado and try to deport him.
Among other things, the law, intended to rid the country of
criminal immigrants, states that any immigrant convicted of a crime
of ``moral turpitude,'' like rape, is inadmissible and therefore
deportable. But the law offers a respite for people who have
committed only one crime and have not been sentenced to more than
six months' imprisonment. Collado had been sentenced to one year of
probation.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials maintain that they did not err in seeking
the deportation of Collado. Russell Bergeron Jr., an agency
spokesman in Washington, said that immigration inspectors at the
airport had no choice but to detain Collado once he revealed that
he had been convicted of rape.
</P>
<P>
   Bergeron said that lawyers for the agency had become aware that
the exception to the law might apply to Collado only after
carefully reviewing his criminal record last month. He said the
full records of Collado's conviction had not reached the agency
until then.
</P>
<P>
   Bergeron said the judge's decision does not set a precedent or
change the way the immigration agency interprets the laws that have
broadened the definition of what constitutes a deportable crime and
who is subject to deportation or deemed inadmissible to the United
States. Had it not been for that exception, Bergeron insisted, the
agency would have had no recourse but to deport Collado, because
the laws have stripped immigration judges of the power to make
those decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, they must apply the law equally and
retroactively, regardless of the nature of the crime or the
behavior of the immigrant since the crime was committed. Bergeron
said the agency had asked Congress to amend the language of the law
to return to the immigration courts a measure of discretion.
</P>
<P>
   That interpretation of the law is a point of contention between
the agency and members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tried to impress upon INS what the intent of the
legislation was and it clearly was not to deport people like Mr.
Collado,'' said Joseph McMonigle, communications director for Sen.
Spencer Abraham, a Michigan Republican who supports tougher laws
against immigrants who are criminals. ``They have prosecutorial
discretion and they should use it.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Bergeron said, the agency has no procedures in place to
determine when to pursue a deportation case, because, historically,
that has been the role of immigration courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a continual theme in the Collado case,'' said
Lucas Guttentag, director of the Immigrants' Rights Project of the
American Civil Liberties Union. ``Immigration washes its hands and
says: `It's not my fault. It's you!' and Congress points to INS and
says, `No, it's you!' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
