r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     09-03 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS HOPE YOU'RE READY FOR SOME FOOTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the best efforts of Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa, much of
America truly is ready for some football. Baseball may still be the
national pastime, but there's no doubting that the NFL is the
national passion. Or, at least the best reason to make a wager.
</P>
<P>
   The environment for the NFL in 1998 may not change much on the
field the Cowboys will lead the league in arrests, the 49ers will
win the NFC West, the Chiefs will beat the Raiders but it has
undergone a renovation in the broadcast booth.
</P>
<P>
   All four networks involved have raised the bar with their
approach after having the financial bar for TV rights set at a
mind-numbing $17.8 billion. To justify the expense, the networks
are doing whatever they can to get the viewer's to watch their ads,
umm, games.
</P>
<P>
   To wit, if one can use that word when talking about TV:
</P>
<P>
   ABC: The network of Monday Night Football has made three
fundamental changes: 1, it moved kickoff up to 5 p.m.; 2, moved
Frank Gifford out of the booth to make room for former quarterback
Boomer Esiason; and 3, anchored the studio shot for pregame and
halftime segments to ESPN's new theme restaurant in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The kickoff change was designed for East Coast viewers and
affiliates. ABC found that the Nielsens usually declined in the
last hour of a broadcast simply because some people couldn't stay
up until midnight. Affiliates also had to push their local news
back to midnight or later, costing them revenue dollars.
</P>
<P>
   This subtext indicates once again how little the networks think
about West Coast viewers, many of whom will now be stuck in freeway
gridlock between 5 and 6 p.m. Then again, it could be a good reason
to start happy hour earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Gifford move was long overdue. His last pertinent comment as
an analyst was about Y.A. Tittle. Esiason was a great quote as a
player, but it may take him some time to learn to talk in short
bursts. Here's hoping he's a quick study. In ABC's preseason games,
Dierdorf tried to dominate the broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford will co-host the studio show with the terminally boorish
Chris Berman, and one can start taking book on how long he lasts.
He learned he was being bumped from the booth by a reporter. He had
just come to terms with moving to the studio when he learned, again
from a reporter, that the show would originate from Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   There's no truth to reports that ABC put the studio in Baltimore
so Kathie Lee Gifford would always know where Frank was on Mondays.
</P>
<P>
   CBS: Network officials are all misty-eyed about Sunday's opener,
seeing as it's CBS' return to the NFL fold after a four-year
layoff. Viewers could care less. All they want is a clean broadcast
that isn't annoying.
</P>
<P>
   CBS' decision-making regarding talent was schizophrenic. It made
some safe choices in terms of game announcers (Verne Lundquist, Don
Criqui, Randy Cross, Phil Simms) but then hired three rookie
broadcasters for the pregame show Marcus Allen, George Seifert and
Brent Jones. All three men are bright and glib, but that's no
guarantee for instant success.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nantz may have to carry them awhile, and there are those who
believe he has a hard time carrying himself. The pregame show will
be an hour long. To its credit, CBS invested heavily in game
reporters, an often neglected area. Bonnie Bernstine, Armen
Keteyian and Michele Tafoya are the big three.
</P>
<P>
   Fox: The network considered expanding its pregame show to 90
minutes but chose to stick with an hour format for now. It made
probably the best offseason move by picking up Cris Collinsworth on
waivers from NBC. Collinsworth has a sharp tongue, and he and Howie
Long should provide hours of entertainment by cutting the Homer
Simpson of the NFL, Terry Bradshaw, into shreds.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN: The cable operative has expanded its ``Sunday NFL
Countdown'' pregame show to a ridiculous two hours. Does anyone in
America need two hours of prep before a regular season games? Chris
Berman and Tom Jackson host with a cast presumably larger than that
of the film ``Ben Hur.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN responded late to the new contract shakeout, deciding at
the last minute to add Paul Maguire to the game telecast alongside
the overrated Mike Patrick and diarrhea-mouthed Joe Theismann. Not
only will Maguire have difficultly getting a word in, but his sense
of humor may be lost on his partners.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN has seven, count' em, seven NFL-themed shows during the
course of a week. If that isn't corporate boot-licking, what is?
</P>
<P>
   KCBS: With the return of football, CBS' affiliates can now jump
back into the NFL with their own Sunday pregame and postgame shows.
KCBS gets points for moving ultra aggressively. It will air a
one-hour show at 8 a.m., leading into CBS' 9 a.m. pregame show, and
an 90-minute postgame show (4-to-5:30 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hill, who set the tone for local NFL shows years ago, will
co-host this one for KCBS with the underrated Bret Lewis. XTRA's
Steve Hartman, Lisa Guerrero and former Charger quarterback Stan
Humphries will serve as analysts and contributors. The postgame
show will be highlight intensive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
