<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AUBURNGAME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Virginia has no trouble with punchless Auburn
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, Ala. _ If Thursday night's opener with Virginia was a
true indicator, it may be a long, long season for the Auburn
Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn's new conserative, run-oriented offense was ineffective
at best and overwhelemed at worst by Virginia's highly-regarded
defense. When it was over, a Jordan-Hare Stadium crowd of 78,315
fans left in disbelief after watching the No. 22 Tigers stumble and
lose to the No. 16 Cavaliers 19-0.
</P>
<P>
   Down 12-0 in the fourth quarter, a series of plays summed up
Auburn's night. The Tigers got the ball at the Virginia 42-yard
line after a fumble by Thomas Jones. After struggling all night,
the Auburn offense had a chance to redeem itself. But Auburn came
up less than a yard short on fourth down and had to give the ball
back to Virginia with 9:06 left in the game. It would prove to be
Auburn's last gasp.
</P>
<P>
   It was a less than auspicious start for Auburn quarterback Ben
Leard, the sophomore from Hartwell. Leard had a pair of fumbles and
an interception and was generally harrassed all night by the
Virginia defense, which returned nine starters from the nation's
No. 24 unit of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   With Top 10 teams LSU, Tennessee, and Florida all coming up in
the next five weeks, it was clear that the Tigers have a lot of
work to do.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia put the game away early in the fourth quarter with its
best sustained drive of the night, moving from its own 11 to the
Auburn 14-yard line. At that point Todd Braverman kicked his third
field goal of the night to make it 12-0 with 12:54 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Jones added the final points on a 3-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Up 6-0 at halftime, Virginia threatened in its first possession
of the third quarter when it drove to the Auburn 34-yard line
thanks to a 24-yard pass from Aaron Brooks to Casey Crawford. But
on second down Brooks was penalized 14 yards for intentional
grounding, which killed the drive.
</P>
<P>
   But Virginia got the ball back at the Auburn 37-yard line after
a 27-yard punt by Jeremy Zills. The Cavaliers moved the ball to the
Auburn 7 where they settled for a 24-yard field goal by Braverman
with 7:55 left in the period to make it 9-0.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn dodged a huge bullet on its next possession when Leard
fumbled and Virginia recovered at the Tiger 25-yard line. But the
Tigers stiffened and Braverman missed a 39-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
