<HEADER>
A8538 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-WEST-LADN     09-03 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MR. CLUTCH' STILL ALONG FOR THE RIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM McCURDIE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's not disappearing after all.
</P>
<P>
   After some contemplative summer moments spent in the West
Virginia countryside, where he says people still call him Jerry
instead of Mr. West, the most valuable Laker for many of the past
37 years came to one inescapable conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   He is not the retiring type.
</P>
<P>
   Once Jerry West determined he wasn't ready to walk away from his
job as the Lakers' executive vice president, all he needed was a
sign that the club's owner wanted him to stay. That finally came
Thursday, when West signed a four-year contract extension that is
reportedly worth $3.5 million per season.
</P>
<P>
   The contract ensures that West, largely responsible for the
Lakers' quick return to prominence in the NBA after the curtain
came down on the Showtime era, will enter the fifth decade of his
association with the team he broke in with as a player shortly
after the franchise moved to Los Angeles from Minneapolis in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   During a press conference Thursday to announce his signing of
the new contract, West said the extra time afforded him this summer
by the NBA lockout helped him get away from the day-to-day grind of
his job and reflect on whether he really wanted to leave the team
that has been such an important part of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had so much advice this summer,'' he said, ``so many
people pulling and tugging on me. Sometimes, you just need to get
away and listen to your instincts.''
</P>
<P>
   West acknowledged that he had at least one other lucrative
alternative. He declined to reveal what it was beyond saying it was
``incredibly attractive to me.'' But at age 60, retirement was not
an option.
</P>
<P>
   West told ofsaid
</P>
<P>
   a long-time friend of his who retired financially secure, but
died within months of his retirement. ``Sometimes,'' he said, ``I
wonder if the same thing wouldn't happen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   An admitted bundle of tension, West said he was a ``physical
wreck'' at the end of last season, and acknowledged that doctors
have warned him that he was putting his health at risk with
job-related stress. But sources close to West have indicated that
at least part of his frustrations stemmed from lingering financial
issues between he and Laker owner Jerry Buss, including some
outstanding deferred payments from his previous contract.
</P>
<P>
   Buss did not attend Thursday's press conference at the Forum but
issued a statement filled with glowing praise of West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has meant more to the Los Angeles Lakers' franchise
than Jerry West,'' he said. ``Since 1960 he has brought talent,
intelligence, class, dignity and success to this team, this city
and this organization. Keeping him here will ensure that the Lakers
will be one of the best-run franchises in sports well into the 21st
century.''
</P>
<P>
   West expressed relief that the speculation regarding his status
with the team is finally over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not want to be an issue with this team,'' he said. ``I've
never wanted to be an issue in any way, shape or form. I want to
fit in with the scenery here.''
</P>
<P>
   Laker coach Del Harris, who is about to enter the final year of
his contract, said he was not surprised by West's decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always believed he would stay,'' Harris said. ``The
Lakers without Jerry would be like a hamburger without a bun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
