<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHWEST-STRIKE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINNESOTA GOVERNOR URGES CLINTON TO END PILOTS' STRIKE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Subs for new 2nd graf to update)  By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abandoning his neutral stance in the pilots' strike against
Northwest Airlines, Minnesota Gov. Arne Carlson on Thursday called
on President Clinton to order the pilots back to work, but the
White House stood firm against the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest took a tougher stand, too, sending a provocative
signal toits unions by naming the head of its strike-preparation
efforts, Mickey Foret, as its new chief financial officer. Foret
was president of Continental Airlines under Frank Lorenzo, whose
battles with unions at Eastern Airlines and Continental drove both
into bankruptcy. Foret replaces James Lawrence, who Northwest said
would pursue other interests.
</P>
<P>
   The moves came on the sixth day of the pilots' strike and a day
after Northwest laid off more than half its 51,000 workers, many of
whom live in Minnesota, saying that it could not afford to keep
paying them if it was not operating.
</P>
<P>
   Several other Midwest governors have already called on the White
House to intervene. But Carlson, a Republican in the state where
Northwest has its headquarters and where there is wide sympathy for
the pilots, had been reluctant to urge such action, a course that
the pilots oppose and Northwest quietly favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was everyone's hope that the strike could be resolved
without the president taking this action,'' the governor said.
``But now as we enter the sixth full day of this strike with no end
in sight, I believe it is time for the president to act.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House said that the president appreciated the views of
Carlson and other officials but that Clinton felt that the best way
for the strike to be resolved was for the two sides to return to
the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   Talks broke down on Friday, hours before the strike deadline set
by the pilots, and have not resumed since. The pilots want a 14
percent wage increase over three years to make up for pay cuts they
took to help save the airline from bankruptcy in 1993. They also
say they want increased job security. Northwest has offered 9
percent over four years, saying it could not afford more.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides have agreed to meet on Saturday in Chicago with a
federal mediator to determine whether full-fledged contract
negotiations would be productive.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest also said Thursday that it was suspending its
advertising campaign critical of the pilots during the Labor Day
weekend because of the meeting Saturday. The two sides have been
warring with each other in print and television advertising in
Detroit, Minneapolis and other cities. The pilots previously said
that they had stopped their advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater ordered Mesaba
Airlines and Express Airlines I, two Northwest-affiliated commuter
carriers that have stopped flying as a result of the strike, to
come up with a plan to resume service to 17 cities in 11 states by
the end of Friday. Under a federal program, Washington subsidizes
flights to the cities because airlines say it would impossible to
make money serving them.
</P>
<P>
   But both of the carriers said Thursday that complying with the
secretary's order would threaten their viability and therefore
their long-term service to the 17 cities.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear what step the Transportation Department would
take next.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Railway Labor Act, the president has the power to
force the pilots back to work for 60 days while a special emergency
board tries to come up with a solution acceptable to both sides if
he believes that the strike is disrupting the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Oberstar, D-Minn., who has been leading the forces
against White House intervention, said in an interview Thursday
that the economic impact of the strike had been minimal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a national economic impact here,'' Oberstar said.
``The two parties really have to overcome their mutual animosities
and reason together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
