<HEADLINE>
CELEBRITY BIRD  
 HULLABALOO HIRSCHFELD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHARLES STRUM and JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among celebrity watchers this week, Dr. Frank Gill and his
colleagues at the National Audubon Society rank pretty high. A
visitor unknown in these parts, the broad-billed sandpiper, has
just blown into town.
</P>
<P>
   Gill is the senior vice president and director of science for
the Audubon Society, in New York, and he is also a very happy man.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, there's an old adage among birders: `If you stand in
one place in the world, sooner or later every species will fly
by,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This particular sandpiper, a kind of migratory Wrong Way
Corrigan from the Arctic, appeared at the Jamaica Bay Wildlife
Refuge and quickly became the talk of the town among
ornithologists.
</P>
<P>
   The bird was probably on its way to Australia, or perhaps India,
to spend the winter but got blown off course.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the hardest in the world to see,'' he said.
``It's a scarce bird with a limited distribution. Everyone who
builds a world list is eager to bump into it.''
</P>
<P>
   It has never been observed in the lower 48 states, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gill said the piper, a juvenile, is distinguished by its black
and white stripes. It has a wingspan of about a foot and dines on
little invertebrates, aquatic flies and small crustaceans, which it
finds in abundance in Jamaica Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's interesting,'' Gill said, ``is that it's staying put.''
</P>
<P>
   Most birders who want to see one usually have to go to the
Aleutian Islands, he said.
</P>
<P>
   So what does this mean for Gill?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my next to last sandpiper,'' he said. ``I've seen all but
the spoon-billed sandpiper.'' But that's in Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   A Lesson: Careful Who You Praise
</P>
<P>
   Some stockbrokers were hollering in disbelief this week when the
market plummeted, but Judy Chen of Prudential Securities was
distressed for different reasons. A complimentary letter she had
written to a client, Abe Hirschfeld, the real estate developer who
is running for New York state comptroller, had been released to
news organizations as campaign fodder. No one had told Ms. Chen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oooohhhhh, nooohhhhh,'' Ms. Chen said. ``He released it? It
was my personal compliment. It does not represent Prudential's
opinions. When will this be published? Oh, no.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chen's letter, released in full by Hirschfeld's press team,
complimented the candidate on his financial acuity in liquidating
his ``entire equity portfolio'' early this August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am amazed by your judgment,'' Ms. Chen wrote. It was
accompanied by a press release from Hirschfeld's headquarters:
``Abe Predicted Market Fall: Pru Says He Sold Stock Portfolio
Before Downtown'' and a challenge from Hirschfeld to the incumbent,
H. Carl McCall: ``So Carl, what's with you _ did you sell?'' ``I
called the controller's office and a man told me they didn't know
of any stocks they sold,'' Hirschfeld said. ``I know the pension
account has about $125 billion and without any question, it's lost
20 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the state comptroller's office, Steven
Greenberg, angrily denied that there had been a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of March 31, the pension fund was $105 billion,'' Greenberg
said. ``Today, it's approximately $100 billion. In the five years
Carl McCall has been in office, the fund grew from $56 billion to
more than $105 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   Why would the voters choose, to handle state funds, a fellow who
has been indicted with 123 counts of tax evasion, which is to say,
Hirschfeld, Hirschfeld was asked.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschfeld responded with a complex statement that seemed to
suggest a plot between the district attorney and an estranged
business partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``A district attorney can indict even a ham sandwich,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I was indicted last year when I ran for Manhattan
borough president. I received 28 percent of the votes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
