<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIGGEST HOMER ON FOX MAY NOT BE A SIMPSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball's broadcast history is so thick that it has its own
archives. But it's safe to say the game has never received the kind
of unprecedented coverage it will get the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Fox and ESPN have adopted a 24/7 mentality toward the home-run
record chase being waged by Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa, with Fox
prepared to blow out four nights of prime-time programming and
change its NFL schedule Sunday to be present for a record.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' McGwire sits at 59 home runs in 1998, three shy
of breaking Roger Maris' single-season record of 61 set in 1961,
while the Cubs' Sammy Sosa is at 57. Virtually every game over the
next 10 days will be televised.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN will cover tonight's Cardinals game against Cincinnati (5
p.m.), while cable superstation WGN will cover the Cubs-Pirates
game (4 p.m.). Saturday, Fox will air the Cardinals-Reds game at 10
a.m. if
</P>
<P>
   McGwire goes into the game with 60 home runs or more. If he's
still at 59, Los Angeles will see the Dodgers-Giants game at 1 p.m.
as originally scheduled. WGN the Cubs-Pirates at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixty is the magic number,'' said Fox Sports Executive
Producer Ed Goren.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Fox will show the finale of the Cards-Reds series at 1
p.m., following its NFL coverage here of the Packers-Lions. Fox
switched its Sunday NFL schedule in some markets so it could clear
the 1 p.m. slot for McGwire's game. WGN has the Cubs-Pirates at 10
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a point now where it's no use worrying about sleep
until it's over,'' said Fox Sports Executive Producer Ed Goren.
``We put a plan in place Wednesday morning. I got on a plane and by
the time I hit the ground, we had to change the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're taking it day by day, at-bat by at-bat. This
is unprecedented. We're not an all-sports cable operation. It takes
a tremendous commitment from a network to do what we're doing. We
could not have done it, either, without the work of Major League
Baseball to make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   If the chase goes into next week, Fox is prepared to pre-empt
its prime-time lineup on Tuesday, Thursday, Friday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   None of the major events in baseball's recent past George
Brett's flirtation with .400, Pete Rose breaking Ty Cobb's record
for career hits or even Cal Ripken breaking Lou Gehrig's
consecutive games were momentous enough to make a network give up
prime-time hours.
</P>
<P>
   There is an ancillary storyline here which orbits the perpetual
Fox-Disney scuffle. ESPN, owned by Disney, would have been in
position to pick up a bigger share of the McGwire-Sosa programming
if it hadn't angered Major League Baseball over three Sunday night
telecasts in September.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN tried to shift three national Sunday night broadcasts, on
Sept. 6, 13 and 20, to ESPN2 after it landed the entire NFL Sunday
night package. The network said it could do so under a provision of
its contract which said events of ``national significance'' take
precedence.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball felt NFL regular season games did not meet that
qualifier, so it took back those three Sunday games and released
them to the teams involved. One of those three games would have
been Sunday's Cards-Reds game, which truly may be of ``national
significance.''
</P>
<P>
   The rift went even deeper Wednesday when ESPN chose not to cut
into their baseball coverage for live updates of McGwire's 58th and
59th home runs. ESPN issued only a statement about that decision:
``We are being as aggressive as we can within baseball's
parameters.''
</P>
<P>
   Goren was amused. ``They didn't show his home runs Wednesday,
but they sure were calling baseball to get Friday's game,'' he
said. ``If they're tired of the home-run race, we'll be glad to
take the games off their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Disney (Angels) and Fox (Dodgers) also own major
league teams just adds to the untidy little melodrama.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-98 2347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
